<SLUG> BC-Japan-SKorea-Banks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sumitomo Bank to support major South Korean banks
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Sumitomo Bank Ltd. said Wednesday it will support
five major South Korean commercial banks by guaranteeing letters of
credit up to dlrs 100 million.
	   The move by the major Japanese bank will be jointly taken with
the International Finance Corp., an affiliate of the
Washington-based World Bank, said Sumitomo spokeswoman Makiko
Tanaka.
	   Sumitomo said in a release that it has re-guaranteed letters of
credit issued by the banks to help smooth foreign trade in South
Korea, which is facing renewed financial and labor troubles.
	   There are now numerous cases of foreign banks and exporters who
have become reluctant to accept letters of credit from South Korean
banks amid the country's uncertain economic prospects.
	   Under a new plan, Sumitomo said it will guarantee up to 60
percent of the letters of credit to be issued by the South Korean
banks, with the remaining 40 percent guaranteed by the
International Finance Corp.
	   Takana said the new credit support measures will be signed with
each of the five South Korean banks, including Kookmin Bank,
Shinhan Bank and Korea Long Term Credit Bank, on June 23 in South
Korea.
	   South Korea is struggling to rehabilitate its economy after
accepting an International Monetary Fund bailout in December.
	   But the country faces difficulty in drawing foreign investment
and imports because of the increasing amount of bad debt held by
its financial institutions and intensifying labor disputes.
 &UR; (km)
</TEXT>
