w2335 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Singapore-Markets     06-10 0328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore dollar, stock market tumble
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Falling through important psychological levels
for the second time in a week, the Singapore dollar and stock
market both weakened Wednesday as concerns mounted over regional
currencies and the local economy.
	   The stock market's benchmark Straits Times Industrial Index, or
STII, plunged 2.7 percent in morning trading to easily breach the
key support level of 1100. It fell to 1087.35 in late morning
trading, about 30 points off its opening.
	   The Singapore dollar wasn't spared either, breaking up through
the 1.72 level against the greenback for the first time since early
February. In morning trading, the U.S. dollar was quoted at a
four-month high of 1.7215 Singapore dollars, up from 1.7075 late on
Tuesday.
	   The falls come after a series of precipitous drops over the past
week. The market index closed below the 1200 last Thursday, while
the Singapore dollar dropped through the important 1.70 level on
Monday.
	   Current levels are fast approaching lows plumbed during the
height of the financial crisis earlier this year in January, when
the STII dropped to 1073.47 and the Singapore dollar weakened below
1.80 to the greenback.
	   There was increasing speculation by market players over whether
China will devalue its yuan and Hong Kong will abandon its fixed
currency peg against the U.S. dollar, according to a dealer at a
foreign brokerage in Singapore.
	   Uncertainty over the direction of the Japanese yen, and growing
indications of significant economic slowdown or even recession in
Singapore's economy also continue to dampen sentiment.
	   Equity markets were down across the region.
	   A dealer said attention was focused on Hong Kong, where the
benchmark Hang Seng index has dived 253.85 points to 8137.61 in
early Wednesday trading.
	   He said foreign sellers were dropping Singapore's index-linked
stocks to get out of the market. 	   
</TEXT>
