</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thai stock market drops below 300 for first time in 11 years
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Thailand's benchmark stock index
dropped below 300 points for the first time in 11 years as worries
grew over the health of Thai financial institutions.
	   The Stock Exchange of Thailand index dropped to a low of 299.89
points in morning trading, although it quickly rebounded back over
the 300-point mark. Around 11:15 a.m. (0415 GMT), the index was at
300.37 points, down 7.88 points.
	   Dealers attributed the decline to worries over the fate of Thai
financial institutions. Although the Thai central bank has
announced new rules to encourage institutions to restructure
problem loans, few have begun to do so, analysts said.
	   Meanwhile, problem loans are mounting. Standard and Poor's
Corp., a U.S.-based credit rating agency, said last month it
predicted non-performing loans at Thai institutions would peak at
35 percent of total loans in 1999. 	   
</TEXT>
