w2345 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-EastTimor     06-10 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-East Timor </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Protesting East Timorese reject offer by Indonesian president
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos Staffing
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHER TORCHIA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DILI, Indonesia (AP) _ Rejecting a presidential promise of
special status for their homeland within Indonesia, thousands of
East Timorese protested Wednesday, demanding the right to vote for
full independence.
	   More than 3,000 students and others gathered on the grounds of
the state-funded University of East Timor.
	   ``We want total independence. We want to be free,'' said one
protester Licinio Branco at the noisy but peaceful rally.
	   Organizers said Indonesia should allow a full and free
referendum on the future of East Timor.
	   They said the protest was the biggest since euphoric
celebrations were held to mark the awarding of the 1996 Nobel peace
prize to their Roman Catholic spiritual leader Bishop Carlos Belo.
	   Belo earlier asked the protesters to abandon plans to march
through the streets of Dili, fearing that it would only lead to a
violent confrontation with the Indonesian military.
	   In 1991 dozens were killed when troops opened fire on a protest
march.
	   On Wednesday demonstrators stayed safely on the university's
campus. They raised their fists in the air and sang rebel songs.
	   Some wore headbands with the word ``independence'' written on
them. Others briefly held up outlawed rebel flags. Some stood on
the roof of campus buildings and chanted anti-Indonesian slogans.
	   Indonesian troops invaded East Timor, a former Portuguese colony
in 1975, and annexed it the following year.
	   Since then the half-island territory has endured human rights
abuses while a guerrilla war rages between Indonesian forces and
separatist rebels.
	   On Tuesday in Jakarta, President B.J. Habibie signaled a
possible easing of Indonesia's tight control, saying he's ready to
grant special status to East Timor in exchange for peace in the
disputed territory.
	   In an interview with the British Broadcasting Corp., Habibie
also said he had signed a decree to release 10 East Timor rebels
jailed by Indonesia.
	   The new Indonesian leader emphasized, however, that special
status did not mean political autonomy, and that imprisoned East
Timorese rebel leader Xanana Gusmao would remain behind bars.
	   Indonesia regards Gusmao as a criminal, saying he has committed
violent acts in his fight against Indonesia. He is serving a
20-year prison term in Jakarta's Cipinang Prison.
	   Habibie replaced longtime autocrat Suharto as president last
month. Suharto, who ordered the 1975 invasion, steadfastly refused
to make any concessions toward East Timor.
	   And although the granting of special status for the territory
would be largely a symbolic gesture, Habibie's offer is being
regarded as a significant shift in policy.
	   Even so, protesters on Wednesday said it was not enough.
	   As well as a referendum, many at the Dili rally said they wanted
the immediate release of Gusmao.
	   Despite the size of the crowd, no uniformed military personnel
were seen, although organizers said that plainclothes intelligence
officers were mingling with the protesters.
	   Many said they felt freer to express their demands since Suharto
quit after 32 years of authoritarian rule.
	   Habibie has promised sweeping political reform, raising hopes
that a more democratic Indonesia will emerge.
	   ``This is the best opportunity we have had in years and we have
got to take advantage of it,'' said demonstrator Norberto
Gonsalves. 	   
</TEXT>
