<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turks and Caicos-Haitian Refugees,0409 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police fire at Haitian refugee sloop; 30 believed drowned
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS pvs, adding background. &QL; 
 &UR; By RAYMOND HAINEY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HAMILTON, Bermuda (AP) _ Authorities in the Turks and Caicos
Islands, who fired warning shots Monday at a crowded Haitian sloop,
were trying Wednesday to figure out whether their bullets or
panicky refugees capsized the boat. At least 30 refugees were
feared drowned.
	   Police questioned some of the 70 survivors Wednesday. John
Kelly, deputy governor of the British island chain 600 miles (950
kilometers) southeast of Florida, said Tuesday that he has asked
Bermuda to send Creole-speaking police to help with the interviews.
	   The bodies of six drowned Haitians were recovered Monday.
Rescuers searched without success Tuesday for 24 missing people,
Kelly said.
	   Bermudan police, he said, also would investigate unconfirmed
reports that police warning shots hit the sloop. Investigators were
expected to raise the sunken vessel to examine it for bullet holes.
	   He added, however, ``There is no evidence that the police
officers' shots hit the boat, and the six dead did not suffer
bullet wounds.''
	   Bermudan Premier Pamela Gordon said one scenario she heard
indicated the Haitians, who were crowded below deck, panicked when
they heard gunfire and rushed up to one side of the sloop, causing
it to capsize.
	   The Turks and Caicos, located between Cuba and the Bahamas, is a
popular tourist destination for snorkelers and deep-sea divers as
well as impoverished Haitians searching for work.
	   Firing warning shots, Kelly said, is a routine way for
authorities fighting illegal immigration to stop boats that do not
obey verbal orders to stop.
	   ``What the police try and do is to get aboard a boat and try and
see if it's carrying illegal migrants. If it is, it's escorted into
port and the illegals are flown back to Haiti,'' Kelly said.
	   It's not known how many Haitians flee their impoverished island
and make the journey north to Providenciales, the most populated of
the Turks and Caicos islands, which have about 15,000 citizens.
	   In 1996, the local government estimated Providenciales had 7,000
legal residents, including 1,000 Haitians, as well as 6,000 illegal
Haitians.
	   Resentment has grown among non-Haitian residents, who complain
that too much money has been diverted to support the Haitian
population.
</TEXT>
