w2361 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Israel-LaborUnion     06-10 0220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Labor Union </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Labor union boss re-elected in landslide
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) _ The leader of Israel's giant Histadrut
labor federation was re-elected in a landslide victory, the
federation announced Wednesday.
	   Amir Peretz was elected for a second term with over 70 percent
of the vote, while his rival Maxim Levy received only 22 percent.
	   Peretz has led over 600,000 Histradrut members in several
massive strikes over the past two years, mostly to protest the
government's proposal to roll back a pension agreement and its
plans to privatize state-owned corporations.
	   One of the peculiarities of the Israeli trade union movement is
that candidates for office run on a party ticket. Traditionally the
Histadrut was a stronghold of the Labor and left-wing parties, with
the right wing Likud in the opposition.
	   However Tuesday's election cut across traditional party lines.
Peretz, who is from the Labor party, was allied with the Likud.
	   Levy belongs to the Gesher party, which broke away from the
Likud some years ago, and he was allied with the left-wing Meretz
group.
	   Observers said Wednesday this realignment is a sign that the
party system is on the way out and candidates will in future be
elected on a personal basis, as in most other western countries.
 &UR; jk 	   
</TEXT>
