w2364 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Australia-DollarSlump     06-10 0309
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Dollar Slumps </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Aussie dollar continues falling towards 58 U.S. cents
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ The Australian and New Zealand dollars
both continued their free fall Wednesday, heading toward new
12-year lows.
	   In early afternoon trading the Aussie dollar hit a near 12-year
low of 58.30 U.S. cents. Dealers said the Australian dollar
appeared to be heading towards its intraday low of 57.10 U.S.
cents, seen in July 1986.
	   ``We're in uncharted waters,'' Scott Lewis, a foreign exchange
trader with IBJ Australia said. ``The only turnaround will be
profit taking on short positions from these big hedge funds but
there's no reason to suggest that's now.''
	   The Australian currency was also significantly lower against the
Japanese yen, down 1.5 yen from Tuesday's close. It was trading at
82.23-32 yen from 84.01-11.
	   In December 1996, the Australian dollar bought 82 U.S. cents. It
has fallen 28 percent since then.
	   Meanwhile, the New Zealand dollar fell to near 12-year lows
against the U.S. dollar, diving below 50 U.S. cents.
	   In morning trading the New Zealand dollar had fallen to 49.90
U.S. cents, its lowest level since October 1986. By early afternoon
it had climbed back through the 0.50 U.S. cent mark.
	   Currency dealers said they expected the Kiwi dollar, which has
fallen 4.9 percent in the last two weeks, to remain weak,
particularly as the Australian dollar was again under pressure.
	   The recent fall in the Kiwi dollar has also sparked a debate
about economics and the need to increase savings to combat New
Zealand's large current account deficit.
	   The deficit has been seen as one reason for the decline in the
kiwi dollar. Other reasons are a strong rise in the U.S. dollar as
the Asian financial crisis unfolded and the fact the Kiwi dollar
had been previously overvalued. 	   
</TEXT>
