w2368 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HongKong-Stocks     06-10 0361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Stocks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hong Kong shares plunge on weak yen, high local interest rates
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Rattled by the precipitous fall of the Japanese
yen, Hong Kong stocks dropped sharply Wednesday morning, with the
key index tumbling more than 4 percent.
	   Investors fear that the weak yen will force China to devalue its
currency to support exports and foreign investment inflows, leaving
the Hong Kong dollar's firm peg to the U.S. dollar in a precarious
position.
	   The yen's weakness also pushed local interest rates higher
Wednesday, sparking fears that there may be some speculative attack
on the Hong Kong currency, analysts said.
	   ``The yen is showing no signs of getting stronger, which is
putting further pressure on Hong Kong markets,'' said Vincent
Cheung, a trader at Sassoon Securities.
	   The Hang Seng Index, the market's key indicator of blue chips,
tumbled 4.2 percent, or 355.29 points, to 8,036.17 at the midday
close, dangerously close to the intraday low for the year of 7,909
points.
	   The volatile benchmark overnight Hong Kong Interbank Offered
Rate is quoted at 6.125 percent, up from 6.00 percent late Tuesday.
The three-month rate is at 9.25 percent, up from 8.5 percent late
Tuesday.
	   Banking system liquidity has tightened steadily as money has
flowed out of Hong Kong markets, and with markets here weak,
commercial banks have been unwilling long-term lenders.
	   The high interest rates are making it harder for companies to
borrow and eating into their profits.
	   Meanwhile, a senior government official said Wednesday that it
is ``not particularly hopeful interest rates will come down anytime
soon'' as Hong Kong's financial markets continue to be battered by
external factors.
	   Speaking at a conference on Asia's financial turmoil, Secretary
for Financial Services Rafael Hui said there are no short-term
solutions to revive Hong Kong's shrinking economy, such as spending
its way out of the macroeconomic difficulty.
	   Hui reiterated his support for the Hong Kong dollar peg, noting
that in the current environment, ``more so than ever, it makes even
less sense to abandon the system.'' 	   
</TEXT>
