<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Myanmar </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Myanmar to buy crude oil from Malaysia
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Myanmar is buying crude oil worth
dlrs 80 million from Malaysia and an agreement on payment terms is
expected Wednesday, Malaysia's national news agency reported.
	   The Malaysian national oil company Petronas will supply the
crude, Myanmar's visiting Minister of Commerce Maj. Gen. Kyaw Than
said. Officials of both countries were discussing the payment
mechanism, he said.
	   ``We have completed discussions except for the payment terms and
mechanism'' to buy four million barrels of crude, Bernama news
agency quoted him as saying Tuesday. Wednesday's agreement will be
signed with Petronas.
	   Malaysia and Myanmar on Tuesday signed an agreement to expand
trade and enhance economic and industrial cooperation.
	   The governments had agreed to assist private enterprises boost
trade between the two nations, said Malaysia's international trade
and industry minister, Rafidah Aziz.
	   The sale of crude is expected help Myanmar meet a gasoline
shortage. 	   
</TEXT>
