w2373 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Australia-Indonesia     06-10 0283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Indonesia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Australia fears Indonesian economy worsening
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) _ Australian foreign affairs officials
fear that Indonesia's economy is deteriorating, saying Wednesday
that they expect a fifth of all Indonesian workers to be unemployed
by year's end.
	   Two days before the Indonesian crisis forced the resignation of
President Suharto, Foreign Minister Alexander Downer warned that a
handover of power to Vice President B.J Habibie would achieve
little.
	   The minister representing Downer in the Senate, Robert Hill,
said Wednesday that Downer was merely warning that Indonesia needed
to do more than change leaders, and was not casting aspersions on
Habibie.
	   ``Indonesia needed more than a simple substitution, and more
than a simple substitution has occurred,'' Hill told the committee.
	   Nick Warner, head of the Department of Foreign Affairs and
Trade's South Asia and Southeast Asia section, denied relations
with Indonesia had suffered as a result of the change of leader.
	   ``Since Dr. Habibie took over the presidency we have developed a
very good, close, sensible working relationship with him and with
his government,'' Warner said. ``I think he thinks well and
positively of Australia.''
	   However, Warner gave a very bleak assessment of the outlook for
the Indonesian economy.
	   ``All the macro-economic indicators for Indonesia are of course
looking pretty bad and much worse now than they were say three,
four or five months ago,'' Warner said.
	   ``We're looking at a contraction in the economy perhaps of the
order of 10 percent, or maybe more, unemployment perhaps rising to
over 20 percent by the end of the year.'' 	   
</TEXT>
