<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-US Roundup, 2nd Add,0365 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLANTA: Thomson (5-6).
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Angels 10, Diamondbacks 8 &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   In Phoenix, Cecil Fielder hit a grand slam and had six RBIs and
Darin Erstad went 5-for-5 and drove in the go-ahead run as Anaheim
won its ninth straight.
	   Fielder's third-inning homer was the first grand slam at Bank
One Ballpark. Yamil Benitez added one of his own in the bottom of
the inning _ the sixth time two teams have hit grand slams in the
same inning.
	   Chuck Finley (7-2) won his third straight despite allowing six
runs, five walks and five hits in five innings. Troy Percival
pitched the ninth for his 18th save.
 &UR; Giants 7, Mariners 6 &QC; 
	   In San Francisco, the Giants extended the majors' longest
winning streak this season to 11 games, getting a three-run homer
from J.T. Snow.
	   Seattle hit four homers, including Ken Griffey Jr.'s AL-leading
25th, to boost its major league-leading total to 104. But the
Mariners still lost for the eighth time in nine games.
	   John Johnstone (2-2) pitched 1 2-3 innings of relief for the
victory. Robb Nen got the final three outs for his NL-leading 19th
save.
 &UR; Dodgers 5, Athletics 1 &QC; 
	   In Los Angeles, Chan Ho Park pitched eight strong innings and
the Dodgers took advantage of some shoddy Oakland fielding.
	   Park (5-3), who retired the first 10 batters, scattered six hits
while walking none and striking out six.
	   The Dodgers, who have won five of their last seven games, scored
three unearned runs with two outs in the first off Jimmy Haynes
(4-3) thanks to a passed ball and throwing error by Oakland catcher
Mike Macfarlane.
 &UR; Padres 5, Reds 1 &QC; 
	   In San Diego, Greg Vaughn hit a grand slam and Andy Ashby came
within two outs of his fourth straight complete game as the Padres
beat the Cincinnati Reds 5-1 Tuesday night.
	   Ashby (8-4) gave up eight hits, tied his career high with 11
strikeouts and didn't walk a batter before leaving with two men on
in the ninth. Trevor Hoffman struck out the last two batters for
his 18th save this season and 26th in a row overall.
	   Vaughn hit his 22nd homer of the season and fourth career grand
slam with two out in the seventh off Brett Tomko (5-5).
</TEXT>
