<HEADER>
w2381 &Cx1f; wstm-
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-ShrinkingEconom     06-10 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Shrinking Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
More bad news for Japan _ GDP stats may confirm recession fears
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CHESTER DAWSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The official announcement hasn't been made yet, and
optimists are still holding out hope. But for the first time in
more than two decades, Japan's economy may be looking at its first
year of negative growth.
	   The verdict is to come Friday, when the Economic Planning Agency
will release Japan's quarterly gross domestic product figures for
January-March 1998.
	   The figures, covering the final quarter of Japan's 1997 fiscal
year, are widely expected to confirm fears that growth shrank for
two consecutive quarters, the standard definition for an economy in
full-blown recession.
	   If they do, it will be Japan's third dip into recession this
decade and will mean the first year of overall contraction of the
economy since fiscal 1974.
	   ``It has to be pretty embarrassing because Japan had such a
great reputation in the 1980s, but has pretty much lost it,'' said
Peter Morgan, chief economist at HSBC Securities Japan Ltd.
	   Morgan said he expects a 0.1 percent decline in the
January-March quarter-on-quarter GDP.
	   In March, the Economic Planning Agency said Japan's GDP for the
October-December quarter of 1997 fell 0.2 percent.
	   That's a far cry from Japan's boom years in the 1980s, when
Americans saw Tokyo as an economic superpower able to snatch up
landmark buildings such as Rockefeller Center in a single bound.
Japanese business practices became vogue. America was playing
catch-up.
	   No more.
	   Japan's jobless rolls have jumped to a postwar high of 4.1
percent, Japanese corporate earnings have hit the skids and the
Tokyo stock market trades at less than half its peak value in 1989.
	   Even the mighty yen has taken a spill, falling to a seven-year
low of 140 yen to the dollar this week. Now, the infamous dlrs 10
cup of premium coffee in Tokyo's finer hotels can be bought for a
mere dlrs 6.
	   Some economists hold out the possibility of an improvement in
the figures to be released Friday.
	   But even they admit that narrowly averting the official criteria
for a recession won't solve Japan's economic woes.
	   ``Even if we do get a recovery, it will be a jobless recovery,''
said Yasushi Okada, an economist in the Tokyo office of Credit
Suisse First Boston.
	   Okada, who believes the GDP may have bounced back as much as 0.2
percent in the first quarter of the year, said he expects Japan's
unemployment rate to rise as high as 5 percent by next year.
	   The reasons for Japan's sluggishness are many and complex.
	   Rigid corporate business practices such as lifetime employment
and dependence on parent banks for capital, for example, have
hampered innovation, hurt efficiency and slowed restructuring
efforts.
	   Management philosophies aside, analysts point to a clear policy
blunder as having sowed the seeds for the current macroeconomic
slowdown.
	   They blame Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto and the
budget-conscious Finance Ministry for teaming up to pass a tax
increase that took effect April 1 last year.
	   Raising Japan's national sales tax to 5 percent from 3 percent
had a chilling effect on consumer spending, which accounts for
about two-thirds of the country's GDP.
	   Penny-pinching Japanese consumers became even more skittish amid
a string of high-profile bankruptcies of financial institutions in
recent months.
	   Japan's banking system, meanwhile, is awash in bad loans from
the collapse of a real estate price bubble in the late 1980s. And
much of Asia is embroiled in a financial crisis that has crimped
demand for Japanese exports and soured many of Japan's investments
in the region.
	   Some say the worst may be over, however.
	   Ron Bevacqua, an economist at Merrill Lynch Japan Inc., said
that barring another external shock like the Asian crisis or a rash
of new bank failures, consumer spending in Japan should begin to
pick up this summer.
	   The economy will also get a big boost from a 16.7 trillion yen
(dlrs 119 billion) public works-heavy spending package which was
approved by Japan's Cabinet in April, Bevacqua said.
	   Parliament is expected to pass the package later this month.
	   Others, such as HSBC's Morgan, worry that without fresh
government stimulus initiatives such as a sizable permanent income
tax cut, growth could well remain sluggish _ or go negative.
	   Japan's trade minister, Mitsuo Horiuchi, echoed these sentiments
Wednesday when he called for ``one more push'' to put the economy
back on track for recovery.
	   Economic Planning Agency head Koji Omi has studiously avoided
mentioning the word recession, taking pains to highlight the few
bright spots in the economy.
	   He may skirt around the ``r-word'' when the latest statistics
come out on Friday as well.
	   Two consecutive quarters, or six straight months, of negative
growth is almost universally accepted as the threshold for
recession. But Japan reserves formal judgment on this for a panel
of experts assembled by the Economic Planning Agency.
	   Few private economists pay that much heed.
	   ``The authorities in general tend to be quite behind, especially
in denoting the direction of the economy,'' said economist
Bevacqua. 	   
</TEXT>
