<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Oil Loans </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Head of Japanese state-run oil company to resign for bad loans
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The president of a Japanese state-run firm that
finances oil exploration will resign after the company disclosed
massive unrecoverable loans, media reported Wednesday.
	   Kunio Komatsu offered Tuesday to step down as head of the Japan
National Oil Corp. to take responsibility for the losses, which
total more than 1.4 trillion yen (dlrs 10 billion), or more than
the company's annual revenues, the reports said.
	   Calls to Japan National Oil to confirm the reports went
unanswered.
	   The Ministry of International Trade and Industry, which oversees
Japan National Oil, will appoint new executives to restructure the
company, according to the reports.
	   Japan National Oil is the latest in a series of bad loan
debacles that have called into question the stewardship of the
nation's once vaunted bureaucrats over Japan's financial system.
	   With the taxpayers sure to foot the cleanup, calls will likely
intensify for Japan to privatize such state-run finance companies.
	   Japan National Oil was started in 1967 to promote domestic oil
exploration by providing inexpensive capital to private companies.
The government shouldered the risk by not obligating the companies
to repay the loans if no oil was found.
	   Some of the unrecoverable loans also went into copper
exploration. None of the funded projects succeeded.
 &UR; (mef)
</TEXT>
