<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Nepotism </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Ruling party may hear complaints of nepotism
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Leaders of Malaysia's ruling party
are likely to hear about cases of alleged nepotism in handing out
contracts for huge government projects, a newspaper reported
Wednesday.
	   Data on instances of nepotism has been collected and will be
presented at next week's United Malays National Organization
general assembly, Ahmad Zahid Hamidi, the party's youth wing chief,
was quoted as saying by Star daily.
	   A state government minister had challenged Zahid to release
details of the alleged nepotism, the daily said.
	   Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad has said that party officials
were free to raise issues of corruption and nepotism at the June
19-21 meeting.
	   The general assembly is expected to focus on the national
economic crisis, Mahathir told reporters on Tuesday.
	   ``I'm quite sure they (the delegates) are going to talk about
the economic problems because some of them are affected by the
economic downturn,'' Mahathir said.
	   He rejected the opposition's call for talks with the government
on the current economic problems. ``We don't want to politicize
this,'' Mahathir said. 	   
</TEXT>
