<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Cyclone,0228 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Army supervises rescue work after cyclone leaves 130 dead in India
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BOMBAY, India (AP) _ Relief workers distributed food and
searched for bodies in the debris of smashed homes after a cyclone
tore through western India, killing 130 people and leaving hundreds
of thousands homeless, officials said Wednesday.
	   Some 2,500 soldiers were helping local authorities distribute
supplies in remote areas of Gujarat state after Tuesday's cyclone.
State officials said the death toll could increase as aid workers
reach remote villages.
	   Relief workers handed out supplies of wheat, potatoes and
kerosene to residents of Bhuj, Jamnagar and Porbunder districts,
450 kilometers (280 miles) northwest of Bombay, where the cyclone
first struck land.
	   ``Medical teams have been sent out to contain any epidemic that
might break out,'' said R.M. Joshi, a government official at the
state control center.
	   The cyclone, India's worst in 25 years, uprooted trees,
electricity poles and cut off road and telecommunication links.
	   Thousands of people spent the night in the streets after walls
and roofs of mud-and-thatch houses collapsed. Authorities had moved
20,000 people to safety before the cyclone struck.
	   Rainfall has been reported in some places following the cyclone,
which packed wind speeds of up to 100 kph (65 mph).
</TEXT>
