w2404 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-AirlineProt     06-10 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Airline Protest </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesian airline workers protest against Suharto contracts
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos Staffing

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ About 500 employees from Indonesia's
state-owned flag carrier Garuda Indonesia, including pilots and
cabin crew, demonstrated outside the airline's headquarters
Wednesday.
	   They demanded it end contracts linked to the family of
ex-President Suharto and said they were worried that cash-strapped
Garuda was planning big layoffs.
	   As many as 2,000 ground staff from Jakarta's Sukarno Hatta
Airport are set to join the demonstrators during the day,
protesters said.
	   Flights were not expected to be disrupted, an airline spokesman
said.
	   The demonstrators said they wanted a review of contracts held by
PT Angkasa Buana Wisesa which handles cargo for Garuda. Angkasa
Buana is owned by Cardig Air, which is part of Suharto's middle son
Bambang Trihatmodjo's Bimantara Group.
	   The employees are also calling for the review of a ground
equipment contract granted to Gapura, a unit of Angkasa Buana.
	   The calls are the latest examples of a growing backlash against
companies perceived to have benefited from collusion, nepotism and
corruption during the Suharto years.
	   Suharto stepped down as president on May 21 following protests
and riots, ending 32-years of authoritarian rule.
	   Critics say he and his family amassed billions of dollars and
built huge empires by abusing their power and position.
	   Some have called for the state to seize Suharto's assets and use
them to help Indonesia overcome its worst economic crisis in
decades.
	   The government of new President B.J. Habibie is planning a broad
inquiry into corruption during the Suharto era and has already
ended or placed under review many state contracts with companies
linked to the Suharto clan.
	   The Garuda employees said they are also demonstrating against
unconfirmed claims that the airline is to cut 4,000 jobs at the
struggling state-owned airline.
	   Garuda, like Indonesia's other airlines, is crippled by huge
foreign debt that has been worsened by a huge drop in the value of
the rupiah against the dollar.
	   Most of Garuda's revenues are in rupiah while its debt is
predominately in dollars.
	   According to State Enterprises Minister Tanri Abeng, it needs to
be restructured ``immediately'' to avoid isolation from the
international air network.
	   Some 50 percent of the company's dlrs 200 million foreign debt
is past due and Tanri said earlier this week that the airline's
liquidity isn't enough to pay for operations.
	   He also said Garuda would invite either foreign or domestic
investors to take a stake in the company, noting that the
government wasn't in a position to inject capital.
	   A company spokesman said he didn't know of any plans to cut
4,000 jobs.
	   Last week, Indonesia's third largest airline, Sempati, stopped
operating after posting big losses. 	   
</TEXT>
