w2419 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AsianMarkets     06-10 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Asian Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Asian markets continue slide on weak yen
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ A weaker Japanese yen _ bad news for many Asian
economies _ pushed down regional stock prices and currencies
Wednesday, with share prices in Thailand plummeting to 11-year
lows.
	   Many investors were reluctant to bid up stocks and currencies
ahead of a meeting of finance officials from the Group of Seven
industrialized nations scheduled to open in Paris later Wednesday.
	   ``No one knows what will come out of the G-7 deputy's meeting
and people are nervous,'' said Yasuhisa Morikuni, assistant vice
president at Bank of America.
	   The unease stems from concern the yen could fall further against
the dollar if officials attending the G-7 meeting do not issue a
statement pledging to support the battered Japanese currency.
	   The yen fell to seven-year lows against the dollar this week,
making the price of Japanese exports cheaper in foreign markets.
Many investors worry that the drop in the yen will force Japan's
Asian neighbors to devalue their currencies to remain competitive.
	   The dollar rose against the yen in mid-afternoon Tokyo trading.
It bought 140.98 yen, up 0.62 yen from late Tuesday in Tokyo and
above its late New York level of 140.30 yen overnight.
	   Meanwhile, the U.S. dollar broke through key psychological
levels against the Singapore dollar, the Thai baht and the
Indonesian rupiah in early trading.
	   The Singapore dollar broke through the 1.72 level against the
greenback for the first time since early February. In morning
trading, the U.S. currency was quoted at a four-month high of
1.7215 Singapore dollars, up from 1.7075 late on Tuesday.
	   Singapore's benchmark Straits Times Industrial Index breached a
key support level of 1,100 points. It was down 2.7 percent to close
at 1,091.76 points as of the midday close.
	   In Bangkok, the benchmark stock index dropped below 300 points
for the first time in 11 years. The baht fell through the key
support of 43.00 baht to the dollar level, as worries grew over the
health of Thai financial institutions.
	   The Stock Exchange of Thailand index dropped to a low of 299.89
points in morning trading, although it quickly rebounded back over
the 300-point mark. In late morning, the index was at 300.37
points, down 7.88 points.
	   Dealers attributed the decline to worries over the fate of Thai
financial institutions. Although the Thai central bank has
announced new rules to encourage institutions to restructure
problem loans, few have begun to do so, analysts said.
	   In Jakarta, the rupiah fell through a key resistance level early
Wednesday falling to 12,000 to the dollar, a level not seen since
before former president Suharto resigned last month.
	   Domestic demand for dollars kept continued pressure on the
rupiah, driving it further south, dealers said.
	   In Hong Kong, the yen pushed up interest rates, which further
hurt market sentiment and sparked fears that there may be some
speculative attack on the Hong Kong currency, analyst said.
	   The key Hang Seng Index tumbled 4.2 percent, or 355.29 points,
to 8,036.17 at the midday close, near the intraday low for the year
of 7,909 points.
	   The volatile benchmark overnight Hong Kong Interbank Offered
Rate was quoted at 6.125 percent, up from 6.00 percent late
Tuesday. The three-month rate was at 9.25 percent, up from 8.5
percent late Tuesday.
	   ``The yen is showing no signs of getting stronger, which is
putting further pressure on Hong Kong markets,'' said Vincent
Cheung, a trader at Sassoon Securities.
	   A senior government official said Wednesday that it is ``not
particularly hopeful interest rates will come down anytime soon''
as Hong Kong's financial markets continue to be battered by
external factors.
	   But Secretary for Financial Services reiterated his support for
the Hong Kong dollar peg, noting that in the current environment,
``more so than ever, it makes even less sense to abandon the
system.''
	   In Tokyo, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 190.91 points,
or 1.23 percent, closing at 15,339.26.
	   Share prices in Jakarta and Kuala Lumpur also fell in morning
trading. 	   
</TEXT>
