</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bangladesh-Long March,0342 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
More people join long march in Bangladesh
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo DHA101-2 &QL; 
 &UR; By OSMAN GHANI MANSOOR &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CHITTAGONG, Bangladesh (AP) _ Thousands of protesters from all
over Bangladesh were converging Wednesday on a southern town for an
anti-government rally.
	   The protesters _ most traveling by bus despite calling their
campaign the ``long march'' _ say a peace accord the government
signed last year with rebels from the Buddhist Chakma tribe gives
the Chakmas too much local power at the expense of Muslim settlers
from the north.
	   Opponents of the accord plan to hold a rally later Wednesday in
Khagrachari, a Chakma stronghold 400 kilometers (250 miles) south
of the capital, Dhaka. Chakma rebels, who have surrendered their
arms in exchange for local autonomy, had fought the government for
20 years. The violence left more than 20,000 people, mostly
Muslims, dead.
	   A stream of up to 50,000 protesters set off Tuesday from Dhaka
and had reached the halfway point of their journey by midmorning
Wednesday. The convoy, led by former Prime Minister Khaleda Zia,
was delayed nine hours on the outskirts of Dhaka on Tuesday by a
road block of abandoned trucks set up by supporters of Prime
Minister Sheikh Hasina.
	   A second stream of what organizers said were 200,000 people set
off Wednesday from Chittagong, 95 kilometers (60 miles) north of
Khagrachari. Zia supporters from all over the country had gathered
at the two starting points Tuesday.
	   Pro- and anti-government protesters fought in Chittagong on
Tuesday, leaving 60 injured and scores of trucks and shops damaged,
police said.
	   Protesters from both sides also held marches in Khagrachari
overnight, but did not clash.
	   The protest is seen as a test of strength for Zia, who since
losing power two years ago has called almost daily strikes, which
often erupt into violence.
	   Business leaders condemned the latest protest, fearing further
economic losses as shops shut down and vehicles stayed off the
roads.
</TEXT>
