w2426 &Cx1f; wstm-
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru   06-10 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. dollar rises, Tokyo stocks finish lower
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with closing Nikkei, mid-afternoon dollar and bond
prices &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar rose against the yen Wednesday in
Tokyo as traders awaited the outcome of a meeting of Group of Seven
finance officials later in the day. Tokyo stocks finished lower in
light trading.
	   In mid-afternoon trading, the dollar bought 140.98 yen, up 0.62
yen from late Tuesday in Tokyo and above its late New York level of
140.30 yen overnight.
	   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
fell 190.91 points, or 1.23 percent, closing at 15,339.26. On
Tuesday, the average rose 235.46 points, or 1.52 percent.
	   The dollar advanced on buying amid speculation that deputy
finance ministers of the G-7 industrialized nations will not issue
a statement in support of the yen after their meeting in Paris.
	   Japanese officials have recently warned of the yen's excessive
weakening against the dollar, suggesting possible yen-buying
intervention. Finance Minister Hikaru Matsunaga has hinted that the
G-7 officials might touch on the recent exchange market movement.
	   Traders said they will keep watching the G-7 meeting and
congressional testimony by U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan, also later Wednesday.
	   The U.S. currency had gained value steadily against the yen in
recent weeks as investors shifted more and more funds out of
Japan's sagging markets and into the robust U.S. economy.
	   Concerns over Japan's economy drove the dollar to a new
seven-year high of 141.35 yen on Tuesday.
	   Such worries also weighed on domestic prices, offsetting
optimism the stronger dollar would boost the earnings of Japanese
exporters.
	   On the stock market, traders said continued weakness in bank
issues on selling from foreign investors dampened sentiment.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section shed 10.08 points, or 0.83 percent, to 1,198.60. The
TOPIX closed up 10.32 points, or 0.86 percent, the day before.
	   Analysts said foreign investors will likely keep selling their
Japanese holdings if the yen keeps weakening. That's because a
weaker yen erodes the dollar value of Japanese stocks.
	   ``The weak yen is good for exporters, but our concern is that it
will hurt the sentiment of foreign investors,'' said Tsuyoshi
Nomaguchi, a strategist at Daiwa Securities Co.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond fell to 1.200 percent from Tuesday's finish of
1.210 percent, driving its price higher to 112.02 yen from 111.96
yen. 	   
</TEXT>
