<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Peace Talks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government and rebels blame each other for stalled peace talks
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Peace talks between Cambodian
government troops and resistance forces broke off Wednesday with
both sides blaming each other for the deadlock.
	   Gen. Hun Phoeung, chief negotiator for resistance forces loyal
to deposed co-Prime Minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh, said the
stalemate was caused by the government's refusal to formalize a
ceasefire agreement and guarantee amnesty for rebel commanders.
	   Ranariddh was deposed last July in a bloody coup d'etat led by
co-Prime Minister Hun Sen. Ranariddh has returned to Cambodia to
compete in elections scheduled for July.
	   Several hundred of his troops, however, have been holed up along
the border with Thailand for months fending off attacks by Hun
Sen's army.
	   They are led by Gen. Nhek Bunchhay, who was convicted in a Hun
Sen-controlled court earlier this year of weapons smuggling and
attempting to overthrow the government, in a trial most observers
said was politically motivated.
	   Hun Sen's negotiators are demanding talks move immediately to
the reintegration of the rebels into the Cambodian army.
	   ``They only talked about integration which we can not accept
because we don't feel we will have a guarantee since we have been
attacked,'' Hun Phoeung said.
	   ``We proposed a joint ceasefire be signed before reaching an
integration of forces, but they disagreed,'' he said.
	   Gen. Dam Vuthy, chief negotiator for the Phnom Penh government,
accused the resistance group of intentionally stalling to buy time.
	   ``They put forth various conditions in a bid to delay or to
refuse to integrate into Royal Cambodia Armed Forces,'' Dam Vuthy
told reporters.
	   He warned that by sticking to their demands for having a joint
cease fire signed and amnesty for their commanders, resistance
forces might not be able to integrate in time for July's elections.
	   ``We hope they move faster for their own sake, not ours, so they
can regain full rights,'' Dam Vuthy said, adding that no date has
been scheduled for resumption of talks.
</TEXT>
