w2443 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Philippines-LandConve 1stLd-Writethru   06-10 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Land Conversion, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Militant Filipino farmers storm golf course to protest land
</HEADLINE>
conversion
 &UR; Eds: Corrects date in 9th graf to December 1997 sted of 1977.
 &UR; AP Photo Available
 &UR; By CLARO CORTES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ About 200 militant farmers stormed a
government-operated golf course in Manila on Wednesday and laid
rice seedlings on the 10th hole to protest the 10th anniversary of
the country's land reform program.
	   The members of the Alliance of Nationalist Farmers criticized
the program for allowing land owners to convert land into
industrial estates, golf courses or housing developments to avoid
distributing it to landless farmers.
	   ``We hope that someday we will no longer clear mountains to make
farms,'' said rally leader Pablo Rosales. ``We can always turn golf
courses into useful land planted with crops.''
	   The farmers intended to dig holes in the green to plant the rice
but later agreed to a ``ceremonial planting'' in which they laid
the seedlings in rows on the ground after frantic security guards
pleaded with them not to damage the course.
	   Several golfers had to skirt the 10th hole during the three-hour
protest.
	   Many of the farmers say they come from farms being converted
into golf courses and housing developments.
	   ``We are feeling the hardship caused by land conversion while
foreigners and capitalists take advantage of our land,'' said Ed
Mora, another alliance leader.
	   The protesters had originally intended to target a private golf
course but decided against it because they are heavily guarded,
with high fences.
	   The Department of Agrarian Reform says about 56,168 hectares
(138,734 acres) of farm land were legally converted from 1988 to
December 1977.
	   The Philippine Peasant Institute, however, says the figure is
closer to 200,000 hectares (494,000 acres), most of which was
illegally converted.
	   President-elect Joseph Estrada said Tuesday he may suspend all
conversion of agricultural land until his administration crafts a
national land use policy.
	   Estrada, who takes office June 30, said a comprehensive land use
program will be one of the priorities of his first 100 days in
office.
	   The land reform program's goal was to purchase and distribute
4.29 million hectares (10.6 million acres) of land to landless
farmers. So far only 2.72 million hectares (6.7 million acres) have
been distributed, and the program has been extended until the year
2004.
</TEXT>
