r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Malaysia-OfficialChar     06-10 0271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Official Charged </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Official charged with corruption pleads not guilty
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo KL101

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ A top Malaysian politician
acquitted on currency violations by an Australia court pleaded not
guilty Wednesday to corruption charges at home.
	   Former chief minister of the central state of Selangor, Muhammad
Taib, appeared calm when the charge against him was read out, the
national news agency Bernama reported. His wife, Rohani Asnan, and
other family members were also present in court.
	   Muhammad, 52, a prominent member of Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad's United Malays National Organization party, is charged
under the Prevention of Corruption Act for not declaring his
assets. If convicted, he could face one year in jail and a 2,000
ringgit (dlrs 500) fine.
	   On May 29, a court in Brisbane declared him innocent after a
trial for violating Australian laws by carrying more than a million
dollars in foreign currency in his hand luggage during a trip to
Australia in December 1996.
	   Muhammad said he was not aware that he had to declare any cash
in excess of U.S. dlrs 3,100 (5,000 Australian dollars) while
traveling in the country.
	   At the time, he was chief minister of Selangor. He resigned his
post and has also taken leave from his position of vice president
of UMNO.
	   But during the trial he revealed he had purchased a farm, houses
and several pieces of land valued in Australia and New Zealand
under the name of his wife.
	   That led to demands from the opposition and the ruling party to
investigate the former chief minister.
</TEXT>
