w2456 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HongKong-Tung     06-10 0339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Tung </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hong Kong's leader rules out change in currency peg
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo Available &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Hong Kong's Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa
insisted Wednesday the government will keep its 14-year currency
peg to the U.S. dollar, despite increasing calls for action to help
Hong Kong fight a liquidity crunch.
	   Speaking at a conference on Asia's financial crisis, Tung said
the government won't alter the currency's peg to ease a liquidity
shortage in the local banking system.
	   The news pushed the benchmark three-month interest rate up to
10.375 percent in early afternoon, up from 9.25 percent early
Wednesday. The one-month rate soared to 11.0 percent from 9.625
percent.
	   Hong Kong's benchmark Hang Seng Index opened the afternoon
session down 5 percent and then slipped to its lowest level so far
this year, as interbank interest rates surged following Tung's
comments.
	   The index lost 423.41 points, or 5 percent, to 7,968.05 when the
afternoon session opened, then slipped to as low as 7,906.39, its
lowest level in more than three years.
	   Tung said floating the currency would ``cause speculative
attacks against the Hong Kong dollar and increase interest rates.''
	   ``The government will maintain Hong Kong's long-held tradition
of fiscal prudence,'' Tung said.
	   Tung said that recent pressure on the territory's currency was
due to the weakness of the Japanese yen.
	   Investors in the region fear that the weak yen will force China
to devalue its currency to support exports and foreign investments,
leaving the Hong Kong dollar's firm peg to the U.S. dollar in a
precarious position.
	   The devaluation of the two currencies will likely bring more
chaos to the already weakened financial markets in the region.
	   Locally, the Hong Kong government is under increasing pressure
to delink the Hong Kong currency as interest rates remain at high
levels to defend the Hong Kong dollar, making borrowing extremely
difficult for local companies and eating into their profits. 	   
</TEXT>
