w2466 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-Fire 1stLd-Writethru   06-10 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Fire, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rescuers find 25 dead in burned shopping center, more victims
</HEADLINE>
feared
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS; UPDATES with 25 bodies found; ADDS quotes, details
 &UR; AP Photos staffing
 &UR; By ALI KOTARUMALOS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PALEMBANG, Indonesia (AP) _ Rescuers searching a burned down
shopping center and movie theater complex Wednesday said they had
recovered a total of 25 bodies, but feared more dead were still
inside.
	   Fire swept through the Megahira shopping center Monday night.
	   Parts of the six-story building were smouldering two days later,
hampering the search for victims.
	   Witnesses said stores in the center had been shut for several
hours when the fire started.
	   Police said at least 54 people were known to have been in three
movie theaters inside. Dozens more were playing pool in an adjacent
amusement center.
	   ``Many victims are still inside,'' police chief Brig. Gen. Dedde
Janrigadi was quoted as saying by the Sumatra Espres newspaper.
	   The cause of the fire has not been established, he said.
	   Police spokesman Lt. Col. Sardjo Sadjat said 19 people were
injured, 14 of them treated in hospitals in the city, 460
kilometers (285 miles) northwest of Jakarta.
	   Survivors said panic broke out when the building was engulfed in
smoke. None said they saw any flames.
	   One man told the newspaper Republika that people ``trampled on
one another'' to get out.
	   Others alleged that fire exits had been locked by security
guards. Police said they were investigating that claim.
	   Some survivors climbed down ropes holding a window washing
platform on the outside of the building. Others went onto the roof
and jumped to the top of a neighboring building.
	   ``I think no one can survive,'' said Djaieni, a fire department
official.
	   Most of the bodies were badly charred. Only two had been
identified. Distraught relatives of missing moviegoers crowded
around the fire site as rescuers, their faces covered by cloths,
carried out human remains.
	   ``My son was at the movies with his girlfriend. He never came
home,'' said one woman who identified herself by the single name,
Daya.
	   The shopping center, in Palembang on the island of Sumatra, was
built in 1976. It was rebuilt after fire destroyed much of it in
1985, when one firefighter was killed.
	   Last month several shopping malls were set afire during riots in
the capital, Jakarta. Hundreds of people died, mostly looters
trapped inside.
</TEXT>
