w2477 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-China-BusinessSchool     06-10 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Business School </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Wharton School to train senior Chinese officials
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By RENEE SCHOOF &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ The Wharton School plans to begin training senior
Chinese government and state enterprise officials how to compete in
the market economy, the school said Wednesday.
	   President Jiang Zemin announced the program, which will begin in
September, when he visited the Wharton School at the University of
Pennsylvania last October.
	   Premier Zhu Rongji has said China must turn around its
debt-ridden state sector in the next three years in order to stem
heavy losses, put millions of laid-off workers back to work and
keep the economy growing.
	   China's success in reforming state companies ``is going to
depend on economic growth, development of firms and markets in
China, the expansion of the economy and the ability of state-owned
firms to transform themselves and be able to compete,'' said
Stephen J. Kobrin, a professor of multinational management who will
teach some of the courses in Beijing.
	   ``We're not arrogant enough to believe that we can solve the
problem through Wharton faculty coming to China. But we do think
they're important programs and that they focus directly on what the
market economy is,'' he said.
	   Barbara Kahn, a professor of marketing, said her courses would
cover keeping customers satisfied over the long term, developing
global brand names and market expansion strategies.
	   ``It seems the market here is not customer focused. That's not
easy to change,'' Ms. Kahn said.
	   A group of officials from southeastern Jiangsu province, one of
China's most affluent regions near Shanghai, will spend six weeks
at Wharton, in Philadephia, next fall studying business strategy,
marketing, finance, technology and management, they said.
	   The U.S. business school also plans to start training young
Chinese mangers at joint ventures in Shanghai, China's financial
and industrial center, beginning next summer.
	   Wharton's program is helped by its ties with President Jiang and
with the National School of Administration and Qinghua University,
China's leading engineering and business school.
	   Other universities from the United States and other countries
also have set up joint programs to train Chinese MBAs.
	   At a professional training seminar held by the Australian Trade
Commission in Beijing this week, Australian Ambassador Ric Smith
said China needs many well-trained managers for the government's
twin programs of reforming the state sector and streamlining the
bureaucracy.
	   Maurine Chong, Australia's senior trade commissioner in Beijing,
said Australian institutions also plan to cooperate with the
Ministry of Personnel and the State Economic and Trade Commission
to train Chinese managers. 	   
</TEXT>
