<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Cyclone, 1st Ld-Writethru,0478 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Death toll in cyclone-hit India climbs to 205
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RAISES death toll from 130 to 205, injured from 400 to 1,200;
ADDS details, storms in Pakistan. ADDS byline. No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; By RAMOLA TALWAR &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BOMBAY, India (AP) _ Relief workers distributed food and
searched for bodies in the debris of smashed homes after a cyclone
tore through western India, killing 205 people, injuring 1,200 and
leaving hundreds of thousands homeless, officials said Wednesday.
	   The toll could rise, as many people remain missing and relief
workers have yet to reach some remote villages.
	   The death toll was highest in Kutch district, where a 12-foot
(four-meter) tidal wave flooded low-lying areas near Kandla port,
290 kilometers (180 miles) northwest of Bombay.
	   As many as 140 people, including fishermen and port workers,
drowned or were swept into the Arabian Sea, government officials
said. Nearly 125 people have been listed as missing and officials
fear the casualty figure could reach 200 in Kutch alone.
	   The other deaths and injuries were mainly caused by lightning
and collapsing houses in the rural districts of Junagadh, Bhuj,
Valsad and Jamnagar near Porbunder, the town where the storm first
struck land, 450 kilometers (280 miles) northwest of Bombay.
	   Nearly 800 workers living in makeshift tin-roofed camps at the
Reliance refinery project at Jamnagar were injured by flying
debris. Officials said 150 of them were hospitalized in a nearby
town. The district reported 35 casualties.
	   Some 2,500 soldiers were called in to help restore
communications and distribute supplies in remote areas of Gujarat
state after Tuesday's cyclone.
	   Relief workers handed out wheat, potatoes and kerosene to
residents of Bhuj, Jamnagar and Porbunder.
	   ``Medical teams have been sent out to contain any epidemic that
might break out,'' said R.M. Joshi, a government official at the
state control center.
	   The cyclone, India's worst in 25 years, uprooted trees,
electricity poles and cut off road and telecommunication links.
	   The worst affected districts of Kutch, Jamnagar and Porbunder
were without electricity for the second day Wednesday.
	   Thousands of people spent the night in the streets after walls
and roofs of mud-and-thatch houses collapsed. Authorities had moved
some 20,000 people to safety before the cyclone struck.
	   Heavy rainfall has been reported in western India and eastern
areas of neighboring Pakistan following the cyclone, which packed
wind speeds of up to 100 kph (65 mph).
	   Pakistan's port city of Karachi was battered by rains blamed for
the deaths of 12 people. Most of the dead, according to the
Associated Press of Pakistan, were electrocuted after high winds
toppled power lines and left live wires strewn across several busy
streets.
</TEXT>
