<SLUG> BC-Britain-People-Ulrika-Collymore </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Football star Stan Collymore apologizes for fracas with TV
</HEADLINE>
personality Ulrika Jonsson &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Football star Stan Collymore has apologized for
punching and kicking his girlfriend Ulrika Jonsson in a Paris bar.
	   Jonsson, 30, a Swedish-born television personality, returned to
her home in Cookham Dean, 25 miles (40 kms) northwest of London,
following the incident Monday night. She told reporters on
Wednesday: ``I don't want to talk about it.''
	   Collymore's adviser and agent Paul Stretford confirmed witness
reports, including that of a Scottish Television news reporter,
that the Aston Villa striker hit and kicked Miss Jonsson at a late
night World Cup party for Scotland fans on Monday.
	   Scottish Television reporter Martin Geissler said Collymore
``dragged her out of the bar into a back room, pushed her to the
ground and aimed kicks at her head. She was lying on the ground
screaming and bar staff then grabbed Collymore and threw him out.''
	   Stretford read a statement issued by Collymore, 27, in which he
admitted that ``a stupid and silly argument had developed
throughout the course of the day.''
	   ``My actions were totally reprehensible, something I am not
proud of and finding very difficult to come to terms with. In a fit
of petulant temper I struck out at the girl I love and immediately
regretted my actions, but by then it was too late.
	   ``I could hide behind a facade of excuses and no comments but
petulance, jealousy and possibly having too much to drink are the
real reasons behind this
	   regrettable and avoidable incident.''
	   Collymore also confirmed that he had been head-butted by someone
in the bar, and he apologized to that unidentified man ``for
causing him to feel that he had to take such action.''
	   Collymore said he had privately apologized to Miss Jonsson.
	   (rb)
</TEXT>
