<HEADLINE>
Italians arrest suspected terrorists as World Cup starts
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ As the World Cup kicks off in France Wednesday,
Italian police arrested at least 20 people suspected of belonging
to an Algerian terrorist group allegedly planning attacks during
the games.
	   Paramilitary police in Bologna said approximately 23 people had
been arrested and dozens of others were being questioned. News
reports linked those arrested to the Armed Islamic Group, a violent
Muslim militant movement blamed for murdering tens of thousands of
people in Algeria.
	   A Europe-wide anti-terrorist sweep over the past month has led
to nearly 100 arrests in France, Italy, Germany, Belgium and
Switzerland.
	   French authorities in May said they had found evidence of
possible terrorist attacks planned during the month-long soccer
tournament to be played in 10 French cities. They also urged the
public to watch out for bombs.
	   Algerian militants have staged terrorist attacks in France in
the past to pressure Paris to cut its ties with the military-backed
government of the petroleum-rich North African nation.
	   (vg)
