w2493 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Thailand-Corruption     06-10 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Corruption </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mayor of Thailand's second largest city resigns
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CHIANG MAI, Thailand (AP) _ The mayor of Chiang Mai, Thailand's
second largest city, has abruptly resigned in the face of political
pressure connected with the proposed site of a new municipal dump.
	   An official of Chiang Mai province said Wednesday that Sakol
Karanthakasuwan was caught between the demands of his political
organization and opposition among residents of the area where the
dump would be located.
	   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Sakol's
resignation Tuesday might further weaken the control the Navarat
Pattana Group, one of northern Thailand's biggest business groups,
has exercised over the city government.
	   The Navarat Pattana group is involved in real estate and
retailing.
	   Sakol gave no public reason for his resignation, but was
believed to want to cut his association with the group, said the
official.
	   The party to which Sakol belonged was closely associated with
the group, and two years ago controlled all 24 seats in the
municipal legislature. But political infighting, fueled by
scandals, has led many to defect, and with Sakol's resignation, the
group now controls only 11 seats.
	   The founder of the Navarat Pattana Group, Maj.-Gen. Intarat
Yodbangtoei, is facing trial for allegedly running an extortion
racket at four Chiang Mai markets, including the Night Bazaar, a
popular shopping area among foreign visitors.
	   Chiang Mai, 580 kilometers (360 miles) north of Bangkok, is a
popular tourist destination and university town.
	   Sakol was being pressured by the Navarat Pattana Group to
purchase land from a particular seller for the city's dump site,
said the provincial official.
	   He said public anger about the affair was running so high that
Intarat recently came close to being attacked by some 300 villagers
while he was inspecting a dump site in Hang Dong district.
	   Provincial Governor Pravit Sihasopon was nonetheless expected to
appoint Intarat's wife, Busaba, to replace Sakol unless the council
members who had broken with the Navarat Pattana Group could unite
and agree on an alternative candidate, said the official.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Thailand-Corruption; CT:i; 
(REG:ASIA;)
(REG:ENGL;)
