<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup-Home Fans,0664 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
French need some heavy prodding to get charged for World Cup
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By RAF CASERT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ The home fans color any World Cup. Their fervor,
even craziness, can provide that extra sparkle to make memories
live on forever. Their indifference can turn the finals into an
out-of-body experience.
	   The French have a tall task ahead over the next month to make
themselves inseparably intertwined with their Coupe du Monde.
	   ``We never really felt a groundswell,'' said Jacques Lambert,
the general director of the World Cup organizing committee.
	   Two decades ago, the confetti and paper rolls cascading down
River Plate's Monumental Stadium and snowing under the pitch
symbolized an Argentinean nation totally enthralled with the
success of the home team.
	   A dozen years ago in Mexico, an opening win over little Belgium
turned Mexico City into a seething mass of celebrating fans and
wild fiestas with hundreds of thousands of fans continued with
every win until Germany prevailed in a quarterfinal penalty
shootout.
	   The Italian fans tried hard to enliven the 1990 finals, but they
will always be remembered for weeping openly in Naples' Sao Paolo
stadium after Argentina's Diego Maradona denied them a place in the
final during a penalty shootout.
	   Despite the huge crowds in the United States four years ago, the
host nation was mesmerized by the murder charges facing football
star OJ Simpson and much more absorbed by basketball and ice hockey
finals instead of a soccer sideshow.
	   The hope always was that by returning the World Cup to its
French cradle, the national enthusiasm would automatically follow.
	   Don't necessarily count on it. Especially not the home team.
	   The French team already thank the lucky stars that their opening
match Friday against South Africa is in Marseilles, the
Mediterranean port where the southern heart truly beats for Les
Bleus, as the team is known.
	   ``The whole of the ... south will be there,'' said defensive
mainstay Laurent Blanc. ``It's the best place to start. They're
more exuberant.''
	   Coach Aime Jacquet agreed. ``We feared stadiums full of people
without fervor. So this is a good decision.''
	   Marseilles's antithesis is Paris, a town that can react to the
team with a cool disdain.
	   Parisian fans are known to whistle the team. ``France has a
habit of denigrating those that they loved just a few weeks
earlier,'' said Cyrille Auvillain, a member of the fledgling
official fan club of the French team.
	   Last year, the team got a cool reaction when it disappointed at
its Tournoi de France, a warmup for the World Cup. Since they have
also been whistled in Lens and St. Etienne, despite winning on both
occasions.
	   ``How to explain this lack of love,'' asked French federation
president Claude Simonet. ``The French are impatient, demanding.''
	   The official fan club for France was founded half a year ago,
and has lured just 4,000 members in a country of 58.5 million.
	   The lukewarm mentality of the French fans even has opposing
teams figuring out special strategies.
	   As a Frenchman, South African coach Philippe Troussier knows all
to well how fickle the French can be. On Friday, he wants his team
to come strong from the start, knowing how the crowd can turn if
its team doesn't start well.
	   Soccer observers say a French team led by brilliant playmaker
Zinedine Zidane can go all the way to the final and even President
Jacques Chirac, the first among French fans, has spoken of his
expectation that he will offer the Cup to French captain Didier
Deschamps July 12.
	   But soccer fever is not running through the whole nation yet.
``Maybe we don't like winners,'' Auvillain said.
	   One thing is sure _ one of France's biggest sporting legends is
cyclist Raymond Poulidor, who made a career out of finishing second
in the Tour de France.
</TEXT>
