<HEADLINE>
Security strengthened at Bangladeshi power stations for World Cup
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) _ Authorities in Bangladesh have beefed
up security at the country's power stations, concerned that outages
during World Cup broadcasts could lead to attacks by angry soccer
fans.
	   Bangladesh's national team is not playing in the World Cup
tournament, which begins Wednesday, but the country has many avid
soccer fans.
	   The government flew in two Russian engineers from Moscow on
Sunday to repair a 210 megawatt power stations to ensure there was
adequate power supply in the capital, Dhaka, newspapers reported
Wednesday.
	   Outages are routine in Bangladesh, which generates only 1,700
megawatts of power, an inadequate amount of electricity for the
country. In some areas, power cuts last up to 12 hours, leading to
street demonstrations.
</TEXT>
