<SLUG> BC-Air France-Strike, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Air France says agreement reached with striking pilots
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: combines urgent series, adds byline &QL; 
 &UR; By IAN PHILLIPS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Air France said Wednesday it had reached an
agreement with striking pilots to end a ten-day walkout which has
severely undermined preparations for the World Cup.
	   In a statement, Air France said the pilots had agreed to accept
company shares in exchange for salary cuts.
	   The company called for an immediate return to work.
	   The World Cup kicks off later Wednesday with a match between
Brazil and Scotland.
	   ``This global accord is aimed at assuring the development of Air
France by improving its competitivity with regards to its rivals,''
the statement said.
	   The company also said it would scrap a two-tier salary scale,
under which new pilots earned less than their colleagues.
	   The strike was an acute embarrassment to the company, the World
Cup's official carrier, and the French government.
	   Wednesday's agreement was reached with the SNPL, the main
pilots' union which represents the vast majority of Air France
pilots.
	   Air France had been locked in bitter talks with pilots' unions
over the last ten days.
	   On Tuesday night, as World Cup celebrations began in Paris,
negotiations seemed deadlocked.
	   The pilots had been protesting a proposal for 500 million francs
(dlrs 83 million) in salary cuts. Air France had said the cuts were
needed to modernize the airline, which was saved from bankruptcy in
1993 but reported profits in 1996 and 1997.
	   In the statement, Air France said part of the agreement involved
guaranteed training for young pilots.
	   Only one in four Air France planes was flying Tuesday, and other
carriers were cashing in on the carrier's woes.
	   British Airways estimated it was bringing in an additional 1
million pounds (dlrs 1.6 million) daily as a result of the Air
France strike.
	   Air France had arranged special flights to transport teams to
their destinations during the World Cup.
	   An estimated one million fans are expected to travel to France
for the month-long soccer tournament. Many fans have already
arrived, and some have been forced to switch airlines.
	   As well as the airline strike, France has been hit in recent
days by walkouts by train drivers, baggage handlers, and some bus
services.
	   (ip)
</TEXT>
