<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore dollar, stock market tumble
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with index passing this year's low.

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Singapore's benchmark stock index plunged 4.1
percent Wednesday to hit its lowest level this year and the
Singapore dollar fell to a four-month low against the U.S.
currency.
	   Dealers said foreign sellers were abandoning Singapore's
index-linked stocks to get out of the market.
	   Mounting fears that the local economy is worse than official
figures show, a stagnant property sector, concerns about bank
exposures to regional bad loans and the weakening Asian currency
markets have contributed to the rapid slide of Singapore's markets
in the past two weeks.
	   The benchmark Straits Times Industrial Index easily breached a
key support level of 1100 in early trading and before closing had
fallen more than 45 points, to a low for the year, 1071.94. The
index's last low was on Jan. 12, when it hit 1073.47.
	   On that day, considered to be the height of the financial
crisis, the Singapore dollar had also weakened to below 1.80 to the
U.S. dollar.
	   The Singapore dollar wasn't spared on Wednesday either, breaking
through the 1.72 level against the U.S dollar for the first time
since early February. The U.S. dollar was quoted at a four-month
high of 1.7215 Singapore dollars in morning trading, but the
currency fluctuated within one Singapore cent.
	   The falls come after a series of precipitous drops over the past
week.
	   There was increasing speculation by market players over whether
China will devalue its yuan and Hong Kong will abandon its fixed
currency peg against the U.S. dollar.
	   Uncertainty over the direction of the Japanese yen, and growing
indications of significant economic slowdown or even recession in
Singapore's economy also continue to dampen sentiment.
	   Equity markets were down across the region.
	   Dealers said attention was focused on Hong Kong, where the
benchmark Hang Seng index had dived. 	   
</TEXT>
