<SLUG> BC-Uganda-Rebels </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Newspaper: death toll in rebel school attack rises to 80
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By HENRY WASSWA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) _ The death toll in a rebel attack on a
technical training college in western Uganda has risen to 80, a
newspaper reported Wednesday.
	   President Yoweri Museveni condemned the Monday attack on
Kichwamba Technical College, the bloodiest carried out by the
Alliance of Democratic Forces since they appeared on the scene two
years ago. He said the group included former security agents in the
dreaded secret police of former dictator Idi Amin.
	   Museveni, himself a former rebel leader, spoke Tuesday evening
at a ceremony honoring those who died in the 1981-86 rebellion he
led against the government of Milton Obote.
	   The ADF rebels reportedly attacked the training college near
Kabarole, 316 kilometers (196 miles) west of Kampala, to carry off
young men to serve in their ranks. When the students barricaded
themselves inside one of the college buildings, the rebels set fire
to it.
	   On Wednesday, the government-owned New Vision said the death
toll had risen to 80 and that another 60 people were missing and
feared abducted.
	   The ADF rebels and those of the Lord's Resistance Army operating
in northern Uganda force civilians to join their ranks; the LRA
usually carries off children under the age of 15.
	   Education Minister Apollo Nsimbi went on state radio Tuesday to
express sorrow over the deaths.
	   Many Ugandans have begun to express concern that the army _ the
Ugandan People's Defense Force _ is incapable of dealing with the
three-front rebel onslaught.
	   The ADF is based in the foothills of the Rwenzori Mountains that
form the border between Uganda and the Democratic Republic of the
Congo. The West Nile Bank Front, another rebel group, operates in
the far northwestern part of the country, on the west bank of the
Nile River.
	   The Sudan-based LRA operates mainly in the northern districts of
Gulu and Kitgum, but late last month struck in central Lira
district.
	   ADF rebels operating in Kabarole, Kasese and Bundibuyo districts
have displaced at least 80,000 people from their homes.
	   Aides to Maj. Shaban Bantariza, a military spokesman, said he
had gone to the area to gather information about Monday's attack.
	   The New Vision further reported that army commanders in the the
region blamed troops posted near the trainin college for not
responding swiftly to the rebel attack and said the area unit
commander has been arrested.
	   ``When the rebels attacked the institute at around 5.30 a.m on
the fateful day, the UPDF troops just took off and left the
vulnerable lives of the students in the hands of the brutal ADF
thugs,'' New Vision said.
	   (hw/sl)	   
</TEXT>
