<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. dollar climbs, Tokyo stocks fall
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Wraps up with late dollar, closing bond, other details &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar climbed to a new seven-year high
against the yen Wednesday ahead of a meeting of Group of Seven
finance officials in France. Tokyo stocks fell amid sharp declines
in other Asian stock markets.
	   In late afternoon trading, the dollar bought 140.84 yen, up 0.48
yen from late Tuesday in Tokyo and above its late New York level of
140.30 yen overnight. During Wednesday's trading, the currency
moved as high as 141.57 yen, its highest level since June 1991.
	   The dollar rose amid speculation that deputy finance ministers
of the G-7 industrialized countries will not issue a statement to
curb the yen's slide after their meeting Wednesday in Paris.
	   Japanese officials have recently warned of the yen's excessive
weakening against the dollar, suggesting possible yen-buying
intervention. Finance Minister Hikaru Matsunaga has hinted that the
G-7 officials might address the recent exchange market movement.
	   Traders said they will keep watching the G-7 meeting and
congressional testimony by U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan, also Wednesday.
	   The dollar has gained steadily against the Japanese currency in
recent weeks as investors shifted funds out of Japan's sagging
markets and into the robust U.S. economy.
	   Meanwhile, sharp falls in Asian stock markets, including Hong
Kong, sent Tokyo share prices lower Wednesday. Some investors also
took profits following Tuesday's rise on the main index.
	   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 190.91 points, or 1.23
percent, closing at 15,339.26. On Tuesday, the average rose 235.46
points, or 1.52 percent.
	   Among Wednesday's losers were bank issues, which faced selling
by foreign investors. Japanese banks are still saddled with huge
bad loans left over from the collapse of Japan's speculative
``bubble economy'' in the early 1990s.
	   Trading remained light, with an estimated 340 million shares
changing hands on the first section, up from Tuesday's 314 million
shares. Declining issues outnumbered advancers 746 to 352, with 145
issues unchanged.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section shed 10.08 points, or 0.83 percent, to 1,198.60. The
TOPIX closed up 10.32 points, or 0.86 percent, the day before.
	   Analysts predicted foreign investors will keep selling their
Japanese holdings if the yen keeps weakening. A weaker yen erodes
the dollar value of Japanese stocks.
	   The yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese government
bond fell to 1.195 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.210 percent,
driving its price higher to 112.06 yen from 111.96 yen.
 &UR; (km)
</TEXT>
