<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Air France-Strike, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Air France says agreement reached with striking pilots
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: UPDATES with quotes from Air France president; edits. &QL; 
 &UR; By IAN PHILLIPS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Air France said Wednesday it had reached an
agreement with striking pilots, ending a walkout that had severely
embarrassed the country in the days leading up to the World Cup.
	   In a statement, Air France said the pilots had agreed to accept
company shares in exchange for salary cuts.
	   The company called for an immediate return to work. But the
airline has said previously it would take at least three days for
service to return to normal once the strike ended.
	   Just Tuesday night, as World Cup celebrations began in Paris,
negotiations had seemed deadlocked. Pilots had gathered at Charles
de Gaulle airport and agreed to continue the walkout, despite an
appeal by the transport minister to both sides to continue talking.
	   But in talks overnight, an agreement was reached.
	   Jean-Cyril Spinetta, the president of Air France, told France
Info radio Wednesday morning that ``this is a compromise that is
good for the company, good for the employees and good for the
clients.''
	   But he added that consequences of the strike were ``heavy'' and
that the company had lost a billion francs (dlrs 166 million.)
``Now we have to think of confidence, confidence in Air France,
confidence in its clients,'' he said.
	   ``This global accord is aimed at assuring the development of Air
France by improving its competitiveness with regards to its
rivals,'' he said in a statement.
	   The carrier also said Wednesday it would scrap a two-tier salary
scale, under which new pilots earned less than their colleagues.
The pilots, among the most highly paid in the world, had found this
detrimental to cabin solidarity.
	   The strike, coming as the country tries to put its best face
forward for the world's biggest sporting event, was a severe
embarrassment to the government.
	   The World Cup kicks off later Wednesday with a match between
Brazil and Scotland.
	   Thousands of fans have descended on France for the tournament,
many having to switch airlines at the last minute or take the
train.
	   Air France is the official airline of the World Cup, and many of
its planes, decorated with huge images of soccer stars, sat idle on
runways during the runup to the soccer tournament.
	   Wednesday's agreement was reached with the SNPL, the main
pilots' union which represents the vast majority of Air France
pilots.
	   The airline had been locked in bitter talks with pilots' unions
over the last 10 days.
	   The pilots had been protesting a proposal for 500 million francs
(dlrs 83 million) in salary cuts. Air France had said the cuts were
needed to modernize the airline, which was saved from bankruptcy in
1993 but reported healthy profits in 1996 and 1997.
	   It appeared that much of the 1997 gain has been eaten up by the
strike.
	   In the statement, Air France said part of the agreement involved
guaranteed training for young pilots, at least part of which would
be paid for by the company.
	   Only one in four Air France planes was flying Tuesday, and other
carriers were cashing in on the carrier's woes.
	   British Airways estimated it was bringing in an additional 1
million pounds (dlrs 1.6 million) daily as a result of the Air
France strike.
	   As well as the airline strike, France has been hit in recent
days by walkouts by train drivers, baggage handlers, and some bus
services.
	   (ip-dgs-jn) 	   
</TEXT>
