<SLUG> BC-Caribbean-Summary,1243 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
An overnight summary of Caribbean news
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 
 &UR; TURKS AND CAICOS _ Police fire at Haitian refugee sloop; 30
believed dead &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   HAMILTON, Bermuda (AP) _ Police in the British Turks and Caicos
Islands fired on a boat jammed with 100 Haitian refugees. The boat
capsized, drowning as many as 30 people, authorities said Tuesday.
	   John Kelly, deputy governor of the island chain, said there were
unconfirmed reports the police hit the boat when they tried to
shoot warning shots over its bow on Monday.
	   The sloop flipped over and threw its passengers into the ocean.
	   The bodies of six drowned Haitians were recovered Monday.
Rescuers searched without success Tuesday for 24 missing people,
Kelly said.
	   Kelly said there was no evidence that the police officers' shots
hit the boat, and the six dead did not suffer bullet wounds.
 &UR; PUERTO RICO: Unions OK general strike to protest phone company
sale
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ Union leaders on Tuesday approved a
general strike to protest the proposed sale of the state-owned
Puerto Rico Telephone Co. to a GTE-led consortium, but they refused
to reveal a strike date.
	   The strike threat is intended to pressure Puerto Rican
legislators who must decide whether to approve the dlrs 1.8 billion
sale, a centerpiece of Gov. Pedro Rossello's privatization program.
	   ``It could be tomorrow,'' said Miguel Sisamone, vice president
of the Independent Telephone Workers Union.
	   A small bomb, meanwhile, exploded outside a bank owned by a
partner in the GTE consortium, shattering windows and heightening
fears of violence by opponents of the sale. There were no injuries.
 &UR; UNITED STATES: Cuban exile groups protest Spanish prime minister's
visit
	   MIAMI (AP) _ Several dozen anti-Castro activists called on the
Spanish government to take a stronger stand against the Cuban
regime as Spanish Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar visited South
Florida on Tuesday.
	   Protesters on street corners waved Cuban flags and held up signs
to passing traffic at Florida International University, where Aznar
spoke on the importance of higher education.
	   One of the signs called Aznar a liar. Another said ``Spanish
investors are exploiting Cuban workers.''
	   The demonstration was organized by several Cuban exile groups
that say Aznar's government has been too soft on Fidel Castro's
regime. No arrests were reported.
 &UR; UNITED NATIONS: Cuba says U.S. embargo harmful to drug fight
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Cuba said Tuesday the U.S. embargo was
harming its efforts to fight drug trafficking and rejected as
illegitimate the U.S. procedure of certifying countries as allies
in the drug war.
	   ``The developing world,'' said Justice Minister Roberto Diaz
Sotolongo, ``is where the flow of the resources required to
confront the challenge posed by this evil is most necessary.''
	   Speaking to a U.N. General Assembly special session on drugs,
Diaz Sotolongo said there was political will in Cuba to prevent
using Cuban territory for moving drugs.
	   Cuban authorities prevented 95 million doses of cocaine from
being consumed in other countries between 1994 and 1997, he said.
 &UR; GUYANA: Officials say rights groups ``ganging up'' on Caribbean
	   GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) _ Human rights groups are ``ganging up''
on Caribbean nations to force them to abandon the death penalty,
local justice ministers complained during a forum in Guyana.
	   They urged each other to openly oppose pressure by the United
Nations Human Rights Committee, Amnesty International, Caribbean
Rights and Human Rights Watch to curb their use of capital
punishment.
	   ``This is a fundamental issue that we must address because we
have a number of international organizations ganging up against
us,'' Radford Hill, Antigua's legal affairs and justice minister
said during the meeting last week. ``The better thing to do is for
us to come up with a harmonized approach to the issue. There is
strength in numbers.''
 &UR; PUERTO RICO: Local Justice Dept. probes political donations by
AT&AMP;T
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ The Puerto Rican Justice Department
is investigating allegations that AT&AMP;T Corp. made possibly unlawful
donations to a political party that supports statehood for this
U.S. territory.
	   The government said in a statement that its Special
Investigations Bureau is probing contributions made between 1993
and 1995 to Tele-Pro, a group of Puerto Rican statehood activists.
	   Some of the money was later deposited in bank accounts of Gov.
Pedro Rossello's New Progressive Party, documents published Tuesday
by the El Nuevo Dia newspaper show.
	   At least one of those donations _ a dlrs 4,000 check written in
1994 that ended up in the party's bank account _ would violate a
dlrs 1,000 limit on donations to parties during non-election years
set by Puerto Rican law.
 &UR; UNITED STATES: Jamaican boy dies after being scratched by cat
	   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) _ A 6-year-old Jamaican boy stricken with
a rare complication of ``Cat Scratch Disease'' has died in a
Jacksonville, Florida, hospital, his parents reported.
	   Bosville Anthony Mullings of Westmoreland Parish, Jamaica,
caught bacillary angiomatosis, a rare form of the disease, after a
cat scratched him in March. News of his illness inspired hundreds
of Jamaicans to donate money to fly him to the United States for
medical care.
	   His parents said Mullings died Monday of heart complications
related to the disease.
	   ``The doctors tried their best,'' his father, Bosville Mullings
Sr., said Monday. ``If it's the will of the Lord to take him, then
whatever his will is, that's good enough for me.''
 &UR; CUBA: Italian foreign minister in Cuba
	   HAVANA (AP) _ With Cuba expressing concern about a recent U.S.
pact with Europe, Italy's foreign minister met Tuesday with Cuban
officials to express interest in continuing ties with the communist
island.
	   Lamberto Dini, who arrived Monday, was making the first visit by
a European Community foreign minister since the United States
imposed a tougher new version of its Cuba embargo in March 1996.
	   Cuban foreign minister Roberto Robaina, who met Dini on Tuesday,
said Monday that he was confident Europe continues to oppose the
U.S. law known as the Helms-Burton Act, which authorizes U.S.
sanctions against international companies that deal with Cuba.
 &UR; JAMAICA: University of the West Indies offers scholarship to
spelling champ
	   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) _ She won't enroll for another five
years, but the University of the West Indies is already courting
the Jamaican winner of a prestigious spelling bee contest with the
offer of a full scholarship.
	   Jody-Anne Maxwell, 12, has been offered a free education in the
major of her choice by the university's Mona Campus in Kingston,
Professor Elsa Leo-Rhynie, deputy principal of the university, said
Tuesday
	   Maxwell won the annual Scripps Howard National Spelling Bee
Competition, held in Washington, D.C., on May 29. She became the
first winner from outside the United States in the contest's
71-year history.
	   Maxwell has also been offered a full scholarship to Howard
University in Washington, D.C. She has said she wants to study
corporate law.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Caribbean-Summary; CT:i; 
(REG:CRB;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
