<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-New Yen, 1st Ld-writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ruling party subcommittee wants to revalue Japanese yen
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITTING to fix slug &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with chairman confirming idea under consideration;
EDITS thruout to conform &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ A ruling party subcommittee agreed Wednesday to
study revaluing the Japanese currency to make it more competitive
as an international currency, the committee's chairman said.
	   Hideyuki Aizawa said the Liberal Democratic Party's 30-member
subcommittee on denomination met for the first time Wednesday and
agreed to make a proposal to the government by the end of
September.
	   He said the committee wanted to revalue the yen at roughly one
yen to the U.S. dollar as a means of boosting confidence in the yen
as an international currency alongside the dollar and Europe's
euro.
	   The dollar currently buys about 140 yen.
	   The subcommittee hopes that the government eventually would
eventually draft a bill to revalue the yen by 2001, Aizawa said.
	   It remains uncertain, however, if the idea would ever make it to
a vote in Parliament. Lawmakers have floated such proposals in the
past, only to see them shot down by the powerful Finance Ministry,
which has called a new yen unnecessary and disruptive.
 &UR; (mef-sk) 	   
