<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Markets, 2nd Ld-2nd Add </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
URGENT
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; SINGAPORE: the day.

<TEXT>
	   The growing realization that the crisis will be deeper and
longer than originally expected has begun to affect Singapore, an
island of 3.1 million residents with few resources except its
highly trained workforce and modern infrastructure geared toward
attracting investment.
	   Government predictions have not matched the mounting private
sector forecasts that Singapore will fall into a recession or a
significant slowdown this year, although record unemployment has
already been acknowledged.
	   A stagnant property sector, concerns about undisclosed bank
exposures to regional bad loans and the weakening Asian currency
markets have contributed to the rapid slide of Singapore's markets
in the past two weeks.
	   There was increasing speculation by market players Wednesday
over whether China will devalue its yuan and Hong Kong will abandon
its fixed currency peg against the U.S. dollar.
	   Uncertainty over the direction of the Japanese yen, and growing
indications about Singapore's declining economy also dampened
sentiment. Instead of shopping for bargains, foreign investors
simply sold what shares they had.
	   Media and property group Singapore Press Holdings Ltd., widely
seen as a proxy for the Singapore economy, was the biggest price
loser among index-linked stocks, hitting an all-time low of 11.70
Singapore dollars (dlrs 6.80) on volume of 426,000 shares, before
recovering by a few cents.
	   Equity markets were down across the region.
	   Dealers said attention was focused on Hong Kong, where the
benchmark Hang Seng index had dived. 	   
</TEXT>
