<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Australia-Copper </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Three more Korean companies join in Australian copper search
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Three leading South Korean companies
have joined in a dlrs 2.6 million joint venture to search for
copper in Australia, company officials said Wednesday.
	   Samsung, Hyundai and Daewoo will join in the search along with
South Korea's state-run Korea Resources Corp. and Australia's
Malachite Resources N.N. and LFB Resources N.L.
	   Korea Resources Corp. entered into a 50-50 joint venture with
the two Australian concerns in February. It now has to split its 50
percent share equally with the three new Korean companies.
	   The latest deal calls for all six parties to form a consortium
to search for copper in Yeobal, 350 kilometers (210 miles)
northwest of Sydney, for the next five years, the officials said.
	   Preliminary tests indicate the area has a commercially feasible
copper deposit, they said. If confirmed, the joint venture partners
will mine the ore.
	   South Korea does not produce copper. It imported 883,000 tons of
copper worth dlrs 1.2 billion last year. Its 1998 copper imports
are expected to reach 1.2 million tons worth dlrs 1.5 billion.
</TEXT>
