r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Iran-Newspaper     06-10 0260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iran-Newspaper,0259 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iranian paper stops publishing after press violation charges
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ A new Iranian newspaper has stopped
publication after authorities charged it with frequently violating
press ethics, other newspapers reported Wednesday.
	   The liberal Gozaresh-e-Baz was charged by the Press Supervisory
Board, and its case was forwarded Tuesday to the Justice Ministry
for review, the Iran Daily said.
	   A court case could follow and the newspaper may lose its license
if it is found guilty.
	   Another newspaper, Salam, quoted Gozaresh-e-Baz's director
Mohammad Mahdavi Khorrami as saying he had voluntarily stopped
publishing the paper until a final verdict.
	   The action against Gozaresh-e-Baz, or ``Open Report,'' is seen
as a setback for the press freedom that has been allowed by
moderate President Mohammad Khatami since he took office in August.
	   The Farsi-language newspaper started publishing only last month.
	   The English-language Iran News quoted a Culture Ministry
official, Ahmad Borqani, as saying that the newspaper ``has
followed quite an inappropriate path from the beginning of its
publication to the present day.''
	   Borqani said the paper had also printed ``a false report''
claiming that some Iranian officials had transferred money to
overseas bank accounts. Borqani said such a report is ``aimed at
disturbing public opinion and is against our national interests.''
	   Iran's constitution forbids the media from ``propagating
destructive and anti-Islamic attitudes.''
</TEXT>
