w2563 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Thailand-SoccerGambli     06-10 0293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Soccer Gambling </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Despite hard times, Thais planning to bet big on World Cup
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Despite a crippling economic crisis
that has left many people in dire straits, Thais are planning to
bet more money than ever on the World Cup soccer tournament,
according to a survey released Wednesday.
	   Although Thailand's team didn't qualify, the tournament, which
kicks off Wednesday in France, will be a boon to a range of Thai
businesses, both legal and underground, according to a survey by
the Thai Farmers Bank Research Center.
	   Thais will bet about 30 billion baht (dlrs 700 million)
nationwide, a significant increase from the amount bet on the
previous World Cup played in the United States in 1994, the survey
said.
	   Bangkok respondents to the survey said they were putting aside
an average of 38,860 baht (dlrs 903) to bet, up 35 percent from an
average of 28,740 baht (dlrs 668) last time.
	   More than 57 percent said they would wager with their savings,
while about 24 percent said they would use savings and borrow
money. About 18 percent said they would work overtime or find an
extra job to earn money to bet on the World Cup.
	   Aside from bookmakers, several legal businesses will also get a
boost from the event, the research center said.
	   Sales and use of communications equipment will be on the rise,
as fans trade information by mobile phones, computers and pagers,
the center said.
	   Newspapers should see sales increase, and pubs and restaurants
with big-screen televisions should also see more businesses, the
survey said.
	   Sales of instant noodles and coffee should also perk up as fans
stay up late at night to watch games on television because of the
time difference.
</TEXT>
