<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Stocks, 1st Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hong Kong shares plunge on weak yen, high local interest rates
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES thruout with closing figures; ADDS comments from chief
executive and traders

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Hong Kong shares ended at a three-year low
Wednesday, with foreign mutual funds dumping stocks on concerns
about rising domestic interest rates, weakening regional currencies
and of a possible devaluation of China's currency, the yuan.
	   Following Tuesday's 2.3-percent slump, the blue-chip Hang Seng
Index further tumbled 412.09 points, or 4.9 percent, to close at
7,979.37.
	   Turnover was 7.15 billion Hong Kong dollars (dlrs 916 million),
compared with 3.28 billion Hong Kong dollars (dlrs 420 million) for
the half-day session Tuesday. Trading was suspended Tuesday morning
because of severe rainstorms.
	   The closing level marked the first time in over three years that
the Hang Seng Index ended below the key 8,000-point level.
	   That sent a majority of the blue-chip companies to their lowest
levels this year.
	   ``It was mostly panic-selling by the big fund houses. They were
reducing their weightings on Hong Kong stocks,'' said Francis Lun,
research analyst at Pacific Challenge Securities Ltd.
	   ``Under such stock-clearing selling when the houses dump shares
regardless of the price, share prices nose-dived, especially in the
early afternoon,'' he added
	   The weakening yen dragged down most Southeast Asian currencies
Wednesday and compounded fears of a possible yuan devaluation,
whcih would leave the Hong Kong dollar's firm peg to the U.S.
dollar in a precarious position.
	   Fueling the fear was mainland central bank governor Dai
Xianglong's remark Tuesday that the falling Japanese yen would
exert a negative impact on China's foreign trade, though the
People's Bank of China official reiterated a pledge to keep the
Chinese currency stable.
	   Hong Kong's Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa also insisted
Wednesday the government will keep its currency peg, despite
increasing calls for action to help Hong Kong fight a liquidity
crunch.
	   He said at a conference floating the currency would ``cause
speculative attacks against the Hong Kong dollar and increase
interest rates.''
	   The news pushed the benchmark three-month interest rate up to
10.375 percent in early afternoon, up from 9.25 percent early
Wednesday. The one-month rate soared to 11.0 percent from 9.625
percent.
	   Traders said the interest rate surge further hurt market
sentiment. The high interest rates are making it harder for
companies to borrow and eating into their profits.
	   Minutes before the market's close, Tung told reporters that the
government will not dip into its reserves to keep financial markets
from sliding further before Hong Kong is a free market.
	   Banking system liquidity has tightened steadily as money has
flowed out of Hong Kong markets, and with markets here weak,
commercial banks have been unwilling long-term lenders.
	   The London-based banking giant HSBC lost 9.0 Hong Kong dollars
to 181.0.
	   Property stocks Sun Hung Kai Properties lost 1.90 to 30.30, and
Henderson Land lost 2.85 to 23.40.
	   Among conglomerates, Swire Pacific ``A'' lost 2.60 to 22.0, and
Hutchison Whampoa lost 2.0 to 34.0.
</TEXT>
