<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine peso, stocks decline
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ The Philippine peso fell against the
U.S. dollar Wednesday after the release of a Morgan Stanley report
revising downward its regional exchange-rate forecasts for 1998,
dealers said.
	   The dollar averaged 39.775 pesos for the day, up from 39.470
pesos on Tuesday.
	   The peso, which was relatively steady against the dollar in the
morning, fell sharply in afternoon trading, with the dollar
clipping 40 pesos. The dollar's high for the day was 40.270 pesos.
	   Dealers said the Morgan Stanley report triggered relatively
heavy demand for dollars, with volume rising to dlrs 164.5 million
from dlrs 77.7 million on Tuesday.
	   Morgan Stanley's report forecast the peso would fall to 47 pesos
to the dollar by the end of the year. Since the currency crisis
erupted last July, the peso's lowest level was 46.50 pesos per
dollar, touched in January. The past six months have seen the peso
trade in a range of 37 pesos to 41 pesos per dollar.
	   Morgan Stanley sees inflation averaging 10 percent this year,
higher than the government's target of 7.5 percent to 8.5 percent.
	   With the dollar last traded at 40.060 pesos, dealers expect the
losses to be extended in the coming session.
	   Particular attention will be paid to any yen-supportive comments
made at the Group of Seven finance ministers' meeting in Paris
later Wednesday.
	   In stock trading, shares moved lower as a dearth of positive,
market-moving news sidelined most investors, traders said.
	   Concern over the future of most Asian economies continues to
weigh down regional stocks and will likely do so for the
foreseeable future, they said.
	   The 30-share Philippine Stock Exchange Index fell 6.62 points,
or 0.3 percent, to 1,917.87, after losing 6.10 points on Tuesday.
	   It was the third straight loss for the main index, bringing its
total decline to 39.89 points during the period.
	   ``There's no incentive for investors to come into the market,''
said Edwin Siao, trader for institutional sales of Abacus
Securities Corp.
</TEXT>
