<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-State Enterprises </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government orders improved control of state assets
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Alarmed by the steady siphoning off of state
assets by unscrupulous company managers and local officials, the
government announced Wednesday tougher financial regulations.
	   Acknowledging what already is known to be a serious problem, the
circular from the State Council, or Cabinet, orders local
governments as well as the central bank and courts to do what they
can to prevent further theft and waste of state property.
	   To meet its goal of reforming its bloated and inefficient
state-owned enterprises within three years, the government is
selling off many small- and medium-size firms.
	   Company managers and local officials have sought to cash in on
the process by setting up dummy bank accounts and fake companies to
hold such assets for their personal use and to avoid paying back
their debts, the state-run Xinhua News Agency reported.
	   The State Council has ordered banks to crack down on
unauthorized accounts and to improve accounting oversight and asset
valuation.
	   It also warned local courts to be fair and honest in dealing
with cases of fraud and waste _ alluding to widespread corruption
in the judicial system.
	   Those found guilty of violating the new orders or of causing
economic losses by failing to enforce them would be severely
punished, it said. 	   
</TEXT>
