<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Investments </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Investments in Philippines fall 51 percent in first five months
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ The Philippine Board of Investments
approved a total of 133.65 billion pesos (dlrs 3.4 billion) worth
of projects in the first five months of 1998, 51 percent less than
in the same period a year earlier.
	   BOI managing head Melito Salazar said Wednesday the downturn in
investments is the result of ``temporary belt-tightening among
local firms'' to cope with the Asian financial crisis.
	   Despite the overall slowdown, foreign equity in the projects
approved for the period rose 43 percent to 25.98 billion pesos
(dlrs 666 million) from a year earlier.
	   ``This is significant because other Asian countries have
experienced negative foreign interest in the wake of last year's
crisis,'' he said.
	   The Philippines has not been as badly affected by the currency
crisis as some other Asian countries.
	   A total of 118 projects were approved by the BOI in the first
five months, Salazar said.
	   The sectors that attracted the largest investments were energy,
construction and housing, public utilities, tourism, and
infrastructure and industrial services.
	   Much of foreign interest came from Hong Kong, the United States,
Japan, the Virgin Islands, Canada, and Britain.
</TEXT>
