<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Interest Rates </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cabinet endorses high interest rates for Malaysia
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ A simmering row over the direction
of Malaysia's monetary policy may have been defused Wednesday with
the Cabinet endorsing current interest rates.
	   At the weekly meeting of government ministers, Finance Minister
Anwar Ibrahim informed the Cabinet that the government would retain
interest rates at current levels, according to a government source.
	   The official said the endorsement was reached after a brief
discussion at the meeting that was also attended by Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad, who has repeatedly differed with Anwar on
monetary policy.
	   Anwar, who is also deputy prime minister, has backed the central
bank-prescribed high rates, saying these were needed to prevent a
run on reserves and spiraling inflation. Mahathir has said the
tight monetary policy and high lending rates were hurting
businesses and stifling economic growth.
	   Although both Mahathir and Anwar have denied there was a rift
between them on economic policy, markets have reacted nervously to
the contradictory signals.
</TEXT>
