<SLUG> BC-Iran-Kuwait,0138 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iran and Kuwait sign deal to expand security, drug cooperation
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ Iran and Kuwait signed an agreement
Wednesday to expand cooperation in security, immigration and
anti-drug smuggling operations, Iranian radio reported.
	   The agreement was signed Kuwaiti Interior Minister Sheik
Mohammad al-Khaled al-Sabah and his Iranian counterpart, Abdollah
Nouri.
	   Sheik Khaled arrived in Iran Tuesday for a three-day visit, the
official Islamic Republic News Agency said.
	   Wednesday's agreement signals improving ties, which had grown
tense during the 1980-88 Iran-Iraq War because of Kuwait's
financial support for Baghdad.
	   But Iran's neutral stand during the 1991 Gulf War that ended a
seven-month Iraqi occupation of Kuwait brought the two Gulf
countries closer.
