</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-RugbyU-New Zealand-Lomu </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lomu trims down for England
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HAMILTON, New Zealand (AP) _ Jonah Lomu may look a little less
imposing to England's struggling rugby players, but a new diet has
left him hungry for more test action.
	   Lomu revealed he had trimmed down from 120 kilograms (265lbs) to
113 kilograms (249lbs) in a few months ahead of this season. He
will take the field against the English, who crumbled to a woeful
76-0 loss against Australia last week, on Saturday for New Zealand
A.
	   All Blacks coach John Hart has put Lomu on notice that he must
perform Saturday or miss out on the June 20 test match.
	   Lomu destroyed England in the 1995 World Cup semifinal, running
over the top of Mike Catt in one sensational play.
	   Faced with Hart's ultimatum, Lomu has, in turn, put the English
on notice.
	   ``I'm lighter now than I've ever been, feeling younger at the
moment,'' Lomu said Wednesday. ``That helps with the turning around
and getting around the field quicker, which is a plus for me.''
	   Lomu said he had given up much of the greasy and fattening
takeaway food that he loved so much.
	   ``You know, I indulge myself sometimes, I go for takeaway food
and things like that, but I've now gone off some of those,'' Lomu
said. ``I eat more rice now than I've ever had in my life, I feel
really good. When I get up I have more energy and I look forward to
another day.''
	   His new eating habits helped with the kidney disorder that
forced him out for almost all of last season.
	   If Lomu comes through Saturday's game in good shape, he will
play the Dunedin test a week later.
	   ``I just want a decent 80 minutes of footie,'' Lomu said. ``I
have to go out there and please the selectors, and have a go. I've
got to put pressure on myself.''
 &UR; (tjh)
</TEXT>
