<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Newspaper </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ukrainian newspaper sentenced to pay dlrs 100,000 to opposition
</HEADLINE>
leader &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) - A Kiev district court ordered a Ukrainian
newspaper to pay 200,000 hryvna (about dlrs 100,000) to compensate
an opposition leader for moral damage, the politician's attorney
said Wednesday.
	   Julia Timoshenko, a top official of the opposition Hromada
movement, sued the Ukraina Moloda newspaper following a Feb. 4
article regarding a church award she allegedly was to receive, her
attorney Viktor Nykazakov said.
	   The order of St. Barbara, ``named after the beaten and beheaded
Christian, was meant for a simple church warden and not for the
canonized oppositioner Timoshenko,'' the newspaper wrote, according
to the Interfax news agency.
	   Nykazakov said the court ruled that the story itself and a photo
collage accompanying the article ``did not correspond to reality''
and ordered the newspaper to publish a photo provided by
Timoshenko, in addition to the fine.
	   The newspaper has the right to appeal the decision to a higher
court.
	   Timoshenko said she plans to transfer the money to the Ukrainian
Orthodox Church.
	   ``The publication, first of all, offended the church, and it
would only be just to use the 200,000 hryvna for the benefit of
believers,'' Interfax quoted her as saying.
	   (sms/ren)
</TEXT>
