w2619 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Malaysia-WaterLawsuit     06-10 0260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Water Lawsuit </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Consumer group plans lawsuit on water rationing
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Consumer groups in the Malaysian
capital are planning to bring a rare class-action suit against
local authorities for failing to provide water to residents, a
spokesman for the groups said Wednesday.
	   The suit against the state government of Selangor, which is
responsible for supplying the area of the capital, would be on
behalf of the residents and could be as much as half a million
ringgit (dlrs 128,000), said A. Jayaseelan.
	   ``We are now doing all the legal research,'' said Jayaseelan,
director of the Selangor and Federal Territory Consumer
Association. The other group involved in the proposed suit is the
Federation of Malaysian Consumers Associations.
	   The final demand for compensation would be decided after people
file claims, said Jayaseelan. Consumer activists had received some
claims and were now involved in a signature campaign for the suit,
he said.
	   The suit, to be filed in about two months, was aimed at proving
that the water shortage was a crisis caused by negligence of the
utilities and not necessarily by the drought in Southeast Asia
brought on by El Nino.
	   Nearly 2 million residents of Kuala Lumpur and its suburbs have
been on severe water rationing for three months and some
neighborhoods receive water only once a week.
	   The decision to file a suit came after the police denied
permission to consumer groups to hold a meeting with residents to
discuss the water crisis.
</TEXT>
