<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesian president offers special status to East Timor
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS to wrap up day's events &QL; 
 &UR; With Indonesia-Troubled Territory; Indonesia-East Timor
 &UR; By GEOFF SPENCER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Protesters in East Timor rejected a
peace offering from Indonesia's new president Wednesday and
thousands in the capital staged another round of demonstrations
against corruption and for higher salaries.
	   Protests, once strictly curbed, have become a daily event in
Indonesia following promises of reform and freedom by new President
B.J. Habibie.
	   In a signal of possible easing of Indonesia's tight control of
East Timor, Habibie said Tuesday he might grant largely symbolic
special status to the troubled territory but said it must stay part
of Indonesia.
	   On Wednesday he signed a decree to free 15 East Timorese
political prisoners.
	   Despite these concessions, about 3,000 students and others
crammed into the campus of the University of East Timor in the
provincial Dili, demanding the right to vote for full independence
from Indonesia, which invaded the former Portuguese colony in 1975.
	   Justice Minister Muladi said the 15 East Timorese inmates would
be released as soon as possible.
	   Another dissident would be released from a prison on Indonesia's
main island, Java, bringing to 20 the total number of political
prisoners freed since Habibie took office on May 21.
	   Despite insistent demands by East Timorese activists, rebel
guerrilla leader Xanana Gusmao will remain behind bars. He's
regarded by Indonesia as a violent criminal, not a political
prisoner or freedom fighter.
	   Habibie replaced longtime leader Suharto as president last month
when the old autocrat was forced from office by a wave of protests
and violence.
	   Suharto, who ordered the 1975 invasion, had steadfastly refused
to make any concessions toward East Timor.
	   In Jakarta, about 2,000 factory workers protested outside the
national Parliament for higher salaries and better conditions as
Indonesia's battles the worst economic crisis in 30 years.
	   The protest comes just days after Habibie signed an
International Labor Organization convention respecting workers
rights.
	   The Indonesian government also said it would ratify United
Nation's human rights conventions against torture and racial
discrimination.
	   Under Suharto, Indonesia was regularly criticised for having a
poor human rights record.
	   Another 200 protesters held a demonstration at the government
social insurance office following accusations of mismanagement and
corruption.
	   More than 500 employees from Indonesia's state-owned flag
carrier Garuda Indonesia, including pilots and cabin crew,
demonstrated outside the airline's headquarters.
	   They demanded it end contracts linked to the family of President
Suharto and said they were worried that cash-strapped Garuda was
planning big layoffs.
	   The protest was the latest example of a growing backlash against
companies perceived to have benefited from collusion, nepotism and
corruption during the Suharto years.
	   Meanwhile, about 1000 employees of Wal Mart stores in Indonesia
demanded to be told if they would soon lose their jobs after a
Indonesian company operating the stores under license from the
U.S.-based retail giant decided to close down its operation.
</TEXT>
