r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Soccer-SouthAf     06-10 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-South Africa,0447 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Injury makes Arendse's dream a nightmare
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By TOM COHEN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VICHY, France (AP) _ South African players have long dreamed of
finally getting the chance to play in a soccer World Cup. For
goalkeeper Andre Arendse, the dream has become a nightmare.
	   Injured in training Monday night, Arendse will likely miss the
tournament. Team officials have called a news conference later
Wednesday on Arendse's condition, but they say privately he is out
because of his damaged left leg.
	   The lanky Fulham F.C. player, who turns 31 later this month, led
South Africa to victory in the 1996 African Nations Cup tournament
but was dropped from the team last year after former coach Clive
Barker resigned.
	   Arendse regained his spot under new coach Philippe Troussier,
who took over in March, but was expected to back up Hans Vonk of
Heerenveen F.C. and Brian Baloyi of local club Kaizer Chiefs at the
World Cup.
	   The news was a lone disappointing note for South African players
lapping up the experience of their first World Cup. Bafana Bafana
begins play on Friday night in a Group C clash with France in
Marseilles.
	   For 28 years until 1992, South Africa was banned from
international soccer because of apartheid. The players watched
World Cup matches on television, but actually taking the field
against the planet's best nations seemed impossible.
	   Midfielder Brendan Augustine, 26, recalled that ``it never
crossed my mind'' that he would play in a World Cup.
	   ``It was out of this world, a dream I never imagined,'' he said.
``Now that it's happening, it's out of this world.''
	   David Nyathi of St. Gallen, another midfielder, took a
philosophical view, saying the World Cup was like any other goal or
challenge a man faces, such as getting married or becoming a
father.
	   ``This is one of those dreams that becomes reality,'' said
Nyathi, 29. ``I have to say thank God I'm one of the people to be
representing South Africa in this glorious moment.''
	   He noted other South African players, including legends such as
former national coach Jomo Sono, never played in a World Cup
because of the apartheid ban.
	   ``It's a pity others never got a chance,'' he said.
	   Defender Mark Fish of Bolton Wanderers also mentioned those left
out by the political imbroglio.
	   ``We're representing South Africa, not only the republic but
also the players of the past who never had a chance,'' said Fish,
25. ``To play the host nation in the World Cup is the biggest
stage. It's a dream come true.''
	   Except for Arendse.
	   (tsc-sl)
</TEXT>
