w2647 &Cx1f; wstm-
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Singapore-Markets 4thLd-Writethru   06-10 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Markets, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore dollar drops, stock market tumbles to 9 1/2-year low
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES in grafs 1-6 with government TV saying 9 1/2 year low.
Picks up 7th graf, `The Singapore ...
 &UR; By LAURINDA KEYS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Fearing the local economy is worse than the
government admits, foreign sellers bailed out of Singapore markets
in a frenzy Wednesday, and the benchmark index plunged 4.4 percent
to its lowest level in more than nine years.
	   The key Straits Times Industrial Index easily breached a key
support level of 1100 in early trading and fell 49 points to close
at 1067.81, a figure government television said was a 9 1/2 year
low. The Singapore dollar also hit a four-month low against the
U.S. currency.
	   The index's previous low this year was on Jan. 12, when it hit
1073.47 in what was considered the peak of the regional economic
crisis.
	   But fears are growing that Singapore _ a hub for transferring
money into, out of, and around the financially weak region _ is now
set to suffer more of the consequences of the Asian economic
crisis. It mostly sailed unscathed through the tumult last year.
	   ``Everyone knows that we have benefited from our neighbors'
growth, and now we have to suffer along with them,'' Philip Wee, a
regional economist with Standard Chartered Bank, told Dow Jones
Newswires.
	   Government television, which has given no explanation in its
market closing bulletins for the rapid slide of the past two weeks,
attributed Wednesday's plunge to heavy selling of the Japanese and
Hong Kong currencies amid fears that China may devalue its yuan and
Hong Kong will abandon its fixed currency peg against the U.S.
dollar.
	   Traders were ``spooked by the yen's bad showing,'' the evening
television report said. The Japanese yen fell to a seven-year low
against the U.S. dollar Wednesday.
	   The Singapore dollar wasn't spared either, breaking through the
1.72 level against the U.S dollar for the first time since early
February. The U.S. dollar was quoted at a four-month high of 1.7215
Singapore dollars in morning trading, and fluctuated within one
Singapore cent through the day.
	   The growing realization that the crisis will be deeper and
longer than originally expected has begun to affect Singapore, an
island of 3.1 million residents without resources besides its
technically trained people. It also has a modern infrastructure
geared toward attracting investment, building new technologies and
handling money.
	   Government predictions have not matched the mounting private
sector forecasts that Singapore will fall into a recession or have
zero growth this year, although record unemployment has already
been acknowledged.
	   ``One or two political leaders have come up to warn about
retrenchments this year. That is probably the clearest sign that we
are headed for some pretty turbulent waters,'' Chia Yew Boon,
research director at Santander Investment Securities, told Dow
Jones Newswires.
	   A stagnant property sector, concerns about undisclosed bank
exposures to regional bad loans and the weakening Asian currency
markets contributed to the rapid slide of Singapore's markets in
the past two weeks.
	   But instead of bargain hunting, foreign investors simply sold
off the shares they had.
	   Media and property group Singapore Press Holdings Ltd., widely
seen as a proxy for the Singapore economy, was the biggest price
loser among index-linked stocks, hitting an all-time low of 11.70
Singapore dollars (dlrs 6.80) on volume of 426,000 shares, before
recovering by a few cents. 	   
</TEXT>
