<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Hotel Occupancy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Malaysia's hotel occupancy stays high at 70 percent
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Despite a sharp slowdown in the
economy, Malaysia's hotel occupancy remains high at 70 percent with
no reports of any layoffs in the industry, a newspaper reported
Wednesday.
	   The high occupancy rate indicates that there are still ample
career opportunities in the hotel industry, Minister of Culture,
Arts and Tourism Sabaruddin Chik was reported as saying Tuesday by
the Business Times daily.
	   ``With this high rate of hotel occupancy there is no reason for
hotel managements to retrench workers,'' he said.
	   Sabbaruddin projected a better prospect this year for the hotel
industry, saying the ministry expects 6.8 million visitors in 1998,
up from 6.2 million in 1997. In 1996, 7.1 million tourists visited
the country.
	   Sabbaruddin added that the optimistic forecast for 1998 is based
on the anticipated increase of visitors in September for the
Commonwealth Games.
	   The sharp depreciation in the value of the ringgit against the
dollar has also made it more affordable for tourists to vacation in
the country, he said.
	   Since the Asian economic crisis began last July, Malaysia's
currency, the ringgit, has lost more than 36 percent against the
U.S. dollar.
</TEXT>
