<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinian,0510 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Palestinian official calls for mobilization against Jewish
</HEADLINE>
settlement &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By HILARY APPELMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ A top Palestinian official called Wednesday for
Palestinians to ``mobilize to defend Jerusalem'' against Jewish
settlement.
	   In Jerusalem, Israeli troops dragged away American and Canadian
demonstrators holding a sit-in to protest expansion of a Jewish
settlement in the Arab neighborhood of Silwan. Some protesters were
beaten and kicked as they were dragged through the dust by their
arms and legs.
	   Palestinian Cabinet Secretary Ahmed Abdel Rahman reacted angrily
to the Israel Interior Ministry's decision Tuesday to approve the
construction of new housing for a Jewish religious seminary in east
Jerusalem on land originally slated for an Arab girls school.
	   ``This decision by the Israeli government is a continuation of
the Israeli aggression toward the city of Jerusalem in order to
make it a Jewish city and deport all the Arab citizens from
Jerusalem,'' Abdel Rahman told The Associated Press in the Gaza
Strip.
	   ``The people have to mobilize to defend Jerusalem and the holy
places.''
	   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat called the Israeli decision
``another violation'' of the Israel-Palestinian peace agreements,
which say neither side should make unilateral changes to the status
quo before a final peace settlement that would determine the fate
of Jerusalem.
	   Settlers, backed by funding from such supporters as U.S.
multi-millionaire Irving Moskowitz, have recently intensified their
campaign to increase the Jewish presence in traditionally Arab east
Jerusalem, which the Palestinians claim as a future capital.
	   On Monday, settlers moved into five apartments in a pair of
buildings in Silwan, setting off clashes with Palestinians.
	   About 50 protesters from the United States and Canada, mostly
members of Christian human rights groups, held a sit-in outside the
buildings Wednesday that was roughly dispersed by Israeli border
police. Palestinian residents watched from surrounding rooftops,
and police said some residents pelted them with stones.
	   ``I came here to look at the situation _ I'm appalled at what
I've seen,'' said Michael Kauffman, a Canadian who was dragged by
his arms and legs.
	   ``We just wanted to show solidarity with the Palestinians who
had their homes taken away by the settlers,'' said Lucy Mayer of
New York.
	   Police said the demonstration was held without a permit, and
that several demonstrators were arrested.
	   Israel captured east Jerusalem from Jordan in the 1967 Mideast
War and later annexed it.
	   Also Wednesday, the Israeli army said that a Palestinian shot
and killed by Israeli troops on Tuesday night had been planting a
bomb outside a Jewish settlement in the Gaza Strip. A second man
involved escaped, the army said.
	   Palestinian police identified the dead man as Aboud Bardawil,
22, and said a joint Israeli-Palestinian investigation into the
incident was underway.
</TEXT>
