w2656 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SouthAfrica-ChemicalW     06-10 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Chemical Warfare </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mandela was target for chemical disabling, scientist alleges
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By PAUL HARRIS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) _ President Nelson Mandela was the
target of a plot to mentally disable him through chemicals after
1990, a scientist who served the apartheid government said
Wednesday.
	   In testimony before a panel probing apartheid crimes, Schalk van
Rensburg described how his superior, Andre Immelman, told him there
were plans to poison Mandela with thallium, a drug that attacks the
nervous system.
	   Van Rensburg said the aim was not to kill Mandela, who had just
been released in 1990 after 27 years in prison and was starting
talks with the then white-run government on ending apartheid.
	   ``The intention, I understood, was to reduce his level of
intellectuality and effectiveness by inducing brain damage,'' he
said.
	   The Truth and Reconciliation Commission is investigating the
former apartheid army's chemical and biological weapons projects,
headed by Wouter Basson, who ran the scheme through an elaborate
network of front companies.
	   There was no suggestion that a plan to poison Mandela was ever
carried out, but documents introduced by the Truth Commission
suggested a possible link with the highest levels of the state.
	   Truth Commission lawyers presented a 1986 report from the State
Security Council, a shadowy body made up of apartheid's top
government ministers, that suggested Mandela could be released only
when he was in such a poor state of health that he could not
continue to lead the African National Congress.
	   Van Rensburg said he had never seen the document.
	   Jaap Celliers, a lawyer representing Basson and other top
scientists in the program, denied the document indicated a plot to
actively poison Mandela. He said the minutes could have just meant
that Mandela should be kept in jail long enough to damage his
health.
	   ``It was the longer detention, not active conduct,'' he said.
	   Basson, who has been called to testify later this week, was
forced to resign from the army in 1993 after a government report
fingered him in making poisons and chemical bombs. He is currently
being investigated on charges of making and possessing ecstasy and
mandrax drugs.
	   Earlier this week, scientists who worked in Basson's projects
described working in a poison factory that churned out chocolates,
drinks and cigarettes spiked with lethal chemicals that were passed
to government hit squads.
	   Scientists also developed large supplies of lethal
micro-organisms such as anthrax and cholera that could have been
used to cause epidemics.
	   Mandela and the ruling ANC that were elected in 1994's first
all-race elections set up the commission to uncover the truth about
apartheid crimes and promote racial healing.
	    &UR; (ph-pr-tl)
</TEXT>
