w2661 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Malaysia-PoliticalAsy     06-10 0443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Political Asylum </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. declares 22 Indonesians political refugees
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ALVIN UNG &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ The United Nations announced
Wednesday it would arrange political asylum for 22 Indonesians who
took refuge in the U.S. embassy and U.N. compound to escape
deportation.
	   ``We have interviewed all 22 of them, we have investigated, and
we have concluded that they are refugees, in need of international
protection,'' said Hege Rudd of the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees.
	   The UNHCR had not decided where the refugees would be given
asylum, Rudd said, adding they could be sent to different
countries.
	   ``The UNHCR is in close communications with the Malaysian
government to see what the next step will be for these refugees,''
she said.
	   The U.N. was asked to intervene after the Indonesians refused to
leave the U.S. embassy in downtown Kuala Lumpur, saying if deported
they would be tortured and even killed by the Indonesian military.
	   The refugees belong to Aceh, a region in the northern tip of
Sumatra, where an armed separatist movement has been active since
the 1970s. Human rights groups have accused the Indonesian military
of persecuting and executing Acehnese rebels.
	   Fleeing a police crackdown on illegal migrants, 14 Indonesians
rammed a truck through the gates of the UNHCR compound on March 30.
Eleven days later, eight more Acehnese hoisted themselves over the
walls of the U.S. embassy to escape the police and sought political
asylum.
	   The UNHCR would try to resettle the 22 men by seeking legal
protection, and in certain cases, citizenship, from governments who
agree to allow them in, the official said.
	   But the fate of two dozen other Indonesians who scrambled over
the walls of the Swiss, French and Brunei embassies on April 9
hangs in balance.
	   Unlike the U.S. and the U.N., these embassies handed the illegal
aliens over to Malaysian police. They were then taken to a
detention camp.
	   ``The UNHCR has not been able to see them,'' said Rudd.
	   Malaysia says the Acehnese are economic migrants and not
political refugees and hence should be deported like all other
foreigners found working without valid permits.
	   Malaysia has already deported 30,000 Indonesians this year in an
attempt to secure jobs for its own people in a sliding economy.
	   Prior to Southeast Asia's economic crisis, hundreds of thousands
of foreign workers were welcomed in Malaysia to provide much of the
work force to the booming property sector. Of its 8 million labor
force then, 3 million were migrant workers, half of them
Indonesian.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
