<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iran-Newspaper, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iranian paper stops publishing after press violation charges
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS name of newspaper throughout to Gozaresh-e-Ruz sted
Gozaresh-e-Baz &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ A new Iranian newspaper has stopped
publication after authorities charged it with frequently violating
press ethics, other newspapers reported Wednesday.
	   The liberal Gozaresh-e-Ruz was charged by the Press Supervisory
Board, and its case was forwarded Tuesday to the Justice Ministry
for review, the Iran Daily said.
	   A court case could follow and the newspaper may lose its license
if it's found guilty.
	   Another newspaper, Salam, quoted Gozaresh-e-Ruz's director
Mohammad Mahdavi Khorrami as saying he had voluntarily stopped
publishing the paper until a final verdict.
	   The action against Gozaresh-e-Ruz, or ``Day's Report,'' is seen
as a setback for the press freedom that has been allowed by
moderate President Mohammad Khatami since he took office in August.
	   It was not clear if hard-liners opposed to Khatami's reforms
were behind the crackdown on the paper.
	   The Farsi-language newspaper started publishing only last month
and on its third day it printed a front-page color picture of a
teenage boy with a teenage girl wearing a head scarf. The caption
read: ``Friendship Under Fear.''
	   The Culture Ministry warned it to ``respect the Press Law and
the society's ethical and religious standards,'' the
English-language Iran News said.
	   It quoted a ministry official, Ahmad Borqani, as saying that the
newspaper ``has followed quite an inappropriate path from the
beginning of its publication to the present day.''
	   Borqani said the paper had also printed ``a false report''
claiming that some Iranian officials had transferred money to
overseas bank accounts. Borqani said such a report is ``aimed at
disturbing public opinion and is against our national interests.''
	   Iran's constitution forbids the media from ``propagating
destructive and anti-Islamic attitudes.''
	   On Monday a court convicted the editor of the popular Jameah
newspaper of defamation and lies. The sentence was not made public.
 &UR; av-fsa/vj
</TEXT>
