<HEADLINE>
Italians arrest suspected terrorists as World Cup starts
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Italian police arrested at least 20 people suspected
of belonging to an Algerian terrorist group allegedly planning
attacks during the World Cup, which started in France on Wednesday.
	   Paramilitary police in Bologna said more than 20 people had been
arrested and dozens of others were being questioned. News reports
linked those arrested to the Armed Islamic Group, a violent Muslim
militant movement blamed for murdering tens of thousands of people
in Algeria.
	   An anti-terrorist sweep over the past month has led to nearly
100 arrests in France, Italy, Germany, Belgium and Switzerland.
	   French authorities in May said they had found evidence of
possible terrorist attacks planned during the month-long soccer
tournament, which is being played in 10 French cities.
	   Algerian militants have staged terrorist attacks in France in
the past to pressure Paris to cut its ties with the military-backed
government of the petroleum-rich North African nation.
