<SLUG> BC-EU-Mad Cow 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU Commission recommends lifting ban on most British beef
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; URGENT &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Commission approving lifting of ban &QL; 
 &UR; By PAUL AMES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ The European Commission on Wednesday
backed the lifting of the worldwide ban on British beef exports
imposed more than two years ago at the height of Europe's ``mad
cow'' scare.
	   The 20-member European Union executive body ruled British beef
and most beef products from cattle older than six months and
younger than 30 months, should be cleared for export. That would
cover most potential beef exports.
	   British Agriculture Minister Jack Cunningham told the BBC the
decision would be ``a very, very important step.''
	   However, despite the Commission's approval, the EU's complex
decision-making process means it could still take months before
British beef is back on foreign markets.
	   The decision needs approval by a panel of veterinary experts
that is scheduled to meet Friday, but the specialists are divided
and if they fail to agree, the issue will be put to a vote at a
meeting of EU agriculture ministers.
