<SLUG> BC-Papua New Guinea-Luggage </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Airline chief may be sacked after clothes mishap on state visit
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PORT MORESBY, Papua New Guinea (AP) _ The head of Papua New
Guinea's national airline may be fired after an embarrassing mishap
last week left an official delegation to Indonesia stranded without
a change of clothes, Papua New Guinea Prime Minister Bill Skate
said Wednesday.
	   Skate denied that Chris Mek, the acting managing director Air
Nuiguini had already been denied removed, but said the Cabinet will
consider his future at an upcoming meeting.
	   ``We will decide his fate,'' Skate said. ``Whether he stays or
whether he is removed to another area.
	   ``We are not going to chuck him out, we are going to find him a
job where we think he will be better utilized,'' he said.
	   The blunder happened last Wednesday, when Skate's chartered Air
Niugini airbus landed in Jakarta for a four-day state visit, but
airline staff failed to unload the luggage.
	   Members of the delegation were left without their clothes and
gifts intended for Indonesia's new President B.J. Habibie also went
missing.
	   The Papua New Guineans desperately searched for new clothes to
wear to an official state dinner on Thursday, with the prime
minister's secretary Robert Igara reportedly spending U.S. dlrs
2,000 (Australian dollars 3,400) on a formal dinner suit, two
shirts, a tie and a pair of socks.
	   Skate said he was only embarrassed by the lack of gifts to give
to Habibie. 	   
