w2697 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Switzerland-Church     06-10 0295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Switzerland-Church </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New bishop chosen to replace controversial conservative
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) _ The cathedral chapter of Chur has
chosen a new bishop to replace the controversial conservative
Wolfgang Haas, a member of the chapter said Wednesday.
	   Bishop Amedee Grab was chosen by the 24-member body of Chur
clergy from a shortlist of three candidate bishops in a closed
meeting Tuesday, said Franz Stampfli, the canon of Zurich.
	   The appointment still has to be accepted within eight days by
Grab himself and confirmed by the Vatican, Stampfli said.
	   The Chur post has been vacant since Haas in December moved to a
newly created post as archbishop of Liechtenstein.
	   The announcement came in response to mounting pressure from the
Swiss government and Catholic establishment. It was greeted by
overwhelming relief in Switzerland and surprise in neighboring
Liechtenstein.
	   Tensions between Haas and other leading Swiss Catholics had
mounted since 1990 when he took over as bishop of Chur. The diocese
covers Zurich and a large mountainous area in eastern Switzerland,
and until December also included the tiny principality of
Liechtenstein.
	   An arch-conservative, Haas angered the liberals in his flock by
opposing moves to allow in women and lay preachers.
	   Grab, 68, is currently bishop of Fribourg, Lausanne and Geneva
and president of the Swiss bishops conference. Although a
conservative, he is seen as more moderate than Haas.
	   Pope John Paul II was seen as imposing his protege Haas upon the
Swiss, whose roughly 3.5 million Catholics have a history of
independence from Rome. The pope was accused of violating a Vatican
pledge to give Chur clergy three candidate bishops to choose from.
 &UR; (gm)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Switzerland-Church; CT:i; 
