<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Farm Trouble </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mismanaged grain eroding China's ability to feed itself
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ELAINE KURTENBACH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Dishonest grain dealers are costing China
billions of dollars and have left farmers unwilling to plant more
grain _ weakening the nation's ability to feed itself, according to
state-run media reports.
	   In yet another concession to market forces, the government plans
sweeping reforms of the state grain buying system responsible for
ensuring that enough staple food reaches the country's 1.2 billion
people, the state-run Xinhua News Agency said Wednesday.
	   Under the new system, farmers are to sign contracts with
authorized grain dealers, rather than local governments, and grow
only the grain they can sell, it said.
	   Apart from ensuring food reaches all, the grain purchasing
system is the government's main tool for keeping the vast
countryside stable.
	   Farmers have watched city residents prosper while their own
incomes have lagged far behind. With unrest rising among the
millions of city dwellers laid off by reforming state-owned
factories, the ruling Communists can hardly afford to risk turmoil
in the countryside.
	   Premier Zhu Rongji announced shortly after he took office in
March that the government-run grain system would have to go.
	   Specifics of the reform plan have not yet been announced. But
reports this week in the state media documented the widespread
mismanagement and corruption.
	   They point to a severe deterioration in the grain industry, with
losses reported by state grain firms ballooning to 27 billion yuan
(dlrs 3.27 billion) in the first quarter of this year, compared
with 48 billion yuan (dlrs 5.81 billion) in 1997 and 19.7 billion
(dlrs 2.38 billion) in 1996, the Communist Party newspaper People's
Daily reported Tuesday.
	   The newspaper blamed state grain companies for being too
bureaucratic, refusing to buy grain at the subsidized prices set by
the state, and charging illegal fees and taxes.
	   Government funds intended for grain purchases often were
embezzled or funneled into other uses. Farmers have been forced to
sell the grain at lower prices than promised and are sometimes paid
with IOU's.
	   Imbalance between supply and demand has pushed prices lower by
30 percent or more, despite government promises that state
purchasing price would remain steady.
	   The Xinhua report noted that farmers in central Hubei province
had produced 48.6 percent more rice per capita in 1997 than in
1996, but that their per capita income from grain sales had fallen
because of a glut.
	   Meanwhile, food processing factories were using imported wheat
because locally grown varieties were not suitable for their
products, it said.
	   The reports of troubles inside the grain distribution system
come as some experts warn of a growing gap between China's needs
and its ability to increase grain production.
	   They believe that water shortages, limits on the ability of
farmers to boost yields through better technology and the loss of
farmland to other uses will force China to import growing amounts
of grain over the next few decades, putting pressure on world grain
prices. 	   
</TEXT>
