</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-World Cup-Street Battles </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police say 34 injured in clashes
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JOCELYN NOVECK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Late-night clashes between drunken soccer fans,
Parisian youths and riot police left 34 policemen injured,
including one who was in critical condition after being hit in the
head with a beer bottle, police said Wednesday.
	   The others were only slightly injured, according to a midmorning
police report. The man in critical condition was the commander of a
motorcycle unit.
	   About 15 people were arrested in the unrest, during which police
used tear gas to disperse drunken soccer fans and apparently also
Parisian youths who threw bottles and tried to knock down a phalanx
of policemen, using a steel barrier as a battering ram.
	   Two of those in custody were Scots, police said. An Algerian, a
Liberian and a Congolese were also arrested. The nationalities of
the others weren't immediately known.
	   The World Cup kicks off later Wednesday with the opening match
between Brazil and Scotland. Thousands of Scottish fans have
descended on Paris for the match.
	   The incidents Tuesday night and early Wednesday on the
Champs-Elysees marred the festive atmosphere of the meticulously
planned pre-World Cup events.
	   They came as four ``giants'' _ 60-foot-tall robots _ made their
way through the city to the Place de la Concorde, where tens of
thousands watched a spectacle involving acrobats and dancers in
fanciful costumes.
	   Scottish fans said Wednesday that it wasn't all the fault of the
soccer fans. They said youths from Paris' troubled suburbs actually
began the disturbances.
	   ``Some young kids started throwing things just for the hell of
it, I think,'' said Derek Christie, from Fife in Scotland.
	   ``Everybody was having a good time, and I don't think they liked
it,'' said his friend, John Morrison, of Iverness.
	   When the unrest between the groups got out of hand, the police
charged, they and other witnesses said.
	   Christie and Morrison were strolling through Paris Wednesday,
waiting for their team's late-afternoon match.
	   In London, the Foreign Office said two Scots were in custody in
Paris, but they said it was a separate incident from the troubles
in the center of Paris.
	   ``They are currently being held in police custody on assault
charges,'' a spokesman said.
	   In the early morning hours Wednesday, bands of soccer fans were
roving the streets, many desperately seeking transportation back to
where they were staying.
	   Outside a Scottish pub in the Marais district, a group of
partying fans in kilts blocked traffic. When a taxi tried to drive
through, the fans surrounded it, a few of them jumping on the hood
and pounding on the windows. The taxi, and other cars, hastily
retreated.
	   The trouble began around 10:30 p.m., when dozens of people threw
beer bottles at the helmeted riot police, who responded by charging
at them. The fans dispersed. The incident was repeated several
times.
	   About an hour later, just after midnight, several hundred
people, led by young fans armed with security barriers as battering
rams, tried to break through a line of policemen on the
Champs-Elysees.
	   This time police charged them and used tear gas. The fans
quickly dispersed.
	   While the police were clashing with the youths, tourists and
passers-by, in the area to soak up the post-parade atmosphere,
snapped pictures or filmed them with minicams.
	   (jn-parf-mr-var) 	   
</TEXT>
