<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Labor-Indonesia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. agency chiefs welcome Indonesian adoption of labor standards
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   GENEVA (AP) _ International Labor Office chief Michel Hansenne
and U.N. human rights commissioner Mary Robinson Wednesday welcomed
Indonesia's decision to ratify an international convention
guaranteeing workers' trade union rights.
	   ``The ratification of this all-important convention represents a
major step on the road to institutionalizing democracy and human
rights in the workplace,'' ILO Director-General Hansenne said in a
statement issued during the U.N. agency's 86th annual conference.
	   The formal signing of the convention and adoption of other ILO
international labor standards is the latest indication of
Indonesia's reformist approach to workers' rights following the
rise to power of new president B.J. Habibie.
	   Since he took over from ex-president Suharto, Habibie has
relaxed tight restrictions on labor unions and freed prominent
political prisoners including trade unionist Muchtar Pakpahan.
	   Indonesia's manpower minister Fahmi Idris formally notified
Hansenne of Indonesia's ratification of the convention at a
conference session Wednesday.
	   On Tuesday, Idris indicated the country's intention to ratify
other ILO conventions on abolition of forced labor and workplace
discrimination.
	   ``The ILO stands ready to help Indonesia in the transformation
under way,'' Hansenne said.
	   In the first appearance of a U.N. human rights commissioner at
an ILO conference, Robinson on Wednesday applauded Indonesia's
decision.
	   She urged the swift adoption by countries of a new convention on
the worst forms of child labor and said she was ``heartened'' by
the conference's discussion of a proposed declaration on workers'
fundamental rights.
 &UR; (pw)
</TEXT>
