<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Spain-Atlantic Record, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cross-Atlantic speed record broken by Australian-built ferry
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with company claiming a second record; CORRECTS style
in 2nd graf &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   CEUTA, Spain (AP) _ The record for the fastest Atlantic crossing
by a commercial passenger vessel has been broken by an
Australian-built ferry, the company said Wednesday.
	   The 91-meter (300 foot) Catalonia arrived in the Spanish enclave
city of Ceuta in north Africa around 10:00 p.m (20:00 GMT) Tuesday,
clocking an average speed of 40 knots during it's cross-Atlantic
sprint that began in New York at 0035gmt on Sunday, said Ivonne
Sentis, spokeswoman for Buquebus, an Argentine-Uruguayan company
which owns the ferry.
	   Hoverspeed Great Britain set the previous record with an average
speed of 36.65 knots in 1990. Both ships were built by Incat
Australia.
	   Winning the record carries with it the Hales Trophy, donated by
British Member of Parliament Harold Hales in 1933, and first held
by the Italian Liner Rez which set a speed of 29 knots in the same
year.
	   The Catalonia claimed a second record when it became the first
commercial vessel to sail more than 1,000 nautical miles in a 24
hour period, its maker Incat Australia said. Its top 24-hour run
was 1,015 nautical miles.
	   To qualify for a record attempt the ships must not refuel en
route.
	   Within the next few days, the 450-ton catamaran is due to make
its way around southern Spain and up the eastern coast to the city
of Barcelona.
	   The ferry, that has room for 900 passengers and 240 cars, is to
work the route between Barcelona and the Mediterranean resort
island of Mallorca from June 15.
	   It is scheduled to make that far less demanding crossing in
about three hours.
	   (jt/mr)
</TEXT>
