</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thai stock market drops below 300 for first time in 10 1/2 years
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with closing stock prices, other details; ADDS photo
tag
 &UR; AP Photos BK101,BK105

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Thailand's stock exchange index on
Wednesday fell below 300 points for the first time in 10 1/2 years,
as share prices made their biggest single-day drop in four months
because of worries about debt-servicing capabilities.
	   The Stock Exchange of Thailand index closed at 292.10 points,
down 16.15 points from Tuesday.
	   An estimated 118 million shares valued at 1.63 billion baht
(dlrs 37.9 million) changed hands Wednesday, up from some 92.7
million shares valued at 1.31 billion baht (dlrs 30.5 million)
traded the previous session.
	   At Wednesday's close, the SET index was down 21.6 percent from
its closing level on the last trading day of 1997.
	   Dealers attributed the market's plunge to selling by foreign
investors concerned that Thai companies will have increasing
trouble financing their debt.
	   On Wednesday, a big listed company, Robinson Department Store,
announced it would stop servicing about 6.8 billion yen (dlrs 48.2
million) in floating-rate notes for six months while it completes a
corporate restructuring.
	   The company said, however, that it will remain in business. Its
stock closed at 1.20 baht (dlrs 0.028) a share, down 0.40 baht
(dlrs 0.009)
	   ``The outlook for the stock market will be very dim until we
know all these companies will be able to service their debts,''
said Songyos Kulvichien, a dealer with Securities One. ``So far,
there's been no reassurance on that front.''
	   Analysts have long identified 300 points as a key support level
for the exchange's index, meaning a decline below that point would
trigger a massive sell-off.
	   The index hasn't been below 300 points since Jan. 4, 1988, when
it closed at 287.71. At that time the index was just beginning to
recover from the Wall Street stock market crash of October 1987.
	   Some dealers surmised the across-the-board sell-off might also
reflect a decision by fund managers to concentrate their
investments outside Asia's troubled emerging markets.
	   Thailand's stock market enjoyed a healthy rebound in the first
half of the year, they said, making it attractive for investors to
cash in the gains rather than take the risks associated with
waiting any longer.
</TEXT>
