u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Philippines-AirlineSt 2ndLd-Writethru   06-10 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Airline Strike, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine Airlines declares pilot strike over, to reduce
</HEADLINE>
operations
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with union reaction in grafs 8 and 9; trims
 &UR; By JIM GOMEZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Financially beleaguered Philippine
Airlines announced Wednesday it will no longer accept back about
600 striking pilots and will sharply reduce its operations to match
the few pilots it now has.
	   In a surprise move, the airline said it will sell several of its
54 aircraft, including some just purchased, and concentrate on
domestic routes to cope with the effects of the five-day walkout.
	   The airline said it now considers the strike over because the
pilots defied a government back-to-work order Tuesday and have all
been fired.
	   PAL said it will operate with just 25 management pilots _ senior
pilots who train other pilots _ until it is able to hire and train
new personnel.
	   It has already begun the process of hiring replacements, it
said.
	   ``The strike is over and a downsized Philippine Airlines emerges
from the five-day illegal walkout,'' it said in a statement.
	   ``The move will maximize PAL's limited capacity to sustain
financial viability under the present circumstances,'' it said.
	   The pilots' union said it was not surprised by the dismissals
and would not capitulate.
	   ``We still believe in what we're espousing,'' said Capt. Amy
Gloria, a union spokeswoman.
	   The union repeatedly refused attempts by the labor department to
formally deliver the back-to-work order and continued its walkout
despite appeals from President Fidel Ramos.
	   Ramos urged both sides Wednesday to resume negotiations.
	   The pilots began the strike Friday to protest a management
policy of ordering pilots to retire who have reached 20 years of
service or flown 20,000 hours, regardless of age. The policy puts
about 200 pilots in danger of forced retirement, the union said.
	   PAL, however, said it was not a unilateral management policy but
a provision in a collective bargaining agreement signed by airline
and union officials.
	   The airline earlier announced plans to sharply reduce staff,
slash costs and cut flights to survive its long-term financial
problems.
	   Talks at the labor department Wednesday on the dispute ended
without success.
	   PAL said the strike has cost it about 150 million pesos (dlrs
3.8 million) a day in lost revenue. It said it lost 8 billion pesos
(dlrs 205 million) in the last fiscal year _ three times more than
the previous year.
	   PAL president Jose Antonio Garcia said the strike caused several
potential foreign buyers of the airline, including Northwest
Airlines, to break off talks.
	   The strike has affected thousands of passengers and is
threatening to prevent many Filipino and foreign guests from
visiting the country to celebrate the June 12 centennial of the
Philippines' declaration of independence from more than 300 years
of Spanish colonial rule.
	   PAL earlier tried to recover from its spiraling losses with an
ambitious dlrs 4 billion modernization program, ordering 36 new
aircraft. But Asia's currency crisis sharply reduced passenger
numbers and bloated the airline's debt in local currency terms,
forcing it to delay many of the orders.
	   PAL, Asia's first airline, is controlled by Chinese Filipino
tycoon Lucio Tan. It had been completely owned by the Philippine
government until it was partly sold in 1992.
</TEXT>
