<SLUG> BC-Nigeria-Army Rulers-Box </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nigeria's many army rulers
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Nigeria &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Since the end of British colonial rule,
much of Nigeria's 38 years of independence have been under military
rule. A list of Nigeria's past army leaders:
	   _Maj. Gen. Johnson Aguiyi-Ironsi; seizes power in a January 1966
coup.
	   _Lt. Col. (later Gen.) Yakubu Gowan; installed as head of state
in July 1966 after Aguiyi-Ironsi is assassinated.
	   _Gen. Murtala Ramat Mohammed; assumes power in July 1975 after
Gowan is ousted in a bloodless coup while attending an Organization
of African Unity summit in Uganda.
	   _Lt. Col. Bukar Dimka; believed to have held power very briefly
after assassinating Mohammed in February 1976.
	   _Lt. Gen. Olusegun Obasanjo; emerges in full control of the
country in February 1976 after several days of confusion following
Mohammed's assassination.
	   _Maj. Gen. Muhammadu Buhari; seizes power after leading a coup
on Dec. 31, 1983, to depose civilian government of President Shehu
Shagari.
	   _Gen. Ibrahim Babangida; assumes power in August 1985 after
peacefully deposing Buhari.
	   _Gen. Sani Abacha; declares he is head of state in November 1993
after resignation of interim civilian leader Ernest Shonekan who
was installed following the cancellation of presidential elections
in June of that year.
	   _Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar; sworn in as head of state in a
pre-dawn ceremony June 9, 1998, hours after Abacha's death by heart
attack is announced.
 &UR; (ids/bk)
</TEXT>
