<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 1100 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Many Asian stock markets and currencies plunged
through important support levels Wednesday as the U.S. dollar
climbed to a new seven-year high against the yen, sparking fears
that China would soon be forced to devalue its currency. The
benchmark Thai index closed at its 10 1/2-year low, while the index
in Singapore plunged to its seven-year low. Hong Kong stocks also
dropped to their three-year lows. Southeast Asian currencies also
sank lower against the U.S. dollar after U.S. investment bank
Morgan Stanley released a report revising downward its region
exchange rate forecasts for 1998. The Thai baht, the Indonesian
rupiah, the Singapore dollar and the New Taiwan dollar all breached
important support levels. In late afternoon trading, the dollar
bought 140.84 yen, up 0.48 yen from late Tuesday in Tokyo and above
its late New York level of 140.30 yen overnight. Tokyo's benchmark
225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 190.91 points, or 1.23 percent,
closing at 15,339.26. (ASIAN MARKETS)
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ The European Commission on Wednesday
recommended the lifting of the ban on British beef exports imposed
more than two years ago at the height of Europe's ``mad cow''
scare. The 20-member European Union executive body ruled British
beef and most beef products from cattle older than 6 months and
younger than 30 months should be cleared for export. That would
cover most potential beef exports. However, despite the
Commission's approval, the EU's complex decision-making process
means it could still take months before British beef is back on
foreign markets. (EU-MAD COW)
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Sales and profits for Japanese companies fell in
the quarter ended in March as managers said they are more
pessimistic about the economy than they've been in at least 15
years, according to a government survey released Wednesday. Pretax
profits for Japanese companies plunged 25.4 percent in the three
months ended in March compared with a year earlier as sales sank
6.8 percent, the largest decline in 40 years, the Ministry of
Finance said in a quarterly survey. The report follows a string of
bad news for the Japanese economy which is stuck in its worst
slowdown in decades. Many economists expect a report due out later
this week will show the country has sunk into recession.
(JAPAN-COMPANY PROFITS)
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russian stocks took a double beating Wednesday,
dropping because of market falls in Asia and fears that Western
governments won't bail Moscow out of its financial mess, traders
said. The Russia Trading System (RTS) index fell 5.8 percent in the
first 90 minutes of trading, dropping to 185.13. Volume was light,
but traders said Russian financial institutions were selling
aggressively. The Russian economy is stagnating, with little or no
growth in most areas. The government has promised deep cuts in
public spending and improved tax collection to try to improve the
situation. (RUSSIA-MARKETS)
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Three leading South Korean companies
have joined in a dlrs 2.6 million joint venture to search for
copper in Australia, company officials said Wednesday. Samsung,
Hyundai and Daewoo will join in the search along with South Korea's
state-run Korea Resources Corp. and Australia's Malachite Resources
N.N. and LFB Resources N.L. Korea Resources Corp. entered into a
50-50 joint venture with the two Australian concerns in February.
It now has to split its 50 percent share equally with the three new
Korean companies. (SKOREA-AUSTRALIA-COPPER)
</TEXT>
