<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0669 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of late news from The Associated Press. Some items
have moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f''
category codes:
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Nigeria's new military ruler says he
supports a transition to civilian rule, although Gen. Abdulsalam
Abubakar has given little indication of how the enormous shift from
his predecessor's brutal dictatorship will be carried out as
quickly as anticipated. Air Vice Marshal Mohammed Alfa, a senior
military junta aide, told reporters Tuesday that Abubakar would
turn the country over to an elected civilian government by Oct. 1.
Neither he nor Abubakar provided details. In his first address to
the nation, Abubakar did say Tuesday night that Nigeria's many
political exiles are welcome home. His televised address came hours
after the military junta appointed him to replace Gen. Sani Abacha,
who died Monday of a heart attack. (NIGERIA)
	   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) _ Eritrean forces attacked Ethiopia's
biggest border post during a dawn raid Wednesday, the government
said. Spokeswoman Salome Tadesse said the attack in northwest
Tigray province, on the Badme-Shiraro front at Erde Mattios,
started at 6 a.m. She said there were no further details except
that the fighting is continuing. Ethiopia says Eritrea set off the
current border conflict on May 6 when it moved into Ethiopian
territory in that region. The Ethiopians said Tuesday's attack came
from Eritrean forces inside Ethiopia. A languishing peace proposal
put forth by the United States and Rwanda includes a recommendation
that Eritrea withdraw to positions it held prior to May 6.
(ETHIOPIA-ERITREA)
	   BOMBAY, India (AP) _ Relief workers distributed food and
searched for bodies in the debris of smashed homes after a cyclone
tore through western India, killing 205 people, injuring 1,200 and
leaving hundreds of thousands homeless. Officials said Wednesday
that the toll from the cyclone, India's worst in 25 years, could
rise because many people remain missing and relief workers have yet
to reach some remote villages. The death toll was highest in Kutch
district, where a 3-meter (12-foot) tidal wave flooded low-lying
areas near Kandla, a port 290 kilometers (180 miles) northwest of
Bombay. As many as 140 people, including fishermen and port
workers, drowned or were swept into the Arabian Sea, government
officials said. Some 125 people have been listed as missing and
officials fear the casualty figure could surpass 200 in Kutch
alone. (INDIA-CYCLONE)
	   DILI, Indonesia (AP) _ Rejecting a presidential promise of
special status for their homeland within Indonesia, thousands of
East Timorese demonstrated Wednesday for the right to vote for full
independence. More than 3,000 students and others gathered on the
grounds of the state-funded University of East Timor. ``We want
total independence. We want to be free,'' said Licinio Branco at
the noisy but peaceful rally. Organizers called for a full and free
referendum on the future of East Timor, a former Portuguese colony
invaded by Indonesian troops in December 1975 and annexed in
January 1976. Since then, the territory has endured human rights
abuses and separatist rebels have fought a guerrilla war.
(INDONESIA)
	   PARIS (AP) _ Air France said Wednesday it reached an agreement
with striking pilots, ending a walkout that severely embarrassed
the country in the days leading up to the World Cup. In a
statement, Air France said the pilots agreed to accept company
shares in exchange for salary cuts. The company called for an
immediate return to work. But the airline has said previously it
would take three days for service to return to normal once the
strike ended. Just Tuesday night, as World Cup celebrations began
in Paris, negotiations had seemed deadlocked. Pilots had gathered
at Charles de Gaulle airport and agreed to continue the walkout,
despite an appeal by the transport minister to both sides to
continue talking. (AIR FRANCE)
</TEXT>
