<SLUG> BC-Sudan-Attack,0291 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Three aid workers killed in ambush in southern Sudan
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MOHAMED OSMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) _ Armed assailants opened fire at a United
Nations relief convoy in southern Sudan, killing three officials
and wounding four others, the official Sudanese News Agency
reported Wednesday.
	   SUNA said two of those killed in Tuesday's attack worked for the
U.N.'s World Food Program and the third was attached with the
International Committee of the Red Cross. All victims were
Sudanese, sources told The Associated Press.
	   Among the injured was a government soldier, SUNA said.
	   A Sudanese government minister, Gen. Hassan Dahawi, accused the
rebel group Sudan People's Liberation Army of carrying out the
attack on the three-car convoy in the Southern Kordofan province,
about 500 kilometers (310 miles) southwest of the capital Khartoum.
	   The WFP office in Khartoum refused to comment.
	   The ICRC resumed only last week its relief work in southern
Sudan, which had been suspended in November 1996 after a rebel
faction allied with the government seized a relief plane and three
Red Cross workers.
	   ``We call upon all U.N. organizations and the voluntary
organizations to continue their humanitarian mission without paying
attention to such ugly provocations that target humanity and
peace,'' Dahawi was quoted as saying by SUNA.
	   SPLA rebels have been fighting since 1983 for autonomy and
development in the predominantly Christian, African and animist
south, which has traditionally been dominated by the Muslim and
Arabized north.
	   An estimated 1.5 million people have died in the fighting and
related famines. The WFP runs a big program in the south to feed
the people. 	   
</TEXT>
