w2747 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UN-SovietDrugs     06-10 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Soviet Drugs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Drug problem is downside of the collapse of Soviet Union
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ROBERT H. REID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Taking advantage of the collapse of the
Soviet Union, drug traffickers have established links across
Central Asia to smuggle narcotics from Afghanistan to lucrative
markets in Western Europe.
	   Leaders of the newly independent states such as Tajikistan,
Uzbekistan and the Kyrgyz Republic complain they lack the resources
to combat criminal syndicates based in Russia and Western Europe.
	   The end of the Soviet Union, with its police state internal
controls, gave traffickers a freer hand to move large amounts of
opium and other drugs across Central Asia to markets in Western
Europe.
	   ``The drug problem is acute throughout the Central Asian
region,'' the prime minister of the Kyrgyz, Kubanychbek Jumaliev,
told the U.N. special session on drugs Tuesday. The three-day
conference ends Wednesday.
	   ``Two or three years ago, people in Kyrgyzstan had only a
theoretical idea what heroin is,'' Jumaliev said. ``Nowadays, it
has become one of the main drugs on the illegal market.''
	   U.N. officials say the problem is made worse because of the
decades-long instability in Afghanistan, which along with Myanmar
produces most of the world's illicit supply of opium.
	   The newly independent states of Central Asia, some of which have
suffered their own internal instability, lack the means to control
their borders and maintain surveillance on drug traffickers moving
in and out of Afghanistan.
	   ``Today, it is possible to say with confidence that the main
source of growing, producing and delivering drugs to the European
countries is Afghanistan,'' said Foreign Minister Abdulaziz Kamilov
of Uzbekistan.
	   Afghan factions permit the drug trade to earn money to buy more
weapons, which in turn produces more fighting and instability, he
said.
	   The president of Tajikistan, Emomali Rakhmonov, complained that
the international community has devoted considerable resources to
combatting drugs in Latin America and Southeast Asia but has left
poor Central Asian states on their own.
	   Rakhmonov said that in 1991, the year the Soviet Union
collapsed, police in Tajikistan seized only 10 kilograms (22
pounds) of narcotics. In 1997, Tajik police seized more than 4.5
tons.
	   He estimated that the figure seized amounts to no more than 15
percent of the total amount of drugs which passed through Tajik
territory.
	   ``The Republic of Tajikistan is not yet in a condition to
finance independently the programs and measures to combat this
evil,'' Rakhmonov said. ``We require active support and assistance
to block and control illicit drug traffic.''
	   Officials from those countries said privately they would like
the European Union to provide more assistance since most of the
drugs passing through Central Asia will end up sold on the streets
of Berlin, Paris, London and other Western European cities.
	   Kamilov suggested that the European Union help Central Asian
states establish a coordination center to monitor the flow of drugs
and develop plans for curbing the flow.
</TEXT>
