<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Armed Forces-Harassment </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sexual harassment rife in defense force school, investigation
</HEADLINE>
finds &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) _ Australia's defense training school
has a pervasive culture of sexual harassment with half of the
female cadets and one in ten men experiencing unwanted sexual
advances, a new report released Wednesday said.
	   Problems at the Australian Defense Force Academy stem from a
culture in which ``seemingly decent and personable young men and
women engaged in extraordinarily nasty and brutish activities,''
the report said.
	   The report is the product of a study, conducted jointly by
defense personnel and academics, commissioned after news reports
that sexual misconduct was rife throughout the Australian Defense
Force.
	   It found 14 female cadets at the academy said they had suffered
sexual assault or attempted sexual assault, as did one male cadet.
Fellow cadets were the culprits in the majority of cases and
excessive alcohol consumption was a major contributing factor.
	   The report said the number of incidents at the academy was
substantially higher than the reported incidence of sexual
misconduct in the wider forces, despite a well-publicized policy of
zero tolerance of sexual harassment.
	   ``Crude and offensive behaviors are experienced by both male and
female cadets but the sexist behaviors are experienced mainly by
females,'' the report said.
	   ``It would appear that at the Defense Academy these behaviors
have become a pervasive and public feature of the environment, part
of the day to day social life of cadets.''
	   The situation at academy is very similar to comparable academies
in the United Kingdom, the United States and Canada, the report
said.
	   Defense Force Chief General John Baker said the review found a
culture within the cadet body which conflicted with the aims of the
institution.
	   ``We have a zero tolerance for all forms of sexual harassment
and this report gives us the way ahead,'' Baker said of the
recommendations, which include curbing cadets' drinking.
	   He said he expected cadets and other armed forces personnel to
undertake a higher standard of personal conduct than members of the
general public.
	   The impact of reforms introduced as a result of the report will
be felt throughout the armed forces, Baker said.
</TEXT>
