<SLUG> BC-Poland-Railway Strike </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Polish train drivers threaten nationwide strike
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ Train drivers on Wednesday threatened to
strike next week unless the government-run railway meets their
demands for pay raises and earlier retirement.
	   Jan Zaborowski, head of the train drivers' union, said the
government has until June 16 _ or one week _ to meet the demands.
Otherwise, the strike would begin June 17.
	   A spokeswoman for the Transport Ministry said negotiations
between the union and the government were under way.
	   The drivers want a 300-zloty (dlrs-88) raise in their monthly
pay, currently about 1,000 zlotys (dlrs 300).
	   They want to be eligible for retirement at 55 if they have
worked for at least 20 years. They want the age limit dropped for
those who have worked for at least 30 years. The current retirement
age is 65 for men and 60 for women.
	   In addition, the drivers want the government to funnel 1 percent
of its annual budget to subsidize the railways, which are strapped
for cash but need to lower prices to compete with cheaper road
travel.
 &UR; (ms-aet)
