</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Greece-Bank Protest </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Court rules bank strike illegal
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ In the third decision of its kind in the
past two weeks, a court ruled Wednesday that the month-long strike
by employees of Greece's fourth largest bank was illegal.
	   Ionian Bank employees, who walked off the job on May 8, are
protesting plans to privatize the bank.
	   The strike has threatened to derail government efforts to
streamline the economy and meet European Union criteria for joining
its single currency club in 2001.
	   A court has ruled twice before that the strike is illegal, on
grounds that no skeleton staff were appointed to serve customers.
	   Both times, workers claimed they would not be violating the
court orders by failing to return to work if they were covered by
strikes called by umbrella trade union organizations.
	   But the latest ruling against the strike, this time declared by
GSEE, Greece's largest trade union, leaves workers with no
alternative but to return to work or risk losing their jobs.
	   The court also banned any new strike with the same demands and
said GSEE leaders will be liable for a fine of 500,000 drachmas
(dlrs 1,655) each for every additional strike day.
	   During the trial, Ionian deputy general manager Emmanouil
Santorineos said the bank's operation has been completely paralyzed
since the strike began, with 45,000 civil servants unable to
receive their salaries as their accounts had effectively been
frozen.
	   Before the court decision was announced, Ionian union leaders
said they would continue their strike until Thursday and then chose
``other forms of protest,'' local media reported.
	   There was no immediate reaction from the union after the court
ruling.
	   GSEE has also called for a demonstration outside the bank's main
computer center on Thursday ``to condemn the authoritarianism
criminalization of workers' mobilizations.''
	   Workers have not been bowed by the government's concession to
one of their main demands last week _ providing current Ionian
employees with a guaranteed job until the retirement age of 62 _
saying they want to see the concession in writing.
	   (eb) 	   
</TEXT>
