<SLUG> BC-Sri Lanka-War,0280 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Defense minister says 433 killed in latest battle
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) _ Recent fighting between Sri Lankan
forces and Tamil rebels for the control of a strategic highway
killed 433 people, the country's defense minister said Wednesday.
	   Defense Minister Anuruddha Ratwatte, speaking in Parliament,
said 198 soldiers, 10 officers and 225 Tamil Tiger rebels were
killed in fighting since May 28 in the north where militants among
the country's minority Tamils are fighting for an independent
homeland.
	   Ratwatte said his troops were in control of the operation.
	   The statement was the first official report of the major
military operation to dislodge rebels of the Liberation Tigers of
Tamil Eelam from the highway that will link the former rebel city
of Jaffna with the rest of the country.
	   Ratwatte said the news censorship imposed on reporting of the
war was a temporary measure. It was aimed at not letting the enemy
know about government operation.
	   He said 206 soldiers suffered major injuries and 1,269 sustained
minor injuries during the operation. Many of those who sustained
minor injuries have gone back to the battle front.
	   He said the Tamil Tiger rebels lost at least 225 combatants and
600 were wounded.
	   Government troops backed by the artillery and air force are
fighting near Mankulam, the last Tamil-held town on a road that
troops have been trying to capture since May 1997.
	   Rebels among Sri Lanka's minority Tamils want a homeland in the
north and the east to end what they call discrimination by the
majority Sinhalese. The war, which started in 1983, has left more
than 52,000 people dead. 	   
</TEXT>
