<SLUG> BC-Asian Markets, 2nd-Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Asian markets continue slide on weak yen
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS Singapore stock index fall to ``9 1/2 year low'' from
``7-year low,'' grafs 2 and 16.

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Many Asian stock markets and currencies plunged
through important support levels Wednesday as the U.S. dollar
climbed to a new seven-year high against the yen, sparking fears
that China would soon be forced to devalue its currency.
	   The benchmark Thai index closed at its 10 and a half-year low,
while the index in Singapore plunged to a 9 1/2 year low. Hong Kong
stocks also dropped to their three year lows.
	   Southeast Asian currencies also sank lower against the U.S.
dollar after U.S. investment bank Morgan Stanley released a report
revising downward its region exchange rate forecasts for 1998.
	   The Thai baht, the Indonesian rupiah, the Singapore dollar and
the New Taiwan dollar all breached important support levels.
	   Many investors were reluctant to bid up stocks and currencies
ahead of a meeting of finance officials from the Group of Seven
industrialized nations scheduled to open in Paris later Wednesday.
	   ``No one knows what will come out of the G-7 deputy's meeting
and people are nervous,'' said Yasuhisa Morikuni, assistant vice
president at Bank of America.
	   The unease stems from concern the yen could fall further against
the dollar if officials attending the G-7 meeting do not issue a
statement pledging to support the battered Japanese currency.
	   In late afternoon trading, the dollar bought 140.84 yen, up 0.48
yen from late Tuesday in Tokyo and above its late New York level of
140.30 yen overnight.
	   During Wednesday's trading, the currency moved as high as 141.57
yen, its highest level since June 1991.
	   Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 190.91
points, or 1.23 percent, closing at 15,339.26.
	   The yen's fall has made the price of Japanese exports cheaper in
foreign markets. Investors worry that a further drop in the yen
will force Japan's Asian neighbors, including China, to devalue
their currencies to remain competitive.
	   Hong Kong's Chief Executive reiterated Wednesday that the
government will keep the currency peg, saying floating the currency
would ``cause speculative attacks against the Hong Kong dollar and
increase interest rates.''
	   His comments immediately sparked a surge in the interbank
interest rates, which dragged down share prices in the afternoon.
	   Hong Kong's benchmark Hang Seng Index nosedived 412.09 points,
or 4.9 percent, to close at 7,979.37, adding to Tuesday's
2.3-percent drop.
	   ``It was mostly panic-selling by the big fund houses. They were
reducing their weightings on Hong Kong stocks,'' said Francis Lun,
research analyst at Pacific Challenge Securities Ltd.
	   In Singapore, the key Straits Times Industrial Index easily
breached a key support level of 1,100 in early trading and fell 49
points to close at 1,067.81, a 9 1/2 year low.
	   The index's previous low this year was on Jan. 12, when it hit
1073.47 in what was considered the peak of the regional economic
crisis.
	   The U.S. dollar was quoted at a four-month high of 1.7215
Singapore dollars in morning trading, and fluctuated within one
Singapore cent through the day.
	   ``One or two political leaders have come up to warn about
retrenchments this year. That is probably the clearest sign that we
are headed for some pretty turbulent waters,'' said Chia Yew Boon,
research director at Santander Investment Securities.
	   In Bangkok, the benchmark stock index dropped 16.15 points to
292.10 points, ending below 300 points for the first time in
10-and-a-half years.
	   The baht fell through the key support of 43.00 baht to the
dollar level, trading at 43.23 to the U.S. dollar in afternoon
trading.
	   Dealers said foreign investors are growing worried that Thai
companies will have increasing trouble financing their debts.
	   Indonesia's rupiah fell to a four-month low of 13,000 rupiah to
the U.S. dollar late Wednesday, a level not seen before former
president Suharto resigned last month.
	   After falling to 13,000, the rupiah rebounded slightly and ended
Jakarta trading at 12,950, down from 11,750 late Tuesday.
	   The JSX Composite Index closed down 0.7 percent, or 2.992
points, at 408.080.
	   In Taipei, the Weighted Price Index plunged 3.1 percent to
7,223.13, while the New Taiwan dollar finished at a new 11-year low
against the U.S. dollar.
	   The U.S. dollar breached the important barrier of 35.000 dollar
level 30 minutes before the closing bell, but ended a touch lower
at 34.896.
	   In Kuala Lumpur, the Composite Index fell 3.1 percent to close
at 489.86 points.
	   The dollar was quoted at a midrange of 3.9800 ringgit, up from
3.9500 late Tuesday.
	   In Seoul, the benchmark index also plunged 4.3 percent, closing
at 324.54.
	   In New Zealand, the key index plunged 30.47 points to 2,067.47,
its lowest level since July 1996.
	   Elsewhere:
	   SYDNEY : The key Australian index ending 1.2 percent lower at
2,623.9, the lowest close since mid-January.
	   MANILA: Stock prices fell for the third day. The key index fell
0.3 percent to 1,917.87.
</TEXT>
