<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Military Thefts </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Intelligence report indicates possible left-wing involvement in
</HEADLINE>
thefts &QL; 
 &UR; By PAT REBER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ Government officials can't
seem to agree whether it was right-wing or left-wing activists who
stole weapons and ammunition from a military base over the past
several weeks.
	   A police intelligence report indicates that members of the
former anti-apartheid liberation armies stole the materiel to be
used in disrupting next year's elections, SABC radio reported
Wednesday.
	   The report contradicts comments by government officials last
week that the thefts were connected to right-wing pro-apartheid
whites who wanted to create havoc.
	   SABC said it obtained a copy of the secret report and that it
was compiled by Police commissioner George Fivaz to be presented to
President Nelson Mandela and Parliament last week.
	   But Mandela's spokesman denied the report had been destined for
the president.
	   ``The report was not meant for the president,'' spokesman Parks
Mankahlana told The Associated Press. ``We have decided the matter
will be handled by Commissioner Fivaz.''
	   SABC said Parliament never received the report. It was told
instead by a Defense Department official that the thefts had a
right-wing connection.
	   Fivaz and the parliamentary committee on security could not be
immediately reached for comment.
	   SABC said the secret report named a group behind the thefts as
MKAPLA _ an acronym connecting the ruling African National
Congress' former armed wing to the Azanian People's Liberation
Army, another former anti-apartheid military group.
	   In an SABC interview, Mankahlana dismissed the report as
possibly being one of a number of ludicrous and unfounded documents
that have been emerging.
	   Earlier this year, South Africa's military chief Georg Meiring
resigned amid a controversy stirred up by a report about a coup
plot that the government says never existed. Meiring had given the
report to Mandela. A panel of judges said the report was unfounded
and never taken seriously by military personnel.
	   Three men with alleged right wing connections were arrested for
the theft of 117 weapons _ including mortars and rocket launchers _
and 200,000 rounds of ammunition from a truck from Tempe base.
	   Last week, a group calling itself the Boere Weerstandsbewging,
or Boer's Resistance Movement, claimed the theft was done by Boers,
the white descendants of Dutch settlers.
	   (pr-aos)
</TEXT>
