<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Guinea-Bissau </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Talks seek peaceful end to coup attempt in Guinea-Bissau
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ A parliamentary delegation scheduled a
meeting Wednesday with renegade soldiers holed up in a military
installation since launching a coup attempt four days ago in this
West African nation.
	   Parliamentarian Zinha Vaz said in a telephone interview
broadcast by Portuguese state radio RDP-Africa that the meeting
would be held at 11 a.m. (1100GMT)near the suburban military
complex. Whether the meeting had begun on schedule could not be
confirmed immediately.
	   The four-member delegation, which was hoping to end the standoff
between the rebels and government troops surrounding the base,
included leaders from each of the four parties represented in
Parliament.
	   Vaz declined to comment on the agenda for the talks, but said
the aim was to seek a peaceful resolution to the conflict.
	   Loyalist troops have tried unsuccessfully to dislodge the rebels
from the arms depot and barracks at Bra, 15 kilometers (10 miles)
outside Bissau, the capital. The former Portuguese colony has a
population of 1 million.
	   Troops from neighboring Senegal and the Republic of Guinea
arrived in the country on Tuesday to support the government forces.
	   The rebels, led by former armed forces chief Brig. Gen. Ansumane
Mane, have demanded that President Joao Bernardo Vieira and the
government step down and that a transition government be installed
ahead of elections in July.
	   There was no information on the size or firepower of the rebel
force.
	   A spokesman for the U.S. embassy in Bissau said it was quiet
Tuesday night.
	   ``There was some sporadic mortar fire overnight, but it was a
whole lot quieter than it has been,'' Bryan Hunt said in a
telephone interview. ``It's a stalemate situation.''
	   Hunt said he heard army trucks moving through the capital
towards Bra during the night.
	   He said reliable sources had told him that 400 soldiers from
Guinea and 250 troops from Senegal were in the capital.
	   Downtown areas were calm early Wednesday. The airport, located
near Bra, remained closed, but it was not clear if it was under
rebel control.
	   Mane, describing himself as head of the self-proclaimed Military
Junta for the Consolidation of Democracy, Peace and Justice, said
in a statement Tuesday that he had no intention of seizing power
himself and offered talks to ``avert a bloodbath.''
	   The brigadier, fired six months ago during an investigation into
arms trafficking with the separatist rebels of Casamance, a
Senegalese region that borders Guinea-Bissau to the north, had
waited until Saturday to officially step down.
	   Foreign Minister Fernando Delfim da Silva rejected the call for
an early ballot, saying legislative elections were scheduled for
this year and a presidential election was due in 1999.
	   (bh/krt)
</TEXT>
