<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Norway-Strikes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bus drivers end strike in Norway, nurses defy arbitration
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   OSLO, Norway (AP) - A strike by 10,000 transport workers ended
Wednesday with record pay raises of up to 13.7 percent, while
health workers in a separate labor conflict refused to immediately
respect a government order to return to work.
	   The transport workers, many of them public bus drivers, walked
out on May 14. The strike resulted in traffic jams, packed trains
and long taxi lines as Norwegians sought other ways to commute to
work.
	   The drivers had vowed to strike until their wages were raised to
match those of similar professions.
	   The transport workers' union and employers resumed talks
Tuesday, and reached a new contract during the night with pay hikes
of 8 to 13.7 percent.
	   ``This is a historic settlement,'' said Per Oestvold, leader of
the Transport Workers' Union.
	   About 1,600 nurses, nurse's aides and technicians remained on
strike despite a government order Tuesday binding them to
arbitration because the conflict threatened public health.
	   ``We totally disagree with that assessment,'' Laila Davoey,
leader of the striking nurses, was quoted as telling the Norwegian
news agency NTB. ``Only 1,100 of about 40,000 nurses are on strike.
This is not a situation that threatens life and health.''
	   The strike can legally continue until Parliament passes a
special law calling for binding arbitration. However, unions
traditionally end strikes as soon as the government orders a forced
arbitration.
	   The health personnel were among 3,800 Academic Union members
ordered to strike for better pay on May 28.
	   (dm-mhh)	   
</TEXT>
