</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-Animal Cruelty </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taiwanese gangsters practice on stray dogs
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ Taiwanese gangsters are training new
recruits by having them attack stray dogs with knives and acid, an
animal rights group claimed Wednesday.
	   The Animal Protection League said it has recorded 107 cases of
the abuse in the greater Taipei area as of the end of May.
	   Based on eyewitness reports, the attacks are carried out by
junior high school-age gang recruits taking part in group ``courage
building'' sessions, said Shen Jung-chen, the league's director.
	   The group's investigation was prompted by the discovery of
strays burned with acid in the Taipei suburb of Panchiao in May
1997, Shen said.
	   Newspapers have reported dozens of similar attacks on strays,
including one on the campus of prestigious National Taiwan
University. No perpetrators have ever been caught.
	   Taiwan has come under international criticism for its treatment
of strays. In many places, the dogs are housed at garbage dump
pounds and destroyed by drowning, poisoning or electrocution.
	   Animal rights groups have called for the passage of an animal
protection law to require strays be treated humanely.
	   The island is believed to have at least 5,800 gang members
belonging to 126 organized crime groups. Though handguns are their
weapon of choice, watermelon knives, acid and baseball bats are
also popular.
</TEXT>
