w2780 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Britain-MadCowReax     06-10 0462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Mad Cow Reax </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
British cattle farmers relieved `mad cow' nightmare may be ending
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DIRK BEVERIDGE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Business Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ From livestock auctions to cattle farms, Britain's
beef industry cautiously applauded Wednesday's news that the ``mad
cow'' nightmare could be ending, as European regulators sought to
lift an export ban.
	   ``It'll take the gloom out of the market,'' said David Williams,
who runs the Williams Wholesale slaughterhouse in tiny Woebley,
western England. ``It'll be a great morale booster for the whole
industry.''
	   Williams' wife, Sheila, alluded to more blows that the beef
dealers have suffered _ including the Labor government's ban of all
beef on the bone in Britain, based on the minuscule possibility
that T-bones or prime rib could give humans the incurable brain
ailment caused by the mad cows.
	   ``Is that bone-in, or bone-out?'' Mrs. Williams asked as the
European Commission recommended that British farmers be allowed to
export beef and most products from animals older than six months
and younger than 30 months.
	   Actually, the bones will have to be out, and the EC
recommendation doesn't yet end British cattle farmers' troubles.
	   The farmers have bitterly complained that they make some of the
world's best beef but have seen the product unfairly tarnished by
British government bumbling and European politics.
	   The crisis erupted in March 1996 when Britain acknowledged a
link between cattle with bovine spongiform encephalopathy, or BSE,
and the fatal human brain ailment Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease.
	   European Union veterinary experts still must study Wednesday's
recommendation on lifting the export ban, and it could be put to a
vote of agriculture commissioners from the 15 EU nations.
	   ``We've now turned the corner and we're in the home straight,''
said Ben Gill, president of the National Farmers Union. ``The
momentum must not be lost. We are confident that the huge weight
which has burdened the farming community for more than two years
will soon be removed.''
	   At the Hereford Cattle Society in Hereford, the English town
that shares the name of the famous cattle breed, secretary David
Prothero said his members also are pulling for an end to the ban on
live exports.
	   The Hereford breeders have sold cattle to make herds all over
the world, and they were hit by an export ban in 1990, years before
mad cow fears pushed British beef out of the international market.
	   The ban has forced the Hereford society to cut its staff from a
dozen workers to just four.
	   ``We've really been suffering,'' Prothero said. ``We think it's
been more political rather than down to any common sense that the
ban should remain.''
	   (db-kg)
</TEXT>
