<SLUG> BC-Finland-Earns-Raisio </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cholesterol-blocking margarine company's profit surges
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HELSINKI, Finland (AP) _ Raisio Group more than doubled its
four-month pretax profit to 165 million markkaa (dlrs 30 million),
from 70 million markkaa in 1997, mainly because of growing sales of
cholesterol-blocking margarine, the company said Wednesday.
	   Net sales from January to April also increased, to 1.8 billion
markkaa (dlrs 333 million), from 1.6 billion markkaa during the
same period last year.
	   The margarine division's net sales fell slightly to 540 million
markkaa (dlrs 100 million), but Benecol _ the cholesterol-blocking
bread spread _ increased its turnover to 167 million markkaa (dlrs
31 million), up from 19 million markkaa in 1997.
	   Raisio, one of Finland's largest food, animal feed and chemical
groups, is best known for Benecol that inhibits the absorption of
the health-threatening form of cholesterol.
	   It introduced Benecol in 1995, but sales of the margarine had
been limited to Finland for more than two years due to a shortage
of the key raw material, plant sterol, a fat-soluble plant alcohol.
	   Now, the company says, it is increasing the production of plant
sterol at Raisio, and plans to build a factory near Charleston,
South Carolina, to manufacture the heart-friendly margarine's key
ingredient. The plant is expected to be ready in early 1999.
	   In March, Raisio finalized a deal with McNeil Consumer Products
_ a subsidiary of the Johnson and Johnson group _ to market Benecol
worldwide.
	   Last year, Raisio increased its pretax profit by 25 percent to
208.5 million markkaa (dlrs 38.6 million), and net sales grew to
4.9 billion markkaa (dlrs 916 million).
	   The company employs 2,850 people in 14 countries.
	   (mhh-yl)
</TEXT>
