<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-US-Rubin </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. Treasury Secretary to visit Malaysia
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ U.S Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin is scheduled to visit Malaysia at the end of June amid a
heated debate over interest rate policies among the nation's top
leaders.
	   Rubin will meet his counterpart, Finance Minister Anwar Ibrahim,
during his June 28-29 visit, the national news agency Bernama
quoted Anwar's spokesman as saying Wednesday.
	   Diplomats at the U.S. embassy confirmed they have been informed
of Rubin's visit, which will follow a trip with President Bill
Clinton to China.
	   Rubin has reiterated that the United States has always been
ready to help crisis-hit Asian countries reform their sagging
economies which have been weakened by sharp currency depreciations
since last July.
	   He has also emphasized in a recent meeting of Asia-Pacific
finance ministers in Alberta, Canada, that reforms undertaken by
local governments must be accepted by their people.
	   ``If the difficult reform measures that are necessary to restore
confidence are going to work, there has to be a broad public
acceptance,'' he said.
	   Rubin's visit comes as the top echelon of Malaysia's government
debates the direction of the country's monetary policy.
	   Anwar, who is also deputy prime minister, has been pushing for
high interest rates, saying these were needed to prevent a run on
reserves and spiraling inflation.
	   Mahathir, however, has said the tight monetary policy and high
lending rates were hurting businesses and stifling economic growth.
	   Both Mahathir and Anwar have denied there was a rift between
them on economic policy.
</TEXT>
