</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Switzerland-Obit-Roth </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Swiss artist who worked chocolate, waste paper, dead at 68
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BASEL, Switzerland (AP) _ Dieter Roth, an impish German-born
artist whose provocative works included art materials such as
sausage, waste paper and howling dogs, has died, his family
announced. He was 68.
	   Roth died at home of a heart attack last Friday, Swiss
newspapers reported.
	   He was a sculptor, poet, video and graphic artist, book
publisher and cacophonic musician whose works included many
scatological references. He explored everyday objects for their
artistic value.
	   Roth described himself as a ``slugger'' who liked to ``punch
everyone in the nose.'' He had lectured at Yale University and at
times lived in Philadelphia, Denmark and Iceland.
	   Born in 1930 to a Swiss father and a German mother in Hanover,
Germany, he first came to Switzerland in 1943 to escape World War
II. He studied graphic art in Bern and in 1953 launched an art
periodical, ``Spirale.''
	   Roth's first forays into art were geometrical drawings, but he
soon found that too limiting and, as he described it, began to
``smear.''
	   His 1950s exhibits soon branched into improvisational performing
art with a concert of howling dogs.
	   Following his ``accumulation principle,'' in 1976 he declared
300 binders of his waste paper to be a work of art. In 1987 his
exhibit in Hamburg, Germany, included table cloths covered with
random stains, notes and doodles.
	   He often featured food _ from chocolate-covered glass busts of
Beethoven to sausage _ and saw their deterioration in exhibits as
foreshadowing his own death.
	   He liked to give himself humorous German aliases, such as Otto
Hase (hare), Max Plunderbaum (trashtree) and Fax Hundetraum (dog
dream.)
	   He continued active until his death. Last year he made a
150-hour-long video of a sheep titled ``Solo scenes.''
	   An exhibit of his work was held in New York earlier this year.
Currently there are exhibits in Vienna and Zurich.
	   He is survived by two sons, Bjoern and Karl, and a daughter,
Vera.
	   A notice in the Basler Zeitung on Wednesday omitted funeral
details, but said only that the burial would be conducted in the
most intimate circle.
 &UR; (agh-gm)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Switzerland-Obit-Roth; CT:i; 
