r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-Rapes     06-10 0473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Rapes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesian social groups claim Chinese women raped by rioters
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By IRWAN FIRDAUS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Indonesian human rights and women's
groups Wednesday claimed dozens of ethnic Chinese women were raped
and assaulted during a wave of rioting that rocked Jakarta last
month.
	   An official estimate says at least 1,188 people were killed in
the violence, which help forced ex-President Suharto to resign,
ending 32 years of authoritarian rule.
	   Volunteer social workers said some attacks appeared to be
carried out so as to terrorize the minority Chinese community when
the violence climaxed on May 13 and 14.
	   ``Women were gang raped in front their neighbors. Some were
stripped naked and forced to dance. They were humiliated,'' said
Nugroho Katjasungkana a volunteer from a coalition of social
welfare groups.
	   He said more than 100 cases had been documented.
	   Many of the rapes were allegedly committed by mobs who broke
into Chinese-owned shops and homes that were also looted and set
afire.
	   Some victims were badly beaten and wounded. Others trapped in
burning houses.
	   Similar reports had been made in other cities and towns where
rioting took place.
	   The Jakarta Post newspaper quoted Ita Nadia of the women's group
Kalyanamitra as describing some attacks as ``brutal, inhumane and
heartless.''
	   She cited one case of a 12-year-old girl being raped by a group
of seven intruders who forced her parents to watch.
	   One man said a group of rapists mutilated his wife with a razor.
	   Another man said his two sisters were gang raped and then thrown
into a burning building where they died.
	   Indonesia's Chinese Christian and Buddhist minority make up only
about 4 percent of the predominately Muslim population of 202
million.
	   The Chinese dominate the country's economy and industry and have
been attacked as scapegoats as inflation and mass unemployment
soars during Indonesia's worst economic crisis in 30 years.
	   The government-appointed National Human Rights Commission has
said that Chinese have been targeted. It is now investigating the
rape allegations as well as other cases of violence against
Chinese.
	   Last weekend new President B.J. Habibie called on Indonesians to
end racial discrimination against the Chinese community.
	   Social workers said investigations into individual rape cases
would be difficult.
	   Rape victims in traditionally conservative Indonesia are often
too shamed or afraid to press charges. The anarchy that reigned
during the rioting might also make it difficult to locate
independent witnesses and identify suspects.
	   Police have said they have no reports of multiple rapes during
the riots. However, they admit that many victims won't come forward
with official complaints.
</TEXT>
