<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Arabs United,0475 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Soccer succeeds where politics fails _ in uniting Arabs
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By TAREK EL-TABLAWY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MONTPELLIER, France (AP) _ For centuries, Arab and Muslim
leaders have tried to unite the Arab Middle East's diverse peoples.
But where tangible steps could have been taken, rhetoric often
prevailed.
	   Soccer now appears to be fostering a sense of unity among Arabs
at the World Cup.
	   With three Arab countries participating in the France 1998, Arab
soccer fans here say that while they would like their respective
team to win, they will be more than happy if Morocco, Tunisia or
Saudi Arabia make it to the second round _ or even the
quarterfinals.
	   ``The important thing is not that a particular Arab team win,
but that just one of them makes a decent showing. That way, we, as
Arabs, can hold our head up high before the world,'' Youssef
Hussein, a 42-year-old Tunisian subcontractor living in Marseille,
told The Associated Press.
	   If history has a say in this Cup competition, the face-saving
Hussein wants may be delivered by a strong Moroccan team which, in
the 1986 Mexico World Cup, became the first African country to
reach the final 16.
	   ``Naturally, I'm rooting for Tunisia. It is, after all, my
country,'' said Hussein, who had the red Tunisian flag draped
across his shoulders like a cape.
	   ``But if Morocco or Saudi advances, I'd be delighted. They are,
after all, Arab teams and we are, first and foremost Arabs.''
	   In Montpellier, host of the Group A Morocco-Norway match
Wednesday evening, other Arabs shared Hussein's spirit of
unanimity.
	   About 50 Morocco supporters from Egypt and Jordan, as well as
Morocco, unfurled a large Moroccan flag and chanted in Arabic,
``With our blood, with our soul, we support you Morocco.'' The
chant is a modified version of a popular rallying cry for the
charismatic president of Egypt in the 1950s and 1960s, Gamal
Abdel-Nasser. He is still celebrated 27 years after his death for
his efforts to unite the Arab world.
	   Egyptian Tamer Sayed, 29, said the only thing Arabs have been
able to agree on is that they ``hate Israeli occupation of Arab
land.''
	   Soccer may not be ``all that important compared to peace, but
it's about all we have that's not political or religious,'' said
Sayed, who traveled from Belgium to join Moroccan friends in
rooting for the team.
	   One way of boosting Arab achievements in soccer, suggested
Hussein, the subcontractor, would be to set up an Arab national
team made up of the best players in the Arab world.
	   ``But it is, of course, just a dream _ like the Arab common
market,'' he said, referring to a plan proposed in the 1960s that
would offer greater opportunities for integrating Arab economies.
	   (tt-dm)
</TEXT>
