<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Investment </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Korean immigrant in the U.S. to invest dlrs 200 million back home
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Responding to a call for help from his
native country, a Korean-born American businessman will invest dlrs
200 million in South Korea's financially troubled Cho Hung Bank,
his spokesman said Wednesday.
	   Jeong Kim, 37, jumped onto the Fortune magazine's list of the
100 richest high-tech executives in the United States when he sold
his small Yurie Systems Inc. to Lucent Technologies Inc. for dlrs 1
billion in April.
	   Kim got dlrs 510 million under the deal, with the rest going to
the other shareholders of Yurie Systems, based in the Washington
suburb of Landover, Md.
	   ``Mr. Kim's decision reflects his desire to play a role in
helping his native country,'' said Kim Young-moon, an executive of
Yurie Korea Inc.
	   Kim is among the more successful of the over 1 million ethnic
Koreans in the United States. Now on a trip to Washington,
President Kim Dae-jung has urged them to invest back home to save
the battered Korean economy.
	   Cho Hung Bank officials were talking with Kim on the terms of
the investment. Cho Hung, one of Korea's top five commercial banks,
said it wanted Kim to buy new shares the bank planned to issue.
	   South Korean banks are desperately seeking foreign investment to
help rebuild their depleted capital base. They have been crippled
by a wave of loan defaults since the country's economic crisis
began last year.
	   Kim's investment will be the second major inflow of foreign cash
into the troubled banks. In May, Commerzbank AG of Germany said it
would invest dlrs 250 million in Korea Exchange Bank.
	   Kim's family emigrated to the United States when he was 14. He
put himself through school by working nights at 7-Eleven and went
on to establish his company just six years ago.
	   Yurie, with about 240 employees, made equipment for Internet
service providers, telephone companies, and corporations that
connect their communications networks to very high-speed
technology.
	   Kim remains with his old company as president of Lucent's
carrier networks division.
</TEXT>
