<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-Izetbegovic </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bosnia's Muslim President says he may seek revision of Dayton
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) _ If those obstructing peace
implementation come to power in September elections in Bosnia, its
Muslim president says he will request a revision of the Dayton
peace agreement.
	   Alija Izetbegovic, the chairman of Bosnia's three-man presidency
spoke Tuesday in Luxembourg at a session of international officials
overseeing peace implementation in the wartorn Balkan nation.
	   ``Our standpoint is clear: either full implementation of the
Dayton peace agreement or its revision,'' Izetbegovic said in
comments carried by Bosnian state TV.
	   It was the first time the Bosnian Muslim side spoke of possible
revision.
	   While the United States and its allies are most unlikely to
agree to any change in the Bosnian peace pact, the Muslims,
claiming protracted obstruction by the other two ethnic groups,
might not feel obliged to comply either.
	   At the same session, Carlos Westendorp, the top international
official in Bosnia, praised the peace process as a ``success,'' but
conceded there were also ``disappointments.''
	   He listed such issues as a common flag, currency and passport
that had been agreed upon, saying the return of refugees was also
on the increase.
	   However, these symbols of Bosnian nationhood had to be imposed
by Westendorp because no agreement could be reached among leaders
of the three ethnic groups _ Muslims, Croats and Serbs.
	   Westendorp urged the people of Bosnia to use the chance of the
September elections to vote for those who will bring the country
forward.
	   (ac/rp) 	   
</TEXT>
