<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Myanmar-Economic Growth </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Myanmar says economy grew 4.6 percent, short of target
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   YANGON, Myanmar (AP) _ Myanmar's economy grew 4.6 percent in the
last fiscal year, failing to reach the targeted growth rate of 6.4
percent, according to newly-released official statistics seen
Wednesday.
	   Statistics issued by the National Planning and Economic
Development Ministry said the country's gross domestic product for
the fiscal year ending March 31, 1998 totalled 74.329 billion kyat,
equal to dlrs 12.4 billion at the official rate of exchange, or
dlrs 256.3 million on the free market.
	   Per capita income for 1997-98, calculated at 1985-86 constant
price, increased 2.7 percent to 1,532 kyat (about dlrs 255 at the
official exchange rate compared to 1,492 kyat (dlrs 249) for
1996-97.
	   The official report attributed the lagging growth to the
disappointing performance of the agricultural sector, which
dominates the economy.
	   The sector's poor performance was due to a decrease in
production of wetlands rice because of flash floods and a decline
in oil crop production due to drought, the ministry's report said.
	   A growth rate of 6.2 percent is earmarked for the current fiscal
year ending March 31, 1999, the report said.
	   Many Western economists look skeptically at official statistics
from Myanmar _ also known as Burma _ since foreign exchange
controls foster a huge underground economy. The large scale export
of opium and heroin and other illicit drugs also contributes
unaccounted transfers to the economy.
</TEXT>
