<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Politics-NATO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Opposition softens stance on upcoming NATO enlargement vote
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ The center-right opposition softened its stance
Wednesday on an upcoming vote on NATO enlargement a day after
threatening to bring down Premier Romano Prodi's government.
	   While in favor of NATO's plans to enlarge, the opposition had
vowed it would not bail out Prodi when the vote comes up in the
Chamber of Deputies this month.
	   ``When the time comes to make a decision, we will act as men of
the West,'' media mogul Silvio Berlusconi, the opposition leader,
said Wednesday.
	   He suggested the opposition may abstain, but quickly added that
no decision has been made.
	   The government lacks a majority in the Chamber and generally
depends on the votes of a hard-line Communist party. The
Communists, however, are opposed to the NATO alliance and the party
said it would vote against the Western alliance's expansion to the
east.
	   In the meantime, Prodi's political allies are hoping to persuade
Fausto Bertinotti, leader of the Communist Refoundation party, to
keep the government afloat while allowing parliamentary approval of
NATO expansion.
	   ``We are looking for a way out,'' said Achille Occhetto,
president of the Chamber's Foreign Affairs commission.
	   He indicated a solution would involve parliamentary procedure,
such as the Communist deputies leaving the hall before the vote.
	   The political opposition was emboldened by a strong showing in
local elections Sunday.
	   ``Only in Italy can a vote on NATO hinge on the election of some
mayors,'' Occhetto said.
	   The Senate has already approved NATO expansion. The vote will
come up in the Chamber the week of June 22. bsdy
	   (vls)
</TEXT>
