<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Tung, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hong Kong's leader rules out change in currency peg
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with closing stock figures, additional comments from
Tung
 &UR; AP Photo Available

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Hong Kong's Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa
insisted Wednesday the government will keep its 14-year currency
peg to the U.S. dollar, despite increasing calls for action to help
Hong Kong fight a liquidity crunch.
	   His comments immediately pushed up interest rates, which in turn
dragged the benchmark stock index further down to close at its
lowest level in three years.
	   Despite the fall in the stock market and persistent pessimism
over Hong Kong's economic future, Tung told reporters minutes
before trading that the government will not inject funds to keep
the financial markets from sliding further.
	   At the conference, Tung said floating the currency would ``cause
speculative attacks against the Hong Kong dollar and increase
interest rates.''
	   ``The government will maintain Hong Kong's long-held tradition
of fiscal prudence,'' Tung said.
	   The news pushed the benchmark three-month interest rate up to
10.375 percent in early afternoon, up from 9.25 percent early
Wednesday. The one-month rate soared to 11.0 percent from 9.625
percent.
	   The surge in interest rates triggered a 4.9-percent plunge in
the blue-chip Hang Seng Index.
	   The index tumbled 412.09 points, or 4.9 percent, to close at
7,979.37, the lowest level in three years, adding to Tuesday's
2.3-percent fall.
	   Tung said that recent pressure on the territory's currency was
due to the weakness of the Japanese yen.
	   The weakening yen dragged down most Southeast Asian currencies
Wednesday and compounded fears of a possible yuan devaluation,
which would leave the Hong Kong dollar's firm peg to the U.S.
dollar in a precarious position.
	   Fueling the fear was mainland central bank governor Dai
Xianglong's remark Tuesday that the falling Japanese yen would
exert a negative impact on China's foreign trade, though the
People's Bank of China official reiterated a pledge to keep the
Chinese currency stable.
	   The Hong Kong government is under increasing pressure at home to
float the Hong Kong currency as interest rates remain high, making
borrowing extremely difficult for local companies and eating into
their profits.
	   Pressure also mounted for the government to increase public
spending and make further tax cuts to lift the economy. A coalition
of seven political parties and several independent legislators,
forming a majority in the newly-elected legislature, has said they
would back a deficit budget if necessary.
	   But Tung hinted the government would not consider budgeting a
deficit, saying that would bring a new round of currency
speculation against the Hong Kong dollar.
	   ``If we have a deficit budget ... foreign speculators would
doubt our confidence in our currency peg and attack they would
attack our dollar,'' Tung said.
	   He also ruled out dipping into the reserves to lift Hong Kong's
weakening economy, which shrank 2 percent in the first quarter this
year, the first contraction in 13 years.
	   This ``is a free market. The government will not interfere,'' he
said. Hong Kong's ``stock market will stabilize when stability
returns to the region.''
</TEXT>
