<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 1st Ld-Writethru,0437 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thousands protest Serb attacks, ethnic leader to Europe
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with protests, Rugova in Europe, information on
refugees in Montenegro &QL; 
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI
 &UR; Associated Press Writer

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Decrying the latest Serb aggression,
thousands of ethnic Albanians took to the streets of Pristina in
protest Wednesday, while their leader headed to Europe's capitals
to seek assistance for his people.
	   Some 20,000 Kosovo Albanians marched through the main street of
the provincial capital bearing banners that read: ``NATO, Kosovo is
burning'' and ``NATO, tomorrow will be too late,'' and carrying
Albanian and U.S. flags.
	   The protesters fervently chanted ``U-C-K,'' the Albanian
language acronym for the Kosovo Liberation Army _ a militant
organization fighting to wrest the southern province away from
Serbia _ and sang a popular Albanian song, praising their ethnic
leader Ibrahim Rugova.
	   No police were present. The rally _ the 60th consecutive protest
in the capital _ ended peacefully.
	   No immediate violence was reported early Wednesday elsewhere in
the province, where ethnic Albanians outnumber Serbs 9-to-1.
Kosovo's restless Albanian majority seeks independence from Serbia,
which stripped its autonomy in 1989 and has since ruled the
province with a heavy military and police presence.
	   More than 250 people have died in escalating clashes in Kosovo
between Yugoslav troops and ethnic Albanian militants began in
early March.
	   In last week's fighting alone, more than 50 people were killed
and 200 were missing and presumed captured in western parts of
Kosovo, according to ethnic Albanian sources.
	   Chased by the fighting, some 20,000 Kosovo Albanian refuges
flowed into neighboring northern Albania last week.
	   An additional 10,000 fled to the neighboring republic of
Montenegro, which together with Serbia makes up Yugoslavia. The
Montena-fax independent news agency in Montenegro reported a
``river of refugees'' was crossing dense, mountainous territory on
foot to reach Montenegro.
	   Another 50,000 people have been displaced within Kosovo since
March, according to the Pristina-based Committee for the Defense of
Human Rights.
	   Meanwhile, Rugova headed for the European capitals of Paris and
London to attend meetings of the Contact Group nations, which
monitors developments in the former Yugoslavia, and seek help for
his people.
	   Demonstrations announced by the independent human rights
organization Society for Threatened Peoples were to simultaneously
take place in European capitals. 	   
</TEXT>
