r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Israel-BridgeCollapse     06-10 0385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Bridge Collapse </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Army bid to build ill-fated bridge rejected as too expensive
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DANIEL BEN-TAL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) _ The Israeli army offered to build a
bridge strong enough to bear tank traffic for the ill-fated opening
ceremonies of the Maccabiah Games, but was turned down because its
bid cost too much, a general testified Wednesday.
	   The bridge that was eventually built by a private company for
less than half the cost collapsed during the opening ceremony of
the games last summer, killing four Australian athletes and
injuring dozens of others.
	   About 100 Australian athletes were on the bridge when it
buckled, plunging them into the polluted river below.
	   Two contractors, the engineer who designed the bridge, the
director of the event and the chairman of the Maccabiah organizing
committee are being tried on charges of negligent homicide and
building without proper permits. They face up to three years in
prison if convicted.
	   Two army officers testified Wednesday for the prosecution, which
is trying to show that the event organizers acted to cut costs at
the expense of safety.
	   Brig. Gen. On Ragonis said the army had offered to build the
bridge for 288,000 shekels (about dlrs 82,000)
	   Yoram Eyal, the chairman of the organizing committee, asked for
the price to be lowered, and appealed to Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai to build the bridge for free, Ragonis said.
	   The civilian contractor that was eventually chosen entered a bid
of 120,000 shekels (about dlrs 34,000).
	   ``The Maccabiah organizing committee wanted the army to
construct the bridge,'' Ragonis said. ``Yoram Eyal asked us to
lower the price to the level of the civilian contractors.''
	   Another witness, Lt. Col. Avi Matzur, said the army would have
built a 12-section Bailey bridge designed for tank convoys to pass
over.
	   ``The army has been building such bridges for 50 years,'' Matzur
said.
	   Ragonis said that in the past, the army would have built the
bridge for free. But the military is being streamlined and now
charges to cover its costs, he said.
	   Ragonis added that the army provided considerable logistical
support to games for free, including military orchestras and an air
force flyby.
	   db-hla
</TEXT>
