<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iran-Saudi </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Saudi oil minister in Iran to push for production cutbacks
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ Saudi Oil Minister Ali al-Naimi met with his
Iranian counterpart Wednesday to lobby Iran to cut oil production
in an attempt to boost prices.
	   Al-Naimi, who arrived in Tehran Tuesday, briefed Oil Minister
Bijan Namdar Zangeneh on the recent accord between Saudi Arabia,
Venezuela and Mexico to cut back 450,000 barrels a day from the
market, Iran's state-run Tehran radio reported.
	   Al-Naimi has been touring the region to push for additional
cutbacks to boost sagging prices that have hovered around dlrs 14 a
barrel, some 20 percent lower than last year despite cuts in daily
global production by 1.5 million barrels a day.
	   Iran, the second-largest exporter in the 11-nation Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries, has reportedly been exceeding the
pledged cuts it made in March.
	   Iran had agreed to cut 140,000 barrels a day but wanted the cuts
to come from its daily quota of 3.94 million barrels rather than
its actual production level, which fluctuates but is considerably
lower than the quota.
	   Al-Naimi earlier visited Kuwait, United Arab Emirates and Qatar
and non-OPEC producer, Oman.
	   He secured a pledge from Qatar to cut 20,000 barrels per day
starting July 1.
 &UR; fsa/vj
