<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Muslim Rebels, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
379 former Muslim rebels walk out of Philippine army training camp
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS comment, background, grafs 6-7; deletes garble, graf 5 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ZAMBOANGA, Philippines (AP) _ Several hundred former Muslim
rebels have walked out of an army training camp after complaining
of strictness and manhandling by trainers, the military said
Wednesday.
	   Col. Horacio Lapinid, spokesman of the military's Southern
Command, quoted trainers as saying some of the former rebels
``refused to follow training rules and are stubborn,'' causing a
breakdown in training.
	   The 379 trainees were part of the second batch of former Moro
National Liberation Front guerrillas to undergo six months of basic
infantry training before being absorbed into the army. The training
began June 1.
	   Abu Hamrik Tadik, a former MNLF official who is among those
overseeing the training, said the former rebels complained of being
punched and kicked by the Christian officers.
	   ``This is a big problem,'' Tadik said. ``It is an illegal act of
the military trainers. There should be an investigation of the
incident.''
	   Lapinid said 20 former rebels originally walked out of the 1st
Infantry Division in Pagadian City in Zamboanga del Sur province.
They forced 180 others to join them through beatings and threats of
harm to their families, Lapinid said. Later, the remaining 179
joined the walkout.
	   An earlier batch of 1,101 Moro National Liberation Front rebels
completed training in January and are now in the army. A similar
incident occurred with the first batch but they later agreed to
return to camp and finished training
	   A total of 7,500 former Muslim separatists are to be accepted
into the country's military and police forces under a peace accord
signed in 1996 that ended a quarter-century rebellion that killed
more than 120,000 people in southern Mindanao Island.
	   Two smaller Muslim rebel groups _ the fundamentalist Abu Sayyaf
and the Moro Islamic Liberation Front _ are still fighting the
government.
	   The government has begun peace talks with the MILF but the talks
have been put on hold until President-elect Joseph Estrada takes
office on June 30.
</TEXT>
