<SLUG> BC-Sports-Horse Racing-Fixing </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police arrest eighth suspect for race fixing
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ An eighth suspect has been arrested in connection
with an alleged doping and fixing scandal in English horse racing,
Scotland Yard said Wednesday.
	   A 55-year-old man was taken to central London police station
after raids Tuesday on five London locations. The man was released
on bail and ordered to reappear in September.
	   Scotland Yard would not release the man's name but said he was
not a jockey or a trainer.
	   The race-fixing investigation first came to light in January
when five men, including jump jockeys Leighton Aspell, Dean
Gallagher and Jamie Osborne, were arrested.
	   Aspell was cleared but his two riding colleagues were bailed to
reappear later this month. Two other men, including a professional
bettor, were arrested in February.
	   The police investigation was launched following the discovery of
illegal substances in the samples of Avanti Express and Lively
Knight, two horses beaten at short odds in jumps races in March
1997.
	   The police were called in to investigate the allegations of race
fixing after Jockey Club stewards discovered links between the two
doping incidents.
	   Jockey Club spokesman John Maxse said Wednesday that the man
arrested was not licensed by the Jockey Club and, therefore, it was
a police matter.
	   (jp/sw)	   
</TEXT>
