<SLUG> BC-Netherlands-Kosovo Protest </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ethnic Albanians protest bloodshed in Kosovo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo Planned &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) _ Hundreds of ethnic Albanians
demonstrated Wednesday against recent bloodshed in the Yugoslav
province of Kosovo and appealed for international intervention.
	   ``Violence in Kosovo has to stop immediately,'' said march
organizer Louis Gojani.
	   Although the United States and the European Union have imposed
new sanctions on Serbia, protesters want tougher military actions.
	   ``There must be international intervention. It's not important
how that happens, it's important that it will happen,'' said Gojani
of the Coordination Council of Albanians in the Netherlands.
	   Protesters marched to government buildings and handed petitions
to lawmakers and foreign ministry representatives.
	   Around 400 demonstrators participated in the march, according to
an estimate by local police.
	   More than 250 people have died this year in escalating clashes
between government forces and the pro-independence Albanian
militants, known as Kosovo Liberation Army.
	   U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen and his NATO colleagues,
who are meeting in Brussels Thursday and Friday, are expected to
order military planners to take a hard look at possible military
measures.
	   (jc) 	   
</TEXT>
