<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Macau-China-Adidas, 1st-Ld Writehru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S.-based Chinese dissident claims Chinese prisoners made World
</HEADLINE>
Cup footballs &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: ADDS comment from Adidas spokesman, graf 5 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MACAU (AP) _ Shortly before the opening of World Cup Wednesday
in Paris, an exiled Chinese dissident claimed that Chinese
prisoners had made some of the footballs to be used in the matches.
	   Bao Ge, 34, who served three years in a labor camp in Shanghai,
told a press conference in Macau that he was among Chinese
prisoners forced to make ``make some Adidas footballs.''
	   Some of the balls, he said, were marked ``France 98 FIFA World
Cup, Official Championship Ball.''
	   But a spokesman for Adidas, the World Cup's official football
supplier, denied the allegations, saying the balls the prisoners
made were probably souvenir balls for other companies, not Adidas
footballs for World Cup matches.
	   Peter Csanadi, Adidas' director of global public relations said
in Herzogenaurach, Germany, that the design for the official
football ``wasn't even finalized yet'' when Bao was in prison, and
the match footballs were manufactured only in Morocco.
	   He added that about 20 other companies were licensed to use the
World Cup logo on souvenir balls, he said.
	   ``We believe (Bao) is acting in good faith,'' he said. ``We know
he is telling the truth,'' about making footballs with the World
Cup logo.
	   ``Either the balls were of these other companies or they were
counterfeit,'' said Csanadi.
	   Bao spent three years in a labor camp for political activism and
has been in exile in the United States since last November, shortly
after Chinese President Jiang Zemin's U.S. visit.
	   ``The guards in the camp compelled the prisoners to work at
least 15 hours a day, or even more. If the prisoners could not meet
the quotas for the day, they were penalized by having to stay up
all night without any sleep,'' Bao said.
	   Bao said he would file a lawsuit in Hong Kong against Adidas for
compesation for his work. He said other Chinese dissidents on exile
will sue the company in Germany and the United States.
</TEXT>
