w2850 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-IMF     06-10 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-IMF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMF top man in Asian returns to Indonesia as rupiah drops
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ The International Monetary Fund's top
official in Asia arrived in Jakarta on Wednesday to oversee a
thorough review of the IMF-led assistance program for Indonesia.
	   Hubert Neiss flew into Jakarta after Indonesia's battered
currency dropped below 13,000 rupiah against the U.S. dollar as
financial markets doubted the economy would be able to recover any
time soon.
	   The IMF's dlrs 43 billion bailout was derailed last month when
protests and riots broke out, forcing ex-President Suharto to quit
after 32 years in power.
	   Loan installments under the plan were suspended amid the
political and social turmoil, which many feel have worsened
Indonesia's economic crisis, marked by soaring inflation and mass
unemployment.
	   The IMF wants Indonesia to make sweeping economic reforms.
	   ``The purpose of the visit is to review macroeconomic targets
and to continue the restructuring of the financial system and also
continue the structural reform,'' Neiss told reporters after his
arrival at Jakarta's Sukarno Hatta airport.
	   He said it would take ``two to three weeks'' to conduct the
review and only after then can the loan program resume.
	   This is Neiss' second visit to Jakarta in 10 days.
	   During his previous visit, Neiss met a veritable who's who of
the Indonesian establishment including government members,
prominent opposition leaders, even trade unionists.
	   Neiss said then that the fund would have to revise the
macroeconomic targets for the country, in the light of recent
developments in this sprawling Southeast Asian nation.
	   A team of IMF economists has been here since Monday to begin
that task.
	   The IMF was scheduled to disburse dlrs 1 billion from its dlrs
10 billion standby credit arrangement with Indonesia on June 4.
	   The prospect of the current review lasting two to three weeks
confirms the payment of that dlrs 1 billion installment is at least
a month away.
	   After revising the targets, Neiss will have to report to the
IMF's executive board, which can only then vote to release the next
tranche. The IMF has indicated however, that it will release the
aid once the review is complete.
	   The IMF is likely to predict a contraction in the Indonesian
economy of at least 10 percent, from a 5 percent contraction
estimated earlier.
	   The fund is also expected to revise its inflation and possibly
exchange rate targets, as well as other budgetary estimates.
	   The latest IMF program's exchange rate target is for 6,000
rupiah to the dollar by the end of the year, a figure most
economists dismiss now as wildly optimistic.
</TEXT>
