<HEADLINE>
Saudi foreign minister consults with Mubarak on Arab summit
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Saudi Arabia's Foreign Minister Prince Saud
Al-Faisal on Wednesday discussed with President Hosni Mubarak the
prospects of an Arab summit on the Middle East peace process.
	   The meeting comes amid reports _ denied by Saudi Arabia _ that
the United States has pressured it to delay the summit, which had
anyway made little headway because of differences and doubts among
Arab leaders on the stand to be adopted against Israel.
	   Prince Saud told reporters that if a conference is held it
``should be on the highest level and well prepared to serve the
cause of peace and the Arab rights.'' He did not elaborate.
	   Arab leaders began discussing the summit after signs that the
United States has been unable to convince Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu to Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to
accept a compromise of a further 13 percent troops pullback from
the West Bank.
	   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has been pushing for the
conference to put pressure on Israel to accept the compromise.
	   The United States had reportedly asked Arab leaders to postpone
the summit, arguing that it needed more time to persuade Netanyahu
to accept its suggestions.
