<HEADER>
w2852 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Nigeria 1stLd-Writethru   06-10 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New Nigerian ruler promises return to civilian government in first
</HEADLINE>
speech &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS lead to update with reaction to Abubakar's televised
democracy pledge; ADDS quotes. UPDATES with opposition protests
planned before Abacha's death still to go ahead. Edits throughout
to conform. No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; With Nigeria-Economy, US-Nigeria &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos LAG2, LAG101-102,NY190,LON102-104,JRL102 &QL; 
 &UR; By TIM SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ The country's military ruler is promising
democracy, but many Nigerians _ accustomed to years of political
deceit _ were reserving judgment Wednesday on their newest
generalissimo and his pledge.
	   In his first address to the nation Tuesday evening, Gen.
Abdulsalam Abubakar vowed to support a transition to civilian rule,
but gave no details on how the process would be carried out.
	   ``We don't want another Sani Abacha,'' said 25-year-old shoe
repairman Joseph Akpan. ``We've had enough Sani Abacha.''
	   To ordinary Nigerians life has gone quietly on since the death
this week of much their maligned dictator, Gen. Sani Abacha. Many
simply said they want an end to military rule.
	   Opposition leaders say they will go ahead with demonstrations on
Friday to mark the fifth anniversary of the day in 1993 when
presidential elections were canceled.
	   ``We are under no illusion that by Abacha's death, military rule
has come an end,'' the United Action for Democracy said in a
statement, adding ``the struggle against military rule in all its
guises will be renewed with vigor.''
	   On the streets of Lagos, Nigeria's sprawling commercial capital,
there were few signs that life had changed in any dramatic way in
recent days.
	   Flags flew at half mast at government offices in honor of
Abacha, but otherwise, the teeming city went about its daily
business.
	   The legacy of Abacha's leadership is visible everywhere in
Lagos, from the lines for gasoline that stretch for blocks to the
flickering electricity and the phones that can't call across town.
	   Abubakar, speaking on national television hours after he was
appointed by the ruling military junta to replace Abacha, also said
the country's many political exiles were welcome to return home.
	   ``I invite all Nigerians in self-exile to return home to join
the process of reconstruction and reconciliation,'' said the
general, who remained stone-faced throughout the five-minute
speech.
	   Such well-known exiles as Wole Soyinka, a writer and Nobel
laureate, have warned that the military must give way to civilian
leadership.
	   ``I'm afraid that if the military does not bow to the will of
the people, armed insurrection becomes inevitable,'' he said in
Jerusalem, where he was lecturing. ``The signs of it are already
there.''
	   Although Abubakar, a career soldier, gave no specifics on how
the military would hand power over to a civilian government, he
said his administration was committed to a transition process
introduced by Abacha.
	   ``We will do everything to ensure its full and successful
implementation,'' Abubakar said Tuesday night.
	   Earlier, Air Vice Marshal Mohammed Alfa, a senior military junta
aide, told reporters that Abubakar would turn the country over to
an elected civilian government by Oct. 1 _ but gave no details.
	   Civil rights groups, meanwhile, called for the release of jailed
businessman Moshood Abiola, the presumed winner of the 1993
annulled presidential elections.
	   Abacha, a dictator well-known for his brutality, had long
promised that his transition program would end military rule in
Nigeria. But he was also widely seen as manipulating the system to
have himself transformed into a civilian ruler.
	   Though he never officially declared his candidacy, he was the
only person nominated by Nigeria's five registered political
parties for Aug. 1 presidential elections.
	   Countries around the world called for Nigeria's military, which
has ruled Nigeria for the vast majority of its 38 years of
independence, to finally step aside for good.
	   Abacha himself seized power in a 1993 coup. During his years in
power, about 7,000 government critics and dissidents were
imprisoned.
	   In Washington, White House spokesman Mike McCurry said the
Clinton administration hoped that Abubakar would soon surrender
power. Similar calls for democracy in Nigeria came from France,
Britain and members of the Commonwealth of former British colonies.
	   Still, several nations in West Africa praised Abacha for making
his military a regional peacekeeper. Sierra Leone President Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah was returned to power earlier this year as a direct
result of Nigeria's military intervention.
	   And Liberian President Charles Taylor called for a national day
of mourning for Abacha _ whose troops helped to implement peace
accords that ended seven years of civil war in Liberia.
	   In Lagos, which was officially in mourning, there were few signs
of tears over Abacha's death.
	   ``There's no reason to be upset,'' said Kehinda Suleiman, a
40-year-old Lagos resident. ``We're happy he's gone. He was not
such a good leader.''
 &UR; (tjs/ids/bk)
</TEXT>
