<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Denmark-Faeroe Bank </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Denmark, Faeroes settle lingering dispute over bank sale
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) _ Denmark and its semiautonomous Faeroe
Islands on Wednesday settled a five-year dispute over the sale of
the island's only bank that left the tiny archipelago with an
unmanageable debt burden.
	   The government of the Faeroe Islands, home to about 45,000
people north of Scotland, was encouraged by Denmark to buy the bank
Foeroya Banki in 1993, only to discover that it was 1.2 billion
kroner (dlrs 166 million) in debt.
	   Earlier this year, the 18-island Faeroes sued Denmark over the
sale, and an independent report criticized the Danish government
and Den Danske Bank, Denmark's largest bank, for pushing the sale
of the heavily indebted Faeroese bank.
	   After all-night talks Wednesday, Denmark's Finance Minister
Mogens Lykketoft and Faeroese Prime Minister Anfinn Kalsberg agreed
that Denmark would write off 900 million kroner (dlrs 129 million)
of islands' debt and make 500 million kroner (dlrs 71.4 million) of
debt interest free. The remaining debt of around 4 billion kroner
(dlrs 571 million) will be repaid over 20 years.
	   In return, the Faeroes agreed to drop their lawsuit against the
Danish government, which gives the islands about 1 billion kroner
(dlrs per 143 million) a year in aid, but would continue legal
action against Den Danske Bank.
	   The Faeroes rely on fishing, and suffered a severe slump in the
1980s and early 1990s when fish stocks declined. The islands
economy has showed signs of recovery in recent years.
	   Under a self-rule agreement, the islands' government handles
most domestic matters and leaves defense and foreign policy to
Denmark.
	   (jo/dm)
</TEXT>
