<SLUG> BC-India-Cyclone, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0512 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Death toll in cyclone-hit India climbs to 216
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RAISES death toll from 205 to 216, ADDS quotes. CORRECTS the
distance of Kandla port from Bombay. No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos available &QL; 
 &UR; By RAMOLA TALWAR &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BOMBAY, India (AP) _ Relief workers distributed food and
searched for bodies in smashed homes Wednesday, a day after a
cyclone tore through western India, killing 216 people, injuring
1,200 and leaving hundreds of thousands homeless, officials said.
	   The toll from Tuesday's storm, the worst to hit India in 25
years, could rise, as many remain missing. Relief workers have yet
to reach some remote villages.
	   The death toll was highest in Kutch district, where a 12-foot
(3-meter) tidal wave flooded low-lying areas near Kandla port, 530
kilometers (330 miles) northwest of Bombay.
	   As many as 140 people, including fishermen and port workers,
drowned or were swept into the Arabian Sea, government officials
said. Nearly 125 people have been listed as missing. Officials fear
the casualty figure could reach 200 in Kutch alone.
	   The cyclone winds that reached speeds of up to 100 kph (65 mph),
uprooted trees, electricity poles and cut off road and
telecommunication links.
	   Other deaths and injuries were mainly caused by lightning and
collapsing houses in the rural districts of Junagadh, Bhuj, Valsad
and Jamnagar near Porbunder, where the storm first struck land, 450
kilometers (280 miles) northwest of Bombay.
	   Nearly 800 workers living in makeshift tin-roof camps at the
Reliance oil refinery project at Jamnagar were injured by flying
debris. Officials said 150 were hospitalized in a nearby town. The
district reported 35 casualties.
	   Some were injured by flying objects when they left their homes
believing the cyclone had passed, Reliance worker Parth Pandya said
by telephone from Kamnagar, 470 kilometers (295 miles) northwest of
Bombay.
	   Some 2,500 soldiers were called in to help restore
communications and distribute supplies in remote areas of Gujarat
state.
	   ``The worst hit were the salt factory workers in Kandla. They
are very poor people and didn't understand the gravity of the
warnings to stay away from the coast,'' said Kuntan Sanghvi, a
government official in Ahmedabad, the Gujarat state capital 465
kilometers (291 miles) north of Bombay,
	   The worst affected districts of Kutch, Jamnagar and Porbunder
were without electricity for the second day Wednesday. Thousands of
people spent the night in the streets after walls and roofs of
mud-and-thatch houses collapsed. Authorities moved some 20,000
people to safety before the cyclone struck.
	   Heavy rain fell throughout western India and eastern areas of
neighboring Pakistan following the cyclone.
	   Pakistan's port city of Karachi was battered by rains blamed for
the deaths of 12 people. Most of the victims, according to the
Associated Press of Pakistan, were electrocuted after high winds
toppled power lines and left live wires strewn across several busy
streets. 	   
</TEXT>
