w2863 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-STARTII 1stLd-Writethru   06-10 0429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-START II, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Duma postpones START II hearings until fall
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS two final grafs with foreign ministry pledging to
continue pushing for START II ratification, minor editing. ADDS
byline. &QL; 
 &UR; By VLADIMIR ISACHENKOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The Russian Parliament's lower house on Wednesday
put off hearings on the START II arms reduction treaty from next
week until the fall, further delaying hopes of ratification.
	   Acting on ultranationalist Vladimir Zhirinovsky's proposal, the
State Duma voted 235-39 to postpone the hearings. The move reversed
a Duma decision last week to hold hearings June 16.
	   The hearings, which would precede a ratification debate, would
involve Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov and other top officials
discussing why the treaty should be approved.
	   START II was signed in 1993 and ratified by the U.S. Senate in
1996. President Boris Yeltsin has been urging the Duma to do the
same. The treaty would halve Russian and American nuclear arsenals
to 3,500 warheads each.
	   Communists and nationalists dominating the Duma have balked at
ratifying START II, claiming that cutting strategic weapons would
harm Russia's security and be too expensive for the cash-strapped
nation.
	   Communist Duma speaker Gennady Seleznyov has warned that the
hearings will be shelved if U.S. President Bill Clinton continues
to pressure Russia to pass the treaty.
	   Clinton has said he would prefer to come to Moscow for a
proposed summit with Yeltsin after START II has been ratified.
	   Retired Gen. Albert Makashov, a Communist deputy in the Duma,
backed Zhirinovsky's proposal to put off the hearings, saying that
the Kremlin wants them to exert pressure on lawmakers to ratify the
treaty.
	   ``It's Clinton who needs it,'' Makashov said.
	   Russian military leaders support ratification. They say that by
2007 _ the treaty's deadline for destroying weapons _ Russia's
intercontinental ballistic missiles with multiple warheads will be
at the end of their service life and will have to be discarded
anyway.
	   Foreign Ministry spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin said Wednesday
that the government would continue pushing for the treaty's
ratification.
	   ``We will continue working with the State Duma, since we believe
that the ratification of START II is an important step for
Russia,'' Rakhmanin said, according to the ITAR-Tass news agency.
``Ratification of START II will allow us to begin considering START
III which will provide stronger security guarantees.''
	   (vi/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
