<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Chemical Warfare, lst Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mandela was target for chemical disabling, scientist alleges
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: CLARIFIES time sequence of intention to poison Mandela in top
4 grafs and 8th graf; PICKS UP 9th graf previous
 &UR; PAUL HARRIS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) _ Officials in the apartheid-era
government plotted to mentally disable Nelson Mandela with poison
during the final years of his imprisonment and shortly thereafter,
a former government scientist testified Wednesday.
	   There was no suggestion that the plan was ever carried out.
After his release from prison in 1990, Mandela led his African
National Congress to victory in the nation's first all-race
elections in 1994 and became president.
	   Testifying before a panel probing apartheid crimes, Schalk van
Rensburg described how his superior, Andre Immelman, told him soon
after Mandela's release there were plans to poison him with
thallium, which attacks the nervous system.
	   ``The intention, I understood, was to reduce his level of
intellectuality and effectiveness by inducing brain damage,'' van
Rensburg said.
	   Van Rensburg said the aim was not to kill Mandela, but to
disable him. The plot was considered in the final years of
Mandela's imprisonment and at least for a short time afterward,
according to the scientist.
	   The white-run government started preparing Mandela for his
release as early as 1989, and began talks with him on ending
apartheid shortly after his release.
	   But the apartheid government apparently did not want him to be a
viable political opponent.
	   A 1986 report from the State Security Council, which coordinated
the crackdown on anti-apartheid activists, suggested Mandela could
be released only when he was in such a poor state of health that he
could not continue to lead the ANC.
	   The Truth and Reconciliation Commission is investigating the
former apartheid army's chemical and biological weapons projects,
headed by Wouter Basson, who ran the scheme through an elaborate
network of front companies.
	    &UR; Jaap Celliers,, 9th graf pvs
	   (ph-pr-aos)
</TEXT>
