<HEADLINE>
(Currency review), NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
(Currency review), NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Tan Kee WeeASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE greenback rose further against the ringgit last week after
the Malaysian Government said the economy declined by 1.8 per cent
year on year in the first quarter. News of a plan to take over
banks' non- performing loans failed to support the ringgit. The
greenback closed at 3.8900 last Friday, up from 3.8300 the week
before.
	   The Sing dollar ended the week higher last week even as both the
Sing dollar and the ringgit fell against the greenback. The Sing
dollar could drift sideways against the ringgit for a while. The
Sing closed at 2.3020 last Friday, from 2.2810 the week before.
	   The Japanese yen strengthened against the greenback and the
ringgit last week on talk that the G-7 nations would call for a
stronger yen over the weekend. However, the medium-term outlook for
the yen is still bearish.
	   The yen ended last week at 2.8000, up from 2.7540 the week
before.
	   Sterling rose against the ringgit last week after UK interest
rates were unexpectedly raised Thursday. The central bank cited
rising wages and a tight labour market as a justification for its
move. Sterling closed last Friday at 6.3610, up from 6.2300 the
week before.
	   The Aussie dollar fell last week against the ringgit even though
Australian GDP growth in the first quarter was a higher than the
expected 1.3 per cent year-on-year. This is because investors
figured that the best was over for the Australian economy. The
Aussie closed last Friday at 2.3590, down from 2.3700 the week
before.
	   
</TEXT>
