<BODY>
<SLUG> PK-RESOURCES-DIVERSIFIED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PK Resources - a diversified group, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
PK Resources - a diversified group, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   S.N. LockASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ONCE again, the key KLSE heavyweights came under strong selling
pressure in sending the KLSE Composite Index 6.17 per cent lower to
505.05 level.
	   The overall market performance, as reflected by the KLSE All
Share Emas Index, did better when it lost 4.37 per cent.
	   The under-performance displayed by the KLSE CI was underlined by
the major weakness on these index-linked stocks, particularly
Maybank Bhd, Telekom Malaysia Bhd and Tenaga Nasional Bhd.
	   Persistent selling pressure emerging towards the last two
trading days sent the KLSE CI breaching the 517 critical support.
	   The KLSE Emas did better on some fundamental support on selected
second and third liners. It out-performed the KLSE CI by 180 basis
points.
	   Recent corporate reportings gave us an insight into some of the
better managed companies which continued to report healthy earning
during the recent currency and financial problems. Investors simply
ignored the fundamentals of the company.
	   PK Resources Bhd is one such company that reported healthy
earnings for the year ending Dec 31, 1997.
	   The company was incorporated in Malaysia on March 1, 1974, as a
private limited company and was converted into a public limited
company on Aug 8, 1991.
	   Later, it changed its corporate identity from Peladang Kimia Bhd
to PK Resources Bhd on Sept 29, 1997, to reflect its diversified
business activities.
	   The group is principally involved in the manufacture and
merchandising of fertilisers and chemical products.
	   Its subsidiaries are involved in property development, hotels,
quarry, landscaping and nursery, golf course construction and
maintenance.
	   In addition, the group had also diversified into providing
higher education when it established the Nilai College. It ventured
into private tertiary education with a consortium of leading
Australian universities led by La Trobe University.
	   For the financial year ending Dec 31, 1997, the group reported a
profit before tax of RM121.912 million, while its profit after tax
was RM52.718 million, translating into a net earnings per share of
42.71 sen (fully diluted). Its net tangible asset increased to
RM3.45 per share from RM3.07 per share in 1996.
	   Chartwise, its price trend fell from its all-time historical
peak of RM8.80 posted in 1996. It staged another attempt to take
out its all-time peak.
	   It failed when its price trend reversed at RM8.60 level on March
28, 1997. Since then, its price trend retraced all the way down to
its recent low at RM1.20 level on June 5.
	   Here are the readings of some of its technical indicators:-
Moving Averages: Its price trend continued to stay below its 10-,
20-, 30-, 50-, 100- and 200-day moving averages.
	   Momentum Index: Its short-term momentum index continued to
consolidate further in search of its next downside support.
	   On Balance Volume: Its short-term OBV continued to stay below
its 10-day exponential moving averages.
	   Relative Strength Index: Its 14-RSI had since retraced to its
grossly oversold position at 9.17 level on June 5.
	   OUTLOOK: PK Resources' diversification programme over the last
few years transformed the group into a diversified but focused
group with exposure into the productive sectors.
	   Its property development project, Bandar Baru Nilai, is able to
benefit from its close proximity to the Multimedia Super Corridor,
Kuala Lumpur International Airport and Putrajaya, the new Federal
Government administrative centre.
	   At current price valuation, PK Resources' price trend is trading
at a not too demanding price earnings ratio multiple of 2.86 times.
Its current price trend reflected a 64.64 per cent discount, or
RM2.23, to its NTA of RM3.45.
	   PK Resources is one of the first few listed companies that
started buying back its own shares. Its first buy-back exercise was
initiated on March 3. Since then, the company had bought back more
than 2.6 million shares. Its ongoing buy-back exercise will
continue to underpin its price trend.
	   Technically, PK Resources' price trend had since retraced to its
five- year low. Its low PER valuation coupled with a steep discount
to its NTA are all pointing to an imminent technical rebound. At
current levels, its price trend provides opportunity for an
intermediate-term low risk investment.
	   From the perspective of its technical oscillators, indications
are pointing to a grossly oversold position. A technical rebound is
imminent to correct its current technical imbalances. Its
intermediate-term retracement objective is likely to retrace back
to RM1.68 to RM1.80 levels.
	   
</TEXT>
