<BODY>
<SLUG> KLSE-COMPOSITE-INDEX sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KLSE Composite Index: Technical rebound imminent, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
KLSE Composite Index: Technical rebound imminent, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   S.N. LockASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   LAST week, share prices on the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange
(KLSE) took another beating influenced by both the local and
foreign factors. The KLSE Composite Index (KLSE CI) resumed its
previous week's weak momentum when it closed another 6.17 per cent
lower to 505.05 level on June 5.
	   Overall market sentiment was depressed further on investors'
growing concern over a poorer economic outlook in the country.
Investors' concerns derived from the general market perception of
even weaker economic performance over the next two quarters.
	   The slow growth in the economy was reflected by Malaysia's gross
domestic products growth for the first quarter - at minus 1.8 per
cent while that of Hong Kong's was at minus 2.0 per cent.
	   Reacting to the negative news, investors sold down key blue
chips and other index-linked stocks when they drove the KLSE CI
sharply down to 518.00 level on June 1, giving a retracement loss
of 20.24 points, or 3.76 per cent.
	   The KLSE CI dipped briefly to 517.79 level in the morning trades
before staging a technical rebound to its intra-day high of 535.24
level on June 2. However, its rebound was shortlived when investors
took the opportunity to sell down their positions.
	   Amid the heavy selling and profit-taking liquidations, the KLSE
CI closed off its intra-day high. The market behaviour was
literally the same on June 3, 1998, when the KLSE CI rallied to its
intra-day high first before marking lower at market close.
	   After two days of erratic rebound, the KLSE CI resumed its
earlier prior trend when it retraced 7.75 points, or 1.47 per cent,
down to 518.61 level on June 4.
	   Investors had once again turned cautious following the further
weakness on the Malaysian ringgit to the dollar cross-rate. The
ringgit touched the 3.99-level in tandem with the weakness in the
regional currencies. The KLSE CI closed broadly lower to close at
505.05 level on June 5.
	   Reflecting the reaction to the negative growth for the first
quarter, the KLSE CI fell 33.19 points, or 6.17 per cent, over the
week to close at 505.05 level. The KLSE All Share Emas Index
dropped 5.96 points to 130.55 level.
	   The KLSE Industrial Index was down 32.23 points, or 3.11 per
cent, to 1,003.17 level. The KLSE Second Board Index eased 2.06
points, or 1.85 per cent, to 109.41 level.
	   On the sectoral performance analysis, plantation sector
out-performed the rest of the field with a marginal loss of 0.45
per cent followed by the consumer sector with 1.18 per cent. The
mining sector was the top loser with a week-on-week loss of 19.48
per cent.
	   Chartwise, the KLSE CI suffered heavy losses on June 1, 1998,
before recovering marginally on June 2 and 3. It resumed its
downtrend on June 4, before heading for a lower close at 505.05
level.
	   Following are the readings of some of its technical indicators:-
Moving Averages: The KLSE CI continued to stay below its 10-, 20-,
30-, 50-, 100- and 200-day moving averages.
	   Momentum Index: Its short-term momentum index is currently
staging a re- test of its recent downside support.
	   On Balance Volume: Its short-term OBV trend breached both of its
short- and intermediate-term support.
	   Relative Strength Index: Its 14-RSI is staging a re-test of its
recent downside support registered on May 13.
	   OUTLOOK: Against the backdrop of more negative factors
influencing the local market sentiment, the KLSE CI retraced
sharply to re-test this column's envisaged symmetry wave support at
517 levels. It did provide critical support at 517 level for four
consecutive trading days.
	   The KLSE CI staged the first re-test of this support level on
June 1 when it closed at 518.00 level. Its second successful
re-test was recorded on June 2, when the KLSE CI hit its intra-day
low of 517.79 level before staging a rebound to 535.24 level.
	   After hitting its rebound high of 535.24 points, the KLSE CI
retraced to stage its third re-test of this support level when it
hit 518.61 level at its close on June 4.
	   All hell broke loose when the KLSE CI staged its fourth re-test
on June 5. This confirmed the validity of the Gann Study's Rule of
Four. The Rule of Four states that support or resistance would
normally give way on the fourth re-test.
	   Following its swift retracement from its recent high, the KLSE
CI's daily and weekly MACD (moving average convergence and
divergence) continued to trend downwards. As commented previously
in this column, the KLSE CI would have to consolidate further with
downside bias.
	   Its 14-RSI is currently tracing out a possible positive
divergence to the KLSE CI. Simulations showed the positive
divergence is imminent on the technical front. In other words, the
KLSE CI may breach the 500 support momentarily to re-test its
January 1998 support.
	   With that, the KLSE CI will pave the way for a technical rebound
to correct its grossly oversold position. This technical rebound
will likely take the KLSE CI back up above the 500 support. Bargain
hunting activities would certainly emerge when the KLSE CI re-test
its critical support zone around 488-500 levels.
	   
</TEXT>
