<SLUG> BC-Russia-Cyprus-Missiles </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cyprus to test disputed new missile system in Russia
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Cyprus will test its new air defense system in
Russia later this month, the Russian air force commander said
Wednesday.
	   Turkey has threatened to use force to stop the deployment of the
Russian-built missile system on the divided Mediterranean island.
	   Cmdr. Anatoly Kornukov told reporters that Cyprus is scheduled
to test the S-300 system at a base near Astrakhan, a city on the
Caspian Sea in southern Russia, the Interfax news agency reported.
	   Kornukov said officials would decide late this summer whether
the Russian air force would deliver the system to Cyprus, according
to Interfax. The ITAR-Tass news agency quoted an unidentified
``military-industrial'' official as saying the system was ready for
shipment, and that Cyprus had already made advance payments.
	   A Russian newspaper reported Tuesday that Cyprus had already
received the missile system. Russian officials strongly denied the
report. The Rosvooruzheniye arms trading monopoly said the missiles
would be sent to Cyprus in mid-August as planned, Interfax said.
	   Russia has said the weapons are defensive, but Turkey considers
the sale to be a provocation and has warned that it will use force
to stop the system's installation.
	   Turkey has maintained 30,000 troops in a divided sector of
Cyprus since it invaded the island in 1974, following a failed coup
by supporters of union with Greece.
	   (ml/ls) 	   
