<SLUG> BC-Japan-Parliament, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan's Parliament extends session to vote on economic stimulus
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with opposition decision to submit no-confidence
motion; poll showing support for Cabinet has fallen to lowest-ever
level &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan's Parliament voted Wednesday to extend its
current session by eight days to complete passage of a 16.6
trillion yen (dlrs 119 billion) economic stimulus package, an
official said.
	   The extension will keep Japan's Parliament, which was scheduled
to recess on Wednesday, in session until June 18, a lower house
spokesman said.
	   The ruling Liberal Democratic Party wanted the extra time to
finish cobbling together the largest economic stimulus package in
Japanese history, which is aimed at reviving an economy on the
brink of recession.
	   Meanwhile, two opposition parties _ the Democratic Party of
Japan and Liberal Party _ decided to jointly submit a no-confidence
motion against Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto for his handling of
the economy, said Haruo Semba, an official of the DPJ.
	   Such a measure is unlikely to pass as the LDP holds a majority
in the 500-seat lower house.
	   But it adds to Hashimoto's headaches as a new poll released
Wednesday showed that support for the Cabinet had fallen to a
record low.
	   A Kyodo News Agency survey showed that support for the Hashimoto
Cabinet had slumped to an all-time low of 35.0 percent from 37.1
percent in April. The dispproval rating was also at a record high
of 58.8 percent, up from 56.1 percent.
	   Kyodo said it had questioned 3,000 adults at random across the
nation on June 6-7. It gave no margin of error.
	   The extension of Parliament's session means that crucial upper
house elections scheduled for this summer will likely take place
between July 8 and 18, Kyodo reported.
	   The extension comes one day after Parliament passed a bill to
streamline the nation's bureaucracy.
	   The new law will trim the number of agencies and ministries to
13 from 22 within five years. It will cut the number of public
employees by about 10 percent and strengthen the prime minister's
control over policy making.
	   The new law was a key policy objective of Hashimoto, who has
promised to cut costs and rein in Japan's powerful ministries.
 &UR; (mef-sk) 	   
</TEXT>
