<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Sri Lanka-New Zealand, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New Zealand restricts Sri Lanka to 200 for 8
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with details at the end of day's play &QL; 
 &UR; By CALLISTUS DAVY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) _ Sri Lanka was struggling at 200 for 8
in its first innings on the opening day of the third and final
cricket Test against New Zealand Wednesday after winning the toss
and electing to bat in overcast conditions.
	   The home team never looked comfortable after the dismissal of
its star batsman Sanath Jayasuriya with the total at 24, and
finished the first two sessions making just 124 runs for the loss
of five wickets.
	   Sri Lanka and New Zealand have won one test each in the
three-test series.
	   Paceman Chris Cairns triggered a Sri Lankan collapse when he had
Mahela Jayawardena caught behind off a rising ball, the first after
lunch, and in the last ball of the same over dismissed Aravinda de
Silva.
	   De Silva top edged an attempted hook shot and was caught by
Craig Spearman at fine leg for 4. Jayawardena made 16.
	   A few moments later, medium pacer Craig McMillan made it 70 for
4 by having a hand in the exit of skipper Arjuna Ranatunga who made
just 4 runs.
	   Ranatunga was at the non striker's end and could not beat a
deflection off McMillan's right hand in the face of a full blooded
drive from Marvan Atapattu.
	   Atapattu and Hashan Tillekeratne staged only a minor recovery
with an alliance of 32 runs for the fifth wicket and were back in
the pavilion after missing half centuries by two and seven runs
respectively.
	   Atapattu swept a ball from off spinner Paul Wiseman but only
succeeded in top edging the delivery to short fine leg where Daniel
Vettori took the catch.
	   Atapattu made 48 in 178 minutes of batting, hitting seven fours.
	   Tillekeratne was out half an hour before the scheduled close
when he edged a ball from McMillan into the hands of Bryan Young at
slip.
	   McMillan also came in handy for New Zealand when Romesh
Kaluwitharana played a delivery from him onto the stumps to be out
for 28, made off 78 balls.
	   Tillekeratne occupied the crease for 158 minutes and dispatched
seven balls to the fence.
	   Earlier in the day, Sri Lanka lost the wicket of Jayasuriya who
was caught at second slip by Young for 13 in the ninth over of the
innings.
	   (cd/aks)
</TEXT>
