<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Miners </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Protest march by Ukrainian miners edges close to Kiev
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By EFREM LUKATSKY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BORYSPIL, Ukraine (AP) - The miners, naked to the waist, marched
quickly and silently under the scorching sun, cheered by honks from
passing cars and applause from villagers lining the highway.
	   On Wednesday, the column of about 1,000 striking Ukrainian
workers was just several kilometers (miles) outside Kiev, the
capital, after having marched for some 500 kilometers (310 miles)
from coal-producing areas of eastern Ukraine.
	   The protest march began last month, accompanying scattered
strikes that have idled dozens of mines as workers demanded their
long-overdue wages. Over 40 mines are now on strike, union leaders
say.
	   The miners are owed an average of eight months in back wages and
the overall wage debt stands at 2.2 billion hryvna (dlrs 1.1
billion), according to the Coal Industry Ministry.
	   The miners also want wage and pension increases and more funding
for the coal industry, plagued by numerous accidents caused by
aging equipment and neglect for safety rules.
	   The cash-strapped government, which blames managers in the coal
industry for many of the problems, has sent some money to coal
regions and is supposed to forward another 600 million hryvna (dlrs
300 million) allocated by parliament to help the struggling
workers.
	   Miners held separate demonstrations in front of parliament and
President Leonid Kuchma's headquarters in Kiev on Wednesday.
	   ``The miners shall stay ... until overdue wages are paid in
full,'' union leader Viktor Derzhak said, according to the Interfax
news agency.
	   The newly appointed Coal Industry Minister Serhiy Tulub told
ministry officials Tuesday that overdue wages have caused ``great
social tension,'' Interfax reported.
	   ``We must devise a tactic to end the protest actions in Kiev,''
he said, suggesting that ministry spending be slashed by 15 percent
so as to come up with some money.
	   On the highway to Kiev, the marchers were greeted with an
outpouring of sympathy. Many Ukrainians, whose country of more than
50 million people has experienced economic decline since the Soviet
collapse, feel affinity to the miners.
	   Among the column was Sergei, a shepherd father of five who said
he had abandoned his cattle in eastern Ukraine to join the march.
``He has even gained some weight,'' the miners joked.
	   Cars honked and people came out to give food and bottles of
mineral water to the marchers. Some elderly women waiting at bus
stops along the highway shouted slogans in support of the bygone
Soviet Union as the column approached.
	   In Kiev, the Socialist Party _ one of the left-wing forces that
have been seeking to capitalize on the miners' protests _ called on
residents to join the march when the workers reach the capital
Thursday.
	   The marching miners, however, said they had no political demands
to raise and pledged to return to their homes as soon as back wages
are paid.
	   (el/sms/ml)
</TEXT>
