<HEADLINE>
AMD unveils processor with 3DNow! technology, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
AMD unveils processor with 3DNow! technology, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ADVANCED Micro Devices has introduced the AMD-K6-2 processor
which is claimed to be the first Microsoft Windows compatible x86
microprocessor with 3DNow! technology.
	   According to the company, the AMD-K6-2 processor combines 3DNow!
instructions and superscalar MMX capability to deliver life-like
images and graphics, big-screen sound and video.
	   ``For the first time, AMD has introduced a processor that is
differentiated not solely by megahertz (MHz) or price, but also by
innovative technology that delivers a new level of
three-dimensional (3-D) performance and realism,'' said AMD's
executive vice president and chief technical officer S. Atiq Raza.
	   AMD said personal computer (PCs) makers such as IBM and Fujitsu
are planning to use the AMD-K6-2 processor with 3DNow! technology
in their forthcoming systems.
	   Microsoft is supporting 3DNow! technology in DirectX 6.0, a
common set of application programming interfaces (APIs) for
multimedia services in the Windows platform.
	   DirectX 6.0 optimised for 3DNow! technology is expected to be
available next month. Software applications that leverage the
forthcoming DirectX 6.0 API, the OpenGL 1.2 API and 3Dfx Glide API
will add value to improve 3-D performance as they will be optimised
for the 3DNow! technology.
	   According to AMD, numerous software titles, including Incoming
by Rage, Unreal by Epic MegaGames, Microsoft's Baseball 3-D,
Imagine Studios' Ares Rising and LiveArt 98 by Viewpoint Data Labs,
have also been optimised for 3DNow! technology.
	   Other new titles tuned for 3DNow! technology are expected to
debut throughout the year, the company said.
	   
</TEXT>
