<HEADLINE>
Vietnamese military chief visits China
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) _ Vietnam's defense minister, Senior
Lt.-Gen. Pham Van Tra, has begun an official friendship visit to
China to strenghthen bilateral military ties, the official
newspaper Vietnam News reported Wednesday.
	   Tra left for Beijing Tuesday at the invitation of Chinese
Defence Minister Chi Haotian, the newspaper reported.
	   Relations between Vietnam and China have recently been getting
warmer, and the two countries have been exchanging regular
high-level visits since their relations were normalized in 1991.
	   The two former communist allies fought a brief but bloody border
war in 1979 shortly after Vietnam invaded Cambodia to oust the
Beijing-backed Khmer Rouge government there.
	   The two countries still have territorial disputes involving
their land borders as well as maritime claims in the Tonkin Gulf
and around the Spratly Island chain, an area believed in be rich in
natural resources.
</TEXT>
