<BODY>
<SLUG> EPSON'S-NEW-PORTABLE-LCD sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Epson's new portable LCD projector, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Epson's new portable LCD projector, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Subashini SelvaratnamASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   EPSON Trading (M) Sdn Bhd has unveiled what it claims is world's
brightest portable liquid crystal display (LCD) multimedia
projector, the EMP-7300.
	   Epson Trading's marketing executive sales and marketing division
Norafesa Abu Kassim said the newprojector incorporates the latest
features such as an ultra-high efficiently lamp, ultra-high
aperture LCD panel and an improved projection lens to achieve 1,200
ANSI lumens output brightness.
	   The lamp is said to last up to 1,000 hours, while the LCD panel
which uses the micro lens array technology has improved the
aperture ratio to 70 per cent.
	   According to Epson, the new improved projection lens focuses on
the critical portion of light onto the LCD panel resulting in a
higher light efficiency.
	   The 1,200 ANSI lumens output supports extended graphics array
(XGA) at 1,024 by 768 resolution and is able to compress SXGA/WS
images.
	   Other technologies incorporated in the EMP-7300 projector are
polarisarion conversion for more uniform brightness, panel on prism
for sharper images and real-time image resizing for accurate data
compression and digital gamma correction for better colour
gradation.
	   ``The EMP-7300 projector is Epson's first multimedia projector
which is equipped with the line doubler technology,'' Norafesa told
Computimes.
	   She said the line doubler technology is used to filter images
which consist of two fields of scanning lines. If infiltrated, the
images can cause flicker.
	   Besides filtering images, the line doubler also converts a
traditional interlace video image into a non-interlaced one by
eliminating the horizontal lines which appears on the projection
image.
	   The EMP-7300 projector comes with a contrast ratio of 300:1 and
weighs 6.2 kilograms. It is compatible with Digital, IBM and
Hewlett-Packard workstations and it can be connected to a personal
computer (PC), Mac and other video devices.
	   Targeted at workstation users and high-end users such as
engineering, medical, military organisations, Epson expects to sell
about 20 to 30 units of EMP-7300 projectors within one year.
	   Currently, the company claimed to have a market share of 16 per
cent for multimedia projectors in the Asia-Pacific region.
	   The suggested retail price for the EMP-7300 projector is
RM73,500 and it is available through local Epson outlets.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
