w2907 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EU-CerealMountain     06-10 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-Cereal Mountain </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU Commission sees grain mountain; Wants more land out of
</HEADLINE>
production &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ Citing fast-growing surplus grains
stock, the European Commission proposed Wednesday that EU cereal
farmers take 10 percent of land out of production in 1999, double
the current level.
	   ``There is a serious danger of (surplus) stocks for cereals
increasing again to unacceptable levels,'' said EU Agriculture
Commissioner Franz Fischler.
	   ``We cannot bury our heads in the sand any longer. We have a
problem.''
	   His proposed remedy must be approved by EU agriculture ministers
who have been divided over the issue.
	   France and Germany _ the EU's biggest cereal producers _ want to
limit the set aside of land to 5 percent or just over that.
	   Fischler told reporters said a doubling of the current rate was
needed to prevent surplus stocks from getting out of hand.
	   ``Our analysis, based on realistic assumptions, indicates that
in the absence of an adjustment ... the European Union could have
30 million metric tonnes (33 million tons)'' in storage by
mid-2000, he said.
	   He called that ``a level which is untenable and which must be
avoided.''
	   Coceral, an EU cereal trade group, said public storage of grains
now total 13.3 million metric tonnes (14.6 million tons), up from
2.4 million tonnes (2.64 million tons) a year ago.
	   Commission officials predicted this will rise to 20 million
tonnes (22 million tons) in mid-1999 and to 29.5 million tonnes
(32.5 million tons) by mid-2000.
	   Surplus grain stocks have long been a nightmare scenario for the
EU.
	   In the past, cereals were stored away in huge quantities across
the EU while people elsewhere went hungry.
	   When they were sold, the EU did so with export subsidies because
the world price of cereals is lower than the EU price. Those
subsidies then led to unfair trade charges from the United States
and other trade partners.
	   Under EU rules, cereal farmers are encouraged, or can be forced,
to let land lie fallow to prevent overproduction.
	   They are then paid for not growing crops. The amount set-aside
land depends on market conditions. This year, 4 million hectares
have been taken out of production, half of it voluntarily.
	   The EU has had a 5 percent set-aside rate in 1997 and 1998, down
from 10 percent in 1996. Unless a new rate is set for 1999 and
beyond, the EU will revert to a more painful rate of 17.5 percent
that was imposed as the norm in 1992.
 &UR; (rw)	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-EU-Cereal Mountain; CT:i; 
