<SLUG> BC-Iran-Interior Minister </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lawmakers calls for impeachment of Iran's interior minister
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By AFSHIN VALINEJAD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ Hard-line members of Parliament on Wednesday
demanded the impeachment of the liberal interior minister, accusing
him of jeopardizing Iran's stability.
	   Thirty-one members of Majlis, or parliament, filed a motion,
saying minister Abdollah Nouri should be impeached for several
reasons, including allowing a pro-democracy rally last month to
protest the influence of the hard-line clergy in Iran.
	   The impeachment motion is the latest attack by the conservative
members in Iran's ruling clergy on officials loyal to reformist
President Mohammad Khatami who took power in August.
	   Shortly after Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri read out the
impeachment motion, Khatami rose to his minister's support, calling
him ``our capable brother, an outstanding personality of the
revolution and the system.''
	   The impeachment motion accuses Nouri of ``creating tension in
the society, making provocative interviews and speeches in
different provinces and appointing inexperienced people to
managerial posts at the ministry.'''
	   His ``continuation in the post is detrimental to tranquility and
stability in the country,'' the motion was quoted as saying by the
official Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
	   Hard-liners have in the past few weeks described the liberal
minister as incompetent and called for his resignation.
	   In the letter, the deputies protested the minister's open
support for Tehran Mayor Gholamhossein Karbaschi who was arrested
in April on corruption charges.
	   Karbaschi, also a Khatami loyalist, is now on trial facing
accusations by the country's judiciary, which is controlled by the
conservative clergymen.
	   Nouri, appointed by Khatami who overcame strong resistance from
Parliament, had set up an office at the Interior Ministry to
coordinate support for Karbaschi. The lawmakers said Nouri's
actions created tensions.
	   Nouri has 10 days to appear before Parliament, where hard-liners
are in a slight majority, and respond to the accusations in the
impeachment motion, which will then be put to vote.
	   Khatami's landslide victory in May against hard-line candidate
Nateq-Nouri, who later secured the Parliament speaker's post, shook
the foundations of Iran's clerical rule.
	   The 20 million people who voted for Khatami, mainly women and
students, called his victory a triumph for civil liberties in this
Islamic republic.
	   Khatami still struggles, however, with hard-line opponents who
accuse him of betraying the 1979 Islamic revolution led by the late
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
	   Ali Khamenei, who succeeded Khomeini, remains Iran's powerful
spiritual leader.
 &UR; av-ti/vj
</TEXT>
