<HEADLINE>
Apple introduces latest notebooks, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Apple introduces latest notebooks, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Wendy LeeASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   APPLE Computer has launched its latest products for the mobile
market, the PowerBook G3 series notebook computers, which feature
the PowerPC G3 processor that is claimed to be twice as fast as the
Pentium II processor, based on BYTEmark processor test scores.
	   The PowerBook G3 series for the Asian market comes in three
configurations namely PowerBook G3/233, G3/250 and G3/292.
	   The PowerBook G3/233 features a 12.1-inch display, 233 megahertz
(MHz) PowerPC G3 microprocessor, 32 megabytes (MB) synchronous
dynamic random access memory (SDRAM), 20X CD-ROM drive and
two-gigabyte (GB) hard drive.
	   The PowerBook G3/250 has similar features to the first
configuration except that it comes with a 13.3-inch display, a
250MHz PowerPC G3 microprocessor, 1MB Level 2 backside cache and
1.44MB floppy disk. The last configuration, the PowerBook G3/292,
features a 14.1-inch display, a 292MHz microprocessor, 64MB SDRAM,
8GB hard drive and other features similar to the first two.
	   All three configurations are bundled with MacOS8.1, RealPC from
Insignia Solutions Inc and third-party software such as FAXstf, Now
Contact, UptoDate and Web-Whacker.
	   The new notebooks also come with a full-sized keyboard and a
sleek black enclosure with rounded contours and soft-gripping
surfaces. The suggested retail prices for the three notebooks are
S$4,249 (RM10,200), S$6,814 and S$8,878 respectively.
	   The PowerBook G3/233 and G3/250 models are already available
while the PowerBook G3/292 model is expected to be available early
this month.
	   According to Apple Computer's South Asia Pte Ltd general manager
Chng Poh Hwa, the company plans to have an official launch of the
PowerBook G3 series in Malaysia this month.
	   ``There is no reason why there can't be a similar launch in
Malaysia; ultimately, it's the users and meeting their needs is our
concern,'' he said.
	   The company is also working towards establishing a direct
presence in Malaysia, but does not have a definite time frame for
its plans.
	   ``Our market will continue to be served by strong distributors
who focus purely on distribution efficiency to the channels and
then to the users,''
	   Chng said.
	   He said the company has been working with ``excellent'' partners
thus far, including Exquisite Discovery Sdn Bhd of the Sapura IT
Group on the local front, and has just signed an agreement with
Electronic Resources in Singapore for the distribution of Apple's
products in the region.
	   
</TEXT>
