<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Vietnam-Army Businesses </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Vietnam's army businesses told to prepare for restructuring
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) _ Vietnam's defense ministry has issued an
edict telling the companies it controls in the business sector to
streamline in order to improve efficiency and competitiveness, a
ministry official said Wednesday.
	   The ordinance _ which was issued last month, but published in
the People's Army newspaper Wednesday _ requires the army's
businesses to restructure in order to build strong corporations
which will be able to take on major projects, and to dissolve
money-losing enterprises.
	   The army engages in businesses ranging from running hotels to
chartering helicopters and producing consumer goods.
	   The official, who asked not to be named, said the edict's order
represented a second wave of restructuring for army businesses.
	   In 1995-96, some 305 army businesses were streamlined by merger
and closures to 193.
	   The new edict did not specify how many army enterprises would be
merged or made to cease operating this time. It said the
streamlining must not reduce production or affect workers' jobs and
living conditions.
	   The ordinance also said divisional and provincial army units and
specialized departments under the defense ministry are not allowed
to set up commercial enterprises.
	   In Vietnam's socialist-oriented economy, the army has a
reputation for discipline, organization, and being a source of
abundant labor. It still has 500,000 troops in its ranks, a
reduction from 1 million over the past decade.
	   The army has teamed up with foreign partners in 55 projects
capitalized at more than dlrs 800 million. They range from hotels,
office buildings, automobile manufacturing and shipbuilding to
projects in the agricultural field.
	   Since Vietnam introduced a law on foreign investment in 1987,
Vietnam has attracted about 1,800 foreign investment projects with
a total pledged investment capital of dlrs 32 billion.
</TEXT>
