<TEXT>
	   Editors: The following stories have moved or will move on the
European circuits of The Associated Press by 1500 GMT, unless
otherwise noted.
	   PARIS _ Air France said Wednesday it had reached an agreement
with striking pilots, ending a walkout that had severely
embarrassed the country in the days leading up to the World Cup.
AIR FRANCE-STRIKE.
	   BRUSSELS _ The European Commission on Wednesday backed the
lifting of the worldwide ban on British beef exports imposed more
than two years ago at the height of Europe's ``mad cow'' scare.
BC-EU-MAD COW.
	   WITH:
	   _BRITAIN-MAD COW REAX. From livestock auctions to cattle farms,
Britain's beef industry cautiously applauded Wednesday's news that
the ``mad cow'' nightmare could be ending, as European regulators
sought to lift an export ban.
	   PARIS _ Late-night clashes between drunken soccer fans, Parisian
youths and riot police left 34 policemen injured, including one who
was in critical condition after being hit in the head with a beer
bottle, police said Wednesday. FRANCE-WORLD CUP-STREET BATTLES.
	   WITH:
	   _ITALY-TERRORIST SWEEP. As the World Cup kicks off in France
Wednesday, Italian police arrested at least 20 people suspected of
belonging to an Algerian terrorist group allegedly planning attacks
during the games.
	   LAGOS _ The country's military ruler is promising democracy, but
many Nigerians _ accustomed to years of political deceit _ were
reserving judgment Wednesday on their newest ruling general and his
pledge. NIGERIA.
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Thousands of ethnic Albanians take to the
streets of Pristina, protesting continued violence in Kosovo, while
the province's ethnic Albanian leader heads to Europe's capitals
seeking assistance for his people. YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO.
	   WITH:
	   _NATO-KOSOVO. With the Serb-led Yugoslav army beefing up its
forces in Kosovo, NATO defense ministers face a growing belief that
the only way to stop the violence may be direct military
intervention.
	   _US-KOSOVO-COHEN. U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen says NATO
defense ministers expect to examine possible military options in
Kosovo. US-KOSOVO-COHEN.
	   _UN-KOSOVO. U.S. seeks Russian endorsement of tougher measures
to stop the violent Serb crackdown in Kosovo.
	   _NETHERLANDS-KOSOVO PROTEST. Hundreds of ethnic Albanians
Wednesday demonstrate against bloodshed in Kosovo.
	   ROME _ Premier Romano Prodi's political allies are hopeful of
keeping a hard-line Communist party from bringing down the
government when parliament votes on NATO expansion. ITALY-POLITICS.
	   PRAGUE _ Ten days before the country's early elections, latest
polls indicate stalemate or minority government rule as a probable
outcome of the ballot. CZECH-POLITICS. ETA 1600GMT.
	   LISBON, Portugal _ After the first peaceful night since a coup
attempt was launched on Sunday, talks are scheduled in the West
African nation of Guinea-Bissau between a parliamentary delegation
and renegade soldiers holed up in a military installation.
GUINEA-BISSAU.
	   MOSCOW _ The Russian Parliament's lower house puts off hearings
on the START II arms reduction treaty from next week until the
fall, further delaying hopes of ratification. RUSSIA-START II.
	   BERLIN _ Anti-military protesters were expected to outnumber
young recruits 20 to 1 when the German army swears in about 300 new
soldiers outside Berlin's city hall Wednesday. GERMANY-ARMY
PROTEST.
	   GENEVA _ U.N. labor chief Michel Hansenne and human rights
commissioner Mary Robinson Wednesday welcomed Indonesia's decision
to ratify an international convention guaranteeing workers' trade
union rights. UN-LABOR-INDONESIA.
	   WARSAW _ German Chancellor Helmut Kohl joins Polish Prime
Minister Jerzy Buzek to dedicate an international youth center
Thursday at the former estate of a Prussian count hanged for
involvement in the 1944 plot to kill Hitler. POLAND-GERMANY-YOUTH
CENTER.
	   WITH:
	   _POLAND-RAILWAY STRIKE. Train drivers on Wednesday threatened to
strike next week unless the government-run railway meets their
demands for pay raises and earlier retirement.
	   MINSK _ Officials in Belarus said Wednesday they had postponed a
deadline for foreign diplomats to leave their residences, but
continued to insist that the diplomats would be evicted to permit
urgent repairs. BELARUS-US.
	   ZURICH, Switzerland _ Credit Suisse Group announced Wednesday it
has agreed to buy Brazilian investment bank Banco de Investimentos
Garantia for dlrs 675 million. SWITZERLAND-BANK DEAL.
	   ZURICH, Switzerland _ The cathedral chapter of Chur has chosen a
new bishop to replace the controversial conservative Wolfgang Haas,
a member of the chapter said Wednesday. SWITZERLAND-CHURCH.
	   Also:
	   _ETHIOPIA-ERITREA. Eritrean forces attacked Ethiopia's biggest
border post in northwest Tigray province early Wednesday, the
government said.
	   _INDIA-CYCLONE. Relief workers distributed food and searched for
bodies in the debris of smashed homes after a cyclone tore through
western India, killing 205 people.
	   _PHILIPPINES-AIRLINE STRIKE. Financially strapped Philippine
Airlines announced Wednesday it will no longer accept back about
600 striking pilots.
	   _INDONESIA. Protesters in East Timor rejected a peace offering
from Indonesia's new president Wednesday.
	   _TURKS AND CAICOS-HAITIAN REFUGEES. Authorities in the Turks and
Caicos Islands tried Wednesday to determine whether police bullets
or panicky refugees capsized a crowded Haitian sloop, an accident
that left at least 30 refugees feared drowned.
