w2929 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  GOVT-WANTS-ISPS-SHAREske     06-10 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> GOVT-WANTS-ISPS-SHARE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Govt wants ISPs to share common gateway, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Govt wants ISPs to share common gateway, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Azlyn A. RahmanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Government has set up the Telecommunications Consultative
Committee for Internet service provider (TCC-ISP), which will be
made up of representatives from the Telecommunications Department
and ISPs.
	   The main responsibility of the consultative committee will be to
study and analyse the growth of Internet services in the country.
	   An immediate issue to be tackled by the committee is a
suggestion from the Government that all ISPs share a common
gateway, or an International Internet Exchange.
	   Energy, Telecommunications and Posts Minister Datuk Leo Moggie
said this issue is important as the individual efforts by the ISPs
to set up an international gateway will necessarily involve large
amounts of investment.
	   He made this call after announcing the appointment of five new
ISPs - Celcom (M) Sdn Bhd, Mutiara Telecommunications Sdn Bhd,
PrismaNet (M) Sdn Bhd, Time Telecommunications Sdn Bhd and Bina
Sat-Com Sdn Bhd.
	   The current ISPs are Mimos Berhad, which operates the Jaring
network and Telekom Malaysia, which manages TMnet.
	   ``The Government has recommended that all seven ISP companies
jointly share the installation of the international gateway,''
Moggie told reporters, after presenting licences to the five new
ISPs in Kuala Lumpur last Friday.
	   ``It is to the benefit of the operators to reduce each
individual investment.''
	   He added that the Government also hopes that the consultative
committee will be able to find ways to review unnecessary
expenditure among the ISPs so that they will be able to offer
competitive and quality services.
	   Commenting on the possibility of market overcrowding with seven
ISPs operating locally, Moggie said this was not an issue as the
growth of the Internet is now twice as fast, and the public also
demands for improved quality services.
	   ``Hopefully, by having more companies offering Internet
services, the public will have more choices to select from,'' he
said, adding that most of the ISPs have indicated that they will
start operations and offer services by end of this year.
	   Director-general of the Telecommunications Department Datuk Hod
Parman said similar to both Jaring and TMnet networks which are
assigned user access code 1511 and 1515 respectively, the new ISPs
will also be assigned access codes from the 151X series.
	   ``The numbers to be assigned to them will be based on the new
ISPs' cellular network access code,'' he said, explaining that this
will make it easier for users to identify the ISPs they are linked
to.
	   According to Moggie, the Government reckons that seven ISPs are
enough, and has no immediate plans to issue new licences though
this position will be reviewed as the need arises.
	   However, he added, applications to become Internet access
service provider or IASP can still proceed.
	   
</TEXT>
