<SLUG> CIVIL-SERVICE-REWARDS-HL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Civil service rewards to continue (HL), NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Civil service rewards to continue (HL), NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Hamidah AtanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MALACCA, Sun. - The Government will continue to reward good and
hardworking civil servants with increments and other incentives
under the New Remuneration System despite the economic slowdown.
	   ``This is a contractual obligation which the Government will
continue to offer to excellent and deserving employees,'' Chief
Secretary to the Government Tan Sri Abdul Halim Mohd Ali said after
launching a time management seminar last night organised by the
Association of Civil Servants' Wives (Puspanita) of Negri Sembilan,
Malacca and Johor.
	   ``We will not stop awarding good civil servants in our attempt
to enhance the administration and machinery of the public sector.
The Government can still afford to reward them despite the current
economic situation as we have allocations for this.''
	   Abdul Halim was asked to comment on whether the cutbacks in
expenditure would affect promotions. He was also asked to comment
on Cuepacs' move to review the scheme.
	   Cuepacs, the umbrella organisation representing civil servants'
unions, has been objecting to the NRS matrix system of appraisal
introduced on Jan 1, 1992, where high achievers are rewarded with
double or triple increments.
	   Abdul Halim said the NRS was the best evaluation scheme thus
far.
	   ``If there are weaknesses in the system, as claimed by certain
quarters, we will review it and try to find a solution to the
problem.
	   ``So far, I have not received any memorandum with regard to the
weaknesses in the appraisal system.''
	   Under the NRS, two per cent of the staff get the diagonal
promotion which gives double or more increment, three per cent the
vertical promotion of double increment while the rest get single
increment.
	   On whether the Government would be paying bonus to civil
servants this year, he said the matter had not been decided.
	   To another question, Abdul Halim, who is also Puspanita's
adviser, said the Government would continue to freeze recruitments
as it headed for an electronic government.
	   ``We are in the midst of trying to downsize the number of staff
at government departments.
	   ``However, not all departments will be affected. The number of
teachers, for instance, cannot be reduced due to the increase in
student population.''
	   Abdul Halim said a review would be conducted from time to time
to identify departments where the number of workers could be
reduced and absorbed by other departments.
	   The staff redeployment plan is to avoid new recruitments in line
with the Government's objective to downsize the civil service.
	   He said the study would also identify departments with excess
staff and re-assign them to other departments without affecting
their work performance.
	   Manpower in certain areas could be reduced with the advent of
electronic government, he said.
	   The Malaysian Administrative Modernisation and Manpower Planning
Unit in the Prime Minister's Department and the Public Service
Department would carry out a study on optimum manpower utilisation
in the civil service, he said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
