<HEADLINE>
Allow criticism, former State DAP leader urges leadership, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Allow criticism, former State DAP leader urges leadership, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ramlan Said; Lee Keng FattASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sun. - The controversy in the DAP over action
against three party leaders deepened with a former State DAP leader
today asking the leadership to allow criticism and ensure
impartiality in disciplinary proceedings.
	   Former Perak DAP chairman Ting Chek Ming said the action against
the three by the central executive committee on Wednesday came as
no surprise as he had also experienced a similar fate when he was
sacked from the State committee last month.
	   In a statement, Ting said that after his sacking, he had
appealed to the CEC but had yet to receive a reply.
	   At a Press conference in Malacca on Thursday, party
secretary-general Lim Kit Siang had announced the suspension of
national vice-chairman Liew Ah Kim and treasurer Fung Ket Wing, and
the removal of national publicity secretary Wee Choo Keong from his
post.
	   This followed complaints from the Malacca and Perak committees.
	   Ting said criticisms must be allowed in the party to attract
professionals to join it.
	   ``Transparency and accountability can only be achieved by the
setting up of an independent and impartial committee to investigate
the half-truths and falsehood told by Kit Siang to the Press.
	   Meanwhile, in Penang, Kit Siang said the three leaders who were
suspended and removed from their posts were welcome to take an
active part in the party's double campaign as they were still CEC
members.
	   One is the ``Sympathy, support and solidarity with Lim Guan
Eng'' campaign and the other is the ``National movement for
justice, freedom, democracy and good governance''.
	   He said in the past two months, Liew, Fung and Wee had not shown
any interest in the two campaigns.
	   ``The two campaigns have gained momentum because of the
tremendous support from the people and Wee, Liew and Fung should
seriously ask themselves whether they want them to fail.''
	   He said this when releasing white doves at a campaign for the
two causes in Bukit Mertajam.
	   Kit Siang said the CEC had removed or suspended the three from
their national party positions because it had lost confidence in
them as national leaders since they had refused to accept the
principle of collective leadership and responsibility for decisions
taken by the CEC.
	   
</TEXT>
