<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Middle East Business Briefs </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Jordan and Kuwait &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Yugoslavia has agreed to settle dlrs 34
million in debts to Jordan in the next few years, a diplomat said
Wednesday.
	   The agreement was reached during a visit by a Yugoslav
government delegation to Jordan earlier in the week, Yugoslav
Embassy spokesman Oliver Potezica said.
	   He told The Associated Press the debt was incurred by phosphate
purchases from Jordan in the 1980s.
	   He declined to say when the debt will be paid off, stressing
that more details must be worked out between the two sides.
	   He said the debt will be paid through tax exemptions on
Jordanian exports to central European and Black Sea countries via
Yugoslavia's free trade zones along the Danupe River.
	   Yugoslavia also agreed to launch two firms that will carry
infrastructural developments projects in Jordan at a low cost, he
added.
 &UR; ___
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ The United States has dispersed dlrs 79.2
million for development projects in cash-strapped Jordan, a U.S.
Embassy statement said Wednesday.
	   The statement said the contribution is part of dlrs 150 million
annual U.S. economic assistance to Jordan, which is saddled by dlrs
6.1 billion foreign debts.
	   Of the total, dlrs 60 million will be spent on financing the
design and construction of waste water management and efficiency of
water supply in Jordan, the statement said.
	   Another dlrs 13.5 million will be used to bolster the functions
of training centers to civil servants. The rest, or dlrs 5.7
million, will be allocated for family planning, including maternal
and child health care.
	   The United States pays an additional dlrs 75 million annually to
Jordan in military assistance.
 &UR; ___
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Germany has agreed to grant Jordan dlrs 5.6
million for various research projects, including watershed and pest
management, a German Embassy statement said Wednesday.
	   Of the total, dlrs 1.2 million will be spent on studies on
unspecified projects carried out by German experts who will also
train Jordanians, the statement said. It did not elaborate.
	   It said dlrs 1.7 million will be spent on new technologies for
long term agricultural and forestry projects in Wadi Ibn Hammad in
Kerak, 125 kilometers (78 miles) south of Amman.
	   The rest, or dlrs 2.7 million, will be spent on improving pest
management methods in Jordan.
 &UR; ___
	   KUWAIT (AP) _ The Pearl of Kuwait Real Estate Co. said Wednesday
it will raise its capital 50 percent to 60 million dinars (dlrs
196.07 million).
	   Abdullah al-Gabandi, the chairman of the company, told The
Associated Press that the firm needed the funds for new projects in
Kuwait and abroad, as well as for restructuring short-term debts of
around 10 million dinars (dlrs 32.67 million). He would not
elaborate.
	   The company, which is one of the largest real estate businesses
listed on the Kuwait Stock Exchange, intends to raise the money by
offering new stock.
	   Al-Gabandi said The Pearl of Kuwait Real Estate incurred losses
in 1997, but managed to recover them in the first quarter of this
year. He declined to provide figures before a general assembly
meeting scheduled for later this month.
 &UR; vars/vj
