<SLUG> EXTEND-TARGET-MARKETS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sun Malaysia aims to extend target markets, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Sun Malaysia aims to extend target markets, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ferina ManeckshaASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   NEWLY-APPOINTED managing director for Sun Microsystems Pte Ltd's
Malaysia branch office (Sun Malaysia) Govinathan Pillai has set a
target growth of between 20 and 30 per cent for the company in the
current financial year which ends in July next year.
	   To achieve this goal, Sun Malaysia will be looking to extend its
reach in its target markets such as education, telecommunications,
utilities, securities, manufacturing industries and government.
	   ``For example, we are strong in the securities segment of the
financial industry and are now moving into commercial banks,''
Govinathan said.
	   ``In the telecommunications industry, we have already
established ourselves in the Internet service provider (ISP)
market, and are making our assault into the commercial applications
arena,'' he told Computimes in Kuala Lumpur last week.
	   According to Govinathan, Sun Malaysia's aim is to find a way to
service the requirements of companies and in the process
establishes itself as a player in the key operational systems of
these organisations.
	   He said under the current economic downturn, it is not
sufficient to have the best, the latest and the fastest equipment.
	   Towards this end, he said, Sun Malaysia will focus on its value
proposition and help companies to optimise, economise and improve
efficiency during this economic uncertainties.
	   ``We want to help customers understand how the implementation of
a particular system can help them save costs and get out of a
financial situation, or help them exploit their strengths to go
into new areas,'' he added.
	   Another area of focus for Sun Malaysia will be in building
stronger channel relationships to help the partners develop their
skills to be in a better position to exploit the market when the
economic situation recovers.
	   ``It is important that the channels know and understand that the
principal does not desert them in difficult times,'' Govinathan
said.
	   Govinathan also intends to change the perception that Sun is
merely a provider of workstations and servers, as well as the Java
inventor. ``We are a mainstream company with full-fledged IT
solutions to offer,'' he said.
	   On his new position, Govinathan said the job offers him a new
management challenge as multinational corporations tend to attract
the top players in the industry and the high achievers with
different cultures and ways of doing things.
	   ``The challenge here is to learn to combine them and get the
best of everything to work as a team. In a local entity we have to
hire them young and as such have to constantly train and create a
working culture,'' he added.
	   Govinathan also said that the worldwide awareness and marketing
programmes undertaken by Sun Microsystems have helped to create
awareness locally, thus making it easier to explore and work with
local companies.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
