<HEADLINE>
Indian businessmen welcome PM's pledge of assistance, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Indian businessmen welcome PM's pledge of assistance, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   JOHOR BARU, Sun. - The Johor Indian Business Association today
welcomed the Prime Minister's assurance that the needs of all
Malaysians would be taken care of during these difficult times.
	   Jiba president P. Sivakumar said Datuk Seri Dr Mahathir
Mohamad's pledge that the Government was taking measures to ensure
all received assistance was also very gratifying.
	   He said such commitment by the country's top leadership was a
clear testimony that the Government had the interest and well-being
of all Malaysians at heart.
	   ``This is the best manifestation of a good Government,'' he
said, adding that it was very heart-warming to know the Government
recognised that all sections of the population had been hit hard by
the economic problems.
	   Sivakumar was commenting on the Prime Minister's speech in Kuala
Lumpur yesterday in conjunction with the 76th birthday of the Yang
di-Pertuan Agong Tuanku Ja'afar.
	   Among others, Dr Mahathir had assured Malaysians that no one
would be neglected or their problems glossed over by the Government
during the current economic situation.
	   He also said everyone, from unemployed workers and traders to
small and big entrepreneurs, would receive assistance or have their
burdens eased as the situation was not of their own making.
	   Sivakumar said Jiba, a non-governmental organisation dedicated
to helping Indian businessmen in Johor, appreciated the
Government's commitment and pledge of assistance.
	   Jiba provides managerial and technical support to Indian
businesses, and is involved in skills training, and joint ventures
with Bumiputera and Chinese enterprises. It also part of a
transport consortium.
	   Sivakumar said one sector of the economy badly in need of
government support and assistance was the transport industry. Small
independent lorry operators are among the worst hit by the
slowdown.
	   ``Hundreds of lorry operators have lost their vehicles to banks
and finance companies for defaulting on their mortgage payments.
Jiba appeals to the Prime Minister to work out a moratorium with
the financial institutions to allow the lorry operators to pay only
interest on their loans for six months, until the situation
improves.
	   ``Without government intervention, more operators will have to
close shop and this will affect the economy even further.''
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
