<SLUG> BC-APTV Outlook,1142 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>

</HEADLINE>
 &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  APTV 1300 GMT OUTLOOK WEDNESDAY JUNE 10 1998  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 

 &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  For Planner / Newsdesk use - stories expected to move in the
next 12 hours. All times are GMT.  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 
----
EXPECTED: &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 
----
KOSOVO: LATEST - APTV's package will include a large demonstration
in Pristina with thousands of ethnic Albanians calling for NATO
intervention in the explosive province. We are efforting pictures of
US envoy Richard Miles' tour of Decani, Miles' meeting with Kosovo
Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova, and pictures from a Yugoslavian army
facility. (First Run Expected Europe Late 1500)
----
ERITREA: WOUNDED - A series of hostilities have erupted since
Ethiopian warplanes bombed an Eritrean military airport over the
weekend. APTV has pictures of the bombing aftermath, including
visuals of the wounded recovering in hospital in Asmara. (First Run
Expected Europe Late 1500)
----
US: KIM - APTV will carry L-I-V-E from 1400 to 1420gmt a speech by
South Korean leader Kim Dae-jung as he addresses a joint session of
Congress in Washington. APTV will provide a comprehensive package of
the highlights following the L-I-V-E broadcast. (First Run Expected
Europe Late 1500)
---
BELGIUM: NATO -  Hundreds of Albanian protesters are outside NATO
headquarters in Brussels calling for troop deployment in Kosovo.
Inside, ambassadors are meeting to determine what kind of NATO
action is needed to stop the conflict. APTV will have pictures of
the demonstration and meeting. (First Run Expected Europe Late 1500)
---
ITALY: COHEN - US Defense Secretary William Cohen is in Rome for a
meeting with Italian Defense Minister Beniamino Andreatta before he
continues on to Brussels for talks with NATO defense ministers.
Kosovo is at the top of the agenda for both meetings. (TBC)
---
WORLD CUP: TICKETS - APTV has the story of disappointed World Cup
fans who've shelled out more than a thousand dollars for a ticket,
but have found they've been duped once they arrive in France. (First
Run Expected Europe 1500)
----
WORLD CUP: FANS - As Scottish and Brazilian fans stream into Paris
for the World Cup, APTV is on site to capture their arrival,
celebrations and the security measures that French authorities hope
will keep them under control. (First Run Expected Europe Late 1500g)
----
MONTPELLIER: FANS - Norwegian and Morroccan fans gather for their
match in Montpellier. (First Run Expected Europe Late 1500g)
----
MACAU: ADIDAS - An exiled Chinese dissident claims Chinese prisoners
have made some of the footballs being used in World Cup matches.
APTV will have comments from Bao Ge, a former Chinese prisoner who
says he made some of the balls, and reaction from an Adidas'
spokesman who denies the accusations. (First Run Expected Europe
Late 1500)
----
BRAZIL: WORLD CUP - APTV is chasing fan reaction in Brazil as the
Scottish and Brazilian teams square off during the opening game in
Paris. (First Run Expected Latin America 1900)
----
UK: DIANA - APTV has exclusive pictures from inside the tiny London
flat where Princess Diana lived when she became engaged to Prince
Charles. (First run expected N.America Late 1930)
----
US: GREENSPAN -  US Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan
testifies before the congressional joint economic committee on
monetary policy at about 1500 GMT. APTV will have his latest
comments on interest rates and the Japanese yen, plus any reaction
following the speech. (First Run Expected Europe Late 1500)
----
FRANCE: ARGENTINA -  Argentina's President Carlos Menem visits with
French leader Jacques Chirac at 1200gmt, then attends the World Cup
opening match at 1700gmt. APTV will provide coverage of the day's
events. (First Run Expected Latin America 1900)
----
US: CHINA - Chinese dissident Harry Wu will address a US
International Relations subcommittee hearing on abortion and
sterilisation in China. APTV will have Wu's testimony in addition to
comments from the former administrator of China's Planned Birth
Control Office; a victim of coercive population control. (First Run
North America Late 1930g)
---
RUNNING &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 
----
INDIA: CYCLONE - APTV has pictures of the powerful storm that has
killed more than 200 people and left hundreds of thousands homeless
in western India. (First Run F-L-A-S-H 1050g) No Access India.
----
JERUSALEM: CLASHES - Israeli police dragged away dozens of Canadian
and American rights activists who gathered in an Arab neighbourhood
of east Jerusalem on Wednesday to protest Jewish settlement
building. APTV has pictures of the violent scuffles, and a soundbite
from one of the protestors. (First Run 0900 Americas)
----
KOSOVO: ENVOY - US envoy Richard Miles is in Decani, a Kosovo town
which has been destroyed by fighting between Serbs and Albanians.
APTV's package includes comments from Miles and pictures of the
burned cars and destroyed homes. (First Run 1050g F-L-A-S-H)
----
RUSSIA: ROYALS - Russia's aristocratic families may be dead, but for
some, like Prince Meshersky, the legacy remains. Now that the days
of Communism have past, the prince has seized back his estate and is
rebuilding it by hand. APTV has pictures of the rebuilding and
comments from the Prince. (First Run Europe Update 1130g)
----
EU: BEEF 2 - APTV is in Brussels where the European Commission is
expected to lift the ban on British beef exports after two years.
Comments include soundbites from EU head Jacques Santer. (First Run
Europe Update 1130g)
---
JAPAN: SCIENCE - An international team of scientists say they have
evidence that an infinitesimally small subatomic particle called the
neutrino has mass. If true, it is a revolutionary finding because
it means the universe is not expanding but in fact contracting.
First run Asia Pacific Late 0715g
----
THAILAND: SPICE - The Spice Girls have inspired lookalike bands
worldwide, but few are more exotic than Bangkok's transvestite band
"Ersatz Spice". APTV has talked to the boys and shot them in action.
First run Asia Pacific Late 0715g
----
FRANCE: DISTURBANCES 3 - This wrap includes pictures of street
revellers being arrested by police in Paris, a soundbite from a
Scottish World Cup fan, (first run Australia/NZealand 0000) and the
"Fete du Football" parade which took place just before on the Champs
Elysee. (First Run F-L-A-S-H 1050g)
---
