<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Croatia,0435 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Croats fight to limit injury list _ and stay motivated
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By TONY CZUCZKA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VITTEL, France (AP) _ Already missing a top striker, Croatian
coach Miroslav Blazevic dreads the idea of performing more
``acrobatics'' with his lineup.
	   But inside defender Slaven Bilic, one of the team's mainstays,
may force his boss to do just that if his hamstring strain doesn't
clear up in time for Croatia's World Cup debut against fellow
newcomer Jamaica on Sunday.
	   Team doctors will wait until Friday to advise Blazevic whether
the 29-year-old Everton defender, who has no easy substitute, is
fit to play.
	   ``It's a crucial problem,'' Blazevic said after Wednesday's
light practice on a rain-soaked field at the local stadium. ``At
that point, I would have to do some acrobatics, something no one
recommends in a serious situation like the World Cup.''
	   A quarterfinalist in the 1996 European Championship, the Croats
are considered a dark horse at the World Cup.
	   They were decimated even before taking up quarters in this
pastoral eastern French spa town when their hottest striker, Alen
Boksic of Rome's Lazio, dropped out with an injury. And forward
Igor Cvitanovic was thrown off the squad for refusing to run laps
in practice.
	   In their last warmup before leaving home, the Croats whipped
non-qualifier Australia 7-0.
	   But Blazevic, a strict disciplinarian who likes to bark martial
orders to his players, wasn't happy with their lackadaisical
performance in the final tuneup, a 2-1 against local third division
team Raon L'Etape on Tuesday night.
	   ``I shouted at all of them,'' he said. ``This was not worthy of
our reputation.''
	   Croatia's top scorer Davor Suker, of European champion Real
Madrid, even missed a penalty kick during the game.
	   Then again, Blazevic may not have been showing his hand because
Jamaican trainer Rene Simoes was in the stands checking out the
Reggae Boyz' first opponent.
	   Blazevic has watched the Jamaicans play twice, against Brazil
and Sweden. He says the main challenge is ``their
unpredictability.''
	   But self-confidence is never in short supply with the Croatians,
who are shouldering the hopes of a traditionally soccer-mad nation
preoccupied with the Yugoslav wars and economic problems this
decade.
	   ``We will play our game,'' Blazevic insists. ``I don't adapt to
others' style.''
	   In its other first-round matches, Croatia meets Japan on June 20
and two-time world champion Argentina on June 26.
	   (tc-sl)
</TEXT>
