<SLUG> VOLUNTEERS-PASSENGERS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Volunteers to assist passengers at KLIA, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Volunteers to assist passengers at KLIA, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Azrani RustamASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sun. - Passengers using the new Kuala Lumpur
International Airport in Sepang will not have to worry about
getting lost as there will be airport ``ambassadors'' to assist
them.
	   Malaysia Airports Berhad, which will be operating the RM10.5
billion airport, has created the service to ensure smooth passenger
flow and reduce incidents of passengers missing flights. The
necessity arose after airport trials revealed that some passengers
at the airport for the first time, had lost their way.
	   It happened again yesterday, in what was the biggest operation
trials comprising more than 3,000 volunteers, with many complaining
that the lack of information and instructions made it difficult for
them to find the check-in counters and aircraft gates.
	   Malaysia Airports (Sepang) Sdn Bhd airport operations executive
Khaw Sim Min said the service will start with about 200 volunteers
from Malaysia Airports.
	   They will be providing help to passengers at ``strategic and
important''
	   locations within the airport.
	   ``The airport is such a huge complex that it could be very
daunting for any passenger coming for the first time. Although we
have enough signages around the airport, there are still people who
will require assistance.
	   ``The ambassadors will not only help passengers find their gates
or check-in counters but also assist them by providing information
on important airport procedures.''
	   He added that the service would bring to the airport a sense of
``user- friendliness'' and show that the spirit of a caring society
was well embedded in its staff.
	   ``It will also provide a warm and friendly treatment to
foreigners who come here and create a lasting positive impression
of the airport and the country.''
	   He said more than anything, the service will mean that
passengers can rest assured that they will pass through the airport
with a sense of safety, security and comfort.
	   Volunteers will have to attend a five-day training programme to
equip them with basic knowledge and skill required for the task.
	   ``This is also to familiarise themselves with every part of the
airport and the services and facilities available.''
	   Asked if the service will be a permanent feature of the airport,
Khaw said: ``We will continue to provide assistance as long as it
is required. We may stop the service once passengers are familiar
with the airport.''
	   KLIA will be officially opened by the Yang di-Pertuan Agong
Tuanku Ja'afar on June 27 and will commence full commercial
operations on June 30.
	   
</TEXT>
