<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Czar's Burial </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government regrets patriarch won't attend burial
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ A deputy prime minister said Wednesday he regrets
that the Russian Orthodox Church patriarch will not attend the
burial of the country's last czar.
	   Boris Nemtsov said he did not know whether Alexy II's decision
means that President Boris Yeltsin will also miss the July 17
service, Russian news agencies reported.
	   The church's Holy Synod said Tuesday that no member of the
church hierarchy would take part in the burial of Czar Nicholas II,
his family and servants, but that local priests in St. Petersburg
could.
	   The church has expressed lingering doubts over the identity of
nine sets of bones recovered in 1991, despite a six-year
investigation and forensic tests in Russia, Britain and the United
States.
	   Despite the patriarch's decision, ``it is a matter of conscience
and honor to bury the remains of the czar and his relatives on July
17 in St. Petersburg on day of the 80th anniversary of the shooting
of the imperial family,'' Nemtsov said.
	   Nemtsov headed the Russian government commission that was in
charge of testing the remains.
	   Russian media have said that Yeltsin would only take part in the
ceremony if the patriarch did. Relatives of the czar may also skip
the burial, Interfax said.
	   ``The Royal House treated the Holy Synod's decision with great
respect because it shares the patriarch's doubts on the
authenticity of the remains,'' said a spokesman for the relatives,
Alexander Zakatov.
	   Zakatov said Grand Duchess Maria Vladimirovna Romanova will
decide by the end of June whether to attend the burial. The grand
duchess and her teen-age son Georgy are considered by most
monarchists to be the heirs to the Romanov throne. Her father was a
first cousin of the czar.
	   The funeral service will be held in the Peter and Paul
Cathedral, the traditional burial site of the Romanovs, who ruled
Russia for 300 years. Hundreds of foreign representatives have been
invited to attend.
	   (ls) 	   
</TEXT>
