<BODY>
<SLUG> LONG-MARCH-ON-WAY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Long March on way to CHT after 9-hour delay, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Long March on way to CHT after 9-hour delay, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The opposition BNP-led long march headed for the Chittagong Hill
Tracts (CHT) on Tuesday evening after being held up for nine long
hours at Mukti Sarani near Kanchpur Bridge, 10 kilometres from
Dhaka, due to roadblocks on both sides of the bridge.
	   The road blocks were put up by placing about 200 trucks and
other vehicles across the street, which caused a huge traffic jam
making movement of vehicular traffic impossible.
	   Tyres of some of these vehicles were deflated by gunfire. As the
day wore on the number of stranded vehicles on both sides of the
bridge swelled.
	   The police cleared the road at around 6 in the evening with the
help of the Roads and Highways Department thus enabling the long
marchers to resume their journey towards Chittagong.
	   At the head of the caravan was BNP Chairperson Begum Khaleda
Zia's vehicle with about 700 automobiles closely following it.
	   At Mukti Sarani and its adjoining areas the nine hour wait was
tension-packed punctuated by burst of gunfire and chase and
counter-chase between the supporters of the march and their
opponents. According to the long marchers at least 50 shots were
fired towards them by unidentified gunmen.
	   Three activists belonging to the Jatiyatabadi Chhatra Dal (JCD)
were injured as a result.
	   Begum Khaleda Zia, talking to newsmen, accused the government of
deliberately creating obstruction to the passage of long march even
though it had promised not to do so. She said that MPs belonging to
the ruling party had organised terrorist activities although the
government through a press note had prohibited carrying of firearms
in political programmes. She particularly held Shamim Osman, MP of
Awami League from Narayangonj responsible for terrorist activities
and for creating obstructions to the movement of traffic.
	   But after crossing the bridge at around 7 pm the BNP and its
allies including the Jamaat-e-Islami demanded that the long march
be escorted by the police upto its destination and official road
clearance be given to complete the march peacefully. The marchers
again started proceeding towards Chittagong when the government
fulfilled their demands. A contingent of police will now escort the
long march and protect it from any kind of intervention by any
quarter in any place along the Dhaka-Chittagong Highway.
	   Jatiyatabadi Jubodal leader Mirza Abbas alleged that the
opponents of marchers also abducted two activists of the party
known to be ward commissioners of Dhaka. The wounded persons were
being treated by the doctors travelling along with the marchers.
	   Local people said that on Monday night a group of armed youth
came near Kanchpur and barricaded the road with trucks and buses.
The youths fired at the wheels of the vehicles so that no one could
remove them from the spot.
	   The plying of buses to and from Dhaka came to a standstill from
10 pm on Monday night. No newspaper from Dhaka could be sent after
Kanchpur from Dhaka on Tuesday due to road barricade.
	   Though the local people alleged that the blockade was created by
the cadres of the local MP, Industries Minister Tofail Ahmed in an
interview with the BBC said that the blockade was created by
truckdrivers in protest against some illegal demands by the JCD
workers, the student wing of the BNP.
	   Meanwhile, angry marchers obstructed by the barricades, damaged
several vehicles near the Kanchpur Bridge as the long march to CHT
stayed halted here.
	   At this stage BNP Chairperson Begum Zia asked her party
activists to remain calm and wait till the road was cleared by the
authorities.
	   ``We will sit here if we are not allowed to move on,'' she told
newsmen who are covering the long march.
	   It was decided that the Deputy Opposition leader Professor
Badruddoza Chowdhury now in Chittagong, would lead the long march
from there if she was kept obstructed.
	   Jamaat-e-Islami and other smaller groups in the seven-party
alliance followed the BNP's march. Leaders of Jamaat and Jatiya
Party (Kazi Zafar) had brief consultation with Begum Zia to review
the situation.
	   When Begum Zia was holding a meeting at Mahanagar filling
station near link road, a group of BNP activists were seen chasing
a group of Awami League activists near Sanarpar. Both the groups
pelted stones at each other.
	   Later the BNP supporters entered the village and ransacked the
area. They also set fire to a shop which was later extinguished by
the people. In this incident one BNP worker was injured.
	   Narayanganj Awami League held a rally at Kanchpur Bridge
crossing from 7 am to 10 am when its leaders Prof Nazma Rahman,
Shamim Osman MP and Major Gen (Retd) KM Shafiullah warned that they
would not allow the marchers to pass through the area.
	   Riot police, armed battalion and Ansars, deployed there passed
the time as onlookers. Local people alleged that some armed
youngsters fired at several trucks and looted several buses which
were either coming from Chittagong or going from Dhaka. There was a
rumour that some of the women passengers were not only looted but
also being molested by the armed hooligans.
	   Later, when trucks and buses were coming to the spot, armed
hooligans stopped them and burst the tyres. As such there was a
total mess on the highway and no vehicles could ply on the road
till the police cleared the way at around 6 pm.
	   Driver Alauddin alleged that the armed goons snatched away 1800
taka from him, while Babul Hossen alleged that he was robbed of
Taka 5000. Besides Sirajul Haque a shrimp businessman said that he
was robbed of Tk 7,000 while another businessman Abu Bakar said
that the armed goons snatched away 12,000 taka from him.
	   One newly-wed woman was forcibly brought down from a Dhaka-bound
bus and was allegedly violated by the armed hooligans.
	   BNP leaders contacted the Home Ministry from the spot by
telephone and the authorities were learnt to have instructed
on-duty police to clear the road as soon as possible.
	   The source in the administration however said that the police on
duty were instructed only at around 4.30 pm to clear the way. The
source expressed surprise that when the administration could have
given instruction instantly why it took about 20 hours time to do
so.
	   Shamim Osman talking to our Narayanganj Correspondent Mostafa
Karim said that they did not do anything beyond the programme
announced by the central leaders. He said that the Awami League
brought out only peace procession in the morning and in the evening
from Shiddhirganj area. He said that the AL workers did not stage
any sit-in on the Dhaka-Chittagong Highway. He alleged that the
workers of the BNP wanted to snatch the buses and trucks on Monday
night. He said as the drivers of the vehicles fled out of fear of
the BNP cadres there was an automatic road barricade.
	   He said that he had heard the reports of firing but did not see
anything like that. He said that there was no intention of
attacking the democratic procession of any party.
	   When asked, the District Administration did not blame anybody
for blocking the road. However Additional District Magistrate Ujjal
Bikash Dutta said that the administration was trying to maintain
law and order.
	   During the tension Begum Zia addressed gathering several times
and each time she urged upon all to be patient in the face of all
kinds of provocation.
	   Addressing party workers after remaining stranded on the
Dhaka-Chittagong Highway at Sanarpar point within the
Dhaka-Narayanganj-Demra (DND) area for more than nine hours, as
rival political activists blocked the way, she said the government
would not be able to undo the movement by closing roads used by the
people.
	   Begum Zia made her address after holding a meeting with the
members of the BNP Standing Committee and some senior leaders at
the roadside office of a petrol filling station and announced the
decision to continue the long march.
	   The BNP chief sought to know from the long marchers if they were
ready to resume the march towards the CHT. The audience replied in
a thunderous chorus, ``Yes.'' She then advised the long marchers to
peacefully wait before the march started again after the painful
delay.
	   BNP workers had earlier become restive and had been raising
slogans in favour of a tough stance to break the barricade at the
Kanchpur point and carry forward the long march. Party workers
expressed spontaneous jubilation when Begum Zia finally announced
resumption of the long march.
	   Earlier addressing the brief rally at Paltan Maidan from where
the march started in the morning Begum Zia charged the government
with conspiracies to hand over the CHT to India. She posed a
question as to why the government did not want the people to go to
the CHT although citizens had the right to go anywhere and hold
meetings and processions.
	   Announcing the start of the long march from there she said,
``Allah is with us.'' She invited all long marchers to join in a
munajat for its success. The munajat was led by Rafiqul Islam Bakul
MP.
	   Leader of the Opposition started the long march of BNP from
Paltan Maidan by warning the government that it would have to bear
the responsibility of any consequences arising out of any
obstruction.
	   She reached the historic site at around 8.40 am and was straight
driven to the centre of the ground in an off-white jeep, driven by
her son Tariq Rahman. The BNP Chairperson briefly addressed the
huge gathering standing on the jeep.
	   The marchers carried national and BNP flags and portraits of
late President Ziaur Rahman and Begum Khaleda Zia. They shouted
various slogans, including down with Sheikh Hasina, scrap the black
CHT accord, and resist Indian conspiracy.
	   From early morning, thousands of party activists from the city,
its adjoining districts and far flung areas started to converge at
the Paltan Maidan to join the march as more than 5000 police and
para-military BDR guarded the capital.
	   Activists of Jamaat gathered at Ramna Green and began the long
march at 9.45 am. Party Chief Professor Golam Azam addressed the
gathering before leading the march.
	   At Sanarpar Begum Zia said that the government had seized all
buses and trucks at the police lines to obstruct the long march
because it had been detached from the people. Begum Zia said that
her party workers had stayed on the highway peacefully for the
whole day.
	   Earlier talking to newsmen immediately after the long march
caravan came to a halt due to obstructions created on the Kanchpur
bridge she alleged that the government had intentionally done this
which proved that the government had done something wrong regarding
the CHT and did not want other people to go there.
	   Meanwhile, the streets of the metropolis were still mostly
vacant and Dhaka dwellers were yet to begin the normal chores of
life when the BNP rally began at the historic Paltan Maidan at 7
A.M. before the start of the long march to the Chittagong Hill
Tracts (CHT).
	   Among the central leaders of the party who reached there early
were: Khondker Delwar Hossain, Barrister Abdus Salam Talukdar,
Chowdhury Kamal Ibne Yusuf, Justice Habibul Islam Bhuiyan, Sheikh
Tayebur Rahman, Mayor of Khulna City Corporation, Khondoker
Mahbubuddin Ahmed, Moudud Ahmed, Dr. Khondker Mosharraf Hossain,
Abdul Matin Chowdhury, Salahuddin Quader Chowdhury, Lt. Gen (retd)
Mir Shawkat Ali and Mirza Abbas former Mayor of the Dhaka City
Corporation.
	   Their faces were grim as they already had information that the
route of the long march had been blocked all the way from Jatrabari
to Kanchpur. Moudud Ahmed told one central leader that the earlier
the march was started the better because trouble might increase
with the passing of the morning hours.
	   As streams of people continued to come, BNP's Publicity
Secretary Fazlur Rahman Patal told the gathering that police was
forcibly taking away motor vehicles brought by party workers for
use in the long march.
	   Abdul Mannan Bhuiyan while addressing the gathering advised long
marchers who came in buses and microbuses not to disembark fearing
that the vehicles might be requisitioned by police.
	   After Mannan Bhuiyan's address Muhammad Qamruzzaman of Jamaat
spoke wishing the programme a success. Abdus Salam Talukdar,
Barrister Moudud Ahmed, KM Obaidur Rahman MP, Amanullah Aman MP,
Advocate Nurul Huq Majumder of the National Democratic Alliance,
and Shawkat Hossain Nilo of the Progressive Nationalist Party spoke
at the rally. The Programme was cut short when Begum Khaleda Zia
reached the venue and the long march began with a short speech made
by her. The Paltan area by then turned into a human sea.
	   Our Comilla correspondent adds: the people who came to
participate in the long march here on Tuesday became agitated at
the news that the motorcade of the opposition leader Begum Khaleda
Zia had been obstructed at Shanir Akhra near Dhaka. The agitated
mob uprooted rail-line at Paduar Bazar near Comilla.
	   The agitated mob also ransacked an inter-city train, seven
buses, three trucks, a BDR vehicle, a police van and the local
Awami League office.
	   About 20,000 people from Comilla, Sylhet, Moulavibazar,
Habiganj, Sunamganj, Kishsoreganj, Brahmanbaria, Chandpur, Laxmipur
and Noakhali thronged at the Paduar Bazar on the Dhaka-Chittagong
highway at about 12 noon. The movement of vehicles came to a
standstill on the Dhaka-Chittagong highway as well as the Noakhali
and Chandpur road due to the gathering.
	   The long marchers pelted stones at the inter-city Upakul Express
which was going to Noakhali from Dhaka at about 4.30 pm.
	   At about 5.15 pm the long marchers uprooted the tracks rail near
Paduar Bazar. They also ransacked signalling apparatuses. Train
communication between Dhaka and Chittagong, Noakhali, Chandpur and
some other parts of the country got snapped following the incident.
	   Chase and counter chase occured between the pro-long march
processionists and supporters of a peace rally at Chandina. Four
Awami League leaders including the Comilla (North) district Awami
League general secretary Jahangir Alam Sarker were injured. One of
the injured Kazi Golam Mostafa was admitted to Comilla Medical
College Hospital. Long marchers ransacked a truck at Kabila on the
Dhaka-Chittagong highway.
	   No vehicles plied the Dhaka-Chittagong highway.
	   Begum Zia addressing a way side gathering at Padua Bazar said
that the future movement would be for protecting the independence
and sovereignty of the country and for removing the autocrats from
power.
	   Begum Zia reached Comilla at around 11.15 p.m and addressed the
gathering from her Pajerp Jeep. She urged the people to be united
to bring the downfall of the autocratic government.
	   
</TEXT>
