<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Germans battle for places in starting lineup
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NESHA STARCEVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NICE, France (AP) _ Coach Berti Vogts has created such an
intense competitive atmosphere in the German team that apart from
goalkeeper Andreas Koepke virtually none of the other 21 players
are certain to be among the starters.
	   While often such rivalries breed jealousies and hostilities, at
least some German players think they can help the team capture its
fourth World Cup title.
	   ``I think our strength can be that everyone accepts that not
everybody can be among the starters and that all players are ready
to take on any role assigned by the coach,'' Olaf Thon said
Wednesday.
	   Thon, the 32-year-old libero, himself is in such a position.
	   Recalled to the team after a four-year absence to replace
injured Matthias Sammer, Thon himself fell victim to an ankle
injury that left his fitness in doubt shortly before the World Cup.
	   That prompted Vogts to recall Lothar Matthaeus, the 37-year-old
veteran with a German record of 125 caps who is in his fifth World
Cup. Matthaeus is usually not content with a bench role.
	   Thon said he wasn't worried. ``It's very good that our coach can
choose from two very good players for each position,'' he said.
	   ``I am relaxed about it, I think the coach will look at the
performance of each players and I think I belong in the starting
lineup,'' Thon said. ``I'll try to play libero but if necessary I
can also play in the midfield.''
	   With so many experienced players around _ Germany's average age
is 29 years and seven months _ many players are used to leadership
positions in their clubs and the national team.
	   Juergen Klinsmann is the captain, a role that used to belong to
Matthaeus, who likes being the center of attention. They have
officially buried the hatchet but their well-publicized feuds could
erupt any time.
	   Midfielder Andreas Moeller said there was good team spirit in
the camp, but that competition was greater than two years ago when
Germany won the European title.
	   ``It's the main difference in our preparation,'' Moeller said.
``Berti has really fired up the competition among us, he's getting
the maximum out of all players.''
	   ``No one feels secure and you can see and feel the fire on the
pitch every day in practice,'' Moeller said.
	   ``I don't really think there is one leader, I think the
leadership is spread out among several players,'' he said.
	   ``Each players should concentrate on his strengths and everybody
will be judged on their performances,'' Moeller said.
	   (ns-sl)
</TEXT>
