<SLUG> WILDLIFE-DEATH'S-DOOR sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Wildlife at death's door, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Wildlife at death's door, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   WILDLIFE in exile. Such is the sorry fate of the country's
numerous wildlife species which have been purged from their natural
habitats by rapid and ill-conceived development.
	   But unlike man, these displaced forest creatures are not endowed
with the intellectual wherewithal for smooth and fast adaptation to
a new environment. Most do not survive. The passing of each day in
a hostile environment brings the animals closer to the brink of
extinction. Without the thick cover of the foliage, they are most
vulnerable to the insatiable appetite of some for exotic meat and
trophies. They either end up on a plate with head and skin pierced
to the wall or left maimed, if not bleeding to death in the traps.
	   Neither are these homeless creatures welcomed in our midst. The
tampering of the natural ecology by urban expansion has driven the
animals to the edge of the concrete jungle and people's backyards.
Sightings of civet cats, monitor lizards, monkeys, slow lorises and
boa constrictors arouse more shudder than sympathy. Ironically,
these homeless creatures are accused of encroaching into the lives
of city dwellers. It is unfortunate that very few are willing to
link the displacement of the animals to forest encroachment by man
- all in the name of development.
	   But it is no longer correct to argue that this is the price we
have to pay for progress.
	   Development is indeed a necessity that should be finely balanced
in harmony with nature. Walking this fine line encompasses the
question of prioritising matters and practicality. True, reality
dictates priorities but it is a realism which must be rooted in the
understanding that man's needs should not assume a greater
importance over the needs of nature's habitants. The endurance and
loveliness of the landscape, plants and animals depend on the human
ability to respect their right to existence.
	   Man is endowed with intellectual prowess and consequently, it is
man who has the greater responsibility to protect the natural
resources as assets which will be turned over to the next
generation with increased, and not impaired, value. Taming nature
does not imply its destruction. Acceptable compromises should be
seen as sustainable solutions.
	   The nation does not lack a comprehensive environmental
protection policy. But the long list of endangered species suggest
that there are troubling weaknesses in its implementation. The loss
of the rhinoceros habitat in the Endau-Rompin area indicates that
our eco-tourism activities pay homage to tourism comfort and needs
than the continued survival of the animals. There is an urgent need
to ensure the country's eco-tourism activities are carried out in a
manner that is sensitive to the needs of the habitats. An animal's
conservation site is not meant to be a circus.
	   As important as eco-tourism may be as a revenue earner, the
authorities should control the type of infrastructural development
built in these areas. It defeats the ultimate aim of environmental
protection if trees are felled and animals booted out to make way
for roads and chalets. The number of visitors per visit into the
wildlife and botanical sanctuaries should also be controlled.
	   The proposed review of the Protection of Wildlife Act is indeed
timely.
	   But it must be realised that the long-term survivability of the
wildlife species and their natural habitats will involve much more
than tougher legislation and set-aside refuge sites. Funds should
be pumped into sanctuaries to ensure they are scientifically
managed.
	   
</TEXT>
