<BODY>
<SLUG> 20-INJURED-IN-AL-BNP sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
20 injured in AL-BNP clash in Ctg, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
20 injured in AL-BNP clash in Ctg, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Abul BasharASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   At least twenty persons, including a leader of the Awami League
city unit, were injured and about 30 vehicles damaged when the
workers of BNP and Awami League were locked in a clash in New
Market areas here this evening.
	   Some eight persons were also arrested from different points.
Arms and ammunition were recovered from their possession.
	   Meanwhile, the Deputy Leader of the Opposition in Parliament, Dr
Badruddoza Chowdhury today said the long march towards Khagrachari
will start from here at 8 am tomorrow if the situation remains
normal.
	   Senior leaders of BNP, including Badruddoza Chowdhury at a press
briefing this evening alleged that Awami League workers attacked
the procession of BNP in Darul Fazal Market area when the
procession was crossing the area. They claimed that police and
workers of Chhatra League opened fire in the New Market area.
	   When asked, an official of Chittagong Metropolitan Police (CMP)
told The Independent that police lobbed tear gas shells and fired
into the air to disperse the rival groups.
	   Joint Secretary of Awami League city unit Kazi Enamul Hoq Danu
was injured by the brickbats hurled at him by the BNP men in Darul
Fazal Market area.
	   According to city corporation sources, at least 10 vehicles,
including the jeep of the Mayor, were damaged by the BNP activists
at different points in the city. The jeep of the mayor was damaged
in front of the Awami League office where he was attending a
meeting. Some BNP workers entered the City Corporation office and
damaged the vehicles, the corporation sources said.
	   Later addressing a rally at the Kazir Dewri Corner of the Port
city, Dr Badrudduzza Chowdhury alleged the government was hatching
a conspiracy to foil the long march. According to him, the
government will hand over the Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT) to
Shanti Bahini leader Santo Larma.
	   The president of city BNP Meer Naseer Uddin was in the chair.
The city unit held the rally in protest against the barricade on
the Dhaka-Chittagong Highway near Kanchpur. Badruddoza said the
workers of Awami League were trying to foil the long march
programme of BNP and its allies. He alleged that the government did
not want to allow the exercise of democratic norms and practices in
the country. ``The government had failed to run the state and
become an anti people government'' he said referring to power and
gas crises.
	   Oli Ahmed, member, BNP standing committee and convenor of the
long march supervisory committee alleged that at the directive of
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina, local Awami League leaders had sent
six hundred trucks towards Dhaka last night. The Awami League
workers led by Shafiullah MP and Shamim Osman MP of Narayangonj
placed the trucks on the road to foil the long march, he alleged.
	   Oli Ahmed MP warned that the Port city will be paralysed and
Sheikh Hasina will not be allowed to arrive here if the government
does not refrain from undemocratic activities. The rally was also
addressed, among others, by joint secretary of BNP Abdullah Al
Noman and Giasuddin Quader Chowdhury MP.
	   Jamaat-e-Islami also held a rally and brought out processions in
protest against the road barricade at Kanchpur near Dhaka. The
rally was chaired by the Jamaat city ameer Maulana Abu Taher.
Addressing the rally, Shahjahan Chowdhury, Prof Mofizur Rahman,
Afsaruddin Chowdhury and Shamsul Islam called upon the people to
join the long march towards Rangamati led by ameer Professor Golam
Azam tomorrow.
	   Meanwhile, the Awami League city unit held a rally in front of
the party office at Nasimon Bhaban in protest against the attack on
the party office reportedly by BNP workers.
	   Akhteruzzaman Chowdhury Babu, the central Commerce and Industry
Secretary of Awami League presided over the rally. The city Awami
League secretary and Mayor of Chittagong Alhaj ABM Mohiuddin
Chowdhury, vice president Alhaj Abul Kalam Showdagar, Dr Saydur
Rahman, Nayeemuddin and Advocate Ibrahim Hossain Babul addressing
the rally called for resisting the people who were engaged in
anti-social activities.
	   They said, the BNP workers attacked the AL office when they held
a meeting after their procession in support of the peace agreement
on CHT. ABM Mohiuddin Chowdhury termed the BNP as the patron of
terrorism and anarchy adding BNP was hatching a conspiracy to
destabilise the country.
	   Our Correspondent from Khagrachari adds: The members of law
enforcing agencies are on full alert in Khagrachari district town
to maintain law and order during the long march of BNP. Besides,
the Army was patrolling the Khagrachari-Chittagong road.
	   Meanwhile, BNP workers are preparing to welcome the long
marchers when they arrive at Khagrachari.
	   Shajuddin, the convenor of the All-Party Unity Council and long
march of BNP said at least four thousand Bangalees were waiting to
receive the long marchers. The All-Party Unity Council held a rally
at 8.30 pm at Shapla Chattar.
	   Earlier, Awami League held a rally at the same place in support
of the peace agreement on CHT. A large number of Awami League
workers carrying white flags attended the rally which was presided
over by Khagrachari district president of Awami League Nurunnabi.
	   The BNP also brought out a procession of trucks in support of
the long march.
	   The chairman of Khagrachari Pourashabha Md. Abul Kashem in a
statement said he will welcome the long marchers in the town.
	   Santo Larma, the chairman of Parbattya Chattagram Jana Sanghati
Samity (PCJSS) now staying in the town has directed his supporters
to maintain peace and discipline during the long march.
	   
</TEXT>
