<HEADLINE>
Long march to prove people against CHT deal: Jamaat, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Long march to prove people against CHT deal: Jamaat, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Jamaat-e-Islami ameer prof. Golam Azam yesterday said that the
long march would prove that the people of Bangladesh were against,
what he said, the black' Chittagong Hill Tracts Peace accord.
	   He was addressing a rally of the party at the Ramna Green prior
to the start of the long march towards Chittagong Hill Tracts.
Prof. Golam Azam led the march which started at about 9.45 am with
several thousand activists of the Jamaat-e-Islami shouting slogans
like ``Scrap the black accord, we don't accept the
unconstitutional' CHT agreement''.
	   Sitting on a jeep the 76-year old Jamaat ameer led the marchers
who were riding in buses, cars, jeeps and trucks. Some workers also
followed the motorcade of the marchers on foot.
	   Jamaat-e-Islami nayeb-e-ameer Maulana AKM Yusuf, Jamaat
parliamentary party leader Maulana Delwar Hossain Saidee MP, Jamaat
assistant secretary general Muhammad Quamaruzzaman, Ali Ahsan
Muhammad Mujahid, publicity secretary Abdul Kader Mollah, Jamaat
city unit leaders Maulana ATM Masum and Saiful Alam Khan Milon
spoke. Jamaat city ameer ATM Azharul Islam presided.
	   BNP standing committee member and former minister Barrister
Abdus Salam Talukdar addressed the rally expressing solidarity of
his party with the Jamaat programme. Jagpa vice president Dr. MA
Aziz and Dhaka University prof. Hasanuzzaman also spoke. BNP leader
Anwar Zahid was also present.
	   Prof. Golam Azam said the long march was organised to protest
against the announcement of the three hill districts as the special
area for a particular tribe. He said the Bangalees living in the
Chittagong hill tracts who owned half of the hilly areas were made
second class citizens through the Chittagong Hill Tracts peace
agreement. He said this could not be accepted and added that the
agreement must be cancelled.
	   The Jamaat ameer urged the tribal people not to be misled by the
India propaganda. He said India would soon demand gas, transit and
Chittagong port facilities from Bangladesh, and if those demands
were not met then an independent Jhumland' would be announced. He
said that Hasina government wouln't be able to avert such a
situation.
	   Condemning the government for the repressive measures it has
taken against the long marchers, prof. Golam Azam said ``we will go
to the Chittagong Hill Tracts, inshallah''.
	   Maulana AKM Yusuf said the long march was a spontaneous protest
of the people against the Chittagong Hill Tracts accord.
	   Maulana Delwar Hossain Saidee said the long march was supported
by the Quran and Hadith. He said it was the moral duty of every
Muslim to join the long march. He said all political parties and
intellectuals except those belonging to the Awami League were
supporting the long march.
	   Muhammad Quamaruzzaman said the government was trying to foil
the long march. He said police were creating obstacles at Kanchpur
and Tongi to prevent the long marchers from leaving Dhaka city for
Chittagong.
	   
</TEXT>
