<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Lending Rate,0283 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bank boosts lending rate by 2 percent
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ Two South African commercial
banks said Wednesday that they were increasing their prime lending
rate by 2 percentage points.
	   ABSA Group Ltd., one of the country's four major commercial
lending groups, said its boost to 20.25 percent would occur
Thursday. NBS Boland also announced an increase to 20.25 percent.
Other banks are expected to follow suit, Dow Jones Newswires said.
	   The interest hike follows the Central Bank's decision last month
to increase interest rates to attract investors to its bond and
currency markets to ward off a speculative raid on the South
African currency.
	   Last week, Chris Stals, governor of the Reserve Bank, persuaded
banks to hold off on lifting rates. As a sign of good will, the
bank eased its repo rate _ the main lever for setting monetary
policy _ 0.5 percentage point to 17.50 percent and promised further
cuts.
	   But market turmoil in Asia and eastern Europe has been
accompanied by a further weakening of the rand, bond and equity
markets.
	   ``As ABSA cannot absorb this negative impact on lending margins
for an indefinite period, it had no option but to adjust its
lending rates accordingly,'' the statement said.
	   The move came a day after Finance Minister Trevor Manuel urged
banks to stave off interest hikes.
	   ``We hope banks will grit their teeth in the interests of the
economy for a few more days,'' Manuel was quoted as saying in
Wednesday's Business Day.
	   ABSA is one of South Africa's four major commercial banking
groups, formed through acquisition of three other banking concerns
in 1991. 	   
</TEXT>
