w2980 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  KIBRIA'S-NEW-LOOKsked     06-10 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> KIBRIA'S-NEW-LOOK sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kibria's new look budget Thursday, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Kibria's new look budget Thursday, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Faruque AhmedASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The budget for 1998-99 to be presented in Parliament tomorrow
(Thursday) will introduce a new classification system of public
heads of expenditure to make the budget document clear and easy to
understand by ordinary people, an official source indicated,
yesterday.
	   The source said that the existing budget format developed in
1938 by colonial rulers was now inadequate to meet the requirements
of a modern state in which the role of the government had expanded
to new areas and more activities.
	   The source said that the need for a new comprehensive budget
format was felt by almost all the previous governments.
Accordingly, a working group was constituted in 1989 to suggest
``reforms in budgeting and expenditure control'' (RIBEC). It
carried its work over the past couple of years to develop the new
budget format.
	   Finance Minister SAMS Kibria in his budget speech last year
indicated that he would introduce a new classification system of
public expenditure in this year's budget.
	   An experts group tested the new format in the preparation of
last year's budget and the year before it. The Finance Minister
this year decided to present the budget taking up the new
classification form.
	   Asked what was the difference between the existing format and
the new format, an official source said that the allocations in the
existing system to ministries were made broadbased without
arranging information about financial aggregation at different
levels.
	   The new system would give budgetary information from many points
of view on a ministry, division or sector and on even very small
issues related to them.
	   For instance, the present format did not give information about
how much fuel cost or expenditure for buying stationery were
allocated to a ministry. Likewise, there was no room, said the
source, to find income receipts from the sale of confiscated goods
by police or old stores by customs.
	   The new format had a 13 digit numbers to present wide-ranging
information both on revenue and expenditure sides and capable of
responding to any budgetary queries within a ministry or at the
inter-ministerial level.
	   The database in the new format would be clearer and
comprehensive and offer more analytical capability by using graphs,
charts and other profiles.
	   The new format would reflect the administrative and legal
structure of the government in its framework and directly respond
to the requirements of the government's financial statistics as
mandated by the IMF.
	   It would further facilitate technical integration of the revenue
and development budget as both sides of the budget would be
accommodated within the classification structure.
	   In the new budget, numeric codes would be used as opposed to an
alphanumeric code now in practice. The budget documents and other
reports could be produced in two languages -- Bangla and English -
in the new format from the same source of data stored in the
computer.
	   It would be also applicable to all government's financial
transactions accounted for through the Consolidated Fund or Public
Account.
	   The sources said an on-line network had been established between
the Accounts Consolidation System located in the Office of the
Controller General of Accounts (CGA) and the Budget Database Office
at the Ministry of Finance.
	   It would give the Finance Ministry the ability to monitor
expenditure of the ministries and government's agencies.
	   
