<HEADLINE>
World airlines spend $1.6 billion to fix 2000 bug, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
World airlines spend $1.6 billion to fix 2000 bug, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The world's airlines are spending $1.6 billion to avoid being
bitten by the millennium bug, according to the International Air
Transport Association (IATA) , reports Reuters.This does not
include billions more being spent by air traffic control systems,
airports, computer reservations systems and other third party
suppliers and vendors to make sure that global air travel is not
seriously impaired by Year 2000 computer problems.
	   Nor does it include $20 million IATA is spending to assist and
monitor Year 2000 upgrades by suppliers such as commercial airports
and air traffic control systems.By mid-1999, IATA says it will make
available its audit information on airport and air traffic services
readiness so that planners at the carriers can determine whether
there are airports they would like to avoid on January 1, 2000.The
US Federal Aviation Administration is spending $190 million to
update that country's air traffic control system, FAA administrator
Jane Garvey said.
	   She told IATA's 54 annual general meeting here this week that
the FAA was originally thought to have weighed in too late on
upgrading or replacing its systems so that they can function
normally after January 1,2000.In January, Garvey had the programme
accelerated. A Year 2000 project coordinator was appointed within
the agency.Major US airlines are spending over $100 million each to
upgrade their systems. American Airlines is budgeting $160 million
and Delta Airlines $125 million, an IATA official said.
	   
</TEXT>
