<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Argentina-Dirty War </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Menem says Videla arrest case is strictly an Argentine affair
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By IAN PHILLIPS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Argentine President Carlos Menem said Wednesday the
arrest of former dictator Jorge Videla did not mean other countries
would succeed with lawsuits against other ``dirty war'' officials.
	   Menem, referring to Tuesday's arrest in Buenos Aires of Videla,
said it was a matter strictly ``for the Argentine justice system.''
	   Videla, 71, was charged Tuesday with ordering the kidnapping of
children born to parents who were killed during the 1976-83 dirty
war, and for falsifying identity documents.
	   Menem, whose 1990 pardon freed Videla and other senior members
of the dictatorship from jail, said Videla would have to answer the
charges.
	   ``All those who commit this type of crime must answer for it
before the courts,'' said Menem, on a two-day visit to attend
Wednesday's World Cup opening game between Brazil and Scotland.
	   As chief of the military, then general Videla had final
authority over death squads that waged a war of torture and murder
against political opponents, mainly leftists.
	   A Spanish judge investigating the disappearance of more than 300
Spaniards during the repression has said he wants Videla to appear
in court, either in Spain or Argentina.
	   ``This has nothing to do with them,'' Menem said, referring to
the Spanish investigators after a meeting with French President
Jacques Chirac.
	   ``This is a matter for Argentine justice.''
	   He added that ``contrary to what some might say, this shows that
the Argentine legal system is one of the best in the world.''
	   Argentine human rights groups are urging the Argentine
investigating judge to check allegations that some children of
dissidents who were slain were handed over to members of the
military, who raised them.
	   Videla is accused of being involved in more than 30 such cases.
	   The Argentine government claims 9,000 people disappeared during
that time, but some human rights groups put the figure at 30,000.
	   Videla was sentenced to life in prison in 1985 for human rights
abuses during the dictatorship. He since has lived as a virtual
recluse in the Argentine capital.
	   (ip-dgs)	   
</TEXT>
