<HEADLINE>
Tsang, parties in positive talks, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Tsang, parties in positive talks, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   May TamASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A TWO-HOUR meeting last night between Financial Secretary Sir
Donald Tsang Yam-kuen and leaders of seven political parties
defused what was quickly building into a head-on collision between
the administration and the parties.
	   Those involved in the discussions were quick to point out
afterwards that the meeting had been ``positive'' and ``not
confrontational''.
	   Liberal Party leader Allen Lee Peng-fei, who chairs the
cross-party coalition addressing the economic decline and
unemployment problems, said earlier there would be no room for
compromise on the six measures to revive the economy.
	   The government would have to accept the lot.
	   He also implied that legislators from the parties might block
legislation and funding applications from the government, unless
the administration accepted the measures.
	   After the meeting Mr Lee said the attitude of Sir Donald and
other officials' towards their proposals had been ``positive'',
even though Sir Donald had not made any commitments on some
proposals involving public money.
	   These include cutting property rates, returning provisional
taxes, reducing fuel taxes and trimming rents for commercial units
belonging to the Housing Authority.
	   Mr Lee said Sir Donald promised to consider the suggestions.
	   He stressed the attitude of the government officials had
improved.
	   ``The most important thing is they are not saying no to all
ideas raised, like before . . . this meeting will be a beginning.''
The next meeting has been scheduled for next week.
	   Sir Donald said both sides had a ``very frank, candid, and open
exchange''.
	   He denied feeling threatened by the combined number of votes the
opposition would be able to muster in the new Legislative Council.
	   ``I don't feel any pressure at all . . . We are like a group of
friends studying the same problem. I don't feel my colleagues
having pressure, either.'' But he did express reservations about
returning provisional taxes because he would have to take into
account its negative effects.
	   There were two measures where consensus was reached _ speeding
up infrastructural works and opening social services posts in a bid
to increase jobs.
	   
</TEXT>
