<SLUG> LAWSUIT-FOR-ADIDAS-OVER sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lawsuit for adidas over World Cup balls, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Lawsuit for adidas over World Cup balls, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Lucia Palpal-latoc and Sam YungASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A MAINLAND dissident will file a case in Hong Kong against
sportswear giant adidas for allegedly using prisoners such as
himself to produce soccer balls and other items for World Cup '98.
Bao Ge, 34, head of the US-based Chinese Voice of Human Rights,
said similar court cases would also be filed in the US, France and
Germany within the next few weeks. Details of the legal battle will
be unveiled by Mr Bao at a press conference in Macau today in time
for the opening of the World Cup in France. The legal action in
Hong Kong may serve as a test case on whether the SAR Government is
adhering to the principles of the International Labour
Organisation's convention against forced labour. The SAR is
required to eliminate forced labour because the convention
continues to apply even after the handover. Beijing, on the other
hand, has not signed the convention. The convention also applies in
the three countries where the cases will be filed. Mr Bao yesterday
said adidas should be held responsible for the use of forced labour
in prison camps to manufacture its products. After his arrest in
1994 for counter-revolutionary offences, he was sent to a labour
camp in Shanghai for three years. ``I was forced to produce the
footballs, some of which were marked with the words `France 98 FIFA
World Cup'.'' Mr Bao said he had submitted a writ to a US court and
was waiting for a reply as to when the legal proceedings could
start. But he refused to reveal whether there would be any form of
protest when the World Cup matches start today. Director of the
Information Centre on Human Rights and Democratic Movement in
China, Frank Lu Siqing, said he was not sure whether Mr Bao would
be successful in his legal battle. ``We are more concerned about
people's awareness on the use of forced labour in the mainland for
the production of goods for big companies.'' He said prisoners on
the mainland were forced to work 16 hours a day without any
compensation. The office of adidas in Hong Kong could not be
contacted last night.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
