<SLUG> BC-Bangladesh-Long March, 1st Ld-Writethru,0463 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede CHITTAGONG
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Long March ends at Khagrachari
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with end of long march. ADDS details and quotes.
CHANGES byline. No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos DHA101-102 &QL; 
 &UR; By FARID HOSSAIN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KHAGRACHARI, Bangladesh (AP) _ Thousands of protesters who
traveled from all over Bangladesh ended a two day anti-government
rally at a southern town Wednesday, voicing their opposition to a
peace accord with tribespeople in the southeast.
	   Opposition leader Khaleda Zia, who led one stream of protesters
400 kilometers (260 miles) by bus and car from the capital Dhaka,
addressed a cheering crowd of 35,000 at the stadium where just six
months ago, Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina signed the accord.
	   ``Success of the long march had proved beyond doubts that the
people in general do not accept the peace accord,'' Zia said.
	   The protesters, who traveled mostly by bus despite calling their
campaign the ``long march,'' say the peace accord with rebels from
the Buddhist Chakma tribe gives the Chakmas too much local power at
the expense of Muslim settlers from the north.
	   Chakma rebels, who surrendered their arms in exchange for local
autonomy, fought the government for 20 years, leaving more than
20,000 people, mostly Muslims, dead.
	   Zia said peace was welcome, but the accord was flawed because it
``sowed the seeds of separatism in the country.''
	   Abdul Quddus Mian, a 47-year-old school teacher, said most
locals participating in the opposition-sponsored protests were
Muslim settlers who felt the peace accord denied them equal status
with the tribespeople. Chakmas, the majority in the region, are
expected to dominate local councils that will have extensive power.
	   The protest was seen as a test of strength for former Prime
Minister Zia, who since losing power two years ago, has called
almost daily strikes, which often erupt into violence. The long
march ended without much violence.
	   The march began Tuesday in Dhaka, where it was delayed nine
hours by a road block of abandoned trucks, many with deflated tires
or no tires at all, set up by supporters of the prime minister.
	   Zia has called for a nationwide strike June 18 to protest
attempts to stop the march. Hasina had said she would allow the
protest. It was unclear whether her supporters acted with her
consent when they set up the road block.
	   Pro- and anti-government protesters fought Tuesday in
Chittagong, the starting point for another stream of protesters,
leaving 60 injured and scores of trucks and shops damaged, police
said.
	   One of the buses carrying protesters to Khagrachari skidded off
the road and fell 300 feet (100 meters) into a ravine, killing
three people and injuring 27. 	   
</TEXT>
