<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Yugoslavia-Savicevic,0432 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Savicevic, key Yugoslav midfielder, injured
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DUSAN STOJANOVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAINT GALMIER, France (AP) _ Yugoslav team preparations for the
World Cup suffered a serious setback as their key midfielder Dejan
Savicevic failed another fitness test Wednesday, ruling him out of
the opening match against Iran.
	   The formidable technical skills of the 31-year-old AC Milan star
_ nicknamed ``The Genius'' by Yugoslav and Italian fans _ are
believed to be crucial in Yugoslavia's World Cup campaign.
	   He is also considered the spiritual leader of the squad which
plays in Group F along with Iran, Germany and the United States.
	   ``It is well known what Savicevic means to our team,'' said
Yugoslav captain Dragan Stojkovic. ``He will definitely not play
against Iran and we hope to have him back fully recovered for our
next game against Germany.''
	   Savicevic, who is currently negotiating a transfer from AC Milan
to Fiorentina in the Italian league, suffered a knee ligament
injury while playing a club match about a month ago.
	   He has been plagued by a string of injuries during the past
season in Italy and has rarely played league matches for AC Milan.
During his four-year stay in Italy, Savicevic often was the key
figure in AC Milan's success.
	   Aside from reserve goalkeeper Dragoje Lekovic and Stojkovic,
Savicevic is the only Yugoslav player with World Cup experience as
he led the team to the quarterfinals at the 1990 championships in
Italy.
	   On Tuesday when the Yugoslavs arrived in France, Savicevic only
did light warmup exercises on the edge of the pitch while the rest
of the squad practiced full force. On Wednesday, Savicevic failed
to show up at the rain-soaked training grounds in this picturesque
village just outside Saint Etienne.
	   ``I didn't want to expose him to any risks on the slippery
surface,'' said Yugoslav coach Slobodan Santrac. ``But I hope to
have him ready soon. We are not playing only one match at the World
Cup and there will be several chances for Savicevic to show his
skills.''
	   ``I don't feel fully fit and I'll have to be patient and work
real hard in training to get back to full fitness,'' a grim-faced
Savicevic said as he watched his teammates' training practice
Wednesday.
	   Dejan Stankovic, the 19-year-old rising star who this summer
signed a multi-million-dollar contract with Lazio Rome, is likely
to take Savicevic's place in the midfield against Iran on June 14.
	   (ds-sl)
</TEXT>
