WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A 12-member delegation of Bangladesh Chamber of Industries
yesterday called on President Justice Shahabuddin Ahmed, and urged
him to initiate dialogue with the political parties with a view to
building up national consensus for the economic development,
reports BSS.
	   Led by the President of the BCI, Sharif M Afzal Hossain the
delegation yesterday met Shahabuddin Ahmed at Bangabhaban here, and
exchanged views on various issues including industrialisation.
	   Hossain said, law and order situation is the precondition of
economic development. He emphasised the heed of infrastructure
development, increase of electricity and gas facilities, protection
of industry, stopping of illegal activities in the name of trade
union and removal of bureaucratic complications.
	   Full globalisation will start after 2005 and to face this
challenge of global economy, rapid industrialisation is a must in
the country, he observed.
	   BCI president said, the image abroad of Bangladesh at present is
bright and is known as the proper place of investment. The foreign
investors are coming to Bangladesh and the financial structure of
the country is enriched by natural and mineral resources, and these
opportunities must be utilised, he added.
	   
