<HEADLINE>
Suspected rebels kill 10 policemen and two civilians in southern
</HEADLINE>
India &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ Suspected guerrillas triggered a land
mine that blew up a jeep, killing 10 policemen and two civilians in
southern India on Wednesday, United News of India news agency said.
	   No one immediately claimed responsibility for the attack in
Warangal district of Andhra Pradesh state, 1,375 kilometers (860
miles) south of New Delhi. Police blamed the banned Peoples' War
Group.
	   The PWG, which did not immediately respond to the allegation,
frequently targets police and government officials, claiming they
connive with rich land owners to oppress poor, low-caste farm
hands.
	   The Marxist group has been fighting since 1980. The violence has
left more than 4,000 people dead. 	   
