<BODY>
<SLUG> JS-BUDGET-SESSION sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JS budget session begins today, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
JS budget session begins today, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Abu Musa HasanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The budget session of Jatiya Sangsad begins today amidst a
political stand off between the ruling party and the opposition BNP
aggravated by the long march programme.
	   It will be the third budget session of the Seventh Parliament.
According to the decision of the Business Advisory Committee of the
Sangsad, Finance Minister SAMS Kibria will place the national
budget for the fiscal year 1998-99 before the House at 3 pm
tomorrow. The budget speech of the Minister will be telecast and
broadcast live from Parliament.
	   In view of the long march, all the MPs belonging to the BNP and
the Jamaat-e-Islami, who are now on way to the CHT, will not attend
the first day's session of the house even through they had earlier
announced that they would join the budget session.
	   Meanwhile, a meeting of the Business Advisory Committee, last
evening fixed the agenda of the current session. According to
sources, the meeting resolved to complete the business of the
budget session by July 10. It also decided to hold a total of 40
hours general discussions on the supplementary budget of the
current fiscal year and the proposed budget of the fiscal 1989-90.
	   The meeting, chaired by Speaker Humayun Rasheed Chowdhury, was
attended by its members, Leader of the House Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina, Deputy Leader of the House LGRD Minister Zillur Rahman,
Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad, Commerce and Industries Minister
Tofail Ahmed, Deputy Speaker Abdul Hamid Advocate, Chief Whip of
the House Abul Hasnat Abdullah and Advocate Rahmat Ali, MP of the
Awami League. Leader of the Jatiya Party's Parliamentary Party HM
Ershad was represented in the meeting by Advocate Fazle Rabbi, MP,
while the Finance Minister SAMS Kibria and Whip Vice Principal
Abdus Shahid attended the meeting being invited by the Speaker.
	   The BNP and Jamaat members of the committee did not take part in
the meeting.
	   Ruling party sources said that the Business Advisory Committee
might meet again with the participation of the BNP members to
review its decision. ``We are prepared to accommodate the proposals
of the BNP to make the budget session a meaningful one,'' said a
leader of the ruling party.
	   According to the sources, yesterday's meeting of the Business
Advisory Committee resolved that the current session would continue
till July 10. It has also decided to hold general discussion on the
supplementary budget for the current fiscal year and the national
budget for the fiscal 1989-90 for 40 hours.
	   The sources said that the supplementary budget would be passed
after holding discussion for maximum three days beginning from June
14. The new budget will be adopted in the Sangsad by June 30.
	   According to the decision of the Business Advisory Committee,
the house would meet at 2 pm every day except on Friday. The
questions and answers will be tabled and the weekly private members
day on Thursday will remain suspended till June 30 to facilitate
the completion of 40-hour general discussion and approval of the
national budget according to the decision of the committee, meeting
sources said.
	   The current session will also consider some bills after adopting
the budget by June 30. Among others, the Code of Civil Procedure
Amendment Bill, which is now pending before the Standing Committee
on the Law, Justice and Parliamentary Affairs Ministry, may come up
for the consideration of the House. The Parliament Secretariat has
also received notice of another bill titled 'Bangabandhu
Agricultural University Bill, 1998'.
	   The sources said the meeting decided that from now on after
completion of the day's business as per the order of the day,
opposition members will be allowed to raise unscheduled issues of
public importance in Parliament for 15 minutes and the treasury
bench members would also be allowed 15 minutes to reply to queries
on those issues.
	   This 30-minute business will be in addition to the usual call
attention notices as per rule 71 of the Rules of Procedure of
Parliament. The decision was taken at the meeting as per the
proposal of the Speaker.
	   The sources said that the Speaker made the proposal in
accordance with the practice of the House of Commons. Earlier the
Speaker narrated his experience during his recent visit to the
United Kingdom. He said that he had exchanged views with the
Speaker of the House of Commons on various issues.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
