<SLUG> BC-Greece-Explosives </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police investigating theft of chemical explosives
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ Police on Wednesday were investigating the
disappearance of nearly half a ton of chemicals they reportedly
fear could be used by terrorists to make bombs.
	   The disappearance, which could be the result of a bureaucratic
mistake, came shortly after security forces were put on a state of
alert because of a surge in urban terrorism.
	   More than 150 offices and cars have been firebombed since
January. Most attacks, none of which caused any injuries, were
claimed by shadowy, left-wing groups.
	   According to local media reports, 425 kilograms (935 pounds) of
an ammonia-based chemical went missing Tuesday from a mining
company in Larimna, 70 kilometers (43 miles) northwest of Athens.
	   It could be used used to produce a significant number of bombs,
local media quoted police as saying.
	   November 17, one of the world's deadliest militant groups, has
in the past used bombs to target American officials and companies.
They have killed 22 people since their 1975 assassination of the
CIA station chief in Athens.
	   In 1989, November 17 stole dozens of anti-tank rockets from a
military depot. The rockets have been used in several attacks,
including a failed attempt against the U.S. embassy in Athens.
