<SLUG> NEED-FOR-CREATING sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Need for creating public awareness of road safety stressed, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Need for creating public awareness of road safety stressed, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A British transport expert has stressed the need for creating
public awareness of road safety to reduce road accidents in
Bangladesh.
	   Both the print and electronic media could make the people aware
of road safety, said Allan Quimby of Transport Research Laboratory
in the United Kingdom at a seminar in the city yesterday.
	   The seminar on ``Road Safety Publication'' was held at the
secretariat of National Road Safety Council of Bangladesh (NRSC).
Some 30 experts on road safety including Chairman of Bangladesh
Road Transport Authority AN Hussain and NRSC Secretariat
Coordinator Patrick Gleeson attended the seminar.
	   Quimby said that road accident is one of the biggest problems in
Bangladesh in the world the situation was deteriorating at a
frightening rate. Publicity in a systemic and scientific manner
could improve the situation, he added.
	   He suggested that documentaries be aired by television centres
and special articles be published in newspapers to create public
awareness of road safety.
	   About 3,000 people were killed in road accidents in the country
last year, according to the seminar sources. The seminer reveled
that the safety problem in Bangladesh is almost double compared to
that in Pakistan and India and 20 times worst than the USA and UK.
	   
</TEXT>
