<HEADLINE>
WFP urged to continue assistance, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
WFP urged to continue assistance, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad yesterday urged World Food
Programme (WFP) to continue its assistance for the poor people,
particularly the distressed women.
	   ``The less privileged sections of society particularly the poor
and the distressed women usually receive maximum benefit from food
aid, and hence Azad it should be increased told the WFP country
representative.
	   Werner Kiene, the WFP Representative in Bangladesh, yesterday
called on the Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad at the latter's
office, an official handout said.
	   Kiene who gave a resume of WFP activities in Bangladesh, said
efforts are underway to raise the UN body's cooperation programme
in the country by extending further assistance to the poor and the
needy in Chittagong Hill Tracts.
	   The World Food Programme annually gives around three lakh tons
of food aid to Bangladesh which is valued at Taka 270 crore, the
handout added.
	   The food aid is used in rural development and improvement of the
condition of distressed women and spent through government and
NGOs.
	   Azad requested the country representative to further extend its
activities in aid of rural development and distressed women.
	   
</TEXT>
