<BODY>
<SLUG> HERO-LOST-IN-STORM sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hero lost in storm rescue, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Hero lost in storm rescue, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Antoine So and Cheung Chi-faiASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A RESCUE hero was missing feared drowned last night after
leaping into a flooded nullah to save two young brothers.
	   The search for father-of-two Lee Ying-kwong, 51, was abandoned
last night because of darkness and atrocious weather.
	   Mr Lee pulled one of the boys, Sze Kin-keung, 9, to safety from
the Quarry Bay torrent.
	   But he was swept away when he went back for the other, Sze
Kin-man, 12, who was later pulled unconscious from the water.
	   The tragedy came on a day of chaos in which torrential rain
brought floods and landslides across the urban areas and the New
Territories, closed courts and schools and swamped homes and
businesses.
	   The red and black rainstorm signals were hoisted for 16 hours _
the longest since the warnings were introduced after another tragic
downpour in 1992.
	   In many areas, the total rainfall exceeded 300mm for the 24
hours to midnight. It was heaviest in Mong Kok, Tai Po and Sai Kung
from 4am to 8am, with more than 500mm recorded in Sai Kung _ site
of numerous landslides and flash floods.
	   As shopowners and householders mopped up, firemen called off
their four-hour hunt for Quarry Bay victim Mr Lee, a recent
mainland migrant, about 8.30pm.
	   Mr Lee's wife, Yip Bo-heung, 44, wept as she came to terms with
the fact that he was dead.
	   ``They did not find my husband,'' she said. ``I am prepared that
he is killed. I have to face up to the reality.'' Sze Kin-man was
in critical condition in Pamela Youde Nethersole Eastern Hospital
last night after being winched from the nullah not breathing and
with no pulse. His pulse returned in hospital.
	   Kin-Keung suffered only bruises and was in stable condition.
	   The drama began about 4.30pm when Kin-man, Kin-keung and a
friend defied the rain to hike up Kam Tuk Chi Ma Path on Mount
Parker.
	   Minutes later, Kin-keung tried to leap across the 1.5 metre-wide
nullah and plunged in. While his friend Ng Siu-pang, 12, dashed to
call police, Kin-man dived into the torrent after his brother.
	   Both were swept more than 12 metres before being caught in
grating at the mouth of a culvert.
	   Hearing their cries for help, Mr Lee climbed down handrails on
the wall of the nullah and carried Kin-keung to safety.
	   He went back for Kin-man, but the raging water tore his grip
from the grating and he was swept away, as shocked witnesses
watched.
	   ``I saw a man climb down into the nullah,'' one said. ``Soon he
picked up a boy but then he went down again.'' Firemen, summoned by
the friend, arrived to find Kin-man pinned to the grating by the
flood and no sign of Mr Lee.
	   After initial attempts were foiled by the current, they cut
through a safety fence on the bank and two divers abseiled down the
nullah wall to reach the unconscious boy.
	   While the boys were taken to hospital, the search for Mr Lee
began.
	   Rescuers searched the nullah and its outlets in Quarry Bay
Street, Finnie Street and at the waterfront at Hoi Yu Street.
	   Mr Lee, a plumber, was working on a freelance project in Mount
Parker Lodge. He lived with his wife and 11-month-old baby in Lek
Yuen Estate in Sha Tin. Anolder child is in Xinhui.
	   The Sze brothers are also mainland migrants, living in Sunway
Gardens.
	   Plumber repaid debt with his lifeTHE grief-stricken wife of
plumber Lee Ying-kwong, feared drown while trying to rescue two
boys from a Quarry Bay nullah, said she was not surprised by her
husband's heroism.
	   A tearful Yip Bo-heung, 44, said that two years ago, her husband
almost drowned but was saved by a man.
	   ``That left a very deep impression on him. Perhaps because of
this, he wanted to repay (the act) by saving the two boys,'' she
said.
	   Mr Lee had loved swimming since he was a teenager, she said.
	   The couple were married in Xinhui, Guangdong, in 1979.
	   Their eldest son Kwok-hung, now 18, was born there.
	   Mr Lee came to Hong Kong after the birth of Kwok-hung.
	   Three years ago, Ms Yip was permitted to join him.
	   The plumber had always worked hard for the family, making about
$10,000 a month as a part-timer, she said.
	   The couple have a second son, Kwok-fai, now 11 months.
	   The family lives in a public-housing flat in Lek Yuen Estate in
Sha Tin.
	   ``He loves his sons. He loves helping people. This is him,'' Ms
Yip said.
	   She said she wanted the Immigration Department to exercise its
discretion to allow Kwok-hung to see his father's face for the last
time.
	   ``That will be the last time he could see his father's face. I
plead with the government to fulfil this wish,'' Ms Yip said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
