<BODY>
<SLUG> ARMY-DEPLOYED-AT-POWER sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Army deployed at power stations, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Army deployed at power stations, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Members of the armed forces have been deployed at important
power installations and grid sub-stations of the country to avert
any untoward incidents that might occur during the month-long World
Cup football tournament that starts in Paris from today.
	   Two Russian engineers who arrived in capital last Sunday
completed repairs of the Unit 3 of the Ghorashal Power Plant
yesterday, a Power Development Board (PDB) official told The
Independent.
	   On completion of the repairing, the PDB has decided to make the
unit generate 210 mw electricity from today to meet the power
shortage in the country.
	   Petrobangla authorities have assured the PDB officials of
supplying gas as per their requirement to generate electricity.
	   The ministry concerned, the Dhaka Electricity Supply Authority
(DESA) and the PDB in the meantime, have also taken a good number
of steps including forming of 16 high-powered task forces to ensure
a loadshedding free, undisrupted power supply in Dhaka and the rest
of the country during the World Cup football.
	   The steps taken by the agencies concerned on the eve of world
football were decreasing systems loss, snapping of illegal
connections, and closing of all shops and markets in the evenings.
The power supply people felt that 200 megawatts of electricity
could be saved through such steps throughout the country.
	   The task forces to be supervised by Executive Engineers and
Superintendent Engineers and special squads formed in this
connection would help maintain and look after electric lines during
the World Cup so that they could meet the emergency needs.
	   The officials of DESA and PDB apprehend that some sort of
sabotage or other destructive activities might take place at
different installations or power grid sub-stations following
possible loadshedding or shortage of supply of power.
	   Considering the security of these important installations and
sub-grid stations, the DESA and PDB authorities have taken some
precautionary measures. They, in the meantime, have deployed law
enforcing people and their own securitymen at these installations.
In some places, members of the armed forces were deployed, PDB
sources said adding that the number of the armed forces personnel
and Bangladesh Rifles (BDR) would be increased to guard the power
sub-stations especially during the world cup football.
	   In the meantime, news of disruption of power supply as well as
loadshedding at different places including the capital city and
district headquarters continued to be reported.
	   The people of the affected areas gheraoed the power supply
offices at different places of the country demanding normal supply
of power immediately.
	   The power disruption and loadshedding agitated the people in
Netrakona, Gopalganj, Manikganj, Pabna, Brahmanbaria, Sherpur,
Sylhet, Hobiganj, Chittagong, Khulna, Jessore for which they
brought out processions.
	   The frequent power failure in 10 thanas in Netrokona forced the
people to gherao the PDB office to demand smooth supply of power
during the world cup football.
	   Superintendent Engineer and Executive Engineer of Mymensingh
power supply office yesterday visited Netrokona and met the Deputy
Commissioner (DC) and Superintendent of Police (SP) and requested
that the security of PDB officials he ensured, our Netrokona
correspondent said.
	   Our correspondents from different district headquarters and
thanas said that the PDB officials were passing their days in great
anxiety following the frequent disruption of power and
loadshedding. In many cases, they demanded security fearing
possible attacks by angry people, especially during the World Cup
football.
	   Our Barisal Correspondent adds: angry power consumers attacked
the power sub- station at Rupali, Banaripara, Daulat Khan,
Borhanuddin, Swarupkhati, Betagi and Bakergani police stations
following disruption of power and load shedding Monday night.
	   At least 15 persons were injured when the angry people attacked
the Thana Nirbahi Officer's (TNO) residence at Betagi after the
power disruption. Police arrested 8 persons in connection with the
attack on the TNO's residence. The correspondent also added that
power supplies Patharghata and Borgona have remained suspended for
the past 13 and 2 days respectively. Due to shortage of power, the
Barisal Pourasava authorities only supplied 10 lakh gallons of
water against the 90 lakh gallons required by the people.
	   Our Thakurgaon Correspondent said that the office of the
Resident Engineer at Thakurgaon was attacked by angry youths of the
locality following a power disruption for about 16 hours. The
youths from Hajipara brought out a procession and ransacked the PDB
office at 10 yesterday night.
	   The PDB officials filed a case against the youths following the
incident.
	   A total of 1000 rice mills were closed down following the
loadshedding and power failure for which the price of rice went up
causing suffering to the people.
	   UNB from Mymensingh adds: Power supply in five districts under
greater Mymensingh remained cut off for about four hours due to
technical fault in the 33-KV sub-station line near Bhairab on
Tuesday.
	   According to officials, power supply to Jamalpur, Sherpur
Netrokona, Kishoreganj and Mymensingh districts was suspended from
the Ashuganj Power Plant after the fault was detected in the line.
	   They said the power supply to the region was restored at about 6
pm yesterday.
	   Our Rajshahi Correspondent says: Local people of Gomastapur
thana on Monday night attacked the local power supply centre
demanding smooth supply of electricity. The mob also damaged the
furniture at the centre to protect the disruption.
	   APB from Jamalpur adds: In rowdy protests against continuous
loadshedding for long hours, subscribers stormed and ransacked the
Power Development Board offices in three thanas of the district
yesterday.
	   The angry protesters also blocked rail and road traffic,
officials said.
	   They put barricades at the Nandina Bazar Railway Station and on
Jamalpur-Mymensingh highway in the morning in protest against
power-supply disruption in these hot summer days.
	   PDB Resident Engineer Mojammel Haque said that supply of power
in greater Jamalpur district had drooped to 4-5 megawatt over the
past three days as against daily requirement of, 22 MW.
	   The angry people launched separate attacks on PDB offices in
Sadar, Sarishabari and Melandah thanas as power supply shrank to 3
MW on Tuesday, he said.
	   Some of the places faced outages for 10-12 hours on Tuesday due
to the abnormal shortages.
	   In sadar thana, some trains, including Jamalpur-bound Padma and
Dinajpur-bound Teesta, were halted for four hours at Nandina Bazar
station with a rail-blockade enforced at about 10 am.
	   About a hundred vehicles remained stranded on the
Dhaka-Mymensingh highway for three hours due to the barricade.
	   
</TEXT>
