w1037 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  HK-RECORD-DOWNPOURsked     06-10 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> HK-RECORD-DOWNPOUR sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HK grinds to a halt in record downpour, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
HK grinds to a halt in record downpour, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE downpour yesterday broke records as it wrought havoc and
brought Hong Kong to a standstill.
	   It brought the first black rainstorm warning of the year, a new
record for the daily rainfall in June, and the longest hoisting on
record of the red and black warnings.
	   During the more than 16 hours from the hoisting of the red
signal at 4.40 am until it was lowered at 9 pm _ the longest since
the system was introduced in 1992 _ schools and courts were closed,
businesses were swamped, hillsides collapsed and roads were
inundated.
	   The downpour, brought by a trough of low pressure along the
South China coast, is expected to continue for the next three days.
	   The red rainstorm warning was upgraded to black at 6.35 am.
	   It was downgraded to red at 9.50 am.
	   As of 11 o'clock last night, 410.4 millimetres of rain has been
recorded, setting a new daily rainfall record for the month since
12 June 1966.
	   ``It's (also) the longest rainstorm warning episode since the
rainstorm warning was introduced in 1992,'' Lai Sau-tak of the Hong
Kong Observatory said.
	   The thunderstorm warning was in force since late Monday night
until 10.40 pm yesterday while the landslip warning, raised at 4.52
am, was still in force early today.
	   The worst-hit area was northern New Territories where flood
water was as deep as 1.5 metres in some locations.
	   Twenty people were injured, including 14 seamen involved in a
collision of two cargo ships off Victoria Harbour, two being hit by
falling objects on Hong Kong Island and four others suffering from
flood-related injuries.
	   A family of four in Siu Lam village was rescued from their home
by Fire Services officers in dinghies when flash floods swamped the
village at 4 am.
	   Two other families, including four adults and one child, were
stranded in Tin Ping Shan village, Sheung Shui about 10 am, and
were also rescued by firefighters in dinghies.
	   Scores of vehicles broke down and had to be towed or pushed away
on flooded roads. At least 20 bus routes were diverted.
	   A total of 74 reports of flooding and 42 cases of landslip were
made.
	   At Kai Tak, 10 flights were delayed. Judges and lawyers today
face a hectic day catching up on a backlog of cases following
yesterday's blanket court closure.
	   The Education Department cancelled classes.
	   The Stock Exchange and the Futures Exchange closed their morning
sessions.
	   A Sheung Shui housewife said she and her husband had been
putting off having a second child because of the flooding.
	   Stalled vehicles add to chaos on the streets FLOODS caused
traffic chaos throughout Hong Kong despite fewer vehicles on the
roads yesterday.
	   Vehicles on the Tuen Mun Highway were stationary for almost the
whole morning because of flooding in Tsuen Wan.
	   In Sai Kung, mud was flushed onto Hiram's Highway, which links
Sai Kung and Kowloon, and vehicles had to slow down.
	   Nathan Road, usually jammed at peak hours, was a scene of
confusion, with broken-down cars and taxis in the rising
floodwaters.
	   Police were kept busy helping move these vehicles to the
roadsides.
	   Double-deckers were still able to negotiate the waters but
getting on or off the buses posed a problem for passengers.
	   Since the buses could not get close to the stops, passengers had
to wade into the flooded road.
	   A Kowloon Motor Bus spokeswoman said buses were running 20 to 40
minutes behind schedule.
	   Services were back to normal in the afternoon when the waters in
Mong Kok subsided.
	   On the island, Peak Tram services were suspended from about 1pm.
	   A spokeswoman said it was not known when services would resume
as the rain had affected work being carried out by the Civil
Engineering Department.
	   MTR and KCR services were not affected. But crowds did not
appear until about 10 am when the observatory lowered the black
rainstorm warning to the red one.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
