<BODY>
<SLUG> POWER-CRISIS-MAY-EASE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Power crisis may ease after mid-August, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Power crisis may ease after mid-August, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Sharif ShahabuddinASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The government might set up 10 to 50 MW-capacity skid-mounted
and trolley-mounted plants for quick generation of electricity to
combat the worsening power situation, sources said.
	   ``The government may use the Army's purchase system to procure
the plants within the shortest possible time.''
	   An official of the Power cell said on condition of anonymity
that the country was passing through a crucial phase due to the
electricity crisis and that some quarters were trying to achieve
their selfish ends by exploiting the situation. He said that the
government was trying to solve the crisis as early as possible but
that the situation was too difficult to overcome. He, however, said
that there were yet possibilities of a good result.
	   According to the Power Development Board (PDB), the government
has decided to increase power generation by up to 722 MW by
September 1998.
	   Prof Rafiqul Islam, State Minister for Power, Energy and Mineral
Resources told The Independent that by August 31 some 522 MW of
electricity would be generated from different power stations in the
country through utilising their utmost generation capacity and that
two barge-mounted plants would add 200 MW in September contributing
to the total increase of 722 MW.
	   ``We have taken it as a challenge, and we will succeed in
mitigating the sufferings of the people,'' the minister said
expressing his optimism. He added that the Prime Minister herself
had taken charge and was trying her best to tackle the situation.
	   ``We have a long tradition of pursuing a pro-people politics
initiated by the Father of the Nation Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur
Rahman and we have made a commitment to the people that we will put
in our best efforts in this regard,'' the minister said.
	   It was shown earlier that the average demand of electricity was
2290 MW and the estimated production 1700 MW. But official sources
said that the demand usually increased 10 per cent in each
successive year. And with the increase of 10 per cent the actual
demand stood at approximately 2500 MW. The government therefore has
to think of generating 2500 MW, the minister said.
	   With a view to meeting the growing demand, the government is
quickening negotiations for the 360 MW Haripur power project and
450 MW Meghnaghat Power project.
	   Negotiations were going on with the AES Corporation of the USA
while the Energy Ministry approved the Meghnaghat project last
week. Within a couple of weeks the signing of the deal would be
held between the PDB and AES, ministry sources said.
	   It is learnt from a reliable source that the site preparation of
the Meghnaghat plant has become difficult for unknown reasons. The
PDB source said that a sort of confusion was created in the process
of negotiating the international tender for the site preparation of
the Meghnaghat plant and that the PM's office had ordered an
investigation in this regard. The source said that if it was not
resolved in due time the main project would be hindered and the AES
would demand compensation as per the terms and conditions.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
