<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-Economy, 1st ld-Writethru,0540 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Silver lining to Pakistan's economic woes: Finance Secretary
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with annual economic survey. EDITS to conform. No
pickup &QL; 
 &UR; By KATHY GANNON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ Although the stock market is down,
the latest credit rating is poor and foreign currency accounts have
been frozen to prevent a panic exodus of U.S. dollars, there may be
a silver lining, Finance Secretary Moeen Afzal said Wednesday.
	   Pakistan may use this economic emergency to make some
fundamental changes to its economic policies, Afzal said.
	   Also Wednesday, Pakistan released its annual economic survey
which showed a healthy growth in the agricultural sector, a modest
increase in the manufacturing sector and annual per capita income
rose five dollars to dlrs 457 in 1997-98.
	   The figures, however, were compiled before foreign currency
accounts were frozen last month after Pakistan tested six nuclear
devices. The explosions were in response to its traditionally
hostile neighbor India, which conducted five nuclear tests.
	   Pakistan expected to be hit with severe economic sanctions as a
result of the testing, which it feared would spark a run on foreign
currency. Pakistan's foreign exchange reserves were at dlrs 1.3
billion, barely enough to pay six weeks of imports.
	   Afzal said changes may include taxing foreign currency accounts,
thus denying rich Pakistanis a tax shelter. Currently, the wealthy
in Pakistan can keep millions of dollars in foreign currency
accounts without having to pay taxes or explain the origins of the
money.
	   Monetary liberalization in Pakistan is barely seven years old.
When Pakistan encouraged foreign exchange accounts, Afzal said it
opened the door wide, promising not to ask the origins of the
money. Critics said that allowed people with black market or drug
money to legally launder it.
	   Afzal said the government wants to correct this, tighten up
regulations and have people pay taxes.
	   The government also wants to push forward with banking reforms
aimed at putting an end to loans with little or no collateral. It
also wants to collect millions of dollars in unpaid loans and widen
its tax net.
	   Barely 1 million people pay taxes in Pakistan and most of them
are small businessmen and professionals. Some of the elite,
including politicians, barely pay dlrs 100 in income tax.
	   It is expected that Pakistan's budget, which is being released
Friday, will be loaded with new tax measures.
	   According to the economic survey, the government hoped to raise
dlrs 7 billion in taxes in 1997-98, but that estimate was later
revised to dlrs 6.4 billion. Even then, the government only raised
dlrs 4.8 billion, 75.6 percent of the target.
	   The deficit is expected to be down to 5.4 percent, slightly over
the target of 5 percent. Inflation should drop to 8.5 percent down
from 10 percent.
	   Since India detonated its first series of nuclear devices on May
11, the Karachi Stock Exchange began a free fall, which has brought
it to a record low of 998 points. Standard and Poor's downgraded
Pakistan on June 1 to a single-B-minus from a single B-Plus and put
Pakistan on a creditwatch.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Pakistan-Economy, 1st ld-Writethru; CT:f; 
