	   Classes of BUET will resume June 14, after an unscheduled
closure of more than two months caused by wrangling between
government and teachers.
	   A meeting of the Dean Committee yesterday decided to resume the
classes after the ``deadlock'' ended on Monday.
	   It also announced a revised academic programme of the university
and instructed all students to attend the classes timely, said a
BUET press release.
	   The impasse ended on Monday as the BUET Teachers' Association
suspended its strike following an appeal of Vice Chancellor Iqbal
Mahmud.
	   The trouble started on April 4 following a mass resignation 71
teachers of the university from their administrative posts,
including the VC, to protest what they called government's undue
interference in the university's internal affairs.
	   
