<BODY>
<SLUG> SHOPKEEPERS-RESIGNED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Shopkeepers resigned to wet fate, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Shopkeepers resigned to wet fate, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A SOGGY sense of deja vu hung over Nathan Road yesterday.
	   As shopkeepers along the flood-prone Prince Edward section
mopped up yet again, they did so knowing they would have to do it
again . . . and again . . . until a big drainage project is
completed in about four years.
	   ``I expected this scenario last night,'' said Liu Kam-chiu,
whose cafeteria was flooded knee-deep.
	   ``We moved everything to the table tops so as to minimise the
loss.'' Despite the precautions, he estimated his loss at $10,000
to $20,000.
	   ``Every time after the flood, I have to call an electrician to
check all the switches and the stove,'' he said.
	   Mr Liu said yesterday's flood was not the worst he had seen.
	   ``The Drainage Services and the Urban Services Departments came
quickly and the water was gone within an hour.'' At a bakery near
Mr Liu's shop, the staff had erected an iron plate about 1.5 metres
high in the front door the night before, which kept the worst of
the water out.
	   Nonetheless, it took an hour to clean up after the flood, and
business was about $10,000 less than usual.
	   While the clean-up went on, customers stood outside to give
their orders, which staff handed out to them.
	   In a nearby boutique, two saleswomen spent most of the morning
cleaning up.
	   One said they had learnt from past experience and had covered
everything with plastic bags before sealing the door.
	   Workers from the Drainage Services Department and Urban Services
Department were sent to flooding blackspots in Kowloon West.
	   A Works Bureau spokeswoman said improvements to the drainage
system in Kowloon West would be completed in 2002, when the problem
should be solved.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
