<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq-Weapons Butler </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iraq, U.N. gearing for row on weapons again
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By LEON BARKHO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ The tug-of-war between Iraq and the United
Nations over disarmament may trigger a fresh crisis in the Gulf if
Baghdad continues to insist it has no more information on illegal
weapons.
	   Chief U.N. weapons inspector Richard Butler arrives in Baghdad
Thursday, armed with satellite images, charts and material evidence
to back his position that Iraq is still hiding weapons in secret
depots.
	   Butler will carry a three-page list of what he says are Iraq's
unfulfilled obligations to complete the elimination of its illegal
weapons.
	   Until Butler certifies that Iraq has dismantled all its weapons
of mass destruction, Iraq won't be free of the U.N. economic
sanctions imposed after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
	   A glance at Butler's register shows that Iraq still has a long
way to go before obtaining a clean bill of health. For instance,
the list asks Iraq to provide ``full disclosure'' of its
destruction of missile propellants and to account for its
mustard-gas artillery shells and bombs used for chemical and
biological weapons.
	   In his meetings with Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz, Butler is
likely to try to prove that Iraq has not yet come clean in the
areas of long-range missiles, chemical weapons and biological
weapons.
	   The mass of evidence that Butler presented earlier this month at
the United Nations swung a number of skeptical Security Council
members to his side. But the Iraqi team, led by Foreign Minister
Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf, remained adamant that Iraq has done all
it could to dismantle its weapons.
	   Sticking to that position could lead to another standoff. The
alternative would be to accept Butler's demands, which would show
that Iraq had lied when it said it had nothing more to declare.
	   Butler's latest mission to Baghdad is similar to the trip he
made early this year when he failed to persuade the Iraqis to open
presidential sites for inspection.
	   That row led to the United States and Britain amassing forces in
the Gulf for a possible strike against Iraq. War was averted by the
last-minute intervention of U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan who
persuaded Iraqi leaders to open the palaces.
 &UR; lb-vj/jbm-lm 	   
</TEXT>
