<HEADLINE>
Iran to cut oil production by 100,000 barrels per day
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with output cut announcement, quote. CHANGES overline.
No pickup &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ Iran announced Wednesday that it will cut
its oil output by 100,000 barrels per day, joining other countries
in an effort to boost global prices.
	   The announcement, which takes effect July 1, was made by the Oil
Ministry following a meeting between visiting Saudi Oil Minister
Ali al-Naimi and his Iranian counterpart, Bijan Namdar Zangeneh.
	   ``Iran undertakes to trim output by 100,000 barrels per day as
of July 1, in addition to the 140,000 barrels per day cut
previously agreed upon,'' the official Islamic Republic News Agency
quoted an oil ministry statement as saying.
	   Saudi Arabia has been lobbying several countries to cut oil
production in an attempt to increase sagging prices that have
hovered around dlrs 14 a barrel, some 20 percent lower than last
year despite cuts in daily global production by 1.5 million barrels
a day.
	   Al-Naimi, who arrived Tuesday in Tehran, briefed Zangeneh on the
recent accord between Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and Mexico to cut
back 450,000 barrels a day from the market, Iran's state-run Tehran
radio reported.
	   Iran's new cut will be in addition to the 140,000 barrels a day
production cut it pledged to make in March. Iran said that
reduction should be made in its daily quota of 3.94 million barrels
rather than its actual production level, which fluctuates but is
considerably lower than the quota.
	   Iran, the second-largest exporter in the 11-nation Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries, had reportedly been exceeding the
pledged cuts.
	   Al-Naimi earlier visited Kuwait, United Arab Emirates and Qatar
and non-OPEC producer, Oman.
	   He secured a pledge from Qatar to cut 20,000 barrels per day
starting July 1. 	   
</TEXT>
