<SLUG> FLOOD-HIT-VILLAGERS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Flood-hit villagers plead for housing, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Flood-hit villagers plead for housing, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Martin WongASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   VILLAGE residents hit by flood waters yesterday expressed hope
that the Home Affairs Department's pledge to move them into public
housing will come soon.
	   ``The government should give us special consideration because of
our situation,'' said Mrs Ng, 40.
	   Mrs Ng, her husband and their two children, Pak-chiu, 9, and
Hiu-ki, 16, have lived in a tin hut in Kwan Tei, Sheung Shui for
more than 10 years. The hut stands in one of the areas worst hit by
the rain.
	   Yesterday was the second time in three weeks that the family had
been forced to spend the night at a temporary shelter in Sheung
Shui, after their hut was flooded again.
	   Mrs Ng said the family had not been able to clean up the mess
caused by the flood on 24 May, the day of the elections.
	   ``But now that my home has been hit again, I will have to buy
many new electrical appliances to replace what was in the hut,''
she said.
	   Mrs Ng said all she and other residents of Kwan Tei, affected by
heavy rain, wanted was to be allowed to live in public housing.
	   ``Mrs Shelley Lau Lee Lai-kuen (Director of the Home Affairs
Department) visited us earlier today and she told me that she would
offer us public housing soon. I do hope it is for real.
	   ``Of course we want to move out but the rents outside are too
expensive,'' Mrs Ng said.
	   Her husband is a vegetable hawker and the rent that the family
pays now is just $1,000.
	   She said she stays awake whenever it rains hard so she can can
sound the alarm if necessary.
	   But not so for young Pak-chiu, he thinks being flooded out makes
for a great adventure. ``I think it's lots of fun and I can tell
you that I have practiced the evacuation more than a million
times.''
	   
</TEXT>
