<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Africa-Briefs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
contents in Zimbabwe item may be offensive to some readers
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Ghana, South Africa, Benin, Zimbabwe;
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ------
	   DAR ES SALAAM, Tanzania (AP) _ Tanzania threatened Wednesday to
deploy more troops to the Biharamulo region on its western border
with Burundi, where Tanzanian citizens are fleeing alleged attacks
by Burundian refugees.
	   ``We shall dispatch the paramilitary force to conduct special
operations'' there, the independent daily Guardian quoted Home
Affairs Minister Ali Ameir Mohammed as saying.
	   Nearly 500 Tanzanians are reported to have fled from Burundian
Hutu refugees living in camps in Biharamulo district and the Kagera
region.
	   Mohamed said he had already directed the police in Kagera region
to arrest all armed Burundian refugees pending the arrival of the
paramilitary force.
	   There are 109,000 Burundian refugees in camps in western
Tanzania. The U.N. refugee agency has pledged to assist Tanzania to
improve security within and outside the camps.
	   Tanzania has long denied claims by Burundi's Tutsi-led
government that Hutu rebels live in the refugee camps and attack
Burundi across the border.
	   -----
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) _ After finding two men not guilty
of murder, a court on Wednesday sentenced them to jail for robbing
British immigrant Stuart Gaskell, who was killed during a robbery
in February.
	   Morne Bosch received a 10-year sentence while Winston Blaauw
received a six-year term.
	   Both men were on Tuesday found not guilty of the murder charges.
	   A third suspect, Quintin Marinus, was cleared of all charges.
	   Charges against a fourth suspect, Hilton Scott, were dropped
last month because he was shot in the head and suffered severe
memory loss.
	   Cape High Court Judge Pat Tebbutt said there was grave suspicion
about Bosch's guilt on the murder charge, but suspicion was
insufficient to convict him of murder.
	   ------
	   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) _ Former President Canaan Banana lured a
young unemployed man to have homosexual intercourse with him on the
promise of finding him a job, the High Court heard.
	   Ernest Ngwenya, a state witness, alleged on Tuesday that Banana
gave him money and arranged later meetings for sex at a hotel in
the second city of Bulawayo and his Harare home.
	   Banana, 62, an ordained Methodist minister who served as
figurehead president after independence in 1980 until 1987, faces
11 charges of sodomy and homosexual assault.
	   He has pleaded innocent to charges that carry a penalty of a
fine or imprisonment.
	   Eleven people allege Banana made unwanted sexual advances toward
them, some saying he abused his power in office to coerce them and
force them to remain silent.
	   Homosexual acts are illegal in Zimbabwe, where President Robert
Mugabe has waged an outspoken campaign against gay rights,
describing same-sex partners as ``lower than dogs and pigs.''
	   Ngwenya, 24, told Judge Godfrey Chidyausikyu he met Banana in
the street in Bulawayo in 1995. The ex-president allegedly invited
him to a hotel and later fondled him until he was sexually aroused
and was made to perform anal sex on Banana.
	   Allegations of Banana's predatory homosexuality emerged last
year during the trial of a police aide who was sentenced to 10
years in jail for the murder of a police colleague who taunted him
as ``Banana's wife.''
	   -----
	   WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) _ Workmen are dismantling an electric
fence on the border with Botswana to stop the death of wild animals
that got entangled in it.
	   Botswana's Director of Animal Health and Production, M.V.
Raborokgwe, was quoted Wednesday in the Namibian newspaper as
saying his government had ordered the dismantling of one of the
fences in Ngamiland to open up the seasonal wildlife migration
route.
	   Only a 30 kilometer section of the fence on the Northern
Buffalo-Kwando River would be taken down, he said. Work started two
weeks ago.
	   The fence stretches from Caprivi's Mahango Game Reserve to the
Kwando River.
	   Namibia pushed for the dismantling of the fence. A Namibia
Ministry of Environment and Tourism official, Maria Kapere, said on
Tuesday that the two countries agreed that only wild animals and
not cattle be allowed to move freely.
	   Botswana erected effective cattle control areas throughout its
countryside over the past several years to combat hoof and mouth
disease that can also move through wild game herds.
	   ----
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) _ Government negotiators and a
teachers union settled differences over staff layoffs in a
last-minute effort to avert a nationwide strike called for next
week.
	   Sporadic actions, including a stay-away, continued around the
country on Wednesday because union officials were not able to reach
their membership after the agreement was made near midnight
Tuesday.
	   The South African Democratic Teachers' Union hailed the
agreement as a victory, saying all their demands had been met.
	   Education Minister Sibusiso Bengu agreed to a moratorium on
layoffs of temporary teachers and other demands, including
participation of teacher representatives in the budget process.
	   Two smaller teachers' unions were still negotiating with the
government.
	   The government withdrew proposed regulations that the unions
said would have resulted in at least 50,000 teachers losing their
jobs and an increase in student-teacher ratios.
	   (var-pr)
</TEXT>
