<HEADLINE>
SADF proposes Hasina be nominated for Nobel Peace Prize, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
SADF proposes Hasina be nominated for Nobel Peace Prize, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A Dhaka-based human rights organisation has proposed that Prime
Minister Sheikh Hasina be nominated for the 1998 Nobel Peace Prize,
for her ``unique contribution to the cause of peace.''
	   Sheikh Hasina's name was proposed for the prize in view of her
historic peace initiatives in the Chittagong Hill Tracts that ended
two decades of a bloody ethnic strife there.
	   South Asia Democracy Forum (SADF), having its branches in all
the remaining six SAARC countries, made the proposal on the basis
of a consensus by a jury of eminent personalities from all seven
member-states of the regional forum.
	   The recommendation was conveyed to the Nobel Foundation in Oslo
for consideration, said a press release.
	   ``Hasina's contribution to the cause of peace in Bangladesh as
well as in the world will go down in history as remarkable'' as she
has been able to make her voice of peace heard in the region, the
forum said.
	   ``It is against this backdrop that Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina
made a fervent appeal to both India and Pakistan that nuclear tests
and missiles can never serve the cause of humanity,'' it said in
its recommendation.
	   The latest peace initiatives in Ireland were taken only after
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina began negotiations with the tribal
insurgents of Chittagong Hill Tracts, the organisation observed.
	   
</TEXT>
