<SLUG> RAINSTORM-A-SIDE-EFFECT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rainstorm a side-effect of global warming, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Rainstorm a side-effect of global warming, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Valerie BolcinaASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   YESTERDAY'S rainstorm was just one of the disastrous effects of
global warming, a visiting international expert said.
	   The bird flu, red tide and mad cow disease are also symptoms of
the greenhouse effect, according to Shen Sin-yan, director of the
Global Warming International Centre in the US. Dr Shen is in Hong
Kong for the 9th Global Warming International Conference and Expo.
	   And the increasing strength of the El Nino phenomenon, linked to
this year's heavy rains and warm spring weather, is a clear
indication that the build-up of greenhouse gases is raising the
global temperature.
	   Dr Shen said humidity pockets created by the rise in the Earth's
temperature allowed micro-organisms to adapt to new environments as
human immune systems weakened.
	   Viruses move from tropical to sub-temperate climates while algal
blooms flourish forming potentially hazardous red tides.
	   He said both the warming effect of burning fossil fuels and the
atmospheric build-up of the carbon dioxide produced increased
temperatures. To counteract this effect water evaporates from the
ocean and the result is storms such as yesterday's downpour.
	   Another effect of heavy cloud cover is loss of sunlight which
leads to failed crops.
	   Dr Shen said: ``We need to stabilise the current climate by
reducing our heat input and greenhouse gases.'' Of Hong Kong's
greenhouse gas emissions, 52 per cent are from power stations.
	   Of all such gases emitted, carbon dioxide accounts for 92 per
cent. Methane makes up 6 per cent and 2 per cent is in the form of
nitrous oxide.
	   The conversion of China Light and Power's Black Point power
plant from coal- to gas-fired production led to a significant
decrease in emissions.
	   Hong Kong currently produces 36.6 million tonnes of greenhouse
gases annually. This figure is expected to rise to 60,000 tonnes
during the next 10 years.
	   Figures released in 1990 show that Hong Kong's per capita
production of greenhouse gases is 6.8 tonnes a year, compared to
19.5 tonnes in the United States.
	   Director of Environmental Protection Robert Law said yesterday
it was hoped the LPG trial scheme would be made permanent this
summer.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
