<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Cameroon-Austria,0435 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Spark and unpredictability vs. experience and
</HEADLINE>
doggedness &QL; 
 &UR; By GEORGE JAHN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOULOUSE, France (AP) _ Toulouse _ or not to lose.
	   No matter how you say it, Thursday's Austria-Cameroon game in
southern France city will go a long way toward making or breaking
two of the most unpredictable World Cup teams.
	   ``We're not interested in safe soccer,'' said Claude Le Roy,
coach of Cameroon's Indomitable Lions. ``Some risks always have to
be taken.''
	   Defying the defensive, avoid-the-loss tactics so prevalent in
soccer today, Austrian forward Andreas Herzog also dropped hints of
an offense-minded strategy at Stade Municipal _ at least until the
first goal.
	   ``We will try to score in the first few minutes,'' Herzog said.
``Then things will be easier.''
	   The game is probably the best chance for either team to get a
victory at the World Cup, although Cameroon enters the game with
better momentum.
	   Austria was a surprise winner of its European qualifying group,
ahead of the likes of Sweden and Scotland, but lost to lowly
Hungary and the United States in exhibtion matches before posting
unconvincing victories over marginal qualifier Tunisia and even
lower-ranked Liechtenstein. Austrian fans booed at the home games.
	   Cameroon also took first place in its qualifying group in
Africa, and followed it up with a 0-0 draw against the Netherlands
in May and a 2-1 victory over Denmark on Friday, a possible sign
that the Lions have put their miserable 1994 World Cup performance
behind them with an eye on recreating the magic to 1990, when they
became the first African team to reach the quarterfinals.
	   Le Roy appears to have infused his squad with oft-lacking
cohesion and team spirit since May, when he retook the job he had
already held between 1985 and 1988.
	   Cameroon has also survived the loss of Marc Vivien Foe, a
standout midfielder with newly-crowned French champion Lens, who
broke his leg in training. Veteran striker took over as field
leader, scoring both goals against Denmark and restoring the team's
confidence again.
	   Despite their differences, one thought unites the two squads _
the need to get off to a winning start.
	   ``Our World Cup will depend a lot on how we will get out of that
first match against Austria,'' Le Roy said.
	   ``Cameroon is a tough team,'' Austrian defender Anton Pfeffer
said. ``And because it's our first game, we'll have a tough time
coming back if we lose against them.''
	   (gj/rac/jw)
</TEXT>
