<SLUG> SLOPE-WORK-MAY-BY-LAW sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Slope work may have to be enforced by law, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Slope work may have to be enforced by law, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Michael WongASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PROPERTY owners may be forced by law to carry out slope safety
work if they continue to neglect doing the necessary maintenance,
an engineering official said.
	   Speaking after a day of landslides following torrential rain,
government geotechnical engineer John Massey said about two-thirds
of private slope owners were neglecting maintenance.
	   ``People are aware of their responsibility, but only about 40
per cent of them are actually doing anything to discharge their
responsibility,'' Mr Massey said.
	   ``It may be necessary to seek legislation to compel private
owners to carry out maintenance of their slopes if further efforts
on public education and assistance to encourage owners to maintain
slopes is not successful,'' he said. ``Certainly 40 per cent of
private owners maintaining their slopes is not satisfactory.''
About 12,000 of the 18,000 private slopes in Hong Kong were
neglected, Mr Massey said.
	   Of these, about 6,000 ``would have high consequences if they
failed'', he said. In addition, about 10,000 government slopes
would have ``high consequences'' if they failed.
	   Mr Massey said the main difficulty in getting private owners to
do the necessary work was the lack of a co-ordinated effort among
property owners.
	   Many buildings had no owner's association to discuss the issue
and come up with the money _ even though most flat owners would not
have to pay more than $1,000 each.
	   Mr Massey said the Geotechnical Engineering Office (GEO) would
step up its television advertising campaign after a survey
indicated that many people still don't know what to do in case of a
landslide.
	   The survey, conducted by Hong Kong University, found that the
number of people concerned about slope safety increased to 76 per
cent last year from 70.1 per cent in 1996.
	   But 30.8 per cent still do not know what to do when a landslip
warning is issued.
	   The results were part of a random telephone survey commissioned
by the GEO last November, in which 1,530 people were interviewed.
	   Robert Chung Ting-yiu of the university said yesterday 40 per
cent of those interviewed did not know the signs of landslips such
as debris falling from slopes. Mr Massey said more TV ads would be
produced to teach the public how to detect signs of a landslip and
what to do afterwards.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
