<HEADLINE>
Action on high-risk coral reef fish urged, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Action on high-risk coral reef fish urged, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Julie ChuASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A QUARANTINE system should be set up for high-risk coral reef
fish which have poisoned at least 200 people so far this year,
provisional urban councillors have urged.
	   PUC members meeting yesterday unanimously passed a motion that
together with the Agriculture and Fisheries Department and
Department of Health contingency measures be adopted and long-term
solutions studied to safeguard people from high-risk seafood.
	   Provisional Councillor Wong Kwok-hing who is also a member of
Democratic Alliance for the Betterment of Hong Kong (DAB), pointed
to the 268 cases of ciguatoxin poisoning from imported deep-water
coral reef fish so far this year.
	   He said an increasing number of poisoning cases had made it
necessary for the council and government departments to adopt
contingency measures.
	   Long-term solutions, such as an import quarantine system for
high-risk seafood, having sales records and collection systems in
place and developing rapid tests, should also be looked into.
	   Such systems would enable the ``normal sale'' of non-high-risk
seafood, he added.
	   He said it was within the government's power to check dangerous
fish as there were only a few such fish being imported. Coral reef
fish account for about 10 per cent of the 21,000 tonnes of seafood
imported last year.
	   Democratic Party member Fred Li Wah-ming said he had raised a
``very similar'' motion on shellfish last March which was not
supported by DAB members.
	   Mr Wong admitted to have studied Mr Li's motion before drafting
his own proposal. He believed his motion, which concentrates on a
specific kind of fish, was more feasible.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:ACTION-ON-HIGH-RISK sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
