<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Amnesties </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Truth body says it may invalidate 132 amnesty applications
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) _ A panel investigating apartheid
human rights abuses said on Wednesday 132 amnesty applications from
a black nationalist group could be declared invalid by the end of
the week.
	   The Truth and Reconciliation Commission said that accounted for
about half the amnesty applications from the Pan-Africanist
Congress, a radical grouping whose armed wing bombed and attacked
white civilian targets in its fight against apartheid.
	   In a statement issued by its chairman Desmond Tutu, the
commission said the applications would be voided unless the PAC
provided more information on what acts had been committed and the
identities of its operatives.
	   ``No real names or specifics of acts in respect of which amnesty
is sought are given,'' the statement said.
	   Set up in 1995 to probe abuses by all sides in the fight against
white rule, the commission can grant amnesty to people who tell the
full truth about their actions and prove a political motive.
	   Many of the applicants had just filled out their code names on
the application forms which ranged from common African first names
like Sipho to more bizarre nicknames like Scud Missile, Russian
Tank and Karl Marx.
	   The commission was set up after 1994's first all-race elections
which ended apartheid and swept the African National Congress into
power. It aims to uncover apartheid crimes and promote racial
healing.
	   (ph-aos)
</TEXT>
