w1078 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sweden-NewPeaceConcep 1stLdWritethru   06-10 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sweden-New Peace Concept, 1st Ld Writethru,0587 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nations urged to rethink peace; India-Pakistan conflict
</HEADLINE>
highlighted &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: Updates with quotes, details from news conference. No pickup &QL; 
 &UR; By JIM HEINTZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) _ Governments should enter the 21st
century understanding that peace means more than countries arming
themselves so heavily that no one will attack, a respected research
institute said Wednesday.
	   The recent nuclear testing by neighboring rivals India and
Pakistan is an example. Both see nuclear possession as a convincing
military deterrent. Nevertheless, both seem potentially on a path
to a showdown.
	   ``War is quite possible,'' said Eric Arnett, a co-author of the
Stockholm International Peace Research Institute's yearbook. ``It's
also quite possible that nuclear weapons might be used.''
	   Arnett, author of the report's section on military research and
development, said India appeared to have 20-30 nuclear warheads,
compared with 10-20 for Pakistan.
	   SIPRI's annual report is regarded as a definitive assessment of
global security issues.
	   The 29th edition covers 1997, before the balance of power issue
took a worrisome turn with India and Pakistan demonstrating the
respective nuclear weapons capability with a series of test blasts
last month.
	   Their armed conflict was one of 25 worldwide last year _ down
from 27 in 1996 and 36 in 1989 in which at least 1,000 people were
killed.
	   SIPRI noted that most conflicts since the end of the Cold War
occur within a country rather than between nations; and happen more
often in ``failed'' authoritarian states rather than in democratic,
prosperous ones.
	   ``The security agenda ahead must be founded on a new political
philosophy, encompassing a common, institutionalized system of
standards and shared values rather than concepts based on the
balance of power,'' it said stated.
	   The institute called for the ``complete elimination of nuclear
weapons,'' though the report, and comments from its authors
indicated that was unlikely to take place any time soon.
	   Developments in 1997 were not all discouraging. Favorable events
included the movements toward peace in Northern Ireland and the two
Koreas. Also, the signing of an international treaty on banning
anti-personnel mines, and the ratification by Russia, China and the
United States of the Chemical Weapons Convention.
	   Nevertheless, peace prospects for the Middle East remain
distant, for which Peter Jones, co-author of that section of the
report, blamed Israeli Prime Minister Benhamin Netanyahu.
	   ``Although there is ample blame for all the parties involved,
the conclusion cannot be escaped that Netanyahu's commitment to the
peace process has never been more than equivocal,'' he stated.
	   Additionally, the START II treaty to reduce nuclear arsenals
remained ``in limbo'' in 1997, ``despite agreement between
Presidents Bill Clinton and Boris Yeltsin on a series of measures
to boost its chances of being ratified by the Russian Parliament,''
it said.
	   Among the report's other highlights:
	   _ Annual world military expenditure declined by about one-third
from 1988 to 1997, when spending was estimated to be about 740
billion dollars.
	   _ Russia's military expenditure in 1997 was less than 10 percent
of what the Soviet Union spent a decade earlier.
	   _ Peace accords last year in Liberia, Tajikistan and Bangladesh
can be considered ``major successes in armed conflict resolution.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sweden-New Peace Concept, 1st Ld Writethru; CT:i; 
