<BODY>
<SLUG> CHAN-HAILS-LEGISLATURE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chan hails balanced legislature, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Chan hails balanced legislature, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Susan LanninASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   CHIEF Secretary for Administration Anson Chan Fang On-sang said
the first legislative elections under Chinese sovereignty had
produced a balanced legislature, contrary to pre-election
criticisms.
	   Speaking in New York during a 10-day visit to the United States,
Mrs Chan said the outcome proved critics wrong.
	   ``I am aware of criticisms that the election arrangements were
flawed, that they were designed to lessen the prospects of the
pro-democracy candidates, and boost the chances of the so-called
China-friendly candidates. I believe the outcome proved
otherwise,'' she told the annual dinner of the Hong Kong Trade
Development Council at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel on Monday (NY
time).
	   ``There were no boycotts, but plenty of hard, noisy, colourful
campaigning, which is very much Hong Kong style,'' she said.
	   ``The elections were conducted freely, fairly and honestly. They
produced a balanced legislature, including a good slew of members
who were most critical of the arrangements.'' Mrs Chan will spend
three days in Washington meeting senior administration officials
and members of Congress.
	   She said Hong Kong had confounded its critics because fears of
loss of freedom through interference from Beijing had proved
unfounded.
	   ``The promises of a high degree of autonomy for Hong Kong have
been honoured in word and deed . . . Hong Kong people are now
running Hong Kong within the framework of our constitution.''
	   
</TEXT>
