w1085 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Adoptions     06-10 0325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Adoptions </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Adoption bill clears parliament's upper house
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The upper house of parliament passed amendments to
Russia's adoption law on Wednesday that would tighten control over
foreign adoptions and encourage more Russians to adopt children.
	   The changes, passed by the lower house on Friday, were
unanimously approved by the Federation Council. They must still be
approved by President Boris Yeltsin before becoming law.
	   Yeltsin has not publicly stated his opinion on the subject.
	   The amendments were proposed by the Communist head of the State
Duma's women and family affairs committee, Alevtina Aparina, who
argued they were needed to better protect children's rights.
	   Aparina and her allies said foreign adoption agencies often
bribe Russian officials to arrange illegal adoptions.
	   The amendments that were approved were a watered-down version of
those first proposed.
	   The original version said that Russia must sign agreements with
other countries to codify adoption procedures by Sept. 1, 1999.
Adoption workers and human rights activists warned that the
proposal could discourage prospective adoptive parents and leave
most Russian orphans with no hope of finding a home.
	   There are many more Russian orphans than Russians interested in
adopting them.
	   The final version contained no time limit for the prospective
international agreements to be signed, meaning pending adoptions
will not be stalled by the measure.
	   The bill would allow foreign adoption agencies to operate in
Russia only after their country signs an agreement with Russia
setting out the rules. In the interim, prospective foreign parents
can use the services of proxies and interpreters as they do now.
	   According to parliamentary estimates, there are about 80 foreign
adoption agencies, mostly American, currently operating in Russia,
usually through Russian intermediaries.
	   (vi/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Russia-Adoptions; CT:i; 
