w1086 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Soccer-WorldCu     06-10 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup Briefs,0931 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Includes items on German training schedule; power problems in
</HEADLINE>
Haiti, Bangladesh; soccer gambling in Thailand; Saudi coach;
high-risk matches; FIFA scholarship &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   NICE, France (AP) _ When Brazil and Scotland kicked off the
century's last World Cup on Wednesday afternoon, the German team
had better things to do than watch. It trained.
	   But in a concession to players who wanted to see at least part
of the game, coach Berti Vogts moved forward the start of practice
session to 5:15 p.m. (1515 GMT). Originally, the start of practice
had been set for 5:30 p.m. (1530 GMT), the time of the opening
kickoff.
	   With a slightly earlier start of practice, the players hoped to
see at least part of the second half.
	   The Germans had been the day off Tuesday and did not train
Wednesday morning.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Haitians will have to turn off air
conditioners, refrigerators and all other appliances during soccer
matches if they want to watch the World Cup live.
	   The state utility, which routinely cuts off power to the capital
for 12 hours each day, has promised to double the city's
electricity supply to 100 megawatts daily during the tournament.
	   But the power-starved nation cannot generate a further 15
megawatts, the minimum needed to meet a full day's worth of
consumption in Port-au-Prince.
	   Officials therefore appealed to Haitians to turn off all
appliances while watching the soccer matches in order not to
overburden the power system, the Nouvelliste daily reported.
	   Fewer than a third of Port-au-Prince's 2 million residents own
television sets. But many were invited to crowd into friends' homes
or visit neighbors selling seats in front of their TV sets.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) _ Authorities in Bangladesh have beefed
up security around the country's notoriously unreliable power
stations because of concerns that angry soccer fans might attack
them in case of power cuts during matches.
	   Soccer is arguably the most popular sport in Bangladesh. Though
its national team didn't reach the World Cup tournament that begins
Wednesday in France, fans cheer on dozens of local teams.
	   The government flew in two Russian engineers from Moscow on
Sunday to repair a 210 megawatt power station to ensure there was
an adequate power supply in the capital, Dhaka, newspapers
reported.
	   Power cuts are routine in Bangladesh. In some areas, power cuts
last 10-12 hours, resulting in street demonstrations.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Although their national team did not
qualify for the World Cup, Thais are planning to bet a record
amount on the tournament, according to a survey released Wednesday.
	   The tournament will be a boon to a range of Thai businesses,
according to a survey by the Thai Farmers Bank Research Center.
	   Thais will bet about 30 billion baht (dlrs 700 million)
nationwide, the survey said.
	   Aside from bookmakers, a number of other businesses will get a
boost from the event, the research center said. Sales and use of
communications equipment will be on the rise, as fans trade
information by mobile phones, computers and pagers. Newspapers
should see sales increase, and pubs and restaurants with big-screen
televisions should get more business, the survey said.
	   Sales of instant noodles and coffee will also perk up as fans
stay up late at night to watch games because of the time
difference.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   PARIS (AP) _ The coach who won the 1994 World Cup with Brazil,
Carlos Alberto Parreira, is back for the 1998 tournament with the
Saudi Arabian team. Parreira has no hopes of winning this time
around.
	   ``Even with a team that has no chance of winning the Cup, just
being here, playing against France, the host country, being a part
of the big picture. ... I just waited to make sure that Saudi
Arabia was not in the same group as Brazil,'' Parreira said
Wednesday in an interview with French daily L'Equipe.
	   Parreira was happy not to be coaching Brazil this time around.
The pressure of having to win was too great.
	   ``Believe me, I don't regret anything,'' said Parreira about his
decision to stop coaching Brazil, ``I'm happy.''
	   ___ &QC; 
	   PARIS (AP) _ The French organizing committee and the interior
ministry have put three matches on a security black list. Security
will be beefed up for Netherlands-Belgium, United States-Iran and
Colombia-England.
	   Neighbors Netherlands and Belgium are both notorious for the
animosity between their supporters and the level of organization of
their hooligans. For the United States-Iran match, organizers are
unsure how Iranian fans will behave given the political situation
between the two countries.
	   English hooligans are most feared by the French police and
security forces, especially since the Colombia-England match is in
the northern city of Lens, the French daily le Parisien reported.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   PARIS (AP) _ The international soccer federation is setting up a
scholarship fund in honor of retiring FIFA president Joao Havelange
to help students researching soccer-related subjects.
	   The fund will enable students from developing countries to
pursue their studies at universities in Europe and the United
States, FIFA officials said.
	   Applications for the new scholarships will be awarded depending
on the potential impact the studies will have on the development of
football in student's home country.
	   (sl/jw)
</TEXT>
