<HEADLINE>
Online virus update considered, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Online virus update considered, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HEALTH authorities are considering setting up an internet link
with Taiwanese doctors on the deadly intestinal virus that has
killed at least 32 babies in Taiwan.
	   The Department of Health says it is continuing to monitor the
intestinal ``enterovirus type 71''.
	   But it stopped short of issuing health alerts to Hong Kong
doctors saying it was waiting for more information from Taiwanese
authorities. A spokeswoman said the department remained concerned
over the outbreak and was monitoring the situation.
	   She said the department was considering setting up an internet
link to Taiwan so that local doctors could obtain more information.
	   President of the Hong Kong Medical Association Dr Lo Wing-lok
said the government should alert doctors and the public to the
potential dangers of the enterovirus, as well as advising
travellers to take precautions.
	   He said an internet site would be the most effective way of
doing that. Yesterday, Singapore's health and environment
ministries announced there was ``no unusual occurrence'' of the
viral infection in the country, but that medical practitioners
would be warned to be on the watch for outbreaks of the illness.
	   At least 10,000 children in Taiwan have been affected by the
virus, which is usually spread through food and physical contact
with an infected person.
	   More than 32 children have died as a result of the infection.
The infection breaks down immunity, leaving infants at risk of
contracting various fatal diseases.
	   Taiwan's health department director, Chan Chi-hsien, said the
rate of infection was slow based on similar outbreaks in the United
States, Bulgaria, and Malaysia.
	   He accused the mainland of hindering Taiwan's attempts to
control the outbreak, because it was not a member of the World
Health Organisation and therefore was unable to get the antiserum
to test the virus.
	   
</TEXT>
