MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HONGKONG Telecom is among many companies which have agreed to
join a self-help program proposed by the Hong Kong Council of
Social Service to create jobs.
	   A number of companies in the retailing sector will provide
retraining courses as part of the program.
	   The Job Creation Program announced yesterday is aimed at
creating more than 16,800 vacancies.
	   The proposal has been submitted to the Chief Executive's Office
and the Financial Secretary Sir Donald Tsang Yam-kuen.
	   The ambitious project is aimed at helping the unemployed, middle
income group as well as middle and small-sized enterprises overcome
economic hardships through self-help and mutual help.
	   Dr Choi Yuen-wan, chairman of the council's Integrated Project
on Employment, said more than 6,500 vacancies would be created in a
recycling program alone.
	   Plans included creating five flea markets or special areas for
hawkers throughout Hong Kong. These would be tailored for the
disabled to sell hand-made crafts and second-hand goods donated by
voluntary organisations.
	   
