<HEADLINE>
Counter-plan likely to be rejected: Chan, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Counter-plan likely to be rejected: Chan, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Chloe LaiASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A COUNTER-PROPOSAL for the municipal councils to take over full
responsibility for food safety and environmental hygiene was likely
to be rejected, Deputy Secretary for Constitutional Affairs Maureen
Chan Leung Mong-lin said yesterday. Mrs Chan was speaking to
reporters after an extraordinary meeting at the Provisional
Regional Council was postponed due to the small number of
councillors who turned up. The meeting was to have discussed the
government's proposal to assume the councils' food safety and
environmental hygiene powers. The proposal was contained in a
public document released last week for public consultation in the
next two months.
	   Mrs Chan said the government was not aware of the councils'
counter-proposal until it was reported in the press last week.
	   She said nowhere else in the world were food safety and
environmental hygiene supervised by a municipal council.
	   Members of the two councils, including chairman of the
Provisional Urban Council Ronald Leung Ding-bong and chairman of
the PUC Lau Wong-fat, had suggested the councils should assume all
duties of food and environmental protection, including those being
supervised by the government.
	   Mrs Chan acknowledged that the government document showed
preference for the assumption of the municipal councils' powers.
	   But she said the public could still give practical suggestions
on protecting public health during the consultation exercise.
	   Mrs Chan said 20 submissions had been received so far on the
Review of District Organisations document, all of which supported
the proposal to strip the councils' powers on food and
environmental hygiene.
	   Responses differed on the four options for the structure of the
district organisations, she said.
	   
</TEXT>
