AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IT was a truly black day at the Provisional Regional Council
chambers.
	   First came the black rainstorm warning that forced cancellation
of a meeting to hear a briefing on planned reorganisation of the
municipal councils.
	   Next, Deputy Secretary for Constitutional Affairs Maureen Chan
Leung Mong-lin declined to give an impromptu briefing, which put
some councillors in a black mood.
	   Then a group of opponents tried to present Mrs Chan with a big
black paper box symbolising the government's ``black box''
operation in planning the changes.
	   Mrs Chan initially refused to accept it _ making the
councillors' mood even blacker _ but eventually she asked her staff
to receive the ``gift''.
	   The meeting was called off by council chairman Lau Wong-fat,
although 16 members had already arrived, and will be rescheduled.
	   Members accused Ms Chan of being insincere about gathering their
opinions, after she declined to stay on and brief those present.
She rejected the accusation, saying she did not want to have to
give the explanation twice.
	   
</TEXT>
