<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Opposition </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Defying a police ban, opposition party gathers illegally
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Defying police orders not to
gather in public, hundreds of supporters turned up Wednesday for a
brightly lit open-air dinner organized by Malaysia's main
opposition party.
	   ``We haven't received any news whether or not the police will
repeal the ban at the last minute, but we're going ahead with the
dinner,'' said Lim Guan Eng, deputy secretary-general of the
opposition Democratic Action Party.
	   Vehicles clogged the road adjoining the field, where over 60
dinner tables had been placed for their supporters. Volunteers
dashed to open more seats for the larger-than-expected crowd.
	   Lim said this was the fourth police crackdown against public
meetings over the past 10 days and the second time police has
banned a gathering organized by the DAP.
	   ``If there's a ban on political gatherings, where is democracy
and where is civil liberty?'' he said.
	   Last Tuesday, Malaysian authorities suddenly withdrew permission
for a meeting of residents to discuss the city's severe water
rationing.
	   Police also broke up a gathering of lawyers at a city hotel on
May 30, saying the organizers hadn't obtained a permit. Lim and his
father, who heads the DAP, were to speak at that meeting.
	   Since the cancelations of public meetings in recent weeks,
dozens of opposition parties, volunteer and consumer organizations
have demanded more civil liberties and free speech.
</TEXT>
