<HEADLINE>
Macau magistrate frees alleged senior triad member, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Macau magistrate frees alleged senior triad member, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Harald BruningASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   AN alleged top triad member was released yesterday on his own
recognisance after 15 hours of questioning by an examining
magistrate of the Macau District Court.
	   Wong Tat-hou, 30, had been handed to the District Court by
Macau's Judicial Police on Monday.
	   Police said at the time that Wong was facing possible
arraignment over a number of alleged crimes, namely membership of a
triad gang, homicide, blackmail, casino loansharking and
kidnapping.
	   Senior police sources have described Wong as one of the top
office-bearers of the 14K triad gang, whose alleged leader,
``Broken Tooth'' Wan Kuok-koi, has been in pre-trial detention on a
preliminary charge of ``criminal association''.
	   ``Criminal association'' is the local legal term for organised
crime membership.
	   A judicial source said examining magistrate Mario Chaves had
decided to release Wong on his own recognisance because of an
apparent lack of circumstantial evidence.
	   The District Court on Sunday ordered the pre-trial detention of
two female suspected triad members who were allegedly ``very
close'' to their detained leader, Wan.
	   Wong Wan-wa (widely known by her Cantonese nickname Fei Mui or
Fat Girl) and Lam Iok-im (known by her nickname Dai Ga Je or Big
Sister) are both facing a wide range of preliminary charges, namely
criminal association, blackmail, kidnapping and handling
contraband.
	   Wong Wan-wa, 34, is said to be known in the local underworld as
``the queen of smuggling''.
	   The District Court earlier this week also ordered the pre-trial
detention of a local 23-year-old Thai national, Pholpimeis
Suralhart, who allegedly carried an explosive device when arrested
by police last week.
	   He worked as a bouncer for a local discotheque reportedly owned
by Wan. Police sources have said the ``Heavy Club'' discotheque is
a hangout for triad suspects.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:MACAU-MAGISTRATE-FREES sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
