<BODY>
<SLUG> LONE-JUDGE-TO-DECIDE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lone judge to decide on appeals, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Lone judge to decide on appeals, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Neil WesternASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   STEPS to deter time-wasting criminals from slowing the wheels of
justice are to be introduced in the Court of Appeal from today.
	   Procedures are being installed which will enable a single judge
_ rather than a full panel of three _ to decide whether to grant
leave for convicts to appeal against their sentence.
	   Applicants who are given leave will have a hearing before a full
panel.
	   Those who are refused leave can still insist on a full court
hearing, but will be warned they could end up serving longer in
jail if their application is considered worthless.
	   The procedures will apply only to appellants who have been
refused legal aid and do not have a lawyer to represent them.
	   The measures follow a judiciary study which showed 85 per cent
of the 400 convicts a year who appeal against sentences were
refused legal aid and were unrepresented.
	   A judiciary spokeswoman yesterday said the scheme was being
introduced ``with a view to reduce the number of unmeritorious
applications before the full Court of Appeal''.
	   The scheme will be tried out for two to three months after being
given the go-ahead by Chief High Court Judge Patrick Chan Siu-oi.
	   It was one of several ideas which were considered by the
Criminal Court Users' Committee under the chairmanship of Justice
Barry Mortimer.
	   When the proposal was revealed almost a year ago by the Hong
Kong Standard it sparked some concern among lawyers and human-
rights activists.
	   But Bar Council chairwoman, Audrey Eu Yeut-mee, SC, said
convicts who persevered to a full court hearing after being refused
by a single judge were likely to face longer in jail.
	   ``It's a filtering mechanism. It gives the applicant some
warning.'' But Ms Eu added the trial would have to be evaluated
before its merit could be determined.
	   The court has the power to order that some of the time served by
a worthless applicant does not count towards his sentence.
	   The judiciary spokeswoman said the scheme was authorised under a
section of the Criminal Procedure Ordinance but ``had not been used
for some time''.
	   ``The matter has been discussed with senior judges of the Court
of Appeal and members of the legal profession,'' the spokeswoman
added.
	   The procedures were to begin yesterday, but will start today
following the closure of all courts because of heavy rain.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
