<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-East Timor, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
East Timorese stage noisy protests against Indonesian control
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS for AMs. ADDS new detail; TRIMS &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHER TORCHIA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DILI, Indonesia (AP) _ Under a searing sun, more than 3,000 East
Timorese protested Wednesday against Indonesian control of their
homeland, roaring freedom anthems, briefly brandishing outlawed
rebel flags and bowing their heads in Roman Catholic prayer.
	   Later, a dozen buses packed with students clinging to the
runnerboards and swaying on the roofs drove in a joyous convoy
through Dili, the capital of the former Portuguese colony, shouting
slogans in support of a vote on self-determination.
	   The military, accused of widespread abuses in the disputed
territory, did not intervene. It has kept a low profile since
longtime authoritarian leader Suharto quit last month and a new
government with an agenda of democratic reform took over.
	   The demonstrations were an emphatic rejection of a proposal by
Indonesian President B.J. Habibie to grant special status to East
Timor, which could ease the tight, often violent grip the
government has exerted there since invading in 1975.
	   ``We want total independence. We want to be free,'' said
protester Licinio Branco. Others echoed his view that Indonesian
authorities were taking only half-measures.
	   In another conciliatory gesture, Justice Minister Muladi
announced Wednesday that Habibie had signed a decree allowing the
release of 15 East Timorese political prisoners in Dili. Muladi
said they would be freed ``as soon as possible.''
	   The list does not include jailed rebel chief Xanana Gusmao, a
symbol of the separatist struggle who was hailed by protesters who
gathered in a yard at the state-funded University of East Timor.
	   ``Release Xanana,'' they shouted, fists raised. They unfurled
banners with his image, as well as a poster with a crude drawing of
an Indonesian soldier cutting off the breast of a civilian woman
with a knife. One painted slogan read, ``Get rid of Indonesia.''
	   In an interview broadcast Wednesday on Portuguese state radio,
Gusmao described Habibie as a ``clown'' who loyally served his
mentor, Suharto, while East Timor suffered repression.
	   It was one of the biggest political demonstrations in recent
years, and many protesters said they felt freer to speak out. They
shouted abuse at military officers who peered over the fence from
an adjacent barracks.
	   But activists only flashed banned rebel flags, signaling that
fear of the military still runs deep. In 1991, dozens were killed
when troops opened fire on a protest march near a Dili cemetery.
	   After ordering forces into East Timor, Suharto annexed the
territory as Indonesia's 27th province, refusing to make
concessions despite international complaints about the deaths of
tens of thousands of people. The United Nations does not recognize
Indonesian control there.
	   A new military commander for East Timor, Col. Suhartono
Suratman, was sworn in Wednesday in a ceremony in Dili. His
predecessor and 11 other top officers and soldiers were killed in a
helicopter crash in bad weather last week.
	   The army said it was an accident, but East Timorese separatists
based in Portugal said rebels had shot it down.
	   The guerrilla war against the military has dwindled to
occasional hit-and-run attacks that pose no threat to Indonesian
authority. The symbolism of the long rebel struggle, however, is a
more potent force that serves as a rallying point for
pro-independence activists.
	   On Wednesday, student protesters in buses drove by a military
barracks, shouting ``Viva Xanana'' in honor of the jailed rebel
chief. Dressed only in shorts, a few off-duty officers stepped out
of their homes for a glance before strolling back inside.
</TEXT>
