<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Elections, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
President, son take opposite sides in municipal elections
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS that tough race expected in Baalbek, CORRECTS in 4th graf
that Skaff is Greek Catholic and Zahle is majority Greek Catholic &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ President Elias Hrawi and his son George
are set for an electoral showdown next week, backing rival tickets
in the municipal elections in their hometown of Zahle.
	   Newspapers said Wednesday the race for Zahle would be close, and
the results could have a bearing on the president's political
prospects. Hrawi's extended term of office expires in November, but
it is thought he may accept another extension.
	   Hrawi, his younger son Roy and his nephew, Khalil Hrawi, a
member of parliament, have endorsed a slate of candidates for the
21-member town council in Zahle, eastern Lebanon.
	   But Hrawi's eldest son George has backed the ticket of his
father's arch-foe, Elie Skaff, a Greek Catholic legislator. The
town is mostly Greek Catholic.
	   Zahle, some 37 kilometers (23 miles) east of the capital Beirut,
is the largest Christian city in the Bekaa Valley, where the fourth
and last stage of Lebanon's municipal elections will be held
Sunday.
	   Skaff and Hrawi, a Maronite, are long-time rivals for the
leadership of the town.
	   ``I respect my father and admire his achievements in Zahle ...
but I follow my own convictions in politics,'' George Hrawi told
the newspaper An-Nahar.
	   George Hrawi, who shied away from politics until recently, said
he did not agree with his father's policies. He did not elaborate,
but predicted the disagreement would ``snowball'' in the next few
days.
	   The president has not commented on his son's remarks.
	   Some political observers have speculated that the president may
have advised George to back the rival slate, so that the Hrawi
family would have supporters on the council, regardless of which
ticket wins.
	   A tough town council race is also expected in eastern Lebanon's
ancient city of Baalbek between the Hezbollah and Amal guerrilla
groups.
	   Candidates fielded by Hezbollah, the main guerrilla group
fighting Israel, scored major gains during elections in southern
Lebanon last Sunday and in the Shiite suburbs of south Beirut on
May 24, defeating rivals backed by Amal.
 &UR; zk-jbm/vj-lm 	   
</TEXT>
