<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Italy-Chile, 1st Ld-Writethru,0558 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Italy seeks to break tradition with good start against
</HEADLINE>
Chile &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Chiesa to replace Ravanelli; TRIMS &QL; 
 &UR; By PIERO VALSECCHI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BORDEAUX, France (AP) _ Italy seeks an untraditionally good
World Cup start in Thursday's Group B match against Chile to launch
its quest for a record-equaling fourth title.
	   Initial matches of past world competitions often have presented
headaches for the ``Azzurri.'' Coach Cesare Maldini and his son
Paolo, the team captain, hope for an easy start this time against
the Latin American team.
	   ``We have a lot of respect for Chile, but we need to begin with
a victory. The first match of the first round is often decisive for
qualifying,'' said Paolo Maldini, a 30-year-old AC Milan defender
with 87 caps on the national team.
	   Italy won the world title in Spain, in 1982, barely escaping
first-round elimination following three draws. It suffered a 1-0
first-match upset by Ireland in 1994 before rallying to reach the
final against Brazil in Pasadena.
	   The Chilean team, which qualified for the World Cup finals
following a 16-year absence, is considered the underdog compared
with three-time champion Italy.
	   However Ivan Zamorano and Marcelo Salas, the Chilean strikers of
international fame, could produce an early sensation in the
tournament if the Italian defense does not prove tighter and more
attentive than in recent warmup games.
	   A defensive lapse of young Alessandro Nesta touched off Italy's
last-minute 1-0 loss against Sweden in last week's tuneup.
	   Nesta is going to mark Zamorano with agile Fabio Cannavaro
taking care of Salas.
	   Zamorano and Salas, who combined for 23 goals in World Cup
qualifying, ``are a threat for any defense,'' Cesare Maldini said.
	   On offense, Italy must overcome the loss of striker Fabrizio
Ravanelli, who was dropped from the squad Wednesday with an
infection in his right lung. The Italians petitioned FIFA for a
roster change, with Parma forward Enrico Chiesa set to take
Ravanelli's spot.
	   Italy will also be without its ``Golden Boy'' Alessandro Del
Piero, just recovered from a right thigh strain.
	   However the team will not miss imagination and play-making skill
in front with veteran Roberto Baggio taking over the place of his
younger teammate.
	   Baggio, Italy's World Cup hero in 1994, said he was looking
forward to an outstanding performance against Chile and then
sitting on the substitutes bench against Cameroon.
	   Del Piero, considered a key to Italy's fortunes in the World
Cup, is likely to return to action against the African team in
Montpellier on June 17.
	   A 2-0 rout of England at Wembley and an undeserved 1-0 loss
against Argentina in recent warmup games have greatly boosted
Chile's prestige and self-confidence while causing alarm in the
Maldini family.
	   ``Chile is not only Zamorano and Salas. Midfield and defense are
good. It's a tough team,'' the Italian coach said.
	   As a result of the growing internationalization of European
leagues, Thursday's match features a duel between club teammates _
Inter Milan's goalie Gianluca Pagliuca on the Italian side and
Chile's Zamorano.
	   (pv-sl-jw)
</TEXT>
