<BODY>
<SLUG> GAUGING-PEREGRINE-ASSETS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Gauging Peregrine assets `no easy matter', HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Gauging Peregrine assets `no easy matter', HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   DETERMINING the amount of assets that could be recovered from
collapsed Peregrine Investment Holdings is very difficult because
the group is made up of 200 entities, an executive of provisional
liquidators Price Waterhouse said yesterday.
	   Partner Colin Bird said a US$1 billion (HK$7.8 billion) figure
that has been floated might be an over-optimistic assessment of the
amount likely to be recovered.
	   Price Waterhouse is holding a series of meetings this week,
starting today, for creditors to decide the course of action for
Peregrine's winding up.
	   The first meeting will include a vote by contributors on a
decision to apply to the court for an order winding up the company.
	   The second meeting will entitle creditors to determine by
resolution that a liquidator be appointed subject to court
approval, whether an application shall be made to the court for the
appointment of a committee of inspection to act with the
liquidator, and who the committee members are to be.
	   ``At the meetings, we will give the best estimates we can,'' Mr
Bird said.
	   ``It's very difficult to say the exact amount.'' Mr Bird said
his secondment from Price Waterhouse's London office was to view
the Peregrine case from a global perspective, as well as draw on
his experience of dealing with similar cases. ``I have a lot of
experience with these kind of complex firms.'' Questions have been
raised over the circumstances surrounding a US$265 million loan to
an Indonesian company and whether the firm failed to inform the
market about its financial circumstances in a timely manner.
	   The Securities and Futures Commission is under pressure to
explain its lack of action towards the firm and its failure to
launch an inquiry. But SFC sources have not ruled out further
action.
	   If the SFC does not feel it has the power to investigate
Peregrine, Financial Secretary Sir Donald Tsang Yam-kuen can
appoint an inspector to investigate the firm under Section 143 of
the Companies Ordinance.
	   The government will only act if there appears to be
circumstances suggesting its business had been conducted with
intent to defraud creditors.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
