<SLUG> BC-Czech-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Latest polls predict stalemate in early elections
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PRAGUE, Czech Republic (AP) _ Ten days before the country's
early elections, polls indicate a stalemate or a minority
government as a probable outcome of the crucial ballot.
	   According to a Sofres-Factum opinion poll published Wednesday,
opposition Social Democrats led by Milos Zeman have a solid lead
with a 27.8 percent support followed by the Civic Democratic Party
of former Premier Vaclav Klaus with 16.9 percent.
	   A total of 2,025 people were queried in May 7-29, but no margin
of error was given by the polling agency.
	   Zeman and Klaus, citing irreconcilable differences in their
political program and style, repeatedly have ruled out a grand
coalition that would allow majority rule.
	   Klaus led the country through painful economic reforms and the
1993 breakup of the Czechoslovak federation.
	   He was ousted from office after the Christian Democrats, led by
Josef Lux, left his three-party coalition amid accusations of dirty
campaign financing.
	   Soon after Klaus' political demise, his opponents inside the
party, led by former Interior Minister Jan Ruml, defected to form
their own Freedom Union.
	   Lux and Ruml then helped form the current interim government of
Premier Josef Tosovsky, designed to lead the country to early
elections on June 19-20.
	   The move seems to have backfired because the interim coalition
government's two main components are not exactly popular: the
Christian Democrats' support has sunk to an all-time low of 5.4
percent and the Freedom Union has the backing of 7.2 percent of
voters, according to Sofres Factum.
	   Orthodox unreformed communists have a steady support of 9
percent, the xenophobic Republicans hover around 6 percent, and the
a party called Pensioners for Secure Living enjoys a support of 7.8
percent.
	   But the latter three parties are considered extremist and most
likely will be shunned in post-election coalition plans.
	   While the election outcome is still uncertain, Zeman is largely
expected to be the first to have a shot at forming the new cabinet.
	   He has virtually no chance of forming a majority government
without the support of one of the three extremist parties, and he
would need Klaus to tolerate his minority government.
	   President Vaclav Havel's role as power broker could be crucial
if his health allows him to take active part in coalition talks.
	   The absence of a clear winner, frequent party infighting and
personal animosities among leaders who have dominated Czech
politics since 1989 make the ballot, and political negotiations
afterward, difficult.
	   (oh/nr/rp)
</TEXT>
