<SLUG> BY-PRODUCTS-OF-SUGAR sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
By-products of sugar mills go waste, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
By-products of sugar mills go waste, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A huge amount of by-product of the Panchagarh Sugar Mills such
as molasses and sugarcane coir is wasting. Molasses could be used
as raw materials in distilleries to make alcohol and spirits and
the coir in the paper mills of the country. The Panchagarh mill
produces some eight to 10 lakh tonnes of coir a year, said Yasin
Ali, a sugarcane expert and former principal of the Haji Danesh
Agricultural College, Dinajpur.
	   But the North Bengal Paper Mills at Paksey requires only 80,000
tonnes of coir per year, he further said. Mahbubul Alam, Thakurgaon
Sugar Mills general manager, said the total demand for alcohol and
spirits in the country is 11,000 barrels a year while the sugar
mills produces about 100,000 tonnes of molasses annually.
	   With one in Panchagarh, as many as five distilleries are there
in the country and all these could produce 50,000 barrels of
alcohol from about 50,000 tonnes of molasses a year, Alam added.The
state-owned Carew and Company Ltd is currently working to only 40
per cent of its capacity. But a huge quantity of molasses is lying
waste in the sugar mills which could be used in alcohol-making.
	   The Panchagarh mill general manager Mirza Azim said, most sugar
mills in the country are selling molasses at throwaway prices. If
the distilleries are allowed to export some of their products, they
can well use the excess molasses lying with the sugar mills to
produce more alcohol, Azim added.
	   
</TEXT>
