<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-World Cup-Tickets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thousands of World Cup tickets still undelivered in Japan
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo TOK103 &QL; 
 &UR; By MARI YAMAGUCHI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The planes are booked, the hotel rooms reserved,
and thousands of Japanese soccer fans are getting ready to cheer on
their national team in its World Cup debut this Sunday in France.
	   The only problem? Most of the tickets haven't arrived.
	   And Japan's tour operators are panicking.
	   Of the 14,700 tickets ordered for Japan's opening match Sunday
against Argentina, only 2,200 have been delivered, Jun Ishiyama,
spokesman for the Japan Association of Travel Agents, said
Wednesday at a news conference.
	   The 13 travel agencies who attended the news conference said
they may be forced to cancel tours because time is running out.
	   Some of the tour operators even admitted they have considered
using the black market to acquire missing tickets.
	   ``I can't believe this,'' said Shigeki Murayama, managing
director of Nippon Travel Agency Co. ``We have organized many tours
in the past for variety of sports events, including Olympics, but a
problem like this has never happened.''
	   The tour agents have already paid ticket fees to the World Cup's
official organizing agents, and they had been ordered through
authorized vendors, Murayama said.
	   The tickets had been promised by mid-May, he said.
	   While apologizing to their customers, tour agency officials
placed the blame squarely with the French World Cup organizers.
	   ``Delay in ticketing by the World Cup organizers has caused the
trouble,'' said Tsutomu Igarashi of Japan Travel Bureau.
	   It was not immediately clear whether it was only Japanese tour
groups that were having the ticket problem.
	   Earlier in the day, JATA protested to the French department of
tourism, as well as the French Embassy in Tokyo, demanding an
investigation and explanation of what was causing the delay.
	   JATA's Ishiyama said the association is currently conducting a
survey of Japanese travel agencies who are organizing World Cup
tours, and will also send a written protest to the World Cup
organizers.
	   Japanese tour agents said they have not received a clear
explanation or apology from the event's officials.
	   Tour agency officials declined to disclose how many tickets had
been delivered for Japan's two remaining first round games.
	   But they said canceling tours for the first game alone would
cost them an enormous amount, especially for those who are flying
chartered flights to Paris.
	   The Japanese team, making its first ever World Cup finals debut
in the nation's soccer history, will play against Argentina on
Sunday in Toulouse, Croatia on June 20 in Nantes and Jamaica on
June 26 in Lyons.
 &UR; (may-js)
</TEXT>
