<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-South Korea-Injuries,0391 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Key midfielder Choi injures ankle, further damages South
</HEADLINE>
Korean bid &QL; 
 &UR; With Sports-Soccer-South Korea &QL; 
 &UR; By ERICA BULMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ South Korea's campaign to win its first match in
five World Cup appearances has suffered yet another blow as one of
its key midfielders, Choi Sung-yong, injured his ankle. He may have
to miss the team's first match against Mexico this week.
	   It is the second blow in less than a week for the South Korean
squad, which saw its star striker Hwang Sun-hong hurt his left knee
last Thursday during a 1-1 draw with China.
	   Hwang will not play in the team's opening match against Mexico
on June 13 in Lyon, and it is unlikely Choi will either, team coach
Cha Bum-kun said after a training session Wednesday.
	   ``We have two injured players now,'' said Cha. ``Choi's ankle
will probably keep him out of the first match, it is difficult to
say. Maybe he can play the second game.''
	   Choi, who twisted his right ankle in Tuesday's closed training
session, was forced to miss Wednesday's practice, instead doing
fitness training in a nearby gym. Hwang, however, was present on
the field, doing stretching exercises and jogging lightly around
the field.
	   Though the team's line-up has taken a few punches, Cha refuses
to let the situation dampen the team's spirit.
	   ``We are missing two players right now but the rest of the
team's condition is improving,'' said Cha, a former international
who led South Korea to the World Cup in Mexico in 1986. ``So there
is no problem right now.''
	   ``The team is at 80 percent of its top condition and after this
afternoon and tomorrow's training it should be at about 95 percent
of its top form,'' Cha said.
	   Though the South Koreans usually play in 4-4-2 configuration,
the absence of Hwang will probably force Cha to go for a 3-6-1
setup. He used that formation with relative success in a 2-1 loss
to Brazil in a friendly last August and its 2-1 qualifying victory
over Japan in Tokyo last September.
	   Cha will likely play South Korea's top-scorer Choi Yong-su up
front and place heavy emphasis on the midfield in an effort to
strangle opposition attacks. The team's only hope of scoring in
such a case would be on a break.
</TEXT>
