<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Censorship </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Turkish police storm pro-Kurdish paper, censor edition
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) _ Police seized hundreds of copies of a
pro-Kurdish newspaper for printing statements by a Kurdish rebel
leader, the paper said Wednesday.
	   Istanbul-based Ulkede Gundem was censored late Monday night
after printing a report in which rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan
called on village guards to stop fighting.
	   About 90,000 village guards have been recruited by the
government to fight Kurdish rebels in the southeast.
	   A later edition was distributed without the report on Tuesday.
	   In Wednesday's edition, the paper said it was seriously
concerned by increasing state pressure on the daily's editorial
policy.
	   Prosecutors were not available for comment.
	   The police often confiscate copies of the paper on charges of
separatist propaganda. Last month, an appeals court imposed a
10-day ban on the daily for publishing an article advocating
Kurdish separatism.
	   Ocalan's Kurdistan Workers Party has been waging a guerrilla war
for autonomy in Turkey's southeast since 1984. The war has claimed
some 37,000 lives.
	   (ht-sh/djw)	   
</TEXT>
