<BODY>
<SLUG> HEATWAVE-MAKES-LIFE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Heatwave makes life miserable in Rajshahi, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Heatwave makes life miserable in Rajshahi, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Heatwave that has been sweeping through the divisional town and
its adjoining areas for the last one week has made the life of the
people miserable. Local meteorological office sources said, the
highest temperature recorded in Rajshahi was 40.1 degrees Celsius
on Monday while the lowest was 29.5 degrees. During the past week
the highest and the lowest temperature were 38 degrees and 29
degrees on an average respectively.
	   The difference between the highest and the lowest temperature
being minimum, the people are suffering from persistent heatwave.
The heatwave has caused a number of problems for the people
including profuse sweating and turning the colour of urine yellow .
Aged people and children are the worst sufferers. Blisters have
been noticed on the bodies of school children. Most of the schools
have withdrawn their ``follow in parade'' due to sizzling heat. At
least 25 people have been reported to be killed in heat-related
complications in the district during the last seven days.
	   Rajshahi Medical College Hospital sources said, the patients
with high pressure, diarrhoea, influenza and tonsilitis are being
admitted in increasing numbers in the hospital. The roads of the
city turn deserted after 12 noon. The businessmen of the city are
almost sitting idle in their shops in absence of customers . Due to
broiling heat people do not come out of their homes to buy things
of their choice except in emergency cases.
	   On the other hand frequent power disruption has added to the
suffering of the people . Supply of water in the city areas has
also disrupted due to sweltering heat and loadshedding. In many
parts of the city the hand-driven tubewells have become inoperative
due to sharp fall in the level of underground water intensifying
the suffering of the city people.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
