<SLUG> BC-Vietnam-Australia-New Ambassador </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former TV executive named new Australian envoy to Vietnam
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) _ A former television executive has been
named Australia's new ambassador to Vietnam, the Australian Foreign
Ministry said Wednesday.
	   Michael Mann will replace Susan Boyd, who took up her posting as
Australia's envoy to Vietnam in October 1994. Boyd, who earned a
reputation for being outspoken and witty, will be posted to Hong
Kong.
	   Mann worked from 1994-1997 as chief executive of Australia
Television under the state-owned Australian Broadcasting
Corporation, and continued in that position after the network was
taken over by Channel Seven.
	   Before his broadcast work, he served as a diplomat in Osaka,
Phnom Penh, Rome, Beijing and Bali, having joined what was then
called the Department of External Affairs in 1966.
	   In February 1998 he resumed his diplomatic career by rejoining
what is now called the Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade.
	   His appointment coincides with the 25th anniversary of the start
of bilateral relations between Australia and Vietnam. Australia is
the 12th largest foreign investor in Vietnam, with projects valued
at dlrs 800 million.
	   Bilateral trade in 1997 amounted to dlrs 823 million, up from
less than dlrs 2 million in 1982.
</TEXT>
