<SLUG> WEAK-YEN-'HURTING' sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Weak yen `hurting' mainland, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Weak yen `hurting' mainland, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Patricia Lee and Fong Tak-hoASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   CHINA'S central bank governor yesterday warned the current
weakness of the Japanese yen was severely hurting the mainland's
external trade, but pledged to keep the renminbi stable.
	   ``The depreciation of the Japanese yen is having a very negative
impact on Chinese imports and exports and the utilisation of
foreign capital,'' People's Bank of China (PBOC) governor Dai
Xianglong said. ``The depreciation of the yen will also cause more
pressure on China's economic structural reforms and adjustments.''
The US dollar briefly climbed above 141 yen for the first time in
seven years before easing in late trade.
	   Mr Dai urged the Japanese government to take stronger measures
to stem the drop of the yen and prevent further regional
instability.
	   ``I believe the depreciation of the Japanese yen is not
conducive to the stability of the East Asian countries. It has also
exerted pressure on China. However, the exchange rate of the yuan
will continue to be stable,'' he said.
	   On Monday, currency dealers warned that the drop in the yen had
put more pressure on the yuan in ``grey-market'' forward trading.
Economists said the falling yen could have wide-ranging
repercussions for the mainland economy.
	   Wang Zhen-quan, an economist with a Hong Kong research
institute, said the falling yen would hurt the mainland's export
trade and cut direct foreign investment into the country.
	   About 60 per cent of mainland exports in Asia go to Japan.
	   However, DBS Securities economist S W Chu did not think the
weakening yen would cause immediate pressure on the yuan.
	   ``China's central bank is cash-rich and it can intervene in the
market if necessary,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
