</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Herzog-Jews </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Jewish group honors German president for reconciliation efforts
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BERLIN (AP) _ Germany's Jewish community awarded President Roman
Herzog the Leo Baeck Prize Wednesday for his efforts in building
understanding among Germans, Jews and other groups.
	   Ignatz Bubis, chairman of Germany's Central Council of Jews,
which awards the prize, said Herzog had taken every possibility in
speeches to note Nazi atrocities so that they are not forgotten.
	   Bubis cited Herzog's ``deeply humanitarian convictions'' and
said the president has made clear how ``strongly he has taken to
heart the coexistence of different cultures and religions.''
	   Polish President Aleksander Kwasniewski, who attended the Berlin
award ceremony, lauded Herzog for ``breaking the last ice'' in
reconciliation with Poland when he asked the Polish people for
forgiveness during 50th anniversary ceremonies marking the Warsaw
uprising against the Nazis in 1994.
	   Herzog said Germany had suffered a terrible loss when it tried
to wipe out Jewish culture during the Nazi period. He also called
for more tolerance in Germany today, especially toward foreigners,
and welcomed a revival in Germany's Jewish community.
	   ``Openness for a better future should rule our thoughts and
dealings, not defending against supposed foreigners or unknowns,''
he said.
	   The Leo Baeck prize is named after the rabbi of the same name
who was the top Jewish representative in Germany during the Nazi
era. It has been awarded annually since his death in 1956 to people
who helped build warmer relations between Germans and Jews.
	   Baeck was deported to the Nazi concentration camp Theresienstadt
in what is now the Czech Republic in 1943. He survived the ordeal,
lived in London after the war and taught for a while at the Hebrew
Union College in Cincinnati, Ohio, while working to restore
understanding between the Jews and Germans.
	   (gb-im)
</TEXT>
