<SLUG> BC-Iran-Interior Minister,0372 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lawmakers call for impeachment of Iran's interior minister
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By AFSHIN VALINEJAD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ Hard-line lawmakers on Wednesday demanded
the impeachment of Iran's liberal interior minister, accusing him
of jeopardizing the Islamic nation's stability.
	   The impeachment motion was the latest attack by conservative
members of Iran's ruling clergy on officials loyal to reformist
President Mohammad Khatami, who took power last August.
	   Thirty-one members of Iran's Majlis, or parliament, signed the
motion urging that Interior Minister Abdollah Nouri be impeached
for, among other things, allowing a rally last month to protest the
influence of the hard-line clergy in Iran.
	   After Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri read out the motion, Khatami
rose to his minister's defense, calling him ``our capable brother,
an outstanding personality of the revolution and the system.''
	   The motion accuses Nouri of ``creating tension in the society,
making provocative interviews and speeches in different provinces
and appointing inexperienced people to managerial posts at the
ministry.'''
	   His ``continuation in the post is detrimental to tranquility and
stability in the country,'' the lawmakers said, according to the
official Islamic Republic News Agency.
	   In the past few weeks, hard-liners have described Nouri as
incompetent and called for his resignation.
	   In the letter, the deputies protested the minister's open
support for Tehran Mayor Gholamhossein Karbaschi, who was arrested
in April on corruption charges.
	   Nouri has 10 days to appear before Parliament, where hard-liners
hold a slight majority, and respond to the accusations in the
impeachment motion, which will then be put to the 270-member body
for a vote.
	   Khatami's landslide victory in May 1997 shook the foundations of
Iran's clerical rule and was considered a triumph for civil
liberties in this Islamic republic.
	   Khatami still struggles, however, with hard-line opponents who
accuse him of betraying the 1979 Islamic revolution led by the late
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
	   Ali Khamenei, who succeeded Khomeini, remains Iran's powerful
spiritual leader. 	   
</TEXT>
