<HEADLINE>
Compact, mini discs just right for Tonic, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Compact, mini discs just right for Tonic, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Teresa LeeASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ELECTRONIC products maker Tonic Industries Holdings expects 10
per cent growth for 1998 despite the economic crisis.
	   Executive director Au Wai-man yesterday said total orders
received this year are expected to see a 40-50 per cent increase,
thanks to the rising popularity of portable compact discs (CDs) and
related products.
	   The substantial increase in orders has been boosted by
favourable conditions in the US market as well as increased demand
from Europe.
	   ``With the popularity of portable CDs and mini- disc products,
product prices are expected to see a 5 per cent drop in general
this year compared to last year,'' Mr Au said.
	   Tonic's new mini-disc products will begin production and be
launched later this year.
	   The ``MD mini HiFi'' systems will be sold at US$150 (HK$1170) to
US$200 and account for less than 10 per cent of total turnover.
	   Profit margin will be maintained at 20 per cent.
	   The effect of the plunge of the yen on the company is still
unclear and will be seen in the next month or two, he said.
	   
</TEXT>
