<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Spain-Zubizarreta,0345 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Spanish veteran Zubi says he may not be finished yet
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CIARAN GILES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CHANTILLY, Spain (AP) _ Just three weeks after his retirement
was announced, 36-year-old Spanish keeper Andoni Zubizarreta
surprised many Wednesday by saying he may not be finished yet.
	   ``I said I was finished with Valencia and the Spanish league,
but nothing else,'' said Zubizarreta at the Spanish team base north
of Paris. ``Who can talk about retirement when you're just about to
take part in a World Cup?''
	   On May 16, the media in Spain took Zubizarreta's comments that
``his batteries were running out'' and that he had played his final
league game to be the confirmation of months of rumors that the
veteran keeper was hanging up his boots.
	   ``Playing all your life, who wouldn't want to continue
playing,'' he said, adding with a smile: ``Working is the difficult
part.''
	   ``Right now I have absolutely no offers, besides to stay on at
Valencia or work for the (Spanish) federation,'' the Basque keeper
said. ``You never know what happens in life. I never close the
door. What I'll do after July 12, the truth is I don't know.''
	   Zubizarreta has been Spanish coach Javier Clemente's preferred
keeper since he took over the team in 1992. A fellow Basque,
Clemente has regularly had to fend off criticisms that Zubizarreta
was finished.
	   ``Zubi is number one. He works a lot harder than many younger
players,'' Clemente said of him prior to coming to France. ``It's
about time Spaniards were appreciated in the same way as foreign
stars are.''
	   Zubizarreta has 124 caps for Spain and has allowed in 96 goals
since he first appeared for the side in 1985.
	   In domestic league play he has manned the posts for 622 first
division games with Athletic de Bilbao, FC Barcelona and, most
recently, Valencia.
	   Asked how he felt about playing a fourth World Cup, he said:
``More excited because you know what's to be won.''
	   (cg-sl)
</TEXT>
