<SLUG> THE-PERIPATETIC sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
The peripatetic literary personality, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
The peripatetic literary personality, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Mahbub Husain KhanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Seventeen years ago V.S. Naipaul undertook a journey through
Indonesia, lran, Pakistan and Malaysia, which formed the basis of
perhaps his most significant travel book, among the believers .
Much has happened in these lands since then, politically and
economically, including the bloodbath of the Iran-Iraq War. All
this tempted Naipaul back for a second set of journeys (from
1995-1997) of which his latest book, Beyond Belief: Islamic
Excursions Among the Converted Peoples, is the fruit. Back in 1971
Naipaul had said, ``When I speak about being an exile or a refugee
l'm not just using a metaphor, l'm speaking literally''.
	   In that year he had lived in Wiltshire, the West lndies, South
America, and New Zealand. I met him on a flight from Rome to
Bombay, a journey that produced his second book on India -- India:
A Million Mutinies Now. When one considers his movements over the
past 48 years after he left Port- of- Spain in 1950, his life has
been a series of onward bookings-- or, speaking literally and
figuratively, flights. Vidiadhar Surajprasad Naipaul was born in
the country town of Chaguanas in Trinidad in 1932, of a family
originating in Uttar Pradesh in India. At the age of seven he was
taken to Port-of-Spain to live, and there he received his early
education. One guesses that his upbringing was very similar to
Anand's (Biswas's son ) in A House for Mr. Biswas.
	   ln 1950 he joined University College, Oxford . Naipaul's first
novel was The Mystic Masseur published in 1957, at his age of 25.
Then one of his masterpieces A House for Mr. Biswas, at the age of
29. Mr. Stone at 30, An Area of Darkness at 32, The Mimic Men at
35. The Times described him as `` the youngest of the W.H. Smith
Award winners, and a quarter of a century light of the average.''
If Naipaul had a country he would have made a useful diplomat for
difficult postings . He has travelled to the interiors of India and
Africa and South America, and crossed North America; he has
reported on them. And he has travelled the Islamic world resulting
in two of his books.
	   He speaks French well and Spanish, though his Hindi is tentative
as I found on the flight to Bombay.He has had more home addresses
than any author that I know of. Once Naipaul had a house in
Stockwell. It was in a poor condition when he bought it, but he
renovated and redecorated it. Then he went to Africa. less than two
years after returning from Africa he sold the house, moved into a
hotel, then into a friend's house, and finally went to California.
It makes moving for him something like the colonial ideal on a
small scale, setting a place on its feet and then withdrawing from
it. The Srinagar Hotel Liward where Naipaul was a guest (he gives
it a chapter of An Area of Darkness), actually improves with his
residence, as he puts idling employees to work, reminding them of
their duties, encouraging them in their skills.
	   I find that it is as a travel writer that Naipaul performs best,
though his A House for Mr. Biswas was really a masterpiece. His
eye, attentive for the smallest detail, can give an apparently
common landscape or unremarkable physique many features. Hence his
books dealing in or originating from his travels are such
remarkably good reads. A few years ago, Naipaul made a statement --
much ridiculed at the time--to the effect that the novel had died
as a viable literary form, and that the future lay with non-fiction
narrative. To an extent, his latest book Beyond Belief vindicates
that claim of his . The designation Writer in his passport ( a
British passport but no more an indicator of his nationality than
Joseph Conrad's was) describes him perfectly . He has never been
anything but a writer.
	   As he says: `` I have never had to work for hire; I made a vow
at an early age never to wotk, never to become involved in people
in that way. That has given me a freedom from people, from
entanglements, from rivalries, from competition . I have no
enemies, no rivals, no masters ; I fear no one.'' I wish many of us
could say the same.
	   
</TEXT>
