<HEADLINE>
Chamber may ask Beijing help on wages and rents, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Chamber may ask Beijing help on wages and rents, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Cyrus LiASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A MISSION from the influential Hong Kong General Chamber of
Commerce will leave today for a three-day visit to Beijing to
assess mainland economic policies that could affect the SAR.
	   The chamber was also considering whether to lobby for controls
on wage increases and rents to boost Hong Kong's competitiveness.
	   And it wants bank to reduce the interest rate to help Hong
Kong's small and medium-sized enterprises.
	   The Beijing mission, which is being led by chairman Peter Sutch,
is the chamber's first since last year's change of sovereignty.
	   ``We want to hear from senior officials China's economic
policies as they affect Hong Kong,'' said chamber director Eden
Woon.
	   C C Tung, brother of Hong Kong Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa,
will be one of the delegation's two deputy leaders.
	   Addressing the Lions Club of Tai Ping Shan yesterday, Mr Woon
said Hong Kong was going through a period of adjustment as a result
of the crisis. That warranted controls on wages and rents, he said.
	   Mr Woon said some international firms were reconsidering setting
up headquarters in Hong Kong because of the drop in property
prices.
	   The chamber is also backing the Hong Kong dollar peg to the US
currency, believing it would stabilise the economy and give foreign
investors confidence.
	   Mr Woon also said that the chamber expected the US Congress to
renew the mainland's most-favoured nation status, which was
important for the local economy.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
