<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup-Brit Fever </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup fever rises in Britain
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JOHN PYE &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Even before a ball was kicked Wednesday, the World
Cup was the undisputed No. 1 item on just about every British
agenda from the House of Commons in London to the Loch Ness Pub _
in Brazil.
	   With the World Cup expected to be telecast to 37 billion viewers
over the next month, Britain is clearly gripped with soccer ever.
	   The morning's front-page headlines were dominated by reports of
a riot on the Champs Elysees and a brawl between one-time England
World Cup hopeful Stan Collymore and celebrity girlfriend Ulrika
Jonsson in a Scottish pub in Paris.
	   The opening World Cup match later in the day between Scotoland
and Brazil also took precedence over matters of state in the
Commons.
	   Prime Minster Tony Blair told the chamber he hoped to ``keep an
eye on'' the game.
	   ``I'm sure the whole House joins me in wishing the Scottish and
English teams the best of luck in the World Cup,'' he said to
cheers from members of both parties.
	   The World Cup won an early mention in the Commons as Labor MP
Jim Fitzpatrick managed to squeeze a good luck message for Scotland
into a debate on housing reform.
	   His good cheer prompted a politically incorrect retort by his
colleague, Karen Buck, who suggested that all men in politics would
have only one thing on their minds for the next month.
	   Scots living in London, wearing the blue Scotland football
shirts and draped in national flags, started booking their places
early at the bars and ordering drinks in time for the kick-off.
	   Meanwhile, exiled Scots in Brazil gathered at Rio de Janeiro's
own Loch Ness pub for the long-awaited opening game.
	   The kilt-clad fans felt at home among familiar surroundings of
draped Scottish flags, posters and blue and white soccer balls.
Chef Walbercy Valentim said the menu would include some traditional
fare but definitely no haggis.
	   Back in Britain, even the Salvation Army's newspaper, The War
Cry, got in on the World Cup act, producing the front page headline
``Hod's Squad'' _ referring to England coach Glenn Hoddle's side.
	   The back page remained soccer free but the front page was
devoted to the England team, likening the squad to the final 12
apostles chosen by Jesus.
	   The War Cry editor Captain Charles King said every week he
focused on whatever people were talking about and clearly this week
it was the World Cup.
	   In Glasgow, the World Cup caused a mass exodus from work places
as hordes of people converged on the city center before kick-off.
Others made straight for the nearest pubs to claim a vantage point
in front of TV screens beaming the game from Paris.
	   Chancellor Gordon Brown, a Scotsman, ensured the government was
represented officially at the game, travelling at his own expense
to take advantage of a ticket offered by French Finance Minister
Dominique Strauss-Kahn.
	   Brown joked that Ms. Strauss-Kahn had threatened to hand the
ticket to Brazil's Finance Minister if he did not take it up.
	   Soccer fans who were stuck at Heathrow Airport, away from a more
preferred viewing venue, got a sneak glimpse of the World Cup and
the future of television.
	   In the first public demonstration of digital TV, passengers were
able to watch the tournament kick-off on special wide-screen
televisions at the airport.
	   However, not everybody was happy about the British public's
obsession with the World Cup.
	   Leading economist Maurice Fitzpatrick, of accountancy firm
Chantrey Vellacott, said businesses stood to lose out this month
because of workers leaving their posts to watch soccer.
	   He estimated the World Cup could cost bosses more than 1 billion
pounds (dlrs 1.64 billion), as the economy sacrificed one-third of
day's output over the month.
	   Fitzpatrick said that figure could increase drastically if
England and Scotland go through to the second round.
	   The music industry was also caught up in a World Cup it can't
ignore.
	   World Cup songs could score a hat-trick at the top of the charts
in Europe _ and Three Lions '98 is leading the field.
	   The Baddiel, Skinner and Lightning Seeds song sold 98,000 copies
during the first two days of sales, 20,000 more than its closest
rival Vindaloo by Fat Les.
	   And predictions are that Dario G's Carnaval De Paris _ based on
a European terrace chant _ will enter the charts at No. 3 on
Sunday.
	   (jp/sw) 	   
</TEXT>
