<SLUG> BC-Britain-Mad Cow Reax, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
British cattle farmers relieved `mad cow' nightmare may be ending
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs version; LEADS with additional quotes, information about
prices, EDITS to tighten &QL; 
 &UR; By DIRK BEVERIDGE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Business Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ After two years of devastation that seemed like a
bad dream, British cattlemen finally got word Wednesday that the
``mad cow'' nightmare could be ending.
	   From livestock auctions to cattle farms, Britain's beef industry
cautiously applauded the announcement that European regulators want
to lift an export ban.
	   But the ban wasn't immediately repealed, and the optimism in
Britain's cattle country was tempered by recognition that the
battered market has no chance of bouncing back instantly.
	   ``There's no real reason to throw your hat in the air,'' said
Paul Gentry, who auctions cattle in Newark, about 120 miles (192
miles) north of London. ``This is good news, but whether it
materializes, your guess is as good as mine.''
	   Prices for live cattle at Gentry's lot are as much as 50 percent
lower than before the European Union banned all exports of British
beef.
	   A likely end to the ban improved the mood among farmers selling
livestock at Gentry's auction on Wednesday morning, but did nothing
for prices.
	   ``You can't believe it's gone on so long and cost so much
money,'' Gentry said.
	   Still, the prospect of an end to the crisis was just what
everybody in the industry has been waiting for.
	   ``It'll take the gloom out of the market,'' said David Williams,
who runs the Williams Wholesale slaughterhouse in tiny Woebley,
western England. ``It'll be a great morale booster for the whole
industry.''
	   Williams' wife, Sheila, alluded to more blows that the beef
dealers have suffered _ including the Labor government's ban of all
beef on the bone in Britain, based on the minuscule possibility
that T-bones or prime rib could give humans the incurable brain
ailment caused by the mad cows.
	   ``Is that bone-in, or bone-out?'' Mrs. Williams asked as the
European Commission recommended that British farmers be allowed to
export beef and most products from animals older than six months
and younger than 30 months.
	   Actually, the bones will have to be out.
	   The British farmers have bitterly complained that they make some
of the world's best beef but have seen the product unfairly
tarnished by British government bumbling and European politics.
Some consumers remain scared to eat British beef, and many
restaurants in Britain advertise non-British beef on their menus.
	   The crisis exploded in March 1996 when Britain acknowledged a
link between cattle with bovine spongiform encephalopathy, or BSE,
and the fatal human brain ailment Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease.
	   European Union veterinary experts still must study Wednesday's
recommendation on lifting the export ban, and it could be put to a
vote of agriculture commissioners from the 15 EU nations.
	   ``We've now turned the corner and we're in the home straight,''
said Ben Gill, president of the National Farmers Union. ``The
momentum must not be lost. We are confident that the huge weight
which has burdened the farming community for more than two years
will soon be removed.''
	   (db-kg)
</TEXT>
