<SLUG> UNRESTRICTED-MOVEMENT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Unrestricted movement of visitors spoiling Mainamati, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Unrestricted movement of visitors spoiling Mainamati, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Subrata Kumar DasASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The glorious history of Mainamati is the pride of the nation. A
nation is known not only by its present activities but its previous
achievements dignify its identity. All the archaeological
discoveries of our country occurred in the present century. The
excavations expose the ruins of Mahasthan, Paharpur and Mainamati.
Our knowledge of the works of Jnan Atish Dipankar, one of the great
preachers of Buddhism throughout the whole of South East Asia or of
Mahasthabir Shilbhadra, one of the greatest scholars of his time
and Acharya (head) of Nalanda Viswavidyalaya, have been possible
only due the large-scale excavations. Mainamati of Comilla is
famous for Buddhist cultural heritage. The culmination of Buddhist
civilisation that took place from eighth century to the 12th
century occurred here. But evidence of this was hidden under earth
till the Second World War.
	   During the war, the existence of this civilization was first
noticed. Some five miles away from Comilla town, Shalban Vihar and
other fragments of the culture are found. The name Shalban' was
derived from the name of a nearby village Shalbanpur. The large
Vihar, 550ft. X 550ft. in area has a wall of 16.5ft. A total of 115
rooms having an area of 12ft. X 12ft. each have been identified
which are set surrounding the whole area.Everyday thousands of
visitors come to Mainamati to have a glimpse of the past. They
wander here and there destroying the brick-pieces. This may lead to
the quick destruction of the excavated sites. Couldn't we impose
any restriction on roaming of the visitors? No one, except the
staff and historians who will be allowed there with prior
permission, should have the right to walk on the brick-made places.
All walking should be on the ground only.
	   If possible, an over-bridge over the hall-room can be set up so
that the visitors can have a glance from above. This sorry state of
affairs is not only at the Shalban Vihar. Since we are failing to
protect these historical ruins, it would have possibly been
betterif we had not excavatedthem.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
