r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  MFN-STATUS-VITAL-TO-HKsk     06-10 0413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> MFN-STATUS-VITAL-TO-HK sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MFN status vital to HK, says Chan, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
MFN status vital to HK, says Chan, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   CHIEF Secretary for Administration Anson Chan yesterday warned
the non-renewal of China's Most Favoured Nation (MFN) trading
status with the United States would undermine the SAR's capability
to act as a ``fire wall'' to prevent the Asian financial crisis
from spreading globally.
	   Mrs Chan made the remark in the annual dinner of the Hong Kong
Trade Development Council at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel in New York.
	   She said Hong Kong would suffer if the MFN status was revoked.
``There would be a loss of income up to US$4.5 billion (HK$35
billion) and around 61,000 to 87,000 jobs. This would not only deal
a devastating blow to business confidence in Hong Kong when we are
grappling with the fallout from the regional turmoil.
	   ``It would also undermine our ability to continue to play the
role of a fire wall in the Asian financial crisis.'' She pointed
out that continued US investment and trade in the region were of
utmost importance to the revitalisation of the hard-hit Asian
economies.
	   ``We strongly believe that a successful Hong Kong will
contribute to the success of China.
	   ``A successful China will contribute to the success of Asia. And
a successful Asia, fortified by the lessons learned from recent
adversity, will resume its role as a catalyst for growth of the
global economy.'' Despite the current difficulties, she believed
Hong Kong's economic prospects for the longer term remain good.
	   ``This is underpinned in particular by sustained high economic
growth and further reform and opening up in the mainland of China
and, of course, the continued buoyancy of the US economy.'' She
added a soft landing of property prices and rentals will help
contain the cost of doing business in Hong Kong and improve the
SAR's competitiveness.
	   
</TEXT>
