<BODY>
<SLUG> VINITA'S-QUEST sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Vinita's quest for an Arcadia in the desert of mechanised world, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Vinita's quest for an Arcadia in the desert of mechanised world, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Kazi Mostaque AhmedASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Peace, joy, happiness, calm joviality and serenity are the
effect one experiences in the desert of this mechanised world, when
one looks at the rich array of 41 paintings of Shahla Vinita Karim,
put on show at the city's Drik Gallery from 4 June to 10 June.
These works of oil and mixed media done within only five months
with strenuous effort have become the second solo of the artist in
Bangladesh - the first one being in 1995 at the La Galerie. At the
previous exhibition in Bangladesh, Vinita put only water-colour
paintings.Born in Yangon, Myanmar, the artist moved from place to
place, country to country for the sake of her life and art. She had
her education in Fine Arts Studies at Gerlesborg Art School, at
Stockholm, Sweeden in 1981 and joined two art workshops - the first
one under guidance of SOLANKI, International Women's Association'
in Chennai, India in 1996 and the second one under Shahabuddin
Ahmed at Bangladesh Shilpakala Academy this year.
	   Besides the two in Bangladesh, she had five more solo
exhibitions in Switzerland. She also participated in four group
exhibitions.Presently a free-lance artist, Vinita has also many
private and institutional collections in Dhaka and Chittagong in
Bangladesh; in Nuremberg and Munich in Germany; Stolkholm and
Gothenberg in Sweden; Colorado, Los Angeles and Detroit in the USA;
Berne, Murten, Geneva and Zurich in Switzerland; and Delhi, Chennai
and Mumbai in India.An artist expresses his or her self through
images - whatever be the medium he or she works in - words, sounds
or colours, and the world is so full of objects. Choosing the right
objects, interpreting them and putting them into harmonious ways to
express his or her thoughts and feelings make one artist superior
to another. Vinita can choose objects, manipulate them in a
masterly way with her brush using strong colours of her choice
until a thought-provoking and finished work is produced.
	   Take, for example, her Quest For An Arcadia where she lodges
herself in a jovial yet serene mood with rich and vibrant colours,
but very subtle and gentle in expression of abstract and
semi-abstract figures, to live in a world of Arcadian fantasy from
this strife-torn cruel world. She finds peace and happiness in her
works - in the objects she chooses, in the atmosphere she creates,
not like an escapist but as her spontaneous and genial self finds
her true abode there.Boat as a symbol of journey predominantly
recurs in a number of her works. Drawing a composition, to Vinita,
is like a journey into the inner self. ``Painting objective and
abstract compositions is more like a continuous dialogue with her
own inner self - it is the mood, the feeling that ultimately
decides the shape of her composition; but the effects are
nevertheless equally thought provoking,'' says Syed Monzoorul Islam
about the process of making of Vinita's art.''Life is a mystery and
a journey,'' she remarked.
	   The boat symbol thus appears to be very apt as far journey
through this mysterious life and exploration of her true self on
the canvas are concerned. She has an Infinite Attraction for life,
for its Radiant Beauty, for its Rhythmic Movement, for its Golden
Harvest - she enjoys all the positives life can offer. She is not a
blind but a true optimist.Vinita also celebrates nature - water,
birds, flowers, plants, sunshine, moonlight, etc. ``Nature is the
source of everything, she is the kind mother earth for all,'' she
said. Interplay of light and darkness and the mysterious night
appear to her with meanings. Her objective work Nocturnal Verses
with a full-blown lily and a bud growing from the core of the night
and abstract ones Nocturnal Mystery - 1, 2 suggestive of riddles
and mysteries involved with night are among the many works that
speak of her calm and cool seeing eyes.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
