<SLUG> BC-Israel-Teen Killing, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Prosecutor: accused teen claiming Israeli citizenship `cynical
</HEADLINE>
exploitation'
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS byline &QL; 
 &UR; By VITA BEKKER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ An Israeli prosecutor argued Wednesday that it
would be ``cynical exploitation'' of Israel's citizenship laws to
allow a U.S. teen-ager charged in a grisly murder in Maryland to
take refuge from American justice by claiming Israeli citizenship.
	   The prosecution wrapped up its case in favor of extraditing
17-year-old Samuel Sheinbein on Wednesday; the defense is scheduled
to present its final arguments in Jerusalem District Court on July
9. No date has been set for a decision.
	   Sheinbein is charged in Montgomery County, Maryland, with
killing 19-year-old Alfred Tello Jr. last September. He fled to
Israel after the murder and is claiming Israeli citizenship in an
attempt to prevent his extradition. Israeli law bars citizens from
being sent abroad to stand trial.
	   Israeli prosecutor Irit Kaan said Wednesday that allowing
Sheinbein to take refuge in Israel would be a ``cynical
exploitation'' of Israel's citizenship laws.
	   Sheinbein ``has no link to the state of Israel and is only using
the state as a means of escaping from the country in which he
committed the crime,'' she told the court.
	   Sheinbein's lawyers argue that his father, Sol, is an Israeli
citizen, and that the status was automatically passed on to him.
	   But Israel says that Sheinbein's father lost his citizenship
because he moved his family to the United States in 1950, before
the country's citizenship law went into effect several years later.
	   ``It's obvious that the Sheinbein family had transferred the
center of its life to the United States before the decisive date,''
Kaan said.
	   Sheinbein, who had never lived in Israel and never held an
Israeli passport, ``never saw himself as an Israeli citizen,'' she
said.
	   Sheinbein's lawyer, former justice minister David Libai, said
only, ``If the father is not an Israeli citizen, then the Interior
Ministry should take away his Israeli citizenship.''
	   Another teenager charged in the murder, 18-year-old Aaron
Needle, hanged himself in his Maryland cell in April.
	   vb-hla
</TEXT>
