<BODY>
<SLUG> CALL-TO-PROTECT-HOME sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Call to protect stay-home workers, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Call to protect stay-home workers, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Lucia Palpal-latocASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THERE should be laws to protect workers from unreasonable
dismissal and wage deductions when they stay home during a black
rainstorm warning, a union leader said.
	   Confederation of Trade Unions chief executive Elizabeth Tang
Yin-ngor said thousands of people went to work yesterday despite
the storm warning.
	   ``The workers are worried either of losing their jobs or getting
wage deductions so they decided to go to work,'' she said.
	   Hundreds of worried workers flooded the hotlines of the Labour
Department and offices of local trade unions with queries.
	   The department said employers and employees should reach an
agreement without delay on work arrangements during bad weather.
	   ``Employers are strongly advised to adopt a flexible approach in
drawing up work arrangements during inclement weather,'' a
spokesman said.
	   ``Due consideration should be given to employees' safety in the
workplace as well as their journey to and from work.'' The
department's code of practice for typhoons and rainstorms states
that employees injured in a work-related accident during a storm
are entitled to compensation.
	   The same rule applies to civil servants.
	   But Ms Tang said existing laws were inadequate to protect
workers unable to go to work during heavy rain or natural
calamities.
	   She said a pre-handover law against unreasonable dismissal did
not cover the absence of workers because of natural disasters, and
the department's guidelines for rainstorms allowed employers to
deduct wages if workers were absent or late.
	   ``This is unfair because the rainstorm is beyond the control of
workers.'' Newly elected legislator and unionist Leung Yiu-chung
said he would study whether to revive his private member's bill
against unreasonable dismissal to increase protection for workers.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
