w1179 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  A-PLAYWRIGHTsked     06-10 1442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> A-PLAYWRIGHT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A playwright contemporary all the times, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
A playwright contemporary all the times, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Ataur RahmanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   World famed German poet-playwright-director Bertolt Brecht would
have been a centenarian on the 10th February this year had he still
been alive. Theatre practitioners, playwrights, critics and, above
all, the theatre audience all over the world are celebrating his
birth centenary. Newspapers, magazines, journals, television and
radio media, have, in the meantime, widely covered Brecht's
hundredth anniversary. In Bangladesh Brecht's centenary is going to
be celebrated in a befitting manner jointly by the Bangladesh Group
Theatre Federation, the International Theatre Institute and the
Goethe Institute. He died in 1956 at the age of 58.
	   But he is still a socio-politically relevant and popular
playwright in many countries in the world. Brecht's life was truly
dramatic. His life in Adolf Hitler's Germany, life of a fugitive in
Scandinavia, life of a refugee in the United States of America and
subsequent banishment from the USA for non-American activities and
return to his native land after the second World War, which by then
changed to German Democratic Republic (G.D.R.) as the socialist
part of Germany, busy days in his own theatre organisation Berliner
Ensemble' made his entire life sonorous as well as spicy. During
his life time he worked with a good numbers of celebrated
directors, theorists, actors and actresses, composers, musicians
which included Erwin Piscator, a pioneer of the political theatre
movement and Charles Laughton, a highly talented stage and film
actor of his time.
	   In 1947 Brecht directed The Life of Galileo in the USA where the
lead role, Galileo was portrayed by Charles Laughton reflecting
Hiroshima massacre. In 1994 an interesting biography of Bertolt
Brecht entitled The life and Lies of Bertolt Brecht by John Fuegi
was published. This book of more than 700 pages contains many a
exciting, often scandalous and unbelievable information regarding
Brecht, which, quite naturally blemish to his world-reputation. The
contents of this book is interesting, readable and at the same time
debatable. Financial Times commented on the book as a provocative
detective story, like the best of Le Care'. This book, perhaps,
carries lots of truth about the great German playwright-director
but ultimately that could not tarnish his image to his innumerable
fans and admirers. Brecht carried with himself a number of cultural
and literary identities.
	   He was and is still acknowledged as a poet, a composer, a
playwright, a director and an innovator of a new theatrical form.
Brecht in the midway of his career turned out to be a people's
playwright'. Since then, an ardent believer of Marxism and
Leninism, his whole life was spent in establishing proletarian
theatre. In collaboration with another stalwart in the field, Erwin
Piscator, Brecht endeavoured to use theatre as political weapon in
order to help changing the society where there would be no
difference between the haves and have-nots. But to achieve this
goal, he never used theatre as a poster or an instrument of
political propagation. Plays written and directed by him, as such,
never lacked the high prosaic quality of dialogues and artistic
fervour in its entirety. As a carrier of message of his plays, he
evolved a new theatrical form, which was quite opposed to age-long
established Aristotelean or Dramatic theatre. This dramatic form is
well-known to today's theatre practitioners as Epic theatre' which
is essentially narrative in nature.
	   Brecht as a theatre director never believed in creating a stage
illusion by using realistic stage decors, effect-light projections,
superb costumes, make-up and back-ground music or sound effects. He
always tried to avoid these ideal traits of dramatic theatre. He
never meant to baffle or mesmerize the audience with the illusory
effects on stage. He always thought that an emotionally charged
audience tends to see the happenings on stage through a veil of
mist and thus how he fails to see the social realities. He tried to
disillusion the audience by using all the stage aids as open, stark
and artificial. He tried to impress upon his audience that what
they are watching is a play, hence unreal, may be, it is mere
repetition of a street accident which happened this morning. He
wanted to elevate the fun-loving audience to dispassionate or
rather scientific audience.
	   In his search for properly arming his theatrical form, he
applied Alienation or A-Effect through the introduction of chorus,
posters, placards, slide projections, songs and, at times, quite
irrelevant dialogues. Thus, how he used to intervene against the
coiling emotion within the minds of the audience and keep them free
from the contrived mood. With conscious efforts, he turned his
plays narrative and episodic with the skillful use of prologue and
epilogue. It needs to be mentioned that Brecht picked up the
narrative form of theatrical performance from the Orient, specially
from China and India. Brecht went so far to propagate that an actor
who is crying on stage, the audience has the right to laugh at him
and conversely an actor who is laughing on stage, the audience
might feel like crying for him. Alas, Brecht's propagation in
several occasions turned into contradiction as also happened with
the initiator of modern Method' acting in theatre, Russian
Stanislavsky.
	   This reminds us of the oft-used maxim, theory contradicts the
practice. Brecht's plays have to-day been universalized because of
the unique qualities of the plays in getting assimilated and merged
with any society irrespective of geographic settings. That his
plays, specially the ones with political messages, are easily
adaptable to any society irrespective of its cast, colour and creed
of the masses, once again reminds us that mankind remains to be a
political being and as such life and art are inseparable. As
Germans have no problem in identifying the annihilator Hitler
through the gangster of the play The Resistable Rise of Arturo Ui,
similarly Bangladeshi audience had no problem in identifying their
own gangster when they saw the Bangla adaptation of the same play
entitled Dhurta Ui at the Guide House auditorium in Dhaka. The
Group Theatre Movement of the country intensified when the Dhaka
audience first saw his play The Good Person of Setzuan in 1975.
	   The production won the heart of the entire community of the then
theatre-goers. After that Dhaka stage continued to be enliven with
his plays one after another, like Puntila and his Man Matti, The
Rise and Fall of the City of Mahagony, The Three Penny Opera, The
Caucasian Chalk Circle, Mother (Brecht &AMP; Gorky)'' The Resistable
Rise of Arturolli, The Life of Galileo, Man is Man and Mother
Courage and Her Children. Audience in Chittagong also saw his play
Sinora Carrer Rifle, The Exception and the Rule and The Measures
Taken. In fact, Brecht is the most practised foreign playwright in
our country who surpasses Shakespeare and Moliere's popularity.
Dewan Gazir Kissa - an adaptation of his play Puntila and His Man
Matti has the rare distinction of the country's most popular
production which has recently completed 300 performances. Through
the connection of Brecht, we saw the work of an extremely revered
and meritorious German theatre director, Fritz Bennewitz who
directed in Dhaka Brecht's play Man is Man in Bangla. Fritz died in
Germany a few years ago.
	   Entire life's experience taught Brecht to be merciless against
hypocrisy, religious bigotry and all kinds of conceits and he did
not fail to express his insurmountable hatred to these social
vices. He has become a man of our heart because he speaks in our
terms socially, politically and above all theatrically. In his
hundredth birth anniversary, I am sure, theatre lovers of the
country will not fail to pay their heartfelt tribute to the genius
of the most living playwright of the century, Bert-Brecht. We hope,
he will stride through the next millennium with equal might.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:A-PLAYWRIGHT sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
