<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Execution </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Egypt hangs two Islamic militants
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Egypt on Wednesday hanged two Muslim
militants convicted of killing a policeman, police said.
	   Mohammed Fawzi Abdel Adhim and Mohammed Mustafa Sulaiman were
hanged early in the morning at Istanaf prison in Cairo, police
officials said, speaking on customary condition of anonymity.
	   Their deaths raised to 11 the number of Islamic militants
executed this year. The extremists have been waging a violent
campaign to destabilize the secular government of President Hosni
Mubarak.
	   A state security court in February sentenced the two to death
after a retrial in which they were found guilty of the 1993 slaying
of a policeman in the southern town of Tama, 340 kilometers (240
miles) south of Cairo.
	   The two had earlier been found innocent after a court found that
laboratory tests of the bullets allegedly used to kill the
policeman did not match guns that police said were used in the
attack.
	   A military prosecutor refused to endorse that ruling and
referred the case to a higher court.
	   Since 1992, more than 1,200 people have died in the insurgency
by Muslim militants. Most of the casualties have been police and
extremists.
