<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Injury makes Arendse's dream a nightmare
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Arendse comment, details of injury, treatment;
Radebe training again &QL; 
 &UR; By TOM COHEN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VICHY, France (AP) _ South African players have long dreamed of
finally getting the chance to play in a soccer World Cup. For
goalkeeper Andre Arendse, the dream has become a nightmare.
	   Injured in training Monday, Arendse will miss the tournament
after having damaged ligaments removed from his left knee on
Tuesday night.
	   ``My dream is gone,'' the lanky Fulham F.C. player, who turns 31
later this month, said after getting out of the hospital Wednesday.
``I have to put it behind me.''
	   Arendse led South Africa to victory in the 1996 African Nations
Cup tournament but was dropped from the team last year after former
coach Clive Barker resigned.
	   He regained his spot under new coach Philippe Troussier, who
took over in March, but was expected to back up Hans Vonk of
Heerenveen F.C. and Brian Baloyi of local club Kaizer Chiefs at the
World Cup. Team officials named Paul Evans of local club Supersport
United as Arendse's replacement.
	   The news was not all bad Wednesday, as captain Lucas Radebe of
Leeds United returned to fulltime training after bruising his heel
in Saturday's 1-1 draw against Iceland.
	   South Africa begins play Friday night in a Group C clash against
host France in Marseilles. Arendse's injury was a lone
disappointment so far for players lapping up the experience of
their country's first World Cup.
	   For 28, 6th graf pvs
