<HEADLINE>
World Cup 1998, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
World Cup 1998, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The French are hosting soccer's biggest bonanza, the World Cup,
in an absolutely electrifying atmosphere. The first ball will roll
today in the match between Brazil and Scotland as fans all over the
world get ready to enjoy every bit of it. To many, soccer is an
inspiring symbol of national pride; to others, it is a passion not
rivalled by anything else. Today, it is more than a sport -- a
great leveller, a converging point for humans of every colour and
creed. And what more can we expect from a pursuit which, at first
glance, appears to be nothing more than a brawl for the possession
of a mere ball?It is precisely here that modern soccer differs so
greatly from its ancient form. It is no more a brawl. So the fans
love to watch the superstars who have elevated the game into
something of a subtle art with tremendous ball-control, strategic
planning, stamina, and an almost uncanny ability to score goals.
	   And they have to beat the ever vigilant and sturdy defenders who
won't allow a fly to go past them -- let alone an enemy striker!
Yet, the impossible will happen time and again. It is really
interesting to see how people in this country have prepared
themselves for the matches. They are not ready to miss anything
whatsoever. Buying television sets and appealing for an
uninterrupted supply of electricity (a logical demand, in any case)
are indicative enough of their deep love of soccer. They do not
have a team of their own, but that does not affect the enthusiasm.
There are those big teams to choose from -- Brazil, Argentina,
Germany, to name but a few. The bond of soccer seems to transgress
the national boundaries and all other barriers . The fight for
supremacy will quite possibly remain confined to the artistic Latin
Americans and the robust Europeans, as most pundits believe the
dangerous Africans' will have to go a little further to win the
World Cup.
	   Brazil appear to have an edge; but in the presence of so many
formidable sides, few experts will hazard a prediction not
punctuated with some ifs' and buts'. We look forward to a month of
exciting, quality football that should please the game's countless
fans.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
