<HEADLINE>
Virgin signs deal to lease Cathay aircraft, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Virgin signs deal to lease Cathay aircraft, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Mukul MunishASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   CATHAY Pacific Airways said yesterday it had signed a deal with
Virgin Atlantic Airways to lease two of its B747-200 aircraft to
the London-based carrier.
	   Cathay Pacific said that the lease agreement would last five
years, and Virgin had an option to extend it for a further two
years as well as an option to purchase the aircraft.
	   The two aircraft are amongst the five B747-200 ``Classic''
aircraft that Cathay is planning to sell or lease this year. ``The
move is in response to the current market conditions and taking
into account the fact that Cathay will be taking delivery of 13 new
aircraft in 1998-99,'' Andrew Herdman, general manager, group
corporate affairs said.
	   Cathay is in discussions with other airlines for the sale or
lease of the remaining three aircraft.
	   ``We are still in discussions with other airlines on the
possibility of a sale or lease,'' Mr Herdman said.
	   A Virgin Atlantic spokeswoman in London said the carrier was
also in negotiations with Cathay for the lease of the three other
aircraft.
	   ``We are looking at various options and it could include leasing
of more aircraft from them,'' she said.
	   Virgin's leasing of Cathay's aircraft is in addition to the five
Boeing 747-200 aircraft it bought from Air New Zealand in a US$130
million (HK$1.01 billion) deal last month.
	   Mr Herdman refused to reveal the amount Virgin would be paying
for the lease, but an aviation analyst speculated that it could be
between $12 million and $15 million per 747-400 aircraft a year.
	   ``So if Cathay is able to lease all the five aircraft, they
could get anything between $60 million and $75 million a year,''
Wilson Fen, an aviation analyst at Shenyin Wanguo Securities, said.
	   But he added that the secondary market for aircraft was quite
tight and hence Cathay would be unable to find a buyer under the
present weak economic situation.
	   Cathay has said earlier that if it cannot get a good price for
the aircraft it prefers mothballing them till the time the aviation
market picks up.
	   Virgin Atlantic said it intends to utilise the leased aircraft
and the ones it bought from Air New Zealand to additional routes it
has recently added, namely Barbados and Antigua in the Caribbean.
	   
</TEXT>
