<HEADLINE>
Terrorising small traders, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Terrorising small traders, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A plea has been sent out to the highest level of the government
by the joint committee of a few markets of the city to arrest
terrorists from Adarsha Hawkers Market. A joint committee
representing Bangabazar, Gulistan, Mahanagari and Adarsha Hawkers'
Market has in a memorandum called upon the Prime Minister to free
the markets by July 14, failing which a sit-in demonstration will
be organised in front of Bangabhaban.
	   A memorandum has also been sent to the President.Forceful
occupation of markets is a new form of intimidation of the small
traders while the old forms of extortion are all there.
Extortionism is so random and unchecked that many traders are
finding it impossible to ply their trade. Ultimately it is the
common consumers who have to pay for the extortions. As the racket
was not busted, it went on escalating and struck its roots deeper.
This has been going on for nearly twenty years. Sometimes these
extortionists were even backed, directly or indirectly, by
political parties. The hawkers, shop-owners and traders protested
but were helpless.
	   Perforce they had to meet the rapacious demand for donation
under various pleas and the extortionists were emboldened more and
more. The shop-owners of some markets, in their desperation, even
considered deployment of private police to deal with the
extortionists. This would have further worsened the law and order
situation. Any current improvement in the situation of extortionism
is only quantitative, not qualitative. As for street hawkers, they
have to pay not only to youths but also to some law enforcers.
	   And now it is clear that hawkers, shop owners and small traders
are subjected to other kinds of harassments and intimidations, like
outright occupation of markets by exercising muscle power. A series
of mysterious fires have occurred in the markets of the city
recently. If entrepreneurship, trade and commerce are to be
expanded, the problems faced by the small traders should be
attended to with due seriousness.
	   
</TEXT>
