<HEADLINE>
`Corrupted Bahasa Melayu over radio and television', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
`Corrupted Bahasa Melayu over radio and television', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Tues. - The problem of `corrupted' Bahasa Melayu
over radio and television should be rectified, Information Minister
Datuk Mohamed Rahmat said today.
	   He said many views had been forwarded and criticisms levelled at
RTM over its role in propagating Bahasa Melayu as the national
language and the development of a national culture.
	   ``I welcome the views as in our haste to develop and modernise
the country, we should not forget our responsibility in
implementing the national agenda.
	   ``In this respect, the problem of language and culture is
important as they reflect our integrity and identity,'' he said
after a meeting with Malay linguists at Angkasapuri, here.
	   In addition to representatives from organisations like Gapena,
Mohamed also invited those from linguistic societies in
universities and the recent Fifth Literary Congress to give their
views on the matter.
	   Mohamed said he had received a memorandum containing the
resolutions passed at the congress relating to language and culture
closely associated with RTM's responsibility.
	   ``The problem on the use of corrupted Bahasa Melayu which some
feel has reached a critical stage should be resolved, although we
accept the fact that language is alive and should develop with
time.''
	   Panel chairman Datuk Rais Yatim who was also present said among
the problems which cropped up were pronounciation which was not
standard and the use of `bahasa rojak'.
	   The latter is a mixture of Bahasa Melayu and English.
	   On the Barisan Nasional Member of Parliament from Sarawak
reported to be saddled with some A$2 million (RM4.8 million) in
debts after losing in a casino in Australia, Mohamed said it was a
disgrace.
	   ``If it is true, I hope someone would take action since it is a
disgrace,'' said Mohamed who is BN secretary-general.
	   The MP reportedly paid half of the debts today and would settle
the balance by instalments.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
