<HEADLINE>
Brokers losing favour, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Brokers losing favour, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Teresa LeeASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HONG Kong's stock broking industry is headed towards further
consolidation as reflected by the declining number of brokers being
used by fund management companies.
	   The 1998 Reuters Survey of Hong Kong and China companies _ the
first such survey in this market _ showed that of the fund
management groups participating, 49 per cent said they were using
fewer broker teams and 46 per cent planned to increase their own
in-house research resources.
	   The survey, conducted by Tempest Consultants Ltd, also showed
that fund managers are complaining of a lack of transparency at
companies and poor broker research.
	   Tempest director Stephen Parker said: ``If a market is to be
efficient it has to be based on knowledge and information,'' he
said.
	   The survey of institutional investors and finance directors also
found that fund managers were seeking direct contact with
companies, indicating frustration with the quality of broker
research provided on locally listed firms.
	   ``The fund management groups do say that a lot of broker
research is really, really bad,'' said Mr Parker.
	   Based on the survey of finance directors and fund management
groups, Templeton Investment Management's Allan Lam was voted
``Best Individual Fund Manager'', Fidelity Investments was chosen
``Best Fund Management Group'', Merrill Lynch was picked ``Best
Broker Sales Team'', and Credit Lyonnais was voted ``Best Broker
Execution''.
	   The survey was done over the past three months and involved Hong
Kong's 350 largest quoted firms and the 100 largest institutional
investors.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
