<BODY>
<SLUG> ABACHA-AND-DEMOCRACY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Abacha and democracy, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Abacha and democracy, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   General Sani Abacha's running feud with democracy seems to have
ended. The Nigerian President is reported to have died of a heart
attack last Monday. After Moshood Abiola won the free and fair
election in 1993, General Abacha abrogated the election result,
jailed Abiola and nearly 60 other leaders. He also forced into
exile and imprisoned political leaders, besides cultural and labour
figures as well. Seizing power in a bloodless coup d'etat, he did
not hesitate to shed blood. Assassinations and executions removed
whomever he believed was a threat to his regime.
	   What earned him great infamy was the execution of playwright
activist Ken Sara-Wiwa along with eight other Ogoni activists
despite appeals for clemency from the world.Sitting atop Nigeria's
vast oil wealth, its chief export, Abacha's inept and corrupt rule
pushed the poverty level of the country from almost 41 per cent in
1992 to about 80 per cent this year. Nigeria's electorate suffered
paradoxically from perennial fuel scarcity. Over 90 per cent of
eligible voters boycotted this year's election in a show of unity
not seen since the independence days among the 250 tribes that are
often at loggerheads with one another, and who make up the 105
million Nigerian nation.
	   The April presidential election saw five political parties
participating - and all of them nominated Abacha as their
candidate! The visit by the Pope earlier had fuelled a hope Abacha
might keep his promise to hand over power to a civilian
administration through free and fair elections as Abacha repeated
his previous promises during the Papal visit in a loud voice. But
soon it became clear Abacha had little interest in helping to build
the democratic process in a country which has seen one military
coup after another since the collapse of the civilian government
following the Biafran civil war in 1967. Hopefully with Abacha's
demise Nigerians should now be in a position to build up a
democratic system of governance that can perpetuate itself.
	   
</TEXT>
