<HEADLINE>
Income from property to play key role for Miramar, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Income from property to play key role for Miramar, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Karen ChanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   CONTRIBUTION from property rental is expected to be increasingly
important for Miramar Hotel and Investment Co during the next three
years, director and group general manager Peter Yu said yesterday.
	   With the addition of 110,000 square feet of extra space at the
extension of the Miramar Shopping Centre, the total floor area of
the complex has been expanded to nearly 400,000 sq ft.
	   An extra 230,000 sq ft of space has also been added to the
office tower, bringing the total area to 700,000 sq ft.
	   Speaking after the official signing of the tenancy agreement
between Miramar Hotel and the Grande Entertainment Group, Mr Yu
said that despite the current soft retail leasing market, the
Miramar Shopping Centre is able to maintain a greater than 95 per
cent occupancy level, while the office tower has also achieved more
than 90 per cent occupancy.
	   Property rentals accounted for some 73.9 per cent of the group's
total profit of $228.2 million in fiscal 1997 and the weighting
from this operation is expected to be even more substantial in the
next few years. Mr Yu said monthly rental for Miramar Shopping
Centre ranges from $30 to $200 per sq ft, which the group considers
is a very reasonable level.
	   He admitted that a few existing tenants have asked for rent
reduction and the group has agreed to reduce the rent temporarily
and would re-adjust the rent when market conditions improve.
	   He said the group would invest millions of dollars to promote
the shopping arcade during this year and planning is also underway
for a new footbridge to be completed by the end of the year which
will link the Miramar Shopping Centre and Hotel Miramar's shopping
arcade which will help increase traffic and benefit both tenants
and shoppers.
	   For the hotel operation, Mr Yu said the occupancy for the
Miramar Hotel remains at a healthy 80 per cent, but the average
room rate has dropped some 30 per cent since early 1998 compared to
the level a year ago.
	   He admitted that contribution from the hotel operation is
expected to drop this year, but the group will continue its effort
to expand its operation by finalising more hotel management
contracts.
	   He noted that the group is currently under negotiation to manage
two four-star hotels on the mainland.
	   
</TEXT>
