<HEADLINE>
Free tickets for 50,000 pupils to liven up venues, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Free tickets for 50,000 pupils to liven up venues, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Tues. - Some 50,000 pupils from secondary schools
nationwide will be given free tickets to the Commonwealth Games to
liven up the atmosphere at sports venues.
	   Besides the tickets, food and insurance coverage will also be
provided for the pupils under a programme called Projek Khas
Sekolah-sekolah.
	   Accommodation is available for pupils from out of the city.
	   Education Minister Datuk Seri Najib Tun Razak, who launched the
project today, said the Games would help inspire pupils to excel in
sports.
	   ``It is important to cultivate a love for sports among
schoolchildren when they are still young.
	   ``The pupils will also help liven up the atmosphere at the
stadium with their thunderous cheers,'' he said, adding that there
would be 5,000 pupils a day at the Bukit Jalil stadium throughout
the 10-day Games.
	   Also present during the launch today was Sukom Ninety Eight
Berhad executive chairman Jen (Rtd) Tan Sr Hashim Mohd Ali.
	   The project is a joint effort between Sukom and CYAD Consultants
Sdn Bhd.
	   Three organisations have come forward in support of the project.
They are CYAD Consultants which donated RM100,000, Kingsmen
Builders Sdn Bhd which gave RM50,000 and Konsortium Pembuat
Alatulis Malaysia Sdn Bhd with RM25,000.
	   Najib said at least RM12 million was needed to make the project
a success.
	   ``The money will be used to buy tickets, bring pupils to the
stadium, provide refreshments, souvenirs and insurance coverage.''
On how the selection would be done, Najib said priority would be
given to pupils who excelled in sports and co-curricular
activities. ``We leave the selection to the project committee and
the ministry's schools division.''
	   Najib said each school would be accompanied by two teachers.
	   
</TEXT>
