<BODY>
<SLUG> NUCLEAR-ARMS-RACE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nuclear arms race in the Indian sub-continent, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Nuclear arms race in the Indian sub-continent, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Arshad-uz ZamanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A new dimension has been added to the nuclear arms race in the
Indian sub-continent by the explosion of six nuclear devices by
Pakistan in the desert of Baluchistan. Earlier, on May 11 and 13
India conducted five nuclear tests in the desert state of
Rajasthan. The lid put on by the five nuclear powers led by the USA
has been blown apart. There has been a basic discrimination in the
arrangement for nuclear monopoly engineered by the USA. The five
nuclear powers, namely, the USA, Russia, China, UK and France have
enjoyed a nuclear weapons monopoly. The USA has tried strenuously
to so organize the world that no other country attempts to join the
nuclear club. India had exploded a nuclear device as far back as
1974. In other words, she was in possession of nuclear technology
and the question was not whether but when she would carry out the
tests of her weapons.
	   After nearly a quarter century she carried out the tests. In
between the USA has carried on a tireless campaign to put a halt to
all testing. The fact that five permanent members of the Security
Council of the UN have enjoyed a monopoly of the nuclear weapons
points to a situation of discrimination, which has bedevilled the
world. In between China has joined the nuclear club in a big way
advancing the argument that what she wanted was not a stop to
proliferation of nuclear weapons but a total ban of the weapons.
Indeed nuclear ban has eluded the grasp of the permanent members of
the Security Council. It is a thousand pities that the nuclear arms
race should come to the Indian sub-continent. If we take the
universe as a whole the Indian sub-continent stands out amongst the
most backward and poor. Left behind in the race for economic
development, the expression teeming million' can be very aptly used
for the area. There has been for long half a century a race between
India and Pakistan on conventional weapons.
	   The addition of nuclear weapon will only increase the economic
burden manifold. In retaliation for the five nuclear blasts carried
out by India, Pakistan has reacted by blasting six nuclear weapons.
This tragi-comic situation would not be so grim had it not been for
the fact that the two major powers of the sub-continent have fought
three wars since their independence from Britain half a century
ago. The focus of the territorial dispute is Kashmir, in the north
of both India and Pakistan. The war over this territory started
from the moment the two countries achieved independence back in
1947. Indeed all attempts to extricate the sub-continent from the
dispute between the two major powers of the sub-continent have
foundered on the rock of disagreement on many issues and mainly
Kashmir. Attempts to find a forum where they could cooperate like
South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) have not
made any headway because of the attitude of the two major members
of the Association. Political issues are barred from SAARC.
	   Yet it has surfaced again and again and vitiated the atmosphere
within the organisation. When SAARC was launched there was a
glimmer of hope that it would emulate the highly successful ASEAN.
The result has been a dismal failure as far as SAARC is concerned.
With the testing of nuclear weapons by India and Pakistan, the club
is not only widened but nuclear weapons passed into the hands of
states with not a very strong economic base. It goes right into the
hands of Third World countries. The question that must preoccupy
the nuclear states, but primarily the sole superpower USA, is
whether the club can be limited to its present officially announced
seven members. There is open speculation that Israel possesses the
bomb. With the explosion of the Islamic' bomb, long dreamt of by
some Arab leaders, principally Muammar Gaddafi of Libya, will there
not be an enormous interest in acquisition of the bomb by some
wealthy Arab states?
	   India has carried on her nuclear arms programme irrespective of
the consequences that it would bring in her relations with
Pakistan. She had exploded a device back in 1974 and was marking
time to carry out significant tests. Indian agenda is different
from that of Pakistan: India is a large country, with population
only second to that of China; she has vast resources-and
technologically she is among the most advanced of the world. She is
eager to join the select club of the big powers and hence her
effort to join the Security Council as a permanent member. She is
carrying on the campaign in all the chancelleries of the world and
her voice has been properly registered. Explosion of nuclear device
is an attempt to join the big club. Pakistan has been operating on
a limited agenda.
	   That is that she must match India in weapons. She has no hope of
joining the big league but is determined to match India in the game
of power play. There is a psychological factor that is at work in
this dangerous nuclear arms race. Whereas India has reservations
about the partition of the sub-continent on religious lines, a
reservation that Indian politicians underline every now and then,
Pakistan feels threatened by these utterances. Pakistan has sought
security in weapons and hence her open embrace of the USA since the
beginning of the Cold War. There is talk of moratorium on nuclear
weapons. There is too much euphoria within the two countries to
discuss such a possibility immediately. Yet the leaders of the two
countries of the subcontinent will soon find out that with the
nuclear weapons the best that can be achieved is a balance of
terror.
	   Ever since the USA dropped those bombs on Hiroshima and
Nagasaki, nuclear weapons have been perfected manifold but they lie
in silos. There is a general realization that they are too
dangerous, too devastating in its destructive capacities, to be
used. As has been rightly said, with those weapons the world could
be destroyed many times over.The best that could be hoped for is
that India and Pakistan, after their euphoria has died down, will
reflect cooly over the situation and come to a modus vivendi. If
the great powers with a fantastic nuclear arsenal have come to this
conclusion, there is no reason why India and Pakistan should be any
different. The world is sufficiently unstable as it is. There is no
need to add new elements to this volatile situation.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
