<SLUG> BC-EU-Teething Ban </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU Commission delays decision on banning teething products
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) - The European Commission delayed
Wednesday a decision on whether to ban certain plastic teething
products for babies amid fears chemicals they contain may cause
cancer.
	   The European Union executive body opened an investigation into
teething products that contain two widely-used pthalates, a
chemical substance used in plastic objects to make them supple.
	   The ban, if adopted, would target objects that children might
put in their mouths. Pthalates, which recent scientific evidence
suggests may contain cancer-causing agents, are used in some
teething rings and other products for babies to chew on during
teething.
	   `There is not enough scientific evidence yet to justify a ban,''
said Pietro Petrucci, spokesman for the EU's Commissioner for
Consumer Affairs Emma Bonino.
	   The 20 EU commissioners are expected to discuss the ban again
when they meet next Wednesday but it's unclear whether they will be
able to take a decision by then.
	   EU officials said scientists must determine what level of
pthalates leaking from toy to mouth could pose a health risk and
whether the substance goes through the digestive system or remains
in the body.
	   The Commission must also decide whether the ban should be
applied as an emergency measure - to be applied immediately - or as
a consumer protection measure that will take months to be
implemented in the 15 EU countries.
	   ``If we impose an emergency ban, we must have solid scientific
proof because otherwise any company can take us to court and
overturn it,'' an EU official said on condition of anonymity.
	   A small group of EU countries favor an immediate ban but others
would like to find out first how dangerous the pthalates are.
	    &UR; (as)
</TEXT>
