<SLUG> COMMON-WEALTH-GAMES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Souvenir with a difference for Common wealth Games, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Souvenir with a difference for Common wealth Games, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Chok Suat LingASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Tues. - Among the souvenir items for the coming
Commonwealth Games here is one with a difference - a
mind-challenging series of puzzle books which will serve to
stimulate the brain cells of readers besides providing them general
information about the Games and the country.
	   To be launched by next month, the books are targeted at both
adults and youths.
	   Mindplus (M) Sdn Bhd managing director Sam Samarasinghe, who is
also the author of the books, said there were six types of books
under the series - Mind Bending Puzzles, Creative Puzzles, IQ
Puzzles, Tricky Puzzles, Sports Puzzles and Ingenious Puzzles.
	   The books are also available in Bahasa Malaysia.
	   The Bahasa Malaysia versions are called Teka-Teki Minda,
Teka-Teki Kreatif, Teka-Teki IQ, Teka-Teka Bestari, Teka-Teki Sukan
and Teka Teki Pintar.
	   Samarasinghe is a graduate of the Imperial College, University
of London in the United Kingdom and the University of Ceylon and
holds various qualifications from professional engineering
institutions.
	   He said each book, priced at RM39.90 contained 100 puzzles and
information on the history of the Commonwealth Games, the coming
Games in Kuala Lumpur, sports champions of Malaysia, places of
interest and advertorials.
	   Mindplus (M) Sdn Bhd is licensed by Sukom Ninety Eight Sdn Bhd
to produce the books. Juranas Sdn Bhd is the sole distributor.
	   Samarasinghe, who has written several puzzle books in the past
20 years, said each 230-page hardcover book has full-colour
illustrations and pictures.
	   ``I looked at souvenir books from the previous Commonwealth
Games and Olympic Games and saw that readers generally lost
interest in them after the events.
	   ``By incorporating puzzles, there will be sufficient material in
the books to keep a reader occupied well after the Games,'' he
said, adding that it took him five years to complete writing the
entire series.
	   He said the puzzles needed lttle more than elementary knowledge
to solve as many were based on well-known mathematical and logical
principles.
	   ``The puzzles will help sharpen the reader's analytical process,
logical thinking and mathematical skills.
	   ``At first glance, some of the puzzles may appear difficult but
upon careful reading and thinking, readers will find that the
solutions are relatively easy to get,'' he said, adding that
answers to the puzzles were available in the books.
	   Samarasinghe said the books were also targeted at tourists as it
would provide them invaluable information about Malaysia.
	   Juranas executive chairman Aziz Massod said besides being sold
at the Games venues, the books would also be available at
bookshops.
	   ``We are also looking for sponsors among corporations and
airlines. They can buy the books in bulk and distribute it to
customers and passengers.''
	   Big companies and conglomerates are encouraged to buy the books
as one of the ways to support the Commonwealth Games.
	   The books can be given away as gifts or souvenirs with records
of the Commonwealth Games held here.
	   Corporate sponsors can also buy in bulk and distribute the books
to schoolchildren who may find the puzzles interesting.
	   Those with enquiries can forward them to Juranas at 03-2927311
or 03- 2931224.
	   
</TEXT>
