<SLUG> BC-Britain-Kosovo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Blair: threat of force is key to Kosovo solution
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ A credible threat of military force is a
prerequisite for a diplomatic solution of the crisis in Kosovo,
Prime Minister Tony Blair said Wednesday.
	   Western European government have been pressing Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic to refrain from violently suppressing
ethnic Albanians. NATO defense ministers are expected to consider
plans for possible intervention, including perhaps sending in
troops, air strikes or a no-fly zone over Kosovo.
	   ``Is not one of the lessons of Bosnia that diplomacy seems to
work somewhat better with President Milosevic if it is backed by a
clear and credible threat of compulsion?'' Liberal Democrat leader
Paddy Ashdown asked Blair in the House of Commons.
	   ``Yes, I would agree with that entirely. That's precisely why we
are trying to arrange the maximum support so that we can take
military options should diplomacy fail,'' Blair said.
	   Blair added that he believed Milosevic would only respond to
``diplomatic pressure is if that is backed up by the threat _ the
credible threat _ of military force.''
	   ``Now, the sole hurdle that remains in our way at the present
time is getting the necessary support for that course of action. We
are working as hard as we possibly can,'' Blair said.
	   (rb)
</TEXT>
