<HEADLINE>
No takers for 2,301 low-cost units in two districts, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
No takers for 2,301 low-cost units in two districts, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A TOTAL of 2,301 low-cost houses in Seberang Perai Tengah (SPT)
and Selatan (SPS) districts still have no takers, Deputy Chief
Minister Datuk Shariff Omar (BN-Permatang Berangan) told the House.
	   Shariff, who is chairman of the State Housing Committee, said
the houses were among 4,878 units built in 14 projects in the two
districts.
	   Of SPT's 3,168 houses built under seven projects in Tan Sri
Janggus, Taman Impian Indah, Taman Sri Delima, Taman Titi Panjang,
PPR Sungai Rambai and Taman Pauh, there were only 2,156 buyers.
	   Of SPS' 1,710 houses built under seven projects in Taman Bandar
Mutiara, Taman Pekatra, Taman Seruling Emas, Taman Merak Jaya,
Taman Bukit Panchur, Taman Idaman and Taman Tambun Indah, only 421
applied to buy them.
	   ``Eligible buyers from the lower-income group of both districts
who are registered with the State Housing Department should seize
the opportunity to own low-cost units now.''
	   On the RM6.2 million rental and maintenance arrears of public
houses owed by the occupants till March 1998, Shariff said the
State Government would act against the defaulters.
	   
