<BODY>
<SLUG> NUCLEAR-TENSION sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nuclear tension in the sub-continent, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Nuclear tension in the sub-continent, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Gauranga Chandra DharASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The six nuclear devices conducted by Pakistan on 28 and 30 May,
1998, needless to say, created a threat to regional and
international peace and security. India detonated five nuclear
devices a few days earlier and began nuclear arms race in South
Asia. Actually, Pakistan applied deterrence approach to maintain
balance of power in South Asia. On the other hand, India detonated
five nuclear devices to maintain balance of power with China. At
the time of Cold War, United States followed massive nuclear
programmes. This was because of the fact that Soviet nuclear
programme was not fully known to United States. There was, however,
a balance of power between North Atlantic Treaty Organisation
(NATO) and Warsaw Pact. According to Hans J. Morgenthau, ``The
balance of power and policies aiming at its preservation are not
only inevitable but are an essential stabilizing factor in a
society of sovereign nations''.
	   So the question of balance of power is related to the nuclear
devices of India and Pakistan. But after disintegration of Soviet
Union, geo-economics is more important than geo-politics. Side by
side, it is spreading and becoming the dominant phenomenon in
regional and international context. In traditional international
politics, the goals of great powers were to ensure and extend the
physical control of territory. In the ongoing era of free market
economy, the goals are to extend the market.But it is a matter of
regret that South Asian states, India and Pakistan, are going ahead
in the traditional style. As a result economic development, human
development and poverty alleviation programmes would not gain
momentum.
	   With the celebration of golden jubilee of their Independence,
India and Pakistan began nuclear arms race bypassing the more
important poverty alleviation programme. The Indian sub-continent
is now witnessing an atmosphere of tension and conflict. Pakistani
President Mohammad Rafiq Tarar declared a state of emergency
against the threat of external aggression' as the country faced
sweeping economic sanctions. World leaders condemned Pakistan's
nuclear tests. US President Bill Clinton condemned Pakistan for its
nuclear explosions. US is considering has imposed economic sanction
upon Pakistan like upon India. Japanese government declared
suspension of new economic aid and loans. Nations around the world
condemned Pakistan. Britain, Australia and some other nations
condemned it.
	   So it is evident that economic consequences for Pakistan would
be severe because its economy is dependent on foreign aid. Side by
side, foreign investment in Pakistan and India is under threat. It
is also obvious that the economy of Pakistan would be hard hit. The
socio-economic structure of Pakistan and India will undergo jolts
for escalating the arms race. But in reality South Asia is a
prospective area in the era of geo-economics. There are some
disputes between India and Pakistan and between India and China.
Yet with the end of the Cold War bargaining approach of Thomas C.
Schelling seems to be more relevant, and important, than deterrence
approach in the hostile relationship between two countries.
	   So Indo-Pakistan, Sino-Indian disputes could be settled through
bilateral and regional level and negotiations the future of the
South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) would
brighten. Consequently, the socio-economic development of South
Asia would be a reality and the South Asian nations would emerge as
great economic powers. It is necessary to close the nuclear
umbrella of the nations because the impact of nuclear weapons on
history was devastating.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
