<HEADLINE>
Foreign workers only to address shortage, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Foreign workers only to address shortage, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PENANG will recruit and retain foreign workers only if the State
experiences a shortage of local workers, the House was told
yesterday.
	   Chief Minister Tan Sri Dr Koh Tsu Koon (BN-Tanjung Bunga) said
the State would practise a flexible and pragmatic labour policy
emphasising its economy and local workers.
	   ``The estimated 70,000 foreign workers currently in Penang are
serving as a cushion and will be only retained if there are not
enough local workers,'' he said when winding up the debate on a
motion of thanks to the Yang di-Pertua Negeri Tun Hamdan Sheikh
Tahir for his opening address.
	   Koh said the welfare of local workers had and would always be
the Government's main concern and focus.
	   ``This concern and focus will serve as a basis for our economic
development strategy in promoting investment, tourism, trade,
services, property, agriculture and other sectors.''
	   He also said there had been an increasing number of Bumiputeras
and Indians in professional occupations in Penang.
	   ``In the combined category of engineers, architects, scientists,
system analysts and technicians, the number of Bumiputeras
increased more than eightfold from 671 from a total of 3,483 in
1980 to 5,520 from a total of 14,869 in 1991.
	   ``The number of Indians in this category increased fourfold from
391 in 1980 to 1,603 in 1991, while the Chinese increased a little
more than threefold from 2,211 to 7,622 in the same period.''
	   He also said that between 700 and 900 study loans of RM2,500
each had been allocated over the past five years.
	   Of this figure, between 28 and 45 per cent were given to
Bumiputera students, between 49 and 66 per cent to Chinese students
and between six and nine per cent went to Indians.
	   
</TEXT>
