w1218 &Cx1f; wstm-
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  WallStreetdoesn'tflincho     06-10 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> Wall Street doesn't flinch over GM strike,0480 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AP Photos DT108-109 of June 9
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By BRIAN S. AKRE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Auto Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DETROIT (AP) _ Why is General Motors struggling through its
seventh strike in 18 months even though competitors Ford and
Chrysler have relatively peaceful relations with labor?
	   Analysts say one reason is that GM has been behind its rivals in
going through tough reorganizations and cost-cutting.
	   ``It's a history of bad management,'' analyst David Healy of
Burnham Securities Inc. said Tuesday. ``If Chrysler and Ford can
manage their union relations so there are no strikes and costs are
good, you have to lay the problem on GM's door.''
	   So far, Wall Street has reacted favorably to the strike even
though the world's largest automaker once again faces the threat of
a North American assembly shutdown, with the potential loss of
hundreds of millions of dollars in production.
	   GM's stock has fallen only slightly since the strike began last
week. In morning trading Wednesday, its stock was up slightly, at
31 1/4 cents to dlrs 73.50 per share on the New York Stock
Exchange.
	   ``General Motors is perceived as a multilayered bureaucracy that
is very high-cost and very slow-moving,'' Healy said. ``Any signal
that this is changing through making plants more efficient or
making the organization more flexible is welcomed on Wall Street.''
	   A seventh assembly plant was closed Wednesday because of the
strike at the Flint Metal Center. The Linden, New Jersey, plant
that makes midsize sport utility vehicles and pickup trucks was
shut down, affecting 2,360 workers, the company reported.
	   The strike earlier caused the closure of assembly plants in
Michigan, Ohio, and Kansas. In all, about 17,300 UAW
union-represented workers have been affected. The shutdowns came
quickly because modern assembly plants use a just-in-time delivery
system for parts, rather than costly warehousing at the plants.
	   Talks resumed Wednesday at the plant as the strike entered its
sixth day. No progress has been reported so far.
	   More shutdowns are expected as the strike continues. A total of
16 cities across North America have GM plants that use doors,
hoods, engine cradles and other parts made at the Flint Metal
Center. Analysts estimate the lost production could cost GM dlrs
300 million a week if all those plants close.
	   And if the union strikes another key parts plant in Flint on
Thursday, as it has threatened, virtually all of GM's North
American production could come to a halt.
	   GM insists efficiency is the key issue at Flint, that outdated
union work rules prevent it from using new equipment in ways that
would increase productivity and save money.
	   The UAW maintains it already has negotiated rule changes, but
that GM has not followed through with all of a dlrs300 million
investment it promised. 	   
</TEXT>
