<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Ousting President </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Duma debates bill setting rules of president's dismissal
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ A Russian president would have to undergo a
medical exam if he failed to work full time for more than four
months, under a bill given preliminary approval Wednesday in the
lower house of the Russian parliament.
	   The bill could strengthen the hand of Boris Yeltsin's opponents,
who have long claimed he was unfit for office on health grounds.
	   The Russian constitution says a president must step down if he
suffers a ``lasting inability to exercise his powers.'' The
constitution does not explain the process for removing a president
on these grounds, and the new bill is intended to fill the gap.
	   The bill needs final approval by the State Duma and approval by
the upper chamber of parliament and Yeltsin himself before it
becomes law.
	   The vagueness of the constitution has fueled controversy since
Yeltsin's heart illnesses and bypass surgery in 1996.
	   Doctors say Yeltsin has fully recovered from his surgery and is
in good condition, but Communists and other foes disagree. They
argue he is unfit for office and should step down.
	   Under the bill, parliament may demand a medical exam if a
president is unable to work full time for more than four months or
if doctors order him to reduce his workload.
	   Either house of parliament would be authorized to ask the
Supreme Court to appoint a team of doctors to examine a president
and, based on their findings, rule whether he could remain in
office.
	   The Russian constitution also says that a president can be
impeached if he breaks the law.
	   Communists and others have repeatedly tried to launch
impeachment motions against Yeltsin. All such moves have fizzled,
mostly because Russia's constitution gives the president the upper
hand in confrontations with parliament.
	   Communists are trying to bring another impeachment motion
against Yeltsin, and plan to discuss the issue on Thursday.
	   Even if the Duma votes to start the impeachment proceedings, the
motion has to go to the upper chamber, which is made up of regional
officials, many of whom are loyal to Yeltsin. The charges will also
have to by approved by both the Constitutional and Supreme Courts _
a highly unlikely development.
	   (vi/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
