<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Spain-ETA kidnap </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Basque separatists go on trial for ETA's longest kidnapping
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ Four self-confessed members of the armed
Basque separatist group ETA on Wednesday admitted to keeping a
prison official hostage for 18 months to pressure the government to
move group's prisoners to jails in the northern Basque region, but
denied planning to kill him.
	   The four defendants were responding to charges of kidnapping and
conspiring to murder Jose Antonio Ortega Lara on the opening day of
their National Court trial.
	   All the four men face up to 32 years in jail if convicted on
both counts.
	   Jesus Maria Uribechevarria Bolinaga, Javier Ugarte Villar, Jose
Luis Erostegui Bidaguren and Jose Miguel Gaztelu were arrested last
July hours before police rescued their captive from a hideout in
the northern town of Mondragon.
	   The ETA abducted Ortega Lara in January 1996 and kept him in a
3-meter by 2.5-meter (9-foot by 7-foot) windowless room for 532
days, conditioning his release on improved conditions for 450
jailed members of the group.
	   At the beginning of the trial, the National Court exempted the
former hostage from taking the witness stand after a medical
evaluation presented on Tuesday concluded this could seriously
worsen his already delicate psychological condition.
	   Wearing white T-shirts demanding that Basque prisoners should be
held in Basque jails, the four defendants denied that they planned
to kill or starve their captive to death if the government did not
give in to their demands.
	   The defendants said they had treated ETA's longest ever hostage
correctly.
	   When Ortega Lara was released from captivity his muscles were
wasted, he had lost 51 pounds (23 kilos) in weight and become
anemic.
	   But the four accused stressed that they had fed him everyday and
that they did not have the medical knowledge necessary to diagnose
or treat any illnesses he might have had.
	   ETA, an acronym for Basque Homeland and Freedom, has killed
nearly 800 people and kidnapped 71 people since it began fighting
for independence of northern Spain's Basque region in 1968.
	   Prosecutors are also seeking compensation of 65 million pesetas
(dlrs 424,836) for Ortega Lara, and the trial is expected to
conclude Thursday.
	   (mr/jt)
</TEXT>
