<SLUG> BOOST-INTERNATIONAL-TRAD sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
One-stop agency to be set up to boost international trade, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
One-stop agency to be set up to boost international trade, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE State Government will set up an international business
development centre to act as a one-stop agency to carry out
trade-related activities and co-ordinate with the international
business community to boost the State's commercial and service
sectors.
	   State Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs Committee chairman
Datuk Dr Sak Cheng Lum (BN-Bagan Jermal) told the House that the
Penang Trade Council was finalising a project paper on the proposed
IBDC.
	   The IBDC, he said, would act as a one-stop agency to group all
domestic public and private business agencies to deal collectively
with international business communities like the European Union,
Asean, the US, Japan, Taiwan, China and South Korea for mutual
benefit.
	   It will be a co-ordinating body to set up proper infrastructure
and transportation systems, free commercial zones and other
facilities, and carry out programmes such as international-level
seminars, dialogues and conferences pivotal to business growth.
	   ``The State Government hopes to utilise the IBDC as a cohesive
unit to boost Penang's growth as a regional industrial, commercial
and service centre to benefit the local business community and the
public in general,''
	   Dr Sak said in replying to points raised during debate on the
motion of thanks to the Yang di-Pertua Negeri Tun Hamdan Sheikh
Tahir for his opening address.
	   Dr Sak said presently, many government departments and agencies,
besides various business organisations and companies, were working
independently to establish international business links.
	   However, he said: ``The IBDC does not necessarily mean setting
up a complex or building to act as an international trade centre.
It can even be a division under the Penang Development
Corporation.''
	   Dr Sak said two more free commercial zones - one each in the
Malaysia Airports Berhad complex in Bayan Lepas and North
Butterworth Container Terminal in Bagan - would be established.
	   The proposed FCZ in Bagan will also be a regional trade and
service distribution centre.
	   
</TEXT>
