<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Corporate Profits,0250 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Survey: Japan corporate sales and profits decline; pessimism
</HEADLINE>
spreads &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Sales and profits for Japanese companies fell in
the quarter ended in March, and managers say they are more
pessimistic about the economy than they've been in at least 15
years, according to a government survey released Wednesday.
	   Pretax profits for Japanese companies plunged 25.4 percent in
the three months ended in March compared with a year earlier as
sales sank 6.8 percent, the largest decline in 40 years, the
Ministry of Finance said in a quarterly survey.
	   The report follows a string of bad news for the Japanese
economy, which is stuck in its worst slowdown in decades. Many
economists expect a report due out later this week will show the
country has sunk into recession.
	   The survey, which was conducted in May, also showed corporate
managers didn't expect economic conditions to improve anytime soon.
	   The survey's business sentiment index for major manufacturers _
a measure of corporate optimism _ sank to minus 36.1 from minus
31.0 a quarter earlier. The index is the difference between the
percentage of companies which say the economy is worsening from
those that say it's getting better. A negative number indicates
there are more pessimists than optimists.
	   The survey also indicated that the growing pessimism is
affecting companies' planning for the future. New investment by
Japanese corporations decreased by 5.8 percent over the quarter.
</TEXT>
