<SLUG> PENANG-DAP-VOTE-SPLIT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Penang DAP vote split on suspended members, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Penang DAP vote split on suspended members, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   S. ShankarASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Tues. - The Penang DAP was split 8-8 last night
when it voted on whether the two suspended national officials and
another who was removed from his position should be allowed to
present their case to the members.
	   The deadlock, sources said, had thrown the party into the deep
end as Penang is its power base.
	   On June 3, the DAP's central executive committee suspended
national vice-chairman Liew Ah Kim and treasurer Fung Ket Wing for
criticising the leadership. National publicity secretary Wee Choo
Keong was removed from his position.
	   Of the 18 State DAP committee members, one abstained while
another was not present. The meeting was chaired by Penang DAP
chairman Teoh Teik Huat.
	   Those in favour were Teoh, deputy chairman Gooi Hock Seng,
political bureau chief K. Balasundram, treasurer Cheah Teik Hoe,
youth chief Te Beng Hai, Ong Hock Hun, Ong Eng Khuan and organising
secretary Goh Kheng Huat.
	   Those against were State vice-chairmen Lim Hock Seng and
Zulkifli Ismail, secretary Chow Kon Yeow, publicity chief and Batu
Lanchang State Assemblywoman Chong Eng, Gooi Seong Kin who is
Secretary-general Lim Kit Siang's political secretary, women's
chief Wong Good Yew, Tan Mei Ling and Danny Lauw. Phee Boon Poh
abstained while K. Raman did not vote.
	   Chow said the matter was only ``discussed in passing and not in
detail.''
	   He said the State committee had yet to decide if a formal
meeting should be held to discuss the matter after being briefed by
Kit Siang tonight.
	   However, party sources said it was heading towards a major
crisis.
	   They said the matter was discussed when the three requested that
they be given a fair chance to explain matters.
	   The Penang DAP has about 2,000 registered members. They said it
would be unfair if the committee members only heard Kit Siang.
	   Liew, Fung and Wee have been referred to the disciplinary
committee headed by vice-chairman Ahmad Nor for further action.
Until the board meets, they will remain as CEC members.
	   Liew, Fung and Wee however called for an ``independent and
impartial''
	   committee to investigate the charges against them.
	   Kit Siang claimed that they had made statements that had
undermined party morale, created confusion and caused disharmony as
well as disunity.
	   He had said the decision to remove them followed complaints from
the Malacca and Perak State committees.
	   
</TEXT>
