<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-People-Queen Mother </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Queen Mother unveils plaque to honor policeman killed in World War
</HEADLINE>
II

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Britain's Queen Mother Elizabeth made it easier
Wednesday for Stephen Robertson to rest in peace.
	   The mother of Queen Elizabeth II, who lived in Buckingham Palace
with her husband King George VI throughout World War II, honored
the young policeman with a plaque on the spot where he was mortally
injured 57 years ago.
	   The ghostly figure of the police constable in his wartime
uniform is said to creep stealthily around the tombstone that marks
his grave at Chadwell Heath Cemetery. He has become a London legend
since his death in the line of duty in March 1941.
	   On that fatal night in the heat of the war, Robertson was
patrolling the garden outside the palace, while the king and queen
rested inside.
	   German bombers dropped a basket of phosphorous bombs on the area
Robertson was guarding, and the 25-year-old policeman fought to put
out the flames. Then, a second enemy aircraft scored a direct hit
on part of the building.
	   Stones from the destroyed area fell on Robertson, who mustered
his last energies to cry for help. He died in an ambulance.
	   His friends and former colleagues lobbied for the plaque and
suggested the royal family honor the constable. Many told the Queen
Mother on Wednesday that Robertson did not usually patrol the area
of the palace grounds where he died.
	   Irene Hunt, a close friend, said she spoke with him the day he
died.
	   ''He told me that he had changed duties and asked me to hold his
hand because it was dark at Buckingham Palace,'' she said.
	   (jh-kg)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Britain-People-Queen Mother; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:ASIA;)
