<BODY>
<SLUG> THE-YOUNG-MEN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
The young men and the sea, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
The young men and the sea, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Sam CheongASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SUHAIDI Samiran knows he has a bright future. As third officer
on board Puteri Delima, a liquefied natural gas (LNG) vessel
belonging to Petronas Tankers Sdn Bhd, this 23-year-old is being
groomed to be ``master of his own vessel''.
	   He is one of the young people in the company's Malaysianisation
programme. The country's LNG transportation sector, says Suhaidi,
has great demand for young people who aspire to be captains and
chief engineers.
	   ``The job pays very well, with basic necessities like food and
clothing covered. And by being at sea for months, we have the
opportunity to save.
	   To top it all, my monthly salary is also tax-free.
	   ``If you are the type who loves to travel, then this job is
definitely for you. I've been sailing for five years and it has
taken me to countries in the Middle East, Europe, North and South
America and all over Asia,''says Suhaidi.
	   Puteri Delima is one of the most advanced LNG vessels in its
class. The 274-metre-long ship is equipped with the latest
computer-controlled navigation and engine management system which
enables it to be operated unattended during the night.
	   With a top speed of 20 knots, she can bear a full load of more
than 58,800 tonnes of cargo. She is also capable of generating 2.9
megawatts of electricity and process about 20 tonnes of freshwater
from the sea for the boilers and crew's daily consumption.
	   The ship has three accommodation decks which can house more than
40 people in all, and basic amenities like a dining hall, kitchen,
lounge, recreation room, gym, swimming pool and laundry facilities.
	   Puteri Delima is one of five Petronas Tankers ships which
deliver LNG to Japan, Taiwan and South Korea. It takes six days for
a vessel to reach Tokyo Bay in Japan from Bintulu in Sarawak.
	   Suhaidi, like many of his fellow officers on board the Puteri
Delima, began his career at Akademi Laut Malaysia or ALAM in
Malacca before signing up as a deck cadet under a Petronas
scholarship.
	   ``I wasn't very sure about what I wanted to do after completing
my SPM exams and thought of taking up law or medicine. But when I
saw a advertisement for shipping cadets, I was attracted and knew
that I was on my way to becoming a professional sailor.
	   ``I chose a career on a ship because I love working in a tough
environment. Desk jobs, suits and ties aren't for me. My family
members are very supportive. I personally feel that the prospects
for young people are good although many might think it is not
rewarding.''
	   Suhaidi's understudy, Deck Cadet Mohd Hatta Salmongel, 20, feels
that many young people are not aware of the challenges and perks
that the maritime sector offers.
	   ``My father encouraged me to join the merchant navy after I told
him about my plans to sail with Petronas. The pay is comparatively
better than many other jobs I was considering.
	   ``There's lots of fun and adventure in sailing. I was very
nervous when I boarded and trained on a ship for the first time
because I was not used to the conditions at sea. I have three more
years of training at sea and am looking forward to putting in about
15 to 20 years in this career,'' says Hatta.
	   To sign up as shipping cadets, the minimum qualification is a
Grade One in SPM with distinctions in science, physics and
mathematics. Prospective applicants should also be physically fit
with good eyesight, be able to swim and willing to endure long
trips away from home.
	   Supervising Suhaidi and Hatta is Captain Derek Wallace, a
55-year-old Briton who thinks highly of his junior officers.
	   ``I've been with many Malaysian cadets for over 10 years in
other vessels of similar capacity. These young men are very
enthusiastic because they pay very close attention to what they
have to learn.
	   ``They are well-behaved and polite compared to cadets in the UK.
But the only thing is, they need to speak out. Communication skills
are an important factor in keeping the ship going.
	   ``Many of the earlier batches of cadets were fluent in English
but I find the later batches less proficient. They have to buck up
because English is an internationally-recognised seafaring
language,'' says Wallace.
	   As master of Puteri Delima, the man has a huge task in keeping
the morale of his men high and delivering his cargo on time and
incident-free.
	   This responsibility, he says, will soon be managed by the junior
officers and cadets once they are ready to take the helm.
	   Steering the ship to its designated course and managing the
safety procedures on board are the deck officer's job. But this
task would not be complete without marine engineers like Third
Engineer Sharmee Abdul Hamid.
	   The pursuit of knowledge and adventure travel lured him into the
maritime sector as third engineer on board Puteri Delima.
	   The 24-year-old was sent by Petronas Tankers to train at South
Tyneside Maritime College in Britain for four years before being
posted to serve on board several of the Puteri-class tankers.
	   As Puteri Delima's third engineer, Sharmee is required to sail
for a period of four months before breaking for two-month shore
leave. Leaving one's family behind is a tough thing to do but this
sacrifice, he says, must be made if a person decides to choose a
career at sea.
	   ``I have a tight schedule to keep which occupies most of my
time. As an engineer, I am responsible for ensuring that the ship
sails with no downtime.
	   ``The safety of this ship and its crew takes top priority. This
requires me to be alert and careful in managing the ship's
engineering system.
	   ``It definitely pays off to see a smooth voyage to our
destinations. The bonus here is the temporary shore leave we enjoy
once we offload the LNG at ports in Taiwan, South Korea and
Japan.''
	   Supervising the transfer of technology and nurturing the
knowledge of our young engineering officers are the tasks of Chief
Engineer David McCallum. The 47-year-old Scotsman, whose task is
similar to the ship's master, has four engineering cadets under his
wing.
	   McCallum feels that the young men are being pushed very hard to
achieve the objective of running the vessels on their own.
	   ``There are many aspects of managing a vessel of this class that
we can't learn from books. You will need years of practical
experience. ``It is my job to see to it that these men are trained
to carry out their jobs but my main concern is the rapid pace that
they have to go through. It is fine if they can absorb so many
things in such little time.
	   ``But the challenge here is to handle real-time crises at sea.
Such situations can erode their confidence if they do not have much
experience.
	   But on the whole, we have a group of fine young lads who are
very dedicated to their careers. I think with time, they would be
able to lead the country's next generation of maritime engineers,''
McCallum concludes.
	   
</TEXT>
