<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-France-Opener,0477 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Despite promises, France centers on results, not the
</HEADLINE>
means &QL; 
 &UR; By RAF CASERT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CLAIREFONTAINE, France (AP) _ Adventurous words like ``audace''
_ daring _ haven't been heard much lately. French parlance again
has a touch of ``winning at all cost'' ahead of Friday's opening
match against South Africa.
	   Following a training session with a fully fit squad early
Wednesday, coach Aime Jacquet turned to tactics in the afternoon
and is expected to return to a much more conservative concept than
what was promised two months ago.
	   Gone are the thoughts of a three-man defense and a bolstered
attacking midfield. Back is the solid four-man defense and the two
defensive midfielders. Too much is at stake for any thoughts of
folly.
	   ``The important thing is to win,'' said playmaker Zinedine
Zidane, the man to whom the French will for to provide the creative
spice and add a sense of ``grandeur.''
	   ``The result before all, then it comes down to content,'' said
Jacquet, adding the first round games will all be ``close and
stressful.''
	   Youri Djorkaeff, who will be relied upon for a deft touch and
the inspirational pass, was very frank. ``We don't care to play
well and lose. We'd rather play bad and win.''
	   South Africa already has promised a physical game and a
defensive bulwark to contain the French in the first half before
hoping for a counter in the second to clinch a World Cup upset.
	   Jacquet warned his players not to throw caution to the wind, and
defensive backs Bixente Lizarazu and Lilian Thuram will have to
control their urges to make breaks on the wings so as not to expose
the defense to a counter.
	   It's a far cry from the days this spring when that grand Gallic
phrase ``audace'' was often on Jacquet's lips.
	   ``One does not exclude the other,'' he said Wednesday.
	   After Friday's game in Marseille, France plays Saudi Arabia on
June 18 and closes out its Group C campaign against Denmark on June
24.
	   The final two days ahead of the opening match will be spent
working on set pieces and on improving the flow from Zidane and
Djorkaeff to the forwards. Despite inspirational performances from
20-year-old David Trezeguet, Jacquet is expected to start Zidane's
pal Christophe Dugarry and the French leagues leading scorer
Stephane Guivarc'h.
	   The striker has only one goal in seven internationals,
increasing fears that France will rarely get more than one goal out
of a game.
	   ``If I don't score, it's because there are no chances,'' said
Guivarc'h.
	   That defense may have to come to the rescue again.
	   Central defender Laurent Blanc has saved France on countless
occasions, scoring a dozen goals for Les Bleus, which makes him
second in the scoring list among the 22.
</TEXT>
