<BODY>
<SLUG> BEING-THANKFUL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Being thankful for the small things that we have, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Being thankful for the small things that we have, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   NurmarinnaASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   RECENTLY, my brother, two sisters and I decided to buy our
father a gift, to show our appreciation for all his efforts in
bringing us up to be good people.
	   It was just a small gift, something that he needed badly in the
past few months but couldn't get around to buying, for obvious
reasons.
	   My brother and sisters made a collection. But not finding enough
to buy the gift, my mother chipped in and even included a small
card to go with it.
	   Having wrapped the gift, we all waited anxiously for dear Papa
to come home from work, and as soon as he arrived we presented him
the gift, accompanied by kisses and hugs.
	   Papa was very surprised as it was not his birthday nor an
occasion for gifts, and asked what it was for.
	   We replied that it was a gesture to show our love and gratitude,
seeing how hard he slogged everyday to earn enough money for all of
us, and especially knowing from our mother how he used to take with
him just a slice of bread for lunch in the office.
	   As an ordinary worker his pay is just enough for us to get by
each month, without any savings and treats that others may have,
like the occasional outings or new clothes.
	   Although we have what we want in terms of necessities, we do not
buy something new when we can still use whatever we have, like torn
shoes, faded and shrunk school uniforms, and books borrowed from
neighbours or relatives.
	   When there is a need to wear something nice for a special
occasion, mother will quietly borrow them from her relatives
without telling Papa about it, and sometimes use old dresses,
sewing over them again and again to make them look new.
	   I remember the day when I had to attend school on Childrens'
Day, and mother had to cut my elder sister's dress to patch on to
my old one which was too short and tight for me.
	   Though the dress still looked old and faded I was happy because
it was comfortable, and clean.
	   Papa opened his present and was shocked to find what he had
wanted all along, a Thermos flask that he could put his coffee in
to bring to the office.
	   With bleary eyes he thanked all of us, carefully rewrapped the
present and quietly went to his room.
	   We were all so happy to see the joy on his face and thanked God
for being able to buy him the flask.
	   The next day Papa came home from work and brought several
T-shirts for all of us, plus some nasi bungkus for dinner.
	   We were of course overjoyed to see new clothings, and ate the
food.
	   Early next morning when all of us were getting ready for school,
we overheard mother asking Papa for his flask, as she wanted to
fill it with coffee for him to take to the office.
	   And then we heard from Papa that with the receipt he found in
the gift, he returned to the shop to exchange it for the T-shirts,
and also to buy the food.
	   This is pure love, a parent's sacrifice for his children in
times of hardship.
	   In spite of the difficult circumstances around us, he would
rather see us happy and comfortable than satisfy his own need.
	   What is a flask if he can continue to keep his family happy, and
to see that we have food and clothing.
	   Let us have faith in each other, and be happy with whatever we
have.
	   Let us not succumb to pressure when times are bad, but be
thankful for the small things that we have.
	   And let us slog on until we overcome our problems whatever they
are, so that we can proudly say that we have tried, and have
succeeded in helping each other out.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
