<SLUG> BC-Germany-Train Disaster </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New uncertainty over death toll in German train wreck
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CELLE, Germany (AP) _ A week after postwar Germany's deadliest
train disaster, officials were still uncertain Wednesday about how
many people were killed in the crushed and twisted wreckage.
	   After lowering the death toll twice _ to 95 on Tuesday _ police
spokesman Michael Hanke said the number was now being raised.
``With certainty there were 96 dead, and possibly the number will
rise to 99,'' he said.
	   Forensic experts have been having trouble making a definitive
count because many of the bodies were mutilated.
	   In Hanover, 20 kilometers (13 miles) to the south, the Lower
Saxony state parliament held an hour of speeches and prayers in
honor of the victims of last Wednesday's crash.
	   The parliamentary president, Rolf Wernstedt, praised the efforts
of rescue workers and residents of Eschede, the village north of
Celle where the crash occurred.
	   Afterward, lawmakers joined rescue workers and victims'
relatives for a memorial service in Market Church, a restored
Gothic landmark that is the city's main church.
	   The service started at 11 a.m., around the same time that the
high-speed InterCity Express train derailed and slammed into the
support pillar of an overpass. The impact brought 200-300 tons of
concrete down onto the jackknifed passenger wagons.
	   ``It happened a week ago today at this time: the terrible noise
of destruction, the giant cloud of dust, the stillness and then the
screams,'' Lutheran Bishop Horst Hirschler said in his address to
mourners.
 &UR; (pfg-aet)
