<BODY>
<SLUG> GLORY-DAYS-OF-BADMINTON sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Remembering the glory days of badminton in Malaysia, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Remembering the glory days of badminton in Malaysia, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Yeoh Seng HongASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   FOR years, the threesome Eddy Choong, David Choong and Amy
Choong were just about the best in the world of badminton.
	   Eddy and David combined with devastating effect and demolished
every pair before them; David and Amy won a string of mixed-doubles
titles against the strongest opposition; the immaculate Eddy won 48
national and international Singles titles - a feat that is unlikely
to be surpassed.
	   Eddy, David and Amy lived solely for badminton and their efforts
have been crowned.
	   In 1959, I had a first glimpse of the ``Terrible Twins'' of St
Michael Institution, Ng Boon Bee and Tan Yee Khan. Our team met
Perak schools in the North Zone final. The match was played in the
old market, a derelict, ramshackle building of the colonial era.
	   The firepower was awesome. Tan was lanky and tall. Ng, the
``Pocket Hercules'', could jump like a Jack-in-the-Box and smash
with devastating effect. Needless to say the Penang schoolboys were
packed off with a 5-0 defeat.
	   From such humble beginnings, they went from strength to strength
and before long were world champions.
	   The ice-cool Dane, Morten Frost, had dominated the badminton
world for umpteen years. Recently the world witnessed our coach,
through his magnificent, tactical manoeuvre bringing down his
former Danish teammates.
	   Well done, Frost! In the doubles, Ong Poh Lin is without a peer.
His usual partner was Ismail Marjan. In the Thomas Cup of 1948 and
1952, he combined effectively with Ooi Teik Hock to prevail.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
