<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Drug Summit,0636 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kinkel says hard drug use up 20 percent in Germany last year
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ROBERT H. REID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Hard drug use in Germany rose 20 percent
last year and the damage ``must not be minimized,'' the German
foreign minister said Wednesday on the final day of the U.N.
special session on drugs.
	   Delegates from about 150 countries are expected to wrap up the
three-day conference Wednesday night by adopting a plan to curb
trafficking, money-laundering and narcotic cultivation by 2008.
	   During his speech to the conference, German Foreign Minister
Klaus Kinkel said drug users were ``getting younger all the time''
and the ``the range of drugs supplied ever wider.''
	   ``In Germany we have unfortunately since 1995 seen a steady
increase in the number of users of hard drugs, a rise of 20 percent
last year alone,'' Kinkel said without giving figures.
	   Kinkel urged greater international cooperation to curb
trafficking and applauded a recent declaration by China and
Southeast Asian nations to increase their own regional efforts to
combat drugs.
	   Kinkel indicated that Germany would not follow the example of
neighboring Netherlands and relax laws against ``soft'' drugs.
	   ``Drugs and the harm they do must not be minimized,'' he said.
``They are no token of the modern lifestyle.''
	   During the conference, leaders of drug-producing nations of
Latin America and Asia have blamed the global drug problem on
consumption in wealthy countries and begged them for help to
eradicate crops, offer farmers alternatives to growing cannabis,
coca and opium and for help in improving their own law enforcement.
	   ``Two or three years ago, people in Kyrgyzstan had only a
theoretical idea what heroin is,'' said Kubanychbek Jumaliev,
president of the former Soviet Central Asian republic. ``Nowadays,
it has become one of the main drugs on the illegal market.''
	   Before the conference, some private organizations criticized the
U.N. strategy, saying it was modeled on the U.S. ``war on drugs''
which they called an expensive failure.
	   ``Like the drug war itself, the U.N. drug summit was a
failure,'' said Dr. Ethan Nadelmann, director of the Lindesmith
Center which promotes alternative drug control strategies. ``Rather
than producing the intended unity, the drug summit exposed deep
divisions ... between drug war zealots who advocate spending on a
failed policy and the reformers who want new approaches to protect
our countries and our children.''
	   European delegates generally stressed the need for treatment and
rehabilitation of addicts, as well as programs to offer Third World
farmers incentives to stop growing narcotics.
	   During his speech Monday, President Clinton announced a dlrs 2
billion, five-year media campaign against drugs targeted at young
people. But U.S. officials were non-committal on U.N. proposals for
a growers' incentives program in Afghanistan, Myanmar and
elsewhere.
	   Washington opposes financing programs in countries which have
not been officially certified as U.S. allies in the drug war.
Neither Afghanistan nor Myanmar, formerly Burma, have been
certified.
	   Many countries resent the certification system as an insult to
sovereignty. Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo called for a
``balanced strategy'' in which ``no one can become the judge of
others and no one feels entitled to violate other countries' laws
for the sake of enforcing its own.''
	   But the conference has produced no calls from government
officials to follow the Dutch model and relax controls on ``soft
drugs.''
	   ``No government should jeopardize this situation by considering
to legalize narcotic drugs for other purposes than medical and
scientific ones,'' Danish Health Minister Carten Koch said Tuesday.
</TEXT>
