r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  DANGER-OF-ABUSEsked     06-10 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> DANGER-OF-ABUSE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Danger of abuse and favouritism in NRS real, not imaginary, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Danger of abuse and favouritism in NRS real, not imaginary, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Au Yung MeiASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   I REFER to Enoch Sng's letter (NST, May 27) on the New
Remuneration Scheme for civil servants which was introduced in 1992
and in particular, his claim that ``the NRS is beneficial to
Government employees, and the various workers' unions will vouch
for that''.
	   If the NRS is intrinsically beneficial, all teething problems
would have been ironed out by now, and we would not have a
continuous stream of complaints.
	   It is patently unreasonable for a so-called star performer to be
given a career-long monetary advantage over his colleagues on the
basis of a mere 12 months outstanding performance as perceived by
his superiors. A month or half-month's bonus is enough.
	   What happens if the so-called star performer under-performs
after being given a double or triple increment when no avenue
exists for withdrawal of these increments?
	   When department heads are appointed on a rotation basis (every
two years is not unusual) and the number of employees is large
(say, over 100), is it humanly possible for him to assess fairly?
Might not his judgment be superficial and impressionistic?
	   The NRS is indeed beneficial, but only to a handful of civil
servants, and at the unconscionable cost of disaffection among the
overwhelming majority.
	   Since everything hinges on the annual assessment by one's
superior and there is little transparency in the whole exercise,
the danger of abuse and favouritism is real, not imaginary.
	   As an ex-civil servant with nothing to gain, I sympathise with
my colleagues who are still in service, and whose esprit de corps
is slowly but surely being undermined by the inequities of the NRS.
	   At a time of national austerity, the Government can ill-afford
to stick to a remuneration scheme which is questionable and
unacceptable to the workers' unions.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
