<HEADLINE>
Treasury approval may prove to be a deterrent, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Treasury approval may prove to be a deterrent, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   D.D. DevanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   BESIDES the moral duty of all to bring home their cash
investments abroad to contribute towards overcoming the economic
downturn, the Government has provided a further incentive by
exempting earnings brought in by individuals from abroad from
taxation until the end of the year.
	   While this is appreciated, the need for individuals to submit an
application to the Treasury is not understood. One would have
thought that such approval should be applicable only to funds being
taken out of the country.
	   Are there circumstances where approval will not be given by the
Treasury? This seems contrary to the official policy to get back as
much of the funds as possible from abroad! The hassle of obtaining
this approval will serve as a deterrent especially when
comparatively higher returns are available for investments
overseas.
	   
</TEXT>
