<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Poland-World Bank </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Poland, World Bank discuss loan for mining restructuring
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ Finance Minister Leszek Balcerowicz met
with World Bank officials Wednesday to discuss loans totaling dlrs
1 billion for rescuing Poland's coal industry.
	   Balcerowicz said Poland has two weeks to present a detailed plan
to heal the once-thriving industry, which has debts exceeding 13.6
billion zlotys (dlrs 3.9 billion).
	   ``We can not wait. Losses are accumulating,'' said Balcerowicz,
who met with Basil Kovalsky, World Bank director for Poland and the
Baltic States.
	   The two agreed the mine industry must be privatized quickly.
Poland has already taken steps as part of overall industry reforms
in preparation for joining the European Union.
	   Over the next four years, 105,000 of Poland's 237,000 miners
will lose their jobs and coal production will be cut to 112 million
tons from 137 million tons last year.
	   By 2001, Poland expects the coal mines to turn a profit of 410
million zlotys (dollars 117 million).
	   World Bank director Kovalsky said the plan ``has the potential
to lay the basis for a competitive, efficient coal industry in
Poland.''
	   Coal mining, the leading hard-currency earner during communist
times, is still heavily subsidized under Poland's eight-year-old
market reforms. production.
	    &UR; (ms-aet) 	   
</TEXT>
