<BODY>
<SLUG> THE-PERVERSE-NATURE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
The perverse nature of campus bullies, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
The perverse nature of campus bullies, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Megat Ishak M. RashidASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MY brother recently enrolled in a local university and for the
first week was subjected to numerous, off-syllabus activities,
which included sleeping at 1am and waking up at 3am, being shouted
at and generally being inconvenienced.
	   It is hard to understand the limited mentality of such people
and their desire to maintain a tradition which is both infantile
and pointless.
	   As common sense would dictate, students who enrol at
universities are no longer children; they are to all intents and
purposes, adults. Why should adults be subjected to an introductory
period of humiliation and so-called
``getting-to-know-your-seniors''?
	   I graduated from a university in the United Kingdom where such a
tradition was nowhere to be seen, and yet a healthy student
atmosphere was apparent. That is why I propose that we abolish such
unhealthy practices.
	   Taken to extremes, we come across physical and mental abuse that
borders, and even crosses the line to criminal acts. Those guilty
of inflicting pain and humiliation on new students should not only
be expelled from their universities, but also be treated like
criminals.
	   The effect of such practice is three-fold.
	   First, it embodies a bullying attitude in senior students;
Second, it signifies that senior students are either retributive in
nature, and/or are lacking confidence in dealing with new students;
and third, each new generation of students will emerge into a
working society lacking in confidence due to the misplaced belief
that those before them should be feared merely because of
seniority.
	   The craving for ``control'' over the freshman, or to ensure the
freshman is courteous, polite, respectful towards them shows an
almost perverse desire for power without having the intelligence to
do so in a more constructive way.
	   In our pursuit to be recognised as a developed and civilised
nation, such absurd customs should be left in the past, where they
rightfully belong.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:THE-PERVERSE-NATURE sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
