<BODY>
<SLUG> ETHANOL-BECOMES-NEW-BOON sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHANOL BECOMES NEW ECONOMIC BOON, THE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
Ethanol Becomes New Economic Boon, The News &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE NEWS
   MEXICO
   ENGLISH
   CHRISTINE LARSONLATIN AMERICA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E.,

<TEXT>
2nd Floor WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax:
202-546-4194 COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE
OF FDCH, INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS
CONTAINED HEREIN MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO
WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Visions of garbage-fueled ``Back-To-The-Future'' cars became
more of a reality Tuesday as a two-day international conference on
the use of non-polluting ethanol fuel came to a close The
conference's purpose was to promote the production and use of
ethanol as a clean transport fuel. Ethanol is obtained from
renewable resources such as corn, sugar cane and any other organic
substances.
	   Sweden uses a variety of cellulose fibers such as potatoes,
wheat and wine in its ethanol production, Swedish Ambassador Karin
Elmbom said.
	   Ethanol is an alcohol that can be blended with or used in place
of current petroleum-based fuel products. ``Essentially anything
that has cells can someday be turned into a clean fuel,'' Elmbom
said. That means any organic waste material, including everyday
household garbage, could someday be converted into fuel energy. The
drawbacks in the use of cellulose are the lack of technology and
high production costs involved.
	   ``The prospect of putting our potatoes to use in another form is
certainly interesting, but we're going to have to weigh the
costs,'' National Confederation of Potato Producer's Executive
Director Ana Cecilia Rios said.
	   The conversion speed for producing ethanol alcohol from
cellulose material is, however, much longer due to its smaller
sugar content making the process more costly.
	   ``At this point it's technically tougher to produce ethanol from
cellulose than corn, for example,'' said Dave Loos, a member of the
U.S. Governor's Ethanol Coalition (GEC). Loos was at the conference
along with other U.S. officials to discuss Illinois state's success
with using corn in ethanol production. ``In Chicago, 90 percent of
the gas contains 10 percent ethanol, which not only significantly
reduces the effects of ozone depletion, but gives our corn
producers another revenue outlet'' said Loos.
	   Ethanol burns to produce water and carbon dioxide, a global
warming gas. It does not, however, produce acid-rain pollutants
such as sulfur or nitrogen oxides.
	   Since the introduction of the Gas Reformulation Bill - an
amendment to the Clean Air Act in 1990 mandating the phase in of
corn-based ethanol fuel in highly polluted U.S. cities - the price
of a bushel of corn has increased 20 percent. Phoenix, Ariz.,
Albuquerque, N.M. and most recently Las Vegas, Nev. fall under this
pollution-control mandate while many cities in California have
adopted similar measures.
	   New investment such as the construction of a 65-million-dollar
ethanol processing facility in Freeport, Ill. makes ethanol even
more appealing. The site will employ 25 people and will encourage
several other spin-off industries.
	   Mexican sugar cane growers want a piece of the action, as well.
Following dramatically reduced demand for Mexican sugar due to an
increase in the use of high fructose corn syrup, sugar cane used
for ethanol could revive sugar's tenuous market situation. Brazil
currently uses sugar cane for ethanol production and now mandates a
22-percent blend for a majority of its gasoline. 17-20 percent of
the cars - primarily Volkswagens made in Mexico and modified for
Brazil - run on 100-percent ethanol.
	   As a result of the conference, the GEC has decided to form an
alliance with the Mexican governors of sugar-producing states.
	   Not everyone is completely optimistic, though. ``I'm just not
sure if the economics are here in Mexico - I imagine ethanol is
going to need some type of subsidy to make it interesting for
investors,'' said agro-economist Ken Shwedel.
	   The United States just extended a 5.4-cents-a-gallon subsidy
until 2007 for ethanol production and now produces over 1.5 billion
gallons annually.
	   Ethanol, potentially seen as competition to Mexico's monopolized
petroleum market, may also have to overcome difficult political
obstacles to be successfully introduced in this country.
	   ``I think Pemex (Petroleos de Mexico) could really learn from
the Brazil experience,'' said Jeffrey Knight of the Wisconsin State
Department of Administration. ``Brazil has been successful in
integrating petroleum interests to make the fuel non-threatening to
the oil industry,'' he said.
	   Amoco Oil Company has taken the lead in the United States on
funding ethanol projects and research and British Petroleum and
Shell have also stepped into the ring. ``I'm not sure if these
companies are getting involved to appear environmentally friendly,
or just because it makes good sense,'' said Loos.
	   A foreign oil industry official said Pemex is in a great
position to get involved in ethanol because it already has access
to some of the chemical bases needed for processing. The only thing
lacking, he said, is a little vision and coordination on behalf of
Pemex executives.
	   Luis Tellez, Mexico's Energy Secretary gave a positive welcome
at the start of the conference saying that his department is open
to any new ideas and wants to strengthen ties to other energy
sectors.
	   ``It's encouraging to see his (Tellez's) participation in the
conference. It seems to me he is doing some pretty innovative
things,'' Shwedel said.
	   
</TEXT>
