<HEADLINE>
RM12.5m siphoned from bank branch, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
RM12.5m siphoned from bank branch, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Thanam VisvanathanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Tues. - A cashier spent just two weeks to siphon
about RM12.5 million from a Bank Bumiputra Malaysia Bhd branch in
Johor before disappearing overseas with RM5 million, it was
revealed today.
	   Initial police investigations showed that the 43-year-old man
might have used forged travel documents to flee either to China or
to Hong Kong.
	   Johor police have contacted the Interpol branch at the Federal
police heaquarters in Bukit Aman to facilitate investigations to
track down the fugitive.
	   It was learnt that the cashier - who had been solely responsible
for handling money at the BBMB branch in Johor Baru - had allegedly
kept aside a large sum of money daily to deposit into a fixed
deposit account in his name, at a Hongkong Bank Malaysia Bhd
branch.
	   It is believed he had been doing this for about two weeks in
April, taking out cash daily.
	   Following this, he went on leave for an unspecified number of
days and then failed to return to work.
	   Suspecting something amiss after the man's family had also
failed to locate him, the BBMB branch initiated an audit check. The
probe led to the discovery of discrepancies in documents relating
to cash deposits and withdrawals which were initialled by the
cashier.
	   When bank officials discovered that the man might have siphoned
about RM12.5 million, they lodged a police report at the Johor Baru
Central police station on April 30.
	   The NST understands that following the discovery of the loss,
the branch manager and his deputy were suspended, pending an
internal inquiry.
	   Police contacted Bank Negara in order to freeze all accounts in
the man's name and managed to recover RM7.5 million which was still
in his fixed deposit account at the Hongkong Bank Malaysia Bhd.
	   Johor Criminal Investigation Department chief Senior Assistant
Commissioner II Mohd Mokhtar Hassan said police were trying to
determine whether the alleged siphoning of funds was a one-man
operation or whether the fugitive might have had accomplices.
	   
</TEXT>
