<HEADLINE>
DEBTORS' GROUP ASKS LEGISLATORS TO STOP TALKS, THE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
Debtors' Group Asks Legislators To Stop Talks, The News &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE NEWS
   MEXICO
   ENGLISH
   TIINA TAPIALATIN AMERICA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E.,

<TEXT>
2nd Floor WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax:
202-546-4194 COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE
OF FDCH, INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS
CONTAINED HEREIN MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO
WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Citizens' Debtors Assembly (ACDB) appealed Tuesday to
opposition parties to end congressional negotiations on the bank
bailout fund (Fobaproa) issues, and to propose alternative options.
	   ``Banks should be given a deadline to recapitalize, absorb their
losses, and should negotiate individually with debtors to recover
part of their losses,'' said ACDB representative Gerardo Fernandez.
	   ``The Party of the Democratic Revolution and National Action
Party (PRD and PAN) are deceiving the public because their
negotiations in Congress will benefit only a small amount of
bankers,'' he said. To date, Fobaproa has overtaken 550 billion
pesos in bad bank loans, and the debt is increasing as banks are
being paid interest for some of the debt that was converted into
10-year bonds at cetes- (treasury notes) fixed interest rates.
	   Fernandez questions why cetes, more profitable for banks but an
extra burden for taxpayers, were issued instead of UDIs
(inflation-fixed treasury notes). UDIs would conserve the value of
money more, ``while cetes cause taxpayers to take on more debt.''To
annually prop up the cost of Fobaproa in interest rates alone,
Fernandez said ``government earnings need to increase by about 12
percent.''Both left-of-center PRD and right-leaning PAN have
threatened to stop the financial reform package in Congress if
Fobaproa issues are not dealt with.
	   ``Mexican citizens' position and responsibility, represented by
Congress, is not one of negotiating for anything, not for
democratic or political reform,'' Fernandez said.
	   Mishandling of Fobaproa in other ways has increased taxpayer
debt unfairly.
	   ``Fobaproa helps recapitalize banks that in theory will be
resold to foreign banks at ridiculous prices, take Citibank for
example,'' he said.
	   Analysts find it hard to lend credence to all debtor
organizations, however.
	   ``Populist groups are trying to get attention through publicity
stunts, so its hard to get any credibility,'' said Patrick Boucher,
Santander brokerage banking analyst.
	   Some of these groups do ``whatever is possible to get out of
their obligations,'' he said.
	   But not all are irresponsible. It is important to tell the
difference between groups that provide feasible solutions and those
that try to escape their debt, he said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE NEWS all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
