<BODY>
<SLUG> SAVING-THE-ENDANGERED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Saving the endangered species, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Saving the endangered species, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A NEWSPAPER report that the vast Endau-Rompin area has fewer
than five rhinoceroses from the 20 to 25 animals five years ago is
a clear indication of the increasing threat to Malaysian wildlife
and their habitats posed by the country's rapid development.
	   Thanks to the environment-conscious local print media, the
public has been reminded time and again that not only are the
Malaysian rhinos being threatened but also the tigers, tapir, orang
utan, elephants, leatherback turtles and river terrapins. In fact,
they are on the brink of extinction, included among the endangered
species in the World Conservation Union's red list. The country has
already lost two species - the Javan rhino and the green peafowl -
which once roamed the lowland regions. An anxious Wildlife and
National Parks Department has reported that the list of mammals and
birds under threat is growing. It laments that most of the
wildlife's habitat is in forests outside its jurisdiction and this
has impeded efforts to protect the animals.
	   Against this grim scenario, it was thus most appropriate that
Malaysia became the second country in Southeast Asia on Monday to
adopt the Asian Conservation Awareness Programme. The programme
will provide the opportunity to non-governmental organisations, the
private sector and the public to be actively involved in the
conservation of threatened wildlife.
	   The multimedia campaign launched to create awareness about the
possible extinction of endangered species caused by consumption and
buying of wildlife body parts appears to have the essential
ingredients to get the message across. The message ``When the
buying stops, the killing too''
	   should jolt the conscience of those who unknowingly contribute
to wildlife extinction. It is true that many people, particularly
the East Asian community and their overseas communities, may have
unwittingly contributed to endangering wildwife through regular
demand for medicine and other health products, ornaments and
jewellery made from animal body parts.
	   Belief in and adherence to traditional practices and ignorance
are contributory factors.
	   At home, it is encouraging that increasingly the Federal
authorities are moving towards greater protection of the country's
rich flora and fauna, particularly the endangered species. It is
the hope of those concerned with the environment that the new
National Biodiversity Policy will see better conservation of
wildlife resources, including some 6,000 animal species.
Undeniably, the policy can only be effective if State Governments
take the lead in its implementation as matters relating to land and
resources on land fall under their jurisdiction.
	   Globally, the campaign against the wildlife trade remains a
tough battle as it is lucrative and has a huge network. The
multi-billion dollar illegal wildlife trade ranks third after the
dadah and black market arms business. From the marketable products
which poachers can extract from the rhinos, bears, tigers,
elephants and turtles, it is not surprising that specific species
have been targeted for the protection programme. An arduous task
ahead for concerned countries notwithstanding, an all-out sustained
international effort towards depriving the traders of a market
through education and tough legislation coupled with stringent
enforcement, will undoubtedly have a potent effect given time.
There should be no let-up on this.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:SAVING-THE-ENDANGERED sked; CT:w; 
