w1289 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  SOCIAL-COHESIONsked     06-10 1597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> SOCIAL-COHESION sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Social cohesion, not just Howard's Government, may fall to `Hansonism', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Social cohesion, not just Howard's Government, may fall to `Hansonism', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   K.C. BoeyASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   NOT since Joh Bjelke-Petersen a decade ago has Queensland
figured as much in national life. Queenslanders in the sunbelt
northern Australian State go to the polls on Saturday with more
than the answer on who will form the next State Government hinging
on the results.
	   Prime Minister John Howard is keeping a close watch, as he
contemplates calling his own snap Federal election. So too his
fellow conservative partners in the Federal coalition Government,
the opposition Labor Party, and every one with an interest in where
Australia is headed.
	   Around this State election, the tensions of time-worn Australian
social division are building up to a new defining moment: country
suspicion of city, poor standing up to rich, black against white,
new immigrant versus Old Australian, battlers taking on the elite.
	   Just as with the then Queensland Premier Bjelke-Petersen in
1987, the tension is centred on one individual - this time on
Bjelke-Petersen's fellow Queenslander Pauline Hanson.
	   And just as with the failed Joh-for-Canberra campaign to draft
Bjelke- Petersen as leader of the Federal Government, the Hanson
appeal is to extreme conservatism. As with Queensland then, the
tide is surging from the heartland of populist simplicity - this
time diffused in a backlash against economic and cultural
insecurity.
	   Hanson, far from being the meteorite that Howard dismissed her
to be, has surfaced as the rock on which Howard's Liberal Party,
governing in coalition with the rural-based National Party, might
flounder.
	   Polls show the Liberal-National coalition Government in
Queensland is in danger of being routed. The opposition Labor Party
will be voted in to government with a big majority.
	   Ominously, Hanson's One Nation party could win up to four seats.
At the very least, it could hold the balance of power in the State
Parliament.
	   The inconvenience that would pose to State governance is the
least of concerns. The worry is what the rise of One Nation is seen
to mean, for Australian attitude to One Nation.
	   Queensland is the first electoral test for Hansonism, where One
Nation is putting up 79 candidates for the 89-seat Parliament.
	   Hanson herself had come into politics as an independent member
of the Federal Parliament. It was her controversial maiden speech
in Parliament in September 1996 that catapulted her into prominence
as the face of bigotry in Australia, spawning a phenomenon that
inspired the formation of the One Nation party.
	   A strong showing by One Nation in Queensland spells trouble for
the Federal election that Howard is poised to call. There, too, the
electoral fortune of the Howard Government is of secondary concern.
	   `Hansonism' threatens the very heart of Australian social
cohesion, and Australia's place in the region. As the former
Liberal Party leader John Hewson puts it, ``our aspirations for
integration with, recognition by, and leadership in Asia (will be)
annihilated''.
	   A credible showing by One Nation in electoral contests will
reinforce perceptions of a resurgence of racism in Australia. It
will stall the cause of Aboriginal reconciliation, and Australia's
engagement with the global community.
	   Howard last week launched his first personal attack on Hanson,
accusing her of fanning racism with behaviour verging on those of
the deranged.
	   Hanson had renewed her attack on the ``Aboriginal industry'' in
another speech in Parliament. It was a performance calculated to
milk publicity for One Nation in Queensland.
	   To the political pundits, Howard had played into the hands of
One Nation. Hanson is seen to have finally succeeded in goading
Howard into acknowledging her as a force in Australian politics.
	   The Howard reaction does not hearten the likes of social
researcher Hugh Mackay. ``The answer to Hansonism is not to clobber
Mrs Hanson but to offer an alternative view of Australia and a
superior set of values,'' says Mackay.
	   Howard is seen to fall short on that score. While raising his
voice against Hanson, he continues to refuse to write One Nation
off in his coalition Government's electioneering strategy.
	   He refuses to direct his party members standing for election not
to direct preferences to One Nation candidates.
	   Voting in Australia is compulsory, but elections are not
determined by a simple majority. A single-member preferential
voting system is used to ensure the winning candidate ultimately
has the support of the majority of voters.
	   In an electorate with more than two candidates, voters are
required to rank all candidates in order of preference, with the
votes of minor candidates distributed to the remaining candidates
until a majority is determined.
	   Thus in how-to-vote cards, candidates tell their supporters who
to direct their second and subsequent preferences to.
	   Howard has refused to tell his party members what to do about
One Nation candidates. Not only that, his State colleagues in
Queensland have directed their party members to put One Nation
ahead of the Labor Party in the elections.
	   The decision flies in the face of strong feeling among
conservative party members at State and national levels. They
include Howard's deputy, Treasurer Peter Costello, other State
premiers, and party elders such as former Prime Minister Malcolm
Fraser.
	   The decision smacks of the worst form of political expediency,
says Fraser. It gives One Nation a respectability it does not
deserve, at a time when its support is surging among disenchanted
voters espousing all sorts of causes.
	   Racism is only the most obvious ugly face of Hansonism. The
phenomenon is riding the tide of disillusionment with mainstream
politics, bringing together under one banner the most unlikely of
bedfellows.
	   Extremists of the ``lunar Right'' are marching in step with
members of the gun lobby, conspiracy theorists railing against the
loss of national sovereignty to global governance, economic
nationalists, supporters of the environmental movement and
population control, and people opposed to the multicultural and
Aboriginal ``industries''.
	   One thread through these disparate interests are libertarians
reacting against the ``thought police'' of mainstream politics, the
media and other institutions, and their alleged stifling of
political debate.
	   Some among the disparate interests vehemently stand up to
racism. Like journalist Paul Sheehan, who three weeks ago published
a book seen as likely to be taken up as ``the bible'' that the
semi-literate Hanson and her advisers neither had the brains nor
ability to articulate.
	   Sheehan's Among the Barbarians: The Dividing of Australia, went
into a second reprint days after its launch.
	   Sheehan is no redneck Hanson supporter. Indigenous rights and
culture ``are at the very centre of the Australian soul'', he
writes in an article inspired by his new-found fame.
	   The dramatic change in Australia's racial and ethnic mix since
World War II ``is one of the world's most successful cultural
transformations''.
	   And Asian immigrants ``have provided a jolt of energy and talent
that Australia needed''.
	   To Sheehan, the suppression of debate is a defining reality in
Australian politics in the 1990s. ``The deliberate submerging of
these issues, and the resentment against those who have imposed the
silences, is the real strength of Hanson,'' he says. ``It is not
her policies.''
	   Caught up in all this high-brow debate, and the repugnance of
racism, is the basic insecurity of country Australia, from which
Hanson draws most support.
	   ``The rise and rise of Pauline Hanson can be directly attributed
to the major political parties and their total lack of
understanding of life in the bush,'' one Letter to the Editor came
in from small-town Wonthaggi.
	   Country people can relate to Hanson's ``nervousness and lack of
understanding of the big picture''. As with any rural community,
life is ``pretty simple''. The fears of the community have little
to do with Aboriginal land rights and immigration from Asia. They
fear the loss of tariff protection and the ``not-so-level playing
field''.
	   This sentiment is strong at a time when a Bureau of Statistics
study on social trends shows that in the decade since the
Joh-for-Canberra drive, Australia has become richer, healthier and
cleverer, but not quite sharing it around. The rich are getting
richer, and the poor poorer.
	   ``Racism has no place in Australian society, town or country,
but will fester as rural communities slip further into recession,''
writes Mark Rennie in his letter to The Age.
	   ``History shows us that the first victim of hardship is
tolerance.''
	   The Queensland result will hold valuable lessons for Canberra.
	   
</TEXT>
