<HEADLINE>
HIGH-LEVEL TALKS SET TO BEGIN IN WASHINGTON D.C., THE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
High-Level Talks Set To Begin In Washington D.C., The News &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE NEWS
   MEXICO
   ENGLISH
LATIN AMERICA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E.,

<TEXT>
2nd Floor WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax:
202-546-4194 COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE
OF FDCH, INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS
CONTAINED HEREIN MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO
WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   U.S. and Mexican Cabinet members, as well as presidents Clinton
and Zedillo are set to start high-level talks in Washington D.C.
once the U.N. special summit on drug-trafficking finishes.
	   U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and her Mexican
counterpart, Foreign Relations Secretary Rosario Green, will head
delegations starting Wednesday that will focus on border issues and
how both countries can work together to halt drug-trafficking.
	   The two-day meeting will be the 15th binational conference
between Cabinet leaders from Mexico and the United States.
	   Fourteen working groups will tackle such varying issues such as
immigration, drug-trafficking, money-laundering, science and
technology, education and border issues, among others, said Jose A.
Zabalgoitia, spokesman for the Mexican Embassy in Washington. About
eight or nine Zedillo Cabinet members will attend the meeting,
Zabalgoitia said.
	   U.S. State Department Press Secretary Michael Hahn said a
similar number of Cabinet members from President Clinton's
administration will be attending.
	   The work sessions will be held after Zedillo and Clinton meet in
New York at a special U.N.
	   anti-drug summit, which focuses on controlling drug-trafficking.
Both leaders will discuss the Casablanca money-laundering
operation, as well.
	   After the meeting, Clinton and Zedillo will deliver a public
release together announcing ``greater cooperation in the war
against drugs'' by both Mexico and the United States.
	   It is possible that Mexican secretaries will hold interviews
with Clinton on Thursday, Hahn said.
	   It is suspected that both will discuss Operation Casablanca, an
affair that has caused a great deal of friction between both
countries.
	   
</TEXT>
