<BODY>
<SLUG> WORLD-CUP-MAGS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup mags to keep you on the ball, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
World Cup mags to keep you on the ball, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Tan Gim EanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   AS the clock ticks towards the World Cup '98 kick-off between
Brazil and Scotland (11.30 tonight), it's time to file away the
facts, figures, vital details and trivia on players and teams
meeting in France.
	   Where does a fan start?
	   AllSports' seven commemorative and special editions - all
published by Sunburst Communications - on this 16th soccer series
make an ideal curtain-raiser.
	   World Cup '98 (available in English, Bahasa Malaysia, Mandarin
and Tamil) traces the history of the Cup, from its inaugural match
in Montevideo, Uruguay, in July 1930, to the last meet in the
United States four years back.
	   This year, 32 teams will play in 64 matches - an increase over
the 24 and 52, respectively, in 1994. (Only 13 countries were
represented in Montevideo.) Japan, South Africa, Croatia and
Jamaica are making their Finals debut.
	   The magazine introduces the 10 host cities and venues, and lists
the match guides and tables of the eight groupings. The
complimentary wall chart should help diehards keep track of who's
playing who, when, and the scores.
	   Bookmakers favour reigning champions Brazil to lift the Cup for
a fifth time, and the task of turning on the magic rests on hotshot
Finals debutant Ronaldo (a reserve in the last tournament). Can the
richest footballer in the world deliver, without Romario as
partner? Will three- time winners Italy and Germany equal Brazil's
feat? Where do France, England and Argentina stand in the
competition?
	   As they say, the ball - which, by the way, has been modified
over the years - is round, and the team with the right combination
of skills, tactical know-how, grit and luck will lift the FIFA
World Cup, a trophy that has its own special story.
	   The current official match ball, called the Tricolore, is
designed to fly higher, faster and straighter - making it a
nightmare for goalkeepers.
	   Is there a `Dream Team of the 20th century'? Yes, and AllSports'
line-up includes ``Kaiser'' Franz Beckenbauer; Bobby Moore, who
skippered England's victory in 1966; ``Hand of God'' scorer
Maradona; 1974 Dutch captain Johan Cruyff; Eusebio, alias the
``Black Pearl'', top scorer (nine goals) for third-placed Portugal
in 1966; and the inimitable Pele, who made his debut at 17 in
Sweden 40 years ago. The publishers also pick the 16 teams expected
to make the second round.
	   Both selections grace the pages of World Cup '98 Superstars
(editions in English and Bahasa). These tabloid-sized mags provide
full pin-ups of 39 top footballers and all the competing teams,
plus leading goal scorers in the last 68 years. They also profile
the coaches, a good number of whom were key players in their time.
	   France '98 also packs morsels on match venues and schedules. Its
bonus is a Star Parade of those expected to shine on French turf.
	   Brazil, which claimed permanent possession of the original Jules
Rimet Trophy after being the first to win a hattrick (1958, 1962,
1970), takes front spot in this magazine's Hall of Fame. Readers
also get to walk down memory lane with the players who figured most
in the decades dating back to 1930.
	   Don't miss the bite-size items on what happened during USA '94.
Reports had it that French husbands, fevered by wives calling them
to the dinner table in the midst of matches, often turned violent.
Over 10 per cent of battered wives blamed the World Cup for their
bruises and welts.
	   Many Thai schools closed a day after the final match, to enable
students to catch up on sleep! Over in Rio de Janeiro, a Brazil fan
stabbed his brother-in-law to death for supporting Italy, the
losing finalist.
	   All in, these World Cup publications provide a wealth of
information on a sporting fest that's expected to attract 37
billion television viewers worldwide (32 billion previously) over
the next 33 days. The range of their focus - from country flags to
team crests to top-ranking goal scorers and the arduous road
leading to France - should keep readers in top form till July 12.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
