<SLUG> BC-Jamaica-Nabisco,0196 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nabisco buys Jamaican cookie company
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) _ U.S. food giant Nabisco Inc. has bought
Butterkist Ltd., a Jamaican cookie company owned by the Mechala
Group, for dlrs 9.4 million (Jamaican dlrs 330 million).
	   As part of the deal, another Mechala company, Facey Commodity
Ltd., will become the sole distributor of Nabisco's non-snack
product lines in Jamaica.
	   The 190 employees of the 29-year-old Butterkist will be offered
30-day contracts while Nabisco considers staffing cuts.
	   Nabisco says it will make Jamaica its base for pushing products
in the the Caribbean. It has regional sales of dlrs 75 million,
which it hopes to increase to dlrs 100 million with the acquisition
of Butterkist.
	   Joseph A. Matalon president and chief executive officer of the
Mechala Group, called the deal ``a win-win situation for Mechala,
for NABISCO and for Jamaica generally.''
	   Nabisco makes Oreo cookies, Life Savers candy, Ritz crackers and
other packaged foods.
	   The company operates in more than 80 countries, has 77
manufacturing facilities outside of the United States and employees
27,000 people worldwide. 	   
</TEXT>
