<SLUG> STATE-TO-ENSURE-BALANCED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
State to ensure balanced development, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
State to ensure balanced development, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MERSING, Tues. - The Johor Government will ensure that the State
economy gains resilience through continuous pursuit of balanced
development.
	   This is besides the short-term measures aimed at cushioning the
effects of the current economic problems, Menteri Besar Datuk Abdul
Ghani Othman said today.
	   He described the long-term strategy for balanced development as
an integral part of the reformation process that should
continuously be pursued by Umno and the Government.
	   Speaking at a news conference after the Johor Umno Convention,
he summarised the main issues deliberated during the closed door
function at the Sibu Island Resort.
	   Ghani, who is also Johor Umno liaison committee chairman, said
the need for balanced development, between material and spiritual,
small and big industries, agriculture (including food production)
and industrial sector and between the public and private sectors,
was emphasised during the convention.
	   He quoted the example of the Italian economy, which was strong,
partly due to their small and medium-scale industries.
	   Ghani said as the country was facing economic problems, the
convention called for greater solidarity and strength within the
party, so that efforts could be focused on overcoming the problems
at hand.
	   ``We (Johor Umno) agreed to hold an economic convention to
discuss in detail the steps which can be taken in the near term to
help ease the problems.''
	   He said the convention also agreed that in the efforts to
overcome economic woes, justice, including social justice, must be
upheld.
	   ``The measu1res should not only promote growth, but maintain
justice.
	   Therefore, we need measures to ensure that traders and small
entrepreneurs are not neglected.''
	   These, he said, would include helping small traders in Johor
Baru city to carry out their businesses.
	   Ghani said the need to develop small towns, such as Ayer Hitam,
into commercial centres to provide more opportunities for local
businessmen, was also touched by the delegates.
	   In his assessment of the convention, which was officially opened
by Deputy Prime Minister and Umno Deputy President Datuk Seri Anwar
Ibrahim on Monday, Ghani said the convention had generated
important and intelligent ideas from divisional leaders who were a
combination of young and long-serving party members.
	   
</TEXT>
