<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-World Cup-Street Battles, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Known Scottish hooligan among those arrested in Paris clash
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with later police report; police saying known hooligan
among those arrested; TRIMS &QL; 
 &UR; By JOCELYN NOVECK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Late-night clashes between drunken soccer fans,
Parisian youths and riot police left 34 policemen injured,
including one in critical condition after being hit in the head
with a beer bottle, police said Wednesday.
	   The others were only slightly injured, according to a police
report. The man in critical condition was the commander of a
motorcycle unit.
	   About 15 people were still in custody late Wednesday. Among them
was Stephen Stapley of Scotland, well known as a soccer hooligan in
his country, a police official said on condition of anonymity.
	   The incidents Tuesday night and early Wednesday on the stately
Champs-Elysees boulevard marred the festive atmosphere of the
meticulously planned pre-World Cup events.
	   Police had to use tear gas to disperse drunken soccer fans and
apparently also Parisian youths who threw bottles and tried to
knock down a phalanx of policemen, using a steel barrier as a
battering ram.
	   Among the others in custody were a second Scottish fan, an
Algerian, a Liberian and a Congolese, police said. The
nationalities of the rest weren't immediately known.
	   The World Cup kicked off Wednesday afternoon with the opening
match between Brazil and Scotland. Thousands of Scottish fans have
descended on Paris for the match.
	   Some of them claimed the violence wasn't all the fault of the
soccer fans. They said youths from Paris' troubled suburbs actually
began the disturbances.
	   ``Some young kids started throwing things just for the hell of
it, I think,'' said Derek Christie, from Fife in Scotland.
	   His friend, John Morrison of Inverness, said: ``Everybody was
having a good time, and I don't think they liked it.''
	   When the unrest between the groups got out of hand, the police
charged, they and other witnesses said.
	   In London, the Foreign Office confirmed that two Scots were in
custody in Paris, but said it was for a separate incident from the
troubles in the center of Paris.
	   ``They are currently being held in police custody on assault
charges,'' a spokesman said.
	   In the early morning hours Wednesday, bands of soccer fans were
roving the streets, many desperately seeking transportation back to
where they were staying.
	   Outside a Scottish pub in the Marais district, a group of
partying fans in kilts blocked traffic. When a taxi tried to drive
through, the fans surrounded it, a few of them jumping on the hood
and pounding on the windows. The taxi, and other cars, hastily
retreated.
	   The trouble began around 10:30 p.m., when dozens of people threw
beer bottles at the helmeted riot police, who responded by charging
at them. The fans dispersed. The incident was repeated several
times.
	   About an hour later, just after midnight, several hundred
people, led by young fans armed with security barriers as battering
rams, tried to break through a line of policemen on the
Champs-Elysees.
	   This time police charged them and used tear gas. The fans
quickly dispersed.
	   (jn-parf-mr-var) 	   
</TEXT>
