<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-Mad Cow 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU takes first step to close mad cow chapter
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMS; UPDATES with reactions; CHANGES byline &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT WIELAARD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ Declaring British meat safe again, the
EU head office on Wednesday proposed to lift a global ban on
British beef exports imposed in 1996 because of ``mad cow''
disease.
	   ``We do feel British beef is safe,'' EU Farm Commissioner Franz
Fischler said. Yet it may take months before British beef reaches
dinner tables in the rest of the European Union and beyond.
	   The measure goes first to a panel to veterinary experts from all
15 EU states.
	   Their first meeting is Friday but the experts are divided. If
they don't resolve their disagreement, the lifting of the ban will
be put to a vote by the EU agriculture ministers.
	   Germany, in particular, is wary about resuming British beef
sales, fearing a consumer backlash. Chancellor Helmut may not be in
the mood for concessions in the runup to September elections.
	   In London, British Prime Minister Tony Blair welcomed Fischler's
proposal. However, mindful of the problems that may lie ahead, he
added, ``There's still a long way to go. I counsel caution until we
are through all the various stages of the European negotiation.''
	   The export ban was imposed in March, 1996, after reports that
mad cow disease, a brain ailment in cattle known as bovine
spongiform encephalopathy, is related to an equally fatal human
variant, Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease.
	   The ban started a public health scare causing a slump in demand
for beef across the EU which spent billions of dollars to buy up
beef to support farmers.
	   Also, the ban soured Britain's relations with its partners to
the point that then conservative prime minister John Major
boycotted routine EU business.
	   When the ban was imposed, Britain's beef exports were worth dlrs
8.1 billion a year.
	   Fischler put strict conditions on the resumption of British beef
exports: the meat must be deboned and from animals aged between six
and 30 months of age. The cattle must be killed in approved
slaughterhouses and hail from herds guaranteed to be BSE-free.
	   ``We will do our best to ensure the measures will mean no
further risks for consumers anywhere in Europe,'' Fischler said.
	   The suggestion to lift the entire ban on British beef exports
came two weeks after the EU announced exports from Northern Ireland
could be resumed. That region, unlike the rest of Britain, has a
cattle database that lets officials trace mad cow disease with any
sense of confidence.
	   Though other EU nations have reported cases of mad cow disease,
the overwhelming majority have been in Britain. The outbreak was
blamed on the practice of feeding cattle the ground remains of
sheep and other animals.
	   Britain banned such feed Aug. 1, 1996, and now claims all cattle
born after that ban are free from the disease.
	   Britain also slaughtered 3 million cattle judged at risk and
forbade the sale of cattle parts thought most likely to harbor the
disease.
 &UR; (rw)
</TEXT>
