<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Kuwait-Deportations </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kuwaiti government closes deportation center for stateless
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUWAIT (AP) _ The Kuwaiti government has closed a detention
center for stateless Arabs that had drawn criticism for years from
human rights activists and Kuwaiti lawmakers.
	   The detainees are known as bidoun, taken from the Arabic
``bidoun jinsiya,'' or ``without citizenship.''
	   Most bidoun, who number about 120,000, have lived in Kuwait all
their lives. For decades, they were treated as citizens, but
beginning in 1985, the government made them illegal residents.
	   The government says most of them have other passports that they
are hiding to get Kuwaiti citizenship and its benefits.
	   The Interior Ministry said Wednesday that most of the detainees
were released on bail or were allowed to leave the country and that
the government had closed the Talha Deportation Center.
	   The rest were moved to a smaller center, it said. It did not say
how many remained, but 600 people were held there last month.
	   The inmates at Talha were bidoun with no identification papers
and no permanent residence or debtors who could not leave the
country before they paid what they owed. They also included some
Iraqis who had refused to return home.
	   Human rights groups and lawmakers have criticized the center,
which was set up at a school after the 1991 Gulf War that freed
Kuwait from a seven-month Iraqi occupation.
	   They said some detainees were held there without court orders,
sometimes for years. Dozens have gone on hunger strikes or slashed
their wrists to demand freedom.
