w1317 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Soccer-US     06-10 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-US,0619 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: U.S. says Germans lack respect
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos XLF101-107 &QL; 
 &UR; By RONALD BLUM &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAINT-JEAN D'ARDIERES, France (AP) _ Germany may talk the talk
about respecting the U.S. soccer team, but American players don't
believe it.
	   ``If I could sense any weakness, they may be overconfident,''
midfielder Preki Radosavljevic said Wednesday. ``That could be our
chance.''
	   Ever since the draw in December, Germany has said it must be
careful not to overlook the Americans, who've risen to No. 11 in
the FIFA rankings.
	   ``They say in the papers they do, but deep down they don't
respect us at all,'' Radosavljevic said. ``They think we have a
long way to go. I think they'll take us seriously, but I don't
think they respect us.''
	   So how does the United States react as it prepares to open World
Cup play against the Germans in Paris on Monday?
	   ``It doesn't make you mad, it makes you try harder,'' he said.
``I want our team to prove to everyone in the world we can play in
America.''
	   U.S. forward Brian McBride, who spent one season in Germany,
wasn't as outspoken as Radosavljevic, but he left the same
impression.
	   ``There is definitely a different psychological attitude to this
team,'' he said of the Germans. ``I think they're a very confident
team. I don't think they disrespect us. They're just very confident
in themselves.''
	   At the U.S. camp in the Beaujolais countryside, it's clear the
Americans feel they have something to prove.
	   ``When I was younger, it was always great to be the underdog,''
McBride said. ``Now it's the same way. Before, it was the bottom of
the ninth. Now, it's the soccer field.''
	   Radosavljevic may have more to prove than most. The
Yugoslav-born midfielder spent nine seasons in U.S. indoor soccer,
about as far from the World Cup as you can get in soccer while
still drawing a paycheck.
	   From 1992-95, he went back to the outdoor version, scoring four
goals in 46 games for Everton in England's Premier League and seven
in 47 games for Portsmouth at the next level down.
	   He was 33 by the time he became a U.S. citizen in 1996 and
joined the American team. During all those years, he hadn't thought
about playing in a World Cup.
	   ``Not for States,'' he said, speaking English with a heavy
accent. ``I was thinking a little bit playing for Yugoslavia,
especially when I was playing in England. But they never called me
_ and here I am.''
	   In February, he scored one of the biggest goals in U.S. history,
giving the Americans their first victory ever against Brazil. The
Brazilians had been 8-0 against the Americans, outscoring them 19-0
since 1930.
	   News of that game blew through the soccer world like a storm,
and Radosavljevic became a marked man. When the Americans played
the Netherlands 11 days later, two or three defenders usually
stayed close to him.
	   ``In those situations, Preki has got to learn to give up the
ball rather than dribbling,'' U.S. coach Steve Sampson said.
	   Radosavljevic's role in this World Cup appears to be as a sub.
He came off the bench to score in consecutive games against Brazil
and Costa Rica at the CONCACAF Gold Cup last winter.
	   ``I don't know any player in the world who likes to come off the
bench,'' he said. ``I think it's a difficult role.''
	   When the Americans meet Yugoslavia in their final first-round
game on June 25, it will be the day after Radosavljevic's 35th
birthday. He said he doesn't hold any grudges against his former
country.
	   He just wants a win.
	   ``That,'' he said, ``would be a good present for me.''
	   (rb/jw) 	   
</TEXT>
