<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kuchma approves harsh measures to increase revenues, slash deficit
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ President Leonid Kuchma gave the government
a two-month deadline Wednesday to find ways to slash government
spending and increase revenues.
	   Ukraine is struggling to get its economy in order while it tries
to negotiate new loans from the International Monetary Fund. At the
same time, it is facing frequent strikes and protests by unpaid
workers, including a miners strike that began last month,
	   An IMF mission is expected in Kiev this week to assess Ukraine's
progress in implementing conditions for a dlrs 2.5 billion loan.
	   Last month, the government met one of the key conditions,
slashing the planned budget deficit to 2.3 percent of gross
domestic product from 3.3 percent, although the plan still needs to
be approved by the largely leftist parliament.
	   The IMF refused to approve a loan to Ukraine last year because
of the former Soviet republic's stalled economic reforms.
	   Kuchma's decree also forbids Cabinet and particularly the
Finance Ministry from considering appeals for tax breaks or the
cancellation of tax debts from other ministries, as well as from
regional executive bodies and enterprises.
	   (sms/ls) 	   
