<HEADLINE>
Fresh on the shelf, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Fresh on the shelf, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Tan Gim EanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SAYINGS OF BUDDHA - Teachings on Spiritual Cultivation
illustrated and interpreted by Tsai Chih Chung (Asiapac): Transient
acts, ego, desire, evil, disaster and suffering. Offset these with
endurance, detachment, proper beliefs and thinking, acceptance,
truth - road maps laid down by the Buddha 2,500 years ago. ``No
universal truth contains the ego-self,'' he stressed. Take the
middle path and purify your will. Rise above the pollution of the
mind and slowly, you'll arrive at the ultimate destination -
serenity.
	   FICTION TOM CLANCY'S OP-CENTRE: Balance of Power created by Tom
Clancy and Steve Pieczenik (HarperCollins): This fifth title in
Clancy's Op-Centre series, which highlights US intelligence and
crisis management technology, takes the action to Spain. Rumours
are rife that someone is out to start another civil war. Who, and
why? As the Spanish and American diplomatic service join forces to
avert such strife, an Op-Centre representative in Madrid is
assassinated. What next?
	   EATERS OF THE DEAD by Michael Crichton (Ballantine Books): In
the 10th Century, Arab courtier Ibn Fadlan headed north from
Baghdad into what is now Russia. During his three-year journey, he
encountered the Vikings, a race who appalled him with their
barbaric customs. Sexually wanton women, filthy surroundings and
ruthless human sacrifices. Crichton draws from Fadlan's manuscript
and sends him out again, this time on a fictional encounter with
``the monsters of the mist''.
	   NON-FICTION MANGLISH - Malaysian English at its Wackiest by Lee
Su Kim (Times Editions): Say it anyway will do. It don't matter as
long as you connect.
	   In short, Malaysians readily mangle words and expressions when
they flock together. Hang grammar, tenses and pronunciation. Only
cheh kai folk care about that. More shiok to absorb all the slang
and ethnic terms, and be understood.
	   ONLY THE PARANOID SURVIVE by Andrew S. Grove (Doubleday):
Sudden, unexpected change can throw the best laid plans awry. How
do you keep a rein on calendar, career, customers and emotions when
chaos reigns? Grove, named Time magazine's Man of the Year 1997,
examines how ``tidal waves''
	   affect business, and how they can be harnessed to strengthen an
organisation. Given his experience helming Intel, his slant is on
computers and high-tech industry.
	   DIALOGUE: Rediscover the Transforming Power of Conversation by
Linda Ellinor and Glenna Gerard (John Wiley &AMP; Sons): A dialogue is
not just talk. It involves thinking aloud, widening information
arteries, and taking responsibility for one's actions. In short, it
is the springboard to ``being the change you wish to see''. Good
dialogues centre round questions which make up the larger picture.
They get at the root of recurring problems and encourage creative
thinking.
	   THE CHINESE BUSINESS ELITE IN INDONESIA AND THE TRANSITION TO
INDEPENDENCE 1940-1950 by Twang Peck Yang (Oxford University
Press): Arrivals from China (called the totok) and the Outer
Islands, combined with the home-grown Peranakan Chinese of
Indonesia, make up the country's commerical bourgeoisie. How did
this community operate? What sort of partnerships did the Chinese
businessmen forge with, say, Indonesian revolutionaries or the
power-holders? Twang taps written and oral sources to collate his
research.
	   THE FENG SHUI WORK BOOK by Wu Xing, illustrated by Meilo So
(Asiapac): Health, prosperity and happiness, the triple goals of
life, are yours for the taking once you learn how to tap your ch'i.
Bad feng shui can be righted by using the Pa Tzu compass to map
your lucky/unlucky directions.
	   From home to office, the Wu Xing team of Joanne O'Brien, Martin
Palmer, Zhao Xiaomin and Eva Wong show how you can improve your
environment, room by room.
	   TRADER VIC II: Principles of Professional Speculation by Victor
Sperandeo (John Wiley &AMP; Sons): Lies, fallacies and distortions are
rampant in investment. Sperandeo sieves through them and plucks out
a sound investment philosophy, principles of market forecasting,
trends of money, credit and the business cycle, lessons on the
stock market, and the personality of a stock trader.
	   
</TEXT>
