<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-Kosovo, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Defense ministers to seek plans for Kosovo intervention
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Russian quotes, possible NATO measures &QL; 
 &UR; By JEFFREY ULBRICH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) - With the Serb-led Yugoslav army beefing
up its forces in Kosovo, NATO defense ministers face a growing
belief that the only way to stop the violence may be direct
military intervention.
	   U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen and his 15 NATO colleagues,
meeting at alliance headquarters here Thursday and Friday, are
expected to order military planners to take a hard look at the
intervention option, whether that be sending in troops, conducting
air strikes or enforcing a no-fly zone.
	   ``The worsening of the situation makes it more than advisable to
work out credible options for military action, to have them ready
for a political decision at any time,'' German Defense Minister
Volker Ruehe told reporters.
	   Cohen acknowledged ``a general consensus there should be
accelerated planning'' and that ``all NATO members feel an
increased sense of urgency.''
	   ``There is a genuine concern throughout the region that if this
goes unchecked, it could have much wider implications than just
Kosovo,'' he said.
	   NATO ambassadors worked late Wednesday on detailed instructions
for the military, including a clear statement of the objective of
any intervention.
	   Also under debate was a series of immediate measures, including
air maneuvers in the next few days over Albania and Macedonia as a
show of strength, moves to military establish training and exercise
centers and using NATO transport to help cope with refugee flows.
	   More than 250 people have died in clashes between government
forces and the Kosovo Liberation Army, armed wing of the Albanian
independence movement. Ethnic Albanians, who make up 90 percent of
the province's population, demand independence from Serbia, the
larger of two republics in Yugoslavia.
	   The United States and its allies support autonomy for Kosovo but
oppose rebel demands for independence.
	   In recent days entire villages in Kosovo have been flattened and
thousands of people driven from their homes.
	   ``Kosovo is in grave danger of becoming another Bosnia,'' said
Carlos Westendorp, the High Representative in Bosnia, the man
responsible for enforcing the civilian aspects of the Dayton peace
accords.
	   ``It is as if we repair one house, only to discover the one next
door is burning down,'' he said. ``This is supposed to be the year
of returns to Bosnia, but it is rapidly becoming the year of the
exodus from Kosovo.''
	   The United States and the European Union have imposed tough
economic sanctions on Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, but
few hold out much hope that will result in a government pullback in
Kosovo.
	   ``We have learned the Serbs don't respond to pressure unless it
is military pressure,'' said a senior NATO official, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
	   NATO military planners have for the past two weeks been
following earlier instructions to study indirect options for
pressuring Milosevic. Those involve dispatching up to 20,000 troops
to Albania and Macedonia, including reinforcement of the existing
750-man U.N. force in Macedonia, and helping both countries secure
borders while dealing with refugees and arms smuggling.
	   But, noted another NATO official, ``With the events of the last
week, shoring up the periphery seems of secondary value.''
	   Intervening in Kosovo would require a sound legal basis.
	   The United States is backing a British effort to win U.N.
Security Council approval for a resolution authorizing ``all
necessary means'' to deal with the situation in Kosovo.
	   The Russians have opposed this so far. President Boris Yeltsin
says he will try to use his influence with Milosevic, but remains
firmly against intervention.
	   ``Urgent measures are needed there,'' acknowledged Russian
Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev after a meeting with Belgian
officials. But he added: ``I think we haven't explored all the
peaceful measures that we can use.''
	   (ju-pa)
</TEXT>
