<HEADLINE>
Election Commission making preparations for Sabah polls, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Election Commission making preparations for Sabah polls, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KOTA KINABALU, Tues. - The Election Commission has started
making preparations for the Sabah State election which is expected
to be held within the next nine months.
	   Election Commission chairman Datuk Harun Din said early
preparations were necessary to ensure the election was conducted
smoothly.
	   Based on last year's electoral rolls, 697,336 people are
eligible to exercise their voting rights compared to 598,312 in the
last State election in March 1994 .
	   ``If the State election is held this year, we will use last
year's electoral rolls.''
	   Harun said although the dissolution of the State Assembly was
the prerogative of the State Government, it must be noted that its
five-year term would end in March next year.
	   ``It (election) might be held at any time and therefore we want
to be fully prepared,'' he told a Press conference after opening a
two-day course for returning officers today.
	   Harun said the commission was also checking on old ballot boxes
to determine if they could still be used or needed to be replaced.
	   Harun said the commission had identified 603 polling centres and
1,085 polling stations throughout the State for the election.
	   About 5,000 will be involved in conducting the election which is
expected to cost the commission about RM5 million.
	   Harun disclosed that 13,917 names were struck off the State
electoral rolls over the last three years after they were found to
have registered using the same identity card number with different
names or had moved out of the State.
	   On the re-delineation of the election boundaries, Harun said it
was not done to give advantage to any political party.
	   Certain political parties claimed that they had a better chance
of winning after the drawing of the new boundaries.
	   Harun also reiterated that the commission would be more flexible
in dealing with objections filed on nomination day.
	   ``Nomination is not an exercise to reject but to accept
candidates,'' he said, adding that the commission would not like to
see people making a mockery of the election.
	   
</TEXT>
