<SLUG> BC-Israel-Jerusalem </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Jerusalem's Arab population growing faster than Jewish
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Jerusalem's Arab population is growing far
faster than the Jewish population and is expected to make up almost
half of the city's population in 20 years, according to a report
released Wednesday.
	   Arabs make up 30 percent of Jerusalem's population. Because of
their higher birthrate, they are expected to grow to 45 percent
over the next two decades, according to the Jerusalem Institute for
Israel Studies.
	   ``It's a matter of concern when the non-Jewish population rises
a lot faster than the Jewish population,'' Jerusalem Mayor Ehud
Olmert told reporters.
	   Since 1967, when Israel captured east Jerusalem, the city's Arab
population has increased by 164 percent while the Jewish population
has increased by 113 percent, the institute's report said. In 1967
Arabs made up about 25 percent of the city's population.
	   In 1996, the latest year for which figures are available, the
city's Arab population increased by 3.7 percent, while the Jewish
population increased by one percent.
	   Jerusalem had a population of 602,100 at the end of 1996, of
which 180,900 were Arabs and 421,200 were Jews.
	   Some 5,900 people left the city during 1996 _ 5,700 of them
Jews. Most of those who left were secular Jews driven out because
of Jerusalem's high cost of living.
	   Olmert recently issued a plan to assure that the Jews remain a
majority in Jerusalem. The plan calls for the annexation of Israeli
towns west of Jerusalem.
	   vb-hla
</TEXT>
