<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-World Cup-Chic Souvenirs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Designers, artists offer pricey World Cup souvenirs
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) - From a Niky de Saint Phalle sculpture to a Hermes
scarf, World Cup souvenirs may never been so pricey, - as French
artists and top designers cash in on soccer mania.
	   Eighty contemporary artists from all over the world are showing
works inspired by the little round ball at an upscale Parisian
gallery.
	   For the fashion-conscious, there's a limited edition Louis
Vuitton soccer ball for the well-heeled.
	   It's covered with the traditional brown leather emblazoned with
the famed LV initials and costs 2,800 francs (drls 466).
	   Nini Ricci has come up with a black-and-white soccer ball you
can wear. It's a leather purse with two white straps and sells for
9,500 francs (dlrs 1,583).
	   Hermes, known for creations celebrating special events including
the bicentennial of the French Revolution, toasts the soccer
extravaganza with a scarf depicting a soccer player kicking balls
to the four corners of the silken square.
	   At 1,490 francs (dlrs 248), it runs no more than the other
Hermes designs.
	   Among the works on show at the Enrico Navarra gallery is a Saint
Phalle free-standing piece with two soccer players in brightly
colored uniforms. One is bouncing a ball on his knee while the
other rolls on the grass.
	   Other pieces include multi-screen video art by U.S. artist Nam
June Paik and an accumulation of mascots under plexiglass by French
pop artist Arman.
	   The gallery's the most expensive is an oil painting by Francesco
Clemente which goes for 1.5 million francs, while the cheapest is a
digital image for 12,000 francs (dlrs 2,000) by Michael Roy.
	   But soccer fans on shoestring budget needn't despair. France is
overflowing with cheap T-shirts, pins and socks all decorated with
the World Cup mascot.
	   (ma-dgs) 	   
</TEXT>
