<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Netherlands-Holocaust Survivors </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Institute to probe government's postwar treatment of Holocaust
</HEADLINE>
victims &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) _ Prompted by lingering concerns,
the Dutch government has ordered an investigation into its postwar
treatment of Holocaust survivors and other World War II victims.
	   The probe will be launched next year by the well-respected
Netherlands State Institute for War Documentation, David Barnouw,
the institute's spokesman, said Wednesday.
	   The investigation was prompted by recent controversies that
pointed to insensitive treatment of Dutch Jews and mismanagement of
their possessions after the war.
	   ``The question is whether the government and local officials
were there to receive them (survivors) properly after the war,''
said Barnouw.
	   The probe will also examine the treatment of other victims,
including Gypsies and Jehovah Witnesses, as well as former
prisoners of Japanese camps in the colonial Dutch East Indies, now
Indonesia.
	   One incident, which was revealed last year, was a selloff by
Dutch civil servants of valuables that belonged to Holocaust
victims.
	   During the sale in 1968, Finance Ministry employees auctioned
off _ among themselves and at bargain-basement prices _ jewelry and
other valuables belonging to Dutch Jews who died in Nazi death
camps.
	   Over 75 percent of Dutch Jews _ more than 100,000 people _
perished in the Holocaust.
	   Those who survived faced an uncaring postwar government
oblivious to their sufferings, said Ronni Naftaniel, a spokesman
for the Jewish organization, the Center for Information and
Documentation on Israel.
	   ``The major complaint was the coolness of the government,'' said
Naftaniel.
	   He said government red tape had also prevented Jews from
reclaiming their possessions after the war. Even today, some
families are still trying to recover their assets.
	   Although the investigation will not lead to reparations, it can
still help heal old wounds.
	   ``Survivors are not satisfied with the way the government dealt
with them then, they are trying to get back some understanding and
sympathy,'' Naftaniel added.
	   (jc) 	   
</TEXT>
