<HEADER>
w1341 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  SHAKESPEARE-ON-SCREENske     06-10 1530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> SHAKESPEARE-ON-SCREEN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Shakespeare on the big screen, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Shakespeare on the big screen, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   WATCHING Shakespeare films is more fun than reading about them.
I realised this sombre truth when reading a recent pair of books:
Shakespeare and the Moving Image, edited by Anthony Davies and
Stanley Wells, and Filming Shakespeare's Plays, by Anthony Davies
(both Cambridge University Press).
	   They are a leaden consequence of The Growth of Academic
Criticism (Stanley Wells), itself an outcome of the days when film
courses were introduced into what had hitherto been unsullied
Departments of English.
	   ``In my day,'' growled an Americana academic, ``films were what
we saw when we cut lectures, not went to them.'' Film reviewers in
those days included Graham Greene (whose film criticism is
first-class) as well as Pauline Kael. But now academics have moved
in, if not taken over. Films of Shakespeare are ``useful
resources'' and ``educational tools'' (Ace Pilkington). Their
Commentaries follow. As the French military say, ``L' intendance
suivra''.
	   An immediate consequence is a peculiarly arid species of
formalist analysis. Did you know that the average length of takes
in Olivier's Hamlet is 21 seconds, which is a little more than
Kozintsev's Hamlet, and that the takes in Tony Richardson's Hamlet
average 27 seconds? Go on, bring that nugget along with you to your
next dinner-party, and set the table on a roar.
	   I gleaned it from Neil Taylor, who adds, ``The high-angle shot
can easily communicate moral significance''. Not to me it can't.
All I can see is directors ringing the changes, in concert with
cameramen who like to set their crew shinning up the rigging, and
hoping to impose upon gullible reviewers. Your film bore is a bore
absolute.
	   Still, some themes emerge. There is the eternal ``tension
between text and visuals''. As a general rule, a Shakespeare text
may well need 50 per cent to be cut for cinematic purposes. (This
is not absolute, as Branagh's full-text Hamlet shows; but that was
a controversial experiment.) The peculiar gift of the camera, its
capacity to record surfaces, really has to be indulged. Besides,
cameras are getting better all the time. The technology was in its
adolescence for the black and-white Romeo and Juliet of 1936. That
couldn't show us much of Verona; Zeffirelli's Romeo and Juliet
(1968) could.
	   For Zeffirelli, the towns (Verona was shot in Gubbio, Tuscania
and Pienza) became ``an additional character''. Nowadays, the
camera is so eloquent and precise an arbiter of reality, so
advanced a Chorus to the action, that it demands rights that were
never plausible even a couple of decades ago.
	   Technology will not solve the director's problems. After all,
what does Shakespearean reality look like? An unthinking naturalism
is no kind of policy. Take As You Like It. As I've pointed out, you
can have osiers (willows) and you can have olive trees; they
co-exist in the text. But you can't have them co-existing in the
real world, not if you want Arden to be in Warwickshire. They
belong to different climates and regions.
	   The landscape of The Tempest has the same ambivalence. Is it a
Mediterranean, sub-tropical island, or something much cooler, as
near home as the Scillies? The director will have to choose his
location, and choose the bits of it to record, and through which
lens. And filter.
	   Anyway, what is the camera for? Kozintsev gave the
fundamentalist answer: ``The advantage of the cinema over the
theatre is not that you can even have horses, but that you can
stare closer into a man's eyes; otherwise it is pointless to set up
a cine camera for Shakespeare.''
	   There's a moment in his King Lear where a boat is shown beating
up against the river. Even in the spacious days of Soviet budgets,
it must have been an expensive boat, fitted out to be of its
period. Kozintsev holds the shot for about one second. That's it,
no more boat. Kozintsev did not, as it were, overvalue ``horses''.
	   Then there's the recurring problem of comedy. This is a
well-known difficulty, and Shakespearean films have not cracked it.
Nearly all the best Shakespeare films have been tragedies or
histories. And there's a reason: comedy requires a live audience,
the lack of which poses a killing threat to the film.
	   I once saw a live RSC production of As You Like It just after
the TV version had been screened. The difference was enormous. The
screen version was drab, inert, the acting absorbed into the green
textures of the trees that the camera unwisely made love to. The
stage Touchstone struck up a rapport with his audience, and kept
them in good spirits. Interaction made the comedy work.
	   Michele Willems tells the story of a Merchant of Venice made for
French TV. The actor playing Launcelot Gobbo had rehearsed
successfully performing before an audience of technicians,
cameramen and actors. When silence was required in the studio for
the filming, he became panic- stricken, and the comic quality of
his playing went down. In the end the director felt obliged to cut
the scene. The actor needed an audience, and he needed laughs. Is
it possible that a director may one day opt for canned studio
laughter?
	   The proliferation of Shakespeare films leads to that stock
academic resource, Compare and Contrast. Peter Brook's King Lear
and Grigori Kozintsev's King Lear came out in consecutive years, as
though they had agreed to supply examiners with off-the-peg
questions. ``Show how Brook's treatment of Cordelia differs from
Kozintsev's.'' A student might have to think a little about the
question; the examiner, not at all.
	   I allow though that the occasional insight can arise, and I was
rather taken with a woman student's quoted remark, ``that whereas
Oliver's Henry is the lover every man would like to be, Branagh's
is the lover every woman would like him to be''. Not glamour, but
sincerity is the word! (Discuss) Today's films are
inter-referential. That is to say, there are several pre-existing
versions of some key plays; in the latest, the director will want
to display his awareness of precedent. Branagh's film of Henry V
defines itself in relation to Olivier's film. It is no exaggeration
to say, to react adequately to Branagh you have to know Olivier.
	   Take the climactic shot of Branagh's Agincourt sequence. ``The
long slow tracking shot across the battlefield of Agincourt after
the battle, across the corpses and the survivors, as Henry walks
across it with a dead boy in his arms, is a clear definition of the
film's central attack on the values of war, a recognition of the
costs of battle. But it is also a deliberate inversion of the most
famous shot in Olivier's film, the long tracking shot of the charge
of the French knights at the beginning of the battle.''
	   (Peter Holland) Olivier's French charge from right to left,
Branagh's Henry walks from left to right. This is the consequence
of that. I find this just, but depressing. One is drawn into an
ever-widening pool of allusion. The heroic age is over, when
creative geniuses explored new territory. Now people make movies
about other people's movies. As Gombrich said, ``All art owes more
to other art than it owes to Nature''.
	   Let us draw the conclusions. The Shakespeare filmography is
vast. What films ought one to know about? I'll offer a list of a
dozen films as a core canon. The list is personal but not
idiosyncratic, and I think pretty well everything in it would be
generally agreed. TV versions and ``free adaptations'', such as
Kurosawa's, are excluded.
	   I begin with Reinhardt's A Midsummer Night's Dream (1936), the
first film of modern times one can take seriously. (James Cagney's
Bottom is excellent, and Mickey Rooney's Puck much better than
legend allows.) After that comes Olivier's great trio, Henry V
(1944), Hamlet (1948), and Richard III (1955).
	   Then comes Mankiewicz's Julius Caesar (1953), memorable for
Marlon Brando's Antony.
	   Orson Welles' Falstaff/Chimes at Midnight (1965) covers the two
parts of Henry IV, and contains some astonishingly realistic battle
scenes.
	   Zeffirelli's Romeo and Juliet (1968) showed just what an Italian
could do with the textures of Italy.
	   Kozintsev's Hamlet (1964) I consider superior even to Oliver's.
The same director's King Lear (1970) is a landmark, to be set
alongside Brook's King Lear (1969).
	   Branagh's Henry V (1989) and Much Ado About Nothing (1994) are
not to be missed.
	   Other candidates we will pause upon.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:SHAKESPEARE-ON-SCREEN sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
AP-NY-06-10-98 1155EDT
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
