<SLUG> NEW-NORDIN-BRIDGE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New Nordin Bridge over Perak River opened to traffic, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
New Nordin Bridge over Perak River opened to traffic, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PARIT, Tues. - The new Nordin Bridge, connecting Parit town and
Tanjung Belanja was opened to traffic late yesterday.
	   Many motorists who expected it to to open in the morning
following an announcement by Deputy Transport Minister Datuk Railey
Jeffrey last week, were disappointed to see it was still closed,
forcing them to use the old Bailey bridge.
	   Only the motorcycle lanes on both sides were open to traffic.
	   The 279-metre two-lane Nordin Bridge across the Perak river,
which is part of the Federal Route 73 between Parit and Beruas, was
constructed to replace the old bridge of the same name built in
1954.
	   The old bridge was damaged by the 1969 floods. Bailey bridges
have been used since then.
	   According to State Insfrastructure and Public Utilities
Committee chairman Datuk Ong Ka Chuan, the bridge could not be
opened earlier because of ``minor technicalities'' such as the
absence of road signs and markings.
	   Work also had to be carried out to level the riverbank slopes
under the bridge.
	   Construction of the RM10.5 million Nordin Bridge began in 1995.
It was built based on the concept of Prestressed Segmental Box
Girder.
	   The total width of the bridge is 11 metres. Its height from the
normal water level is 9.46m, about 4.07m above the highest flood
level in the area.
	   With the opening of the bridge, motorists will be assured of
better access to the State's coastal areas such as Beruas, Pantai
Remis, Sitiawan and Lumut. Before 1928, ferry services linked the
two sides of the river.
	   The first crossing was a pontoon bridge suitable only for small
vehicles. When it collapsed in the 1931 floods, ferry services
resumed until the concrete submersible Nordin bridge was
constructed in 1954.
	   However, the coastal areas are also accessible via the Ipoh-Sri
Iskandar-Lumut road.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
