<BODY>
<SLUG> HOTELS-STILL-NEED-WORKER sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hotels still need at least 160,000 workers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Hotels still need at least 160,000 workers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ainon MohdASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Tues. - The hotel industry is still short of
workers and has not seen much retrenchment, even with the economic
slowdown, said Culture, Arts and Tourism Minister Datuk Sabbaruddin
Chik.
	   He said the booming tourism and hospitality industry needs at
least 160,000 workers to cater for 100,000 rooms with a ratio of
two workers per room. There are now 130,000 workers in the
industry.
	   He said with most city hotels maintaining a 70 per cent
occupancy rate for the first half of the year, the demand for
workers would be even greater.
	   ``Right now, we are still employing foreign workers. I do not
think there is any decision to send them back immediately. However,
this is applicable only to those who are not working as frontliners
such as the cleaners and kitchen helpers.''
	   Sabbaruddin said this to reporters after witnessing the signing
of a Memorandum of Understanding between HRR Travel-Trade
management services and Wigan and Leigh College, United Kingdom.
	   With the memorandum, Wigan and Leigh College will work in
collaboration with the newly-established Travetrade College of
Hospitality and Tourism to offer internationally-recognised
qualifications in the field of hospitality and tourism.
	   Also present were chairman of Travetrade College Ibrahim Ahmad,
its managing director Leela Mohd Ali and Wigan and Leigh College
vice- principal Frank Brogen.
	   He said statistics compiled by the World Travel and Tourism
Council showed that travel and tourism are the world's largest
employer, generating more than 120 million jobs worldwide, hiring
one in 15 workers.
	   ``Although we are just recovering from a bad spell during the
two haze- hit months last year, the negative effects of dengue,
cholera and coxsackie diseases, the weakening ringgit has increased
tourists arrivals from the United Kingdom and US.''
	   ``If the haze does not recur this year, we can expect to see an
average of 70 per cent occupancy rate for all hotels. We are
confident of attracting 6.8 million visitors this year,'' he said.
	   Sabbaruddin said last year tourism revenue was RM10.5 billion
from an estimated 6.5 million visitors, a decline of 13 per cent
compared to 11.5 billion from 7.1 million visitors in 1996.
	   In view of this, he said, the country's tourism industry was in
urgent need of quality tourism education.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
