<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria-Political Prisoners </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Uncertain fate for those imprisoned under Abacha
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Nigeria &QL; 
 &UR; By TIM SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ They stare blankly from newspaper ads
placed by desperate loved ones _ plaintive ads with haunting
headlines like ``Where is Femi?'' or ``Whatever happened to
Bagauda?''
	   They are the faces of those who dared to criticize or resist
Nigeria's deceased strongman. Scores who disappeared during Gen.
Sani Abacha's five-year dictatorship remain imprisoned, and there
is lingering uncertainty over their fate under the new military
regime.
	   Throwing his opponents behind bars was a harsh hallmark of
Abacha, who died Monday of a heart attack. Now Nigerians are
waiting to see if his successor, Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar, will
show mercy and release at least some political prisoners.
	   Despite strident appeals from human rights groups, there were no
signs Wednesday that Abubakar was even considering freeing any of
the several hundred government critics imprisoned by Abacha, who
jailed thousands during his rule.
	   It appeared highly unlikely that the top political prisoner _
businessman Moshood Abiola _ would win his freedom anytime soon.
Abiola was the presumed winner of 1993 presidential elections
before Abacha declared the results invalid and seized power in a
coup.
	   Abiola was accused of treason, a crime punishable by death, for
resisting Abacha's annulment of the elections. Jailed without a
trial, he remains in prison, a symbol of Abacha's tyrannical rule.
	   ``Releasing prisoners of conscience imprisoned for defending the
most basic human rights would give a strong message to the Nigerian
people and to the international community that this is a government
ready to allow the exercise of fundamental freedoms,'' Amnesty
International said in a statement.
	   Although Abacha's government in May released 142 inmates ranging
from obscure dissidents to traffic offenders, none of the
best-known political prisoners was among them.
	   Those include Abacha's former right-hand man, Gen. Oladipyo
Diya. In April, he was sentenced to death by firing squad for
allegedly plotting to topple the government last December. Diya,
54, claims he was framed; the sentence has not been carried out.
	   Many of Nigeria's most prominent prisoners were sentenced in
connection with an alleged 1995 plot to unseat Abacha, though
critics have long charged the allegations were invented to lock
away opponents. Twenty-two people, including politicians, activists
and journalists, were convicted in connection with the alleged
plot. Among them:
	   _ Gen. Olusegun Obasanjo, 62, Nigeria's head of state from
1976-1979. Obasanjo, who is serving a 15-year treason sentence,
voluntarily relinquished the presidency after an election and went
on to became a formidable critic of Abacha.
	   _ Beko Ransome-Kuti, a medical doctor and brother of the late
Afrobeat music star Fela. He was convicted of being an ``accessory
after the fact to treason'' and is serving a 15-year sentence.
	   _ Four journalists sentenced to 15 years for ``accessory after
the fact to treason'' for their coverage of the coup attempt trial.
On Wednesday, Paris-based Reporters Without Borders wrote to
Abubakar urging him to free the four, among 15 jailed Nigerian
journalists.
	   Other prominent prisoners include Frank Kokori, the president of
Nigeria's Oil Workers Union. He has been held in detention without
charge since a three-month oil workers' strike he led in 1994.
	   Dr. Frederic Fasheun, who took over as leader of the Campaign
for Democracy after Ransome-Kuti was arrested, has been held since
February 1997 in connection with a spate of deadly bombings that
rocked Lagos. He has not been charged.
	   Food, water and medicine are in short supply or nonexistent at
prisons, said Nwabueze Okoro, vice-chairman of Nigeria's Civil
Liberties Organization. Political prisoners are refused visits and
are often held in hidden locations, he added.
	   Ogaga Ifowodo, a senior researcher with the CLO, was arrested
last November.
	   ``There have been no charges. They haven't held a trial,'' Okoro
said. ``We don't even know where he is.''
	   (bk/ids)
</TEXT>
