<SLUG> BC-Russia-Military Deaths </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian military crisis: More dying now than during Chechen war
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ More Russian servicemen died last year, in
peacetime, than the year before, when Russia was still bogged down
in its war in Chechnya, according to statistics released Wednesday.
	   At the current rate, even more will die this year.
	   The figures, released in parliament and reported by the
ITAR-Tass news agency, offer some of the starkest evidence yet of
the crisis affecting Russia's military.
	   From January to April of this year, 132 members of the armed
services committed suicide, according to the figures contained in a
resolution passed by the State Duma, the lower house of Parliament.
	   The resolution expressed the Duma's concern over the harsh
conditions in the military. Over the past several years, the
Russian military has been plagued by plunging morale, grim living
conditions, and a rash of suicides, hazing deaths and
soldier-on-soldier shootings.
	   ``The actions of officials that have caused this situation in
the army and the navy border upon crime,'' the Duma resolution
said.
	   According to the Duma statistics, 1,037 members of the army and
navy died in 1996, the last year of the war in Chechnya. In 1997,
the number of deaths rose to 1,057. For the first four months of
this year, 477 died. If that rate persists, more than 1,400 can be
expected to die this year.
	   (ml/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
