<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Air France-Strike, 8th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Air France reaches agreement with striking pilots
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: AMs. UPDATES with new color from airport, background on
privatization. Trims. ADDS photo numbers &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos PAR104/105 &QL; 
 &UR; By DEBORAH SEWARD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ After all-night talks, pilots agreed on Wednesday
to end a 10-day strike that has kept Air France from flying players
and fans to the World Cup and soured confidence in the company _
and the country.
	   Nobody really celebrated the agreement, in which the pilots
accepted Air France shares for salary cuts, something the company
had proposed originally.
	   The carrier said it would take 48 hours for all service to
return to normal. At Charles de Gaulle airport, north of Paris, red
lights ominously flashed ``annule'' and ``canceled'' for most Air
France flights Wednesday.
	   Only hours after the strike ended, the World Cup got under way
with the first match, Brazil vs. Scotland.
	   The strike's end did little to appease irritated passengers and
airport workers.
	   ``The pilots can do what they want, but I was against their
strike,'' said Nathalie Seulin, who works at the information desk
at Charles de Gaulle. ``Air France was picking up again, and now
they've lost everything.''
	   ``The pilots are like babies with pacifiers in their mouths,''
said Didier Bernard, a 38-year-old security guard at the airport.
``As soon as you take it out, they cry.''
	   Jean-Cyril Spinetta, president of Air France, called the
agreement a good compromise for the company, employees and
passengers.
	   But he added that the consequences of the strike were ``heavy,''
and said the company had lost a billion francs (dlrs 166 million.)
	   ``Now we have to think of confidence, confidence in Air France,
confidence in its clients,'' he said.
	   In concessions to the pilots, the carrier said it would scrap a
two-tier salary scale, under which new pilots earned less than
their colleagues. The highly paid pilots felt that that system
undermined cockpit solidarity.
	   The pilots seemed satisfied.
	   ``On the whole, the agreement is a good one for everybody,''
said Christian Paris, a spokesman for the SNPL, the main pilots'
union.
	   ``The company had its constraints and its objectives to achieve.
I think it will be able to reach them,'' he said.
	   The strike, coming as the world focused on France, had deeply
embarrassed the government.
	   It inconvenienced thousands of World Cup fans, who had to switch
airlines at the last minute or find alternative transportation.
	   Prime Minister Lionel Jospin welcomed the agreement _ but said
it had been too long in coming.
	   ``But I hope the company above all will benefit, because that is
my primary objective and what guided me throughout this period,''
he said after a Cabinet meeting.
	   Besides disrupting the World Cup, the government had feared the
strike could jeopardize investor confidence and eat up profits
ahead of plans to partially privatize the state-owned airline.
	   Wednesday's agreement was reached with the SNPL, the main union
representing the vast majority of Air France pilots.
	   The pilots had been protesting 500 million francs (dlrs 83
million) in proposed salary cuts. Air France had said the cuts were
needed to provide capital to modernize the airline, which was saved
from bankruptcy in 1993 but reported profits in 1996 and 1997.
	   Air France said part of the agreement involved guaranteed
training for young pilots, at least part of which would be paid for
by the company. The salary-for-shares swap is voluntary.
	   As well as the airline strike, France has been hit in recent
days by walkouts by train drivers, baggage handlers, and some bus
services. There were no major walkouts Wednesday.
	   (parf-dgs-jn)
</TEXT>
