<BODY>
<SLUG> RM5.2M-GAMBLING-DEBT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MP with RM5.2m gambling debt: PBDS to probe, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
MP with RM5.2m gambling debt: PBDS to probe, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUCHING, Tues. - Parti Bansa Dayak Sarawak said today it would
investigate allegations that one of its Members of Parliament owed
Perth-based Burswood Casino A$2 million (RM5.2 million) in gambling
debt.
	   Secretary-general Dublin Unting said if it was true, the matter
would be brought before the party's supreme council.
	   Asked whether he knew who the MP was following an AFP report
from Perth today identifying the MP as a senior member of the PBDS,
Unting said he did not.
	   PBDS president Datuk Leo Moggie when contacted in Kuala Lumpur
said it was a personal matter which would be discussed ``when the
time comes''.
	   The PBDS has six MPs. They are Jimmy Donald (Sri Aman), Jawah
Gerang (Lubok Antu), Datuk Sng Chee Hua (Julau), Billy Abit Joo
(Ulu Rajang), Datuk Leo Moggie (Kanowit) and Joseph Mauh Ikeh
(Selangau).
	   In a front-page report today, The Malay Mail said the MP was one
of eight Malaysian high rollers to be served with writs to recover
bad debts totalling RM10.8 million.
	   The others are doctors, lawyers and businessmen. They owe the
casino between RM120,000 and RM2.4 million each, dating as far back
as 1994.
	   AFP reported from Perth today that the writs would be issued in
Perth in about a month and would be served on the MP in Malaysia.
	   The report quoted Christopher White, a director of the
investigation firm Asean Protective Services as saying that the
debts were incurred at Burswood in December 1994 and January 1995
while the MP was holidaying in Australia.
	   The firm was engaged by Burswood to investigate and prosecute.
	   ``We have attempted to negotiate with him since 1995 and he has
refused to take part,'' White said. ``He made offers and counter
offers but finally refused to pay.''
	   White said there were dozens of Malaysians said to owe an
estimated A$25 million in gambling debts to casinos across
Australia.
	   He said the move to initiate legal proceedings marked a change
by Australian casinos which had previously preferred to negotiate.
	   ``We are well aware that these people have assets and, it would
appear, are refusing to pay only because in the past, the casinos
have not taken legal action,'' he said.
	   White said the debts occurred well before the Asian economic
problem.
	   ``Most of these debtors had the ability to pay then - and most
still do.''
	   Meanwhile, Bernama reported that the MP today made a
``significant down payment'' towards settling the debt and would
pay the balance in instalments.
	   
</TEXT>
