<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Collymore Apology, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Villa striker apologizes for fracas with girlfriend
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Updates with Villa statement

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Aston Villa striker Stan Collymore has apologized
for punching and kicking his celebrity girlfriend in a Paris bar
during a World Cup party _ an incident which could jeopardize his
career with the club.
	   Ulrika Jonsson, 30, a Swedish-born television personality,
returned to her home in England following the incident Monday
night. On Wednesday, she announced that she had ended her
relationship with Collymore.
	   ``I would like everyone to know that I am fine and I confirm
that my relationship with Stan Collymore is now over,'' Jonsson
said.
	   Collymore's adviser and agent Paul Stretford confirmed witness
reports, including that of a Scottish Television news reporter,
that the player hit and kicked Miss Jonsson at a late night World
Cup party for Scotland fans on Monday.
	   Scottish Television reporter Martin Geissler said Collymore
``dragged her out of the bar into a back room, pushed her to the
ground and aimed kicks at her head. She was lying on the ground
screaming and bar staff then grabbed Collymore and threw him out.''
	   Stretford read a statement issued by Collymore, 27, in which he
admitted that ``a stupid and silly argument had developed
throughout the course of the day.''
	   ``My actions were totally reprehensible, something I am not
proud of and finding very difficult to come to terms with. In a fit
of petulant temper I struck out at the girl I love and immediately
regretted my actions, but by then it was too late.
	   ``I could hide behind a facade of excuses and no comments but
petulance, jealousy and possibly having too much to drink are the
real reasons behind this regrettable and avoidable incident.''
	   Collymore also confirmed that he had been head-butted by someone
in the bar, and he apologized to that unidentified man ``for
causing him to feel that he had to take such action.''
	   Collymore said he had privately apologized to Miss Jonsson.
	   Collymore played in some of England's World Cup qualifying games
but was left off the squad for the finals in France.
	   He was Britain's most expensive player when he transferred from
Nottingham Forest to Liverpool for 8.5 million pounds (dlrs 13.8
million) in 1995. Collymore never lived up to his billing and later
moved for 7 million pounds (dlrs 11.4 million) to Aston Villa,
where he also has been a disappointment.
	   His future with Villa was uncertain after the latest incident.
	   ``Naturally we are very disappointed,'' the Birmingham club said
in a statement. ``The player is not due back until July 8, but we
will be talking to him to discuss the position at the earliest
possible opportunity.''
	   Collymore's status was further put into jeopardy when club
chairman John Gregory confirmed he was interested in signing
Italian striker Fabrizio Ravanelli.
	   (sw)
</TEXT>
