<SLUG> BC-France-G-7 Meeting </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Deputy finance ministers discuss Russia, Asian crisis at G-7 talks
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) - Russia's battered economy and the Asian financial
crisis were at the center of talks Wednesday among deputy finance
ministers of the world's leading industrialized nations.
	   No new financial aid packages for either area were announced.
	   Following the regularly scheduled Paris meeting, U.S. Deputy
Secretary Lawrence Summers said the Group of Seven industrialized
countries were ready to consider additional aid for Russia as
``necessary and appropriate.''
	   Confidence in the Russian economy has been shaken recently as a
result of a sharp slide in the stock market, a debilitating miners'
strike and the sluggish rate of economic growth.
	   Summers said the G-7 nations welcomed ``in particular recent
actions to strengthen tax administration.''
	   The Russian government's chronic inability to collect taxes has
left it unable to pay state workers and forces the government to
service a heavy debt.
	   Summers called for quick implementation of the IMF program and
of reforms to accelete growth, saying they are ``the most crucial
actions Russia can take to build market confidence.''
	   The G-7 include the United States, Canada, Japan, the United
Kingdom, Italy, France and Germany. Russia now participates at all
major summits.
	   The G-7 officials also discussed the weakness of the yen.
	   (dj-dgs)	   
</TEXT>
