w1385 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OAU-Ethiopia-Eritrea     06-10 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OAU-Ethiopia-Eritrea </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
African leaders approve peace mission to Eritrea, Ethiopia
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By GLENN McKENZIE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   OUAGADOUGOU, Burkina Faso (AP) _ A delegation of African leaders
will visit the troubled Horn of Africa region in a bid to end a
deadly border dispute between Eritrea and Ethiopia, the
Organization of African Unity confirmed Wednesday.
	   Members of the peace mission will try to persuade both parties
to agree to a cease-fire and peace talks, OAU Secretary-General
Salim Ahmed Salim said.
	   He was speaking at the end of a summit attended by the leaders
of 29 OAU member states.
	   The 34-year-old pan-African body, which is headquartered in
Ethiopia's capital Addis Ababa, did not overestimate its chances of
success.
	   ``We have to be modest,'' Salim said. ``Just because the OAU
adopts resolutions doesn't mean that the two countries will respect
them,'' Salim said. ``It is up to the parties involved to end the
hostilities.''
	   Eritrean Foreign Minister Haile Woldetensae welcomed the
proposal and said his country was willing to immediately withdraw
its troops from disputed territory to create a de-militarized zone.
	   Eritrea was also prepared for direct talks, Woldetensae added.
	   There was no immediate reaction from his Ethiopian counterpart
Seyoum Mesfin, also attending the summit. On Tuesday, Seyoum said
his country did not favor a ``proliferation of mediation
attempts.''
	   The OAU peace mission will led by Burkina Faso President Blaise
Campaore in his capacity as chairman of the pan-African body and
will also include a Rwandan envoy.
	   Mediators from Rwanda and the United States drafted a four-point
peace proposal last week that included recommendations that Eritrea
withdraw to positions held prior to May 6 when the hostilities
began. Ethiopia approved the plan but Eritrea said it was
incomplete.
	   Woldetensae said fighting continued Tuesday on several fronts
and both Ethiopia and Eritrea had suffered ``serious civilian
casualties'' as a result of the border conflict.
	   ``This is not a skirmish. This is a war,'' the Eritrean minister
said.
	   The Eritrean minister said his country had not been prepared for
the fight, which followed a resolution by Ethiopian parliament
demanding Eritrea pull out of several border areas.
	   ``We never thought to build a Berlin Wall on our border,''
Woldetensae said. ``We always thought a long-term peaceful
settlement would be reached. We still believe that is possible.''
 &UR; (gam/ids
</TEXT>
