<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Yassin </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Egypt refusing to entry to Hamas leader
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By SALAH NASRAWI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Egypt is refusing to allow Sheik Ahmed
Yassin, the spiritual leader of the radical Islamic group Hamas, to
travel to Cairo, Hamas officials said Wednesday.
	   Yassin, who was scheduled to arrive in Cairo from neighboring
Sudan Tuesday night, has had to remain in Khartoum since Egyptian
authorities told him that he may not fly to Cairo, said Mohammed
Nazal, Hamas spokesman in Jordan.
	   Yassin has asked to transit through Cairo on his way back to his
home in Gaza.
	   Egyptian officials were not available for comment.
	   Palestinian sources said Egypt was waiting for Israel to grant
permission for Yassin to return to Gaza.
	   ``They don't want another exiled leader, specially someone like
Yassin, to be stuck in Egypt,'' they said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
	   Islamic extremists in Egypt have been waging a violent campaign
to destabilize the secular government of President Hosni Mubarak.
	   Israeli leaders appear to be leaning toward allowing Yassin back
into Gaza, in part because keeping him out could trigger violence
by Hamas supporters. Israel controls the borders of Gaza.
	   Senior Egyptian officials are expected to discuss Yassin's entry
with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat when he arrives in Cairo
Thursday.
	   Yassin has been on a 3 1/2-month tour of Muslim countries to
raise funds and drum up support for Hamas.
	   Hamas opposes peace with Israel. Its military wing has killed
more than 100 Israelis in scores of attacks in recent years.
	   The group's popularity in the Palestinian lands, especially
Gaza, is seen as a growing threat to Arafat's authority.
	   Yassin was freed from an Israeli jail last fall in exchange for
the freedom of two Israeli Mossad agents captured in Jordan during
a bungled assassination attempt against another Hamas leader.
