<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Brazil-Scotland-Halftime,0475 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Late Collins penalty keep Scots even 1-1
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SAINT-DENIS, France (AP) _ John Collins buried a 38th-minute
penalty kick and Scotland kept Brazil to a 1-1 draw at halftime of
the opening match of the 16th World Cup on Wednesday.
	   Collins' penalty came after Cesar Sampaio, who gave Brazil the
lead on a fourth-minute header, was called for running over the
back of Kevin Gallacher as the Scot tried to get to the headed
cross from Christian Dailly.
	   Collins, who plays for AS Monaco and has a legion of fans in
France, drilled the penalty to the lower left corner and gave no
chance to Brazilian keeper Taffarel.
	   Sampaio was yellow-carded for his foul on Gallacher, wiping out
his effort that put Brazil in the lead.
	   Cesar Sampaio's deflected a corner kick from Bebeto at the near
post, beating not only Scottish goalkeeper Jim Leighton, but Craig
Burley and Collins who were marking the Japanese-based midfielder.
	   The Scots were clearly outplayed through most of the half,
taking nearly half a minute to get the opening kickoff beyond the
midfield stripe and rarely looking threatening. It gained more of
the possession as the half wore on, but failed to maintain it for
any extended period.
	   Twice the 39-year-old Leighton, the oldest player in the
tournament, was forced into dramatic saves. In the 16th minute he
had to parry a blast from Roberto Carlos on the left side of the
penalty area, and again in the 20th he knocked away a close-range
shot from Ronaldo, who twisted three defenders around before
getting off his attempt from near the goal box.
	   Scotland's best chance before the penalty came in the 29th
minute when Junior Baiano had to use the outside of his left heal
to clear a short-range cross into the goal box from Kevin Gallacher
with Gordon Durie closing to convert on the pass.
	   The new ban on the tackle-from-behind was tested twice in the
first half.
	   Darren Jackson took a swipe in the 17th minute at Junior Baiano
as the Brazilian went forward with the ball from in midfield. Both
players stayed on their feet and Spanish referee Jose Garcia Aranda
only whistled Jackson for the foul.
	   He issued no card to Jackson, but did summon him over for a
verbal warning.
	   Brazilian defender Aldair was issued a card in the third minute
of injury time, bringing down Gallacher and apparently lucky not to
be ejected.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; Lineups &QC; 
	   Brazil: Taffarel; Cafu, Aldair, Junior Baiano; Cesar Sampaio,
Giovanni, Dunga, Rivaldo, Roberto Carlos; Ronaldo, Bebeto
	   Scotland: Jim Leighton; Colin Calderwood, Colin Hendry, Tommy
Boyd; Craig Burley, Christian Dailly, Paul Lambert, John Collins;
Kevin Gallacher, Gordon Durie, Gordon Jackson.
	   Referee: Jose Garcia Aranda, Spain.
</TEXT>
