<SLUG> BC-Zambia-Treason Trial </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Coup plotters planned revolt weeks in advance, says witness
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) _ Two alleged coup leaders were preparing
their revolt at least six weeks before they led a group of rebels
in an assault on the state broadcast center, a court heard
Wednesday.
	   the testimony, on the second day of the nation's largest treason
trial, contradicted suggestions that the bungled Oct. 28 coup
attempt was hastily carried out at short notice by disgruntled and
drunken officers.
	   Army Capt. Christopher Musonda, a state witness in the treason
trial of 77 coup suspects, testified he had been an information
officer with the broadcast center when he was approached last
September by two of the alleged coup leaders.
	   He told the High Court in Lusaka that Capt. Steven Lungu and
Capt. Jack Chiti asked him six weeks before the coup attempt for
details on how the broadcast center was normally defended.
	   Musonda said he refused to divulge details of his unit's guard
duties.
	   During the coup attempt, Lungu allegedly made a announcement on
state radio under the pseudonym of ``Captain Solo'' that President
Frederick Chiluba had been toppled.
	   All those charged, including two politicians, appeared in court
together and are charged with treason, an offense that carry a
possible death sentence.
	   Lance Cpl. John Ngulube, the first of 163 state witnesses
scheduled to testify in the trial, on Tuesday told Judge Japhet
Banda he was approached in a bar two weeks before the attempted
coup and was asked to join a conspiracy to overthrow the
government.
	   The coup attempt crumbled when loyal troops quickly recaptured
the state radio station.
	   Earlier in the hearing, Banda rejected a defense application to
dismiss treason charges against Dean Mung'omba, head of the small
opposition Zambia Democratic Congress Party, and Nakatindi Wina, a
ruling party women's leader.
	   Lesser charges against former President Kenneth Kaunda and a
bodyguard of failing to report prior knowledge of the revolt were
dropped on June 1.
	   Kaunda, 74, led the nation to independence and ruled for 27
years until he was ousted by Chiluba in Zambia's first democratic
elections in 1991.
	   (str-as-aos)
