<HEADLINE>
Warning strikes as retail workers push for higher wages
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ About 300 retail workers in Hesse
state staged walkouts Wednesday, as union and employer
representatives prepared to return to negotiations next week to
settle a wage dispute.
	   The HBV union is demanding wage increases of 4.5 percent for
some 175,000 retail workers in the Hesse state region, but after
three rounds of failed talks that ended last month, the employers
last offer was 1.26 percent.
	   HBV spokesman Guenter Wolters said the union was preparing to
call for more walkouts prior to resumption of negotiations next
Tuesday.
	   Meanwhile, the HBV, which also represents wholesale workers who
are demanding 5 percent pay increases in the northern Hamburg
region, said 250 people at two companies staged warning strikes
there. Employers in Hamburg have offered 1.7 percent raises.
	   In Bavaria state, where some 40,000 wholesalers work, the union
and employers agreed on 2.5 percent raises effect July 1, which HBV
said was an acceptable offer.
