<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-World Cup-The Crowd,0684 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup opens to sounds of bagpipes and samba
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MORT ROSENBLUM &QC; 
 &UR; AP Special Correspondent &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAINT-DENIS, France (AP) _ A Brazilian ablaze in green and
yellow danced a Highland fling with a tanked-up Scot, whose
blue-painted pals in kilts sang a samba rhythm in passable
Portuguese with a Scottish burr.
	   It was that kind of day. Only a lucky 80,000 World Cup fans got
through the gates of France's brand new space ship-stadium, but
that did not stop the bagpipe and conga drum carnival outside.
	   A Scot in a skirt inadvertently stepped on a whooshing air vent,
a la Marilyn Monroe, and proved the widely held belief that nothing
is worn under a kilt.
	   ``Who's going to win?'' reflected Ray Sangster, a dignified
Aberdeen executive with Scottish colors emblazoned on both cheeks.
``Brazil, of course. But it's all about being here to enjoy the
moment.''
	   He grinned widely and added, ``Win or lose, we'll party all
night.''
	   Most other Scots said they thought they would win, even if all
Brazilians were certain that they would not.
	   ``It'll be 2-0, I promise you,'' assured Tom Brown, in a red
fright wig, who was down to the dregs of a liter of scotch. The
number ``18'' was penned on its side. ``I've already done the other
17,'' he said, possibly exaggerating.
	   Brown had a ticket, and he insisting on showing it. With
elaborate ceremony, he tucked his shirt and unzipped a money belt
wrapped around his waist. ``Here!'' he said, with a snaggle-toothed
grin.
	   A Brazilian weaved back and forth through the crowds on a
12-foot-high bicycle, hardly noticed among the costumes, color and
clamor.
	   Four fetching French women in old-fashioned red striped bathing
costumes posed for photos _ for a price _ with fans from both sides
who tried to get the most for their money.
	   In one corner, Charlotte Bosch, a Norwegian make-up artist,
charged nearly four bucks a cheek (20 francs) to decorate fans from
a rainbow of watercolors spread out on a blanket.
	   ``I do Brazil, Scotland, any country you want,'' she said. Bosch
had painted more Scots, often in full face colors from hairline to
neck. Brazilians preferred more discreet flags, on which she
carefully included the stars of the Southern Cross.
	   One customer was Jo Miranda, 23, with a shaved head and a
diamond in his ear. A student in Switzerland, he came over even
though he failed to get a ticket.
	   ``Brazil, 3-0. Write it down,'' he commanded, waving a clear
plastic cup of cola that was suspiciously pale and reeked of rum.
	   Miranda was furious with France was not making more tickets
available for foreigners. ``Michel Platini really screwed up,'' he
said, referring to the French soccer hero who is co-president of
the organizing committee.
	   His friend, Cristiano Fernandes, flew over from Miami although a
French travel agent did not deliver the ticket he bought. A scalper
outside offered him one for dlrs 2,000.
	   Nearby, a man carried a sign in two languages: ``I'm looking for
a ticket. Normal price please.''
	   Thousands of supporters for each team made it inside, thundering
applause at every slight advantage. When Cesar Sampaio butted in
the first goal, the yellow section went wild. Then it was
Scotland's turn.
	   Scottish fans included Prince Philip, the Duke of Edinburgh, who
sat in a luxious box with French President Jacques Chirac and Joao
Havelange, the retiring president of FIFA, the international
football association.
	   The crowd loved elaborate opening ceremonies, a symbolic
flowering of the world.
	   Fat fuzzy green seeds danced the length of the field, then
covered in with green, from which five huge buds sprouted. These
bloomed into colorful sphere, which released thousands of balloons
over the Stade de France.
	   In contrast to snarls over the past week, transportation systems
seemed to work. Metros and fast suburban trains, if jammed with
rowdy people, rolled along steadily. Taxis got through the freeway.
There was not an empty seat in the house.
</TEXT>
