<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Somalia-Ethiopia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Three factions accuse Ethiopia of interfering in Somali affairs
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By AHMED ABDI NUR &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOGADISHU, Somali (AP) _ Three factions loyal to south Mogadishu
faction leader Hussein Mohamed Aidid on Wednesday accused Ethiopia
of interfering in Somali affairs by supplying weapons, ammunition
and arms to the breakaway Republic of Somaliland.
	   The three factions _ the Somali National Movement, the Somali
Democratic Alliance and the United Somali Front _ originated in
northwestern Somalia _ the same territory now claimed by
internationally unrecognized Somaliland.
	   Forces loyal to Mohamed Ibrahim Egal formed the breakaway
republic in 1991 after some faction leaders allied to oust dictator
Mohamed Siad Barre, and Somalia then broke up into myriad fiefdoms
protected by militiamen loyal to clan-based factions.
	   In a strongly worded statement issued in Mogadishu, the three
factions also condemned Ethiopia for defying resolutions by the
United Nations, the Organization of African Unity and the regional
Inter-Governmental Authority on Development imposing an arms
embargo on Somalia.
	   The faction leaders also charge that Ethiopia violates Somalia's
territorial integrity by sending military envoys to the Somaliland
capital, Hargeisa.
	   The three factions said Ethiopia is serving its own military and
economic interests by opening a mission in Hargeisa and offering an
office to Egal's representatives in the Ethiopian capital, Addis
Ababa.
	   The three factions called in Ethiopia to refrain from actions
that may worse the security situation in the volatile region of the
Horn of Africa.
	   Ethiopia has been accused of supplying weapons and ammunition to
erstwhile Aidid rival and north Mogadishu warlord Ali Mahdi
Mohammed and to the Somali Salvation Democratic Front based in
northeastern Somalia.
	   Ethiopian forces are also reported to have entered the Somali
border region of Gedo in support of the Somali National Front
faction which is fighting the Islamic fundamentalist group
Al-Itihad Al-Islam.
	   Ethiopia's military officers are also reported to be holding
training camps for Hawadle clan militiamen in the central Somali
region of Hiran. At least 750 former militiamen trained in and
supervised by the Ethiopia are said to be active in Hiran.
	   Nearly all Somalis trace their ancestry to six original clans.
These are divided into sub-clans and extended families _ most of
which have become created armed units for protection since the
breakup of the Somali state in early 1991.
	   (aar/sl)	   
</TEXT>
