w1407 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-France-WorldCup-World     06-10 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-World Cup-Worlds Apart </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bitterness and hope in shadow of shiny stadium
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo &QL; 
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHER BURNS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAINT-DENIS, France (AP) _ Barely a football field away from the
World Cup's main stadium, Mamadou Soumare can hear the roar of the
crowd from his housing complex.
	   ``I don't have a seat, but you still hear the music and the
cries,'' said Soumare, the 16-year-old son of African immigrants.
	   Across a footbridge over a canal is the shiny and massive Stade
de France, where tens of thousands of soccer revelers have come
from around the globe to cheer on their teams.
	   They rub elbows with some of the locals, who sell souvenirs or
work as security guards. Some locals won drawings for tickets, but
many others feel shut out, in more ways than one.
	   The Stade de France cost 2.6 billion francs (dlrs 430 million),
and Saint-Denis, a suburb north of the capital, bargained with
Paris to secure more than that amount in development funding.
	   But the funding so far has created only a few hundred long-term
jobs in this depressed town where France once buried its kings.
	   Many say the money isn't trickling down to enough people in an
area devastated by industrial decline.
	   ``The exterior has changed, but the interior is the same,'' said
Soumare, whose Franc-Moisin housing project had a recent facelift
but remains plagued by unemployment and crime.
	   ``They spent so many billions and still people are living on the
edge,'' said Fred Fiquet, a 29-year-old jobless graffiti artist who
stencils his tags on T-shirts.
	   Getting a permit to hawk them outside the stadium would cost too
much, so the nearby Decathlon sporting goods store is selling them
instead.
	   ``I love soccer. It's important to life. But people like me
can't go. The locals aren't enough of a part of the event,'' he
said.
	   The front page of the Le Monde newspaper recently ran a cartoon
of the shiny Stade de France surrounded by high-rise slums. On the
scoreboard was 350 billion francs for the stadium, 0 for housing.
	   ``We Lost!, We Lost!, We Lost!'' shout the shabby buildings.
	   The cartoon outraged city officials, starting with Communist
Mayor Patrick Braouezec. ``It's a caricature, and it's particularly
unjust,'' he said in an interview.
	   ``There's a lot more work to do,'' he said. But the stadium
``was a good deal, because we gained 10 years in urban
development.''
	   Development funding helped the city give the Franc-Moisin
complex new landscaping, a paint and trim. It extended the subway
to a university and built a train station for the stadium.
	   The project brought improved roads and covered France's main
northern highway _ which slices through the heart of the city _
with parks. Outside the stadium is a new commercial complex with
cinemas, fast food restaurants and a sports department store that
all employ residents from Franc-Moisin.
	   ``This used to be a really tough place,'' Sam Berrandou said as
he strolled through Franc-Moisin with his young son. Five police
buzzed by on scooters.
	   But unemployment here remains at 17 percent overall and 28
percent among young adults, and crime has risen in recent years in
the town of 91,000 people.
	   Overcrowding in sometimes violent classrooms sparked a five-week
strike by the city's teachers and students. Parents joined in with
them last month, when they clasped hands around the Stade de
France.
	   ``We didn't want to them to forget us,'' said Darline Guervil,
15, who was part of the human chain. The government promised 3,000
new teaching jobs for the Seine-Saint-Denis department, or region.
	   Officials hope the stadium will help attract a center for sports
medicine, housing, restaurants, a bowling alley and other
businesses, creating more jobs.
	   Mohamed Aid-Ouazou, 21, who's been hired temporarily as a city
transit security aide, is skeptical. ``You know what I think? After
the World Cup, there won't be any more work,'' he said.
	   (cb-jn)
</TEXT>
