<SLUG> BUDGET-FOR-MEDICINES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Budget for medicines up despite downturn, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Budget for medicines up despite downturn, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Tues. - Despite the current economic situation,
the Health Ministry has increased its annual budget for medicines
in Government hospitals and clinics due to the increase in their
cost and the growing number of patients.
	   The budget allocated for medicines this year was RM274 million -
an increase of RM14 million compared to last year - said Health
Minister Datuk Chua Jui Meng.
	   However, he said the amount was still insufficient to meet the
cost of medicines which had risen by about 15 per cent in the past
year, as well as the number of patients which increased by some 20
per cent in Government hospitals and clinics.
	   He said for this reason, the ministry was expecting to receive a
RM78 million loan from the World Bank, through the Finance Ministry
to supplement its existing budget.
	   He said despite the situation, the ministry had asked State
health authorities not to ``be stingy'' and hold back on medicines
to cut cost.
	   ``The Government has given its assurance that money will be
available for medicines,'' he told reporters after his opening
speech on the second day of the third Health Ministry annual
dialogue.
	   In his speech, Chua said the local traditional medicine industry
had made tremendous progress towards complying with the Good
Manufacturing Practise in order to receive legitimate licensing.
	   He said last year, 40 traditional medicine manufacturers were
licensed compared to 11 last year.
	   Ninety more manufacturers are expected to be licensed by the end
of this year.
	   Chua urged the local pharmaceutical industry to invest more in
research and development to produce new drugs, so that the country
can be self- sufficient in medicine supply.
	   Sixteen industrial organisations presented their memorandums at
today's session including representatives of the Cosmetic, Toiletry
and Fragrance Association, Pharmaceutical Association of Malaysia,
National Homeopathy Council, Malaysian Medicinal Industry
Association, and the Soap and Detergent Industry.
	   
</TEXT>
