<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Olympics-London Bid </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Britain rules out 2008 bid, points to 2010
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ The British Olympic Association on Wednesday
virtually ruled out a London bid for the 2008 Olympics, setting the
stage instead for a 2012 candidacy.
	   The BOA noted that Toronto, Osaka and Istanbul have confirmed
their intention to bid for the 2008 games. The Spanish city of
Seville has also declared its candidacy, while Buenos Aires is also
expected to enter the race.
	   The BOA said it is unlikely the 2008 games will be awarded to a
European city since the 2004 summer games will be held in Athens
and the 2006 winter games will be staged at a European venue still
to be determined.
	   A BOA statement said it is continuing to study the issues of
transportation, accomodation and sports facilities for a possible
2012 bid.
	   ``A later bid gives us the opportunity to ensure that we have
the time to plan effectively ... and to deal with the complexities
of mounting a successful bid,'' BOA chairman Craig Reedie said.
	   The United States has already announced its intention to bid for
the 2012 games, with nine separate bids under consideration by the
U.S. Olympic Committee.
	   (sw)	   
</TEXT>
