<BODY>
<SLUG> LEAKING-OF-STATE-SECRETS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Warning by Selangor MB over leaking of State secrets, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Warning by Selangor MB over leaking of State secrets, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SHAH ALAM, Tues. - The Selangor Government has warned heads of
departments, staff and politicians that it will take to court
anyone leaking Government secrets.
	   Menteri Besar Datuk Abu Hassan Omar said he would not compromise
on matters which are classified under the Official Secrets Act.
	   Speaking to reporters after attending the State-level 11th
convention on ``Kumpulan Meningkat Mutu Kerja'' at Dewan Jubli
Perak here, Abu Hassan said it had come to his knowledge that
several state secrets and documents had been leaked to the public
in the last few months.
	   ``We are yet to know who was responsible for the leakage but we
are viewing it seriously. What we fear most is it falling into the
wrong hands,'' he said, declining to say what the secrets are.
	   Abu Hassan said classified information discussed at meetings
held either at State or district levels have been leaked to the
public.
	   ``This is not good and this trend must be stopped. The public
might not know these are official secrets and they might pass it on
to others including the media. We want to control it before it gets
out of hand.''
	   Abu Hassan said at the last two weekly state executive council
meetings he had stressed this to all Exco members and department
heads to ensure that state secrets and documents classified under
OSA are not leaked out.
	   He said security at the State Government building, which was
``very lax''
	   was being tightened.
	   ``Public and Press members who come to the State Government
building must co-operate with the authorities concerned by
complying with the security measures,'' he added.
	   Earlier in his speech, Abu Hassan said he was happy that several
Government departments and agencies had formed quality groups to
boost productivity by providing better counter services, resolving
consumer problems efficiently and having a good documentation
system which saves a lot of time. ``As we move into realising the
State's Vision 2005, there is need for more value added service and
departments must work towards resolving all forms of complex issues
that arise with development.''
	   He said departments and agencies should come up with more
positive and fast measures on resolving current issues such as
haze, forest fires, water shortage and rationing and most of all
public complaints.
	   Abu Hassan directed State secretary Datuk Hashim Meon to ensure
all government departments and agencies, including local
authorities, form groups to study how best their respective
departments can further improve their services.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
