<BODY>
<SLUG> FREED-OIL-TANKER-ARRIVES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Freed oil tanker arrives in Port Klang, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Freed oil tanker arrives in Port Klang, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PORT KLANG, Tues. - An oil tanker, Petro Ranger, which was
released from custody by the Chinese authorities two weeks ago,
arrived in Port Klang yesterday after undergoing minor repairs in
Singapore.
	   All its seven Malaysian seamen and its new captain, a
Singaporean, were onboard the vessel.
	   The Malaysians were identified as Saravanan Subramanian, Mohamed
Nazri Selamat, Abdul Kadir Soad, Sani Anak Ugie, Mohd Faizal Mohd
Ghazali, Mohd Shizul Khan M. Razali and Mohd Samsuri Abdul Kadir.
	   They are expected to leave the ship today, after being
interviewed by officers from the Marine Department's Maritime
Safety Division.
	   The division's director, Captain Ahmad Othman, said the ship's
former captain, Kenneth Blyth - believed to have suffered
depression following his ordeal at the hands of Indonesian pirates
- was allowed to leave for Australia by ship's owner, Petroships
Pte Ltd, after the crew was released.
	   He said the crew were interviewed by the Singapore authorities
last week before they were allowed to leave.
	   Ahmad said the crew had concurred with the Chinese authorities'
finding that the pirates were Indonesians who boarded the vessel
while it was enroute to Vietnam on April 16.
	   In an unrelated case, Ahmad said the department had received a
report from the Indonesian authorities on an attempted pirate
attack on a Malaysian cargo ship on March 27.
	   The ship, Malaysian Empress, was sailing to Sabah when it was
trailed by a group of men in a speedboat for several hours.
	   The report said the group sped off when the ship's crew turned
on its deck lights.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
