<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Nigeria,0517 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Milutinovic juggles lineup to offset injuries
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By HOWARD FENDRICH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   RESSONS, France (AP) _ Wrestling with a slew of injuries,
Nigeria coach Bora Milutinovic tried various lineup combinations in
practice Wednesday, including working Mobi Oparaku at right back
just hours after the defender was placed on the roster.
	   ``I have 22 players and may wind up using them all,''
Milutinovic said with a smile. ``Anything is possible. I will
announce my lineup one hour before we play.''
	   Oparaku substitutes Jero Shakpore, who was ruled out with a
broken collarbone.
	   The lineup woes do not end there for the Super Eagles, who are
looking to build on their success at the 1994 tournament _ where
they reached the second round in their debut appearance _ and the
1996 Olympic gold.
	   Striker Daniel Amokachi skipped the training session in this
village north of Paris because of a twisted right knee suffered
Tuesday.
	   In addition, Inter Milan forward Nwankwo Kanu, who can dominate
any defense when healthy, worked on his own for the third straight
day.
	   He may rejoin his teammates Thursday, Milutinovic said, but time
is running out for the 21-year-old to reach match fitness ahead of
Saturday's opening game against Spain at Nantes.
	   In a scrimmage at the end of the two-hour session _ the longest
Nigeria has had since arriving in France last Saturday _
Milutinovic juggled his formation.
	   The stocky Oparaku, who plays for Belgian club Kepellen, worked
mostly in Shakpore's spot in the right flank. FIFA, soccer's
governing body, approved the roster substitution Wednesday morning.
	   The rest of the backline looks set, with captain Uche Okechukwu
and Kanu's Inter Milan teammate Taribo West in the middle and
Celestine Babayaro on the left.
	   With Kanu and Amokachi unavailable _ and striker Emmanuel
Amunike not even on the squad because of a knee injury _
Milutinovic had veteran Rasheed Yekini and 1997 African Player of
the Year Victor Ikpeba up front.
	   As he has all week, Milutinovic stressed containment at midfield
and defensive help, with players working on covering passing lanes.
	   The Yugoslav coach, hired in February after being dismissed by
Mexico, expressed concern he has not had sufficient opportunities
to work with the players. The uncertainties with the lineup can't
help.
	   ``You never know how much time you need to mold a team,'' said
Milutinovic, coaching his record fourth different country at a
World Cup. ``You can work years and not get a good result or do
well with little work.''
	   The latter has not been the case for his team, which has lost
exhibitions to Germany, Yugoslavia and the Netherlands.
	   Sunday Oliseh insisted the string of poor outings has not
dampened the players' outlook.
	   ``We may not be candidates for the title, but definitely for the
second round. We just want to do better than (we did in) 1994,''
the Ajax of Amsterdam midfielder said, ``and we expect to.''
	   (hjf-sl)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-Nigeria; CT:s; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
