<BODY>
<SLUG> AIRPORT-WINDING-DOWN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Airport winding down after 33 years, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Airport winding down after 33 years, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   CONTRASTING SCENES ... for these passengers at the Sultan Abdul
Aziz Shah International Airport in Subang (right) yesterday,
nostalgia was not quite the word to describe the country's main
international airport for 33 years. It has less than three weeks to
go.
	   From June 30 it will be a whole new scenario as passengers
travel through the Kuala Lumpur International Airport in Sepang,
dubbed the most modern and sophisticated airport in Asia.
	   It will certainly be goodbye to congestion as Subang is now
handling beyond its capacity of 16 million passengers annually.
	   With 479,404sq metres of passenger space, the new airport will
be capable of handling about 25 million passengers in its first
year of operation.
	   KLIA will have more open areas for passengers to move about, and
higher ceilings to add to its ambience.
	   And with more facilities and retail outlets, it will also offer
passengers a higher level of convenience.
	   As Subang wound down its operations, it was a different scene at
KLIA.
	   Yesterday, workers at the new airport were busy preparing for
its opening ceremony on June 27.
	   The picture shows the arboretum at KLIA's Satellite A building
in the background, depicting the airport's concept of being ``A
forest in an airport and an airport in a forest''.
	   Visitor Ted Klainer, from the United States, looks at the Flight
Information Display System in the foreground which will provide
passengers information on aircraft gates, check-in counters and
flight times.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
