<BODY>
<SLUG> MALCON-V-TROOPS-RETURN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Malcon V troops returning today, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Malcon V troops returning today, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Tues. - The first batch of 300 Malaysian soldiers
serving under the North Atlantic Treaty Organisation's
Stabilisation Force in Bosnia-Herzegovina is expected to arrive
home tomorrow.
	   The 790-strong Malaysian Contingent V, based in the former
Balkan republic, will return home in stages following the end of
Nato's mandate in the country.
	   A Defence Ministry spokesman said the first group, led by Mej
Zulkafli Abdul Aziz, would touch down at the Royal Malaysian Air
Force base in Subang.
	   Armed Forces chief Jen Tan Sri Ismail Omar is expected to
receive them.
	   He said the second and third group would arrive home on June 26
and July 10, respectively.
	   On the assets used during the mission, the spokesman said they
would be transported from Split, Croatia, early next month.
	   Malcon V, led by Kol Syed Khalid Syed Mahmod, assumed duties
from Malcon IV last December.
	   
</TEXT>
