w1422 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Iran-Newspaper 3rdLd-Writethru   06-10 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iran-Newspaper, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Two Iranian papers stop publishing, one after losing its license
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with quotes from editor-in-chief of Jameah, color,
ADDS byline.
 &UR; By AFSHIN VALINEJAD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ One of Iran's most popular newspapers,
Jameah or ``Society,'' had its license revoked Wednesday after its
editor was convicted of defamation.
	   The revocation came hours after a second newspaper ceased
publication because the Press Supervisory Board was accusing it of
unethical reporting.
	   The two moves are seen as a setback for the press freedom
promoted by moderate President Mohammad Khatami since he took
office in August.
	   A court banned the editor of Jameah, Hamid Reza Jalaipur, from
working in a similar position for one year and fined him 16 million
rials (dlrs 3,500), the official Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
	   Jameah's editor-in-chief, Mahmoud Shamsolwaizine, told The
Associated Press that the newspaper will continue to publish
because the Ministry of Culture and Islamic Guidance has not
officially informed it of the revocation.
	   ``The ministry has to issue that order and so far it has not
done so,'' he said, adding that once the order is issued, Jameah
will appeal. ``Meanwhile, we will continue to publish our paper.''
	   The offices of the newspaper were operating Wednesday evening,
with writers and photographers preparing material for Thursday's
issue.
	   ``We strongly protest this order and we believe this is the
harshest punishment for freedoms in the history of Iran's press,''
Shamsolwaizine said.
	   The newspaper's telephone lines were jammed with callers
expressing their support. Some offering to stage rallies to protest
the court ruling.
	   ``We believe this is a political game,'' Shamsolwaizine said.
``The judiciary should prove that this order is a judicial matter
and in that case we will accept it.''
	   Jameah is regarded as a newspaper that tests the limits of the
press freedom introduced since Khatami came to power. An afternoon
paper, its run of 200,000 copies sells out within hours.
	   The prosecution accused Jalaipur of publishing ``insults and
lies.'' The substance of the charge was not disclosed, but
state-run television has said that the Islamic Revolutionary Guards
Corps had accused the paper of falsely publishing that its
commander was opposed to liberalization.
	   The publisher of Gozaresh-e-Ruz, or Daily Report, Mohammad
Mahdavi Khorrami said he was voluntarily stopping the publication
of his paper until a verdict in the case brought by the supervisory
board, the newspaper Salam reported Wednesday.
	   The Justice Ministry is reviewing the complaint against
Gozaresh-e-Ruz. If the paper is prosecuted in court, it could also
lose its license.
	   A liberal publication, Gozaresh-e-Ruz was launched only last
month. On its third day it printed a front-page picture of a
teenage boy with a teenage girl wearing a head scarf. The caption,
``Friendship Under Fear,'' referred to the prohibition on dating
under Iran's strict Islamic code.
	   A Culture Ministry official, Ahmad Borqani, was quoted this week
as saying that Gozaresh-e-Ruz had followed ``quite an inappropriate
path from the beginning of its publication.''
	   Borqani told the Iran News that Gozaresh-e-Ruz had also printed
``a false report'' about Iranian officials transferring money to
overseas bank accounts.
	   The reforms introduced by Khatami are said to enjoy the support
of most Iranians. But conservative elements in the government,
particularly in the judiciary, are opposed to his policies.
 &UR; pvs-ti-lm 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Iran-Newspaper, 3rd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
