<HEADER>
w1424 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RwandaTribunal     06-10 0267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Rwanda Tribunal </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Six arrested in connection with Rwandan genocide
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ARUSHA, Tanzania (AP) _ Six Rwandans have been arrested in
connection with the 1994 ethnic slaughter in their country, the
International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda said Wednesday.
	   One of the six, Emmanuel Bagambiki, has been indicted by the
tribunal on charges of genocide and crimes against humanity. He was
prefect of the southwestern border town of Cyangugu.
	   The other five were arrested provisionally, as allowed by he
tribunal's rules.
	   They are Mathieu Ngirumpaste, once a top foreign ministry
official and president of Rwanda's former ruling party, the MRND;
Edouard Karamera, former party vice president and interior minister
of the interim government; Joseph Nziorera, former president of
Rwanda's National Assembly; Juvenal Kajelijeli, former mayor of the
town of Murkingo; and Omar Serushago, a leader of the interahamwe
militia that carried out much of the killing.
	   At least 500,000 people were killed in Rwanda over a three-month
period in 1994, most of them minority Tutsis slaughtered by Hutus.
	   The tribunal has indicted 35 people; 24 of whom are now in
custody at the tribunal in Arusha. Four are standing trial and one
has pleaded guilty to genoide and crimes against humanity.
	   The latest arrests were carried out by authorities in the West
African countries of Benin, Togo, Mali and Ivory Coast, the
tribunal said in a statement.
	   There was no indication when Bagambiki would be transferred to
Arusha or when or whether the other five would be indicted.
	   (jh-sl)	   
</TEXT>
