<BODY>
<SLUG> CORPORATISED-WATER sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Penang residents wary of a corporatised water authority, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Penang residents wary of a corporatised water authority, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   A. KathirasenASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A BILL to allow the corporatisation of the Penang Water
Authority is expected to be approved in the current meeting of the
Penang State Legislative Assembly.
	   And residents are very concerned. Their experience with
``corporatisation'' and ``privatisation'' has not been entirely
pleasant.
	   Each time they hear these words, they know that rates are going
up.
	   It has not been different this time. Penang residents have been
warned of an imminent increase in water rates.
	   This worry was reflected in the State Assembly proceedings when
several backbenchers and the lone Opposition representative sought
assurances that the corporatisation would benefit the public.
	   Barisan Nasional Assemblyman for Permatang Pasir Ahmad Saad
claimed the services of Penang Port Sdn Bhd were deteriorating and
that fewer ships were calling at the port, where operations were
corporatised in 1994.
	   The Penang Port management is seeking to reduce its staff of
2,300 by not more than 700 through a voluntary retrenchment scheme.
	   Its executive chairman Datuk Zahrain Hashim said the port could
reduce its RM60 million annual expenditure on salaries by RM20
million.
	   Ahmad observed that at the end of the day, the problems faced by
the retrenched workers would be laid on the lap of the Government.
	   Before corporatisation, there was one general manager, but
today, in addition to a senior general manager, there are 10
general managers.
	   One general manager - heading the bulk cargo terminal - has only
33 workers under him.
	   Each general manager earns between RM6,500 and RM8,250 and
enjoys numerous perks including a Peugeot 405SR automatic and a
laptop computer.
	   Staff of Penang Port Sdn Bhd have reservations about some of the
management's decisions, including the purchase of a RM1 million VIP
boat.
	   Penang Port Commission Employees' Union president Zamri Abdullah
said: ``Why buy the boat? It is not going to generate revenue, only
incur expenditure.''
	   In all fairness, it must be said that the PPSB under Zahrain has
not done that badly.
	   There was a 12.5 per cent increase in cargo throughput last year
with a total of 19.69 million tonnes against 17.5 million tonnes in
1996.
	   In 1993, the pre-tax profit was RM24.14 million but after
corporatisation in 1994, this increased to RM41.48 million.
	   In 1995, the pre-tax profit was RM36.01 million and in 1996, it
dropped to RM22.03 million. Last year's profit has yet to be
announced.
	   In 1994, turnover was RM138.87 million, in 1995, it was RM156.02
million, and in 1996, it stood at RM159.71 million while operating
expenditure kept increasing from RM104.71 million (1994) to
RM117.32 million (1995) and RM133.30 million (1996).
	   In 1993, the turnover was RM126.94 million while operating
expenditure stood at RM108.41 million.
	   With negative news about the PPSB management circulating, Penang
residents can be forgiven for being wary about a corporatised PWA.
	   Port and ferry charges were raised when the PPSB came into being
and their fear of an increase in water rates has been confirmed by
Chief Minister Tan Sri Dr Koh Tsu Koon.
	   ``The Government will ensure that the increase will not burden
the people,'' he said in giving an assurance.
	   How? Any increase is bound to be a burden on the wage earner,
especially during difficult times.
	   But Koh is only mouthing what every government leader says. Each
time toll and electricity rates or food prices increase, we hear
the ubiquitous quote: ``We will ensure that the increase in
rates/prices do not burden the public.''
	   Barisan Nasional Assemblywoman for Jawi Tan Cheng Liang voiced
the thoughts of many when she asked: ``Since the PWA has been
making profits running into tens of millions of ringgit, why raise
rates?''
	   According to Koh, the increase is to discourage people from
wasting water.
	   Residents find it easier to gulp down water than this logic.
What if Tenaga Nasional Bhd, Telekom Malaysia Bhd and food outlets
raise charges to ``prevent wastage''?
	   Another issue is who will head a corporatised PWA? Will an
experienced and skilled man be appointed or, as is not uncommon,
someone with political connections get the post?
	   Zamri points to the PPSB as a case in point: ``Datuk Zahrain,
who was then Tanjung Umno division chief, was inexperienced but he
was made executive chairman.
	   ``Is this the manner in which the Government operates in
corporatisation efforts?
	   ``Politics and business should not mix. It is unhealthy. When
politicians are appointed to head business entities or appointed
directors, many problems will arise.''
	   The Government would do well to heed Zamri's observation, which
also reflects that of many Penang residents.
	   
</TEXT>
