<BODY>
<SLUG> HOTELS-HAVE-UNTIL-OCTOBE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hotels have until October to switch to nett billing, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Hotels have until October to switch to nett billing, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PETALING JAYA, Mon. - Hotels have until October to start billing
customers according to a nett charge instead of indicating charges
for service and Government tax.
	   Culture, Arts and Tourism Minister Datuk Sabbaruddin Chik said
even though the ministry would not penalise hotels, their
non-compliance would be viewed as ``lackadaisical and
irresponsible''.
	   The current ++ price tagging practised by the majority of the
hotels nationwide, represents a 10 per cent service charge in lieu
of tips and five per cent Government tax.
	   Sabbaruddin was speaking to reporters after launching the
Malaysia Bagus Luxury Holidays at the Sheraton Subang.
	   After a series of discussions, the Hotel Owners' Association
Malaysia had agreed to discard the ++ tag while giving a nett rate
for guests and to include the service and Government tax in its
nett price.
	   ``Hoteliers will not lose anything if they withdraw the ++
signs. The price will not be lower than now,'' he said. Coupled
with other attractive packages, hoteliers would get more guests.
	   Sabbaruddin said guests would find it easier to calculate their
bills.
	   
</TEXT>
