<HEADER>
w1434 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  THE-FUTURE-STARTS-NOWske     06-10 1443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> THE-FUTURE-STARTS-NOW sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
The future starts now, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
The future starts now, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Edward DorrallASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SINGAPORE has always had a reputation far beyond its shores. The
great port of a hundred years ago where Conrad changed ships so
often, Maugham's early century Grand Hotel of whiskey stengahs and
scandalous stories, the notorious mid-century haven of sin and
crime, followed by a comparatively quiet decade from which it
emerged as the world's squeaky-cleanest city, currently too - if we
are to believe its more serious writes - Big Brother's last
fortress of mental regimentation in return for material prosperity,
why should it not also become, continuing its present development,
the modern robot city of the future? Which is what the back cover
of The Singapore String tantalisingly advertises will happen.
	   Its English author Jenny Gay has lived in Singapore, married to
a Singaporean, for 25 years. She is qualified in Social Work,
English and French literature, Philosophy, and teaching, and is
currently the principal of Chatsworth International School.
	   A (quite unnecessary) photo shows her happily seated with her
mother, husband, and two sons. None of this is interesting for its
own sake, of course, unless Gay is also a good, in addition to
being a serious, writer.
	   At once, let me say that she is, absolutely, in every one of the
11 stories in the volume.
	   These stories, she claims in a preface, are not predictions but
only portrayals of ``a few of the infinite number of positive
futures for Singapore''. Yet she coyly adds that perhaps
Singapore's future ``fact'' may go further, ``indeed show itself to
be stranger than (her) fiction''. For this to happen her stories -
indeed, all good futuristic writing, whether fantasy or science
fiction - should be related to, should be viable projections of,
the present.
	   This, all but one attempt to be. Projecting the future of
today's Emancipated, Emotion-drained, Reason-regimented Singapore
Female, she creates a sexless 17-year-old genius (`Sweet Little
Singapore Miss') who, when it is Singapore's turn to be World
Capital some time after World Unity in 2025, is chosen to be World
President; another ugly she who runs a phenomenally successful
health centre (her story, `Twenty-First Century Mosquito', is the
least futuristic in the book); and yet a third unloved genius who,
having discovered a way for women to have babies without sexual
intercourse, gets rid of nearly all males from the university's
medical faculty (`Hysteria').
	   On the theme of the Machine-controlled Society we have a lonely
woman whose social life is determined and eventually terminated by
her futuristic computer phone (`Human Error'); a homosexual who
falls in love with his robot butler (`Love at First Sight'); and a
suffering widow who cannot marry again because her detested husband
is waiting in a frozen coffin to return to life when a cure is
found for the disease which killed him (`The Late Lamented').
	   The Ugly Singaporean appears in the title story `The Singapore
Sting' and Ugly Singaporean activities in the powerful but sick
`Share and Bear', in which a group of desperate game-show
contestants compete to die in front of the television cameras.
	   The results of world pollution are memorably described in
`Veteran Citizen', and it is only in `Trial Run', about a man in
his fourth body after scientists have discovered how humans, like
cats, can have multiple lives, that fantasy runs riot without any
social implications.
	   All these stories rightly centre on future Singaporeans rather
than their futuristic inventions. For people are always more
important and interesting than things. And Gay's nasty, abnormal
and decent, suffering characters are convincingly depicted. In each
case she seems to have got under their skin, more important, found
the right voice for them.
	   Consequently, if no story is a masterpiece, each sustains the
interest to the end.
	   Nevertheless, for science fiction and even fantasy to succeed
totally the new machines and other inventions must be credible, or
rather a possibility accepted by the reader. Best of all would be a
present reality carried to its extreme, like pollution - for me,
the book's finest moment is when the grandmother tells her
granddaughter in 2029 about her childhood rolling on the grass
which has for decades disappeared from the world.
	   I can easily accept too the tyrannical telephone and the frozen
husband, for the sake of the story even conception without sexual
intercourse and sex with a robot. But, nine lives? A game-show in
which you get the screen to reveal a secret from your wife's past?
Here, for me, the possible impossible becomes the lunatic
incredible. Frankenstein's Monster is the former, the hero of
`Trial Run' the latter. But I think it an insult to the
intelligence to ever pretend you can go backwards in time. A pity
though, for `Share and Bear' promised to be the finest story in the
book.
	   I have deliberately left `A Controlled Experiment', the most
different of the stories, to the end. Here the Third World War has
just ended.
	   Europe and the United States have, surprisingly, succumbed to an
unseen enemy. ``So much for our childish faith in the
invulnerability of the Western World!'' Now Singapore is suddenly
assailed. Everyone dies, first the older generation (including the
Prime Minister) and the babies, then the middle-aged followed by
the youth, till no one is left on the island.
	   A group of American soldiers visits the deserted city. Soon two
of them die suddenly.
	   A dying Singaporean writes to the outside world, ``We
Singaporeans are dying so fast that whatever the ultimate goal for
our future is few of us can live long enough to see it ... Either
the island will be devoid of real Singaporeans and the Sponsor (the
unseen enemy) will have repopulated our island to the extermination
of its true inhabitants ... or we will have become a nation of
slaves, not only physically but also mentally ...
	   I want you to know that we did not easily and knowingly succumb
to our fate but rather that it was imposed upon us by a power that
considered us sub-human, beneath all respect due to fellow beings.
	   ``If you read this you will finally have overcome the enemy, I
beg of you, have no mercy, even as we were shown no mercy ... On
behalf of all the Singaporeans who like me have suffered and died I
beg of you. Do not fail us!''
	   What is really happening here? What unseen enemy (is it even
human?) has only temporarily defeated the Western world but
completely wiped out Singapore, or turned it ``physically but also
mentally'' into ``a nation of slaves''? But why Singapore?
``Someone ... maybe knew the geographical and political advantages
of selecting an island? Someone used to making tough decisions that
would forever rob `lesser' men of their sleep? Maybe even someone
of intelligence? But surely someone with a vital organ missing -
his heart?''
	   Why did the dying (or slavery) begin with the Prime Minister's
generation and the newly born and then spread down to the youth?
Who might the fake, replacement Singaporeans be? And what exactly
is to be fought till it is totally destroyed?
	   Is this story fantasy? It clearly isn't science fiction. Is it a
parable or an allegory, the physical standing for the mental, even
spiritual? Are we in the mad dean's lands unmarked in any known map
but which are all effectively his own Britain in the opening
decades of the 18th century? Is this then a history of what has
been and is, disguised as what will be?
	   If so, then not only are 10 of Gay's stories sensible forecasts
of Singapore life based on today's reality but this 11th and most
important story also set in the century to come is what all great
literature, whether of times past, actual, or ahead, is really
about - what has happened to make our world (here, Singapore) what
it is, today, now.
	   For this story alone, buy The Singapore Sting.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:THE-FUTURE-STARTS-NOW sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
</BODY>
