<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-Kosovo, 1st ld-Writethru,0722 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Defense ministers to seek plans for Kosovo intervention
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Russian quotes, possible NATO measures. INCLUDES
material from NATO-Kosovo-Protest. No pickup &QL; 
 &UR; JEFFREY ULBRICH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ With the Serb-led Yugoslav army beefing
up forces in separatist Kosovo province, NATO defense ministers
face the growing belief that direct military intervention may be
the only way to stop the violence.
	   U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen and his 15 NATO colleagues,
meeting at alliance headquarters here Thursday and Friday, were
expected to order military planners to take a hard look at the
intervention option, such as sending in troops, conducting air
strikes or enforcing a no-fly zone.
	   ``The worsening of the situation makes it more than advisable to
work out credible options for military action, to have them ready
for a political decision at any time,'' German Defense Minister
Volker Ruehe said.
	   Cohen acknowledged ``a general consensus there should be
accelerated planning'' and that ``all NATO members feel an
increased sense of urgency.''
	   ``There is a genuine concern throughout the region that if this
goes unchecked, it could have much wider implications than just
Kosovo,'' he said.
	   NATO ambassadors worked late Wednesday on detailed instructions
for the military, including a clear statement of the objective of
any intervention.
	   Also under debate was a series of immediate measures, including
air maneuvers in the next few days over neighboring Albania and
Macedonia as a show of strength, moves to military establish
training and exercise centers and using NATO transport to help cope
with refugee flows.
	   Outside NATO headquarters Wednesday, hundreds of Albanians
protested, demanding that the Western alliance intervene in Kosovo.
	   ``If NATO doesn't take the decision to intervene as fast as
possible, we fear that the number of victims will increase,''
organizer Ramadan Gashi told Associated Press Television.
	   In Kosovo, more than 250 people have died in clashes between
government forces and the Kosovo Liberation Army, armed wing of the
Albanian independence movement. Ethnic Albanians, who make up 90
percent of the population in the southern province, demand
independence from Serbia, the larger of two republics in
Yugoslavia.
	   The United States and its allies support autonomy for Kosovo but
oppose demands for independence and condemn violence on both sides.
	   In recent days, entire villages in Kosovo have been flattened
and thousands of people driven from their homes.
	   ``Kosovo is in grave danger of becoming another Bosnia,'' said
Carlos Westendorp, the High Representative in Bosnia responsible
for enforcing the civilian aspects of the Dayton peace accords.
	   ``It is as if we repair one house, only to discover the one next
door is burning down,'' he said. ``This is supposed to be the year
of returns to Bosnia, but it is rapidly becoming the year of the
exodus from Kosovo.''
	   The United States and the European Union have imposed economic
sanctions on Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, but few believe
that will result in a government pullback.
	   NATO military planners have for the past two weeks been
following out earlier instructions to study indirect options for
pressuring Milosevic. Those include dispatching up to 20,000 troops
to Albania and Macedonia, reinforcing the existing 750-man U.N.
force in Macedonia and helping both countries secure their borders
while dealing with refugees and arms smuggling.
	   However, ``with the events of the last week, shoring up the
periphery seems of secondary value,'' another NATO official said.
	   Intervening in Kosovo would require a sound legal basis.
	   The United States is backing a British effort to win U.N.
Security Council approval for a resolution authorizing ``all
necessary measures,'' including direct military intervention.
	   President Boris Yeltsin says he will try to use his influence
with Milosevic, but remains firmly against intervention.
	   ``Urgent measures are needed there,'' Russian Defense Minister
Igor Sergeyev said after a meeting with Belgian officials. However,
``I think we haven't explored all the peaceful measures that we can
use.'' 	   
</TEXT>
