<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Chemical Warfare, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mandela was target for chemical disabling, scientist alleges
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with ANC reax; EDITS to conform; MINOR editing
throughout &QL; 
 &UR; By PAUL HARRIS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) _ South Africa's apartheid-era
government plotted to poison Nelson Mandela in an attempt to
inflict brain damage, a scientist testified Wednesday.
	   Testifying before a panel probing apartheid crimes, Schalk van
Rensburg described how his superior, Andre Immelman, told him soon
after Mandela's release there were plans to poison him with
thallium, which attacks the nervous system.
	   ``The intention, I understood, was to reduce his level of
intellectuality and effectiveness by inducing brain damage,'' van
Rensburg said.
	   In earlier testimony before the Truth and Reconciliation
Commission, scientists described working in a poison factory that
churned out chocolates, drinks and cigarettes spiked with lethal
chemicals that were passed to government hit squads.
	   Scientists also developed large supplies of lethal
micro-organisms such as anthrax and cholera that could have been
used to cause epidemics.
	   Mandela's ruling African National Congress compared the former
apartheid government with Adolf Hitler's Third Reich, which used
scientists to devise ways of exterminating millions of Jews,
Gypsies and others.
	   ``What is clear is that leading scientists (were) engaged in
these inhuman experiments in the same way as those who served the
Nazi regime in Germany,'' the ANC said in a statement late
Wednesday. ``If ever there was a program that truly typified the
genocidal programmes of the apartheid regime, this was it.''
	   Van Rensburg said the aim was not to kill Mandela, but to
disable him. The plot was considered in the final years of
Mandela's imprisonment and at least for a short time afterward,
according to the scientist.
	   There was no suggestion that the plan was ever carried out.
After his release from prison in 1990, Mandela led the ANC to
victory in the nation's first all-race elections in 1994 and became
president.
	   The white-run government started preparing Mandela for his
release as early as 1989, and began talks with him on ending
apartheid shortly after his release.
	   But the apartheid government apparently did not want him to be a
viable political opponent. A 1986 report from the State Security
Council, which coordinated the crackdown on anti-apartheid
activists, suggested Mandela could be released only when he was in
such a poor state of health that he could not continue to lead the
ANC.
	   Van Rensburg said he had never seen the document.
	   The Truth Commission is investigating the former apartheid
army's chemical and biological weapons projects, headed by Wouter
Basson, who ran the scheme through an elaborate network of front
companies.
	   Jaap Celliers, a lawyer representing Basson and other top
scientists in the program, denied the 1986 document indicated a
plot to actively poison Mandela. He said the minutes could have
just meant that Mandela should be kept in jail long enough to
damage his health.
	   ``It was the longer detention, not active conduct,'' he said.
	   Basson, who has been called to testify later this week, was
forced to resign from the army in 1993 after a government report
fingered him in making poisons and chemical bombs. He is currently
being investigated on charges of making and possessing ecstasy and
mandrax drugs.
	   (aos)
</TEXT>
