w1446 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Ethiopia-Coffee     06-10 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ethiopia-Coffee </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Officials say fighting has not affected production, exports
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ADDIS ABABA (AP) _ The production and price of coffee,
Ethiopia's principal export, have remained stable despite fighting
along the country's disputed northern border with Eritrea, coffee
officials said Wednesday.
	   They said most of the country's coffee production, which rose to
118,000 tons in 1997 and represents 56 percent of Ethiopia's gross
domestic product, comes from the south and southwestern regions,
far from the conflicts in northern Tigray region.
	   ``There is very minimal production from Tigray,'' said Tsegaye
Berahane, general manager of Ethiopia's Coffee and Tea Authority.
``There has been no impact, no consequences'' from the fighting.
	   Since the first border incident May 6, landlocked Ethiopia has
gradually moved all its exports from Eritrea's Red Sea ports of
Massawa and Assab south the Djibouti on the Gulf of Aden.
	   No figures were available on the cost of moving the coffee
through another port, but Tsegaye said exports had not been
disrupted.
	   In 1995, the last year for which figures are available, Ethiopia
exported coffee worth dlrs 269 million.
	   Tsegaye said the port of Djibouti offered better parking and
storage facilities than Assab.
	   ``The only problem is that coffee must now be exported in
containers, and there are not enough trucks to carry the containers
to Djibouti,'' said Aschenaki Gebrehiwot, general secretary of the
Coffee Exporters Association.
	   Coffee prices remained relatively constant in the daily central
market auction in Addis Ababa from last Thursday, ranging on an
average between 4,500 and 6,000 Ethiopian birr (dlrs 642 to 857)
per ton of washed coffee and between 2,400 and 2,900 birr (dlrs 343
to 414) per ton for sun-dried coffee, according to the government
Coffee Trading Control Office.
	   Supply fluctuated from 47 tons of washed coffee and 378 tons of
sun-dried coffee on Thursday to 80 tons of washed and 556 tons of
sun-dried coffee on Friday to 35 tons of washed and 221 tons of
sun-dried on Tuesday.
	   Aschenaki said the fluctuations were in keeping with the normal,
erratic day-to-day supplies and did not reflect any decline in
production or delivery.
	   It is estimated that the total 1997/98 coffee production will be
as much as 20 percent lower than the 1996/97 harvest of 420,000
tons, due mainly to heavy rains and high winds that damaged ripe
beans awaiting harvest and that the export target of 128,000 tons
will not be met.
	   (aa/dc/sl)	   
</TEXT>
