<SLUG> SANGCHAI-TRIAL-POSTPONED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sangchai trial postponed for two weeks, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Sangchai trial postponed for two weeks, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE judge presiding over the retrial of the Sangchai Sunthornvut
murder case Tuesday postponed the trial for two weeks and ordered
the public prosecutor to turn over all evidence to the defendant's
lawyer as earlier requested.
	   The order was given in compliance with a request by Kriang
Wisitsora-at, who had complained that the information provided by
119 witnesses questioned by police did not constitute new evidence,
thus the retrial was unlawful.
	   Kriang, who represents Ubol Boonyachalothorn, also said his
request was based on constitutional Article 241, which contradicted
the reasoning of the public prosecutor, Amphol Hemakhom, who said a
lawful request must ask for only suspects' information -- not that
of all witnesses.
	   Before ordering that the evidence be turned over to the
defendant's lawyer, Judge Khaimuk Phasanayongphinyo spend almost
two hours going through the information given by the 119 witnesses
and asked Kriang to check on whether any of the new witnesses to be
presented by the prosecutors were the same as the original 119.
	   On Monday, Kriang claimed that the evidence he had requested
could prove that the former director of the Mass Communications
Organisation of Thailand had conflicts with two of the agency's
executive board members before he was shot dead in April 1996.
	   The lawyer named a retired Army general and a businessman as the
board members and claimed that Sangchai's conflicts with the men
were the actual cause behind his killing -- not anything done by
Ubol, who has been accused of masterminding the murder.
	   
</TEXT>
