<BODY>
<SLUG> STOP-TALKING-TO-PRESS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Stop talking to press, Chuan tells Cabinet, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Stop talking to press, Chuan tells Cabinet, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PRIME Minister Chuan Leekpai Tuesday banned Cabinet members from
talking to reporters about the Cabinet meeting for one week, a
government house source said Tuesday.
	   Chuan reportedly sounded out the Cabinet members at a meeting
called Tuesday to discuss the privatisation of the state
enterprises and THAI, the budget bill for fiscal 1999 and the
budget allocation for fiscal 1998.
	   After the ministers returned from their luncheon, Chuan
surprised them with the media ban.
	   ''Lately, the state's confidential information and security
issues discussed at Cabinet meetings have always appeared in
newspapers. To help smoothen the government's administration, I
would like to ask friends, ministers, spokesmen and those attend
the meeting to refrain from telling reporters what was said at the
meeting for one week,'' Chuan reportedly said.
	   Chuan's reason for the ban was believed to stem from the
coalition's wrangling over budget allocation. The Social Action
Party was upset two weeks ago after the budget for the ministries
it oversees were cut by more than Bt500 million.
	   The SAP retaliated by proposing that the plan to construct the
airport at Chanthaburi be suspended reasoning that the project was
not essential. Democrat leaders, including Chuan and Suthep
Thaugsuban, strongly defended the project, vowing to go ahead with
the plan.
	   The party, however, bowed to public and media pressure last week
and postponed the construction on grounds that the money should be
saved for other more necessary projects.
	   Meanwhile, Chuan played down the National Statistics Office's
report that the total number of unemployed has reached 2,800,000.
	   Chuan said according to Interior, Labour Ministry and the
National Economic Social Development Board, only about two million
people were unemployed; which break down to 1.3 million in the
agriculture sector which are seasonal employees, 200,000 laid-off
workers and 500,000 new graduates who enter the workforce but
cannot find jobs.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
