w1465 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  COBRA-FACTION-TO-FORMske     06-10 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> COBRA-FACTION-TO-FORM sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cobra faction to form new party, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Cobra faction to form new party, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE 12 rebel Prachakorn Thai MPs Tuesday ruled out joining the
Democrat Party after their expulsion from the Prachakorn Thai,
saying they would form a new party of their own to be called
Rassadorn.
	   The group also proposed that the Democrats go ahead with plans
to bring in the Chat Pattana to bolster the coalition's stability
and remove the 12 Prachakorn Thai MPs from the coalition.
	   However, Democrat Party secretary-general Sanan Kachornprasart
said Tuesday that the situation had not yet warranted bringing in
the Chat Pattana and the coalition had not yet discussed the issue.
	   Speaking after meeting Sanan at Parliament, Nonthaburi MP
Chalong Riewraeng, one of the 12 rebel Prachakorn Thai MPs, said he
informed Sanan about the group's decision not to join the
Democrats.
	   The Prachakorn Thai is set to expel the 12 MPs, dubbed cobras by
party chief Samak Sundaravej, from the party once the Election
Commission approves the appointment of new members to the party's
executive board.
	   The 12 MPs will not lose their parliamentary status if the
Constitutional Court rules that the expulsion is not justified.
	   Earlier, Sanan said the 12 MPs could join the Democrats after
the Prachakorn Thai expelled them. But several other Democrat
executives were reported to be reluctant to accept the 12 MPs.
	   ''We decided not to join the Democrats because several Democrat
executives don't seem to welcome us. We don't want rifts to occur
within the Democrats because of us,'' Chalong said.
	   He said the 12 MPs would revive the name of Rassadorn Party,
which has been defunct.
	   ''It won't be difficult for us to recruit 5,000 members to
register a new party. We could do it in one day,'' Chalong added.
	   Chalong said he also informed Sanan about the group's decision
to allow the Democrats to bring in the Chat Pattana right away
without having to wait for the group's expulsion.
	   ''For the sake of the country, the Democrats should do it right
away,'' Chalong said.
	   The Chat Pattana has already offered itself as an option for the
Democrats to bolster their coalition's stability.
	   Deputy Finance Minister Pichet Phanvichartkul said Tuesday that
no one in the Democrat Party would mind accepting the 12 Prachakorn
Thai MPs to the Democrat's fold.
	   ''We have worked together for over six months now and we are now
very close,'' Pichet said.
	   Asked to confirm whether the Democrats would bring in the Chat
Pattana, Sanan said Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai had not made any
move over the matter yet.
	   ''Although it could happen, we have to first discuss the issue
with the coalition partners. So far, no discussion has taken
place,'' Sanan said.
	   ''Please note in your report that I am answering a question and
do not want to reshuffle the Cabinet, or else the prime minister
will kick me,'' Sanan quickly added.
	   Also Tuesday, Deputy Interior Minister Vatana Assavahame, one of
the 12 rebel MPs, said his group would file a suit with the Civil
Court Wednesday against the appointment of the new Prachakorn Thai
executives.
	   Vatana said the new appointment was not legal because his group
had earlier filed a suit against an earlier appointment of 11
executives, who took part in the board's decision to appoint the
new executives. Vatana said the court has not yet ruled on the
earlier suit yet.
	   
</TEXT>
