<HEADLINE>
New rules on promotions of monks, NATION
</HEADLINE>
New rules on promotions of monks, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   UNDER new regulations likely to be accepted and put into effect,
monks seeking promotion will have to focus more on developing local
communities, education and environmental surroundings, rather than
merely building monastic installations.
	   Deputy Education Minister Arkom Engchuan, who initiated the new
idea, said Tuesday he would push for a proposal to make amendments
to the existing regulations at a meeting between the Sangha Supreme
Council and the Religious Affairs Department's meeting next Monday.
	   He said the new regulations will encourage greater transparency
and eliminate loopholes, as well as prevent possible corruption, in
ecclesiastical promotion of senior Buddhist monks.
	   Arkom, who oversees the department, explained that current
requirements which impart huge importance to construction work,
distracts monks from performing their basic duties like providing
sermons or propagating Buddhism.
	   Examples of other activities which may be carried out in place
of the construction of monastic installations cited by Arkom
included the building of schools, development work on temple
personnel and providing assistance to help solve social problems in
nearby communities.
	   ''These will result in a greater magnitude of monks'
participation in the society,'' he said.
	   The Nation
	   
</TEXT>
