<HEADLINE>
Justice mulls special probe office, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Justice mulls special probe office, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   OPAS BOONLOMASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Justice Ministry has suggested that a ''special
investigation office'' be established to probe cases that
compromise the economy and national security.
	   The ministry is drafting a bill to establish a ''new Justice
Ministry'' which would give it 12 law-enforcing agencies, including
the Office of the Attorney General, which is now an independent
agency.
	   A subcommittee responsible for drafting guidelines for a new
structure and the authorities of the reformed ministry met Tuesday.
The meeting was chaired by Kramol Thongthammachat and also involved
representatives from related agencies.
	   At the meeting, the ministry proposed the formation of a special
investigation office under it which would oversee cases which
required cooperation between several agencies, sources said.
	   Such cases include crimes that could severely affect the
economy, national security and those committed by government
officials.
	   The ministry claimed such an office would provide greater
justice for the public and reduce damage resulting from the crimes.
It would also enhance the effectiveness of measures taken against
government officials who abuse their authority, the sources said.
	   However, the move was opposed to by the Police Department, which
said the new office would duplicate the duties of the police.
	   
</TEXT>
