<SLUG> BC-Russia-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian markets hit by Asia and concerns about lack of aid
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with closing figures. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russian stocks took a double beating Wednesday,
dropping because of market falls in Asia and fears that Western
governments won't bail Moscow out of its financial mess, traders
said.
	   The Russia Trading System closed 6.2 percent lower Tuesday.
Volume was light, but traders said Russian financial institutions
were selling aggressively.
	   Stocks fell from the beginning of trading, bounced back slightly
in early afternoon, and then continued lower until the close.
	   The Russian economy is stagnating, with little or no growth in
most areas. The government has promised deep cuts in public
spending and improved tax collection to try to improve the
situation.
	   There were also concerns that the drop in the market could
revive pressure on the ruble. The government has ruled out
devaluation, but the Russian Central Bank has limited resources
with which to defend the currency.
	   The Group of Seven industrialized nations were to discuss
Russia's financial problems at a meeting Wednesday in Paris, but
people close to the talks said that a full-fledged aid package was
unlikely.
	   The Russian stock market has already fallen more than 50 percent
since the beginning of the year. Few big investors are ready to
risk any more money in Russia until emerging markets settle down
around the world, dealers said.
	   (dj/ren/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
