<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Gucci, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Servants: Gucci ex-wife asked for help killing him
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CLARIFIES that witness refused request, minor editing &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MILAN, Italy (AP) _ The ex-wife of fashion heir Maurizio Gucci
asked a servant to arrange his death, and when Gucci was fatally
shot, admitted her responsibility, the servant testified Wednesday.
	   ```So ma'am, you did it,' I told her, and she answered, `Yes,
but it's left us in a mess, ''' Luciano Punta said at the murder
trial of Patrizia Reggiani Martinelli, according to the ANSA news
agency.
	   Punta said he was recounting a phone conversation he had with
Reggiani Martinelli some months after Gucci's killing in 1995.
Punta testified he had refused her request in the past.
	   Gucci's ex-wife is on trial for arranging the murder. Four other
people, including the alleged hit-man, also are defendants.
	   Punta, who worked at Gucci's villa in St. Moritz, Switzerland,
acknowledged on cross-examination that he did not like Reggiani
Martinelli.
	   ``She used people and threw them away after using them,'' ANSA
quoted him as saying. When pressed by defense attorneys about why
he didn't go to police when the woman first asked him to help find
a killer, he said, ``I knew they would have reached us sooner or
later.''
	   Before he took the stand, Punta's wife, Alda Rizzi, testified
that Reggiani Martinelli told her several times that she wanted her
husband dead. She resented his relationship with another woman,
said Rizzi, who was housekeeper at the villa.
	   ```I want to see him dead if it's the last thing I do,''' she
quoted Gucci's ex-wife as saying.
	   The prosecution says Reggiani Martinelli was obsessed with
Gucci's estate, and enraged about an alimony cut, so she allegedly
paid her co-defendants dlrs 300,000 to arrange and carry out his
killing.
	   In morning testimony, a businessman who said he had a love
affair with Reggiani Martinelli testified she never could have
arranged Gucci's killing.
	   Renato Verona said he had a ``sentimental affair'' with Reggiani
Martinelli in 1994, after the couple divorced, ANSA said.
	   Also coming to her defense was a dentist, Andrea Stramezzi, who
said he was a close friend.
	   The two men said Reggiani Martinelli was afraid Gucci would
dissipate the family wealth to the harm of the couple's two
children, ANSA reported.
	   (djw/vls)
</TEXT>
