<HEADLINE>
Montree denies he'll quit politics, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Montree denies he'll quit politics, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SOCIAL Action leader Montree Pongpanit Tuesday denied news
reports he planned to quit politics, saying he would run in the
next general election and keep the SAP as a political party, senior
party members said.
	   Montree's denial came at an SAP meeting he chaired, said the
sources.
	   Many dailies reported Tuesday the SAP was disintegrating because
Montree was washing his hands of politics. Many SAP MPs were
reported to be pondering a move to the Democrat Party.
	   Montree Tuesday held a meeting with SAP ministers who were told
the leader ''will absolutely not quit politics nor dissolve the
SAP, and will certainly run in the next election'', according to
Theerawat Siriwannasarn, deputy public health minister.
	   He said the participants at the meeting believed ''a third
party'' was trying to destroy the SAP by creating rumours about
Montree wishing to leave the political arena.
	   Montree will call a press conference Wednesday to deny the
rumours, he said.
	   Meanwhile, the Democrat Party's Communications Minister Suthep
Thaugsuban admitted he recently had a private meeting with Public
Health Minister Rakkiat Sukthana but denied they discussed
Rakkiat's intention to move to the Democrat Party.
	   Rakkiat told reporters senior SAP members wanted to keep the
party ''as long as possible. If I have to choose a new party, I
will choose the Democrat Party,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
