<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-East Timor,0436 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Annan hopes for sustained dialogue on East Timor issue
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ROBERT H. REID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Secretary-General Kofi Annan welcomed an
Indonesian move to free 15 East Timorese political prisoners and
said Wednesday he hoped this would develop into a ``sustained
dialogue'' on the future of the former Portuguese territory.
	   Annan was commenting on an announcement in Jakarta that
President B.J. Habibie had signed a decree to release 15 East
Timorese political prisoners ``as soon as possible.''
	   The list does not include jailed rebel chief Xanana Gusmao, a
symbol of the 23-year independence struggle. Indonesia regards
Gusmao as a criminal who committed violent acts in his fight
against Indonesian rule. He is currently serving a 20-year prison
term in Jakarta's Cipinang Prison.
	   ``The secretary-general welcomes the news that President Habibie
has signed a decree for the release of 15 East Timorese prisoners
and hopes that this will lead to the freedom of all other East
Timorese political prisoners,'' the United Nations said in a
statement.
	   ``He is also encouraged by the beginning of what he hopes will
be a sustained dialogue towards the resolution of the question of
East Timor ... based on a just, comprehensive and internationally
acceptable formula,'' the statement added.
	   In the East Timorese capital Dili, more than 3,000 East Timorese
protested Wednesday against Indonesian control of their homeland.
The demonstrations were an emphatic rejection of a proposal by
Habibie to grant special status to East Timor.
	   Indonesia took over East Timor in 1975 after Portugal withdrew,
ending four centuries of colonial rule. Indonesia annexed the
territory in 1976 in a move the United Nations never recognized.
	   For years, the United Nations has been sponsoring periodic talks
between Indonesia and Portugal under various formulas and echelons
to try to break the impasse.
	   The most recent session _ a working level meeting chaired by
U.N. special representative Jamsheed Markur of Pakistan _ achieved
no breakthrough.
	   During the rule of former President Suharto, who annexed the
former colony, Indonesia stuck by its position that East Timor is
an integral part of its national territory.
	   Portugal has been urging a referendum so East Timorese can
decide the territory's status.
	   Following Suharto's resignation, Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali
Alatas said the change in the presidency has provided an
opportunity for Portugal, East Timorese separatists and Indonesia
to resolve the issue.
</TEXT>
