<BODY>
<SLUG> PWA-RATE-INCREASE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PWA's rate increase approved, NATION
</HEADLINE>
PWA's rate increase approved, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   PIYANART SRIVALOASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PROVINCIAL residents must pay more for water starting this month
and shoulder a rate hike of more than 100 per cent next January as
the Cabinet approved the Provincial Waterworks Authority's proposal
Tuesday.
	   Under the plan, the rates will be adjusted by 30 per cent on
average, from Bt8.17 per cubic metre to Bt11.22 per cubic metre.
	   The residents will be charged Bt0.5 more per cubic metre per
month until the rates, now at Bt3.75 per cubic metre, reaches
Bt7.75 per cubic metre in January of next year.
	   Government agencies, state enterprises, small factories and big
factories will not face a 100 per cent increase even though they
will be subject to the same hike. The government agencies and small
factories which use 27.8 per cent of the total tap water, are
currently charged a minimum of Bt5 per cubic metre. Large factories
which use 14.7 per cent of the total tap water are now charged a
minimum of Bt6 per cubic metre.
	   Of the residents which use 57.3 per cent of total tap water, 63
per cent use less than 20 cubic metres per month, amounting to 19.6
per cent of the total. Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai said the reason
the PWA wishes to increase the rate is acceptable because it has
not increased rates for five years and has operated at a loss. The
agency also requires more money to expand its water production
investments in other areas. More than 18 million people are still
in need of the service.
	   Chuan said the rate hike is inevitable because the government
has no funds to support PWA's investment.
	   He said the PWA has also greatly improved its efficiency by
reducing the number of staff per water user from 17:1000 to 4:1000.
	   Chuan, however, ordered the PWA to reduce the amount of leakage
which has reached 30 per cent. ''This is a problem PWA must
seriously tackle,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
