<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Kazakstan-New Capital </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
President proud of new Kazak capital, many Kazaks object to costs
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos AST101-2 &QL; 
 &UR; By BIRGIT BRAUER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ASTANA, Kazakstan (AP) _ The president beamed. The people danced
in the streets. But behind the daylong celebrations dedicating
Kazakstan's new capital were questions about its cost and doubts
about its future.
	   Astana, a city of 300,000 people in northern Kazakstan, became
the capital of this former Soviet republic in December. On
Wednesday, President Nursultan Nazarbayev threw its coming out
party.
	   ``The new country brings new challenges for us,'' Nazarbayev
told foreign guests. ``We have to build a new state and we need a
new starting ground to ensure our lofty flight.''
	   The party included a free concert, folk-dancing, games on
horseback and a street parade with floats decorated like circular
tents known as yurts. Guests include the presidents of several
other former Soviet republics, the Chinese communications minister
and foreign diplomats.
	   But in spite of the celebration and large turnout, few people in
Kazakstan are enthusiastic about the move.
	   ``This is complete stupidity,'' said Alexander Kubasov, a
65-year-old pensioner. ``I don't see how this improves our lives
one bit.''
	   Many Kazaks believe the cost of the move, which has never been
fully made public, is money that could have been spent on overdue
wages and pensions.
	   The government says Astana was selected as the new capital
because of its central location, and because Almaty is overcrowded,
polluted and prone to earthquakes.
	   Astana has room to expand, is further away from conflicts in
Tajikistan and Afghanistan, and is slated to be the center for the
economic development of northern Kazakstan.
	   However, the chronic shortage of gas and electricity, harsh
winter climate and vicious mosquitoes have made the idea of moving
from comfortable Almaty to Astana unpopular with foreign businesses
and diplomats.
	   ``We have no plans to move until we feel Astana is ready to
support an international operation,'' said Canadian Ambassador
Richard Mann. ``I think we still have some problems with the
infrastructure.''
	   The high cost of setting up new offices and moving personnel are
other factors.
	   ``We did not get money from Congress to build the embassy in
Berlin, so we are not getting the money from Congress to build an
embassy in Astana,'' said U.S. Ambassador Elizabeth Jones.
	   Despite a two-year refurbishment of Astana's Soviet-style
buildings, nothing has been done to remove or hide the thick silver
heating pipes that run above ground along the sidewalk, be it for
lack of money or lack of time.
	   Many houses in the center of Astana were only renovated on the
side that faces the main street where Nazarbayev and his ministers
frequently travel.
	   In an effort to improve the image of the new capital, it was
renamed last month from Akmola _ which means ``white grave'' in
Kazak _ to Astana, which just means capital.
	   Unofficially, the move to Astana is expected to unite the
Russian-dominated north with the south, which is mainly populated
by ethnic Kazaks, and to counter separatist tendencies in the
region that borders Russia.
	   (str/ls/ml)
</TEXT>
