<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Norway-Tunnel Scandal </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Leaking tunnel forces delay in opening rail connection to new
</HEADLINE>
airport &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   OSLO, Norway (AP) _ A troublesome tunnel that is draining nearby
lakes forced Norway's state railroad on Wednesday to postpone the
start of high-speed rail service to a new national airport opening
north of Oslo in October.
	   The 12-kilometer (8 mile) long tunnel was billed as one of
Norway's most important environmental projects when work started
three years ago. Then water from lakes in popular recreation areas
began leaking into the tunnel, leaving what looks like giant mud
puddles in the forests above.
	   The NSB railroad announced that the tunnel would not be done in
time for the Oct. 8 opening of the Gardermoen Airport. It said an
emergency plan for transporting thousands of passengers a day the
45 kilometers (28 miles) from Oslo to the airport would put into
operation.
	   The plan includes extra buses, local trains and road
improvements.
	   Despite efforts to plug leaks that had drained up 4,000 liters
(1,000 gallons) a minute of lake water, the national water
management board said the tunnel was still leaking too fast.
	   The NSB railroad board on Wednesday announced that the tunnel
would not be opened until the problem was controlled. It was not
clear how long that would take.
	   ``I am very glad that the board of NSB has made protecting the
water balance and environment ... job No.1,'' said Minister of
Transport Odd Einar Dorum in a news release.
	   High-speed electric trains leaving the capital every 20 minutes
had been a key element in planning the new airport, which is to
replace the current Fornebu Airport near the heart of Oslo.
Officials fear that a delay beginning train service could lead to
major traffic jams.
	   (dm-ewm)
</TEXT>
