<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Israel </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Complicating deal, Amal says it will not return Israeli remains
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ZEINA KARAM &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ A Lebanese guerrilla group declared
Wednesday that it would not return the remains of an Israeli
soldier killed in southern Lebanon, a move that could stop a
reported deal with Israel to release Lebanese prisoners.
	   The declaration is the latest snag in attempts by the
International Committee for the Red Cross to trade Lebanese
prisoners held by Israel for the remains of as many as two Israeli
soldiers killed in September in southern Lebanon.
	   Officials of Hezbollah, the main Shiite Muslim group fighting
Israel in the south, have been saying for more than a week that an
exchange was imminent, with only ``final touches'' remaining.
	   On Wednesday, Sheik Nabil Kaouk, commander of Hezbollah
guerrillas in the south, said a deal has been reached to swap the
remains of the Israeli soldiers in return for ``more than a
hundred'' Lebanese prisoners and dead guerrillas held by Israel.
	   ``There are still a few details regarding the names of the
prisoners,'' Kaouk said.
	   But Amal, another Shiite Muslim group that is Hezbollah's bitter
rival, said it would not take part in the swap _ which it
apparently fears would bolster Hezbollah's popularity.
	   ``We will not return the remains of the Israeli soldier as long
as we are not in on negotiations regarding the exchange with
Israel,'' an Amal spokesman said Wednesday.
	   Hezbollah declined to comment on the statement.
	   The Iranian-backed Hezbollah says it holds most of the remains
from at least two Israeli soldiers left behind after the botched
commando raid Sept. 5. Twelve Israeli soldiers were killed in the
clash near the coastal village of Insariyeh.
	   But Amal, which also took part in the clash, is believed to have
the scalp of a soldier. Israel says the guerrillas hold the remains
of only one soldier, Itamar Ilya.
	   Hezbollah and, to a lesser extent, Amal are fighting to drive
Israeli troops from a strip of land they occupy in the south.
	   But the two groups have been locked in a power struggle for
control over the 1.2 million Shiites, Lebanon's largest sect. The
rivalry climaxed in a showdown in municipal elections in
predominantly Shiite southern Lebanon on Sunday.
