<SLUG> BC-Russia-Afghans </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nearly 150,000 Afghan refugees in Russia
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Nearly 150,000 Afghans live in Russia illegally,
one-third of them in Moscow and the surrounding region, the
Interfax news agency said Wednesday.
	   Most of the Afghans are linked in some way to the pro-Moscow
government of former President Najibullah and who fled when that
government collapsed in 1992, Interfax said, quoting a U.N.
official.
	   ``They have nowhere to stay,'' said Viktor Andreyev, acting
regional representative for the U.N. High Commission for refugees.
``They cannot work, study or receive medical care, even though
Russia is to blame for what happened to them.''
	   Gulam Muhamed, president of the Afghan Business Center in
Moscow, said the refugees cannot go home.
	   ``People linked to the Najibullah government or Soviet troops
are killed without a trial in Afghanistan,'' he said.
	   (ls)	   
