<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ethiopia-Occupied Village </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With Ethiopia-Eritrea
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Some stay, some flee Ethiopian village occupied by Eritrea
 &UR; AP Photos ASM101-102
 &UR; By KARIN DAVIES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ZALA AMBASSA, Ethiopia (AP) _ Frightened Ethiopians on Wednesday
loaded their belongings in donkey carts and fled their village now
occupied by Eritrean forces. A handful remained, saying the
invaders have been kind.
	   While booming mortars have fallen silent in this nearly empty
border village 105 kilometers (65 miles) southeast of the Eritrean
capital Asmara, fighting broke out to the west at another post
which both sides claim as their territory.
	   Troops fought with artillery and guns on the Badme-Shiraro front
at Erde Mattios, both governments confirmed. No details or casualty
reports were provided.
	   The two Horn of African nations, which earlier less than a
decade ago were part of the same country, are battling over several
stretches of border land. Tensions were fanned late last year when
Eritrea suddenly declared its own currency.
	   The Eritrean government has welcomed a plan approved by
diplomats at an Organization of African Unity summit Wednesday to
send a six-president delegation to mediate the dispute that
threatens to explode into a full-scale war.
	   Zala Ambessa, 2 kilometers (just over a mile) inside Ethiopia,
is not among the disputed areas. But it became a battleground last
week largely because a road linking the port of Massawa to
Ethiopia's Tigray Region passes through the border post. And many
Eritreans blame the Tigrayans for the border conflict.
	   The road that winds through craggy mountains was empty of the
trucks that usually thunder south to the Tigray capital Mekele. In
their place, buses and trucks caked with mud for camouflage ferried
troops and munitions to the front.
	   They drove past Zala Ambessa's short stretch of pastel-painted
shops and houses pockmarked by bullets and gouged by artillery
shells.
	   The lingering civilians among an original population of 15,000
covered their mouths and noses with scarves as they walked past the
stinking, contorted corpses of Ethiopian soldiers killed last week
but left unburied.
	   Eritrean troops rested a day after a fierce battle in which they
pushed at least 10 kilometers (6 miles) into Ethiopia. Some burned
fragrant eucalyptus wood to make steamy cups of sweet tea. One
slept in the shade of a broken down Ethiopian tank being repaired
by Eritreans.
	   Lema, a member of the Eritrean Defense Forces, said the
occupying army's relationship with the Ethiopians remaining in Zala
Ambessa was cordial.
	   ``They are living in peace with us. They are living their
lives,'' he said. Lema, who gave just one name, wore a gauze
bandage around his wounded ankle and a green beret.
	   Just down the paved road, Tsega Teame said now that she's
survived a week of fighting by hiding in her stone-walled house,
she's going to stay.
	   ``The Eritrean soldiers didn't hurt us, so why should I be
afraid,'' the 22-year-old said as she picked small stones from
freshly harvested wheat.
	   Medhin Berhe, stooped and shriveled at 68, said she had no
choice but to stay in the hovel she calls home. ``Where can I go?
Those who can afford it have gone to Mekele. But those of us who
are left, we are poor.''
	   Letebrhan Gebraslasie, 60, and her husband Redae Gebre, 66,
carried their meager belongings _ a small table, and washing basin
and clothes _ on their heads on the long walk to a remote village
where they hope they'll be safer.
	   ``Had it been peaceful, we would be sowing seeds now. If this
war continues, we'll have famine,'' Redae said, recalling hardships
in the border area during Eritrea's 30-year war for independence
from Ethiopia, which ended in 1991.
	   (kjd/sl)
</TEXT>
