<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ethiopia-Eritrea, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Renewed fighting Eritrea-Ethiopia conflict; U.S. facilitators to
</HEADLINE>
return
 &UR; Eds: ADDS OAU saying it will send a peace mission, reaction from
Eritrea. &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Ethiopia-Occupied Village
 &UR; By DIANNA CAHN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) _ Fighting broke out Wednesday
between Eritrean and Ethiopian troops in or near a contested border
area in northwestern Ethiopia, and both sides once again accused
the other of striking first.
	   The conflict has sparked an array of mediation attempts, so many
that they risk futher complicating the situation in volatile Horn
of Africa.
	   On Wednesday, the Organization of African Unity said a
delegation of African leaders would visit Ethiopia and Eritrea on a
peace mission. Eritrea meanwhile proposed that Egypt join the
United States and Rwanda in attempts at mediation.
	   ``Eritrean forces attacked our biggest post on the Badme-Shiraro
front at Erde Mattios, and fighting is continuing,'' Ethiopian
government spokeswoman Salome Tadesse said.
	   She said Erde Mattios lies south of the Tekeze River, outside
the so-called Yirga triangle, a 400-square-kilometer
(160-square-mile) contested slice of northwestern Tigray province.
	   The Eritrean News Agency, however, said Ethiopian forces
attacked Eritrean troops ``in the Badme area inside Eritrean
territory.''
	   Meanwhile, a U.S. team trying to facilitate a peaceful
settlement to the hostilities was expected back in Addis Ababa
later Wednesday, diplomatic sources said. It would be the third
time U.S. facilitators had travelled to the Ethiopian capital since
the simmering border dispute erupted into fighting on May 6.
	   The United States and Rwanda have put forth a four-point
proposal to stop the fighting and start talks. Ethiopia accepted,
but Eritrea demurred, claiming the plan, which suggests that
Eritrea withdraw to positions it held before May 6, needed more
work.
	   ``The proposal as it exists is still on the table and is still
valid,'' said a Western diplomat, on condition of not being further
identified. He added, however, that the plan could be ``worked on
around the edges.''
	   Regional military sources say that under the plan, Rwanda would
supply the peacekeeping forces to enforce demilitarization of
disputed border regions.
	   The 53-nation OAU said its delegation will try to persuade both
parties to agree to a cease-fire and peace talks. Eritrean Foreign
Minister Haile Woldetensae welcomed the proposal and said his
country was willing to immediately withdraw from disputed
territory. There was no immdiate comment fom his Ethiopian
counterpart.
	   In Cairo Wednesday, Eritrean officials said they wanted Egypt to
mediate the conflict as well.
	   ``Both Eritrea and Ethiopia have good relations with Egypt,''
which should facilitate Egyptian mediation between the two
neighbors, Abdullah Mahmoud Jaber, an adviser to Eritrean President
Isaias Afwerki, told reporters after meeting with President Hosni
Mubarak.
	   But Egypt and Ethiopia do not always see eye-to-eye on issues in
the Horn of Africa. Egypt has been backing one set of faction
leaders in an attempt to secure peace and set up a national
administration in war-ravaged Somalia; Ethiopia backs their rivals.
	   Asked why the Eritreans would be pushing into territory they
hadn't previously claimed belonged to them according to the Italian
colonial boundary drawn up in the 19th century, the Ethiopian
spokeswoman replied:
	   ``It is a difficult question to answer from here. They are
insane.''
	   Italy colonized Eritrea in 1885 but was defeated in its attempt
to conquer Ethiopia as well. Britain assumed control of Eritrea in
1941, and the territory later came under a U.N. mandate until 1962,
when it was absorbed into Ethiopia.
	   Rebels under Isaias' command fought Ethiopia for 30 years to
gain independence. They succeeded in 1993, after helping Ethiopian
rebels under now Prime Minister Meles Zenawi oust a 17-year
military dictatorship in 1991.
	   Ethiopia has not offered any figures on its own military
casualties but says Eritrea has suffered heavy losses at Erde
Mattios, some 600 kilometers (372 miles) north of Addis Ababa and
Zala Ambessa, 600 kilometers (372 miles) to the northeast.
	   The Western diplomat expressed concern that both Ethiopia and
Eritrea had pulled troops off their borders with Sudan to bolster
other fronts, thus weakening their western defenses. Both countries
support Sudanese rebel organizations fighting the National Islamic
Front government in Sudan.
	   (dc/sl/jh)	   
</TEXT>
