<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nigerian opposition angrily dismisses new leader's promises
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. NEW throughout to UPDATE with opposition leader lashing
out at Nigeria's new military leader, calling for national strike,
sources say two in Abubakar's inner circle detained under house
arrest. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By TIM SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Angrily dismissing vague promises of a
transition to civilian rule, Nigeria's opposition movement
Wednesday lashed out at the country's new ruler and called for
Nigerians not to recognize his government.
	   ``Nigerians must intensify their struggle to end military
rule,'' said Gani Fawehinmi, a Lagos attorney and one of the
country's best-known opposition activists. ``Nigerians should
expect nothing but a continuation of economic persecution and
political oppression.''
	   The denunciations followed a televised speech Tuesday by Gen.
Abdulsalam Abubakar, who took the helm of Africa's most populous
nation after the death Monday of Gen. Sani Abacha, a close ally who
had run Nigeria as a dictatorship for five years. Abubakar promised
to proceed with a transition to civilian rule that Abacha began,
though he gave no details on how it would happen.
	   To the contrary, he appeared to be consolidating his own power
base.
	   Two members of his inner circle were placed under house arrest
in the capital, Abuja, two independent sources confirmed Wednesday,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
	   ``The empty maiden address of Gen. Abubakar has confirmed that
there is no hope for Nigeria in Abacha's successor,'' said
Fawehinmi, speaking at a press conference on behalf of the umbrella
opposition group, the Joint Action Committee for Nigeria.
	   He said the group would go ahead with demonstrations in Lagos
planned for Friday, the fifth anniversary of annulled presidential
elections that were apparently going to be won by Moshood Abiola, a
billionaire businessman now in prison.
	   The group called on people to observe a nationwide 24-hour
strike, staying away from their jobs and keeping off the roads. It
also urged them not to recognize Abubakar's government.
	   However, it was not clear just how many people would follow the
calls for a strike. Similar calls for demonstrations have sometimes
resulted in only a few hundred people turning out.
	   Their derision of Abubakar's statements echoed the views of many
in Nigeria's opposition.
	   ``I don't see it getting better for now,'' said Clement Nwankwo,
head of the Constitutional Rights Project. He did add, though, that
pressure on Nigeria's opposition groups, which has been increasing
in recent months, may ease for a while.
	   ``They're not going to make any arrests this week because it
would send out too many signals of where they are headed,'' he
said.
	   Abubakar's vow to continue with a transition to civilian rule
has raised many opposition eyebrows.
	   Abacha had blatantly manipulated the system to ensure he would
be the only candidate in Aug. 1 presidential elections. The
transition was to be completed by Oct. 1.
	   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan called Abubakar to
congratulate him and encourage him ``to proceed with a peaceful and
democratic transition to civilian rule,'' Annan spokesman Fred
Eckhard said Wednesday.
	   The problem, many government opponents say, is that little
appears to have changed around the fortified compound in Nigerian
capital where Abacha spent most of his time in recent years,
surrounded by a small circle of advisers.
	   Those advisers selected Abubakar a few hours after Abacha's
death to, the opposition contends, try to keep the country on the
same course. But whether his selection will sit well with others in
the inner circle who also may have wanted the job is still far from
clear.
	   ``I don't know how long this is going to hold,'' said one
political analyst, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``I don't
know if he's been accepted by everyone.''
	   Abacha, who himself came to power in a 1993 coup, apparently
feared losing his authority. It was widely believed that he holed
up not only because of his health problems, but also because he
feared a coup by his fellow soldiers.
	   The compound was selected with defense in mind. Abacha's loyal
secret police are based just across the street and it is two hours
from the nearest major military garrison.
	   The secret police plagued Nigeria's opposition during Abacha's
years in power, tapping their phones, following them and always
leaving them fearing arrest.
	   Abacha also left Nigeria with a legacy of corruption that
crushed a thriving economy _ and left it nearly ruined.
	   Little in Nigeria functions these days, from the water supply to
the telephones. The only people who manage to live easily are those
who can afford to buy generators, truck in their own water and hire
security guards to fend off the rampant crime.
	   Even gasoline is nearly impossible to find in Nigeria, the
world's sixth largest oil producing country, since most of the
nation's refineries don't work and gasoline must be imported.
	   (tjs/bk)
</TEXT>
