<SLUG> BC-Russia-Poaching </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Crackdown on poachers would have caught more but lacked fuel
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ A crackdown on poachers in Russia's Pacific waters
would have been more effective if patrol ships and planes had had
more fuel, the ITAR-Tass news agency said Wednesday.
	   The eight-week crackdown by border guards and fish inspectors
resulted in 50 foreign ships being searched, said Maj.-Gen. Vasily
Neishchenko, acting commander of the North Eastern Border Guard
District.
	   Crews of seven foreign ships and nine Russian ships were charged
with violating fishing regulations, he said.
	   Russian border guards shot and killed two suspected Chinese
poachers after they allegedly resisted arrest and attacked the
Russians.
	   ITAR-Tass said an estimated 30.5 million rubles (dlrs 6 million)
was lost because of poaching. Only 6,000 rubles (dlrs 1,000) and
dlrs 15,000 U.S. were collected in fines.
	   (ls) 	   
