<SLUG> BC-Guinea-Bissau, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Proposed talks to end coup attempt in Guinea-Bissau collapse
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with report of traffic ban in capital in 9th graf,
quote from foreign minister stranded in Lisbon in final graf;
CORRECTS location of Bra suburb in 6th graf, spelling of Missira
sted Missara neighborhood in 9th graf &QL; 
 &UR; By BARRY HATTON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ Talks between renegade soldiers and a
parliamentary delegation collapsed Wednesday just before they were
due to begin, diminishing the chances of a peaceful end to the coup
attempt in the West African Nation of Guinea Bissau.
	   ``The (planned) negotiations fell apart because the president
said he couldn't vouch for the delegation's safety (in the rebel
held areas),'' opposition politician Helder Vaz said on Portuguese
state radio RDP-Africa.
	   The four-member delegation was hoping to mediate a peaceful
solution to the standoff between the rebels and government troops
surrounding them, but President Joao Bernardo Viera said he did not
agree with the talks proposal because he could not guarantee the
deputies' well-being.
	   Vaz said the soldiers who launched the coup attempt on Sunday
feared a major offensive against their positions after learning
that foreign troops had disembarked at Bissau port to support the
government.
	   He accused the international community of standing by while the
government prepared a ``bloodbath''.
	   An unknown number of rebels, led by former armed forces chief
Brig. Gen. Ansumane Mane, are holed up at a military complex, in
the suburb of Bra, 6 kilometers (4 miles) outside the capital.
	   Miguel Amado, the European Union representative in Bissau, said
in a telephone interview that the planned talks had not been
rescheduled. ``We are trying to convince the government not to
attack the rebels,'' Amado told the Lisbon bureau of the Associated
Press.
	   A ceasefire was in place in preparation for the talks, according
to Amado, but he was not sure whether it would hold.
	   The armed forces installed the headquarters of their anti-coup
operation in the neighborhood of Missira near the Bra suburb, and a
ban on the movement of unauthorized vehicles through the capital
was also in place, the Portuguese news agency Lusa reported later
Wednesday.
	   Troops from neighboring Senegal and the Republic of Guinea, that
arrived in the country on Tuesday to support the government forces,
had taken up positions near Bra, Lusa said.
	   The spokesman for the United Nations Secretary-general Kofi
Annan said in New York ``The secretary-general welcomes the
announcement of a cease-fire and calls for the early restoration of
normal and constitutional political dialogue within the country.''
	   Fred Eckhard also said Annan ``strongly deplores this military
confrontation.''
	   A spokesman for the U.S. embassy in Bissau said the capital was
quiet Tuesday night.
	   ``There was some sporadic mortar fire overnight, but it was a
whole lot quieter than it has been,'' Bryan Hunt said in a
telephone interview. ``It's a stalemate situation.''
	   Mane, describing himself as head of the self-proclaimed Military
Junta for the Consolidation of Democracy, Peace and Justice, said
in a statement Tuesday that he had no intention of seizing power
himself. The statement called on the President and the government
to step down.
	   Foreign Minister Fernando Delfim da Silva rejected the call for
an early ballot, saying legislative elections were scheduled for
this year and a presidential election was due in 1999.
	   Speaking from Lisbon Wednesday where he remained stranded
because of the coup attempt, Delfim da Silva said ``Everything
depends on the general...If the Brigadier puts down his weapons he
can obviously avoid a military confrontation.''
	   (bh/jt)
</TEXT>
