w1535 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SouthAfrica-MilitaryT 1stLd-Writethru   06-10 0373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Military Thefts, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police: Report indicating left-wing involvement in arms thefts was
</HEADLINE>
outdated &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with police commissioner calling report outdated;
recasts throughout to conform &QL; 
 &UR; By PAT REBER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ President Nelson Mandela's
office on Wednesday dismissed a police report that former black
liberation guerrillas were stealing weapons from military bases,
saying it was outrageous and shouldn't be taken seriouly.
	   National police Commissioner George Fivaz acknowledged the
report was outdated and contained ``preliminary investigative
assumptions.''
	   ``This report _ as can be expected during running police
investigations _ was overtaken by unforeseen developments,'' Fivaz
said.
	   Those developments apparently included the arrests in recent
days of three men with alleged right-wing connections in connection
with the thefts of 117 weapons _ including mortars and rocket
launchers _ and 200,000 rounds of ammunition.
	   SABC radio said an initial police intelligence report named a
group behind the thefts as MKAPLA _ an acronym connecting the
ruling African National Congress' former armed wing to the Azanian
People's Liberation Army, another former anti-apartheid military
group.
	   Mandela spokesman Parks Mankahlana said the report was not
presented up the chain of command because ``the government
discourages ... questionable reports.''
	   Mankahlana dismissed the report as ``outrageous,'' adding: ``No
one wants to waste time discussing these things.''
	   Fivaz said the police had no intention of misleading the
government about the arms thefts.
	   Earlier this year, South Africa's military chief Georg Meiring
resigned amid a controversy stirred up by a report about a coup
plot that the government says never existed. Meiring had given the
report to Mandela. A panel of judges said the report was unfounded
and never taken seriously by military personnel.
	   Last week, a group calling itself the Boere Weerstandsbewging,
or Boer's Resistance Movement, claimed the thefts of military
weapons and ammunition were carried out by Boers, the white
descendants of Dutch settlers.
	   (pr-aos)
</TEXT>
