<SLUG> BC-Guinea-Bissau, 3rd Ld Writethru,0657 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Proposed talks to end coup attempt in Guinea-Bissau collapse
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with report of traffic ban, CORRECTS spelling of
Missira sted Missara neighborhood in graf 8, CORRECTS location of
Bra suburb in graf 4. ADDS quote from foreign minister stranded in
Lisbon in final graf. No pickup &QL; 
 &UR; By BARRY HATTON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ Talks between renegade soldiers and a
parliamentary delegation collapsed just before they were due to
begin Wednesday, diminishing the chances of a solution to the coup
attempt in the West African Nation of Guinea Bissau.
	   ``The (planned) negotiations fell apart because the president
said he couldn't vouch for the delegation's safety (in the rebel
held areas),'' opposition politician Helder Vaz said on Portuguese
state radio RDP-Africa.
	   The four-member delegation had hoped to mediate a peaceful
solution to the standoff between the government and the unknown
number of rebels led by former armed forces chief Brig. Gen.
Ansumane Mane.
	   The rebels were holed up at a military complex in the suburb of
Bra, six kilometers (four miles) outside the capital.
	   Mane, describing himself as head of the self-proclaimed Military
Junta for the Consolidation of Democracy, Peace and Justice, issued
a statement Tuesday calling on President Joao Bernardo Viera to
step down and urged that early elections be held in July to choose
a new government. Mane has said he has no intention of seizing
power for himself.
	   Viera said, however, that he did not agree with the talks
proposal because he could not guarantee the deputies' well-being.
	   Vaz said the soldiers who launched the coup attempt on Sunday
feared a major offensive after learning that foreign troops were
disembarking at Bissau port. Troops from neighboring Senegal and
the Republic of Guinea arrived Tuesday to support the government
forces.
	   The armed forces installed the headquarters of their anti-coup
operation in the neighborhood of Missira within the Bra suburb, and
a ban on the movement of unauthorized vehicles through the capital
was in place, the Portuguese news agency Lusa reported late
Wednesday.
	   The troops from Senegal and the Republic of Guinea took up
positions with heavy artillery near the capital's main cemetery,
Lusa said.
	   Vaz accused the international community of standing by while the
government prepared a ``bloodbath''.
	   Miguel Amado, the European Union representative in Bissau, said
in a telephone interview that the talks had not been rescheduled.
	   ``We are trying to convince the government not to attack the
rebels,'' he said.
	   A cease-fire had been in place in preparation for the talks,
according to Amado, but he was unsure whether it would hold.
	   In New York, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said Wednesday
that he strongly opposed the use of force for ``non-constitutional
purposes,'' according to a spokesman, Fred Eckhard.
	   ``He strongly deplores this military confrontation, which has
already resulted in the loss of many lives,'' Eckhard said. ``The
secretary-general welcomes the announcement of a cease-fire and
calls for the early restoration of normal and constitutional
political dialogue within the country.''
	   Annan also asked ``all sides to ensure the safety of United
Nations staff working in Guinea-Bissau and to refrain from all
actions which may endanger the lives of the civilian population,''
Eckhard said.
	   Foreign Minister Fernando Delfim da Silva rejected Mane's call
for an early ballot, saying legislative elections were scheduled
for this year and a presidential election was due in 1999.
	   Speaking Wednesday from Lisbon, where he remained stranded
because of the coup attempt, Delfim da Silva said ``Everything
depends on the general ... If the Brigadier puts down his weapons
he can obviously avoid a military confrontation.''
</TEXT>
