w1540 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-France-US-Kosovo     06-10 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-US-Kosovo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sanctions ineffective, Contact Group prepares options
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHER BURNS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Ignoring economic sanctions, the Serbian army has
carried out ethnic cleansing by bombing homes in Kosovo to crush a
rebellion in the restive province, a senior U.S. official said
Wednesday.
	   The growing conflict threatens regional stability, and
Washington feels ``all options are open'' to pressure Serbian-led
Yugoslavia, the official said after meeting of the Contact Group of
nations concerned with the Balkans.
	   In addition to possible military options NATO defense ministers
are to discuss in Brussels on Thursday, Washington was urging the
U.N. war crimes tribunal in the Hague, the Netherlands, to
investigate the ethnic cleansing, the official said.
	   So far, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic ``has not been
responsive to sanctions'' warranting other international measures,
the official said. On the other hand, the Albanian Kosovo
delegation, he said, ``has acted in good faith.''
	   The conflict in Kosovo, where the ethnic Albanian majority seeks
independence, has killed 250-300 people and created as many as
100,000 refugees, the official said. Among them are up to 85,000
displaced people in Kosovo, 10,000 in Albania and thousands of
others who have fled to other countries.
	   Witnesses said Serbian MiG-21 jets have bombed homes, and U.S.
officials have seen heavy artillery damage to homes.
	   The Serbian ethnic cleansing efforts were aimed to create a
cordon sanitaire at the Albanian border to head off arms shipments
to Kosovo Albanians, he said.
	   The bombing and shelling meant ``a landmark has been achieved
because armed conflict exists.'' As a result, Washington was urging
that the war crimes tribunal consider sending investigators, he
said.
	   A G-8 meeting of Western and Russian officials in London on
Friday is to issue a joint statement, which the Contact Group of
political advisers was working on in their Paris meeting Wednesday,
the official said on condition of anonymity.
	   The official said that during the meeting, there was ``a
complete sense of unanimity on where the Contact Group was
heading,'' the official said. He declined to elaborate but said not
to expect any new economic sanctions.
	   The U.S. official declined to say if Russia backed military
action. He said he welcomed Russian efforts to help bring both
sides in the conflict to the table.
	   (cb)
</TEXT>
