<HEADLINE>
Cash award may go, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Cash award may go, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE legal advisory team of the interior minister Tuesday agreed
with a proposal to cancel cash reward for informers leading to
arrests and fines of traffic violators.
	   Thawil Praisont, head of the team, said the fines should be
equally shared between police and the state, instead of giving a
part to informers.
	   Under the current practice, the informer and police each receive
35 per cent of the fine while the remaining 30 per cent is sent to
the government coffers.
	   Earlier, it was alleged that police were corrupt in handing out
the informers' share because only a select few people had collected
the share for informers for almost all traffic fines collected in
Bangkok.
	   Thawil said the advisory team asked the Police Department to
find out how to systematically use or share the 50 per cent of the
fines among the policemen themselves.
	   The Police Department will have to seek approval for the
measures and the Finance Ministry will be kept informed on the
issue, Thawil said.
	   Meanwhile, a highway police sergeant in Phetchaburi complained
to Central Investigation Bureau Commissioner Pol Lt Gen Seri
Temiyavej that he had been harassed by his superiors and fellow
policemen after he exposed how highway police had been receiving
bribes.
	   Earlier, Sgt Chit Thongchit sent a letter to Seri, detailing
system in which truck operators sent bribes to highway and local
police.
	   Chit said he had been harassed in several ways, including being
ordered to do guard duty for more than 10 hours a day.
	   
