<HEADLINE>
Insurance officials discuss Holocaust victim policies
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Insurance officials from several countries,
including Switzerland the United States, met Wednesday in London to
discuss the problem of dormant insurance policies that belonged to
Holocaust victims.
	   The meeting was intended primarily as an ``exchange of
information,'' said Peter Streit, deputy director of the Swiss
Federal Office for Private Insurance.
	   He declined to give any further details of the closed-door
meeting, which was also attended by officials from France and
Austria, or to say what the next steps might be.
	   Heirs of Holocaust victims have filed a federal class-action
lawsuit in the United States seeking dlrs 1 billion from each of 16
European insurance companies. The heirs allege the companies
refused to honor the victims' insurance policies. The state of
California has filed to join the suit.
	   The insurance claims were filed after the heirs of Holocaust
victims lodged multibillion-dollar class-action suits in the United
States against Swiss banks. Swiss commercial banks, Jewish
organizations and lawyers for class-action claimants are currently
involved in negotiations on a global settlement of these claims.
	   (eml-kg)
</TEXT>
