<HEADLINE>
Couch potato soccer fans given a warning, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Couch potato soccer fans given a warning, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ARE you fit enough to watch World Cup matches for several
consecutive weeks starting from Wednesday? If not, health
authorities have some advice for you.
	   Eat more food, drink more water and exercise regularly, and that
will help make watching the event more enjoyable.
	   They are not kidding because watching the World Cup, which
begins Wednesday and ends on July 12, needs not only good planning
and a proper understanding -- it also needs a fit body.
	   Football fans who follow the tips will not only be able to enjoy
the matches more, but they will also not ruin their health, nor
have their work affected or risk a fatal accident because of lack
of sleep, the experts said.
	   Dr Somchai Lithongin, an official at the Public Health
Department, said regular exercise at least three times a week for
20 minutes is enough to help keep the body fit.
	   To prevent viewers from getting too exhausted, it is suggested
that they skip some matches and watch only the ones they are really
interested in.
	   ''People need six to eight hours sleep. But if they cannot make
that long sleep in one go, they should take frequent naps during
the day such as at noon and in the evening before the matches start
and go long into the night. Lack of sleep will lead to catching a
cold,'' he said.
	   The most suitable posture for watching the games is sitting with
the legs hanging down. Wrong posture could lead to body aches and
ruined eyesight.
	   ''Lying down is not good for you because it will hurt your back
and your neck because your head will be elevated,'' Somchai said.
	   More food and water are needed to compensate for the loss of
sleep, but it is not necessary to buy vitamins or supplements.
''Just a sweet or food to fill the stomach will prevent you from
being too tired,'' he said.
	   Sakchai Sakkulwong, director-general of the Welfare and Labour
Protection Department, said the department has issued warnings to
workers who watch the matches to exercise caution when controling
machinery.
	   ''Watching too much football at night could reduce their
efficiency and lead to accidents when using machines,'' he said.
	   The department will keep a record of accidents at work during
the Word Cup to map out preventive measures for the next World Cup
in four years time.
	   Meanwhile, many people who pawned their television sets to pay
school fees and other bills have descended on the pawn shops in
droves to get them back for the World Cup. There has also been a
sharp drop in the number of people turning up with television sets
to pawn, according to one shop in Min Buri.
	   Suriporn Dowudom, a manager at Min Buri Pawn Shop said since the
beginning of the month about 10 people a day had turned up to
reclaim their television sets. Conversely, only two people a day
were pawning their sets compared to an average of 10.
	   The Nation
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
