<HEADLINE>
Serm 'had confessed', NATION
</HEADLINE>
Serm 'had confessed', NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SUDA Pratyapat, mother of murder victim Jenjira Ploy-angunsri,
Tuesday told the presiding judge that defendant Serm Sakhonrat
confessed to killing her daughter because he could not stand losing
his sweetheart to another man.
	   At the sensational trial where the confessed killer retracted
his statement about the grisly killing of the fifth-year medical
student, Suda took the witness stand to shed some light on the
defendant, a computer science graduate and second-year medical
student.
	   After the Jan 26 disappearance of Jenjira and persistent
inquiries by her family, Serm finally requested a meeting three
days later with the mother in his Chon Buri home town, the witness
said.
	   During the meeting, she recounted, the defendant expressed
regret for failing to escort Jenjira home. He also confided he had
a sexual relationship with the victim and could not bear the
break-up of their love affair.
	   Two days before her death, Jenjira informed her mother she had
broken up with Serm and had started dating another boy.
	   The witness added that although she suspected Serm was not
speaking the whole truth, she thought he was only holding Jenjira
against her will somewhere in order to reason with her.
	   The family posted a public missing person announcement the month
after Serm and his mother refused to reveal the whereabouts of
Jenjira.
	   Following his arrest and confession of how he killed her and
covered up the evidence, Serm admitted to Suda that he had killed
his sweetheart because he had been in a rage due to his broken
heart. He also informed her that the sliced-up body parts
discovered in his apartment toilet were Jenjira's remains, saying
there was no reason to lie because ''the game was over''.
	   The Criminal Court has set a June 23 date for the trial to
continue.
	   BY OPAS BOONLOM The Nation
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
