<HEADLINE>
Thai Embassy besieged, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Thai Embassy besieged, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A GROUP of about 60 Cambodians working at a Phnom Penh-based
Thai garment company in Phnom Penh Tuesday surrounded the Thai
Embassy there demanding better welfare from the company, the
Foreign Ministry announced Tuesday.
	   The Cambodians started gathering at about 9.30 am and handed
over a demand that the embassy be a broker in negotiating with the
company's owners.
	   A first secretary accepted a 10-point letter from the group.
	   However, they refused the official's request to disperse, saying
they would continue the demonstration until they got satisfactory
results from the company.
	   Later in the day, Chalermchart Thasukhon, a counsellor, met
owners of the company to seek a compromise between the two sides.
	   The ministry said the gathering had been peaceful and that
Cambodian police were deployed to guard the area.
	   The workers demanded that the company provide better medical
care for its workers, stop forcing them to work on weekends and
appoint representatives to coordinate with the workers.
	   The workers also demanded that the company stop paying them with
fake banknotes.
	   The Nation
	   
