<HEADLINE>
Thaksin in major bid to woo Narong, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Thaksin in major bid to woo Narong, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   VETERAN politician Narong Wongwan confirmed Tuesday he has been
approached to become the chief adviser of the new political party
that communications tycoon Thaksin Shinawatra plans to set up.
	   ''They have made the offer to me but no details have been
discussed yet,'' he said in a telephone interview from his home in
Chiang Rai province.
	   Narong, one of Thailand's senior politicians from the generation
that spawned veterans like Banharn Silapa-archa, Pramarn Adireksarn
and Bhichai Rattakul, was elected several times as the
representative of Phrae province and long commanded staunch voter
support for MPs in his fold in the northern constituencies before
he washed his hands of politics in 1995.
	   During the heyday of his political career, he was the leader of
Ruam Thai Party and later the Samakkhitham Party, which supported
non-elected Gen Suchinda Kraprayoon in the premiership before the
popular uprising that forced the general out in May 1992. Narong
missed the opportunity to be nominated as prime minister after the
election in March 1992 when the US government rejected his visa
application, citing information about his questionable business
background.
	   One thing Narong and Thaksin have in common is that they are
both northerners. Narong said Tuesday he might be able to help
Thaksin's party win at least 35 of 70 parliamentary seats in the
north if he decides to join it as chief adviser.
	   ''I can support them by assuming an advisory role if they will
really need me,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
