<SLUG> BC-Sudan-Attack, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0312 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Three aid workers killed in ambush in southern Sudan
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with WFP statement, quotes &QL; 
 &UR; By MOHAMED OSMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) _ Armed assailants have opened fire at a
United Nations relief convoy in Sudan, killing three aid workers
and wounding four others.
	   The World Food Program said gunmen opened fire Tuesday morning,
killing field officer El Haj Ali Hammad and Sumain Samson Ohiri, a
driver.
	   Maggboul Mamoun, a staffer for the Sudan Red Crescent, was also
killed and three other Sudan Red Crescent workers and an escort
were injured, the Rome-based agency said.
	   All victims were Sudanese, sources in Sudan told The Associated
Press.
	   ``WFP condemns these brutal murders and we are seeking an
investigation into the tragic killings,'' the agency's executive
director, Catherine Bertini, said in Rome.
	   A government soldier was among those injured, the official
Sudanese News Agency reported.
	   A Sudanese government minister, Gen. Hassan Dahawi, accused the
rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army of carrying out the attack on
the three-car convoy in Southern Kordofan province, about 500
kilometers (310 miles) southwest of the capital Khartoum.
	   ``We call upon all U.N. organizations and the voluntary
organizations to continue their humanitarian mission without paying
attention to such ugly provocations that target humanity and
peace,'' Dahawi was quoted as saying by SUNA.
	   SPLA rebels have been fighting since 1983 for autonomy and
development in the predominantly Christian, African and animist
south, which has traditionally been dominated by the Muslim and
Arabized north.
	   An estimated 1.5 million people have died in the fighting and
related famines. The WFP runs a major program in the south to bring
food to refugees and starving people. 	   
</TEXT>
