<BODY>
<SLUG> SPEAKER-TO-FIGHT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Speaker to fight back if challenged, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Speaker to fight back if challenged, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PARLIAMENT President Wan Mohammad Noor Matha Tuesday said he
would fight back in the second round of a war of words if
challenged by Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai.
	   His defiance came after Premier Chuan confirmed on Monday he
would allow his Democrat Party MPs to retaliate against any attacks
from the New Aspiration Party where Wan Noor is a deputy leader,
and after reports that the premier had allowed his deputy secretary
general Nipon Boonyapattharo to send a letter of protest to Wan
Noor for attacking Chuan.
	   Wan Noor said he challenged the premier because he could not
tolerate his public comments on the NAP's attempts to expand its
base in the Democrat Party's traditional stronghold in the South by
giving a false impression that the NAP was trying to buy votes.
	   Wan Noor, a Yala MP, said when he received Nipon's letter of
protest he would have his secretary reply in an open letter so the
public would know what was going on.
	   He said Chuan, the Democrat Party leader, was making unkind
comments on the activities of his party in the South.
	   Responding to criticism on Monday by MP Surachet Wae-asae
(Dem-Narathiwat) that Wan Noor should have resigned as Parliament
president before attacking the premier, he said Chuan should as
well had stepped down as prime minister before flying in public
such false impressions about the NAP.
	   Meanwhile, Deputy Commerce Minister Paitoon Kaewthong, one of
Wan Noor's targets of veiled attacks of vote buying in the last
election, said: ''I can't understand why people of Parliament
President Wan Noor's calibre could recourse to a smear campaign in
the manner of an old style politician. But I've not met him yet.
What he said was not productive.'' He said he defected from the NAP
to the Democrat Party before the last election because the NAP had
become an ''election gang'' and not a political party.
	   Interior Minister and Democrat secretary-general Sanan
Kachornprasart said he did not plan to sue Wan Noor for defamation
because he had not been named in the Wan Noor's accusation of vote
buying.
	   
</TEXT>
