<SLUG> BT50-BN-BOND-ISSUE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Green light to Bt50 bn bond issue, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Green light to Bt50 bn bond issue, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   WICHIT CHAITRONGASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Thai government Tuesday approved the issue of Bt50 billion,
or US$1.16 billion, of domestic bonds as part of the planned Bt500
billion aimed at easing the debt burden of the Financial
Institutions Development Fund (FIDF).
	   The baht-denominated bonds, for domestic sale, would be issued
by the Finance Ministry and have a one-year maturity with a yield
of 12.75 per cent, according to Akapol Sorasuchart, the government
spokesman.
	   The 12.75 per cent interest rate is calculated from the average
fixed deposit rate of the five large-sized Thai commercial banks
minus 0.25 per cent, he said.
	   The issue of the Bt50 billion in bonds is in accordance with the
royal decree which allowed the Finance Ministry to issue bonds
worth Bt500 billion.
	   Akapol said the bonds will be sold by the Bank of Thailand to
financial institutions which are the creditors of the FIDF. The
proceeds from the sale will be given to the FIDF and the FIDF will
spend the money to redeem the bonds earlier sold to the BOT.
	   According to Akapol, the government decided to issue only Bt50
billion in its first tranche of bonds because the interest rate
currently is quite high.
	   The first tranche of bonds are also to test the current market,
he said.
	   Deputy Finance Minister Pisit Lee-ahtam said the remaining Bt450
billion in bonds will be issued within this year.
	   He said the BOT would certainly be able to accomodate the bond
sale with its current daily cashflow of about Bt80 billion.
	   The bonds in the first tranche will be sold only to the
institutions which are indebted to the FIDF, and the later tranches
will be offered to other parties.
	   As of June 5, the FIDF is having total liabilities of Bt1.187
trillion; Bt733.68 billion it borrowed from the repurchase market
and Bt393.42 billion which have been converted to negotiable
certificate of deposit of Krung Thai Bank and Krungthai Thanakit
Plc.
	   With the interest rate of 17-20 per cent per annum in the
repurchase market, the FIDF has to pay for the monthly interest of
Bt12 billion.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
