<BODY>
<SLUG> VINIT-SETS-NEW-GOALS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Vinit sets new goals, Damask goes to BBDO, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Vinit sets new goals, Damask goes to BBDO, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   KWANCHAI RUNGFAPAISARNASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE name ''Damask'' will soon disappear from the local
advertising industry after its founder, Vinit Suraphongchai, sold
his remaining stake of 20 per cent to BBDO Worldwide early this
year, marking the end of his control in the agency he founded 11
years ago.
	   Vinit told The Nation in an exclusive interview that BBDO
decided to delete ''Damask'' from the agency's name and Damask/BBDO
will soon be renamed BBDO Thailand. The agency will be part of the
international BBDO network which now owns 100 per cent the firm.
	   ''It was the beginning and the end that I witnessed during my
era. Just like a boxer, I've tried my best to fight and now it's
over. I want to pass the job on to the next generation,'' he said.
	   However, advertising veteran Vinit remains the company's
chairman, while the chief executive officer post goes to Decha
Tangpanitansook, a former executive at Results Advertising Co, a
subsidiary of Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Thailand. BBDO recently recruited two
top executives -- Decha and Suthisak Sucharittanonta from Results
Advertising Co. Suthisak, who is an international award-winning
creative staff member, has been named BBDO Thailand's executive
creative director.
	   Vinit will act as a supervisor for BBDO Thailand and will not be
involved in routine work and policy-making. The new policy will see
Decha bringing Results' working style to BBDO by grouping account
management and creative people in one team to better serve clients.
	   ''I am old enough to retire and should spend the rest of my life
on contributing to the industry or becoming a lecturer. I will also
spend time playing my favourite sport, golf,'' he said.
	   A rising star in the advertising industry more than a decade
ago, Vinit left Lintas Thailand as the agency's managing director
and founded Damask in 1987, grooming it from a small boutique to
one of the country's top 20 advertising agencies. The agency
recorded Bt610 million in billings last year.
	   When Damask was first established, Vinit acquired a 50-per cent
share with Saravut Krykad, a leading creative man, holding a 40-per
cent stake. Saravut no longer holds any stake in Damask/BBDO. Vinit
gradually sold 30 per cent during the past four years. BBDO started
investing in Damask in 1994 and became a major shareholder in 1996.
It was early this year that Vinit decided to let the last stake go
to BBDO.
	   ''I understand the situation, as it's common for any
multinational agency to expand its business empire by either
starting from scratch or taking over local firms. Never mind that
the name Damask is no longer there, the Thai staff are still
working at the agency and they should benefit as part of an
international network,'' he said.
	   Vinit now prefers to position himself as a ''senior'' of the
advertising community, focusing on the social contributions he can
make. He was president of the Advertising Association of Thailand
during 1984-1986 and was also the chairman of the organising
committee of the 15th Adasia in Bangkok in 1986. Vinit is now
chairman of the Asian Federation of Advertising Associations. His
most recent work for the advertising industry was the first Asia
Pacific Advertising Festival held in March this year. He will also
be a key person in hosting Adasia in Thailand next year.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
