<BODY>
<SLUG> PIONEER-EXPECTS-SALES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pioneer expects sales boost in Thailand, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Pioneer expects sales boost in Thailand, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   SUPUNNABUL SUWANNAKIJASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ALTHOUGH sales of Pioneer Electronics in Asean countries are
expected to plunge by 20 to 30 per cent this year, the company
hopes its operations in Thailand will enjoy a growing market share
due to low costs.
	   Pioneer Electronics Marketing (Asia) Co president Naoki Saito
said the regional economic turmoil will substantially bring down
the company's sales in Asean by 20 to 30 per cent year-on-year.
	   Pioneer's Asean operations in 1997 recorded sales of around YEN
18.15 billion, accounting for around 5 per cent of the
manufacturer's total sales last year worth YEN 363 billion. The
markets in Indonesia and the Philippines have been the worst
affected by the economic turmoil, yet the firm's share of the
shrinking audiovisual market in Thailand is increasing.
	   ''Thailand is our most important market in Asean, next to
Singapore. During the past couple of years, our market share has
been increasing to over 10 per cent because of new product
launches,'' Saito said. To offset the contracting domestic market,
Pioneer is emphasising increasing its market coverage to benefit
from share losses by competitors. In low purchasing markets like
Indonesia and the Philippines, the company plans to limit its
production capacity to suit market demand as well as choose
suitable products for launch in those markets, he added.
	   The parent company has supported its Thai operations through the
promotion of digital video disc (DVD) and mini-system audio
products, Saito said.
	   Masahiro Kawamura, managing director of Pioneer Electronics
(Thailand) Co Ltd, said the company expects to increase its share
this year despite the market sluggishness. At present, the
company's share of the DVD market is 40 per cent, and 30 per cent
for car stereo systems.
	   ''We expect to gain a much greater market share this year due to
price competitiveness,'' he said. The company's production facility
in Ayutthaya province has helped it reduce operating costs by 10
per cent and has slashed 30 per cent from its import duty bill. The
lower production costs have allowed more marketing activities.
	   Pioneer Tuesday unveiled its Pioneer Plasma Display, a 40-inch
viewing screen which can be connected to several sources such as
computers, DVD, laser disc and video players as well as television
tuners. The product, priced at Bt600,000 a set, targets businesses
that need to publicise information, such as the stock exchange,
airports, hotels and advertising companies.
	   The company has approached the Airports Authority of Thailand,
the State Railway of Thailand, the Communications Authority of
Thailand, the Expressway and Rapid Transit Authority of Thailand
and the Stock Exchange of Thailand to market its product. It
expects sales to reach Bt100 million in the first year.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
