<SLUG> BC-Caribbean-Sugar,0252 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sugar production from six Caribbean countries reaches 472,000 tons
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) _ The six member countries of Sugar
Association of the Caribbean together produced about 472,000 tons
(42,800 metric tons) of sugar between November and May 31, the
group reported Wednesday.
	   Barbados, Trinidad and Tobago, Belize, St. Kitts and Nevis,
Guyana and Jamaica exported about 253,000 tons (230,000 metric
tons) to Europe under treaty arrangements giving preference to
Caribbean sugar, and 35,400 tons (320,000 metric tons) under other
arrangements, the group said.
	   Sugar exports to the United States totaled 31,000 tons (28,200
metric tons), and 13,788 tons (12,500 metric tons) went to other
markets.
	   Barbados produced 47,900 tons (43,500 metric tons), Belize,
92,000 tons (83,600 metric tons), and Jamaica produced 141,300 tons
(128,000 metric tons). St. Kitts produced 21,500 tons (19,500
metric tons), Guyana 90,000 tons (81,700 metric tons) and Trinidad
and Tobago, 78,800 tons (71,500 metric tons), the association said.
	   The sugar harvest began in November in Jamaica, December in
Belize, and January in Trinidad and Tobago, Barbados and St. Kitts
and Nevis. The harvest started in February in Guyana.
	   In April, the association lowered its projections for the
1997-1998 crop from 732,000 (664,000 metric tons) tons to 725,000
tons (657,700 metric tons) because of drought in some islands
caused by the El Nino weather phenomenon.
</TEXT>
