<HEADLINE>
Stop the killing in Kosovo now, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Stop the killing in Kosovo now, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Fan Yew TengASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   NOW that thousands of ethnic Albanians are fleeing Kosovo amid
fierce attacks from Serb forces, we are once again seeing Slobodan
Milosevic, President of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia,
destroying what little is left of the land of the southern Slavs.
	   At the height of the Bosnian holocaust four years ago, I had
warned against shaking hands with Slobodan Milosevic because he was
the mastermind behind the genocide there. As a bigger war criminal
than Radovan Karadzic, Milosevic should have been indicted.
Subsequent events have given credence to this contention.
	   Elections just a few days ago have shown that the people in the
constituent republic of Montenegro are sick and tired of Milosevic.
	   As for the people of Kosovo, they have been oppressed by the
Serbs for a long time now. As the tragedies in Bosnia and Rwanda
have taught us, the world cannot wring its hands in despair,
confusion, procrastination and indecision again, and hope that more
meetings and more appeals will solve the problem.
	   The time for action is now, not after hundreds or thousands of
innocent people including women, children, the elderly and the sick
have been slaughtered or raped or tortured.
	   The United Nations, Nato and the European Union should send
peacekeeping forces into Kosovo immediately, not next week or next
month when it will be too late. The talks can come later after the
lives have been saved.
	   
</TEXT>
