<SLUG> BC-Jamaica-World Cup-Glued to TV,0174 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Jamaicans carry TVs to work for first World Cup matches
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) _ Office employees carried televisions to
work and bank customers stood transfixed before sets in bank
lobbies as Jamaica turned its attention to the World Cup on
Wednesday.
	   Few telephones rang and traffic on Kingston's streets dropped
off as the first round of matches began. Most televisions were
tuned to the face-off between Brazil, the defending champion, and
Scotland.
	   Interest in the World Cup on this Caribbean island has been
intense since Jamaica won its first-ever berth in the championship
playoffs.
	   It will be the first chance a Caribbean country has had at the
World Cup since Haiti played in 1974.
	   Jamaica has its first match against Croatia on June 14 and plays
Argentina on June 21. Both of those games will be on Sundays.
	   Business owners said they are bracing for large-scale absences
on Jamaica's first weekday match, a game against Japan at Gerland
Stadium in Lyon.
</TEXT>
