<SLUG> BC-Belarus-US, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Belarusian government bent on evicting U.S., other ambassadors
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS throughout to ADD quotes from ambassador, TRIMS pvs. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo planned. &QL; 
 &UR; By MARINA BABKINA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MINSK, Belarus (AP) _ Belarus said Wednesday that it had
postponed a deadline for foreign diplomats to leave their
residences, but continued to insist that the diplomats would be
evicted to permit urgent repairs.
	   The United States, Russia, France, Germany and Lithuania have
formally protested the planned eviction, which they say is in
violation of international law.
	   France and Lithuania said they will recall their ambassadors for
consultations if Belarus persists, and Washington has said it will
also take some action in response.
	   Belarusian officials reluctantly agreed to extend Wednesday's
deadline for the diplomats to leave until next week.
	   Oleg Novikov, deputy head of the Dipservice state agency in
charge of maintaining the diplomatic residences, told reporters on
Wednesday that his workers hadn't yet cut power and water supply to
the Drozdy complex but would do that next week.
	   ``I think they should use the time left to remove the
furniture,'' he said.
	   Novikov said that ambassadors from Bulgaria and several
ex-Soviet republics had left the complex in pine woods on the
western outskirts of the capital, Minsk, before Wednesday's
deadline and workers have already started on repairs which will
take 14 months.
	   The ambassadors say that under international law, their
residences are considered sovereign territory and governments have
no right to enter without permission or insist that diplomats
leave.
	   U.S. Ambassador Daniel Speckhard said that envoys would prefer
to make arrangements to remain in the complex during the repairs.
He noted that the government's decision appeared to have been
sudden, and that some embassies had signed new multi-year leases
the month before.
	   ``The issue is it's unprecedented in recent times for any
countries in peacetime to evict all of the ambassadors through
ultimatums, deadlines, threats, from what, under the Vienna
Convention is inviolable territory,'' Speckhard said in an
interview with The Associated Press.
	   Officials in the former Soviet republic expressed regret for the
``inconvenience,'' but insisted the diplomats leave, saying the
complex's water supply is no longer safe and the sewage system is
polluting the environment.
	   ``There is a danger that Drozdy will float in its own sewage,''
Foreign Minister Ivan Antonovich said Tuesday on Belarusian state
radio. ``We can't endanger diplomats' lives''
	   Speckhard said he has had no problems with either his water or
sewage systems in the year he has lived in the complex.
	   ``To the contrary, we have excellent water and sewer service,''
he said.
	   The Foreign Ministry has offered the ambassadors apartments in
downtown Minsk, cottages 30 kilometers (18 miles) outside Minsk or
plots on which to build new residences.
	   ``All of these options are very weak,'' Speckhard said, noting
that several countries, including the United States, have spent
considerable sums renovating their residences.
	   The dispute began in April when the government served notice
that the ambassadors would have to vacate their homes in the
rambling, wooded housing compound by Wednesday.
	   (mb/vi/ml/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
