<SLUG> CAMBODIA-PUSHING-ASEAN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cambodia pushing on with preparations to join Asean, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Cambodia pushing on with preparations to join Asean, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Zuraimi AbdullahASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THERE is no hitch in Cambodia's preparations for admission into
Asean.
	   Cambodian Economy and Finance Ministry's senior economic
official Dr Aun Porn Moniroth said he was ``instructed by my Prime
Minister to continue preparing, at the technical level, Cambodia's
entry into Asean''.
	   ``People have asked us to reconsider joining Asean ... but I
think there is politics behind this,'' Moniroth said during a
regional seminar ``New Members of Asean: Dismantling Barriers and
Facing Economic Challenges'' in Vientiane, Laos.
	   He was responding to suggestions that Cambodia continue to
consider its entry into Asean following the recent developments in
the region especially the unrest in Indonesia.
	   Moniroth said it was imperative for Cambodia to join Asean if it
wanted to build its economy.
	   ``Asean will provide new opportunity for growth ... looking
ahead, our natural endowments, low-cost labour force and strategic
location position ... we want to take advantage of access to this
high growth regional market of 500 million people.''
	   Meanwhile, in his presentation, Moniroth said that while it
lacked experience and economic strength, the country nevertheless
had strong vision for its future as a full-fledged and equal
partner of Asean.
	   ``We also have strong commitment to proceed along our chosen
democratic and market-oriented path,'' he said in his paper titled
``Opening Doors: Promoting Market Economy from Cambodia's
Perspective''.
	   He said emerging as an independent nation from colonial rule in
1953, the new Government's first task was to create a consensus on
the national vision, policies and strategies to rehabilitate and
develop the country.
	   ``Guided by strong vision, determination and a strict
discipline, we have brought macro-economic stability to our country
for the first time in several decades.
	   ``The market-oriented shift of our economy started in 1989, and
has been greatly accelerated both qualitatively and quantitatively
by the Government.''
	   He added that trade had been liberalised since 1993 with the
removal of restrictions on trading activities.
	   The country's real gross domestic product growth has reached a
healthy six to seven per cent over the past four years, he stated.
	   Per capita GDP, although still very low, jumped from US$183 in
1991 to US$382 in 1996, despite a 21 per cent increase in
population during that period.
	   Moniroth said to sustain its growth momentum, Cambodia needed to
consolidate past gains as well as ensure stability and put in place
new mechanisms and processes.
	   For example, the country has taken serious measures to encourage
the private sector and foreign investors.
	   The country is also planning to establish internal capital
markets to tap domestic savings and to secure additional outside
capital.
	   ``We encourage investments in infrastructure and BOT
(build-own-transfer) agreement as well as by IPPs (independent
power producers) for power generation,'' he added.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
