<SLUG> BC-OAU-Human Rights Court </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
African summit approves continental rights court
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   OUAGADOUGOU, Burkina Faso (AP) _ African heads of state meeting
at a summit here have approved a plan to create a continent-wide
human rights court, officials announced Wednesday.
	   The African Court on Human and Peoples Rights was approved by 29
state and government leaders attending the three-day Organization
of African Unity summit which ended Wednesday, the OAU said in a
statement.
	   The court will aim to strengthen and improve legal systems in
African countries and help ``protect and promote human rights in
Africa.''
	   Before the court will be created, 15 member states must ratify
the plan.
	   The court is intended to allow member states and individuals
claiming to be victim of human rights abuses to lodge complaints
against other individuals or member governments.
	   Officials have not said what decisions or judgments can be made
by the judicial body. OAU members are to submit nominations for the
eight judges on the court.
	   The court will be based on the Charter of African and Peoples
Human Rights.
	   (gam/bk)
</TEXT>
