</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> FOREIGNERS-MORE-LIKELY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`Foreigners more likely to buy equities', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
`Foreigners more likely to buy equities', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   FOREIGN investors are still keen on Asia, but any major fund
inflows into the region will largely be in the form of buying into
company equities instead of subscribing to debt.
	   This prognosis was made by Arthur Andersen Business Consulting
managing partner for Asia Pacific Thomas P. Vance during an
interview in Kuala Lumpur on Friday.
	   He said foreign investors were more keen on a company's
performance instead of simply investing in the region.
	   ``The recent performance of red chips in Hong Kong is one good
example of how they did well initially but later lost their lustre
as their fundamental operations did not justify their share prices.
	   ``In our global consulting business, we have always emphasised
the need for a company to have a good cashflow to attract
investment and funds, and this advice still holds true.''
	   Vance said most investors around the world still kept a close
watch on developments in Asia as the region continued to represent
potential for strong economic growths which could translate into
solid returns on investments.
	   ``As long as there is a good idea that is implemented well,
there will always be money attracted to such operations, despite
the overall gloom that has been cast over this region.''
	   He also said the region's economic problems had led many top
executives to take another long look at their operations to
maximise their investments so as to ensure strong cashflow
positions.
	   ``Cashflow is perhaps the most important aspect of any business.
For every unit of cashflow, you are usually able to raise between
three and five units of loans from the banks.
	   ``That is the basis on which we advise many of our clients when
they ask us for help to streamline their operations to expand their
businesses. So, getting bank loans is still possible during these
trying times.''
	   Vance, who will be based in Tokyo from August, said the major
emerging markets that many American investors were still keen on
were in Asia and Latin America.
	   ``The Europeans are the ones mostly investing in Eastern Europe
and a bit in Africa.''
	   But he cautioned against raising expectations that American
funds would pour in large amounts into Asia soon as the current
economic outlook in the US was very positive.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
