w1604 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  RISING-CONCERN-FINANCESs     06-10 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> RISING-CONCERN-FINANCES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rising concern over dwindling public finances, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Rising concern over dwindling public finances, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Vadim PotapovASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   FOR the first time in two months, attention of Russian public is
not focused on the governor's elections in Siberian Krasnoyarsk
region. People relaxed for a while after the contenders' impressive
statements over national television.
	   Anyway, a new event appeared the day after this Kraynosarsk
elections was over, and at that time almost half of Russia's 89
regions seemed to get involved in it.
	   It was the biggest miner's strike that Russia witnessed in
recent years.
	   The explosion of protest started in distant mining regions, but
very quickly embraced other areas, posing a serious challenge to
the government.
	   The miners protested for not being paid for several months for
their coal, and blocked main railroads in Siberia and other parts
of Russia.
	   Nickolai, 26, a miner from the Kemerovo region in Western
Siberia, who happened to be in Moscow last Sunday, told me that he
and his friends blocked the vital Trans-Siberian Railroads with
huge logs, thus preventing the scheduled movement of more than 600
trains.
	   Miners in the Vorkuta region in the north blocked the rails and
held about 100 trains.
	   Miners protests were quite widespread in the southern Bostov
region and in other regions and, according to the Railways
Ministry, direct damage as a result of the strike was US$70 million
(RM273 million).
	   However, the problem was only ``damped down'', and the flame of
passion might restart any time in the near future.
	   According to the report of the Ministry of Economics, at the
beginning of last month, the overall wage arrears in 10 main
sectors of national economy were about US$10 billion, three per
cent more than the previous month.
	   The government's share of the arrears was about US$1.5 billion.
The government also acknowledged that unprofitable mines,
especially those in distant areas, should be closed, and new jobs
for the miners should be created (though this is easier said than
done).
	   It appears that such a situation posed a threat to political
stability in the country, and several high-ranking officials,
deputy prime-ministers Nemstov and Sysuyev among them, were sent
into mining regions in order to appease strikers.
	   They succeeded in this task - probably, because they acted not
with their words, but more with deeds, bringing to miners more than
US$47 million cash for immediate back payment of some of their
wages.
	   A government commission has been formed to look into the matter
and punish managers who have misappropriated wage funds.
	   Of course, it was not this partial payment of miners' wages that
dealt a heavy blow to the country's financial system. Anyway, it
took place almost immediately after the crisis over payment of
these wages ended.
	   According to some reports, it was the worst financial crisis in
years at the Russian financial market, with share prices plummeting
about 40 per cent last month and yields on government bonds soaring
to more than 90 per cent at their peak.
	   This turmoil increased concern about country's dwindling public
finances and made the central bank triple interest rates to 150 per
cent.
	   Besides, the central bank was reported spending about US$1.5
billion in several days, thus helping to keep the nominal value of
ruble (Russian national currency) steady at the level of about 6.18
per US dollar, before the crisis.
	   International Monetary Fund is widely expected to issue an
emergency stabilisation package, though Russian officials believe
that it could only help to remove uncertainty in the market.
	   As Vyugin, Russian deputy finance minister, put it, ``such a
credit would play only a psychological role, and stressed that the
market was rocked by a small circle of players.''
	   Meanwhile the central bank chairman Dubinin said that defence of
national currency remained a top priority.
	   The above and similar explanations are good as they managed to
calm the people down a bit.
	   At the same time the steps taken by the authorities in this
situation can be compared to actions of fireman during a fire. Of
course it is important to extinguish the fire, but perhaps, it is
even more important not to let it start again.
	   An old lady that lives not far from my house, Anna, who was
known for many years as a protector of pets (she feeds homeless
cats and dogs in the streets, and is always surrounded by them) I
am sure has never heard these explanations of top financial
officials.
	   When I last saw her, she was explaining to passers-by that she
had saved some 700 rubles (RM440), of her pension, and wanted to
get advice whether to change them into foreign currency or to keep
until the ruble was strong.
	   Naturally people refused or failed to give her any concrete
answer, and I remembered what Alexander Livshits, one of the top
economic advisers to President Yeltsin, had several days before
said about this current situation.
	   He pointed out that the main reason for the financial crisis was
the crisis of people's confidence in the authorities.
	   Dramatic, though, probably, a true explanation. At the moment
the financial crisis as well as that of the miners at least seems
under control, but the future still seems obscure.
	   Now it's the time for final exams in Russian schools, so, what
if school teachers, who also haven't seen their salaries for many
months, decide to postpone final examinations of thousands of
school graduates for an indefinite period?
	   I wonder whether Russian authorities remember that stormy events
in 1968 in France were started by very young people and for far
less vital reasons.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:RISING-CONCERN-FINANCES sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
