<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Sad Scots,0522 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Own goal thwarts big surprise as Scotland loses to Brazil
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ROBERT MILLWARD &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAINT-DENIS, France (AP) _ For 37 minutes, the kilts swirled and
Scottish voices were on song as Scotland was holding mighty Brazil
in the opening game of the World Cup.
	   Tommy Boyd's own goal under a spell of Brazilian pressure ended
all that.
	   Defending champion Brazil won the opening game 2-1 at the Stade
de France on Wednesday when Boyd, facing his own goal, accidentally
shouldered a rebound he couldn't avoid into the net in the 73rd
minute.
	   Brazil's Cafu got around the back of the Scottish defense and
prodded the ball goalward with goalkeeper Jim Leighton off his
line. Leighton blocked the shot, but the ball bounced off the chest
of Boyd and back into the net.
	   While Cafu ran away and did a celebratory somersault, the
Scottish players looked deflated.
	   ``Jim made a great save, but it hit me on the chest and I
couldn't get out of the way,'' said the 33-year-old Celtic
defender.
	   ``It was probably the worst feeling I have ever had to lose a
game like that.''
	   The Scots, who have never been past the first round in seven
previous World Cups, were given little hope of beating the
star-studded Brazilians. But it looked a strong possibility when
John Collins canceled out Cesar Sampaio's early goal.
	   After Sampaio had headed the Brazilians in front in the fourth
minute, he handed the Scots an equalizer by pushing Kevin Gallacher
in the penalty box. Although goalkeeper Taffarel dived the right
way, Collins, who plays in France for Monaco, expertly slotted the
penalty past him with a left-footed shot low into the corner.
	   It was no more than the Scots deserved. Threatened by the
embarrassment of a heavy loss in the opening game before 80,000
fans and a worldwide TV audience, they survived a battering in
which 39-year-old Leighton _ the oldest player in the championship
_ stopped shots from Roberto Carlos and Ronaldo.
	   Then the Scots, roared on by their noisy fans, silenced the
massed ranks of the Brazilian supporters by taking the game to the
mighty four-time champions.
	   They produced a short but productive spell of pressure to earn
an equalizer and scare Brazilian coach Mario Zagallo, who was
frequently out of his seat on the bench and shouting in despair at
his defenders and midfielders.
	   ``Can you the champions sing? No, no'' sang the Scottish fans as
the Brazilians showed more signs of cracking under the pressure.
	   The equalizer came eight minutes later and the first half wound
up even. Although Brazil turned up the pressure again, it was a
little ironic that Scotland had the last two touches to Boyd's own
goal.
	   ``I think the reaction of the Brazilian team on their winning
goal reflected the credit for Scotland,'' said Scottish coach Craig
Brown. ``They realized they were fortunate to win the game.
	   ``There's no denying that the better team won the game, but we
had a great chance not to lose.''
	   (rjm-jw)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-Sad Scots; CT:s; 
