<HEADLINE>
Dell targets personal workstation market, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Dell targets personal workstation market, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Wendy LeeASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   DELL Computer Corp, a direct marketer of computer systems, is
confident of making further inroads into the local and regional
personal workstation market space, which it claims present largely
untapped opportunities.
	   Dell's Precision Workstations' vice president Jeff Clarke said
the opportunities are driven by the rapid pace in the development
of software applications. ``Applications are really driving the
workstation market - that piece of software is what drives the need
for the hardware - and will continue to do so.''
	   ``Hence, we want to grow our enterprise sales which is
essentially in the area of servers and workstations. It's a matter
of how to tap and understand the markets and to make our presence
successful,'' he told Computimes.
	   Dell, Clarke said, is very much focused on such
application-driven workstation markets such as software
development, computer-aided design (CAD), financial and content
creation. As such, he added, Dell recognises that the Multimedia
Super Corridor (MSC) holds large opportunities for the company's
workstation business.
	   ``While we have yet to firm up any plans for the MSC, the
initiative is definitely within our radar and we believe we will be
able to leverage on the strong relationships we have with large
information technology (IT) multinational companies.''
	   Advancements in technology and lower costs, he added, have
caused the worldwide Windows NT-based workstation market to
``explode'', while the Unix-based workstation market ``stays
roughly flat''.
	   ``We see growth in three distinct areas: people who used to buy
PCs but can now buy personal workstations because they are more
affordable; those who are moving from the Unix environment to
Windows as Intel processors become more reduced instruction set
computing (RISC)-capable; and entirely new markets or users who can
now afford the workstations and have access to technology.''
	   He added that apart from the technological developments in the
Intel microprocessor, another factor that has led to the growth in
the personal workstation space is the Windows NT operating system
(OS) which has become more robust and a good platform to work on
within the enterprise.
	   ``Couple this with the fact that the application base has
migrated from being created solely for the Unix marketplace, to
also being available on the NT platform,'' Clarke said.
	   Dell, better known for its direct-selling of PCs, made its first
entry into the personal workstation market around August last year
with the release of its Workstation 400.
	   It recently introduced the Precision Workstation 410 which
houses a dual processor-capable system powered by Intel 350
megahertz and 400MHz Pentium II processors.
	   
</TEXT>
