<HEADLINE>
Woman: Used-car dealer cheated me of RM38,000, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Woman: Used-car dealer cheated me of RM38,000, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PENANG, Sun. - A 27-year-old housewife today claimed that she
was cheated of RM38,000 by a used-car dealer last year.
	   Tan Swooi Swooi said the dealer, known only as ``Ah Yu'', had
failed to sell a car for her.
	   ``I only found out about it after receiving a court summons for
failing to settle a car loan totalling RM46,000 from a finance
company last month.
	   ``I thought Ah Yu had settled the loan when he had sold the
car,'' she told a Press conference held by the State Gerakan public
complaints bureau yesterday.
	   She also showed copies of her police report to reporters. Also
present was the bureau chairman Looi Swee Cheang.
	   Meanwhile, Looi urged the police and Road Transport Department
to form a joint committee to check such cases.
	   He said they should devise stringent measures for the sale of
used cars to prevent cheating by unscrupulous dealers or agents.
	   At the same Press conference, factory manager Lau Chan On
claimed that a finance company in Air Itam had failed to make
deductions after receiving payments for his car loan for two
months.
	   He said he discovered this when the finance company wanted to
repossess his vehicle for non-payment.
	   ``The finance company later claimed that it was due to human
error,'' he added.
	   
</TEXT>
