<HEADLINE>
Taiwanese looking for business opportunities, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Taiwanese looking for business opportunities, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MUAR, Sun. - Malaysia's political stability, abundant natural
resources and low labour cost have prompted many large corporations
in Taiwan to seek investment opportunities here.
	   Health Minister Datuk Chua Jui Meng said he met a delegation of
Taiwanese industrialists in Kuala Lumpur on Thursday. They had come
to explore business ventures.
	   ``They were greatly impressed with our political stability,
racial harmony and unity despite the current economic slowdown.
	   ``The investors toured many Asean, African and Western
countries. But they chose Malaysia.''
	   Chua said the group also explored potential in the tourism
industry here and were impressed with what Malaysia had to offer.
	   Speaking at the opening of the Zhongtian Temple today, Chua said
the Taiwanese would make good their investments.
	   Earlier, he praised the temple committee for raising about
R400,000 to buy the three-storey building within a few months in
spite of the current economic situation.
	   Chua had made a personal donation of RM10,000 to help the temple
organise computer classes for children.
	   
</TEXT>
