<SLUG> BC-Jordan-Hamas Money </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hamas denies it was part of U.S. money laundering scheme
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ The Islamic militant group Hamas denied
Wednesday that it had any connection to an alleged money laundering
scheme in the United States that aimed to fund Muslim radicals.
	   U.S. authorities seized some dlrs 1.4 million in cash and
property near Chicago that allegedly was part of a money-laundering
plot which provided cash to operatives in Israel and the
Palestinian areas.
	   ``Hamas and I have no knowledge or connection whatsoever to the
money which was seized in the United States,'' said Mousa Abu
Marzook, a political strategist for Hamas.
	   ``Political motives are behind such allegations because the
Zionist lobby is pressuring American authorities to terrorize the
Palestinians and hush all political activists in the United
States,'' he said.
	   The FBI affidavit contends that Mohammed Salah, an
Arab-American, received funds from U.S. accounts controlled by Abu
Marzook, who was extradited to Jordan in 1997 following
imprisonment in the United States for violating immigration laws.
	   Abu Marzook denied that he had channeled hundred of thousands of
dollars to Salah from his U.S. bank account.
	   `These are baseless allegations,'' he said.
	   Mohammed Nazzal, Hamas representative in Jordan, said the money
seized in the United States is ``an astronomical number which
exaggerates the financial capabilities of Hamas.''
