<HEADLINE>
Twinning scholars face uncertainty, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Twinning scholars face uncertainty, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   R.B.IASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MY daughter was accepted into one of the teachers' training
colleges on a B.Ed (TESL) twinning programme which involves
spending two years out of a six-year course in United Kingdom.
	   However, due to the economic downturn she and her friends have
been informed that they will not be going to UK to continue with
their course.
	   My daughter was very disappointed by this news but what made her
more upset was the thought of staying on in her college for the
rest of her course.
	   During a meeting with the college authorities, my daughter and
her coursemates were not able to get any definite answers to their
questions.
	   No one could tell them when they had to return for the next
academic term.
	   They were also not told what curriculum they will be studying.
	   I have high regard for local educational institutions. However,
having been to her college, I can say that it is not fit to be a
campus for a degree programme. The classrooms and other facilities
are worse than some secondary schools.
	   I rang the college many times but no one could confirm when my
daughter should return for her new term.
	   Firstly, I would like to know if she is still getting a UK
degree? If she is, is there any way of allowing her to go even for
six months to UK to experience the immersion of the English
language/culture?
	   Secondly, if she is not getting a UK degree could I then
withdraw her from her college and send her to UK on my own?
	   Will a penalty be imposed by the Education Ministry's
scholarship department? Could the scholarship department clarify
this situation as their offer letter promised my daughter a UK
degree.
	   My daughter and her course mates are totally demoralised. I
think the authorities should clarify the matter.
	   
</TEXT>
