<HEADLINE>
Medicine: Hospitals to limit supply to monthly, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Medicine: Hospitals to limit supply to monthly, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PENANG, Sun. - All Government hospitals and clinics in the State
have taken to dispensing a maximum of one-month supply of
medication to patients on long-term therapy to cut wastage and
costs.
	   State medical and health services director, Dr Shafie Ooyub
defended the move today, saying that it was not intended to
inconvenience the public.
	   ``Our main objective is to prevent wastage of medicine
particularly in the face of the economic downturn,'' he told the
New Straits Times.
	   He added that as any medicine kept too long would go to waste,
it was pointless to give patients excessive amounts.
	   ``If we continue giving out large quantities of medication like
three months supply for a patient, we would need to buy and keep
more stocks ourselves, and this would raise our costs.''
	   ``We have also come across patients who stop taking medication
given to them after a while, once the symptoms disappear.
	   ``Imagine the wastage if we were to have supplied him with three
month's supply medicine and he stops taking them after just a
month,'' he said.
	   He added that there were also patients who lost or misplaced
their medication and would return to the hospital after a while to
ask for fresh supplies.
	   
</TEXT>
