<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OAU Summit </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pan-African leaders search for role amid conflict, coups
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By GLENN McKENZIE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   OUAGADOUGOU, Burkina Faso (AP) _ Conceived as a renaissance of
African peace and prosperity, a pan-African heads of state summit
ended Wednesday in the shadow of deadly border fighting, an
attempted coup and political uncertainty in Nigeria.
	   The annual three-day summit of the 54-member Organization of
African Unity, billed by hosts Burkina Faso as a forum for change,
focused instead on averting upheaval on Africa's eastern and
western tips.
	   Measures introduced by the 29 African leaders in a short closing
ceremony in Burkina Faso's dusty capital included sending a peace
mission to conflict-torn Eritrea and Ethiopia, and verbal
condemnation of a rebel uprising in Guinea Bissau.
	   Leaders also pledged to dramatically transform the 34-year-old
pan-African body to prevent it from becoming irrelevant in the
modern age, said Burkina Faso President Blaise Campaore, the OAU's
new chairman.
	   He did not describe the restructuring plan except to say that
the OAU's conflict resolution wing would be strengthened.
	   Salim Salim, secretary general of the continent's largest
political body, conceded the OAU was powerless to prevent its
member states from waging war _ even in Ethiopia, where the OAU is
headquartered.
	   ``We have to be modest,'' Salim said. ``Just because we adopt
resolutions (sending a peace mission to Ethiopia and Eritrea)
doesn't mean the two countries will respect them. It is up to the
parties to end hostilities.''
	   Critics argue that the organization, formed to build alliances
during the height of Cold War tensions and apartheid oppression,
has lost its teeth in an era when friends are found _ and wars
waged _ along nationalist, ethnic and economic lines.
	   OAU leaders delayed responding to Monday's death of Nigeria's
Gen. Sani Abacha, who summarily jailed, killed and tortured
thousands in his own country but helped end oppression in
neighboring West African states.
	   The reason, according to some analysts, is that the Nigerian
dictator accomplished peacekeeping feats that the OAU lacked the
will to initiate or bankroll.
	   Under Abacha's leadership, a West African intervention force was
created to keep peace in Liberia and oust junta forces in
neighboring Sierra Leone, both measures the OAU could neither
afford or agree upon.
	   In the end, muted condolences were proffered by OAU secretary
general Salim to Abacha's family and the Nigerian people. Many
other state leaders remained silent.
	   ``The OAU owes a debt of gratitude to Abacha for solving
problems that they did not,'' said a Western diplomat, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
	   The pan-African grouping will remain a weak cousin to the
world's other regional bodies as long as it shirks from invoking
harsh measures on its own members, some critics say.
	   Despite threatened sanctions against non-paying member states,
the OAU is saddled with huge arrears equal to its own budget,
according to Salim, who did not give figures.
	   And there are other ironies. Republic of Congo President Denis
Sassou-Nguesso, a former Marxist dictator who overthrew the elected
government of Pascal Lissouba last May in a bloody civil war that
killed 10,000, represented the OAU leaders in issuing a plea for
peace Wednesday in Ethiopia, Eritrea and elsewhere in the
continent.
	   Just a year ago, the OAU condemned Sassou-Nguesso for
overthrowing a legitimate government.
	   (gam/bk)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-OAU Summit; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
