<HEADLINE>
Assemblyman out to revitalise Lubok Merbau, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Assemblyman out to revitalise Lubok Merbau, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HAVING good rapport with both the younger and older
constituents, two-term Lubok Merbau assemblyman Jamal Nasir Rasdi
is able to envision a better future for the people he represents.
	   At 39, he is still considered young in politics but his past and
present involvement in the local and national political arena makes
him a leader with vast experience and a rising star.
	   Being a youth leader, he has strong support from the younger
constituents. The older constituents also seem to approve this
father of four.
	   Apart from commitments to his family, Jamal Nasir always has
time to listen to the problems faced by his constituents. He sees
them at his service centre, located in Kuala Kangsar, his house in
Kampung Kroh Hulu, Padang Renggas and any other possible place.
	   Jamal Nasir has big plans for some 60,000 Lubok Merbau
constituents who are mostly involved in agriculture-related
activities.
	   Several co-operatives are setting up a consortium which will
play a pivotal role in economic activities within the constituency.
	   ``The co-operatives will pool their resources and work together
through the proposed consortium to improve the quality of life of
the people of Lubok Merbau,'' he said.
	   Another major task which Jamal Nasir has been working on is to
ensure the younger constituents are properly educated, up to the
highest possible levels.
	   ``My only hope is to see more young people pursue higher
education so that they are better prepared to face future
challenges,'' he said.
	   He foresees significant progress within the next 10 years for
the area though it is still underdeveloped now.
	   He said plans to open a four hectare site there for small and
medium industries are already taking shape.
	   The industrial estate which is expected to create 10,000 jobs
for the locals will be a catalyst for other development and spur
growth of Lubok Merbau as a new development centre.
	   There will also be more economic activities when the Grik-Kuala
Kangsar highway opens.
	   However, Jamal Nasir noted concerns about the effects of future
physical development on the people.
	   ``We are trying to balance it with human and spiritual
development by setting up a Sekolah Agama Rakyat in every village
to provide religious education,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
