<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 5th Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Albanians halt Pristina rallies amid apparent lull in fighting
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. RECASTS and UPDATES with Albanians ending daily protests
in Pristina, Albanian professors reported beaten, Serbian ruling
party's statement, Serbs bringing in fresh reinforcements in
Kosovo, edits throughout. &QL; 
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Organizers of a protest in this
Kosovo capital, in which some 20,000 Albanians took part Wednesday,
decided to stop their daily rallies amid an apparent lull in
fighting.
	   The protesters fervently chanted ``U-C-K,'' the Albanian
language acronym for the Kosovo Liberation Army _ a militant
organization fighting to wrest the southern province away from
Serbia _ and sang a popular Albanian song, praising their ethnic
leader Ibrahim Rugova.
	   Groups of protesters leaving the rally _ the 60th consecutive
demonstration _ got into a stone-throwing scuffle near the
university with Serbs. Police intervened and dispersed the
protesters. Organizers later said they would stop ``this form of
protest.
	   Also on Wednesday, police burst into a meeting of the
underground Albanian-only university in Pristina, beating 24
professors and one student who were there, the pro-Albanian Kosovo
Information Center said. Six professors were seriously injured.
	   More than 250 people have died in escalating clashes in Kosovo
between Yugoslav troops and ethnic Albanian militants that began in
early March.
	   No further violence was reported early Wednesday elsewhere in
the province, where ethnic Albanians outnumber Serbs 9-to-1.
Kosovo's restive Albanian majority seeks independence from Serbia,
which stripped its autonomy in 1989 and has since ruled the
province with a heavy military and police presence.
	   Political observers in Pristina said that Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic apparently has decided to somewhat ease the
situation in Kosovo in view of growing international resolve not to
let the fighting escalate into a new Balkan war.
	   A statement issued after Milosevic presided over a leadership
meeting of his ruling Socialist Party said that the party
``supports measures taken by the state bodies aimed at normalizing
the situation'' in Kosovo.
	   The party, as reported by the state news agency Tanjug, also
stressed the need for ``organized efforts to decrease tensions and
take measures that would restore confidence between members of
different ethnic communities in Kosovo.'' But it warned that
``terrorists'' would be ``decisively'' confronted.
	   Meanwhile, the Kosovo information Center said government forces
had brought in reinforcements in southwestern Kosovo, near the town
of Djakovica, where Albanians spotted ten buses with troops, seven
trucks and six armored vehicles.
	   The center also said a group of Kosovo Albanian parties appealed
to the U.N. Security Council, saying military actions by NATO are
``urgently needed'' in Kosovo because economic sanctions against
Serbia are not enough.
	   Chased by the fighting, thousands of Kosovo Albanian refugees
have trekked on perilous mountain paths into northern Albania.
	   Mans Nyberg, a U.N. refugee official, said Wednesday in Belgrade
the total refugee number in Albania was estimated at about 12,000.
	   An additional 10,000 were earlier reported to have fled to the
neighboring republic of Montenegro, which together with Serbia
makes up Yugoslavia. Nyberg said the number of 5,200.
	   Nyberg said the number of Kosovo people displaced within the
province was estimated at 42,000. A Kosovo-based human rights
organization earlier put the total at 50,000.
	   But the refugee situation has become more complex, with some
2,000 Serbs and Montenegrins fleeing Kosovo to find shelter in
Montenegro and several hundred Gypsies, or Roma, were said to have
fled Kosovo to central Serbia due to threats from ethnic Albanians
who consider them loyal to the Serbian government.
	   Meanwhile, Rugopva, the moderate Albanian leader, went to Paris
and London to attend meetings of the Contact Group nations, which
monitor developments in the former Yugoslavia, and seek help for
his people.
	   (pvs/ms/rp) 	   
</TEXT>
