<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Gerry Weber Open, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Korda beaten, Krajicek advances at Gerry Weber Open
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: ADDS Korda QUOTES about his sickness &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   HALLE, Germany (AP) _ Top-seeded Petr Korda was upset in
straight sets Wednesday at the Gerry Weber Open, while Richard
Krajicek sailed into the quarterfinals behind his big serve.
	   Paul Haarhuis of the Netherlands beat the Czech player, still
slowed by a flu, 6-3, 7-6 (7-4), 6-4 at the dlrs 875,000 grass
tuneup for Wimbledon.
	   Krajicek, the 1996 Wimbledon champion and No. 3 seed, downed
German Davis Cup player Tommy Haas, 3-6, 6-4, 6-1 in just one hour,
27 minutes.
	   Korda said the weakness he still felt from his sickness, where
he was bed-ridden, drained his confidence heading into Wimbledon on
June 22.
	   ``I lack confidence in my body. It's going to take time to come
back to a high level,'' said Korda, the world's third-ranked
player.
	   ``But what could I do against Haarhuis _ everything he did
turned to gold,'' added the visibly disappointed Korda.
	   Last year, Korda started his comeback from a long groin injury
by reaching the event's final. Afterwards he pushed Pete Sampras to
five sets in a fourth-round Wimbledon match, then swept the title
at this year's Australian Open.
	   Haas, a 20-year-old German Davis Cup player, lost control of the
match against Krajicek after he twice failed to break the Dutch
player's serve in the second set.
	   After that he was worn down by the punishing serve of Krajicek,
who blasted 987 aces last year, and his greater experience on
grass.
	   The event has five top 10 players, with French Open champion
Carlos Moya of Spain and defending champion Yevgeny Kafelnikov of
Russia scheduled to play Thursday.
	   Italy's Gianluca Pozzi also beat Australia's Richard Fromberg,
6-1, 7-6 (7-1) and Sweden's Magnus Larsson routed Scott Campbell of
the United States, 6-0, 6-3.
	    &UR; (rk) 	   
</TEXT>
