<SLUG> BC-Swiss Banks-Nazis,0559 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede BERN, Switzerland
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Report: Nazi sympathizers flourished in Switzerland &QL; 
 &UR; By RAYNER PIKE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ A report picturing Switzerland as a place where
anti-Semites and Nazi sympathizers enjoyed strength and influence
during most of World War II was issued Wednesday by the Simon
Wiesenthal Center.
	   The 128-page report, based on material from Swiss archives,
concluded that probably no other country in Europe had a larger
proportion of right-wing extremists than the neutral nation of 4
million.
	   It was formally released at a news conference in New York
Wednesday.
	   The report, ``Survey of Nazi and Pro-Nazi Groups in Switzerland,
1930-1945,'' said the most damning document showed Switzerland's
justice minister, Eduard von Steiger, promising an anti-Semitic
organization at the height of World War II that Swiss borders would
be sealed more tightly against Jews.
	   Von Steiger also told the head of the Swiss Fatherland
Association that he would hold in confidence the association's
recommendation against increasing Jewish influence in Switzerland,
according to a memorandum of a meeting on Oct. 17, 1942, the report
said.
	   ``We intend to reduce fundamentally'' the flow of Jewish
refugees, the report quotes von Steiger as saying.
	   The Swiss maintained they were restricting the flow of refugees
from Nazi-controlled neighboring countries on political and
economic grounds.
	   Even so, the tiny country gave shelter to 27,000 Jewish refugees
during the war, more than the United States, the Swiss government
said in a rebuttal issued through its consulate.
	   Rolf Bloch, head of the Swiss Confederation of Hebrew
Congregations, said in Bern that Switzerland's treatment of some
Jewish refugees was ``a dark chapter,'' but added that the report
appeared to be ``one-sided and exaggerated.''
	   Thomas Borer, head of the Swiss task force reexamining the
country's past, called the report ``absurd and wrong.''
	   Rabbi Marvin Hier, the dean of the Los Angeles-based Wiesenthal
Center, said, ``This is not about the Swiss people, nor is it about
the Swiss government of today. It's about righting a wrong, it's
about making public documents that have for too long remained
dormant.''
	   Hier also promised more such reports targeting other
governments.
	   ``Switzerland is not the only country with a problem of hanging
on to documents,'' he said, ``Everyone knows the Vatican has that
problem, the French have it, the United States has problems with
archives that we can't get a hold of, that are secret after 50
years.''
	   The report's author, historian Alan Morris Schom, said ``a clear
pattern of hatred of Jews'' was evidenced in Switzerland during the
Hitler era, with numerous references to ``stinking Jews'' and ``pig
Jews'' appearing in print.
	   Last January, the center, named after the famed Nazi hunter,
released another report by Schom accusing the Swiss of running
camps where Jewish refugees were used as slave labor and told they
would be handed over to Germany's Gestapo if they complained.
	   Switzerland conceded that some camp commanders had treated
refugees badly, but prominent Swiss Jews and a number of Jews who
lived in the camps said by and large Switzerland was a safe haven
for many on a hostile continent.
</TEXT>
