<HEADLINE>
Seasoned politician an inspiration to upcoming leaders, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Seasoned politician an inspiration to upcoming leaders, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   TALHA ISMAIL is very much a seasoned politician. With more than
30 years in politics, this former headmaster is an inspiration for
young and upcoming politicians.
	   Being a full-time politician, Talha, 62, always makes himself
available to his constituents of 16,000.
	   If he has no other appointment outside Lenggong, his daily
routine will be a trip to the Chenderoh Umno division office in
Lenggong town, a short distance away from his house in Kampung
Gelok.
	   There village headmen, community leaders and the other kampung
folk will come to seek assistance and advice from this two- term
assemblyman.
	   At times, informal meetings take place at a Thai food restaurant
located on the ground floor of the Umno office. The restaurant is
another favourite place where the constituents meet their
representative.
	   Talha said in general, he was satisfied with the development
that had taken place in his constituency.
	   All households in Lenggong have electricity and clean water
supply while roads, health and other social facilities are of
comfortable standards.
	   ``There are however a few sectors which can be further promoted
like tourism, considering Lenggong has been blessed with a
colourful historical past and endowed with natural beauty.
	   ``The discovery of the `Perak Man', pre-historic discoveries,
the Chenderoh and smaller lakes as well as beautiful limestone
hills, are all potential tourist attractions,'' he said. A 3.2ha
site has been allocated for an archaeological museum at Kota
Tampan.
	   Talha would like to have a secondary religious school in the
area, a vital facility, he said, considering the increasing number
of parents who want to see their children pursuing higher religious
education.
	   
</TEXT>
