w1663 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  CHENDEROH-MP'S-PRIORITYs     06-10 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> CHENDEROH-MP'S-PRIORITY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chenderoh MP's priority `to serve', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Chenderoh MP's priority `to serve', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Zakiah Koya; Zubaidah Abu BakarASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ``I want to serve the people and that is my priority as wakil
rakyat,''
	   insists Chenderoh MP Datuk Mohamed Nazri Abdul Aziz, who says
that he tries as much as possible to spend most of his time in his
constituency.
	   Nazri adds: ``I enjoy being wakil rakyat.
	   ``I usually spend Thursday nights in my constituency. I get to
meet many of my constituents during Friday prayers.''
	   The conscientious MP says that he stays on ministering to his
constituents until Sunday night after which he leaves for Kuala
Lumpur where his home is.
	   On whether he thinks he is doing a good job, Nazri replies, ``I
would say that my success rate in accepting invitations to visit my
constituents is 100 per cent.''
	   ``I don't reject any invitation from my constituents,'' he adds,
stating that if he had to make a choice between a programme in KL
``where I am not the main guest'' and an invitation in Chenderoh
``where I am the main guest,'' he would choose Chenderoh.
	   ``In the kampungs, I become the main star,'' says Nazri, who
obviously enjoys the attention he gets as a wakil rakyat in his
rural constituency which lies on the fringes of the two districts
of Kuala Kangsar and Hulu Perak.
	   ``It is not difficult to be the wakil rakyat there. They will
not bother you unless it is truly necessary,'' says Nazri,
contradicting the popular perception of the ``kampung style''
people's representative on call every hour of the day.
	   ``It is mostly bread and butter issues,'' says Nazri, who is
also Deputy Minister in the Prime Minister's department. He says
that the rakyat also approach him when they need assistance for
scholarships and endorsements in relation to their children's
education.
	   ``Then of course they also ask for the basic infrastructures
like roads.''
	   Nazri maintains that it is easy to satisfy his voters.
	   ``I find it easy to perform my duties as the people are
well-mannered and there is so much respect for leaders.
	   ``I don't wear a suit or tie when I am there. I sit with them
and I wear a sarong and T-shirt and crack a few jokes. It helps
break the ice and I find that they are all comfortable with me,''
says Nazri, who adds that due to the fact that the people of
Chenderoh are mainly involved in agricultural activities, they have
accepted that the place will never be as developed as Ipoh or Kuala
Lumpur.
	   ``But that does not mean that I do not look into its
development,'' says Nazri.
	   ``When I was the Mara chairman in 1995, I decided that one of
the new Maktab Rendah Sains Mara should be built in Chenderoh. I
could afford to do this then as I was not the MP at that time.''
	   Nazri says that the project has been delayed due to the economic
downturn but ``it has not been shelved.''
	   ``Once the MRSM comes up, the whole place will be opened up as
there will be outsiders moving in as teachers and students. The
locals will have business opportunities,'' says Nazri.
	   ``The main problem in the schools there is the lack of English
teachers,''
	   Nazri says, explaining that it is difficult to get English
teachers to be posted to Chenderoh as many perceive it as being
very rural.
	   Nazri adds that the schools also lack facilities such as
computers and a big chunk of his allocation goes to buying
computers for schools.
	   On infrastructure such as roads, Nazri says that he has managed
to get them built as ``I hold a high post and I have friends up
there in the respective ministries.
	   ``Furthermore, top ministers are wakil rakyat of the
constituencies bordering Chenderoh and this helps.''
	   Nazri also plans to encourage the people to venture into the
tourism industry.
	   ``It is a beautiful place with a beautiful lake,'' says the
wakil rakyat of the scenic Tasik Raban.
	   ``But we have to `jaga' the sensitivities of the people,'' says
Nazri, who believes ``politics is about people liking you.''
	   ``I am lucky the assemblymen in my constituency are experienced
politicians and we have a close working relationship,'' he says.
	   ``At present, I am happy being an MP in Chenderoh and I enjoy
doing what I am doing,'' he says, adding that to him it is
important to have ``personal satisfaction.''
	   The interview was conducted in the comfort of the Deputy
Minister's office. That day also happened to be his birthday. But
Nazri fidgeted a lot and seemed uncomfortable throughout the
interview.
	   It seemed to give credence to what those who know him say: that
he is uncomfortable being in the public eye. Thus when he does make
an appearance, he is said to make it with a bang and then disappear
as he did when he was appointed to the post of acting Umno Youth
leader back in 1995 in the place of the former Malacca Chief
Minister Tan Sri Abdul Rahim Tamby Chik.
	   ``I try as much as possible not to get into the papers. I am not
a terribly ambitious person and I do not require much publicity,''
says Nazri, with the wide-eyed look of an innocent child.
	   ``To me, what is important is that I do a good job, be it as a
member of the Umno supreme council or as a wakil rakyat.
	   ``I prefer to do my job quietly and I do not believe in trying
to attract unnecessary attention.
	   ``For me, at the end of the day, it is always the voters who
decide the outcome.''
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
