<BODY>
<SLUG> COMPETITION-LIES-HEART sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Competition lies at the heart of all excellence, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Competition lies at the heart of all excellence, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Robin LimASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   WITH the recent upheaval concerning the Unit Pusat Universiti's
mistakes in the matter of entrance for both Sijil Pelajaran
Malaysia and Sijil Tinggi Persekolahan Malaysia students, one can't
help but wonder how an important body like UPU functions. And, more
importantly, why did it do such things?
	   For example, last year, forms for university applications were
sold at post offices. First of all, not all places have post
offices, and then only main post offices were in charge of the
sales.
	   The obvious problem at that time was that people all over had
rushed to the post offices to buy the forms. We all remember that
mess. Not the least of the problem is black market sale of the
forms.
	   Coming back to this year, a minister explained that the mix-up,
delayed reports etc, were due to wrongly filled OMR forms. And not
just a few but almost half of them. Is that possible?
	   You are not dealing with a bunch of primary school children
here, these are SPM and STPM students who intend to go to
universities. So, are Malaysian schools producing students who
can't even fill an application form? Of course not! The obvious
reason is that someone made a mistake and the ministry is trying to
cover it up. This is not the way to improvement. If there is a
problem, admit it! Take responsibility and improve on it.
	   With the UPU assessing and assigning students/applicants to
various universities, each institution of higher learning has a
fair share of ``better'' students and ``average'' students. This
may seem the fair thing to do at the moment.
	   What is the point of every university being exactly the same as
the rest? In the long run everyone is pulled down. The smart ones
will become average and the teachers/lecturers/administrators will
not work hard because if they do, the slower ones will not be able
to catch up.
	   If they don't, the bright ones will score but they will never
excel and push their potential to the maximum.
	   It is a rather cold but real fact that the smart ones need to be
with others of the same intellectual level to really excel. They
need the competition.
	   If raw diamonds aren't polished with diamond dust they will
never shine.
	   The better universities always take in the best students and the
teaching staff are constantly improving themselves in order to
teach these bright students.
	   Other universities won't be left behind in the long run. They
need a model to look up to. They will constantly try to be on par
with that model university.
	   We are always trying to copy renowned overseas universities, we
should have one for our own local universities. This will enable
all our universities to improve their standards.
	   Then we will be able to restore the glorious days when our
universities were recognised even in countries like Britain and
America.
	   We should understand that it is actually an injustice to the
genius of Malaysians that they are not being placed in a better
environment to develop their abilities.
	   A strong nation isn't built by making things easy for the young
generation. Young minds need to be trained. Only by ensuring that
the next generation are able to compete not among ourselves nor
weaker countries but with other stronger nations can we ensure the
survival of the country.
	   Remember that a diamond will not become a diamond if the coal
wasn't put through a journey of tremendous heat and pressure.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:COMPETITION-LIES-HEART sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
