<BODY>
<SLUG> NATIONAL-UNITY-IS-KEY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
National unity is key to racial, religious harmony, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
National unity is key to racial, religious harmony, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Lee Lam ThyeASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ON May 26, the National Unity Advisory panel met under the
chairmanship of National Unity and Social Development Minister
Datin Seri Paduka Zaleha Ismail following its re-organisation and
the appointment of additional members.
	   Appointed by Prime Minister Datuk Seri Dr Mahathir Mohamad, the
59- member panel consisted of secretaries-general of relevant
ministries, state secretaries, departmental heads, representatives
of volunteer organisations, corporate leaders, religious heads and
social activists.
	   Panel members were given a specific task to freely discuss all
issues concerning unity and to make recommendations to the
government on what needs to be done to tackle problems which impede
unity.
	   The panel's role is important considering one of its tasks is to
help the National Unity Department to formulate and implement
programmes to promote unity and resolve potential causes of racial
or religious conflict.
	   Malaysia has often been cited by many foreign visitors as an
example of how a nation of diverse races and ethnic communities can
live in peace and harmony.
	   Yet, Malaysians must not take this unity for granted but instead
continuously work towards nurturing and reinforcing unity.
	   Even though we have been a tolerant and accomodating society, it
is necessary for Malaysians of all races to always be sensitive to
issues or disputes which can lead to unrest.
	   The Hindu temple-mosque dispute in Kampung Rawa, Penang, has
proven how fragile religious and racial harmony can be if problems
pertaining to places of worship are not handled properly.
	   Not only must the followers of the respective religious faiths
be respectful and sensitive to one another, even civil servants and
those in authority including the law enforcers must be sensitive to
the needs and wants of the community so as to ensure actions taken
will not give rise to racial conflict.
	   As pointed out by the Yang di-Pertua Negeri of Penang, Tun Dr
Haji Hamdan Sheikh Tahir, the Kampung Rawa incident should serve as
a reminder so that everyone should be careful, tolerant and
sensitive to the feelings of other communities.
	   It is imperative that Malaysians of all races work for racial
harmony and enhance efforts to promote understanding and unity
which is vital for economic recovery and nation-building.
	   Unity which involves the fostering of shared values and a shared
destiny with a feeling of a common identity is a fundamental
prerequisite for the realisation of Vision 2020.
	   We must therefore ensure that there is unity between the
communities, unity between labour and management, unity between
business and government and above all unity between the political
parties and within the national leadership.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
