<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Drug Board,0368 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. Drug Board member resigns, conflict of interest a concern
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With UN-Drug Summit &QL; 
 &UR; By NICOLE WINFIELD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Colombia's federal prosecutor has resigned
from the U.N. board that combats narcotics trafficking following
concerns of a possible conflict of interest.
	   Alfonso Gomez Mendez, who once defended a former foreign
minister implicated in Colombia's biggest drug scandal, stepped
down last month, said the president of the International Narcotics
Control Board, Hamid Ghodse of Britain.
	   Ghodse said the decision was made because Gomez ``has an
extremely tight work schedule and therefore he didn't think that he
can serve the board adequately when he has so much commitment
nationally.''
	   The U.N. legal office, however, believed Gomez's service as
federal prosecutor might impair his impartiality. The 1961 treaty
that established the board states that members should not hold
other jobs that might impair their impartiality.
	   After joining the board in 1997, Gomez was appointed Colombia's
federal prosecutor, replacing Alfonso Valdivieso, an
anti-corruption crusader whose investigations nearly toppled
President Ernesto Samper.
	   In a May interview with the Radionet network in Colombia, Gomez
denied that his defense of former Foreign Minister Rodrigo Pardo
was a factor in any possible conflict of interest. He said he was
considering quitting the board, but for other reasons.
	   Ghodse said the drug board last week asked member countries to
submit their nominations for a successor to fill Gomez' term, which
runs through 2002.
	   A choice was expected by February. A Colombian or a
representative from the region would be the natural choice, said
Herbert Schaerpe, secretary of the Vienna-based board, who joined
Ghodse at a news conference during the U.N. General Assembly
special session on drugs.
	   The narcotics board is one of the least known but most powerful
U.N. organizations. It works with governments to determine what
drugs should be declared illegal.
	   It also helps regulate ``precursors'' _ chemicals that are not
banned but can be used to manufacture illicit drugs.
</TEXT>
