<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup-Jamaica, 1st Ld-Writethru,0370 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Jamaicans confident and relaxed during training
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: CORRECTS identification of Simoes as head coach, Brown as
assistant &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   CHAUMONT, France (AP) _ The Jamaican team was settling into its
camp Wednesday after getting a keen reception by local children
during its first organized stroll though this northern town.
	   School children who were released from classes Tuesday in this
town of 8,000 asked for autographs from everyone from striker
Walter Boyd and head coach Rene Simoes to the dietitian and the
press officer.
	   The Reggae Boyz were holding nighttime practices Wednesday and
Thursday to simulate the 9 p.m. local time start of their opening
Group H game Sunday against Croatia in Lens.
	   The team looked nothing like the World Cup rookies they are as
they trained Tuesday night at the Georges Dobin Stadium.
	   After slick skills work, under the watchful eye of assistant
coach Carl Brown, Jamaica rounded off the two-hour session with
shooting and penalty drills in front of a crowd of 700 locals.
	   Boyd, who is still fighting hard to regain fitness after an
extended absence from the squad, appeared sharp and keen, as did
fellow striker Marcus Gayle, who is pressuring the out-of-sorts
Deon Burton for a starting role up front Sunday.
	   Coach Carl Brown said the team was relaxed and, despite a ``few
niggling'' injury problems, ready to make its historic World Cup
debut.
	   ``They have been working extremely hard and well and they are
all in a positive state of mind,'' said Brown. ``I am sure they
will give a good account of themselves on Sunday against a very
tough team.''
	   Missing from the drills were key central defender Linval Dixon,
and defenders Frank Sinclair and Steve Malcom.
	   Dixon will miss Sunday's encounter because of a knee injury but
claims he will be available for the team's second match against
World Cup giants Argentina in Paris on June 21.
	   Sinclair is still feeling the effects of a groin injury, while
Malcolm felt soreness in one of his feet after a team meeting
Monday night and was rested from Tuesday's two sessions.
	   (str/sab/mc/jw)
</TEXT>
