<HEADLINE>
Subang Jaya council needs a good deal of shaking up, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Subang Jaya council needs a good deal of shaking up, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   S. FadzliASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   RECENTLY I read a few complaints about the Subang Jaya Municipal
Council in our local newspapers. The most recent was the one
published in the Malay Mail with the heading, ``Unfair fines, cry
SJ ratepayers''.
	   Well, being a USJ resident for the past three years has indeed
made me realise that the town council really needs a lot of
``shaping-up''.
	   The complainant was right in saying they shouldn't be compounded
for failing to pay the assessment. Although the notice I received
is dated March 18, the postmark showed May 15.
	   The Public Relations Officer of MPSJ said Datapos should be
blamed as ``she did not realise that they sent the notices late''.
This clearly reflects that the PRO does not even know such things
are going on.
	   The second issue I wish to raise is the MPSJ payment collection
system.
	   Many of my colleagues and I have noticed that if you pay by
cheque, the amount is not debited in a week, or even a month, but
only six months later.
	   This results in bounced cheques because we no longer have
maintained our accounts because rationally, one would think that
the amount should have already been cleared.
	   Thirdly, try calling their 1-800-885235 (the 731-1616 is even
worse) and one would be passed around like a ball, because no one
wants to take responsibility. They shove you away before you can
even voice your complaint.
	   And finally in our current water crisis, the council should be
more helpful in giving us information. When asked questions on the
topic, they simply decline or refuse to speak.
	   We went to the extent of calling Sime UEP and we were fortunate
enough to get some information from them and telephone numbers of
the Selangor Waterworks Department and Subang Jaya State
Assemblyman Lee Hwa Beng's office. They were more accommodating
when answering our questions. And how did they achieve this? By
reading local newspapers. This is what the council personnel lack.
	   My friends and I have called (and still call) MPSJ to ask for
information regarding various issues. The council either declines
or redirects us nowhere. Sometimes we have no choice but to call
Lee Hwa Beng's office or even Sime UEP, because we do not know
where else to turn.
	   
</TEXT>
