<SLUG> MALAYSIA-ECONOMY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Malaysia is 17th most competitive economy, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Malaysia is 17th most competitive economy, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   P. Selvarani in LondonASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MALAYSIA has been ranked 17th among the world's most competitive
economies, a drop from its previous ninth placing, the World
Economic Forum's Global Competitiveness Report 1998 said.
	   Singapore topped the table followed by Hong Kong and the United
States.
	   Thailand is down to 21, from 18th placing, and Indonesia has
fallen 16 places down to 31st placing.
	   The other 10 most competitive economies were the United Kingdom,
Canada, Taiwan, the Netherlands, Switzerland, Norway and Luxemburg.
	   Competitive countries are those that have the highest capacity
for medium-term economic growth, taking into account their starting
level of income.
	   The competitive index is based on several factors including
openness, government finance, infrastructure, technology,
management, labour and institutions.
	   According to Jeffrey Sachs, director of the Harvard Institute
for International Development, and co-chairman of the Advisory
Board of the Global Competitiveness Report, the rankings define
which countries have a range of markets and factors of production,
and other characteristics which give them the capacity to achieve
sustained economic growth.
	   He said a healthy market economy was an indispensable condition
of competitiveness, with private sector-led growth, rule of law and
well- functioning markets as keys.
	   ``In 1997, East Asian countries received high scores for small
government, high savings rates, low labour costs and flexible
labour markets ... export-led growth.
	   ``They received low scores for institutions. There is basically
no reason to look at that and see economic collapse.
	   ``In fact, what is happening in the markets is a blow-up that is
vastly more extreme than the situation merits.''
	   The report described Singapore and Hong Kong as ``well-run''
countries, adding that as both provide financial and other services
to their neighbours, it is natural that they would suffer somewhat
when their neighbours suffer.
	   ``Our data however, continues to indicate that conditions for
medium-term growth - over a five to 10-year period - is good in
both economies.
	   ``Both economies continue to be organised around open trade and
finance, small government, superb infrastructure, rigorous
enforcement of commercial contracts and low levels of corruption.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:MALAYSIA-ECONOMY sked; CT:w; 
