<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Queens </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rain halts play at Queens
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP)_ Australia's Patrick Rafter was in the middle of a
fightback against compatriot Scott Draper at Queen's, when the rain
that has dogged the event halted play late Wednesday.
	   Less than 30 minutes of tennis was possible between rain
showers.
	   When organisers eventually called an end to play Draper, who
last year sent Michael Chang packing and has a winning head-to-head
record over the US Open champion, led 4-3.
	   Only one game was completed before the players were forced off
court initially, and when they returned it was Draper who
impressed.
	   While third seeded Rafter struggled with his serve, hitting six
double-faults in four service games, Draper struck some crisp
volleys, served steadily and made some good returns.
	   Draper's enterprise paid off when he broke to lead 2-1 as Rafter
failed to make a low volley.
	   Draper then held two break points leading 4-2 but Rafter held
his ground and when rain intervened he led 40-15 on Draper's serve.
	   No other play was possible, leaving players with the prospect of
playing two matches Thursday.
	   Due to the backlog of matches and public interest in second seed
Greg Rusedski and seventh seed Tim Henman, world number one Pete
Sampras will be relegated to a secondary court when - or if - play
gets underway Thursday.
	    &UR; (bw)
</TEXT>
