<SLUG> BC-UN-Singapore,0353 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With UN-Drug Summit
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Singapore says tough laws, executions have brought drug problem
under control &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT H. REID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Singapore defended its harsh drug
penalties, telling the U.N. drug conference that tough measures
which include mandatory execution had brought the drug problem
``very much under control.''
	   ``We take the drug problem seriously because our geographical
location puts us at constant risk of being used as a transshipment
point for drug trafficking,'' Home Minister Wong Kee Seng said.
	   ``Our stringent deterrent laws are well-known,'' Wong added.
``Drug offenders are treated with the same gravity, regardless of
whether they are Singaporean or foreign nationals.''
	   This month, Singapore's parliament imposed the death penalty for
trafficking in methamphetamine, and introduced corporal punishment
and long jail terms for repeat drug offenders.
	   The previous law dictated sentences of less than two years in
drug rehabilitation centers for repeat offenders. Singapore imposed
mandatory death by hanging in 1975 for drug trafficking.
	   But the government no longer makes public the number of people
hanged.
	   Under the new law, anyone convicted of dealing in more than 250
grams (8.75 ounces) of methamphetamine faces the gallows.
Traffickers in 167-250 grams (5.85-8.75 ounces) of amphetamines
face life in prison and 15 strokes of the cane.
	   Lesser amounts are punishable by up to 20 years in prison.
	   Wong said such policies were part of a longterm plan to ``create
a national consensus toward zero tolerance for drug abuse,'' which
he said was showing results.
	   Since 1994, he said, the number of persons arrested for drug use
had declined from 6,160 to 4,750 _ a 22 percent decline. The
relapse rate had dropped by 15 percent, he said, although he
acknowledged that two-thirds of those who underwent treatment
resumed drug use after their release.
	   Nevertheless, he said the figures were enough to show that ``the
drug situation in Singapore is very much under control.''
</TEXT>
