<SLUG> BC-Britain-Japan-Veterans </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WWII POWs seeking Japanese compensation meet with Blair
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Former prisoners of war who were held by the
Japanese during World War II met with Prime Minister Tony Blair on
Wednesday to press their campaign for compensation from Japan.
	   The issue returned to the news two weeks ago during the state
visit by Japan's Emperor Akihito. Veterans turned their backs on
him in protest when the emperor appeared in public.
	   The veterans said they were encouraged by Wednesday's meeting
with Blair and that the prime minister told them the government had
the political will to take up the issue with Japan again, if legal
opinion supported such action.
	   The government earlier had said it could not seek more
compensation because the matter was finalized in a 1951 treaty that
could not be reopened.
	   The veterans said two legal experts concluded that ``good
arguments can be made to support the view'' that the time-lapse
since the 1951 treaty ``would not be an insurmountable obstacle in
the present case,'' according to lawyer Martyn Day, who is
campaigning with the veterans.
	   ``As far as the legal issue is concerned, they (the government)
are prepared to review the position in the light of the legal
opinion we provided them,'' he said. ``They will come back to us
once they have had the chance to review it.
	   A spokesman for the prime minister said Blair wanted to do all
he could, but didn't want to make any promises he couldn't keep.
	   Government lawyers are studying the new legal opinion.
	   (acw)
</TEXT>
