<HEADLINE>
Quit Klinik to help smokers kick habit, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Quit Klinik to help smokers kick habit, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IPOH, Mon. - The Ipoh Hospital opened the country's first Quit
Klinik today to help smokers kick the habit.
	   The clinic provides counselling for smokers who find difficulty
in trying to quit smoking, and for those who have stopped smoking
but need help to prevent them from lighting up again.
	   Hospital director Dr Umar Said Amad, who opened the clinic, said
the move was one of the hospital's efforts to help discourage
smoking, especially among the younger generation.
	   He said despite anti-smoking campaigns launched by the
Government and other agencies, there were still many people,
especially youths, who take up smoking and who refused to quit.
	   Dr Umar said the number of young smokers increased tremendously
over the past few years.
	   ``For the first quarter of this year, there was a 30.7 per cent
increase in the number of habitual smokers aged below 18, compared
to 10 years ago.
	   ``Female smokers in the same age group increased by 14.4 per
cent compared to a decade ago,'' he said.
	   Dr Umar attributed the increase to the aggressive promotions
carried out by tobacco companies in recent years.
	   ``The tobacco companies spend millions of ringgit on cigarette
commercials and this has defeated the purpose of our awareness
programme,''
	   he said.
	   He also said 2,971 people were issued compounds during the
first-third of this year for smoking in public places. Of this, 402
were below 18 years old.
	   From today until Saturday, Quit Klinik will open from 8am to
4pm.
	   However, from next week, it will be opened once a week on
Thursdays from 9am to noon. Appointments can be made by calling
05-5222030 or 05-5222031.
	   
</TEXT>
