</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BRAKING-IN-THE-WET sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTO TALK: Braking in the Wet, NATION
</HEADLINE>
AUTO TALK: Braking in the Wet, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Last week we talked about maintaining brakes during the rainy
season. This week, we'll see why the car fails to stop, even though
you've hit the brakes.
	   First of all you must be aware how much the brake pedal sinks
every time you brake (which is simply the distance between the
brake pads and the discs). In other words, if the distance
increases, that means that the brake pads are wearing out. Another
way to check the brake pads, especially in cars with disc brakes,
is the amount of brake oil remaining in the cylinder in the engine.
The wearing out of the pads will result in the oil filling that
space. So if there is little brake oil left, the pads are worn out
as much.
	   If you see the brake warning bulb light up on the dashboard,
even though the handbrake has been released, and the brake oil
level is lower than usual, it's likely that the brake pads have
been worn out and it's time to replace them.
	   Brake pads for drum brakes have a longer life, usually about
three times of those for discs. The reason is that drums have a
much larger contact area.
	   Oh, I almost forgot to mention this -- always remember that
brakes are not the only thing that stops the car. Imagine that you
are on a wet road and brake heavily. You can feel that the wheels
are locked, but the car just doesn't stop.
	   The purpose of the brakes is not to bring the car to a complete
halt, but to reduce the power from the engine and transmit the
force to the tyres. The tyres, in fact, are the last factor that
determines whether the car will stop. Therefore, it is very
valuable to know whether the stopping problem is caused by the
tyres or not.
	   Tyres with a particular type of tread pattern provide a short
braking distance even though the wheels are locked, but those with
large block patterns tend to take a longer distance depending on
the tread pattern and rubber compound. Those with larger blocks and
harder tyre composition, which is aimed at increasing tyre life,
will still slide more while braking whether on a wet or dry road.
	   In a nutshell, worn-out tyres provide for a poor braking
performance -- and can be dangerous.
	   Using the wrong tyre pressure, especially if it's too high, also
significantly reduces the braking performance of a car, even if the
brakes are in good condition. The problem is, that with too much
pressure there is less contact area between the tyres and the road,
thus less grip. So regularly checking the tyre pressure is helpful
in maintaining a good stopping distance, especially on wet and dry
roads, as well as on slippery surfaces such as sand-covered roads.
	   Braking problems are sometimes caused by things you might be
unaware of, such as the car carrying a too heavy load or not
distributing the weight properly around the car.
	   In hard times like these, many are forced to earn more income
and a popular trend now is selling things at car-boot sales on the
weekends. Some of us put pile things into the boot, whith could
total 200 to 300 kilogrammes, and that is bound to cause problems
since the front of the car is levered up resulting in poor handling
and braking distance.
	   That's why the driver should have a reasonable understanding
about the associated problems because some of them can be taken
care of easily and most of all, free of charge.
	   So remember, that if you are carrying extra weight, try to
distribute it around the car, such as on the front and rear
passenger seats, apart from the trunk.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BRAKING-IN-THE-WET sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
