<SLUG> TRAIN-INDUSTRIAL-WORKERS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japanese to train industrial workers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Japanese to train industrial workers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SUNGAI PETANI, Mon. - The Japanese Government will spend two
billion yen (about RM7 million) to train workers in the Southeast
Asian industrial sector this year.
	   The training programme aims to improve the skills of workers and
help to increase the ability of industries in Southeast Asia to
compete at the international level.
	   The manager of the Japanese Association for Overseas Technical
Scholarships (AOTS), Hidetaka Kawai, said the programme was also
established as part of the efforts to help Southeast Asian
countries facing economic problems.
	   ``We hope such training programmes will help to increase overall
productivity in local industries and boost exports from the
region,'' he said after launching an engineering course organised
by the AOTS.
	   The five-day course was organised in co-operation with
Sharp-Roxy Corporation (M) Sdn Bhd and the AOTS Alumni of Malaysia.
	   Hideki said the association would identify workers to be trained
in several areas of high technology. The trainees will undergo part
of their programme in a Southeast Asian country and the rest in
Japan.
	   The AOTS was established in 1959 as a non-profit organisation
and trains about 1,000 workers in the industrial sector in Malaysia
annually.
	   
</TEXT>
