<BODY>
<SLUG> RIDING-OUT-A-STORM sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Riding out a storm, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Riding out a storm, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   KINGSLEY WIJAYASINHAASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Sometimes you have both the money and the desire to buy a new
car, but those available on the market and sold through
distributorships just don't appeal to you. You need something more
distinguished and something that comes with the latest
technologies. So where do you go? You go to a 'grey' market car
dealer.
	   But considering the exchange rate and the increase in import
duty for completely-built-up (CBU) vehicles to 80 per cent flat,
you wonder if the greys are still around.
	   Indeed, many independent car dealers have simply disappeared
since the economic turmoil really kicked in, and many have turned
themselves into appointed dealerships such as Benz Bangna, formerly
a grey market importer, but which has now become a Thon Buri
Automotive Assembly Plant (TAAP) Co appointed Mercedes-Benz dealer,
or Benz Inter Co Ltd, which has now joined as one of the Bangkok
dealers for the Ford Army.
	   Apart from the fiscal problems, another reason for the fall of
the grey importers is the fact that many do not have an after-sales
service facility.
	   ''To operate a car dealership business, you have to provide a
complete service to the customer,'' says Sompong Vittayarakrangsan,
managing director of SEC Group Co, a major grey market car importer
specialising in Japanese cars.
	   Sompong, who is just 30 years old, said that customers are
staying away from independent importers that do not provide
after-sales service.
	   ''Many importers have gone out of business because they just
sell the car to the customer and then forget about everything --
which is the wrong approach,'' he said.
	   SEC is quite serious about doing business, he says. Apart from a
reasonable stock of parts worth Bt40 million, the company also
provides a 24-hour hotline service to customers just like the big
car companies do.
	   ''We keep a large amount of spare parts because we have to cater
for our old customers who have purchased cars like the Toyota MR-2,
Supra or Celica from us. We might not import some of these cars
anymore, but we must be able to service them.'' Despite the auto
market dropping by as much as 75 per cent this year, SE has not
been affected that much. ''We forecast a drop of only 20 per cent
compared to a 75 per cent total market drop, because we deal with
the upper market where the customers still have purchasing power.
Even though the economy has dropped, our customers are the
well-to-do and have budgets for cars unlike the middle and lower
market segments.
	   He said that despite the fluctuating exchange rate and increased
import duties, the business is still making money. ''Japanese
imports are still able to cater to the buyers' needs, are as safe
as European counterparts and are easy to maintain.'' SEC started
business seven years ago when the Thai government liberalised the
automobile industry, and has sold over 2,600 imported cars. Last
year alone it sold 700 units worth Bt1.6 billion and despite the
current economic condition, plans to sell another 500 units worth
Bt1.4 billion this year.
	   ''After five months, we have already sold 250 units,'' Sompong
noted.
	   The company has also expanded from its Rama 9 head office, with
new showrooms in Bang Na, Chiang Mai and Rayong, and there is a
plan to open another showroom in the Sathorn area later this year.
''We see the importance of expanding to get closer to our
customers. For example, we decided to open the Bang Na branch
because 30 per cent of our customers are located in that area.
Chiang Mai and Rayong are tourist destinations with lots of
customers too.'' Among the current imports include the Toyota
Granvia multi-purpose vehicle (Bt2.55 million), Land Cruiser VX100
(Bt4.1 million) and the Toyota Harrier off-roader (Bt3.1 million).
Other brands and models could also be imported upon request.
	   
</TEXT>
