<SLUG> BC-Azerbaijan-Oil </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Azerbaijan may seek international arbitration in oil deal
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BAKU, Azerbaijan (AP) _ The government of Azerbaijan may seek
international arbitration in the dispute between its state-run oil
company and an international consortium over a pipeline for early
Caspian Sea oil.
	   The pipeline will cost dlrs 591 million, which is dlrs 276
million more than the international consortium estimated, the
deputy chief of the oil company said.
	   The consortium insists that Azerbaijan make up the difference
through its share of oil sales. Azerbaijan says it will not
compensate the consortium for its mistake.
	   Azerbaijan also believes the dlrs 591 price tag is too high,
said the oil company official, Ilkham Aliev, who is also a son of
Azerbaijani President Geidar Aliev.
	   The pipeline would run from Baku, the Azerbaijani capital on the
Caspian, to Supsa, a Georgian port on the Black Sea. It is expected
to carry 5 million tons (33.5 million barrels) a year.
	   The route for the main export pipeline has yet to be determined,
but Azerbaijan has indicated it favors a Turkish proposal over
those put forward by Russia, Georgia and Ukraine.
	   Ilkham Aliev suggested Wednesday that if Azerbaijan and the
consortium failed to come to terms in three months, the government
would have to turn to international arbitration.
	   The consortium is made up of 11 oil companies from seven
countries _ including American firms Amoco, Exxon, Pennzoil and
Unocal.
	   Azerbaijan's Caspian Sea reserves are believed to be the world's
richest after the Middle East.
	   (ls) 	   
</TEXT>
