<BODY>
<SLUG> PROVIDING-THE-EXTRAS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Providing The Extras, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Providing The Extras, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Volvo V70 XT's added features does provide a dash of style
to their earlier wagons and gives you the worth for the extra money
you pay, reports Kingsley Wijayasinha.
	   The Volvo V70 XT might not classify as an off-roader or even a
sports utility, but this turbocharged wagon definitely does provide
that extra touch of freedom while retaining the famous practicality
of Volvo wagons.
	   The initials ''XT'' stand for cross-terrain, which does explain
the concept of the car. Based on the standard V70 2.3T model, the
XT come with several extra features ranging from a heightened
suspension, new bumpers to roof racks and coolers.
	   But don't mistake the V70 XT for the V70 XC that was introduced
last year. The big difference is that the latter comes with an
automatic all-wheel-drive system (AWD) and traction control that
makes it much more versatile under rugged conditions. But that's
going to cost a lot, and would seem inappropriate, especially in a
time when the market is slowing and sales are down.
	   Retail price for the V70 XT is Bt2.389 million, but V70 owners
can get their standard wagons fitted with the same features. That's
if they happen to have a spare Bt250,000 to hand.
	   The front and rear bumpers, with fibre lining that goes all the
way to wrap the entire body, are larger and gives a bolder, tougher
appearance to the car while the ''XT'' and ''Cross Terrain''
stickers on the rear doors and hatch distinguish it from standard
V70's. A fibre side skirt and rear spoiler with brake light gives
the finishing touch.
	   Other exterior differences are the new front air dam with
foglights and a new, meaner grille. Dual exhaust pipes add a sense
of sportiness to the rear while a heightened suspension with
16-inch mag wheels gives the car a robust look.
	   Since it is based on the standard V70, it comes with the same
engine -- a 20-valve five-cylinder 2.3-litre that is souped up with
a light-pressure turbo. The powerplant develops 190 brake
horsepower at 5,400rpm, which is almost 30bhp lower than the T-5
high-pressure turbo version, but the 270Nm (newton-metres) of
maximum torque could be produced right from just 1,800rpm and goes
all the way to 4,800rpm. This engine is flexible! The low-pressure
turbo and cross-terrain concept does go together well, since the
rich low-rev torque will show its benefit especially when going
uphill or on rugged surfaces -- the natural environments of the XT.
	   And thanks to the low-pressure turbo, the problem of turbo lag
has been successfully taken care of, the engine responding
instantly to throttle inputs. The XT performs well in stop-and-go
traffic, taking off with respectable acceleration, and provides
adequate pulling power for comfortable overtaking. The only area
that it might not stand out strongly is high-speed acceleration,
which appears to be just average.
	   However, there seems to be a high level of engine noise entering
the cabin, even at cruising speeds.
	   The four-speed automatic gearbox shifts smoothly, and comes with
three driving modes -- sport, economy and winter. The buttons for
these programmes, which earlier used to cause some inconveniency
since they were located on the left of the gearshift lever, has
been moved to the centre and are now easier to select.
	   Despite possessing a similar chassis layout with the standard
version (front spring strut and rear multi-link), height has been
increased by 35 millimetres to tackle more demanding surfaces.
	   On normal highways, the suspension performs similarly to the
original, but the increased height results in more body roll than
usual. However, it also takes care of vibrations better, especially
sharp inputs from potholes and speed bumps. The extra height is
also advantageous in terms of mobility, especially when going
through floods.
	   Not counting the increased roll, handling is similar to the
standard version, with the solid steering feel accompanied by a
good level of understeer during heavy acceleration. Traction
control (Tracs), which could be found in the T-5 model and would
greatly suit the ''Cross Terrain'' concept as well as minimising
understeer, is not available.
	   The four-wheel-discs have ample stopping power and the
smooth-pulsing ABS starts to activate only in extreme braking
conditions. The brake pedal, however, is a bit firm and needs a
strong kick to get the message.
	   The rack-and-pinion power steering has a best-in-class turning
radius of only 5.1 metres, and has a rather good weight, although
if it was lighter at parking speeds it would be even better.
	   Both the reach and rake of the steering wheel could be adjusted,
and for safety reasons the steering column is collapsible during a
frontal collision.
	   The interior is highlighted by the two-tone steering wheel and
console, with wooden veneers adding the luxury.
	   Both front seats are powered, with three memory positions for
the driver seat, and there are manually-adjusted lumbar support
knobs for both.
	   Performance of the air-conditioner might not impress everyone,
but considering the interior volume of the wagon, it does justify
itself. But cost-cutting is seen again as the controls for the a/c
are all manually-operated rather than coming with automatic
temperature settings.
	   Apart from traction control, something that would benefit the
traveller, but is available only in the T-5, is the info switch
which displays data such as average fuel consumption, remaining
distance until fuel runs out, temperature, etc. Another
cost-cutting that is easily detected is the disappearance of the
vanity mirror on the driver side.
	   But major components like electric windows, mirrors (with
defroster) and central locks with remote are included, as well as a
top-notch sound system with both a three-disc (front unit) and
six-disc cd-changer (luggage compartment). It even comes with a
built-in Dolby Pro Logic surround processor that improves imaging
dramatically.
	   The master switches for the electric windows, located on the
driver armrest, have automatic function for the driver-side, but
are too firm and the automatic function doesn't work for closing.
	   Other standard features for the XT are aluminium side steps,
roll bar in the engine room, roof racks and 16-inch mags with
205/55 tyres.
	   Our demonstration car also came with the ''Lifestyle'' option
list that stresses the XT's concept further. A highlight is a
DC-powered cooler for both hot and cold drinks located in the
luggage compartment area and held in position by a safety belt.
Others are roof rack for bicycles, sun visors for the rear windows,
coin tray, luggage nets and extra reading lights for both front and
rear.
	   If you think the conventional Volvo wagon is already outstanding
in terms of practicality, the V70 XT goes a step further, although
with a price. The XT is still far from being a true ''Cross
Terrain'' without the AWD system, or at least some sort of traction
control, but it is still a good move by Volvo to stimulate the
market by introducing continuous improvements to its existing
products.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:PROVIDING-THE-EXTRAS sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
