w1742 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  THINK-ABOUT-POST-CHUANsk     06-10 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> THINK-ABOUT-POST-CHUAN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Let's think about post-Chuan era, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Let's think about post-Chuan era, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   SOPON ONKGARAASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Does the Democrat Party's economic team still exist? If it does,
the public is not quite sure whether the once much-hyped members
are team players. More disheartening is the fact that the Democrats
no longer boast about this selling point. This underlines the grave
economic situation the country is facing.
	   The names frequently mentioned today are either Deputy Prime
Minister Dr Supachai Panitchpakdi or Finance Minister Tarrin
Nimmanahaeminda, who have to endure persistent news that they still
don't see eye to eye with each other, and that the worst is yet to
come.
	   Already six months in office, Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai and
his team must have realised that their task of propping up the
economy proved far more daunting than expected and probably beyond
their capability, taking into account the pressure for them to
produce results before the public completely loses faith and
confidence in the government.
	   Should we presume that we are heading towards a worse condition
and that the chance to stop the economic tailspin is no more than
zero?
	   When the Democrats campaigned for votes in the previous
election, they lined up a list of candidates with impressive track
records. They represented the Who's Who of economic managers in
politics, unmatched by other parties. Even the Chat Pattana Party,
which also boasts its own economic team, had to step aside because
it was incomparable.
	   Those much-touted people have suddenly become quiet. There were
no comments from them on economic issues. It could be that they
allowed only Dr Supachai and Tarrin to speak for the government
while they were acting as back-room supporters. A problem is that
the public does not think that is what is actually going on.
	   Let's guess then. Do the Democrats feel increasingly uneasy over
the obvious failure to effect an economic turnaround, and that
disquiet would soon become nervousness and then alarm?
	   Of course, there must have been some worries among the Democrats
that they will not be able to sport a brave face when it's time for
them to ask the angry voters for continued support. They have to
produce a very nice explanation as to why they could not achieve
what they were expected to.
	   They are losing their grip; that's what the public perceives.
And this is not good at all. The Democrats can still think that
they remain the best now and the public does not have much choice
-- another alternative is the New Aspiration Party (NAP).
	   ''This government is still the best under present
circumstances,'' argue the people who shudder at the thought of
having Gen Chavalit Yongchaiyudh and his team back to govern. It
was enough somehow to prevent critics of the Chuan administration
from becoming harsher with their attacks.
	   The NAP just does not care. Its members are rejoicing when they
see the Democrats struggle hard to tame the economic turbulence --
and not yet showing any signs of success. They believe that it
would not take long before they would be on a par with the
Democrats if the government's economic rescue efforts flop.
	   They score more points somewhere else. The NAP heavyweights shed
crocodile tears for the poor, scoff at the urban rich and blame the
Democrats for a twisted irony that the two layers in society should
suffer simultaneously.
	   A disturbing question is: What do the Democrats intend to do
from now on until the election, amidst signs of falling popularity?
	   For the public: What should the people expect if the Democrats
finally fail to live up to their expectations? Will disappointment
turn into anger and outburst which can lead to unpredictable
consequences?
	   It might not be wrong for those who still believe that the
Democrats remain an acceptable choice as the coalition leader after
the next election. The Democrats have to see the light, no matter
how pain they feel, that their leader Chuan will not be a selling
point. A third term of premiership would be too much for him, and
for the country.
	   And Chuan should understand his limits, no matter how much
self-confidence he has. The fast-changing times are having effects
on him and the country needs a better replacement and certainly
that person must not be among the present party leaders.
	   Chavalit must be kidding if he still thinks that he deserves
another chance. Does he think ex-president Suharto would ever
forgive him for the collapse of his empire? Will Dr Mahathir
Mohamad want to see him in Kuala Lumpur if the Malaysian economy
manages to survive the currently growing adversity by that time?
	   The Democrats have to plan for the future. Of course, they are
doing exactly that, thus such advice is unwarranted. The hard task
is to find someone to succeed Chuan. The modest man from Trang
province must not be punished by taking the third term through an
election. Cabinet reshuffles excluded.
	   There has been idle talk that the party should woo, persuade,
cajole, plead, request, or beg Anand Panyarachun to take the party
leadership to ensure public support for the party and restore
public hope that continuity will stoke recovery.
	   If Anand agrees, of course, because he has been shunning
politics by being actively in politics all along. What he has been
doing right now is something like prime minister without portfolio,
anyway.
	   This arrangement, with Anand as the Democrat leader, can last a
few years, or even longer if he delivers, until another generation
takes over. That person could be Dr Supachai, Tarrin, or other
Democrats who believe that they are big enough for their britches.
	   This is a short-term solution for the Democrats, for long-term
economic results, with political reforms as a by-product which
eventually lays down a foundation for transparency, good governance
or whatever ideals we hope for, as frequently sought by Anand.
	   If the Democrats don't like this idea, it's not entirely
unexpected. It's not their fault either. They are just like that by
nature, and political heritage. But they should present a better
choice before the people truly realise that they are not that smart
after all.
	   
</TEXT>
