w1745 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  HUMAN-RIGHTS-DEFENDERSsk     06-10 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> HUMAN-RIGHTS-DEFENDERS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Honour our human-rights defenders, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Honour our human-rights defenders, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   KAVI CHONGKITTAVORNASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Thailand needs to give recognition to its human-rights defenders
of yesteryear and today as we commemorate the 50th anniversary of
the Universal Declaration of Human Rights. Otherwise this year-long
celebration would not help increase awareness on the important role
which human rights play in our society and everyday life.
	   Thailand was among the first 48 countries which signed and
ratified the declaration when it was adopted in 1948. According to
the declaration, everyone has the right to freedom of opinion and
expression and the right to peaceful assembly and association.
However, over the past five decades, Thailand has not been immune
to human-rights violations.
	   To celebrate this special event, the Thai government has set up
a national committee in March chaired by Justice Minister Suthas
Ngernmuen together with six sub-committees to work out plans for
the year-long commemoration. These activities include issuing a
special phone-card, conducting seminars, and reviewing laws related
to human rights. The initial plan calling for special commemorative
stamps has, however, been cancelled.
	   Judging from the planned programmes and activities, there seems
to be little substance in the commemoration. Besides, it reflects
the shallow thinking of Thai officials who are prone to believe
that the commemoration amounts to nothing more than a publicity
exercise.
	   The Thai people have yet to take the concept of human rights
seriously. Owing to the country's violent past, as reflected in the
events in October 1973 and 1976 as well as May 1992, the Thai
public usually associate the violation of human rights with armed
confrontation between those in uniform and civilians.
	   Certainly for the three decades between 1950 and 1980 when
communist ideology was considered a major threat to the country's
security and stability, very few people criticised the detentions
without trial, disappearances and extrajudicial killings as
violations of basic human rights. Thais in general believe that
there are no human-rights violations from rampant shootings by
errant law-enforcers. That explains why the demonstrations by
labour groups and non-governmental and grass-roots organisations
have not received much moral support from the public at large. Some
of these rallies are even labelled social nuisances.
	   The protection of human rights covers individual, civil,
political, and workers' rights as set forth in the declaration.
These rights include freedom from torture or other cruel, inhuman,
or degrading treatment or punishment. It also states that all
people have the inalienable right to change their government by
peaceful means and to enjoy basic freedoms without discrimination
on the basis of race, religion, national origin or sex.
	   Most importantly, as stipulated in the new Constitution adopted
last year, universal human rights aim to incorporate the respect
for human dignity into the processes of government and law. In this
respect Thailand still has a long way to go despite the existing
liberal-democratic atmosphere.
	   The country is a signatory to only a few of all 24 international
human-rights conventions. Thailand last year signed the Covenant of
Civil and Political rights after years of delay due to the
Parliament's bureaucratic red tapes and MPs' lack of understanding.
But Bangkok has yet to accede to Covenant of Economic, Social and
Cultural Rights.
	   To ensure that the commemoration would not be a wasteful
exercise, it is crucial that the Thai government give recognition
to some of our more prominent human-rights defenders. Without
knowing and learning of these people's dedication and sacrifices,
how can the public appreciate, let alone value and respect human
rights? In addition, to sustain and protect fundamental rights
there is a need for a new generation of human-rights fighters.
	   For instance, Thongbai Thongbao could be named one of the
country's foremost human-rights defenders along with Vitit
Muntarbhorn of Chulalongkorn University. Both of them have spent
most of their lives fighting against all forms of totalitarianism.
	   As a lawyer, Thongbai has defended hundred of cases of
human-rights violations in this country. As an educator, Vitit uses
his knowledge to raise awareness in Thailand and the whole region
of all aspects of human rights. At the same time there are also
labour-union and farmers' leaders who have sacrificed their lives
in defending those bodies' rights, many of them unknown and
unrecognised.
	   The UN Human Rights Commission has approved a declaration on
human-rights defenders which will be adopted by the UN General
Assembly at the end of the year. It says that ''everybody has the
right, individually and in association with others, to promote and
to strive for the protection and realisation of human rights and
fundamental freedoms at the national and international level''.
	   It is unfortunate that Thailand does recognise human-rights
defenders as do other countries. Well-known human-rights fighters
such as Czech President Vaclav Havel, South African President
Nelson Mandela and South Korean President Kim Dae-jung virtually
walked out of prisons to become national leaders.
	   Finally there is a question closely associated with the
human-rights issue -- the quality and commitment of Thai
politicians, who constitute the largest pool of Thai leadership.
Without their active support, the promotion of human rights will be
stymied as many archaic pieces of legislation need to be repealed
or amended in Parliament. All this can only be done with their
consent and unwavering support.
	   If Thailand's history is any judge, politicians and those in
uniform have been colluding with one another to block the
development of the promotion of human rights in Thailand. They feel
that if the public enjoyed greater human rights, their existence as
societal arbitrators would be restricted. The delay in the
establishment of the national commission on human rights was a case
in point. Now under the new Constitution the commission will be set
up within two years, and that is an important step forward.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
