<HEADLINE>
`Danaharta may issue more bonds', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
`Danaharta may issue more bonds', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Kasmiah MustaphaASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   DEPUTY Finance Minister Datuk Dr Affifudin Omar said Pengurusan
Danaharta Nasional Bhd may raise more funds through issuance of
bonds if the initial amount is insufficient.
	   ``The mechanism of the company allows it to issue more bonds ...
(But) the company just started its operations. Let the management
assess the situation first.''
	   Affifudin said the bonds may only be issued if the initial RM25
billion is insufficient, and this decision would be made by the
Cabinet. Last Thursday, Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister
Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim said the national asset management company
may need about RM25 billion to take up the non-performing loans of
the banking system.
	   The company will initially raise RM10 billion through the issue
of bonds locally and abroad. Of this, the equivalent of US$1
billion (RM4 billion) to US$2 billion would be sourced from the
international bond market. The bonds are Government-guaranteed.
	   Pengurusan Danaharta was formed by the Government to deal with
banks' non-performing loans, which stood at 9.3 per cent of total
outstanding loans as at March this year.
	   The establishment of the AMC is aimed at reviving still-viable
assets and allowing banks to focus on their daily operations, both
of which the Government hopes would assist in the economy recovery.
	   Affifudin said with the NPLs taken over by Pengurusan Danaharta,
the banks would be able to increase their efficiency and liquidity.
	   ``The recent (lending) problem faced by the banks is because
they do not have enough liquidity. They will have more liquidity if
they are not burdened with NPLs.''
	   He was speaking to reporters after officiating the Asia Pacific
Co- operation Customs Industry Dialogue or Acid '98 in Kuala Lumpur
yesterday.
	   Affifudin said the setting up of Pengurusan Danaharta was
similar to the ``Brady scheme'' and has proven to be successful
when it was implemented in Latin America.
	   He refuted claims that Pengurusan Danaharta was set up as
``bail-out''
	   agency adding that the company is taking the collateral pledge
to the banks.
	   Earlier, Affifudin said the customs law, regulations and
procedures need to be more transparent so as to ensure certainty
which would benefit those involved in trade.
	   Although the issue has been tackled by the Apec Sub Committee on
Customs Procedures, he said there still remained a lot to be done
in terms of ensuring a greater degree of simplification of customs
clearance procedures.
	   Jointly organised by the Customs and Excise Department of
Malaysia and the National Chamber of Commerce and Industry of
Malaysia, the dialogue precedes the annual Apec leader's meeting to
be held in Kuala Lumpur in November.
	   
</TEXT>
