<HEADLINE>
Indian software firm moves Asean ops here, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Indian software firm moves Asean ops here, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   NIIT (M) Sdn Bhd, the local subsidiary of the India-based IT
company NIIT Ltd, yesterday launched its Software Solutions
business in the country and hopes to turn in total revenue of RM127
million in five years, said managing director Rahul Patwardhan.
	   With the launch of the Software Solutions business, NIIT
Malaysia assumed from Singapore operations the role as the Asean
headquarters for NIIT Ltd and will establish a software development
centre here to support its parent company's global business, he
added. The Multimedia Super Corridor-status company, which
commenced operations in January this year, has surpassed its modest
whole-year revenue target for 1998 by generating RM5 million within
five months.
	   The company expects by the year 2000 to make up 25 per cent of
NIIT Ltd's Asean business expected to record a total revenue of
RM400 million by the turn of the millennium.
	   Bullish on its activities here, NIIT Malaysia will continue
recruiting locals to make up 50 per cent of its staff in three
years' time and has allocated a sum of RM32 million for investment
purposes for the next five years.
	   Patwardhan said this in Kuala Lumpur after the official launch
of NIIT Malaysia's Software Solutions business by Multimedia
Development Corporation chief operating officer Dr Mohamed Arif
Nun.
	   The new unit under NIIT Malaysia, called NIIT Consulting,
Software and Systems Integration Business Group, will focus its
activities in the government, transportation, manufacturing,
telecommunication and financial services sectors.
	   It offers to these sectors IT services such as IT consulting,
systems integration, software development, professional services,
implementation, facilities management and outsourcing.
	   Its technology activities include client-servers,
Internet/Intranet, networking, multimedia, workflow, Year 2000
solutions and enterprise resource planning.
	   Patwardhan said the company's SSB unit is expected to contribute
60 to 70 per cent to its five-year target revenue figure.
	   On the parent company's decision to shift its regional
headquarters from Singapore to Malaysia, he said the move was made
due to higher operating costs in Singapore.
	   NIIT Malaysia, which has 20 employees hopes to increase its
strength to over 100 in five years.
	   
</TEXT>
