<HEADLINE>
SC wants foreign cap in brokerages be raised to 70pc, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
SC wants foreign cap in brokerages be raised to 70pc, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Securities Commission has proposed that the Government raise
the foreign equity cap in local stockbroking firms to 70 per cent
from 49 per cent currently.
	   The idea is to attract foreign parties into the current effort
to assist ailing stockbroking firms, SC chairman Datuk Dr Mohd
Munir Majid said yesterday.
	   He also called on other strong local stockbrokers to emulate the
example of Hwang-DBS Securities Bhd in assisting clients of ailing
stockbroking firms, should their licences be revoked - as in the
case of Omega Securities Sdn Bhd.
	   ``I am not saying more stockbroking licences may be revoked.
But, it is better to be prepared,'' he said at the SC office in
Kuala Lumpur.
	   Munir said the SC initiated the reimbursement scheme some weeks
ago, and Hwang-DBS had come forward to assist in the case of Omega
clients.
	   The scheme was initiated to keep the existing RM314 million
Compensation Fund - managed by the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange -
from being depleted.
	   ``We have approached a number of other strong stockbroking
firms, but Hwang-DBS was the only one to come forward with full
gusto.''
	   As an incentive a participating stockbroker would be allowed to
open additional branches - subject to minimum capital investment
requirements.
	   But this incentive is only applicable to the reimbursement
scheme which, Munir pointed out, was not tied in any way with the
SC's prerogative to revoke or suspend any stockbroker's licence.
	   Hwang-DBS, which is contributing RM70 million towards the
reimbursement scheme for Omega Securities' clients, would now be
allowed to operate a new branch in Shah Alam, Selangor - where
Omega Securities operated.
	   Hwang-DBS managing director Datuk Hwang Sing Lue, who was also
present at the Press conference, said the branch would be opened in
a few months.
	   Under the reimbursement scheme, Hwang-DBS will be sending by
June 15 letters to eligible clients of Omega Securities.Replies
opting to accept payments must be in by June 30.
	   KPMG Peat Marwick have been appointed as special auditor to
verify these clients.
	   Those who fail to meet the deadline will have to claim from the
KLSE Compensation Fund. Remisiers will have to seek other legal
redress under contract laws for their deposits paid and other
claims.
	   Payments to eligible clients of Omega Securities under the
reimbursement scheme will be made at the KLSE between July 13 and
17 between 9am and 5pm.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
