<HEADLINE>
FDA issues warning on flu vaccination, NATION
</HEADLINE>
FDA issues warning on flu vaccination, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   FOLLOWING last week's reports that young actress Catleeya
Macintosh had fallen sick after being innoculated against the 'flu
-- or khai wad jai as it is called in Thai -- the FDA has issued a
warning for those who are planning to get their jabs.
	   According to Banphot Tontheerawong, deputy secretary of the Food
and Drugs Administration (FDA), the anti-influenza vaccine
manufactured by French pharmaceutical giant Pasteur Merieux was
granted FDA approval subject to certain conditions.
	   Under the present regulations, the vaccine is only available
under prescription from hospitals. The FDA has ordered physicians
to produce safety reports on the flu vaccine at quarterly intervals
over the next two years.
	   The drug is not yet classified as an essential vaccine at the
national level. Studies remain to be conducted on efficacy and
potential side-effects.
	   Banphat recommends that people interested in being vaccinated
check with their doctors to find out whether they might be
unwittingly placing themselves at risk.
	   The vaccination should not be given to individuals falling into
the following categories. - Known allegery to to albumin or egg
white - Known allergy to sodium thiomersal - Anyone running a high
fever - People suffering from persistent health disorders should
delay getting their shots.
	   Women in the first trimester of pregnancy and breast-feeding
mothers.
	   Health specialists recommend that the vaccination be given just
prior to the onset of the rainy season.
	   General side effects are mild pain at the injection site and a
low-grade fever lasting no longer than 48 hours.
	   However, Banphat concludes that the easiest way to prevent a
dose of flu is through regular exercise, a healthy diet and being
blessed with a strong immune system. THE NATION
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
