<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup-Brazil Reax,0315 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Brazil grinds to a halt to watch World Cup
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MICHAEL ASTOR
 &UR; Associated Press Writer

<TEXT>
	   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ Rush hour came early Wednesday as
Brazilians abandoned work to watch their team's first appearance in
this year's televised World Cup.
	   In front of the big hotels in Rio de Janeiro's Copacabana
district, tourists jostled with prostitutes and transvestites in an
effort to glimpse Brazil's match with Scotland on televisions at
beachside beer stands. Brazil won the game, 2-1.
	   The normally packed beaches were bare, and roads that were
jammed an hour before the game _ broadcast at 12:30 p.m. local time
(1430 GMT) _ emptied as it approached.
	   Half an hour before kickoff, Rio's downtown business district
was a ghost town except for random crowds clad in green and yellow
_ Brazil's national colors _ blowing on cheap plastic trumpets and
waving flags before large-screen TVs set up at several stores.
	   Banks closed at noon, and hospital emergency workers cared for
their patients with one eye on the game.
	   ``We're fully staffed and ready for any emergency, but we're
Brazilians so we'll find a way to do our work and root for Brazil
at the same time,'' said Dr. Fernando Mattos, who heads the
emergency room at the Miguel Couto hospital on Rio's upscale south
side.
	   On the city's poorer north side, residents painted the streets
with images of their favorite players under yellow and green
streamers strung across the road.
	   Barbecues were set up on sidewalks alongside TVs where fans
lounged in beach chairs.
	   In Bento Ribeiro, home of team superstar Ronaldo, cautious
enthusiasm turned to glee late in the second half, when Brazil took
the lead with an own goal by Scotland off a shot by Cafu.
	   Fabio Barata, one of Ronaldo's cousins, spoke for many his
fellow fans: ``What a relief!''
</TEXT>
