<BODY>
<SLUG> EMPTY-OIL-PALM-FRUIT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Clean way to make fertiliser from empty oil palm fruit bunches, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Clean way to make fertiliser from empty oil palm fruit bunches, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Mon. - About eight million tonnes of empty oil
palm fruit bunches (EFBs) per year can now be turned into organic
fertiliser in a cheap and environment-friendly way.
	   The BWS Composting System, the technology of Bio-Waste Solutions
(International) Ltd, eliminates the need for EFBs to be burned or
mulched.
	   The system is being promoted by Indus Inova (M) Sdn Bhd.
	   Bio-Waste Solutions director of marketing, Steve Lyons said two
palm oil mills were currently using this method on trial runs, but
declined to name them.
	   The system uses a decomposition process under aerobic
conditions, thus there is no obnoxious odour. A blend of organic
materials and a variety of micro-organisms are used for the
biodegradation process.
	   ``This system will help reduce air and water pollution. It will
also eliminate the use of inorganic fertiliser which is harmful and
costly with the current economic downturn.''
	   It will cost about RM1 million for mills to implement this
method, Lyons said, and the biodegradation process takes 28 days.
	   He said Malaysia imported RM1 billion in fertiliser last year.
	   ``All material and substances that make up our system are
Malaysian-made so our prices are not subject to the fluctuating
currency levels,'' he said.
	   Indus Inova's executive chairman P. Panjalingam said the system
can presently only be used by the palm oil industry but there are
plans to expand it to the other industries.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
