</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> THE-WATER-OF-LIFE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
The Water of Life, NATION
</HEADLINE>
The Water of Life, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   UMA TIWARYASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE world was taken by surprise back in 1977 when the seemingly
invincible Indian Prime Minister Indira Gandhi was voted out of
power.
	   Within weeks, when her replacement sprightly septuagenarian
Morarji Desai was being sworn in, the international community was
hit by a second shock wave. Desai announced that his excellent
state of health could be put down to his long-time practice of
drinking his own urine.
	   The Indian public was considerably less shocked and dubbed
Desai's preferred beverage ''Morarji Cola''. His habit may have
brought him health -- Desai lived to the ripe old age of 97 -- but
it failed to promote political longevity; he was upstaged by Charan
Singh a year later.
	   Urine therapy has been practiced in Thailand for many years, but
it has seen a resurgence during the last five years among educated
people as well.
	   Although urine therapy has been practised for thousands of
years, the origins have never been traced back to any single
country. It is known that most of the yogis who lived at high
altitudes in the Himalayas, indulged in a warming cup of urine to
survive the bitter cold, so it's probably fair to assume that the
therapy developed on the Subcontinent.
	   Amarohi (the practice of ingesting one's own urine) is also
mentioned in the Aryurveda . There are references to shivambhu
kalpa vidhi which means ''the method of drinking urine in order to
rejuvenate''. It is said that Shiva himself encouraged the therapy
especially among those who practised meditation.
	   To many of us, the very thought of drinking what we've excreted
is unpalatable. How can imbibing the substances that our bodies
have rid themselves of improve our health? Yet this unorthodox
regime is embraced by a surprisingly high number of well-educated
people who are more than satisfied with the benefits it brings.
What's more, urine therapy now appears to be gaining recognition as
a promising preventive protocol.
	   In February 1996, the first World Conference on Urine Therapy
was held in India. Participation was higher than anticipated -- the
conference attracted specialists in different fields from all over
the world. The second international symposium is scheduled to take
place in Germany later this year.
	   The Thai Public Health Ministry specialist, Somsong Rakphao
recently appeared on the small screen to clarify the benefit versus
risk equation. ''People who practise urine therapy are very health
conscious and they may develop some psychological reactions which
are positive in the healing process,'' he stated. ''But from
medical point of view, drinking urine can be harmful to the
kidneys. Like the effects of hypnotism on the human spirit, the
benefits cannot be scientifically proven.'' Manop Udomdej, a
respected Thai movie director, argues that urine is not, as most
believe, just poisonous waste excreted by the body. ''Its
composition is not toxic,'' he says. ''The body naturally absorbs
urine. We don't realise it, but it contains an enormous amount of
water and useful substances. There's nothing to worry about from a
toxicity point of view if you drink a small amount.'' Manop has
been drinking his urine for more that four years and swears he has
benefitted from the practice. ''I was allergic to dust and couldn't
stop sneezing whenever I was in a dusty environment. Then in 1993 I
read an article in a local newspaper about a Japanese doctor called
Nagao Rioji who was promoting urine therapy as a way of preventing
disease and maintaining good health. I found it fascinating.
	   ''I started to explore the practice. From the questions I asked,
I learned that many people in rural communities routinely drank
their urine. There was nothing new about it, they'd been doing it
for years.'' But although his interest was piqued, Manop still had
doubts about whether it would work for him. Nevertheless, he
decided to give it a go and in spite of what he now describes as an
''initially unpleasant experience'' stuck rigidly to the regime.
Much to his surprise, his allergic reaction to dust disappeared.
Manop stopped the therapy after four months and the allergy
returned, this time exacerbated by itchy eyes and other unpleasant
symptoms. He went back to drinking urine and has remained faithful
to his routine ever since.
	   Not everyone shares his faith. Says one male non-believer after
his first experiment with the therapy, ''The taste was unbearable.
Actually, it wasn't just the taste, but I could actually feel some
substances going down my throat. It was horrendous. And all I'd had
to drink the night before was half a bottle of beer and a pot of
Chinese tea. If people really fancy drinking the waste from their
bodies, why don't they try to make it in tablet form? Anyway, I
felt like throwing up after the second gulp and I shall only try
again if I'm trapped in a dessert.'' Urine is composed of 95 per
cent water, 2.5 per cent urea (a crystalline nitrogenous compound
that contains some toxic substances) with the remaining 2.5 per
cent being made up of a mixture of minerals, salts, hormones and
enzymes. Practitioners of the therapy argue that it is a sterile
liquid with many antiseptic qualities.
	   Over the last 10 years, Nagao Rioji has been one of the major
movers in introducing the revolutionary regime to this part of the
world. He has conducted considerable research and come up with some
interesting results. He has even started a ''Miracle Club'' in
order to encourage the practice.
	   Rioji's studies have shown that urine contains a substance known
as interferon (a protein released through the cells). This acts as
a ''cursor'' and results in several chain reactions in the body.
Rioji says that this naturally-produced interferon helps the body
to fight back certain illness by increasing immunity. Morning urine
also contains traces of melatonin, a hormone with
immunity-enhancing qualities.
	   Other health specialists argue that the amount is too small to
be of significant use. Proponents of urine therapy rise to the
defence by pointing out that that the toxic substances contained in
urea are too minor to cause harm.
	   For some, the ''water of life'' may not an advisable option. For
example, the urine of patients taking allopathic (conventional)
medications inevitably contains samples of the drug's active
ingredients. Nor is urine therapy recommended for users of yaa-e
(ecstasy) or other illegal substances -- it is not a recipe for a
cheap morning ''high''. In 1992, Juljira Khontha, a Thai radio
programmer and columnist for the health magazine San Asoke , was
diagnosed with breast cancer. Although the disease was not
sufficiently advanced to call for a masectomy, she underwent
surgery to remove the malignant lump.
	   A few weeks after her discharge from hospital, she discovered
another lump. Terrified at the prospect of another and possibly
more radical surgical intervention, she started drinking her urine.
	   ''In the beginning I drank three glasses a day. It was not a
pleasant experience since I suffered from headaches and noticed
other changes in my body. Fortunately, I had read that these were
normal reactions and would subside once my body had adjusted to the
therapy.'' Juljira continued with the treatment but, on a friend's
advice, reduced her intake to one glass each morning. She checked
her breasts regularly and felt the lump start to shrink and finally
disappear.
	   Had the therapy worked a miracle? No one, including Juljira
herself, will ever know. She didn't consult a doctor when she
discovered the second lump so it could well have been a figment of
her imagination, the post-trauma often associated with surgery for
breast cancer. Nonetheless, Juljira has continued her daily regime
of a glass of urine and adheres to a vegetarian diet. She says that
this has helped her mentally too. The hot-tempered woman is now
calm and serene.
	   Neither Manop or Juljira have been subjected to ridicule by
their friends for their belief in, and practice of urine therapy.
Both say that part of their motivation for starting the daily
regime was enhanced by the fact that the practice is mentioned in
the Buddhist book Phra Traipidok (or Tripitaka ), and is described
as harmless.
	   Juljira pens a column titled Nam Chee Dee Jing Rue ? (is urine
really good?) for monthly magazine San Asoke . Several readers, she
says, write in to share their experiences of drinking urine. Manop
too encourages his friends to give the therapy a try. It is, he
stresses, harmless and cheap.
	   Will urine therapy become a revolutionary treatment? That
remains to be seen but there's no doubting that it's here to stay.
	   In the meantime, to any readers who may be enjoying a glass of
''Morarji Cola'' while reading this article -- cheers!
	   
</TEXT>
