<HEADLINE>
Johor to expand habitat for rhinoceros, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Johor to expand habitat for rhinoceros, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MUAR, Mon.- The Johor Government plans to expand the existing
Johor side of the 49,000ha core rhinoceros habitat in Endau-Rompin.
	   State Executive councillor Dr Chua Soi Lek said today the State
Forestry Department was conducting a study on this.
	   ``This is to allow the animals to have more room and populate,''
he said, when commenting on a New Sunday Times report that fewer
than five rhinoceros were in the Endau-Rompin area.
	   Dr Chua, who is also the State Environment and Consumer Affairs
committee chairman, said in the last census five years ago, about
five to l0 rhinoceros were found at the Johor side of the
Endau-Rompin area.
	   ``The Government has already allocated RM30,000 to enlist about
300 Orang Asli in the forest to ensure the animals within the Park
are safe and protected.
	   ``These people are experts and are considered a part of the
forest and they understand the animals and surrounding well,'' he
said.
	   Dr Chua said indiscriminate felling of trees, logging and
illegal construction might force the animals to flee. As such
strict enforcement is being carried out.
	   Endau-Rompin National Park, managed by Johor Parks Corporation,
only allows 200 people to visit the park daily, and not more than
6,000 visitors a month.
	   He said the State Government welcomed naturalists,
environmentalists and researchers from all over the world to
conduct and document their findings and identify the rare species
of animals, birds, insects and reptiles in the Park.
	   He said: ``We need all the help to explore the virgin jungle to
find ways to preserve the vegetation and conserve the animals
especially the rhinoceros.
	   ``We want to understand the mysteries of the forest in order to
draw up programmes to protect the living world within.''
	   
</TEXT>
