<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Northern Ireland </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lawmakers debate early release of paramilitary prisoners
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam opened a
marathon debate Wednesday over plans to give early paroles to
convicted terrorists, the most controversial section of the Belfast
peace agreement.
	   Mowlam recommended to the House of Commons legislation that
would offer convicts of the Irish Republican Army and two
pro-British gangs, the Ulster Defense Association and Ulster
Volunteer Force, freedom by mid-2000.
	   She said the proposed law struck ``the right balance between the
steps necessary in the interests of lasting peace ... and in
ensuring that public safety will not be jeopardized.''
	   But leaders of Northern Ireland's pro-British Protestant
majority said no convicts should be freed unless the outlawed
groups to which they belong started disarming under international
supervision.
	   The agreement struck April 10 among eight parties specified
mid-2000 as the deadline for such disarmament, but didn't
specifically link this goal with the plans for paroles, which were
more specifically worded.
	   Proposed amendments to the Northern Ireland Sentences Bill, most
of them written by Protestant lawmakers determined to link paroles
to disarmament, will be debated Monday before the law's anticipated
easy passage later this month.
	   Seamus Mallon, deputy leader of the Social Democratic and Labor
Party, which represents most of the north's Catholics, said the
promise of paroles ``places a debt of honor on the shoulders'' of
the IRA, UDA and UVF, whom he said could commit ``no tricks, no
games.''
	   But the Rev. Ian Paisley, leader of the Democratic Unionist
Party and chief critic of the compromise agreement, predicted that
the IRA would retain its weaponry even after its senior imprisoned
members are freed.
	   ``What happens then? Then you get the gun on your head again,
and the IRA says, `We want something more','' Paisley said.
	   In Northern Ireland, Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams told his
supporters in the mainly Catholic town of Newry that he wants to
play ``a full and active part'' in Northern Ireland's new
government.
	   An election June 25 will determine membership in a new 108-seat
legislative assembly, from which a 12-member administration will be
drawn from several parties. The IRA-allied Sinn Fein, which won 17
percent of the vote in elections last year, is likely to be
entitled to one or two top posts.
	   Adams said Sinn Fein was willing to take part in governing
Northern Ireland, a state that the IRA had tried since 1970 to
destroy, because he wanted to enter ``a new century, a new
millenium, where dialogue is the key instrument for change.''
	   (sp-acw)
</TEXT>
