<HEADLINE>
Court releases passports of two Bangladeshis, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Court releases passports of two Bangladeshis, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUCHING, Mon. - The magistrate's court here today allowed a
joint application by two Bangladeshis charged with harbouring their
countrymen to have their international passports temporarily
released after hearing arguments from the prosecution and defence.
	   Magistrate Mahazan Mat Taib, who made the order, fixed June 17
for the trial to begin against them and two others who all pleaded
not guilty to the charge.
	   MD Abdul Razak, 40, and SMA Khan, 32, are jointly charged with
local businessman David Lau Sin Phang, 34, and another Bangladeshi,
Wabiur Rahman Khan, 32, with committing the offence.
	   Lau was released on RM10,000 bail with two sureties while the
three were each released on RM20,000 bail with one surety.
	   The four were jointly charged under Section 56(1)(d) of the
Immigration Act 1959/63 with harbouring 29 Bangladeshis at a
shophouse in Central Park, Batu Tiga here about 3.40pm on May 1.
	   Lau was represented by John Shek and the three by Anthony Tai.
Chief Inpsector Lim Kwai Seng prosecuted.
	   Soon after court adjourned, Lau was arrested by police on
another case.
	   Earlier, in applying for the trial against the four to be
adjourned, Lim said he was prepared to proceed with the trial but
had not received any directive from the deputy public prosecutor to
proceed with the hearing.
	   
</TEXT>
