<BODY>
<SLUG> TRADE-INTERNATIONALLY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Un Decides To Control Drug Trade Internationally, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Un Decides To Control Drug Trade Internationally, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   SU LIN LEWISASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE late twentieth-century has seen the growth of two phenomena:
globalisation and the increase in the use of narcotics. In an
attempt to use one to counter the other, the United Nations is
envisioning a dynamic web of international drug control to counter
the worldwide drug trade at all levels.
	   Today is the last of a three day Special Session the United
Nations General Assembly are holding in New York City, to tackle
the prevailing world drug problem in a cooperative manner. Pino
Arlacchi, Under-Secretary of the UN, former member of the Italian
Senate, and renowned expert on the Mafia and drug control has been
leading the session.
	   Although nations have cracked down domestically on illicit drugs
since the first UN convention on drug control ten years ago, drugs
continue to flourish in the 90's. They are a means of survival in
urban street-life, as well as in developing countries where farmers
can no longer compete with the legitimate agricultural market.
Drugs are popularised by youth subculture from England to Japan and
they are grown or manufactured in nearly every nation in the world,
industrialised or not.
	   And yet there is optimism for the next decade, for now that the
UN has realised that drug-trafficking is a multi-national
operation, it has finally decided that nations should work in a
cooperative manner to try and stem the flow. Adding to this
new-found hope is that nations will enter the next century better
able to cooperate with each other, in spite of ideological
differences (trade in general has had a decided impact on this),
armed with new monitoring techniques, as well as with accumulated
knowledge of drug control.
	   The United Nations International Drug Control Programme (UNIDCP)
is leading the Special Session, with the main goal of developing a
global Action Strategy towards reducing the supply and demand for
illicit drugs. The Programme, operational since 1991, is stressing
tight, international cooperation to counter the worldwide drug
trade from initial cultivation of illicit crops and production of
synthetic drugs, to their manufacturing and trafficking.
	   In the spirit of globalisation, nations are finally expected to
work together through extradition procedures, mutual legal and
research assistance between states, joint training sessions, the
transfer of proceedings from state to state, and tighter monitoring
of sea-routes.
	   The session will also discuss prevention methods and ways of
helping drug abusers break their habit.
	   Other issues include the use of precursor chemicals, which are
diverted from legitimate commerce to process cocaine and heroin,
and to manufacture synthetic drugs. Current monitoring techniques
of the chemical trade, which have been very successful over the
past decade, are to be improved upon and used more frequently.
	   However, a worrying issue is the increase in amphetamine-type
substances (ATS) -- that have become widely available in the 90's.
According to the UNIDCP, these synthetic drugs are now used by 30
million people (5 per cent of the world population) and have now
become the most popular and widespread drug after cannabis, which
is used by 2.4 per cent of the world population).
	   Control of ATS is difficult as it is readily available and comes
in diverse varieties. The UNIDCP can only hope to raise awareness
of these harmful substances, reduce their demand, and continue with
investigation and research into the drugs.
	   While ATS is born out of clandestine laboratories in cities and
suburbs, heroin, cocaine, and cannabis are grown illegally in rural
areas. The UNIDCP needs to create alternate development projects in
areas where the cultivation of illicit crops is occurring.
	   While cannabis is grown worldwide, opium and the coca leaf are
found mainly in Southern Asia and Latin America. In these two
regions, 700,000 families depend on the cultivation of illicit
crops as a source of income. They are open to both exploitation by
ruthless middlemen and the constant threat of crop eradication.
What's more, they are often forced to work on large-scale farms
owned by drug traffickers, thus, the projects' aim must be to find
other sources of income for these families.
	   Thailand is one nation where alternate development projects have
led to the virtual elimination of opium poppy cultivation.
	   Finally, the concern over money laundering by drug traffickers
is being addressed with the aim of confiscating drug profits at
their entry point into the financial system, through international
cooperation and the stricter monitoring of offshore banking.
	   Representatives from 130 governments showed their commitment to
the project in the final preparatory session held in Vienna last
March. However, the issue of whether or not to allow for full
participation of member states was still left open. As we have seen
before, many of the UN's plans and strategies have not had the
success they had hoped for because they were non-binding.
	   So our new ''globalised'' world will just have to wait and see
whether the UN can make drug control a primary issue requiring full
and active cooperation of all member states.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:TRADE-INTERNATIONALLY sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
