<SLUG> MAS-URGED-TO-GIVE-CARGO sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAS urged to give cargo facilities for aquarium fish export, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
MAS urged to give cargo facilities for aquarium fish export, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Valerie NgASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   JOHOR BARU, Mon. - Aquarium fish breeders in Johor want Malaysia
Airlines to provide air cargo facilities for the export of live
fish to markets overseas.
	   More than 80 per cent of all ornamental fish from Malaysia are
now exported through the Causeway via Singapore Airlines.
	   ``We are forced to use a foreign airline because our national
carrier does not have facilities for fish exports,'' said
vice-president of the Johor Aquarium Fish Breeders' Association,
Raymond Cheah.
	   ``Inevitably, many importers often think the fish are products
of Singapore.''
	   Malaysia exported RM60 million worth of aquarium fish in 1996,
an increase of about RM11 million, or 18 per cent, from 1995. (Last
year's figures are not available yet.) The exports included at
least 220 species and 500 varieties of aquarium fish, with the
United States, Japan, the United Kingdom, Germany, France, Italy,
Netherlands, Spain, Belgium, Taiwan and Korea being the biggest
markets.
	   ``The new emerging markets for aquarium fish are China and the
Middle East,'' said Cheah.
	   Most of the parent fish stocks for the farms in Malaysia are
imported from South East Asia countries, Australia, China, India,
Mexico, Colombia, Brazil, Argentina, Congo, Zambia and Madagascar.
	   Cheah said Malaysia had less than 10 indigenous species of
ornamental fish, the most notable being kissing gourami, harlequin
rasbora and pearl gourami which are also exported.
	   There are now about 500 ornamental fish breeders in Malaysia who
give employment to some 2,500 people nationwide.
	   The breeders accounted for exports totalling about RM50 million
in 1995, with Johor alone contributing 62 per cent of the sales,
followed by Perak (22 per cent), Selangor (10 per cent) and Penang
(5 per cent).
	   Johor has over 400 aquarium fish farms scattered around
Jemaluang, Layang-Layang, Ulu Tiram, Pontian, Kulai, Kluang, Kota
Tinggi and Kempas.
	   Cheah said Malaysia had the potential to become a world leader
in the production of ornamental fish, noting that the Government's
encouragement and assistance augured well for the growth of the
industry.
	   He said countries like Indonesia, Thailand and Sri Lanka were
also going big in the breeding of ornamental fish for exports.
	   ``The problem we face is there are not enough big farms with the
necessary infrastructure to spur the growth of the industry.
	   ``There is also a dire need to train new breeders and teach them
the means to penetrate into the booming international markets.''
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
