	   THE effectiveness of the government's economic policies will be
reviewed by a panel of academics and politicians tomorrow during a
discussion, beginning at at 1 pm, at the Faculty of Economics,
Thammasat University (fifth-floor conference room).
	   The opening address will be delivered by Dr Methee Khrongkaew,
president of the East Asian Studies Institute, and speakers will
include PM Office's Minister Abhisit Vejjajiva, former finance
minister Jaturon Chaisaeng, Dr Kowit Charnwitayaphong, a lecturer
in economics at Chulalongkorn University, and Thammasat economics
lecturer Dr Chawin Linabanjong. Admission is free.
	   For further details, phone 516 0042.
	   Students to slug it out in case-study contest TO mark the 60th
anniversary of the foundation of the Faculty of Commerce and
Accountancy, Thammasat University, students from the faculty's BBA
International Programme have organised a case-study competition for
undergraduates, which they hope will become an annual event, called
the Undergraduate Business Challenge.
	   Participants from four leading universities with international
programmes (Bangkok, Mahidol, Thammasat universities and the
University of the Thai Chamber of Commerce) will compete to solve a
case based on a contemporary situation involving a Thai company.
They are required to present their recommendations in English and
then defend whatever standpoint they take.
	   Members of the general public are welcome to attend the
presentation and take part in the question-and-answer session
afterwards. The competition take place on June 14, from 1 pm to 5
pm, in lecture room 201 at the Institute of East Asian Studies,
Thammasat University (Rangsit campus).
	   Admission is free. For more information, visit the website at
http://www.bus.tu.ac.th/bba/ubc.htm Friday last day to apply for
scholarships SIX scholarships worth a total of Bt1.2 million are
being offered to students studying toward a bachelor's degree in
medical technology in government or privately-run universities
throughout the Kingdom. The fund is being set up by the Association
of Medical Technologists of Thailand in conjunction with Safeguard.
	   Applicants must be first-year students at a faculty of medical
technology or an allied health science, have a minimum GPA of 2.50
in all subjects taken at secondary school, come from families with
an annual household income of less than Bt250,000, and have no
record of discipline infringements.
	   Friday is the deadline for receipt of applications. Forms are
available from faculties of medical technology or allied health
sciences at the following universities: Mahidol, Chulalongkorn,
Chiang Mai, Khon Kaen, Thammasat, Naresuan, Walailak, Rangsit and
Hua Chiew. The shortlist of scholarship recipients will be
announced on July 24.
	   For more information, phone 652 1946.
	   Two-week course on aspects of Thailand THE Office of Continuing
Education, Chulalongkorn University, is offering a two-week
programme on ''Perspectives on Thailand'', beginning on July 13.
	   Aimed at those interested in acquiring a broader perspective on
aspects of Thai culture, society, history and the economy, the
programme includes 28 hours of lectures and academic activities,
two half-day and two full-day excursions.
	   Lectures will be given in English. The registration fee is
US$1,200.
	   The closing date for receipt of applications is June 30.
	   For more information and registration details, phone 218
3945-47.
	   Meeting to discuss Unesco programmes THE regional consultation
meeting of the National Commission of the Asia-Pacific Region is
currently underway at Krungsri River Hotel in Ayutthaya. The
meeting continues until Friday.
	   Items on the agenda include: -Making preparations for the Unesco
budget and programmes for 2000-2001; n Improving co-operation on
programme design and implementation among Unesco national
commissions and offices in the Asia-Pacific region; and -Promoting
Unesco projects in the region.
	   Representative from 43 countries in the Asia-Pacific region are
attending the meeting. Call 391 0550 for further information.
	   
