<HEADLINE>
Police cracks down on illegal gathering, arrests lawmaker
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with police crackdown on rally, arresting
opposition lawmaker, opposition leader criticizing goverment. &QL; 
 &UR; By ALVIN UNG &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Malaysian police arrested an
opposition member of the Parliament after he gave a speech at a
political gathering banned by authorities, witnesses said late
Wednesday.
	   Police led away Lim Guan Eng, deputy secretary-general of the
opposition Democratic Action Party, shortly after he spoke to 2,000
supporters at a brightly lit open-air dinner organized by the party
in a suburb south of the capital.
	   Three party members were also arrested after they tussled with
policemen who were trying to cart away the amplifiers and speakers
used at the political rally.
	   ``Just because I'm expressing my constitutional rights to free
speech, I may have to spend the night here in the lock-up,'' Lim
said in a telephone interview from a nearby police station.
	   ``With the government bent on establishing a police state, this
is the end of the freedom of expression in Malaysia. Indonesia's
moving forward, but we're moving backwards,'' he said.
	   Lim said the police had yet to inform him why he was arrested.
The precinct's deputy police chief, Hussein Ismail, who was at the
scene, refused to comment.
	   Several police in riot gear had stood watch at the fund-raising
dinner for Lim, who has been sentenced to 18 months in prison for
printing a pamphlet that questioned Malaysia's political system.
	   A number of DAP leaders spoke during the dinner. Vehicles
clogged the road adjoining the field, where more than 60 dinner
tables had been placed for their supporters.
	   As the night continued, hundreds of people from the surrounding
neighborhoods also gathered to watch the spectacle. Shortly after
Lim began to speak, dozens of police in riot gear moved in to
arrest him.
	   ``We're not criminals, we're not robbers, we're not even threat
to the nation,'' Lim's father, party Secretary-General Lim Kit
Siang, cried out into the microphone shortly after police led his
son away.
	   ``By breaking up the event, the government has created a crisis
which does not exist,'' Lim Sr. said as his supporters jeered at
police. ``The police has alienated the public, making them an enemy
rather than friends.''
	   Several scuffles broke out but no injuries were reported. Police
dispersed the milling crowd shortly after midnight.
	   Lim Sr., who's also opposition leader for Parliament, later said
his party had applied for permission to hold the public gathering
several days ago.
	   He said organizers assumed it was OK to hold the gathering
because there was no response by authorities until the last moment.
	   This is the fourth time police have shut down public meetings
over the past 10 days and the third time police have disbanded
gatherings where opposition leaders were scheduled to speak.
	   Since the cancellations of public meetings in recent weeks,
dozens of organizations have demanded more civil liberties and free
speech.
	   ``In Indonesia, the people who have been muzzled for three
decades are beginning to experience a new freedom of expression,''
said Lim Sr. ``But in Malaysia, the government has suddenly become
afraid of the voice of the people.''
</TEXT>
