</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> HABIBIE-WILL-NOT-SURVIVE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nice try, but Habibie will not survive, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Nice try, but Habibie will not survive, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   For two decades, B J Habibie was Suharto's minister of research
and technology, a position befitting his role as a political
outsider. He has virtually no links with the military. And he was
never considered a potential president, not even by his own
political mentor. No wonder he is still a bit non-plussed about
being the man in the hot seat. During an interview, he had to be
reminded not to refer to Suharto as president. ''You are the
president,'' said his aide.
	   Nevertheless, Habibie knows well that if he is to keep his new
job, he will have to stay ahead of the reform wave. So Habibie the
technocrat, is now Habibie the reformer.
	   In the two weeks he has been president, he has brought changes
once thought impossible in this vast archipelago. He has committed
the government to holding elections by mid-next year. He has
released four political prisoners -- including renegade politician
Sri Bintang Pamungkas and labour leader Muchtar Pakpahan -- and
vowed to free more. He has promised to sign the International
Labour Convention that would permit independent unions.
	   But all this, however, does not wash with a sizeable number of
his countrymen. His close personal ties with Suharto, and his own
well-known nepotism, will make it difficult for him to embrace many
in the opposition, and more importantly, for the opposition to
embrace him. In defending himself, Habibie argued that his two
decades ''in the cockpit'' at Suharto's side had prepared him for
leadership. ''I'm not deaf and blind. I can read. I can see,'' he
said. ''I learned at the hands of the master.'' But that is exactly
Habibie's problem. He may have donned the reformist mantle: yet, to
many he is still Suharto's man. Not surprisingly, despite the
dramatic change in the leadership, there is still widespread
dissatisfaction over the slow pace of reform. Calls are being made
for the expropriation of Suharto's ill-gotten loot, the repeal of
the five repressive political laws of 1985 which, among others,
allows only three authorised political parties; the release of all
political prisoners; and a referendum for the East Timor people.
	   Habibie's major concern now -- and that of the powerful military
-- is to contain this growing chorus for reform. According to his
economic czar, Ginanjar Kartasasmita, reform differs from
revolution. Reform, he said, comes from the top and it should be
orderly as well as constitutional. That is exactly what the new
regime is seeking -- it hopes that tinkering with Suharto's New
Order system will help to pacify the angry masses.
	   But it is hard to imagine how the system founded by Suharto
could be dismantled by the very people who built it. The New Order
regime is not just Suharto. It has been kept alive by the active
collaboration of most of the middle class. Like foreign investors,
this section of the society has no particular love for democracy.
Stability -- to ensure that their money is safe -- is what they
want. And Suharto was able to deliver that for three decades. But
as soon as he was no longer useful, he was quickly discarded. Now
they are putting their money on another creature of the New Order.
	   However, for the mass of suffering poor who are facing the brunt
of an economic meltdown that is not of their doing, patience is
fast running out. They want nothing less than a swift end to the
New Order regime. Thus, the battle lines are already drawn -- on
one side are the elite who want constitutional reform, and the
other, the poor who want total reform.
	   Stepping into this breach are the students and a group of
middle-class activists who want Habibie to immediately give way to
an interim government until elections are held. Others go even
further. Recently released political prisoner Sri Bintang demands
an end to military involvement in politics. Still others want the
constitution overhauled, much as in Thailand, since the existing
one is out of step with democracy. All of them clearly are from the
elite class, but they speak the language of the poor. And it is
they who will determine the extent and shape of the reforms to
come.
	   Indonesia is still in a state of flux. Expectations are running
high. Time is short. Habibie, whether he likes it or not, will not
last, for like his predecessor, he will inevitably be swept away by
the growing tide of reform.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
