<HEADLINE>
Sir David English, Associated Newspapers chief, dead at 67
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Sir David English, chairman and group
editor-in-chief of Associated Newspapers _ who was editor of the
Daily Mail for 20 years_ died Wednesday after suffering a stroke.
He was 67.
	   English was admitted to St. Thomas's Hospital in London on
Tuesday and died on Wednesday, said Lawrence Sear, managing editor
of the Daily Mail.
	   English, who became editor of the Daily Mail in 1971 transformed
the tabloid over the next two decades.
	   Under his leadership, the newspaper became the self-assured
voice of middle England, identifying a fertile new market between
the traditional tabloid territory and the broadsheets.
	   ``With Lord Rothermere he reinvented the Daily Mail which became
the outstanding success story of modern Fleet Street,'' said the
newspaper's present editor, Paul Dacre. ``At heart he was a
newspaperman's newspaperman. He could do every job on the paper
better than anyone else and was an inspiration to everybody who
worked with him at the Mail.''
	   Prime Minister Tony Blair, told of English's death, called the
newspaperman ``a truly outstanding journalist. He never lost his
love and enthusiasm for his chosen profession and never lost his
eye for a good story.''
	   (acw)
</TEXT>
