AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A COMMITTEE on state enterprise policy, chaired by Deputy Prime
Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi, on Monday reaffirmed that three
state enterprises will be shut -- the Government Cold Storage
Organisation, the Preserved Food Organisation and the Textiles
Organisation.
	   Meanwhile, the Glass Organisation and Battery Organisation will
be privatised by setting up joint ventures with the private sector
to continue the businesses.
	   Mala enters aviation sector MALA Chemical Industries formed an
investment venture with Rosti Houseware of Denmark and Comero
Logistics of the Netherlands to win a Bt250 million five-year
contract from Scandinavian Airlines (SAS).
	   The group of companies last month signed the contract in Denmark
to supply melamine products to SAS over the next five years.
	   Manu Sitachit, managing director of Mala Chemical Industries,
said this is the first time the company has entered the airline
industry.
	   According to the alliance agreement, Rosti will be responsible
for marketing and Comero will provide the logistics while Mala
Chemical Industries will supply the products.
	   Leo to join in grand sale LEO Transport Corporation Ltd, an
international air and sea freight concern, says it will participate
in the Amazing Thailand Grand Sale 1998-1999 Project organised by
the Tourism Authority of Thailand and Department of Export
Promotion.
	   The participation will support the government's policy of
promoting exports to boost foreign currency revenue.
	   In participating in this project, the company, being named the
official freight forwarder, will provide transport services to
foreign tourists at a discount of 20 per cent by providing
one-stop-shopping services, from pick-up to packing and customer
clearance, including door-to-door delivery to recipients worldwide.
	   SEC organises workshop THE Securities and Exchange Commission
and Reuters news agency are organising a seminar called a ''Thai
Derivatives Management Workshop'' on Thursday and Friday. The
seminar will take place at the Regent Hotel Bangkok's ballroom. On
Thursday, the seminar will focus on Thai derivatives, and Prasarn
Trairatvorakul, deputy secretary-general of the SEC, will deliver
the opening speech at 8.30 am. On Friday, the topic of the seminar
will be Market Risk Management Techniques.
	   The seminar will be conducted in English but two issues -- the
Regulatory Framework Under the Draft Derivatives Market Act and the
Ongoing Derivative Projects of the SET -- under the topic of Thai
Derivatives on the first day will be discussed in Thai. Admission
is free and anyone interested can contact the SEC.
	   Petrochemical summit CENTRE for Management Technology (Thailand)
Co will organise the sixth Annual Asian Petrochemical Summit in
Phuket on June 22 and 23. Charles Zeynel, director of corporate
ventures for Union Carbide Corp, will give the keynote opening
address and discuss some of the latest developments in the
Petronas/UCC integrated petrochemical complex.
	   Other panellists at the conference to share their views on the
latest developments in the petrochemical scene, new projects and
strategies for the current economic outlook include Kevin Lucke of
Chevron Chemical International, Ed Yu Hwa Sheu of Chian
Petrochemicals Development Corp, Houssein Asempour of National
Petrochemical Co of Iran, Robert Johnson of Bank of America Asia
Ltd and David Huh of LG Polymers India.
	   Jump in tapioca export value EXPORTS of tapioca in the first
four months of this year rose by 49.24 per cent to Bt9.64 billion
in value but fell by 9.05 per cent to 1.62 million tonnes in terms
of volume, according to Pracha Charutrakulchai, director general of
Foreign Trade Department.
	   The value of tapioca pellet exports increased by 30.55 per cent
to Bt4.95 billion but volume declined by 13.82 per cent.
	   Tapioca flour exports reached 360,000 tonnes worth Bt4.68
billion, a rise of 11.97 per cent and 75.88 per cent respectively
during the same period.
	   Pracha said the local cassava price rose to Bt2 to Bt2.30 a
kilogramme.
	   The 1997-98 output fell 16.92 per cent to 14.68 million tonnes
compared with last year's output, causing a rise in the domestic
price.
	   Moreover, Indonesia, a major exporter suffered a decline in
production because of drought caused by the El Nino phenomenon.
	   
</TEXT>
