<HEADLINE>
Contest very popular with students, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Contest very popular with students, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Kamalia AbdullahASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   STUDENTS of two primary schools in Shah Alam had a fun time
recently thinking up the answers in the Kuala Lumpur Mutual Fund
(KL Mutual) Future Grads Contest. The questions were published in
the New Straits Times from May 25 to 29.
	   The contest offered the students of Sekolah Kebangsaan Section
24 and Sekolah Rendah Kebangsaan Section 18 a chance to win
attractive prizes and in the process test their knowledge of
current affairs.
	   ``The students were excited about the contest,'' said Karen Wong
Chek Fai, the English language teacher of SRK Section 18.
	   ``Many of them went home and asked their parents to buy the New
Straits Times because even though we buy the NST under the
Newspaper in Education (NIE) programme, there were not enough to go
around. The students preferred to have a copy for themselves when
they were answering the questions and filling in the entry form.''
	   SRK Section 18 has been buying some 50 copies of the New Straits
Times under the NIE programme since the beginning of this year.
Schools are entitled to a 50 per cent discount under the programme.
	   ``The students learn a lot from the New Straits Times,'' said
Wong.
	   ``I was amazed to see some students looking at the Stock
Exchange pages.
	   When I asked them why, they said that their fathers had shares
in some of the listed companies and they were checking the prices!
``Having access to the New Straits Times means they tend to read
more and hence gain more knowledge,'' she added.
	   Sekolah Kebangsaan Section 24 is also another NIE school. It has
been ordering the New Straits Times for the past two months.
	   Here, too, the students were busy answering the contest
questions.
	   Said teacher Noriha Yusoff: ``The students like referring to the
NST as it is an interesting source of news. They also learn a lot
of new words.
	   ``They also enjoy taking part in competitions like the Future
Grads contest as it offers great prizes and is fun.''
	   Three questions were published daily in the New Straits Times
during the contest period. Participants had to answer 15 questions
and also write a slogan on the importance of saving.
	   Twelve finalists will be selected for the finals to be held at
the Subang Parade shopping complex in Subang Jaya on July 5.
	   The first prize is RM5,000, the second RM3,000 and the third
RM2,000.
	   There will be nine fourth prizes, each worth RM1,000. All prizes
will be in the form of unit trust accounts. There are also 50
consolation prizes.
	   
</TEXT>
