<HEADLINE>
Chemical container blast causes skin irritation, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Chemical container blast causes skin irritation, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   RAYONG -- A container of chemical substances belonging to a gas
company in Mab Ta Phud Industrial Estate exploded Tuesday morning,
resulting in a massive permeation of white dust all over nearby
areas which caused skin irritation.
	   The chemical, called Perlite and used as an insulator in the
nitrogen container, spread, causing skin irritation and respiratory
problems. It also resulted in a school being closed.
	   The Mab Ta Phud Phan Phitthayakharn was affected by strong foul
fumes emitted from factories in the estate last week. School
director Winij Prathanraj announced an indefinite closure of the
institution.
	   Jamnongjai Noiraj, an engineer of the Bangkok Industrial Gas Co
where the container exploded, said the Perlite was not toxic and
would not cause any problem other than skin irritation.
	   The Perlite cloud was seen over the company compound shortly
after the explosion, it covered the area for a long time before
moving to a major market and the school, which are located a few
kilometres away from the gas company.
	   Meanwhile, a group of 200 local villagers gathered at the estate
to call for the resignation of Industrial Estate Authority of
Thailand governor Somjate Thinnaphong for failing to solve various
problems caused to them by factories in the estate.
	   Daily lunch allowance raised THE Bt7 daily lunch allowance for
students in schools run by the Bangkok Metropolitan Administration
(BMA) will be raised to Bt10 next year, an adviser to the Bangkok
governor said Tuesday.
	   Mahin Tanboonpherm said the additional cash will authorities
retain the nutritional value of the free food for students, and
that the increase will cost the BMA an additional Bt140 million
from its 1999 budget.
	   He added that the students in BMA-run schools would still enjoy
free milk daily since it still does not cost the BMA and the
government more than Bt300 million which they jointly shoulder each
year.
	   During Bangkok Governor Bhichit Rattakul's two-year tenure the
rate was increased once from Bt5 to Bt7.
	   Fee hike plan on hold THE Education Ministry will not endorse a
proposed rise in tuition and other fees for an international school
until it considers a Private Education Commission report on the
proposal, Minister Chumpol Silapa-archa said Tuesday.
	   He said a number of parents complained of being unfairly
burdened by the rise in international school fees. The school,
located on Sukhumvit Soi 15, is seeking a 28-per cent rise in fees,
citing the plunging value of the baht by more than 35 per cent
since its de facto flotation last July. The school also said that
it had to pay more to retain its international teaching staff and
for school aid and equipment.
	   The requested rise was made despite the fact that school had
earlier obtained a fee rise, Chumpol said.
	   Currently, parents have to pay between Bt124,000 in tuition fees
for a pre-school student to Bt234,000 for a grade 13 student, on
top of the one-time admission fee of Bt105,000.
	   Six hurt as 'copter crashes NAN -- A Laotian helicopter, while
on a joint mission with Thai authorities to mark the border,
crashed Tuesday in Bor Klua district, injuring six crewmen.
	   A Lao army officer, who arrived the scene after notifying a
local Thai military unit of the incident and requesting initial
assistance, said the cause of the accident was because of the
aircraft's excessive load and weary condition.
	   The TA-32T chopper, which carried 10 Lao officials and surveying
equipment, left from Hongsa airport in Laos' Sai Buri province. It
crashed while trying to land at an operation base in the district.
	   Two seriously injured crewmen are being treated at Nan Hospital
and will be returned to Laos at a later date.
	   
</TEXT>
