<SLUG> CSA-ADOPTS-CLIENTS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CSA adopts e-commerce in dealing with corporate clients, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
CSA adopts e-commerce in dealing with corporate clients, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IN a bid to entrench its position as a leading systems
integrator in an increasingly wired world, Computer Systems
Advisers (M) Bhd has incorporated electronic commerce to facilitate
online dealings with its corporate customers.
	   Its managing director Chuah Tai Eu said the business-to-business
Internet commerce system is to facilite ease of doing business with
its customers who could now make their orders and other requests
online.
	   Speaking after the company's annual meeting in Petaling Jaya
yesterday, Chuah said: ``The system will increase our efficiency
and will contribute indirectly towards our revenue.
	   ``We expect it to make a significant contribution to our revenue
in two or three years' time. In the long-run, we hope to cement
customer loyalty.''
	   He said the company, which had spent a few hundred thousand
ringgit in the project, is incorporating Internet as an important
part of its operations following IBM's worldwide campaign to push
e-commerce into mainstream business dealings.
	   ``It is the fastest growing computer segment for Global
Information Management now. We see a strong potential there and are
currently focused on business-to-business electronic commerce
solution, and Internet Security and Payment System,'' added Chuah.
	   For the financial year ended Dec 31, 1997, CSA posted group
pre-tax profit of RM19.3 million, a 25.2 per cent increase from
RM15.4 million previously.
	   Group turnover increased to RM370.0 million from RM267.4 million
previously, a hefty 38.4 per cent increase.
	   At company level, pre-tax profit increased to RM18.5 million, an
increase of 26.9 per cent from RM14.6 million in the previous year.
	   Turnover increased to RM270.3 million from RM207.3 million, an
increase of 30.4 per cent.
	   ``We expect to maintain or even increase slightly by 10 per cent
our revenue and profit level for this year. In fact, our first
quarter results this year showed a slight increase from last year's
corresponding quarter.
	   ``In our business, 60 per cent to 70 per cent of our business
come from repeat customers.''
	   Chuah said CSA had clinched a few new contracts worth a few
million ringgit this year but declined to elaborate.
	   ``Our cash position is strong at about RM15 million, and our
gearing very low. We do not expect any major problem in collection.
	   ``We have a good customer base and a balanced portfolio of
products, software services, solutions and revenue streams. Thus, I
would say that overall we could expect another good year in spite
of the economic downturn.''
	   CSA, Chuah claimed, has six to seven per cent of the market
share last year in a RM4 billion market.
	   ``All we need to do is just increase our market share by one per
cent, and that will translate into a 10 per cent increase in our
sales.
	   ``We believe we are the biggest in terms of revenue and size. We
have a total of 800 workers in 24 branches in Malaysia.''
	   Competition-wise, Chuah said, there were no other competitors
that came close to them in terms of the breadth of services and
solutions that they offer.
	   ``We are a totally integrated solutions provider in the real
sense of the word.''
	   Currently, it derives 40 per cent of its revenue from
customising computer systems for its clients which include
financial institutions, stock brokerages, manufacturers and the oil
and gas industry.
	   Their wholesaling and distributing activities contribute 20 per
cent, while another 20 per cent comes from system integration and
software development including Internet applications.
	   Chuah said one of its strategies is to diversify its client and
supplier base, ``that is, we monitor our exposure to ensure that we
are not overly exposed to one single client.''
	   ``Last year, not one of our single customer contributed more
than two per cent of our turnover, or about RM8 million.
	   ``We maintain the level to less than five per cent, and if sales
from one client contributed more than that, we will try to increase
the overall sales base so that we do not depend too much on one
single client.
	   ``Similarly, we do not take more than 30 per cent of our
supplies from one single principal (supplier).''
	   Chuah said 20 per cent of its total turnover last year came from
banks/financial institutions, 15 per cent from stock brokerages,
five per cent from manufacturing, two to three per cent from the
oil and gas sector, and 20 per cent from its wholesaling and
distributing activities.
	   On the impact of the lower ringgit, Chuah said that for the last
financial year, its forex losses amounted to RM2.9 million.
	   However, he added that this year the impact should be
significantly reduced because almost all except three of its
suppliers have agreed to quote in ringgit, or have locked the
exchange rate for future dealings.
	   The three suppliers that still bill the company in US dollar are
Microsoft Corp, Sun Microsystems Inc and Cisco Systems Inc which
together account for 20 per cent of their supplies.
	   Chuah said the slower economic growth had not impacted the
company as much as some other industries, ``as we still expect a
lot of activity in providing or recommending others for
Y2K-compliant (Year 2000) solutions, and work from MSC-related
projects.
	   ``In fact, in spite of the squeeze on financial institutions,
there is no reduction in business from them. When it comes to
cost-cutting, I believe IT will probably be the last thing they
will cut back on,'' he said.
	   The company which was one of the first few companies to be
granted MSC status had booked two lots in Cyberjaya and expects to
move some of its activities there including the research
department, which is now located in Technology Park Malaysia, Bukit
Jalil in Kuala Lumpur.
	   ``We have also exercised our option in purchasing three floors
of Wisma CSA, the building we are in now, at a very good rate of
RM170 per square foot.''
	   
</TEXT>
