<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-DFS Classic, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Graf wins first match of comeback
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: updated with Steffi quotes, results including seeds out.

<TEXT>
	   BIRMINGHAM, England (AP) _ Steffi Graf, playing her first match
in four months, rallied to beat Rennae Stubbs in three sets
Wednesday at the DFS Classic grass-court tournament.
	   The former world's No. 1 player recovered after losing the first
set and downed the Australian 5-7, 6-2, 6-4 in 1 hour, 51 minutes.
	   The two players, who are close friends, hugged at the net after
the match.
	   Graf, who received a first-round bye, advanced to a third-round
meeting against Kristie Boogert, of Netherlands.
	   After Wednesday's match she declared herself ``physically fit''.
	   ``I've been feeling good for the last few weeks _ now I need
matches and to play points, which I've not really done,'' she said.
	   ``With another 10 or 11 days I'll get better and better and
physically stronger.''
	   Graf, the winner of 21 Grand Slam singles titles, had played
only two tournaments since undergoing reconstructive surgery on her
left knee a year ago.
	   In February, she won a match at Hanover before losing a
quarterfinal clash with Sabine Applemans of Belgium 6-3, 7-6.
	   The next month, she won three matches at Indian Wells but had to
retire in the third set of the semifinals against Lindsay
Davenport.
	   Recent planned comebacks were postponed due to various injuries.
	   The start of Wednesday's match was held up by rain, which has
disrupted the first three days of the tournament.
	   Graf started the match with a brace on her left knee but she
removed it early in the first set.
	   Stubbs broke Graf twice in winning the first set. But the German
took control in the second, and her break of serve in the first
game of the third set held up the rest of the way.
	   Graf squandered two match points before closing out the match
with a trademark forehand winner.
	   Graf struggled with her serve, hitting 12 double faults to go
with her five aces.
	   Graf also plans to play next week at Eastbourne before starting
the challenge for her eighth Wimbledon singles title.
	   American Lisa Raymond was one of five seeds who lost to
qualifiers in round two, going down to Australian Kerry-anne Guse.
Guse won in three sets 6-3, 3-6, 6-1.
	   Third seeded Nathalie Tauziat, of France, was trailing
Zimbabwe's Cara Black by one set when play was suspended.
	   (str/sw) 	   
</TEXT>
