<HEADLINE>
New shipping laws being drafted: Ling, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
New shipping laws being drafted: Ling, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Kang Siew LiASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Transport Ministry is still in the process of drafting a new
legislation to replace the various ordinances which govern merchant
shipping in Peninsular Malaysia, Sabah and Sarawak.
	   Transport Minister Datuk Seri Dr Ling Liong Sik said the
proposed Malaysia Shipping Act will ensure that the shipping laws
of Malaysia are up to date and kept abreast with international laws
and practices.
	   ``It will also ensure that there is a single uniform law for the
entire country,'' he said in his opening address at the Fourth
Biennial International Maritime Conference on ``Maritime Industry:
Meeting New and Changing Demand Conditions in Asia'' in Subang Jaya
yesterday.
	   The two-day conference is organised by the Malaysian Maritime
Institute.
	   The three ordinances include the Merchant Shipping Ordinance
1952, the Merchant Shipping Ordinance (Sabah) 1960 and the Merchant
Shipping Ordinance (Sarawak) 1960.
	   He said the reason why the three existing ordinances need to be
replaced is that they were inherited from the British colonial
administration and thus, are quite archaic.
	   ``For a similar reason, we are drafting a new Carriage of Goods
by Sea Act.
	   ``The objective of the proposed Act is to update the liability
regime for sea transport.
	   ``At present, the current legislation enacted in 1950 adopts the
Hague rules of 1924. The new Act will adopt the Hague Visby Rules
of 1968,'' he said.
	   ``After these two Acts are passed, we can safely say that the
legislative framework would have been put in place,'' he added.
	   Dr Ling also urged all Malaysian shipping companies which have
yet to obtain their International Safety Management (ISM) Code
compliance certificate to start the process soon.
	   ``This is to ensure that their ships do not face any difficulty
when calling at foreign ports,'' he said.
	   1998 will be the year is when the ISM Code will be fully
implemented.
	   ISM Code compliance ensures that safety is given high priority
in the operation of the ships.
	   The Marine Department has been put in charge of issuing the
document of compliance certificate as well as supervising the
classification societies responsible for issuing the ISM Code
compliance certificate.
	   ``There are four lead auditors as well as four auditors from the
department authorised to issue the document of compliance
certificates.
	   ``To date, they have issued the certificates to 12 shipping
companies,''
	   he added.
	   Dr Ling also reminded the maritime industry of the new extended
Traffic Separation Scheme in the Straits of Malacca and Singapore
that will be enforced on December 1 this year.
	   ``This has already been agreed to by the Maritime Safety
Committee of the International Maritime Organisation. The scheme
will be complemented by the vessel traffic system.
	   ``It is at present undergoing pre-commissioning trials and is
expected to be fully operational soon,'' he said.
	   In line with the Government's efforts to position Port Klang as
a national and regional hub, Dr Ling said it has improved the
infrastructure facilities at the port, and Port Klang now has the
capacity to handle up to 77 million tonnes of cargo.
	   ``We have also improved the supporting landside infrastructure
leading into and out of the port.
	   ``The existing rail link to Port Klang has been doubled-tracked
and a new rail link to West Port is expected to be completed by the
end of this year,'' he said.
	   He added that the Government's efforts have shown encouraging
success resulting in over 90 per cent of the major shipping
alliances call at Port Klang.
	   Currently, 47 main line operators call at Port Klang compared
with 10 in 1990.
	   Malaysian ports handled 165.7 million tonnes of cargo last year,
up 10.2 per cent over the 1996 volume.
	   
</TEXT>
