<HEADLINE>
THAI offer awaits Tarrin, NATION
</HEADLINE>
THAI offer awaits Tarrin, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Finance Ministry Tuesday failed to win Cabinet support for
its privatisation proposal for Thai Airways International as
Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanahaeminda left for the G-7 conference
in New York.
	   The Cabinet agreed in principle to sell 335 million shares in
the airline -- 235 million existing shares owned by the government
and 100 million new shares --in what is seen as an attempt to
retain THAI's national airline status with a continued government
holding of 71.5 per cent.
	   The Finance Ministry wanted to sell 380 million shares to dilute
the government's stake to less than 70 per cent.
	   Permanent Finance Secretary Supachai Phisitvanich said that at
current prices the sale would add about US$300 million to the
national coffers and would reduce the government's stake to 71.5
per cent from about 93 per cent at present.
	   A government spokesman said the Cabinet approved the
establishment of a committee to select a consultant for the
privatisation process. However, it appointed permanent secretary
for transport and THAI board chairman Mahidol Chantrangkurn to head
the committee instead of the Comptroller-General director-general
following a recommendation by the Finance Ministry.
	   The consultant will be responsible for drawing up the terms of
reference to select a strategic partner, and setting a timeframe
and share price as well as adopting criteria for a share allocation
to airline employees.
	   The Cabinet also agreed that the airline should sell the shares
to strategic partners and institutions through private placements
and public offerings. Earlier, the Finance Ministry proposed that
the Cabinet sell the entire shares to a strategic partner to pave
the way for the airline's management to be revamped.
	   A Transport Ministry official said many international airlines,
including British Airways, Northwest Airlines and Singapore
Airlines, have expressed interest in becoming a strategic partner,
but most want more than a 20 per cent stake to give them an active
role in the airline's management.
	   THAI is a member of the Star Alliance led by United Airlines,
Lufthansa of Germany, SAS, Air Canada and Varig of Brazil.
	   Some time ago the Cabinet assigned the Finance and Transport
ministries to work on possible privatisation plans involving
diluting the government's stake to less than 50 per cent.
	   Under economic reform guidelines agreed with the IMF earlier
this year, Thailand proposed to accelerate the privatisation of its
national industries, including several strategic national
companies.
	   Shares in Thai Airways, Bangchak Petroleum Co and Electricity
Generating Plc were all slated for sale this year. Next year, the
government has promised to sell several other national bodies,
including telecommunications companies.
	   Meanwhile, the Cabinet approved a plan to strengthen the
airline's performance amid the regional crisis. The airline is
expected to cut its spending budget further in the 1998 fiscal year
to equal to last year, while adjusting its marketing strategy and
flight operating plan to boost its revenue.
	   The government urged the airline to improve its operating
performance -- excluding forex gains -- to attract investors and
ensure a good share price.
	   
</TEXT>
