<BODY>
<SLUG> TENAGA-SET-ACQUIRE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tenaga set acquire 20pc stake in Malakoff (HL), BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Tenaga set acquire 20pc stake in Malakoff (HL), BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Wendy LimASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   TENAGA Nasional Bhd (Tenaga) will emerge as a major shareholder
in Malakoff Bhd, with at least a 20 per cent stake, after the
proposed disposal of its stake in TNB Janamanjung Sdn Bhd and of up
to 20 per cent interest in Segari Energy Ventures Sdn Bhd.
	   Malakoff will issue new shares of RM1 each to Tenaga in the
exercise.
	   The number of shares to be issued will only be determined upon
the finalisation of the valuations of Janamanjung and Segari and
the percentage of Segari to be acquired.
	   The two major shareholders in Malakoff's are Malaysian Resources
Bhd with 21 per cent and National Power Plc (15 per cent). Malakoff
also holds 75 per cent in Segari.
	   Janamanjung, with an authorised share capital of RM25,000, is a
wholly- owned subsidiary of Tenaga.
	   It was set up to develop and operate a 2,100MW coal-fired plant
near Lumut.
	   Janamanjung is estimated to be worth around RM200 million
(excluding the power purchase agreement and engineering,
procurement and contraction contract).
	   Commerce International Merchant Bankers Bhd, in a statement to
the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange, said Tenaga and Malakoff signed
yesterday a memorandum of understanding to initiate the process of
the share acquisition.
	   The two companies have to enter into share acquisition
agreements for the proposed acquisitions by August 9 1998.
	   Tenaga executive chairman Datuk Dr Ahmad Tajuddin Ali, speaking
to reporters after witnessing the signing of a power purchase
agreement between the utility giant and Janamanjung, said: ``This
is only an intention from the two parties. All the terms of the
deals need to be negotiated and due diligence is also under way.''
	   ``It will take about two months to finalise the details pending
the approval from the related government agencies,'' he said,
adding that Tenaga views the exercise as a long-term investment.
	   Details of the agreeement are expected within two months.
	   It is understood that Tenaga will be using its equity in Segari
as an adjustment to keep its equity holding about 20.4 per cent in
Malakoff.
	   Tajuddin said the move is in line with the industry
restructuring as the utility company reduces its role in the
independent power plants.
	   It will, instead, concentrate on equity partnership with power-
generating companies.
	   The exercise, he said, is being undertaken considering that
Janamanjung is a priority project to the nation and the ability of
Tenaga to raise funding for the project.
	   The exercise, he said, will be strategic to both companies which
are involved in the power-generation business and providing a
strategic and synergistic benefits to Tenaga.
	   Tajuddin said the financing of the project will be decided by
the new owners of the company.
	   The project, which has been estimated to cost close to RM7
billion, will be financed through project financing, turning to
shareholders only as the last resort.
	   Credit Facility Agency will be providing up to 45 per cent of
the project financing in Janamanjung to finance the foreign portion
of the project.
	   Sources said while the Government wants the project to have
foreign direct investment, Tenaga views it as a lost in earnings if
the project is given to a foreign party.
	   ``The exercise will benefit Tenaga as it is able to lift the
financing off its books and consolidate it in a single account in
Malakoff.
	   ``At the same time, it is able to generate earnings from
Janamanjung and convert a future earning stream into immediate
earning through its stake in Malakoff.
	   ``Unlike Tenaga which has the Government as its majority
shareholder, Malakoff is much freer to make decisions.
	   ``The presence of National Power Plc in Malakoff is positive as
the foreign partner is able to inject funds at the project level or
take an active role in the project itself,'' the source said.
	   The source added that foreign direct investment in Janamanjung
is also possible to finance the project.
	   However, the combination of Tenaga, MRCB and National Power will
make it easier for the company to seek foreign funding.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
