<HEADLINE>
Hotel bids for revival of Pattaya for family holidays, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Hotel bids for revival of Pattaya for family holidays, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   KENNETH YWINASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   FOR Mercure Hotel Pattaya Resort, being alone does not mean
lying down and going to sleep on the beach.
	   Don't let the signboard fool you as you look at it from the main
Sukhumvit Road leading a few kilometres to Pattaya.
	   Mercure Hotel is indeed set along the beach, among 25 rai of
lush tropical gardens, a four-star resort focusing on vacations for
the entire family.
	   ''I strongly believe that Pattaya, despite its notoriety, can
still be a vacation destination for families. Here, is where we can
offer luxury, privacy, leisure and tranquility to unwind from the
hustle and bustle of city life,'' said Herbert Williams, general
manager with 17 years of experience under his belt.
	   Just two-years-old, Mercure Pattaya Resort has gained a
reputation for offering a get-away setting for both leisure and
business needs.
	   ''Besides our 540 rooms and three presidential suites, we have
52 self-contained executive apartments [from Bt45,000 to Bt95,000
ranging from 70 square metres to 140 square metres in size] for
long-staying corporate guests working in the Eastern Seaboard,''
said Williams, a Bombay-born graduate from Castle Klessheim in
Slazburg, Austria. The apartments are from the 16th to the 23rd
floor.
	   Williams, who replaced John Gardner (now in Indonesia), has been
here for around four months and is strongly convinced that Pattaya
can compete with Phuket. ''If Phuket is a 100-per-cent family
destination, then Pattaya can be 80 per cent.'' He points to mass
tourism as the solution to filling up Pattaya and said that ''only
time will tell''.
	   As part of the ''Amazing Thailand'' campaign, Williams perceives
that Pattaya has picked up in terms of tourist arrivals. ''We too
have benefitted from the campaign.'' If Pattaya segregates its
areas for different activities, Williams, with work stints in
Zurich, the Philippines, Jakarta, Jamaica, Taiwan and China, notes
that Mercure Pattaya Resort can be part of the family-oriented
area. Mercure Pattaya Resort has the facilities for families from a
fully-equipped fitness centre, swimming pool and outdoor jacuzzi,
mini-golf and golf driving range, indoor board games, squash and
tennis courts, snooker tables and saunas.
	   ''We provide free shuttle services on the hour into Pattaya
city. For parties and business conferences, up to 1,000 people can
be accommodated in our ballroom.'' The 'Arabian Nights' theme party
going on at the poolside is just one of the many that have included
'Russian Nights' and 'Indian Nights'.
	   Williams admits re-engineering had been done some time back to
cope with the economic downturn and expenses were trimmed last
year. ''Our exchange rate benchmark with foreign tour operators has
been around Bt45 and this will keep both parties happy.'' Although
a newcomer, Williams perspective of Pattaya does echo some old-time
managers' in Pattaya: ''Before Pattaya was relatively known for its
night life. With top brands like Delaney's, Ripley's and Central
coming in, the city has pitched more for families and 30 per cent
of the tourists over the weekends here are Thais.'' If you talk
family, then there must be a ''Kiddies Fun Centre'' where cartoon
videos and freebies are provided. ''We have that,'' Williams
smiled.
	   Despite the stiff competition in the initials years, Williams
now claims a 70 to 80 per cent occupancy rate. ''More Russian and
Taiwanese tour groups.'' During the low season, 65 per cent, he
said. ''Most of our guests are from Asia, 70 per cent, and the rest
from Europe. The Arabs are coming back.'' He is happy with the
local government for cleaning up the environs and cites the Bt1.86
billion water treatment plant which will be operation in June next
year for Chonburi, Naklua, Pattaya and Jomtien.
	   
</TEXT>
