<HEADLINE>
DPM: Govt mulls incentives to boost unit trust sector, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
DPM: Govt mulls incentives to boost unit trust sector, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Kamarul YunusASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Government will look into the possibility of providing tax
reduction or exemption as well as other incentives to unit trust
holders and funds to boost the industry.
	   Deputy Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim said the
Government has to continue to implement measures to safeguard the
interest of unit trust holders in view of the long-term benefit
derived from such an industry.
	   ``Besides being able to collect funds from all segments of the
community, the unit trust industry helps to ensure a fair and just
society,'' he said at the Federation of Malaysian Unit Trust Fund
Managers' (FMUTM) second annual general meeting in Kuala Lumpur
yesterday.
	   Anwar, who is also Finance Minister, was responding to FMUTM's
suggestion that the Government, particularly the Finance Ministry,
provide incentives to boost the industry.
	   Earlier in his speech, FMUTM president Abdul Azim Mohd Zabidi
said the federation had submitted a proposal to the Finance
Ministry to consider providing incentives such as tax exemption on
long-term savings in unit trusts, pension funds's investment in the
unit trusts and on unit trusts' earnings.
	   Anwar also reiterated that the Government will take the
necessary measures to revive and strengthen the economy.
	   ``We will have to continue to undertake the necessary financial
reform measures.
	   ``In admitting the truth, we can no longer afford to deny the
shortcomings ... there is a need to assert governance associated
with policy and implementation, including lack of transparency and
its related thought.
	   ``Corporations, too, can suffer from poor health due to their
lack of fairness, responsibility and transparency,'' he said,
adding that there should not be any compromise on the need to
ensure professionalism and strengthen the management of the unit
trusts.
	   In this regard, Anwar praised the FMUTM for making the efforts
to improve the level of professionalism through its various courses
and programmes.
	   ``With constant and healthy progress of the unit trust industry,
this will mobilise the growth of the capital market,'' he added.
	   On the overall unit trust performance, Anwar said, it is still
considered below expectation, adding that there is still room for
improvement.
	   ``As at March 31 this year, the unit trust industry was valued
at RM43 billion, which accounts for 9.5 per cent of the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange's market capitalisation.
	   ``This is considered low. Although we have vast experience such
as through Permodalan Nasional Bhd and state unit trusts, our
performance is still below par compared to those in Thailand and
India,'' he added.
	   The unit trust industry in Thailand and India was valued at 15
per cent and 25 per cent of the market capitalisation respectively.
	   ``The statistics surprise me because we have been conducting
intensive campaigns to promote the industry and ensure effective
unit trust management,'' Anwar said.
	   Anwar also said the move to impose a freeze on
Government-sponsored trust funds from December 10 last year was to
ensure the existing unit trusts can manage their funds effectively
and efficiently.
	   ``This is to enable them to strengthen their positions and
enhance their performance,'' he said.
	   In spite of the present downward performance of the local unit
trust industry, Anwar said, this is the opportune time for
Malaysians to buy the undervalued unit trusts for the long-term.
	   ``Since the middle of last year, the prices of the units,
including the eight state-sponsored ones, have fallen below RM1 a
unit,'' he said.
	   As an example, he cited Amanah Saham Sabah. The unit was valued
at RM1.38 on July 31 last year but now it is worth only 28 sen.
	   
</TEXT>
