<HEADLINE>
Jaya Jusco sees RM40m profits despite downturn, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Jaya Jusco sees RM40m profits despite downturn, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   T.L. KhooASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   RETAILER Jaya Jusco Stores Bhd is confident of returning to the
black by achieving a net profit of about RM40 million this year
despite registering a loss after tax of RM14.44 million for the
year ended Feb 28, 1998.
	   The loss has been attributed to unrealised foreign exchange
losses of RM48.5 million from the company's offshore loans.
	   ``We have taken care of it (the loss) and if the ringgit
stabilises against the US dollar, we can expect to make some profit
this year,'' said chairman Datuk Abdullah Mohd Yusof.
	   The loans were to finance Jaya Jusco Stores' plan to set up more
retail outlets.
	   Managing director Masaaki Toyoshima said the company would
embark on a new strategy known as the Neighbourhood Shopping Centre
in anticipation of a difficult year ahead in the retail industry
and weakened consumer spending power.
	   ``The NSCs will be located in suburban centres away from city
centres.
	   Ten locations have been identified within the Klang Valley and
Johor Baru vicinity,'' said Toyoshima.
	   ``We expect a turnover of RM30 million and an investment of
about RM15 million for each store.''
	   When asked why the company continued to expand despite a
downturn in the retail industry, Toyoshima said: ``We are in a good
position to do so and the downturn does not affect us because we
are not selling speciality merchandise.''
	   The expansion will be funded through internally generated funds
to reduce the gearing ratio of the company which stands at between
0.51 and 0.73.
	   Currently its outstanding debts stand at about US$42.16 million
(RM168.64 million).
	   Toyoshima said the company's overall first quarter peformance
this year (March to May) improved by 4.9 per cent from the same
period last year.
	   Besides the NSCs, Jaya Jusco Stores will embark on ``we
identify, we design, we lease and you build'' concept to reduce
investment expenditure.
	   This concept, according to Abdullah, was used successfully for
the One Utama store in Petaling Jaya where its only expenditure
consisted of fitting out the store at a cost of RM30 million.
	   Currently, the company has six stores in Taman Maluri, Wangsa
Maju, Bukit Raja in Klang, Bandar Utama, Malacca and Ipoh.
	   There are also new stores in the making located in the Mid
Valley Mega Mall in Kuala Lumpur which is expected to be completed
by October next year, and in Penang and Johor Baru.
	   However, the opening of its stores in Bayan World Megamall in
Penang and Seri Alam Shopping Centre in Johor will be delayed by
one to two years due to a delay in the development.
	   The company will expand its Malacca and Taman Maluri stores into
new shopping centres by December and March 2000 respectively.
	   Jaya Jusco Stores is part of the AEON Group based in Japan.
	   The company registered a turnover of RM692.5 million for the
year ended Feb 28, 1998 - a 14.8 per cent rise over last year's
results. Operating profit also increased by 23 per cent to RM54.4
million while profit before tax fell 86.3 per cent to RM6.1
million.
	   
</TEXT>
