<SLUG> RATES-FOR-REFRIGERATED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rates for refrigerated cargo to Asia on carriers under WTSA to increase on July 15, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Rates for refrigerated cargo to Asia on carriers under WTSA to increase on July 15, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   EFFECTIVE July 15, rates for all refrigerated shipments to Asia
on carriers under the Westbound Transpacific Stabilisation
Agreement (WTSA) will be increased by US$150 (US$1  &QC;  RM3.94) per
FEU (40-foot equivalent units). Subsequent increases will follow
suit effective October 1 1998 (US$200 per FEU), and January 1 1999
(US$200 per FEU).
	   These increases, according to the WTSA chief executives who met
in Seoul recently, will be cumulative in effect for a total of
US$550 per FEU on refrigerated commodities.
	   Exceptions to the scheduled three-stage increase are beef and
pork from all origin points and poultry shipped via US East Coast
ports. These cargoes will see increases of US$350 per FEU on
October 1 1998 and US$200 on January 1 1999.
	   The increase is part of plans adopted by the 13 container
shipping lines to stabilise current rate levels and partially
recover a portion of lost revenues following declining cargo and
plummeting freight rates from the US to Asia in recent months.
	   The 13 major carriers in WTSA had reported an overall drop in
freight charges ranging from US$600 to US$800 per FEUs (40-foot
equivalent units) for both ``dry'' and high-value, time-sensitive
refrigerated cargoes, since the beginning of 1998. The WTSA chief
executives agreed on the need for a series of rate adjustments
through this and early next year, aimed at partially restoring rate
levels for refrigerated commodities.
	   WTSA, in a statement released in Kuala Lumpur yesterday, said
members also approved procedural steps aimed at stabilising and
improving revenues for dry cargos not exempted from tariff filing,
much of which now move under individual service contracts.
	   Members committed to developing a restoration programme that
would raise overall non-exempt dry cargo levels by US$250 per FEU
effective September 1 1998.
	   One exception, hay - which has seen rates cut by more than half
last year - will see a rate plan put in place effective July 15,
with the lowest rates from the from the US West Coast to Japan
ranging from about US$890 to US$965 and more uniform rules covering
charges associated with trucking, storage, container cleaning and
other practices specific to the carriage of hay.
	   For destinations other than Japan, hay rates be increased by
US$250, effective July 15. ``A strong dollar, tight credit and
pressures to export in Asia have led to a serious trade and cargo
imbalance in this large and complex market,'' WTSA executive
director Albert A. Pierce said.
	   ``The economies of positioning containers in Asia, recovering
high equipment and handling costs for refrigerated shipments, and
meeting total voyage costs, all make a rate restoration effort
essential, especially when cargo volumes are down. It makes no
sense for carriers to chase a larger share of a shrinking market
through discounting, when fixed costs are so high and service
demands are increasing,'' he said.
	   WTSA members are American President Lines Ltd, China Ocean
Shipping Co, Evergreen Marine Corp, Hanjin Shipping Co Ltd,
Hapag-Lloyd Container Line GmbH, Hyundai Merchant Marine (America)
Ltd, Kawasaki Kaisha (K Line) Ltd, Maersk Line, Mitsui O S K Lines
Ltd, Nippon Yusen Kaisha Ltd (NYK Line), Orient Overseas Container
Line Inc, P &AMP; O Nedlloyd B V Ltd and Sea-Land Service Inc.
	   
</TEXT>
