<HEADLINE>
PTT, GSB set to acquire National Fertiliser shares, NATION
</HEADLINE>
PTT, GSB set to acquire National Fertiliser shares, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   WATCHARAPONG THONGRUNGASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Petroleum Authority of Thailand and the Government Savings
Bank have confirmed that they will fully subscribe to the new
capital-increase shares to be issued by National Fertiliser Plc,
NFC vice president Trakul Chatdarong said Tuesday.
	   NFC announced Tuesday its plans to increase its registered
capital to Bt5 billion from Bt4 billion by issuing 100 million new
shares to existing shareholders at Bt5 apiece. Par value is Bt10
per share.
	   The Bt500-million capital increase plan is expected to lead into
a change in the shareholding structure of NFC since major
shareholders are expected to increase their stake in the firm,
against minority shareholders.
	   On the local stock market, NFC shares closed at Bt3 apiece on
Monday, down Bt0.10 from Friday.
	   According to Trakul, the five largest shareholders of NFC, who
hold a combined 65-per cent stake, are expected to participate in
the capital increase and maintain their holding ratio in the
company.
	   The top two NFC shareholders, the PTT and GSB, have provided
letters confirming their intention to subscribe to the new shares
and are even ready to increase their proportional holding in NFC if
other shareholders decide to dilute their holding, the NFC vice
president said.
	   Existing shareholders will be offered the chance to exercise
their right to subscribe to the capital-increase shares under the
ratio of four old shares per one new share. NFC will seek approval
at a shareholders meeting to be held on June 23.
	   Thammasek, a Singaporean investment firm, has also confirmed
through NFC's adviser Capital Nomura Securities Plc that it would
like to purchase NFC stock, but NFC prefers to wait and see the
results of the capital-increase programme before considering the
possibility of share sales to the Singaporean firm, Trakul said.
	   ''Others said they would rather see NFC remain a Thai-owned
company'', he explained.
	   NFC is 22.5-per-cent owned by PTT, 13.5-per-cent each by GSB and
Industrial Finance Corp of Thailand, nine-per-cent by the Crown
Property Bureau and 7.3-per-cent by the Finance Ministry.
	   As of June 3 NFC has about 3,000 shareholders. NFC shareholders
will have to pay for the new shares during a four-day period
beginning on July 20.
	   For the first quarter of 1998 NFC reported a net profit of
Bt1.77 billion, or Bt4.42 per share, including a foreign-exchange
gain of Bt2.2 billion. The company operates a
one-million-tonne-per-annum chemical-fertiliser factory in Map Ta
Phut Industrial Estate.
	   
</TEXT>
