<SLUG> DIGITAL-BOON-TO-AMATEUR sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Digital boon to amateur photography, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Digital boon to amateur photography, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   FUJI Photo (Malaysia) Sdn Bhd yesterday unveiled the latest
Fujifilm digital camera, the MX-700, taking amateur photography to
new heights with its 1.5 million pixel resolution for better
picture sharpness.
	   Set to capture 12 per cent of the local digital camera market,
Fuji has forecast RM13 million in sales this year for the camera
which is retailed at RM3,400 each.
	   The first Fujifilm digital camera was introduced in Malaysia in
1996.
	   Unlike it's older brother the DS-7 and other digital camera for
amateurs which only has a resolution of about 300,000 pixels, the
MX-700's pixel 1.5 million is set to revolutionise amateur
photography.
	   (A pixel is the small dots that make up a picture. The smaller
it is, the finer the picture).
	   At a Press conference to unveil the camera at Fuji Photo's
office in Kuala Lumpur, managing director Hiroatsu Machida said the
new camera was also the most compact of its kind available in the
market and would lead a new batch of digital equipment that allows
amateurs to take professional- level pictures.
	   This is because apart from the digital camera's ability to
produce pictures as shown on the small screen on it, users can also
make on-the- spot alterations to the colours even while focusing on
an object.
	   Conventional cameras, while still the popular choice due to its
huge consumer base, has the problem of the need to get proper
lighting and other factors.
	   Amateurs tend to end up with less than desirable results as a
picture might not be like what they saw through the lenses.
	   Still, the digital camera's average resolution of around 300,000
pixels leaves a lot to be desired compared to the conventional
one's picture grains that is equivalent six million pixels.
	   Thus the MX-700 high resolution is welcomed as it is learned
that previously the highest available resolution for digital camera
is 1.4 million pixels and even then it was made and priced for
professional photographers.
	   However, Machida said, this resolution gap between digital and
conventional would be closed in a few years although digital
cameras would not wipe out conventional ones. They would instead
complement it and expand the scope of photography.
	   ``What it offers is more possibilites for more people,'' he
said.
	   
</TEXT>
