<BODY>
<SLUG> SUBSTANTIAL-COMITMENTS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Substantial commitments made by KL to liberalise sector, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Substantial commitments made by KL to liberalise sector, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Fadzil GhazaliASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MALAYSIA has so far made substantial commitments to liberalise
the shipping industry under the General Agreement on Trade in
Services (GATS), according to a World Trade Organisation (WTO)
official.
	   WTO Trade in Services Division legal officer Pierre Latrille
said the country had joined the other 38 nations offering partial
commitments under GATS to liberalise the shipping and maritime
sector.
	   In his paper entitled ``Maritime Industry: Meeting New and
Changing Demand Conditions'' presented at a seminar in Subang Jaya
yesterday, he said Malaysia offers commitments of passenger
transportation, freight transportation, and supporting services for
maritime transport.
	   Latrille said in view of the slow progress of the liberalisation
in this sector, what Malaysia did can be considered as significant
and would yield benefits for the country.
	   There had been up to now two stages in negotiations under GATS.
One which was not distinct from the general negotiations on
services at the end of the Uruguay Round (1990-1993), and a second
one specifically related to maritime in 1995-1996.
	   Latrille said the first negotiation failed for various reasons.
The first of those of reasons had been the general reluctance of
the shipping profession towards GATS system.
	   The second reason was the specific position of the US in
shipping, making it reluctant to alter its existing maritime policy
that relies on a strong anti-trust system designed to favour small
shippers.
	   Latrilles said in the second round of negotiation in 1995-1996,
there was no real progress in the efforts to liberalise the
maritime sector other than mere technical progress, where new
jargons were introduced.
	   ``Without any possibility of linkage or trade, there was nothing
attractive enough to induce the US to make an offer. The US has
therefore used the argument that the critical mass, notably in
South-East Asia, Latin America and Africa, was not there,'' he
added.
	   He said those countries in turn did not feel the the need to
make substantial offers as they perfectly knew that the US, a major
actor, would not deliver in the end, which amounted to a very
unbalanced overall final package.
	   The European Union, entrenched in its classical tactical game
with the US, could not for political reasons maintain its offer in
the end, and wanted to keep ammunition for future debates on
audiovisual.
	   Latrille said the result was that only countries with genuine
interest in liberalising shipping or that for general policy
reasons wanted to advance liberalisation committed themselves in
the end.
	   Only a few new commitments were taken at this occasion -
modification of pre-existing commitments for Canada and Malaysia -
adding themselves to the 30 commitments taken at the end of the
Uruguay Round in 1993.
	   Latrille said for the Malaysian shipping industry the
provisional results of these negotiations is two-fold.
	   On the one hand, this industry will enjoy the legal stability
and the national treatment and the most-favoured-nation treatment
granted by the commitments taken by the 39 countries that have made
the commitments.
	   On the other hand, Malaysia shipping industry will have to face
the potential competition of the foreign providers that Malaysia
has allowed by its own commitments as a price for getting
commitments from the other members of WTO.
	   Shipping is a service. It is covered since 1995 by the WTO
disciplines known under the name of the GATS.
	   The concept of liberalising trade in services was introduced
during the preparation of the Uruguay Round in 1982, and discussed
during the Round itself between 1986 and 1993.
	   The result of these discussions was GATS, largely inspired by
the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) that had been so
successful in dismantling Customs duties and more generally
barriers to trade in goods, but adapted to the specificity of
services.
	   The core principles of GATS are universal coverage, shipping,
most favoured nation (MFN) clause, the transparency, market access
and national treatment when the sector is offered, irreversibility,
the submission to WTO dispute settlement procedures and the
progressive liberalisation.
	   
</TEXT>
