<HEADLINE>
Creditors to vote on Westmont's future, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Creditors to vote on Westmont's future, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Mona Fairuz NordinASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   WESTMONT Industries Bhd's creditors will decide on Aug 29
whether to allow the company to proceed with its proposed rescue
scheme under Section 176 of the Companies Act 1965.
	   ``The High Court has set the date (Aug 29) for the creditors to
vote (on the proposal),'' director Datuk Jaffar Indot told a Press
conference at Petaling Jaya, Selangor yesterday.
	   The proposal is to provide the group with the financial ability
to enable it to continue its operations on a going-concern basis
and, in the long term, to regain profitability.
	   The High Court had earlier granted a Restraining Order applied
for by Westmont Industries to allow the company to proceed with its
rescue scheme.
	   The exercise has several major components - including a proposed
capital reduction in which 33 sen will be cancelled for each
Westmont Industries RM1 share.
	   Then, three shares - now worth 67 each - will be consolidated
into two RM1 shares - with the final result seeing the reduction of
accumulated losses by RM77.67 million.
	   The capital restructuring will reduce Westmont Industries issued
capital from RM233.2 million to RM155.4 million.
	   This proposal will be followed by a proposed restricted issue of
new shares to the major shareholder, Swascojuta Sdn Bhd, to raise
about RM61.15 million.
	   Following the restructuring, Swascojuta would hold directly and
indirectly 21.8 per cent of Westmont Industries' revised capital,
compared to 16.5 per cent currently.
	   As at Dec 31, 1997, both Westmont Industries and wholly-owned
subsidiary Sabah Shipyard Sdn Bhd owed (to debenture holders,
partially secured creditors and unsecured creditors) RM66.49
million and RM907.3 million respectively.
	   The rescue exercise could be conducted by Westmont Industries if
it gets the approval of creditors - by 75 per cent in value of
debts and 50 per cent in number of each of the classes of creditors
affected.
	   Meanwhile, chairman and substantial shareholder of Swascojuta
Datuk Md Desa Pachi said the company had completed preliminary
meetings with all classes of creditors.
	   ``The thrust of our meetings has been to convince our creditors
that Westmont Industries' value is more than the sum of its parts,
and that its business has tremendous potential.
	   ``Liquidation of Westmont Industries is not a viable alternative
as most creditors would not receive full payment while
shareholders' investment in the company would likely be rendered
valueless.''
	   The response from creditors was encouraging as it remained the
best alternative for restoring the long-term viability of Westmont
Industries and Sabah Shipyard.
	   ``We are hopeful for a quick resolution and approvals from the
various authorities,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
