<SLUG> RINGGIT-CLOSES-AT-3.95 sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ringgit closes at 3.95 against US dollar, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Ringgit closes at 3.95 against US dollar, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Adeline OngASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE ringgit closed stronger yesterday at 3.9500/600 against the
US dollar compared with Monday's close at 4.0000/100.
	   Dealers said the ringgit was traded at a high of 3.9350 and a
low of 4.0150 and activities on currency could be mostly attributed
to regional sentiments.
	   ``News in the market was that US funds sold dollars, sold enough
to push the ringgit up. The ringgit moved some 600 points today,''
a dealer said yesterday.
	   Another dealer said the stronger ringgit yesterday was also due
to activities on the ringgit-Singapore dollar front.
	   ``Players are selling the Singapore dollar for the ringgit after
Singapore's Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong said that
Singapore's banks will no longer hide reserves and bad loans, will
open to foreign competition and have more liquidity.
	   ``There are indications that interest rates may be lowered in
Singapore and this has helped the ringgit strengthen a little,''
she said.
	   The ringgit closed mixed against other currencies. It ended a
stronger 2.3086/185 against the Singapore dollar from Monday's
2.3349/428. It also ended firmer against the yen at 2.8132/213
against Monday's 2.8424/505.
	   Against sterling, it firmed to 6.4559/742 from Monday's
6.5170/354.
	   As for other regional currencies, it was reported that there was
hardly any trading interest offshore in the Indonesian rupiah,
which closed at 11,800 against the greenback, down from Monday's
close of 11,700.
	   The Taiwan dollar ended at an 11-year low of 34.715 against the
US dollar, down from 34.697 while the Philippine peso rose to 39.40
from 39.63, as did the South Korean won at 1,395 from 1,400.
	   On the securities front, markets across the region closed mixed.
The Kuala Lumpur Composite Index ended 7.85 points up to 505.64 but
on generally quiet trading.
	   
</TEXT>
