<BODY>
<SLUG> WE-HOPE-TO-CHART-COURSE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
We hope to chart new course, says group head, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
We hope to chart new course, says group head, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   WESTMONT Industries Bhd hopes to close its sad chapter of
financial difficulties and chart a new course for the group's
future, said chairman Datuk Md Desa Pachi.
	   ``Looking at our financial status as well as the current
economic climate, the management will have its hands full in the
months and years ahead.
	   ``Out task is to ensure that our existing operations remain
viable and efficient, while seeking solutions to turn around the
fortunes of the group,'' he told journalists yesterday.
	   He added that Westmont Industries' crown jewel and wholly-owned
subsidiary Sabah Shipyard Sdn Bhd had received several enquiries on
shipping-related jobs, but had to turn down the offer.
	   The company had to decline the jobs due to uncertainty about the
direction of the group in view of the pending court case.
	   The High Court had on Feb 4 granted a Restraining Order applied
for by the company to allow it to proceed with its rescue scheme
pursuant to Section 176 of the Companies Act 1965.
	   ``We knew that the state of affairs we inherited was gloomy, but
we needed to determine definitively the size of losses and debts.
We know it is not going to be an easy task,'' said Md Desa.
	   Westmont Industries registered a group operating loss of
RM108.641 million for the year ended Dec 31, 1997 against a group
pre-tax loss of RM664.79 million previously.
	   Md Desa was appointed to the board on April 24 last year
following the acquisition of 32.9 per cent stake in Westmont
Industries, through Swascojuta Sdn Bhd, from Promet Bhd.
	   He is the substantial shareholder of Swascojuta.
	   Promet has earlier purchased the 32.9 per cent stake in Westmont
Industries from Westmont Holdings Sdn Bhd, which is controlled by
businessman and politician Datuk Joseph Chong Chek Ah.
	   Meanwhile, Westmont Industries executive director Mohd Shafeii
Abdul Gaffoor said Sabah Shipyard's ship repair operation had
commenced since March and it was currently doing well.
	   ``(The business) is more than sufficient to cover our current
overhead costs,'' he said, adding that the company hoped to
re-enter the ship building activity in the medium term.
	   Sabah Shipyard is said to be one of the largest and best
shipyards and builders of power barges and structures for the
offshore oil and gas industry, not only in Malaysia, but also in
the region.
	   Strategically located in Labuan near the oil fields off Sabah
and Sarawak, Md Desa said it played a key support role for the
country's oil and gas industry with a strong record of past
achievements.
	   Last week, the company was awarded the HSE Management Safety
Performance Award by Petronas for meeting its safety targets for
the last three years.
	   
</TEXT>
