<SLUG> 296-PROJECTS-WITH sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
296 projects with foreign equity approved: Rafidah, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
296 projects with foreign equity approved: Rafidah, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Hamisah HamidASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE International Trade and Industry Ministry has approved 296
projects with foreign equity in the first four months of the year.
	   According to its minister Datuk Seri Rafidah Aziz, the ministry
had received 212 applications valued at RM4.027 billion during this
period.
	   Of the total, domestic applications amounted to RM1.823 billion
while foreign applications totalled RM2.204 billion, she said when
addressing a seminar organised by the Malaysian-Swedish Business
Association in Kuala Lumpur.
	   Last year, 759 projects worth RM25.821 million were approved. Of
the total, 462 were new approvals while 297 were for expansion and
diversification of existing operations.
	   Rafidah said despite the regional crisis, Malaysia is still an
attractive investment location for high value-added and
capital-intensive production.
	   Foreign investors also see Malaysia as a good country to
transfer technologies to.
	   ``They see Malaysia as a worthwhile place to carry out their
operations using state-of-the art processes,'' she said, adding
that some companies implement more advanced technology in Malaysia
than in their home country.
	   Some make Malaysia their regional base as they want to tap the
competitiveness that Malaysia offers, she added.
	   She said foreign investors' interest in Malaysia is evident by
the continuous investment in Malaysia.
	   Acknowledging that Malaysia has not been spared the shrinking
foreign direct investment (FDI), Rafidah said nonetheless the FDI
to Malaysia is still coming in.
	   Rafidah said that the Government is fine-tuning some policies
regarding foreign equity structure, incentives and costs.
	   In assessing Malaysia as an investment location, Rafidah said
foreign investors should look at the country's track record and see
beyond the current regional problems.
	   ``Most important is whether there is a market for the product or
services domestically, regionally or globally,'' she said.
	   In this context, investors will have to look at Malaysia's
competitiveness.
	   Rafidah said Malaysia is no longer competitive in
labour-intensive industries but is attractive for industries with
capital investment per employee ratio.
	   She said under the second Industrial Master Plan (1996-2005),
the Government identified 22 sub-sectors of industries where
Malaysia can serve as competitive production base.
	   ``The major elements are skills, capital and
technology-intensive manufacturing that can move the manufacturing
value-chain to a higher plane.
	   
</TEXT>
