<BODY>
<SLUG> PROMET-HAS-NOTHING-HIDE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Promet has nothing to hide, says chairman, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Promet has nothing to hide, says chairman, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PROMET Bhd, which held its annual meeting yesterday after some
delay pending the finalisation of its accounts, said it had nothing
to hide.
	   Chairman Tan Sri Mohamed Ngah Said said an explanation had been
given to the shareholders and they were satisfied with it.
	   President and chief executive officer Datuk Soh Chee Wen did not
attend the meeting which lasted for over an hour.
	   Promet reported a group pre-tax loss of RM169.69 million for the
16- month period ended April 30, 1997. For the year ended Dec 31,
1995, it recorded a group pre-tax profit of RM17.14 million.
	   Turnover was at RM250.98 million during the 16-month period
while for the 12-month period it was at RM292.27 million.
	   Promet's principal activities are steel fabrication, marine
engineering and construction, civil engineering and construction,
property investment and development, and development of
infrastructure projects.
	   In Promet's latest annual report, its auditor, Ernst &AMP; Young,
listed discrepancies in the group's accounts and lack of certain
information. It was unable to form an opinion as to whether the
accounts were properly drawn up in accordance with the Companies
Act 1965.
	   It was unable to give a true and fair view of the state of
affairs of the company and of the group as at April 30, 1997; of
the results of the company and of the group; and, of cash flows of
the group for the same period.
	   The auditor was also unable to say whether the accounting and
other records have been properly kept.
	   When asked about a request by the Securities Commission for
Promet to provide an explanation for the discrepancy in its
accounts, Mohamed said an explanation had been given.
	   ``We are not hiding anything but we don't want to tell
everything to the world. There are some things that should be kept
within certain circles,''
	   he said.
	   ``We have explained (to the shareholders) why it is reported
that way.
	   The impression (of the report) is vague but if you look from the
inside point of view, you will get a different meaning.''
	   However, he declined to disclose what was told to the
shareholders earlier, saying that they were happy with the board's
explanation.
	   As for the group's pre-tax loss amounting to RM169.69 million,
Mohamed asked: ``Which company isn't losing today?''
	   
</TEXT>
