WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SIAM Commercial Bank's wholly-owned subsidiary SCB Real Estate
has taken over two plots of land from Sansiri Plc in an effort to
help its developer clients who cannot repay their loans.
	   Sansiri reported to the Stock Exchange of Thailand Tuesday that
its board of directors has approved the restructuring of Bt225.9
million it owes to Siam Commercial Bank.
	   In Sansiri's report, the two plots of land are in Soi Sala Daeng
and the Bangrak area and will be transferred to SCB Real Estate.
Along with the land, the Bt187 million worth of debts will also be
shifted from SCB to the bank's property subsidiary.
	   The takeover follows that of Somprasong's assets, after the
property developer failed to repay loans and interest. SCB recently
established SCB Real Estate Co Ltd to take over the assets, as a
means to reduce its bad debts and loan provisioning requirement.
	   SCB Real Estate is a 100 per cent-owned subsidiary which will
help it restructure and manage some of its loans to the property
sector. The company will take over the incomplete assets and
complete them. After the properties are on sale, the bank will give
the difference to the developer. If the sales raise less than the
amount required, the developer will pay the difference to the bank.
	   Sansiri said it will issue 2.9 million new shares at Bt10 apiece
and offer them to SCB via a private placement. The allocation of
the new capital shares is part of the company's financial
restructuring programme.
	   Analysts said land transfers are becoming an alternative for
property developers to restructure their debts.
	   Other than Sansiri, MK Real Estate Development Plc has also
restructured its debts by allowing its bondholders, who want
immediate redemptions, to exchange the bonds for company land.
	   Moreover, earlier this year, SCB agreed to absorb risks from its
debtors by taking over the incomplete projects of Somprasong Land
Plc.
	   In late March, SCB, a major creditor of Somprasong, entered into
an agreement with the property developer which states the bank will
take over three plots of Somprasong land. Under the agreement,
Pitcha Park project in Samphran district, Nakhon Pathom, will be
transferred to SCB Real Estate. Somprasong said it will also sell
the project's units and use the money to reduce its debt to SCB.
	   SCB is a major creditor of Somprasong which has been in severe
financial straits since early 1997 when it defaulted on bond
interest payments to both local and foreign investors worth over
US$80 million. Aside from the $80 million in convertible
debentures, the company's liabilities, which are not
collateralised, stood at Bt3.57 billion last April.
	   ''There will possibly be more property development companies to
follow the similar method in restructuring their debts because such
a method is well suited to the current economic situation in
negotiating with the creditors,'' an analyst of ABN AMRO Securities
(Asia) said.
	   However, such debt restructuring methods will need to be
accepted by both the creditors and debtors, he said.
	   ''For the large property development company that has many plots
of land for the creditors to pick, such a restructuring method will
possibly be successful. But for the small company, there are
several limitations,'' he said.
	   An investment banker in Bangkok said the trend of conversion of
debts to land will depend on the creditor side as well as the land
price evaluation method used.
	   An analyst of another brokerage house said if such a debt
restructuring method is successful, the debtor's liquidity position
would improve and the reserve burden on debts for financial
institutions would also be reduced.
	   Due to the huge loans to the property sector, SCB is now
struggling with rising non-performing loans (NPLs). Recently, the
bank announced it would raise its registered capital by Bt34.11
billion to Bt40 billion. The increase will mark the second time the
bank has raised its capital since the financial crisis erupted in
July.
	   In February, SBC Warburg Premiere Securities Co predicted the
bank's NPLs would peak at 34 per cent this year and that it would
need at least Bt200 billion in capital to deal with the problem.
	   
</TEXT>
