<HEADLINE>
Indulging in the novelty of testing products, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Indulging in the novelty of testing products, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Crabtree &AMP; Evelyn flagship store, which opened at the Suria
KLCC in Ampang last month, has a unique marketing feature that sets
its apart from its other stores in Asia - a sink in the middle of
the shop floor to facilitate product testing.
	   The sink is part of the activity counter located strategically
at the centre of the store.
	   Customers can indulge in the novelty of testing all products
including bath gels and massage oils, a tradition very much in
keeping with the company's philosophy.
	   ``We want people to try out our products, to see that they get
good value for their money. We have a large offering of products
and we want people to understand what we have to offer,'' sales and
marketing manager for Asia Pacific Frederic Puech told Business
Times.
	   ``We feel that it is good to put these products up on stage as
it enables a close inspection of the products,'' he said.
	   Customer service and shopping ease is not centred on product
sampling alone. Crabtree &AMP; Evelyn ensures that its staff are all
well-trained and are able to give their customers information and
assistance.
	   The flagship store at Suria KLCC is the second Crabtree &AMP; Evelyn
outlet to be opened in the country. The first opened for business
in December last year at Starhill centre at Jalan Bukit Bintang.
	   In all, said Puech, there are 62 stores in Asia and New Zealand.
	   Worldwide, it has more than 350 company-owned and licensed
stores.
	   Its target market is typically working women in their 20s and
30s who are into lifestyle products and home decoration, said Puech
adding that in Asia, the clientele is younger.
	   ``The product lines are less feminine and there are more unisex
lines,''
	   he said, adding that these make up 40 per cent of its products.
	   He said that the unisex lines also help to make male customers
feel more at ease in the store.
	   While he declined to talk of the investment in the country,
Puech said ``we are pleased with the business and remain confident
of the Malaysian market.''
	   Crabtree &AMP; Evelyn was founded in 1970 as a family-owned business
in Cambridge, Massachusetts. In mid-1996, it was purchased by Kuala
Lumpur Kepong Bhd, based in Ipoh.
	   Crabtree &AMP; Evelyn carries a range of food, fragrances,
toiletries and accessories. Its home fragrance products include
potpourris, candles, environmental oils and room sprays.
	   Its fine foods include teas, biscuits, preserves, marmalades and
condiments created from traditional recipes.
	   In conjunction with its opening at KLCC, during the months of
May and June, visitors to the store will be treated to food tasting
and aromatherapy hand massage.
	   
</TEXT>
