<HEADLINE>
PM: Malaysia keen on barter trading, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
PM: Malaysia keen on barter trading, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Government is no longer concerned about the fluctuation of
the ringgit against the US dollar because the country is more keen
to carry out barter trade, Prime Minister Datuk Seri Dr Mahathir
Mohamad said.
	   ``What we want to do is to get away from the (fluctuation) in
the value of the ringgit and this can be done easily by conducting
trade on a counter-trade basis or through practical bartering,'' he
said.
	   ``We are not very concerned any more,'' he said when asked
whether the Government was concerned about the ringgit's further
decline against the US yesterday morning when the local unit went
below the RM4 mark to RM4.15 against the dollar at one stage.
	   Responding to questions after inspecting the Kuala Lumpur
International Airport in Sepang yesterday, Dr Mahathir said the
ringgit went down to RM4.80 at one time, then recovered before it
declined again.
	   ``This is a play thing which we have no control of,'' he said,
adding the Government would be working out how much the country was
exporting and how much it was importing in terms of goods.
	   ``The value of goods does not appreciate or depreciate whether
the ringgit changes in value.''
	   Citing an example, he said a computer costing US$700 and a tonne
of palm oil costing the same would not change in value even if the
ringgit went up or down.
	   
</TEXT>
