<SLUG> CRISIS-EXPECTED-TO-FORCE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Crisis expected to force out new Vsat providers, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Crisis expected to force out new Vsat providers, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   USANEE MONGKOLPORNASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ONLY well-established companies offering Vsat services are
expected to survive the economic crisis while newcomers will find
it harder to compete and stay afloat, a Samart Telcom Plc (Samtel)
senior executive says.
	   Before the economic crisis, there were six firms providing the
satellite-based communication services. One has already closed down
earlier this year. Of the rest, three are veteran providers.
	   Col Ruangsub Kovindha, president of Samtel, said the current
situation has forced several companies to halt investment and
expansion while strivng to keep up with the competition.
	   Two veteran operators, Samtel and Jasmine International's Acumen
Co, have enjoyed a fixed revenue stream after it won a
controversial bid from the Telephone Organisation of Thailand to
install Vsat equipment.
	   The project is to increase the number of rural telephone
terminals across the nation.
	   Since the middle of last year, Samtel has earned about Bt40-50
million a month, Ruangsab said.
	   Another veteran Vsat operator, Compunet Co, a joint-venture of
Cable &AMP; Wireless and Thai individual shareholders, is pondering
whether it should rewrite its concession with the Post and
Telegraph Department.
	   Compunet earlier won the department's approval to introduce
voice and image communication services, enabling it to create a new
concession with the department, though it has to pay the department
a higher royalty fee.
	   However, the current economic recession has discouraged business
expansion and the department was informed to wait for a board of
directors meeting of Cable &AMP; Wireless. PTD's director-general
Sethaporn Cusripituck said Tuesday that he has yet to receive a
response.
	   ''Compunet has yet to inform us. However, we believe that Cable
&AMP; Wireless remains interested in business expansion,'' Sethaporn
said.
	   After the closure of U-Sat, a new Vsat operator earlier this
year, the other two newcomers, Siam Sat and World Sat, were said to
be in financial difficulties. Siam Sat has served Siam Commercial
Bank which helped set up the company while World Sat is backed by
Thai Farmers Bank and Bank of Ayudhaya. Compunet is partly held by
the executives of Bangkok Bank.
	   However, commercial banks are currently more cautious with
non-performing businesses and question remains over whether they
would continue to support the Vsat businesses.
	   Ruangsub said the Vsat market is radically changing due to the
financial crisis, forcing operators like Samart to seek more
customers in the non-finance and non-banking sectors which used to
be the mainstream customer base.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
