<BODY>
<SLUG> UPM-COURSE-A-BOON sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPM course a boon for teachers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
UPM course a boon for teachers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Kamalia AbdullahASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ELLAMAH Kuppan is a kindergarten teacher. But there are no
preschoolers in her kindergarten.
	   ``My students are teenagers but they are still learning
kindergarten lessons,'' she said.
	   Ellamah, 48, teaches the mentally and physically challenged at
the Selangor and Federal Territory Spastic Centre in Jalan Utara,
Petaling Jaya.
	   Apart from the basics of reading, she also teaches them art and
craft and holds story-telling sessions.
	   Ellamah has not always been a kindergarten teacher. She worked
as a physio-aid at the centre for 14 years but left the job when
she got married and went to Kelantan.
	   She then returned to the Federal capital and began her career as
a kindergarten teacher in Port Klang before coming back to the
spastic centre. She knows many of the teenagers from her previous
stint as a physio-aid.
	   M. Latah Devi is another teacher who is employed at a
kindergarten set up by United Plantation Berhad in Ulu Basir, Lower
Perak.
	   The kindergarten provided by the oil palm estate, Latah said,
was very good and well-equipped.
	   ``The children get a good meal which includes oats, eggs and a
multi- vitamin drink during the break,'' she said.
	   Latah and Ellamah were among 22 kindergarten teachers who
completed a certificate course at Universiti Putra Malaysia
recently.
	   UPM regularly conducts kindergarten courses during the school
holidays but it was the first time they held one specially for
members of the Educational, Welfare and Research Foundation
Malaysia (EWRF).
	   These EWRF teachers teach in kindergartens in plantations and
urban squatter areas.
	   EWRF honorary general-secretary Sumangala Pillai said the course
would not only help them to serve the children of the community
better but also provide for their own career advancement.
	   EWRF is a voluntary, non-political service-oriented organisation
whose objective is to improve the educational, social and economic
welfare of needy Malaysians.
	   ``I have been teaching for the past seven years and have also
attended earlier courses organised by EWRF,'' said Latah.
	   ``The course at UPM will help me to improve the way I teach.''
	   The course was structured in two parts, with 10 days for each
module.
	   The emphasis was on hands-on experience.
	   ``We stressed the need for a balanced education for the
children,'' said Dr Rohani Abdullah, a lecturer with the child
development research centre at UPM.
	   The training programme covered topics such as musical and
creative movements, multi-media and interactive techniques, and the
nutrition needs of young children.
	   ``There was a special lesson meant for teachers handling
disabled children which I found very helpful,'' said Ellamah.
	   ``There were a lot of practical activities. In one of these, we
role- played the children to enable us to think like them and to
see their needs.''
	   According to Sumangala, these kindergarten teachers earn between
RM250 and RM350 a month. Yet they were willing to pay the RM1,000
fee for the course.
	   Latah, Ellamah and their friends would have had to pay a lot
more if not for the New Zealand High Commission and EWRF.
	   The total cost of the package charged by UPM was in the region
of RM50,000. The New Zealand High Commission contributed a grant of
RM12,000.
	   The fees collected from the participants came up to about
RM20,000. The EWRF paid the rest.
	   ``EWRF helped to subsidise the course as the salary the
kindergarten teachers earn would have made it difficult for them to
pay the fee,'' said Sumungala.
	   As to be expected, the teachers were grateful to the New Zealand
High Commission and EWRF for the financial assistance.
	   What motivated the kindergarten teachers was not only the chance
to learn new teaching techniques from a recognised and established
tertiary institution like UPM but also the prospect of enhancing
their own professional and career development.
	   ``We also hope we would be allowed to enrol for the child
development diploma programme which UPM plans to introduce,'' said
Ellamah.
	   According to Dr Halimah Ahmad, dean of the faculty of human
ecology at UPM, kindergarten teachers would find the diploma
programme useful as kindergarten management will be part of the
course.
	   ``After completing the diploma course, they would have the
chance to branch into other areas such as child psychology at
degree level,'' she said.
	   UPM hopes to start the course by May next year once the Ministry
gives the approval.
	   ``At this juncture, the proposal to introduce a diploma course
on child development has been evaluated and we hope to present it
to the Senate soon. After that, we will have to get the Education
Ministry's approval.''
	   So for the moment, the diploma course remains a distant but
enticing dream for Ellamah, Latah and other kindergarten teachers.
	   
</TEXT>
