AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SOME small and medium-sized entrepreneurs (SMEs) are still
unaware of the funds and venture capitals granted by the Government
for them to involve themselves in the Multimedia Super Corridor
(MSC) project eventhough they are qualified for such facilities.
	   Entrepreneur Development Minister Datuk Mustapa Mohamed said
there is a great deal of ignorance and a lack of initiative among
these SMEs as to what is available and how to gain access for the
grants and venture capitals.
	   ``These are very basic information ... Without adequate funding
or access to the venture capitals, it is very difficult for SMEs to
move ahead in the area,'' he said in Kuala Lumpur when opening the
MSC Nationwide Conference 1998.
	   Mustapa said in the current economic situation, many
entrepreneurs complained against banks and financial institutions
for being very selective in approving loan applications.
	   ``Therefore, they (SMEs) need to find other alternatives,'' he
said, adding that he hoped to see more entrepreneurs take advantage
of the opportunities created by MSC.
	   ``MSC has given out some funds to support the growth of SMEs in
the multimedia industry. There are various opportunities provided
by the MSC which are outside the banking system,'' he said.
	   Mustapa said he would like to see that all the funding
opportunities are properly disseminated to those interested and
hoped that the Multimedia Development Corporation (MDC) will double
its effort in promoting these funds.
	   All this while, there is a misconception that MSC caters only
for the ``big boys'' - multinational companies and foreign
companies - that have joint-ventures with local companies.
	   ``With the notion dispelled, I hope it is now firmly established
among the SMEs that the MSC, in actual fact, is also meant for
small and medium- sized enterprises,'' he said.
	   Later in a press conference, MDC executive chairman Tan Sri Dr
Othman Yeop Abdullah said MDC has received about five applications
for the Multimedia Super Corridor Research and Development Grant
Scheme (MGS), which is directly administered by the company.
	   The MGS has allocated an initial sum of RM100 million under the
Seventh Malaysia Plan.
	   Other funds available to SMEs are the Fund for Small and
Medium-sized Industries (RM1 billion), Technology Acquisition Fund,
Commercialisation of Research and Development Fund, Industrial
Linkage Programme, Industrial Technical Assistance Fund (RM50
million), Mechanisation and Automation Scheme for SMEs, Soft Loan
Scheme for Quality Enhancement of SMEs, Technology Development
Programme, Skill Development Programme, Export Development
Programme, Infrastructure Development Programme and Financial
Packages for SMEs.
	   ``By the year 2000, we hope to spawn about 20 companies which
have been granted with MSC status, to become world class
companies,'' he said, adding that currently MDC has 40 companies in
the list.
	   Out of 218 applications so far, 142 companies have been granted
with the MSC status.
	   
</TEXT>
