<HEADLINE>
Analysts welcome proposal to raise cap, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Analysts welcome proposal to raise cap, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Lokman MansorASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   AN increase in the ceiling for foreign ownership in local
stockbroking companies to 70 per cent from 49 per cent now can help
local brokerages spring into the international arena and become
more efficient, analysts said.
	   They said while joint ventures between local stockbroking
companies (SBCs) and foreign companies thus far focused on
research, allowing foreign parties to get into the driver's seat of
the SBCs will see them taking an active role in the operational
aspect of the brokerages.
	   ``They will bring in foreign expertise and, to be honest, there
is room for improvement in the operations of local SBCs,'' one
analyst said.
	   He said while there are already SBCs that have alliances with
foreign companies, these are mostly to provide research on
Malaysian equities to the foreign partner and do not entail
complete technology transfer.
	   Securities Commission (SC) chairman Datuk Dr Mohd Munir Majid
said on Monday the SC has proposed a higher ceiling for foreign
ownership of local stockbroking firms, but the decision rests with
the Government.
	   Initially, foreign corporate ownership in local SBCs was limited
to not more than 30 per cent. In 1988 the cap was increased to 49
per cent.
	   Another analyst said what the authorities hope to see is capital
injection into the SBCs, which need fresh capital given the slide
in the local bourse and exacerbated by the tight liquidity
situation.
	   ``With foreign participation, the stockbroking industry will be
moved to another level of competitiveness. The foreign partners
will have their own captive clients so it will be more competitive
for local SBCs to get foreign clients,'' he added.
	   The analyst said the fact that foreign investors will be taking
up to 70 per cent equity in local SBCs indicates that they see the
current downturn as temporary until the local bourse springs up
again.
	   Another analyst also welcomed the proposal, and said he expects
keen interest as foreign investors have been waiting for a long
time to participate in the local stockbroking industry.
	   However, he questioned why it was not proposed or implemented
sooner, before share prices fell further on the local bourse. ``Now
we have no other choice but to accept foreign participation.''
	   He said the 70 per cent ceiling, while substantial, should not
be reduced as any further revisions will cause a loss of
confidence.
	   Similarly, additional regulations or restrictions need not be
imposed as foreign investors who take up the offer will be looking
to invest for the long-term.
	   ``We have enough regulations. What is more important is
enforcement. I think if we had provided better enforcement we would
not be in the present situation,'' he added.
	   The analyst said there is no need to make adjustments to
stockbroking regulations merely to please the foreign partners.
``If they want to come in, they must follow our rules.''
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
