<HEADLINE>
Ex-bank manager on modesty outrage charge, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Ex-bank manager on modesty outrage charge, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Mon. - An employee of Malayan Banking Berhad told
the magistrate's court today that the bank's former audit division
general manager Ahmad Fisal Abdul Rahman embraced her and
``brushed'' her right breast with his hand.
	   The 48-year-old woman said she struggled to free herself from
his embrace, and after managing to do so, she ran but fell and hurt
her nose and upper lip.
	   She was testifying at the trial of Ahmad Fisal, who is charged
with outraging her modesty by hugging her and touching her breast
in his former office on the 47th floor of Menara Maybank, Jalan Tun
Perak, about 8.55am on Aug 4 last year.
	   Ahmad Fisal, 51, is now Mayban Securities Sdn Bhd credit control
and business development division general manager.
	   Replying to a question from Deputy Public Prosecutor Fatnin
Yusof, the woman said when she fell and hurt herself Ahmad Fisal
came to her aid. She said he apologised but she scolded him by
saying: ``I told you not to play the fool''.
	   The woman said she related the incident to her husband who told
her to lodge a police report.
	   She said she told her husband that she would report the incident
to the bank's management for the matter to be investigated
internally as she had served the bank for 28 years.
	   She said subsequently the bank's industrial relations division
took statements from her and also promised to let her know the
outcome of their investigations.
	   However, she said, she lodged a police report as the bank's
management was taking far too long to investigate.
	   After lodging the report, she said, she decided to let the law
take its course.
	   Hearing before magistrate Ahmad Zaidi Zainal continues.
	   
