<HEADLINE>
Acid '98 meet to help draw up Customs guidelines, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Acid '98 meet to help draw up Customs guidelines, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Asiah BujangASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   RECOMMENDATIONS formulated at the Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation (Apec) Customs-Industry Dialogue (Acid '98) will be
translated into appropriate action, said Deputy Finance Minister
Datuk Wong See Wah yesterday.
	   This will take the form of disseminating inputs, views,
proposals and recommendations to both government and the business
sector.
	   ``They (the recommendations) will provide the Apec business
community with guidelines for Customs administration,'' he said at
the end of the two-day dialogue in Kuala Lumpur.
	   Wong said the resolutions and recommendations outlined at the
dialogue will be taken up at the Sub-Committee on Customs
Procedures (SCCP) meeting in Kuching this September.
	   Custom laws, regulations, administrative guidelines and
procedures should be available to the public promptly and easily,
he said.
	   The Apec forum, which will see the admisssion of three new
members this year, will work closely on enhancing cooperation in
addressing issues such as trade barriers affecting the business
sector.
	   Wong said the dialogue will also help to ensure openness and
transparency in trade dealings and make the Customs and the
business sector more accountable.
	   The inclusion of Peru, Russia and Vietnam in Apec will bring the
total number of members to 21.
	   The dialogue was jointly organised by the Royal Customs and
Excise Department Malaysia and the National Chamber of Commerce and
Industry of Malaysia.
	   
