<BODY>
<SLUG> INCREASE-MONEY-SUPPLY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Govt urged to increase money supply, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Govt urged to increase money supply, NATION &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Thai government should fully guarantee risks incurred from
loans of state-run specialised financial institutions as a way of
increasing the money supply in the system.
	   A report released by Thai Farmers Research Centre (TFRC) said so
far the market has failed to work in an orderly manner due to the
liquidity crunch. New money should be injected into the system
through nationalised financial institutions such as the Export and
Import Bank of Thailand, Government Housing Bank and Government
Savings Bank.
	   Although such guarantees may increase the financial burden on
the national budget, the government should take this alternative
into serious consideration. If the liquidity crunch and high
interest rates continue, local companies are expected to fail due
to a lack of cash to run their businesses.
	   However, what the report suggested is quite different from what
the government intends to do as the exchange rates as well as price
stability are the top priorities for mending the economy.
	   The finance authorities, including Finance Minister Tarrin
Nimmanahaeminda and central bank governor MR Chatu Mongol Sonakul,
have ruled out increasing the money supply to allow interest rate
cuts in spite of the ongoing liquidity shortage.
	   They reasoned that such an increase will cause inflationary
pressure and further weaken the baht against the US dollar.
Moreover, foreign loans are expected to rise sharply in response to
the baht depreciation.
	   The TFRC made the suggestion because commercial banks are
reluctant to provide loans to the real sector, given that risks are
relatively high and their asset qualities may deteriorate further
due to the country's slumping economy.
	   The report said the Thai government should not have trouble with
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) if it decides to proceed with
increasing the money supply.
	   ''In the letters of intent submitted to the IMF, if necessary
the Thai government is given flexibility in managing the monetary
policy, including net domestic assets, net foreign assets and the
monetary base,'' it added.
	   Nevertheless, the TFRC urged the government to take caution if
it decides to increase the money supply in return for interest rate
reductions. The negative affects of such a move include an expected
depreciation of the baht against the greenback which would lead to
inflationary pressure, a rising foreign debt burden and foreign
capital outflows.
	   The report noted the baht should not weaken below 45 to the US
dollar, a level which would help reduce illiquidity and would not
harm the country as a whole.
	   If the government cannot maintain the baht at 45 to the
greenback, it would be forced to reintroduce a high interest rates
policy in defence of the baht, the report said.
	   ''Such a policy is likely as that will stop capital outflows as
well as reduce inflationary worries,'' the report added.
	   Under the current economic circumstances, the TFRC said the
government should adopt a prudent management policy which is in
line with the IMF's tough economic bail-out programme.
	   ''This will absolutely help boost investor confidence,'' it
said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
