<HEADLINE>
Arafat, Jordanian prime minister discuss Mideast peace process
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip (AP) _ Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
met with Jordan's prime minister Wednesday to discuss the stalled
Mideast peace process and prospects for an Arab summit on the
issue.
	   Peace talks between Israel and the Palestinians have been frozen
for over 15 months and Jordan, who has ties to both peoples, has
often tried to help the sides.
	   ``We have very strong relations with Jordan. I had a very
important talk with the prime minister and we discussed ... the
problems facing the peace process,'' Arafat told reporters after
the meeting at his Gaza headquarters.
	   Palestinians have been trying to drum up an Arab summit to serve
as a forum to voice dissatsifaction with Israel over its hadnlign
of the peace process. Arafat said that efforts to such a summit,
hampered by conflicting interests between several countries, were
still underway. ``We are trying to do our best with all the Arab
leaders and we are going to continue this,'' Arafat said.
	   Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul-Salam Majali said that Jordan
would not break ties with Israel, which it signed a peace treaty
with in 1994 but said that ``if the time came when we could show
that cutting ties would benefit the Arab world, we would do so.''
He did not elaborate.
	   Arafat also criticized a decision Tuesday by Israel to build
more houses for Jews in east Jerusalem, which Israel captured from
Jordan in the 1967 Mideast war and the Paleastinians want as a
capital for a future state.
	   ``It's a clear violation to what had been agreed upon, not one
single house (was) to be added to any of settlement,'' he said.
