<HEADLINE>
Loan repayments from former PSD scholars up 10-fold, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Loan repayments from former PSD scholars up 10-fold, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Adeline OngASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Public Services Department (PSD) is currently receiving
about RM1 million a month in repayments from former study-loan
borrowers compared with just RM100,000 before 1997.
	   Its deputy director-general Datuk Khalil Hussain said the
increase in the sum collected is due to the aggressive action taken
by the department.
	   ``The department sends about four to five reminders to former
borrowers.
	   Only when they don't take heed of the reminders do we bring the
matter up to the Attorney-General's Chamber,'' Khalil said.
	   He clarified that it was not up to the PSD to take former
borrowers to court but the Attorney-General's Chamber as the PSD
can only take administrative action whereas legal action will be
taken by the Chamber.
	   It was reported on Monday that the PSD has started bankruptcy
proceedings against 89 former government scholars who have not
repaid their loans or have defaulted on their contracts despite
repeated warnings.
	   Deputy Minister in the Prime Minister's Department Datuk Fauzi
Abdul Rahman on Monday said they were among 1,500 sponsored
students who had failed to respond despite being warned repeatedly
over the last 10 years.
	   ``The PSD is allocated some RM500 million for loans and
scholarships a year,'' Khalil said.
	   He added that the department is in the process of finalising the
number of loans and scholarships for this year's local university
students.
	   Traditionally, about 18,000 students a year benefit from PSD
loans and scholarships.
	   Khalil also said that this year's application deadline has been
extended from May 30 to June 16 because the students have started
their studies at the universities later.
	   It has also been reported that the PSD is expected to spend
about RM300 million on sponsoring students at local universities.
	   The department received some 60,000 applications last year and
about the same number this year.
	   Meanwhile, when asked about government servants who have applied
for optional retirement, Khalil said the economic downturn has not
directly affected the number of those applying.
	   However, he said that the Government stands by its decision to
pay an initial 10 per cent gratuity to civil servants who have
opted for optional retirement, and the balance only after the
country's economy has recovered.
	   It was reported the Government made the decision to pay a small
amount of the gratuity based on the consideration that those opting
for early retirement will have immediate need of money.
	   This is a revision of the Government's earlier decision that it
was only prepared to pay gratuity for optional retirees once they
have reached the age of 55.
	   Civil servants can exercise optional retirement at the age of
40, upon which they will receive a gratuity. Each civil servant
receives between RM20,000 and RM100,000 in gratuity depending on
the length and category of service.
	   The gratuity payment for optional retirees is said to cost the
Government some RM100 million annually.
	   The PSD receives between 2,000 and 3,000 applications for
optional retirement every year.
	   Statistics show the Government spends more than RM300 million in
gratuity payments annually and about RM2 billion in pensions. There
are currently more than 300,000 retired civil servants and 897,000
in service.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
