<HEADLINE>
Amanah Capital revamp, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Amanah Capital revamp, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   AMANAH Capital Malaysia Bhd, through a corporate exercise aimed
at consolidating and rationalising its business activities, is set
to emerge as an integrated investment banking group. In a
statement, Amanah Capital, formerly known as Kompleks Kewangan
Malaysia Bhd, said the move will enhance its presence in the
industry and prepare the group for the liberalisation of the
financial sector. The restructuring exercise will be headed by
Encik Mohd Hata Robani, the acting group chief executive officer in
place of Encik Azman Yahya, who is now heading Malaysia's newly
set-up asset management company, Pengurusan Danaharta Nasional Bhd.
The restructuring, which is pending approvals from the authorities,
involves the transfer of the group's financial services companies
to its listed arm, Amanah Capital Partners Bhd (formerly known as
South East Asia Development Corp Bhd). Upon completion, six core
operational divisions under Amanah Capital Partners will be
created. They are merchant banking, asset management, capital
market and securities, insurance, retail financial and property.
Amanah Capital will remain the group holding company with its
principal investment being the 68.1 per cent equity interest in the
enlarged listed Amanah Capital Partners.
	   
</TEXT>
