<HEADLINE>
`Don't fish in troubled waters,' opposition rep told, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
`Don't fish in troubled waters,' opposition rep told, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SOLE opposition State Assembly representative Chong Eng
(DAP-Batu Lanchang) was yesterday told not to ``fish in troubled
waters'' by raising the issue of the recent demolition of small
Hindu temples and shrines, including by the district offices.
	   State Health Committee chairman and Penang MIC chief Dr.K.
Rajapathy (BN-Prai) told Chong Eng she should not harp on it as it
could be counter productive to State Government's efforts to
enhance racial and religious harmony.
	   Replying to points raised during the motion of thanks to the
Yang diPertua Negeri Dr Rajapathy assured the House that the State
Government would implement a comprehensive plan to tackle
socio-economic problems of the Indian community.
	   ``While I appreciate the Batu Lanchang State Assemblywoman's
move to highlight the problems of Indians in the State, I disagree
that the State Government has done nothing concrete for them,'' he
said.
	   On Thursday and this morning, Chong Eng had questioned the State
Government's ``incompetency'' in resolving ``Indian problems'', in
preventing the Kampung Rawa communal skirmishes in March and the
recent demolition of, and notices to demolish issued against, Hindu
temples and shrines in the State by district offices.
	   On the question of malnutrition faced by Indian children in
estates raised by Tan Cheng Liang (BN-Jawi), Dr Rajapathy said his
committee had carried out various projects to provide nourishing
food to children and pregnant mothers.
	   To a question by Tan why the Sungai Bakap hospital took 10 days
to inform the family of the death of an accident victim recently,
Dr Rajapathy assured he would inform the House after investigation.
	   
</TEXT>
