<BODY>
<SLUG> MINISTRY-TO-PROBE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ministry to probe increase in rice prices, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Ministry to probe increase in rice prices, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Agriculture Ministry will investigate the cause of the
increase in rice prices if the indices indicate profiteering in the
industry.
	   Its minister, Datuk Amar Dr Sulaiman Daud said the ministry will
act after it receives reports on the matter from its Padi and Rice
Price Control and Monitoring Division and Padiberas Nasional Bhd
(Bernas).
	   ``When Deputy Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim announced
the price increase for padi last December, he specifically stated
that it would not increase the retail price of rice,'' he told
reporters after receiving a courtesy call from the Myanmar trade
delegation at his ministry yesterday.
	   If profiteering does exist, he said, the investigation will
cover all related parties including millers, wholesalers and
retailers.
	   He said the ministry has no plan to include Super grade rice as
a controlled item as this will affect the whole industry.
	   Currently, both retail prices for Premium and Standard grades of
rice are controlled by the Government. The price of Super grade
rice is not controlled but the Government has the right to fix its
grade specification.
	   Dr Sulaiman was earlier asked to comment on allegations by the
Federation of the Malaysia Consumer Associations (Fomca) that the
retail price of rice has increased due to Bernas selling imported
rice to its two subsidiaries, which in turn sells to consumers at a
higher price.
	   ``Bernas is not the only importer of rice in the country. Did
they check whether high prices are quoted at Bernas' outlets?'' he
said.
	   Asked whether Bernas should sell its rice directly to the
consumers, Dr Sulaiman said although the ministry encourages such
activity he doubts whether direct-selling is practical for Bernas.
He said Bernas has its own business plan and it will be quite
difficult to change the existing structure.
	   On the Myanmar trade delegation's visit, he said the discussions
involved several agricultural matters including joint efforts for
livestock and fisheries projects as the country hopes to increase
trade with Malaysia.
	   Representatives from the Myanmar trade delegation included the
country's Commerce Minister Major General Kyaw Than, Deputy
Agriculture and Irrigation Minister Brigadier General Khin Maung
and Deputy Livestock Breeding and Fisheries Minister U Aung Thein.
	   Dr Sulaiman, who visited Myanmar on April, said he had asked the
country to source rice for Malaysia.
	   Besides Myanmar, he said, Bernas has also been asked to look for
sources besides its suppliers like Thailand, Vietnam and Pakistan.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
