</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> ALL-KEEP-CITY-CLEAN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
All should keep city clean, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
All should keep city clean, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   CLEANLINESS is next to godliness. It is an axiom on good habits
first learnt and acquired at home. Parents teach the importance of
personal hygiene and keeping the home and the surroundings clean.
Later, these lessons are reinforced in school where pupils are
rostered to maintain the cleanliness of the classroom and the
corridors. These habits acquired early in life remain with us as we
move on to adulthood and establish homes for our families. We
ensure our living, eating, sleeping and bathing environments are
clean. We are particular in packing and disposing of household
waste.
	   But once we leave home, we appear to leave this virtue at the
front door or gate. In public, we evince the attitude that
cleanliness is the responsibility of others. Forgetting, worse
still disregarding, civic duties we dispose of drink cans, food
wrappings and containers any which way we please. The collective
consequence is litter everywhere. Add to this phenomenon, rubbish
that is discarded with little or no thought, and we have dirty
towns and cities. Repeated exhortations in the past, from the Prime
Minister down to other elected and appointed officials, have
prompted little or no response from the public to show more civic
responsibility. Litter and rubbish remain eye-sores, blemishes on
the image of the country. Even frequent complaints on this
unflattering facet of Malaysian life from otherwise impressed
tourists in letters to newspapers have done little to change this
common indifference to the cleanliness of streets and public
places.
	   Our indifference quotient will, however, be taxed soon. In two
months' time, one of the biggest sporting events in the
international calendar will be coming to town, to the capital city.
	   The 16th Commonwealth Games will bring more than 6,000 athletes
and officials as well as scores of thousands of foreign visitors.
Thus, not only the sporting facilities and the organisation of the
Games but also the capital city itself will come under the scrutiny
of foreign eyes before, during and after the Games.
	   Surely we, who have had our temparatures rising in the past over
reports by foreign scribes who associated Malaysia with the
Himalayas and, worse, that we still live up high in the trees,
would not like these thousands of guests returning home with the
image that Kuala Lumpur is a dirty city and by extension, its
inhabitants, unhygienic. They might even circulate exaggerated
reports that we live amid stinking sewers.
	   Clearly, if we do not desire such an eventuality, we should shed
our indifference to the cleanliness of the city. And as Datuk
Bandar Tan Sri Kamaruzzaman Shariff said on Sunday, keeping the
streets, parks and backlanes clean is not the sole responsibility
of City Hall and Alam Flora, ``residents have to a part to play''.
	   Thus, the public should stop littering. To root out this bad
habit, City Hall should impose the maximum fine of RM500, not just
the current RM300, on all who are caught. This should put the fear
of God into those inclined to throw cigarette stubs, drink cans and
food containers anywhere they choose. The authorities should be
serious about hauling polluters of drains and rivers to court. Only
then would the ``Care For Your Rivers and Drains'' campaign, which
City Hall will launch soon, would have any significance. Otherwise,
it might end the way of many past campaigns - much song and dance,
but no action.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:ALL-KEEP-CITY-CLEAN sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
