<HEADLINE>
MISC takes delivery of two more vessels, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
MISC takes delivery of two more vessels, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MALAYSIA International Shipping Corporation Bhd (MISC), a
Petronas-owned company, has taken delivery of two more vessels from
South Korean shipbuilders, bringing the number of ships built by
South Korean companies for MISC to 25.
	   MISC had to date awarded 39 shipbuilding contracts to South
Korean shipbuilders with total contract value of US$1.385 billion
(US$1  &QC;  RM3.94), Petronas said in a statement released in Kuala
Lumpur yesterday.
	   The delivery of the two container vessels, Bunga Raya Satu and
Bunga Teratai Dua, has increased MISC's fleet to 74 vessels with a
total tonnage of 2.76 million deadweight tonnes (dwt). Its fleet
comprises 26 container vessels, 18 bulk carriers, 13 chemical and
parcel tankers, 10 crude oil and product tankers, five Liquefied
Natural Gas tankers and two passenger ferries.
	   Bunga Raya Satu is a 2,700 TEU container carrier built by
Hyundai Heavy Industries Co Ltd. Since 1990, MISC has awarded 28
newbuilding contracts to Hyundai, of which 18 had been delivered
(including Bunga Raya Satu).
	   The remaining will be delivered in stages until the year 2000.
	   Bunga Teratai Dua is a 1,200-TEU container carrier built by
Daewoo Heavy Industries Ltd. It is the second of four container
vessels to be built by Daewoo for MISC, with the remaining two
scheduled for delivery in July and October this year.
	   Petronas said in addition to Hyundai and Daewoo, MISC had
awarded shipbuilding contracts to three other South Korean
shipbuilders namely Korea Shipbuilding and Engineering Corp (four
vessels), Hanjin Heavy Industries (two vessels) and Cheung Ku
Marine Industrial Co Ltd (one vessel).
	   MISC is due to take delivery another 17 newbuildings up to the
year 2000.
	   
</TEXT>
