<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IF last week's efferverscence over the recent French Open in
France and in Europe, Roland Garros - kept most people either
riveted to their TV sets or listening to reports on the champions'
ups and downs, this will soon be swept away by the World Cup
Football tournament scheduled to start tomorrow and end on July 12.
	   At Roland Garros, foreign broadcasters were asked to refer to
the French Open in memory of World War 1 aviator who died shortly
before the armistice, and who, incidentally, preferred rugby to
tennis.
	   This year was marked by the women's game, especially top heavy
talents, such as Anna Kournikova, Venus Williams, Martina Hingis,
but most stunning was Monica Seles's return to Paris where she won
her first Grand Slam title at the age of 16. She defeated the
Hingis who had won the last three Grand Slam singles titles.
	   An English daily commenting on Grand Slam events said: ``If
Wimbledon is a tennis garden-party, the French Open is a far
grander gastronomic experience. While Wimbledon offers a nod to the
proletariat in the form of first come, first served `people's
Sundays', the crowds that pack Paris Roland Garros for the French
Open are there as much for the sophisticated atmosphere and food as
for the clay tennis court.''
	   France, Paris in particular, are awash with preparations of all
sorts for the World Cup Football kick-off tomorrow. France has been
granted the privilege of hosting the event, one of the last grand
international celebrations of the 20th century.
	   The French Organising Committee, chaired by Michel Platini
Fernand Sastre and Jean Tiberi Mayor of Paris, will stage a major
kick-off event 24 hours before the official start of the
tournament, heralding 33 days packed with matches and celebrations
to get the adrenalin going.
	   ``La fete du football'' spectacle will be truly impressive, as
grand as the gods of the football field says the programme.
	   It will incorporate the streets and historic monuments of Paris
which will be broadcast live via satellite to 800 million
television viewers.
	   If Paris is the centre of tournament, nine other cities will
participate in this sports festivity: Saint-Denis, Lens,
Saint-Etienne, Bordeaux, Tourlouse, Montpellier, Lyon, Nantes and
Marseille.
	   Needless to say, these cities have done their utmost to attract,
their foreign guests, by bringing forth their regional varieties of
food, wines, and cultural heritage.
	   To sum it up, a magazine reported: ``Paris `Foot folly', nine
French cities rejoicing''. Dream or nightmare is more or less what
the organisers have in mind.
	   Security problems are immense when you host the world event, the
Olympic Games is a good example, but the particularity of this
event is the very nature of the game that inflames the minds, the
passion, the chauvinist instincts that so often border on frenzy.
	   Fans numbering close to a million will be watching football
players representing 32 countries, among them, no doubt, will be a
few hooligans, that should not be difficult to subdue. Far more
hazardous is the terrorist threat, which thrives in such
surroundings.
	   Security forces are on the war path, the exact number was not
disclosed, for not only crowds are to be controlled, but in a
relatively closed area such as Paris, with numerous state and
ministerial buildings to safeguard, the task is indeed tremendous.
	   The French Organising Committee and FIFA, the World Football
Federation have been criticised for many things as could be
expected, but most stinging was the worldwide system used for
ticket allocations.
	   Their policies have come under attack, even admonished by the
European Union to improve the ticket distribution in a fairer way.
	   If all these headaches were not enough for the organisers,
another, rather unexpected problem arose. Industrial disputes from
several fronts came to the fore.
	   The worst being Air France pilots' strike, threatening to
maintain their walk-out through the World Cup event if their
demands were not met.
	   For once, the public, usually showing empathy for the strikers,
were less than impressed by claims from the world's best paid
pilots.
	   As a follow up to Air France pilots' demands, other social
categories are joining forces to blackmail the government for pay
increases and or social privileges, using the World Cup tournament
as a means of extortion.
	   The public for once, and the Press expressed their disapproval,
and see this as public relations disaster not to mention a further
deterioration of the country's credibility.
	   As negotiations between Air France management and pilots
continue, Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, clearly stated that the
pilots' demands could not unsettle the forthcoming World Cup event,
that the airlines survival was of the essence.
	   
</TEXT>
