<HEADLINE>
Electrolux bases environ work on resource efficiency, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Electrolux bases environ work on resource efficiency, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Sreerema BanooASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ECONOMIC and population growth as well as increased use of
natural resources are the most fundamental reasons for a number of
environmental problems and threats.
	   It is not surprising then that Electrolux, the global appliance
company, bases its environmental work on resource efficiency,
legislations and gradually changing market demands.
	   In its 1997 Environmental Report, Electrolux says its proactive
environmental strategy is paying dividends for both customers and
shareholders by substantially reducing appliance running costs and
increasing investment returns.
	   According to Mr Per Grunewald, head of Environmental Affairs:
``In one key product area, for example, the products with the best
environmental performance accounted for 10 per cent of sales, and
up to 15 per cent of profit.''
	   The 36-page report details Electrolux's efforts in 1997 to
remain a front-runner in environmentally-sound products and
actively stimulate demand for appliances with reduced environmental
impact.
	   At the Conference on Climate Change in Kyoto last December, 38
developed countries agreed to further limit the emission of
greenhouse gases.
	   The protocol establishes that between the year 2008 and 2012,
the total emissions of greenhouse gases in these countries must be
reduced by 5.2 per cent compared to the 1990 level.
	   Decisions made and measures taken will affect Electrolux as well
as the industry as a whole.
	   Electrolux estimates that replacing all of Europe's domestic
white goods with new energy efficient appliances will account for
up to 25 per cent of the greenhouse limitations pledged by European
countries at the Kyoto conference.
	   Last year, white goods accounted for 74 per cent of sales in
household appliances, and for half of the total group sales.
	   The report added that Electrolux is far ahead of schedule in
phasing out ozone-depleting substances and in 1997, it became the
first company to market ozone-friendly refrigerators and freezers
in Brazil.
	   Sales of Electrolux refrigerators and freezers with the highest
environmental performance increased by 18 per cent from the first
to the second half of 1997, the report added.
	   In preventing waste and promoting recycling, Electrolux has
launched take-back of product programmes in several countries.
	   
</TEXT>
