<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Blatter-Johansson,0480 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Blatter, Johansson try to minimize latest row _ slightly
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By BRIAN TRUSDELL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Sepp Blatter and UEFA president Lennart Johansson
appeared to bury their hatchet again Wednesday, but only a few
centimeters deep.
	   The newly elected FIFA president and his vanquished opponent met
for a ``long personal talk'' Wednesday over allegations of
vote-buying in Monday's election by Blatter and ``have clarified
the issue,'' a media release from the world body said.
	   ``Lennart Johansson emphasizes that he at no time made any
accusations of bribery against Joseph S. Blatter,'' the release
said. ``He disassociates himself completely from these allegations
and vows to continue to cooperate with Joseph S. Blatter in his
role as the new FIFA president.''
	   That's not exactly what UEFA said, however.
	   Johansson and his UEFA vice-presidents _ Antonio Matarrese of
Italy, Egidius Braun of Germany, and Senes Erzik of Turkey _ met
with African Football Confederation president Issa Hayatou of
Cameroon, Oceania Football Confederation head Charles Dempsey of
New Zealand and Korean Football Association president and FIFA vice
president Chung Mong-joon to ``exchange views,'' a UEFA release
said.
	   ``They took note of media reports concerning alleged
irregularities in the FIFA presidential election,'' the release
said. ``However, Lennart Johansson stated that he did not wish to
speculate on such reports.''
	   ``Should these alleged irregularities become fact, we will take
the matter up,'' the release quoted Johansson as saying.
	   The dueling releases seemed to lessen the contentious battle
between Blatter and Johansson only slightly.
	   The two fought a bitter 2 1-2-month campaign for soccer's top
office, trading personal attacks and name-calling.
	   After winning, Blatter issued a press release Tuesday night
through FIFA ``categorically'' denying rumors ``of a manipulation
of the vote'' that gained him the post.
	   Rumors apparently were fed by a story in the International
Herald Tribune on Tuesday which quoted Johansson indicating that
Monday's vote wasn't fair.
	   ``Something happened somewhere,'' Johansson was quoted as
saying. ``I had so many promises of votes that I am, to put it
mildly, surprised and disappointed to be beaten so
comprehensively.''
	   Blatter didn't get the necessary two-thirds majority on the
first ballot, but led 111-80, more than enough to win a simple
majority on the second vote. Johansson conceded before a second
vote could be held.
	   In its release Wednesday, FIFA called the issue ``closed.''
	   ``FIFA intends to make no further statements in this connection,
but to concentrate all its efforts on running the football World
Cup in France.''
</TEXT>
