<BODY>
<SLUG> URGENT-NEED-TO-HASTEN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Urgent need to hasten pace of liberalisation, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Urgent need to hasten pace of liberalisation, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Cheng Lee ShuangASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IT is a time for due diligence now as finance companies get down
to brass tacks in digesting the full impact of the recent merger
exercise which is viewed as necessary for the country's financial
well-being.
	   For these 39 finance firms to have been either merged into eight
groups or absorbed by their banking parents by the March 31
deadline, the road ahead is still threatened by many pitfalls.
	   For the next six to nine months, kinks have to be ironed out.
Internal as well as independent auditing has to be done. The
pricing has to be worked out, the mode of payment being dependent
on the strength of the balance sheet.
	   The logistics of rationalising branches and management for some
of these firms will have to be wrapped up.
	   The six core finance company groups are led by Mayban Finance,
Public Finance, Hong Leong Finance, Arab-Malaysian Finance, EON
Finance together with Credit Corporation under Suria Mahsuri Sdn
Bhd and United Merchant Finance.
	   Two other groups are Affin Finance and a strategic partnership
between MBf Finance and Bank of Commerce.
	   The merger of finance firms can perhaps be viewed as a foregone
conclusion. They had little choice but to merge.
	   The question of bad loans looms large in the performance of
finance companies. Among banking institutions, finance companies
experienced the most significant increase in non-performing loans,
rising from 4.3 per cent as at end-June 1997 to 7.8 per cent as at
end-1997.
	   According to Bank Negara's 1997 annual report, the decline in
pre-tax profit for finance companies in the second half of last
year (from RM923 million in the first half to RM381 million in the
second half) was largely due to an increase in loan loss provisions
and shrinking interest margins on their fixed rate loan portfolio.
	   Furthermore, a downturn in the motor industry had affected their
traditional hire-purchase business.
	   As a pre-emptive measure to contain asset price inflation, Bank
Negara had in March last year placed restrictions on hire-purchase
loans for passenger vehicles.
	   Under those guidelines, finance companies were not allowed to
provide financing in excess of 70 per cent of the purchase price of
non-commercial passenger vehicles while the repayment period of
these loans was restricted to not more than five years.
	   The regional financial meltdown had affected the repayment
patterns of borrowers pertaining to loans for the purchase of
passenger cars and commercial vehicles.
	   As at end-June last year, the NPL for this sector stood at RM1
billion or 2.4 per cent of total loans to this sector.
	   In comparison, commercial banks and merchant banks also suffered
a significant decline in profitability in the second half year. The
decline in merchant banks' profitability for the second half of
last year was also attributed to the sharp decline in their
traditional fee-based activities.
	   Banking is a service industry in which the cost is high. ``By
virtue of finance companies' fixed rate loan portfolio, it is
difficult for them to absorb increasing costs if the cost of funds
go up. There will be a squeeze on margins,'' says a senior banker.
	   It depends on whether they can borrow at favourable rates from
the money market, especially if they are smaller capitalised firms.
	   ``One or two bad loans can wipe out the capital of these
companies with small paid-up capital,'' he says.
	   Shareholders' funds of a mere few million ringgit in this day
and age is a pittance considering the advent of information
technology and communications.
	   The need to computerise extensively eventually for economies of
scale as well as sharpening financial institutions' competitive
edge is without doubt, more so when the Multimedia Super Corridor
is in place.
	   Furthermore, some of the financial institutions are family-owned
entities. For those reluctant to let go, having majority control is
good enough.
	   Finance companies which do not have a minimum of RM600 million
paid-up capital are required to top up by the year 2000.
	   Financial strength, together with good management, will
strengthen these companies and give them a better opportunity to
sustain their operations and instil investor confidence.
	   The strength of finance companies with a small capital base has
also been sapped by the size of the domestic market.
	   Pit that base with the number of players before the merger and
the population of Kuala Lumpur numbering about 1.5 million people,
and you have the elements of high cost in the making.
	   With one branch in Kuala Lumpur serving about 10,000 people for
all accounts, small firms may not be able to survive the escalating
cost of business.
	   It is not just finance firms which have to merge. The call is
out for brokerage firms to merge too. It is understood commercial
banks will have to do so by the year 2000 for by then, financial
services will be further liberalised in accordance with Malaysia's
commitment to the World Trade Organisation.
	   The risk of failure in the financial services industry has a
greater repercussion on the economy. If the pace of liberalisation
does not pick up, Malaysia may stand to lose out on cheaper cost of
funds, international sources of funding as well as innovative
financial products.
	   The pace of liberalisation has to be expedited as we need
adequate capital for investment. Liberalisation will require
greater transparency with timely disclosure of relevant
information.
	   In turn, this will enhance the performance of financial
institutions.
	   Strides have been made in improving transparency. The domestic
banking sector's inherent strength is that it does not have a huge
foreign debt.
	   The first corporate earnings reporting season of the year which
ended on March 31 - for companies whose interim of full financial
year ended on Dec 31, 1997 - is out, and it does not paint a pretty
picture.
	   Sharp falls in earnings and losses reported were mainly due to
larger- than-expected provisions that arose from untimely foreign
exchange loans and investments in stocks and shares.
	   The banking system's loan exposure to the broad property sector
has been an area of concern and property represents a sizeable
collateral against banking loans.
	   Though Bank Negara has laid the foundation for a more robust
financial system including more stringent prudential standards
imposed on the recognition of NPLs and provisioning besides
consolidating credit growth without curtailing productive
investments, the next few months are crucial for the financial
system in terms of its ability to withstand strain.
	   The sterling economic performance in recent years has
contributed to strong asset quality and facilitated the build-up of
capital and reserves to healthy levels.
	   As a result, the industry's capital and reserves have increased
by RM34 billion in the last five years to RM47 billion at the end
of last year.
	   Restoring confidence and expediting recovery in the financial
system is of paramount importance in the face of strains in a
difficult environment.
	   The current economic situation can be seen as an impetus in the
consolidation of the financial system, including merger intiatives.
	   Stronger prudential regulations, supervision and corporate
governance as well as greater transparency will strengthen sound
practices.
	   However, further tightening of provisioning rules for
sub-standard loans and off-balance sheet items may amplify the
problems faced by some banking institutions but ultimately, they
will result in stronger balance sheets.
	   These measures have to be instituted to restore investor
confidence and contribute effectively to economic recovery.
	   
</TEXT>
