<HEADLINE>
`Many still opt for S'pore', BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
`Many still opt for S'pore', BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MANY exporters and importers still opt to ship their goods
through Singapore port rather than Malaysian ports.
	   Figures released by the Malaysian International Shippers'
Council showed that 37 per cent or 5.8 million TEUs (20-foot
equivalent units) of the 13 million TEUs of Singapore port's annual
container throughput are from Malaysia.
	   ``This number is huge,'' Council chairman Datuk Kerk Choo Ting
told reporters in Subang Jaya yesterday at the Fourth Biennial
International Maritime Conference on ``Maritime Industry: Meeting
New and Changing Demand Conditions in Asia''.
	   The two-day conference was opened by Transport Minister Datuk
Seri Dr Ling Liong Sik.
	   ``If we can bring back at least 10 per cent of this cargo volume
to Malaysian ports, it would certainly help the local maritime
industry amid the current economic slowdown.
	   ``But it is not easy to convince the shippers to change their
traditional way of practice. There is a reason why they still
prefer to go through Singapore port,'' he said.
	   Kerk said Malaysia has to improve the infrastructure facilities
at its ports, the operations and cargo clearance procedures, and
land transport facilities leading into and out of the ports.
	   ``With these three ingredients in place, I am sure the volume of
cargo going through Malaysian ports will also increase,'' he said.
	   In fact, he said, the Government has already done ``quite a
bit'' to upgrade the ports' infrastructure facilities to attract
exporters and importers to ship their goods directly to Malaysia.
``It is just a matter of time.''
	   Last year, Malaysian ports handled 165.7 million tonnes of
cargo, up 10.2 per cent over the 1996 volume.
	   
</TEXT>
