</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> URGENT-NEED-FOR-ADS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Urgent need for ads to work harder now, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Urgent need for ads to work harder now, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Sreerema BanooASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE advertising industry is looking at a reduction in
expenditure of between 25 to 30 per cent as companies do their
utmost to reduce expenditure and look for ways to keep their
business afloat in times of an economic slowdown.
	   Foote, Cone and Belding (M) Sdn Bhd deputy managing director T.
	   Renganathan said most companies failed to realise that cutting
back on advertisements will be detrimental in the long run.
	   Now more than ever, there is an urgent need for advertisements
to work harder and most cost effectively, he told Business Times in
Kuala Lumpur.
	   ``Gone are the days of mega productions. Advertisements have to
be more cost-effective with a quicker turnaround and at the same
time, they must maintain the brand in the long-term,'' he said.
	   ``Most clients are concerned with their own sales numbers, where
if financial figures are tracked on a quarterly basis previously,
now it is done on a monthly or even daily basis,'' he said, adding
that advertisers then have to work harder.
	   But while clients are looking for short-term ways to bring in
sales, some of the quick ``fix-its'' such as promotional sales will
diminish the standing of the brand in the long-term.
	   Customers, he added, look for value and this may come in the
form of the established brand.
	   ``Customers look for brands which they believe will be around in
the long term. Therefore if companies continue to advertise, they
will get the confidence needed,'' he said.
	   After all, if no one promotes anything, then business may well
come to a standstill, he said adding that the impetus then to
promote confidence and thereby stimulate the economy has to come
from businesses by way of advertisements and marketing.
	   FCB Malaysia's managing director Simon Bolton said one example
of a company that is aggressively advertising and marketing is
Suria KLCC.
	   He added that in times of slowdown, perhaps the last thing
needed is another new mall. ``But the approach taken in launching
the shopping mall is aggressive as seen by the full page
advertisements, radio as well as television commercials.''
	   On the impact of the economic problems on the agency's business,
Bolton assured Business Times that there is no sense of desperation
and ``we are faring a lot better than other companies.''
	   The statement is perhaps humble of FCB Malaysia, considering
that it recently won nine awards at the recent 3rd Malaysian Video
Awards.
	   FCB Malaysia won three gold awards, two for its TMTouch
advertisements and one for the National Cancer Council (Makna).
	   Renganathan said the rebranding of the agency two years ago has
paid off. FCB Malaysia was formerly called AP:FCB, a joint venture
between FCB and AP, a local advertising agency.
	   In 1996, FCB bought up the majority stake in the company.
	   ``Two years ago, we re-strategised plans for the business and we
recruited professionals to run the business and this is now paying
off.
	   ``We have our tools, we are building our client base and
employee confidence,'' Bolton added.
	   And who better than FCB Malaysia to realise the importance of
strong tools.
	   ``Strong tools are important because they help get better
communication for clients. At the end of the day, clients choose an
agency which they believe will give them a better chance of getting
better advertising for their brands,'' Bolton said.
	   And FCB uses and has developed tools such as an electronically
linked network of knowledge which enables any FCB office to tap
into the database of case studies.
	   This, he said, will give them an idea of how past advertisements
worked in another market or environment which then provides
confidence.
	   Another tool which is a FCB proprietary technique of gaining
insight into the behaviour of cosumers, is the ``mind and mood''
technique.
	   Bolton stressed that the ``mind and mood'' technique is
different from typical research as it provides insight into
consumer behaviour which then translates into ideas for better
advertising.
	   ``Mind and mood gives a consumer insight on how they look at
brands and peoducts, their buying behaviour and this then enables
the creative people to be more effective.
	   ``An example of how the technique works is if, say the client is
Mercedes and you want to talk to some S-Class owners.
	   ``These would be Chinese entrepreneurs and it is usually
difficult to meet them. So what happened was we found a sports hall
where some of these Chinese businessmen have played badminton for
the past 20 years.
	   ``So we went there and talked to them about how they felt about
their cars and we found that it is easy to get people to talk about
their passion,'' Bolton explained.
	   Apart from capitalising on their strengths, FCB Malaysia is also
investing in training where it has organised Information Technology
(IT) training programmes, departmental traning programmes as well
as regional programmes.
	   It is running seminar programmes on a variety of topics for
example, ``How to Write Radio Ads'' and ``How to Listen to Clients
Better.''
	   ``We are spending more significantly than we were in the past,''
said Renganathan.
	   Bolton added that FCB Malaysia is also looking for opportunities
to invest in other countries in the Asian region, for example, Sri
Lanka and Pakistan.
	   ``By and large we have a large network and we want to build on
this, be more successful and where there are opportunities, acquire
companies and talent.
	   ``By the year 2000, we hope to be close to the top of the cycle
and be at the top 10 in terms of size and client base,'' said
Bolton.
	   
</TEXT>
