<HEADLINE>
Cross-Atlantic speed record broken by Australian-built ferry
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES in 2nd and 3rd grafs with more precise crossing time;
new 6th graf with official decision to come in 30 days; last graf
with room for 350 sted 240 cars. NEW to some points. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   CEUTA, Spain (AP) _ The record for the fastest Atlantic crossing
by a commercial passenger vessel has been broken by an
Australian-built ferry, the company said Wednesday
	   The 91-meter (300-foot) Catalonia arrived in the Spanish enclave
city of Ceuta in north Africa after 10:00 p.m (2000 GMT) Tuesday,
clocking an average speed of 40 knots during a cross-Atlantic
sprint that began in New York at 0035 GMT Sunday, said Ivonne
Sentis, spokeswoman for Buquebus, the Argentine-Uruguayan company
that owns the ferry.
	   The crossing took three days, nine hours and 55 minutes.
	   Hoverspeed Great Britain set the previous record with an average
speed of 36.65 knots in 1990. Both ships were built by Incat
Australia.
	   Winning the record carries with it the Hales Trophy, donated by
British Member of Parliament Harold Hales in 1933. The trophy was
first held by the Italian Liner Rez, which set the record of 29
knots in the same year.
	   The Catalonia must now turn over its logs to the trophy's
technical review committee, which will render its decision within
30 days.
	   The ferry, with room for 900 passengers and 250 cars, will work
the three-hour route between Barcelona and the Mediterranean resort
island of Mallorca starting June 15. 	   
</TEXT>
