<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Chiapas,0475 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rebels, state police clash in Chiapas; at least one policeman dead
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos pursuing &QL; 
 &UR; By ALEJANDRO RUIZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico (AP) _ Villagers who support
leftist rebels clashed with state police in at least two shootouts
Wednesday in the highlands of southern Chiapas state. At least one
police officer was killed and five were wounded.
	   Witnesses said the clashes started when state police, backed by
army troops, tried to dismantle a parallel town council the rebel
supporters had set up in the village of El Bosque, 25 miles (40
kms) north of San Cristobal.
	   Police and troops moved in early Wednesday to El Bosque and the
nearby communities of Los Platanos, Union Progreso and Chabajebal.
The gunfights began in the early morning, and sporadic shooting
could still be heard outside Chabajebal at 1:30 p.m.
	   Details remained unclear because state police and soldiers
blocked most journalists from entering a ``security cordon.''
	   Jose Luis Zenteno, a public security officer, told reporters in
San Cristobal that he and several other policemen were driving to
search a house in El Bosque when several men _ believed to be
Zapatista rebels and wearing ski masks _ opened fire with automatic
weapons.
	   Zenteno said one officer was killed and five were wounded in the
7 a.m. ambush. The state attorney general's office refused to give
out any information on the incidents.
	   Sympathizers of the Zapatista National Liberation Army had set
up a rebel town council in El Bosque 2 1/2 years ago. Members of
the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party had their own town
council at a house a few blocks away.
	   The two town councils appeared to coexist peacefully until
Wednesday.
	   In Chabajebal, state police and soldiers surrounded the town
early Wednesday afternoon. Rebel sympathizers there faxed a
statement to news media claiming there was much shooting and
``several dead and wounded among Zapatista sympathizers.'' The
claim could not be confirmed.
	   The fax appealed for help from the Red Cross and human rights
organizations.
	   The Zapatista rebels staged a brief uprising on Jan. 1, 1994,
saying they were fighting for more rights and better living
conditions for the Mexico's poor Indians. Peace talks are stalled
over the government's failure to implement an accord on Indian
autonomy.
	   At least 40,000 federal troops patrol the state. The government
has been accused of links to vigilante groups that have clashed
with Zapatista supporters, including a band that massacred 45 rebel
sympathizers in the town of Acteal late last year.
	   Supporters of the Zapatistas have set up 32 parallel town
councils _ most of them a symbolic presence _ since late 1994. The
government late last year began breaking them up, and 28 now
remain. 	   
</TEXT>
