<HEADLINE>
Health Ministry holds dialogue for public inputs, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Health Ministry holds dialogue for public inputs, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Mon. - Fifty-nine organisations representing
professional groups, health-related industries and non-governmental
organisations will present their memorandums during the Third
Health Ministry Annual Dialogue which started today.
	   Health Minister Datuk Chua Jui Meng said the dialogue was to
gather input from health-related bodies to formulate the country's
healthcare policy as well as to evaluate the existing policy's
effectiveness.
	   He said it also provided an opportunity for unions representing
the ministry's employees to present their memorandums on issues
relating to career prospects and conditions of work.
	   Chua said the dialogue was important as several developments in
healthcare had taken place as a result of past dialogues. An
example is the Private Healthcare Facilities and Services Bill
1998.
	   ``The Bill is the answer to calls for the ministry to practise
greater transparency on issues related to healthcare reforms.
	   ``There was concern over unregulated development of managed care
organisations which interfered with professional decision making,
resulting in the under-treatment of patients.
	   ``With the new Bill, the licensee and holders of certificates of
registration of private healthcare facilities will be regulated and
controlled.''
	   Chua also expressed his hope that this year's dialogue would be
as fruitful, if not better than the previous years'.
	   Among the professional groups which presented their memorandums
today were the Malaysian Endocrine and Metabolic Society, Malaysian
Radiological Society, Malaysian Association of Private Medical
Laboratories, Opthalmological Society of MMA, Malaysian Society of
Transplantation and the Malaysian Dermatology Society. Tomorrow,
Chua will meet representatives of industrial organisations.
	   
</TEXT>
