<SLUG> BARGAINS-GALORE-AT-SHOPS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bargains galore at shops prior to big move, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Bargains galore at shops prior to big move, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Tues. - It's bargains galore at the Sultan Abdul
Aziz Shah International Airport as it prepares for closure come the
opening of the Kuala Lumpur International Airport in Sepang at the
end of the month.
	   The duty-free shops are plastered with stickers and placards
announcing the big move to the KLIA along with discount notices in
the hope of finishing their stocks before June 27.
	   Price cuts of up to 60 per cent are offered everywhere,
including at the Habib Jewel store where diamond accessories are
sold at a 50 per cent discount.
	   Even Christian Dior is offering 60 per cent cuts for certain
items although the notice is subtle and soberly printed on a
signage at the entrance.
	   Malaysia Airports Berhad commercial manager Yusuf Jamaluddin
said the shops had stopped acquiring new stocks and were trying to
dispose of all their stocks.
	   ``Some of them have started to transport their goods to the new
airport in Sepang,'' he said.
	   While most of the shops at Terminal Two can move their goods to
the new airport without any hassle, the other shops selling
duty-free goods have to go through the customs and time-consuming
procedures.
	   ``That's why they are so eager to sell off their stocks,'' Yusuf
said, adding that the shops would continue to operate until June 29
when the airport in Subang ceased operations.
	   He said sales, which had been down earlier due to the economic
slowdown, had been picking up again since the ``big move
discounts'' started last week.
	   ``Whatever happens, we want to make sure that customers get the
best bargains until the very last day,'' Yusuf said.
	   
</TEXT>
