<HEADLINE>
Shipping Act to bring laws up to date, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Shipping Act to bring laws up to date, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PETALING JAYA, Tues. - The proposed Malaysia Shipping Act, which
is being drafted, will update the shipping laws and ensure they are
abreast of international laws and practices.
	   Transport Minister Datuk Seri Dr Ling Liong Sik said today the
Act would replace three current shipping ordinances - one each for
Peninsular Malaysia, Sabah and Sarawak passed in 1952 and 1960.
	   He said the maritime industry required additional legislation to
prepare it to face future challenges.
	   ``Shipping trends worldwide show a tendency to hub a few major
ports in each region and the Government has embarked on a policy of
positioning Port Klang, our premier port, as a national and
regional hub,'' he added.
	   Besides the proposed new Act, another one being drafted is the
Carriage of Goods by Sea Act, to update the liability regime for
sea transport.
	   ``The current legislation enacted in 1950 adopts the Hague Rules
of 1924 while the new Act will adopt the Hague Visby Rules of
1968,'' he added.
	   Dr Ling was speaking at the two-day 4th Biennial International
Maritime Conference on ``Maritime Industry: Meeting New and
Changing Demand Conditions in Asia.''
	   Also present were president of Institut Kelautan Malaysia, Capt
Mohd Azmi Ahmad, chairman of Port Klang Authority Datuk Michael
Chen and Transport Ministry secretary-general Datuk Othman Mohd
Rijal.
	   Dr Ling said the new extended Traffic Separation Scheme in the
Straits of Malacca would be enforced by Dec 1, this year.
	   ``The Government is fully committed to ensure safety on the high
seas.
	   TSS has already been agreed to by the Maritime Safety Committee
of the International Maritime Organisation. It will be complemented
by the Vessel Traffic System,'' he added.
	   The International Ship Management Code would be fully
implemented this year.
	   ``This is to ensure that their ships do not face any
difficulties when calling on foreign ports. ISM code compliance
will also ensure that safety is given a high priority in the
operation of their ships,'' said Dr Ling.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
