<HEADLINE>
Egypt refusing to entry to Hamas leader
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with quotes from Jordanian official &QL; 
 &UR; By SALAH NASRAWI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Egypt is refusing to allow Sheik Ahmed
Yassin, the spiritual leader of the radical Islamic group Hamas, to
travel to Cairo, Hamas officials said Wednesday.
	   Yassin, who was scheduled to arrive in Cairo from neighboring
Sudan Tuesday night, has had to remain in Khartoum since Egyptian
authorities told him that he may not fly to Cairo, said Mohammed
Nazal, Hamas spokesman in Jordan.
	   Yassin has asked to transit through Cairo on his way back to his
home in Gaza.
	   Earlier, Jordan rejected Yassin's request to transit through the
kingdom on his way home, Jordanian officials said Wednesday. They
spoke on customary condition of anonymity.
	   Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul-Salam Majali told reporters in
the Gaza Strip Wednesday that ``if he (Yassin) wants to visit as an
ordinary Palestinian he is welcome to do so but if he is planning
to come with political ideas as a VIP, we will decide the date and
the agenda of such a visit.''
