<HEADLINE>
SMEs not making full use of R&AMP;D funds, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
SMEs not making full use of R&AMP;D funds, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Patvinder SinghASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Tues - Utilisation of funds by small- and
medium-scale enterprises for purposes of research and development
has been poor as most entrepreneurs are unaware of the funds.
	   Entrepreneur Development Minister Datuk Mustapa Mohamed said
today this was also true for various other funds set up for
entrepreneurs and was a matter for concern.
	   ``There is something wrong with our entrepreneurs. It is so
difficult for them to be exposed to and understand the various
facilities available,''
	   Mustapa said after opening the Multimedia Super Corridor
Nationwide Conference.
	   Also present was Multimedia Development Corporation executive
chairman Tan Sri Dr Othman Yeop Abdullah.
	   Mustapa said there were ample funds provided by the Government
and the private sector through venture capital and SMEs must take
the initiative to avail themselves of these.
	   Mustapa said the role of the Government and its agencies was to
assist and that the whole country had to ``buck up'' given the
current economic situation.
	   Yeop said MDC, through the MDC Advisory and Consulting Centre
for Enterprises (MDC ACCESS), hoped to develop 20 local IT
companies as world- class companies by 2000.
	   Earlier in his speech, Mustapa said more entrepreneurs should
take up the opportunities offered by the MSC.
	   He said to stay ahead in information technology it was
imperative to develop and nurture home-grown IT and multimedia
companies focused on developing indigenous technologies so it would
in turn, support the development of leading-edge
globally-competitive products and services.
	   ``In today's environment and with the advent of the digital
revolution, the chances of survival for a domestic player are
nearly non-existent unless we buck up and leapfrog,'' he said,
adding that was why despite the current economic downturn, the MSC
project would proceed at full steam.
	   He said the financial crisis was partly brought about by
globalisation and the revolutionary changes in telecommunications
and information technology.
	   Mustapa said it was hoped the MSC would provide an environment
that would nurture a thriving culture of creativity, innovation and
entrepreneurship - one that would accept failure as a natural
prerequisite to success.
	   Risk-taking must be encouraged in order to turn untried and
untested ideas into profitable business ventures.
	   He said his ministry had set up an IT Task Force and Knowledge
Workers IT Training Committee. The members comprised
representatives from the public and private sectors who worked
closely with SMEs.
	   Mustapa said the primary functions of the task force were to
assist entrepreneurs venture into IT-related businesses in the MSC
by helping them apply for MSC status, providing counselling and
guidance, as well as look out for related opportunities.
	   
</TEXT>
