<HEADLINE>
Where Have All the Parents Gone?, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Where Have All the Parents Gone?, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   For I am mindful of the sincere faith within you, which first
dwelt in your grandmother Lois, and your mother Eunice, and I am
sure that it is in you as well. - 2 Timothy 1:5 In 1950 only one
mother in 10 worked; but today four of every ten mothers of
preschool children bundle them off to the sitters or day care
center.
	   Today, five million children under age 13 spend 30 hours or more
a week in the care of someone other than their parents or school
teachers.
	   For years, Dr. Urie Bronfenbrenner, professor of family living
at Cornell, has been warning: Parents who allow surrogate mothers,
or electronic baby-sitters - television sets - to raise their kids
are seriously depriving their children of what no one else can ever
give - the security and warmth of a mother.
	   One of the most strongly worded criticisms, however, comes from
a woman, Dr. Selma Fraiberg, a child psychiatrist at the University
of Michigan, who has written the book Every Child's Birthright: In
Defense of Mothering. She says that children can profit from
half-day nursery school programs with small groups and qualified
teachers. What she objects to are babies and small children
delivered like packages to day care centers where they spend nine
to eleven hours a day - too long a time away from home - without a
good educational program and qualified teachers. And besides, she
points out, the parent who does this has only an hour in the
morning and not much more than that in the evening with the child.
One day care teacher recently said that she'd quit and raise her
child herself, ``no matter what the economic cost.''
	   Ralph Waldo Emerson pointed out that all generalizations are not
worth much, including the one that I am about to make, but I think
it's fair to say that if working mothers deducted the cost of
baby-sitters, additional clothes, gasoline, lunches and incidentals
from their earnings outside the home, and then evaluated the
emotional deprivation of their preschool children, there might be a
host of resignation by next Friday. Yes, it's a valid question.
Where have all the parents gone?
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:ALL-THE-PARENTS-GONE sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
