<BODY>
<SLUG> ENVIRON-AIMS-SHOULD sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`Environ aims should not be discriminatory', BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
`Environ aims should not be discriminatory', BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Sreerema BanooASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THERE is a need for environmental protection to be pursued in
the context of sustainable development, International Trade and
Industry Datuk Seri Rafidah Aziz said ``The promotion of
sustainable development should encompass initiatives which
strengthen and continue the liberalisation of the trading system as
well as consciously putting in place complementary environmental
policies,'' she said in Kuala Lumpur yesterday at the World Trade
Organisation (WTO) seminar on trade and environment for Asia
Pacific.
	   The text of her speech was read by the ministry's parlimentary
secretary Ahmad Kmaruzaman Mohd Baria.
	   Rafidah added that from the perspective of the multilateral
trading system, the WTO principle of non-discrimination should not
be compromised when pursuing environmental objectives.
	   She voiced the country's disappointment that some developed
countries continue to apply environmental policy measures
unilaterally and in a discriminatory manner rather than by
consensus.
	   ``What is of greater concern to the trading comunity including
Malaysia is that such environmental measures are conveniently used
as a covert form of trade protectionism to circumvent the WTO
system.
	   ``Many eco-labelling schemes were being promoted in the name of
sustainability but they could create problems if they are not
implemented based on a multilaterlly agreed criteria,'' she said.
	   Rafidah added that while Malaysia recognises the rationale for
eco- labelling, the indiscriminate use of such schemes as means of
trade harassment are affecting exports of developing countries.
	   ``The greatest challenge which faces the international community
is to effectively refrain from applying discriminatory trade
measures for environment purposes,'' she said.
	   Instead, there is a need to identify alternative means to
resolve regional and multilateral environmental problems.
	   ``Rather than punitive measures, positive measures such as
improving market access, financing, transfer of environmentally
sound technology, and capacity building in assisting developing
countries achieve sustainable development and meet environmental
objectives should be fully explored.
	   ``The special needs and problems associated with small and
medium industries in responding to the environmental challenge
would have to be adequately addressed,'' she said.
	   She reiterated that Malaysia is not oblivious to environmental
protection.
	   ``Various strategies relating to pollution control and
prevention, the integration of environmental consideration in
project planning and implementation and taking into account its
inputs into resource and development planning have been
incorporated into Malaysia's national development plans,'' she
said.
	   The seminar organised by the WTO secretariat in Geneva is the
first regional seminar to be held in the Asia Pacific region.
	   Economics officer of the WTO secretariat Sabrina Shaw said the
objective of the seminar is to bring together government
representatives in trade and the environment sector to promote
dialogue and understanding.
	   The three-day seminar is attended by some 60 participants from
22 countries.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
