<BODY>
<SLUG> CALL-TO-STEP-UP-FIGHT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Call to step up fight against piracy, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Call to step up fight against piracy, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Tues. - The Anti-Piracy Front of Umno Youth today
called on the authorities to be more serious and resolved in
combating intellectual and software piracy.
	   Its head, Abd Aziz Sheikh Fadzir, said pirated items were still
sold openly which indicated that the various measures taken so far
had failed to curb the problem.
	   He felt this would not happen if agencies like the Malaysian
Industrial Development Authority, the Customs Department and police
were more determined in their efforts.
	   Abd Aziz was speaking after chairing the front's annual meeting
at the Umno Youth headquarters at Menara Dato' Onn. Among those
present were representatives of recording companies and the
artistes' association.
	   ``For instance, MIDA should stop issuing new licence to
factories producing compact and video compact discs and revoke the
permits of those found to have been engaged in copyright
infringements.
	   ``But this is not done. New permits continued to be issued
resulting in 17 factories whereas statistics show we only need four
to meet the local demand. The main question that needs to be asked
now is what type of products are being manufactured by these
factories?''
	   Abd Aziz said the Customs Department must conduct more stringent
checks on consigments brought in, especially machines with
duplication facilities.
	   ``Some items should be placed under the list of controlled
items. The imports of raw materials like polycarbonate, an
essential item in the duplication and reproduction of softwares,
should only be allowed if permits are obtained.''
	   He also said enforcement must be intensified and efforts made to
ensure that offenders were not allowed to resume their trade
immediately.
	   ``There are cases where pirates are found to have resumed
operation a day after being raided. In other cases, this has been
made possible because the authorities only confiscated part of
their equipment.''
	   On the copyright laws, he said the current provisions were not
deterrent enough as the culprits were only subjected to a small
fine.
	   The front is proposing that a minimum fine of RM5,000 be imposed
for each infringing copy and a mandatory jail term of six months
for those found guilty of selling pirated items.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:CALL-TO-STEP-UP-FIGHT sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
