<BODY>
<SLUG> BE-MORE-COMPETITIVE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Be more competitive to meet global demands, local ports told, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Be more competitive to meet global demands, local ports told, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Kamarul YunusASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   LOCAL ports must move away from its traditional role as an
interface and make quantum leap into providing a wide range of
highly integrated level of service which is able to respond to the
demands of globalisation of international trade, Kelang Multi
Terminal Sdn Bhd said.
	   Its executive chairman, Datuk G. Gnanalingam, said ports must
explore avenues of cooperation and collaboration in the wake of the
highly competitive forces unleashed by globalisation of trade such
as the structural responses taking place in other industries. ``It
must ensure that the sub-systems which make up the port industry
and operations become a total system working in a cohesive manner
and facilitate ship and cargo handling seamlessly.
	   ``In the long run, the impact of globalisation of international
trade on ports could make national port status irrelevant or less
important, as is evidently becoming in the shipping, airlines,
telecommunications, banking, insurance and petroleum sectors,'' he
said at the Fourth Biennial International Maritime Conference in
Subang Jaya yesterday.
	   Presenting his paper on ``The Response of the Port Sector to
Globalisation of Trade: A Malaysian Perspective'', Gnanalingam said
the pressure on Malaysian ports to respond to globalisation of
international trade is very strong.
	   ``The country is one of the most open economies in the world
with a very high level of dependence on foreign trade.
Globalisation of international trade will have tremendous impact on
the economy of the country and the ports must therefore respond
accordingly,'' he said.
	   In the wake of globalisation of international trade, Gnanalingam
said the demand for port services will be influenced by: The
emergence of large trading centres as opposed to production and
distribution centres.
	   The need to move very large volume of products from one point to
another.
	   The need to move very large volume of cargo in the most
expeditious and efficient manner to meet low or no inventory
requirements.
	   The need for greater integration in the transport and
distribution pipelines.
	   The spread of increasingly paperless transaction and environment
in trade and commerce.
	   Ports, Gnanalingam said, also need to address the response of
the liner shipping sector to the globalisation of trade as
reflected in the emergence of large alliances and deployment of
very large containerships with higher frequency of calls.
	   These lines are deploying ships in the range of 5,000 to 6,500
TEU capacity, with exchange sometimes exceeding 1,000 per call and
with number of calls in rapid succession.
	   He added that there is also a trend of some of these lines to
combine and integrate their operations beyond ocean leg of
transportation by engaging in inland transportation and related
services. The objective of the development is to lower the total
transportation costs, including by achieving economies of scale
with the deployment of bigger vessels.
	   This imposes severe burden and responsibility on ports to ensure
that the efforts by the lines to lower their costs are not
threatened by higher costs brought about by lack of efficiencies at
the ports.
	   ``Ports must, therefore, become more competitive. Shipping lines
will want to see greater efficiencies and improvements in costs at
ports and inland operations to bring about savings in their own
total cost of transportation. ``One way for the ports to respond to
this is, of course, to eliminate the seams in the transportation
chain,'' he said.
	   Gnanalingam said one other response which the ports sector
should be looking at is the scope of alliances. Alliance among
ports could become a counter-veiling power.
	   ``But it will not be easy forging alliance among ports. There
is, in the first place, the intra-port competition to contend with,
including in Malaysia, at Port Klang.
	   ``Then, there is a keen inter-port competition in the region to
be considered.
	   ``Unless ports are ready to shed or dilute corporate image and
identities to foster intra-port cooperation and remove national
identities to forge inter-port alliances, little can be achieved by
proposing alliances, like those taking place in the shipping world
or in other sectors.
	   ``It may be a long way to go before we see alliance among ports
in the same way as those taking place in other industries. But a
start can be made by the port sector in cooperating in specific
areas, including in feedering services, operating inland
facilities, storage and sharing or managing equipment and other
port related activities,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
