<HEADLINE>
Mindanao Golden Fruit to Shine Anew, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Mindanao Golden Fruit to Shine Anew, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Pushing for the participation of Mindanao as a major player in
the country's mango industry, associations of Mindanao mango
growers have once again organized the 2nd Mindanao Mango Congress
'98 from July 30 to August 1 in Butuan City.
	   This year's congress will continue pursuing the goal of
transforming Mindanao's mango industry into the largest industry in
the province by 2005.
	   The event organizer, Agusan del Norte Federation of Mango
Growers, expects about 500 participants from all levels of the
mango distribution chain, including growers, processors,
trader/buyers, exporters, technicians and researchers.
	   Among the factors that have turned Mindanao into a fast-growing
alternative source for local mango production are the increasing
demand for mango in both local and international markets; the rapid
expansion and development of areas for mango production in
Mindanao; and the large attendance of mango growers at major
meetings in the past two years.
	   According to Ted Rodriguez, Enterprises Development specialist
of Growth with Equity in Mindanao (GEM) which assists in organizing
the congress, the congress has multiple objectives. Among them are:
to provide framework for the equitable development of mango-based
enterprises in Mindanao; to promote investment opportunities in the
mango and fruit industry for the Caraga Region and Mindanao; to
update Mindanao mango growers' information about where mangoes are
grown; to present post-harvest and processing technologies; and to
provide a venue for consensus building on policy issues affecting
the Mindanao mango industry.
	   The congress, entitled ``The Philippine Golden Mango: Responding
to Golden Opportunities with New Strategies'', was also organized
in cooperation with the Mindanao Mango Industry Development
Foundation, the Department of Tourism, the Department of Trade and
Industry, the Agricultural Training Institute, Department of
Science and Technology, Jardine Davies-Agchem Division, and the
Department of Agriculture.
	   For further information on the event, call tel. (082) 224-0517
or 221-0649 and look for Giovanni D. Malundo or Lovella B. Lim.
	   
