<HEADLINE>
PHB and PCB revise rights issues, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
PHB and PCB revise rights issues, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PENGKALEN Holdings Bhd (PHB) and Pengkalen Capital Bhd (PCB)
simultaneously revised the basis of their earlier proposed rights
issues, primarily to pump in more capital into the latter's
stockbroking subsidiaries, Pengkalen Securities and Kimara
Equities.
	   Pengkalen Securities and Kimara are both currently under trading
restrictions and require additional capital injections.
	   Both companies, through their respective rights issues, will
raise a combined RM1.01 billion, in part to repay bank borrowings
but more importantly to free the two brokerages from the trading
restrictions.
	   They would have raised a combined RM650.32 million if based on
their respective original rights issues proposed.
	   PHB's earlier proposed 2-for-1 rights issue of 397.23 million
shares has been revised to 3-for-1 of 595.84 million shares of RM1
each, to raise RM595.84 million instead of the previous RM397.23
million.
	   PCB, on its part, revised its earlier 3-for-1 rights issue of
253.09 million shares to 5-for-1 of 421.81 million shares of RM1
each, to raise RM421.81 million instead of the previous RM253.09
million.
	   PHB will use RM366.00 million of the proceeds from its revised
rights issue to repay its bank borrowings and some RM220.43 million
to subscribe for its entitlement of 220.43 million new shares in
PCB's revised rights issue.
	   PCB in turn, will use RM267 million of the proceeds from its
revised exercise to subscribe for its entitlement of 267 million
new shares in Pengkalen Securities' revised rights issue.
	   It will also use another RM148 million to subscribe for its
entitlement of 148 million new shares under Kimara Equities'
revised rights issue.
	   Analysts meanwhile said with the additional capital injection
into the two stockbroking firms, they will have liquid funds as
well as improved cashflows.
	   PHB, on its part, made the revision upon the increase in size of
PCB's cash call. Its parent company, Malayan United Industries Bhd,
which now holds an 80.72 per cent stake in the company, will
subscribe for its full entitlement of 480.94 million shares in
PHB's revised rights issue.
	   On PCB's part, the revision was necessary, to accommodate a
larger size of capital raising required of its two stockbroking
subsidiaries.
	   Meanwhile, both Pengkalen Securities and Kimara Equities
yesterday obtained a restraining order from the High Court of
Malaya to grant them stay from actions against indebtedness or
other obligations to their creditors or claimants for a period of
up to six months.
	   In a separate announcement, Rating Agency Malaysia (RAM) has
downgraded Pengkalen Securities' RM100 million guaranteed revolving
underwritten facility (1995/2000) short-term stand alone rating to
`NP', saying that while the securities company has attempted to
secure rated financial institutions to replace its unrated
guarantors, the situation has remain unchanged.
	   RAM said in the event of default by Pengkalen Securities,
noteholders would have recourse to the consortium of guarantors.
	   It added that while the facility continues to be guaranteed by
the guarantors, some of them are not yet rated by RAM.
	   
</TEXT>
