<HEADLINE>
Misamis Farmers Find Life Better Without Logging, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Misamis Farmers Find Life Better Without Logging, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Marie A. SurbanoASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The effective implementation of the Community Based Forest
Management (CBFM), under the Natural Resources Management Program
(NRMP) of the Department of Environment and Natural Resources
(DENR), has undoubtedly helped upland farmers in Misamis Oriental
to focus on the planting of various cash crops.
	   CBFM has not only stopped logging and poaching activities in the
area but has helped create community organizations in many parts of
Mindanao as well.
	   One successful CBFM beneficiary is the Mat-I Green Agroforestry
Development Association (Mag-Agda), whose membership now totals
184. These members have obtained an agreement under the CBFM
program to take care of 1,500 hectares of forest land, which serve
as Watershed of Dal-as and Mag-Bais creeks.
	   Cirilo Camiros, Mag-Agda chair, recounted that during the Marcos
regime, logging and pouching activities were the prime source of
income of most of the upland farmers and lowland communities.
	   Mag-Agda was created in 1994 to protect and rehabilitate the
forest that hosts the six watersheds providing more than 50% of
Misamis Oriental's water needs.
	   ``The existence of illegal logging was rampant at that time. And
the Dumagats (lowlanders) were the ones conducting the negotiation
with the Lumads (tribesmen) to sell the timber in the forested
areas,'' Camiros said.
	   However, since logging or timber cutting was not that
profitable, the Lumads and Dumagats both decided to abandon and
cease logging operations.
	   They seeked the assistance of non-government organizations that
extend support services to any community.
	   Life After Logging Mag-Agda members are currently enjoying the
benefits provided by NRMP- and DENR-initiated livelihood projects,
while the Department of Agriculture helps the other residents of
Mat-I, Claveria through their own programs.
	   The earlier part of the CBFM program aided Mag-Agda members
obtain initial funding from the provincial government for the
implementation of these projects.
	   Among these projects are the making of tomato crates using
abandoned logs.
	   Cooperatives can make a total of 2,000 crates a week, Camiros
noted.
	   The creation of tomato crates was a big help to members' daily
income.
	   According to data from CBFM, 70% of farmers in Mat-I, Claveria
plant tomatoes. One hectare alone could produce as much as 1,000 to
1,500 crates of tomatoes.
	   Camiros noted that each crate, consisting of P25-30 kilos, can
be sold for as high as P450 per crate and as low as P50 per crate.
The tomato products are disposed mostly in Metro Manila markets,
particularly Divisoria.
	   Aside from tomatoes, upland farmers also plant rice, corn,
coffee and vegetables to sustain their daily needs. There are sweet
peas, Baguio beans, cabbage, carrots, eggplants and onions in the
organization's vegetable plantation.
	   For a capital of P50,000, each farmer can expect a return of
P700,000 a year from his plantation, depending on the crops,
Camiros said. In one season, a capital of P5,000 can even double to
at least P10,000 in estimated income.
	   Hot Deal Recently, Mag-Agda also signed an agreement with Nestle
Philippines to be one of the latter's supplier of robusta, arabica,
leverica and excelsa coffee beans. Camiros said Nestle has agreed
to extend a grant to Mag-Agda members in the form of seeds,
cellophane bags, fertilizer and chemical sprays for every coffee
plantation.
	   As part of the agreement, Nestle will buy the grilled coffee
produce at P45 per kilo to the Mag-Agda members. Camiros added that
they were targeting 100 hectares of coffee plantation a year.
	   Mag-Agda received a total of P720,000 loan from its provincial
government and was the first people's organization in Claveria to
avail of the loan.
	   The loan has been used to utilized certain projects with the
support of the NRMP.
	   NRMP is another DENR project supported through the US Agency for
International Development (USAID). NRMP is a government initiative
to implement the Philippine Strategy for sustainable development
and a 25-year Master plan for forestry development.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
