w1902 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  FROM-SHOPS-TO-FLOWERSske     06-10 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> FROM-SHOPS-TO-FLOWERS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
From shops to pretty flowers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
From shops to pretty flowers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ooi Kok ChuenASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   WHEN Victor Chin formally bade farewell to 15 years of old
shophouse paintings, it was not with the hysterical hoopla of
Seinfeld's last episode.
	   The end, marked by his Garden Pleasures exhibition, was
strangely unceremonious, even with the symbolic frangipani.
	   It was a startling, dramatic change: from watercolours and the
print versions of Straits Eclectic architectural facades of
buildings of Kuala Lumpur, Malacca, Penang and Singapore to, as the
exhibition title implies, flowers! There are heliconia, orchids,
hibiscus, pink and red lilies and the frangipani, of course.
Flowers and more flowers, including one even done on an ambitious
122x116cm scale in acrylic.
	   They are not rendered with the realistic forms of Khaw Sia with
a little bit of Chinese brushstroke influence or with the softer
delicate hues of Teh Siew Joo, nor with the underlying erotic
sensuality of Long Thien Shih or Georgia O'Keefe, or in luxuriant
overgrowth such as those by Aminah Abdul Rahman, Heng Eow Lin
(bougainvillea) and Calvin Chua (morning glory).
	   There are flowers in cutting semi-abstract geometric shapes in
acrylic; flowers in lively rendition in crayons reminiscent of
Rafiee Abdul Ghani's style; flowers in stark monochrome in pencil
and charcoal with its bold, black backdrops; and flowers in
watercolours with a palette of ``unnatural''
	   colours that play on the patterns and mood.
	   And these, from a crusader of architectural conservation with an
idealised oeuvre of quaint landmarks along Singapore's Boat Quay,
Penang's Lebuh Pantai, Malacca's Jalan Tun Tan Cheng Lock, and
Kuala Lumpur's Jalan Hang Kasturi.
	   Over 15 years, Chin has done a portfolio of 64 watercolours
together with the print versions. He started his offset-lithos
prints in 1980.
	   So, how is it like to quit doing paintings of shophouses that
are half a century old or close to a century old, paintings that
established his name and turned him into a media star of sorts?
What brought about the change?
	   ``After my last exhibition in 1994 (Isetan Gallery in Kuala
Lumpur, October-November), I decided I would not paint shophouses
anymore,'' said Chin, who brought the chapter to a close the next
year.
	   ``After 15 years of shophouses, it came to an end by itself. For
a long time, I thought shophouses were the only thing I knew.
	   ``I have been doing nothing else but one subject. It was a
difficult time hanging around at home and doing nothing much. I
want to continue to draw.
	   Then came the simple discovery, something homespun - my little
garden.
	   ``Flowers are the most immediate thing. For years, they are just
there, just next to me. Flower paintings were never my thing. I
thought they are not terribly serious.
	   ``They just came to me in a strange way over a length of time. I
started sketching and drawing,'' said Chin, who resolved various
aesthetic problems as he worked on them and described the learning
process as ``frightening, lonely and desperate.''
	   ``The only thing you have going for you is that doing it every
day gives you the confidence.''
	   Chin is not interested in copying his success. It was this
honesty with himself, his willingness to listen to his heart and a
determined effort to learn and re-learn the painting process that
he started concentrating on watercolours after his
photography-art-orientated Rupa Gallery at the Dayabumi complex in
Kuala Lumpur closed after eight years in 1989.
	   His drawings in pen and charcoal reveal harsh, raw strokes which
assume a rainbow blend in the crayons. In his watercolours, the
colours are vibrant, playing on the fluidity and natural
contrasting shades.
	   His acrylic works thrive on the spatial ambiguity by the
placement of colours, by the intensity and solidity.
	   These are more structured. Though the space looks ``flattened'',
the angular cuts overlapping angular cuts in fragmented forms exude
a hard- edged veneer in parts, more like architectural shapes than
the delicate forms they are universally known for.
	   This has to do with the way Chin works, where every process is
reasoned out and resolved. His preference for the clinical and
clean lines is obvious.
	   ``I prefer clear lines to fuzzy lines. I prefer very resolved
forms to unresolved forms,'' he said.
	   And what he said of his shophouse watercolours years ago is true
of his flower paintings too: ``I craft my pictures. I try to paint
with an economy of lines, shades and design.''
	   Though his flower paintings are by his own admission ``a second
wind'', to his career, he has not turned his back completely on
issues of architectural heritage.
	   He may not be painting them anymore, but he is writing a book on
his experiences in growing up in such shophouses.
	   He is also involved with the Malaysian Nature Society and was
the first president of the Friends of the Heritage Society (1985).
	   Chin also has a series of anti-war works entitled Paradox which
he unveiled in 1988.
	   They reflect on his earlier graphic art training at the Harrow
College of Art in England.
	   Works such as Going Nowhere, Mutual Suicide Pact, Accusation and
the T- shirt The Next War is MAD (Mutual-Assured-Destruction) use
symbolic signposts of arrows, hand-signs and rockets to launch the
message.
	   While his works, either on architectural heritage or war, could
not stop the destruction, they help to create greater awareness
about the environment and Man.
	   While his flower paintings are fixated on more painterly ``how
to''
	   concerns, they are not without the philosophical basis.
	   ``I look at flowers more as a landscape, as a portrait because I
am not copying a flower. The flowers also reflect contemporary
issues of life.
	   ``I see flowers like a cycle of four stages from bud to blossom
to bloom and to withering.
	   ``Not many artists paint withering flowers. We all like to look
at things at full bloom. Youth is the most cherished period but old
age is just as important.''
	   The works in Garden Pleasures are not for sale. The exhibition
ends at the Creative Centre annexe of the National Art Gallery on
June 17.
	   He will also give a talk entitled Matters Within The Frame on
June 13-14 (2-3pm).
	   
</TEXT>
