<SLUG> 13-PROJECTS-FOR-JAPAN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Gov't Submits 13 Projects For Japan OECF Funding, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Gov't Submits 13 Projects For Japan OECF Funding, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Jenniffer D. BaldivinoASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Government has proposed 13 development projects, mostly in the
infrastructure sector, worth some $900 million to be financed under
Japan's Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund (OECF).In a memorandum
to President Fidel Ramos, Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon said
these projects, which were reviewed and discussed by both the
Japanese and Philippine governments, would be financed under the
22nd yen loan package.
	   Japan, the country's biggest source of official development
assistance, wanted the signing of this year's loan agreement held
before the end of Ramos' term this month.
	   Siazon explained this was because the OECF would merge with the
Japan Export-Import Bank on July 1, lessening the fund's financial
power and influence.
	   ``It is, therefore, highly desirable that the 22nd yen loan
package be signed before the merger,'' said Siazon.
	   Among the biggest projects that will be part of the loan package
are the Metro Manila strategic mass rail transit development line
two, N23,668 billion; domestic shipping modernization program,
N19,990 billion; Batangas port development, N14,555 billion:
Central Luzon irrigation, N14,136 billion; and the arterial road
links development, N13,564 billion.
	   Other projects in the list are the Metro Manila interchange,
selected airports development, metro Iligan regional infrastructure
development, Iloilo food control, Agno river flood control,
southern Mindanao integrated coastal zone management, fisheries
resource management and the local government units support credit
program.
	   Tokyo has expressed particular concern over the Central Luzon
irrigation project.
	   Based on Investment Coordination Committee estimates, the
project will cost some P2.6 billion.
	   However, the Japanese government, which estimated a cost of P3.8
billion, wanted the Philippines to accept the maximum rather than
the lower amount during the signing of loan agreement.
	   In view of the ``great efforts'' made by Japan in securing
bigger loans for the country, Siazon agreed with Tokyo's position
and asked the finance secretary to accept the proposal.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
