</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> MARIA-CALLAS-ELEMENT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Maria Callas is in her element here, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Maria Callas is in her element here, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   edward DorallASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE witch Medea is surely the most sympathetic of the terrible
females of Greek mythology. She began by deceiving her father and
murdering her brother, but only so that her lover Jason could steal
away with the Golden Fleece. Later she persuaded the daughters of
the usurper king of Iolchos to cut up their father and boil his
flesh in a cauldron, but this was to ensure that her husband Jason
would gain his rightful throne.
	   Finally she destroyed Princess Glauce on her wedding day with a
present of a poisoned robe and crown to prevent her from marrying
the deceiver Jason, and then murdered her own children by him to
punish him further for abandoning her. It is this last episode
which is the subject of Cherubini's opera, composed in 1797.
	   Maria Callas, by reputation the most temperamental of divas,
fittingly made Cherubini's heroine her greatest role.
	   She appears in the middle of Act I to ruin the wedding
festivities and is onstage for most of the rest of the opera. In
this 1957 recording, made four years after her debut in the role,
Callas' voice is occasionally wild, but her theatrical power is
stunning throughout. For 1 1/2 hours her Medea threatens, accuses,
pleads, cajoles, laments, feigns, curses, invokes, relents, and
finally exults over her enemies in a tour de force of dramatic and
vocal powers.
	   The other performers hardly count. Only Miriam Pirazzini as
Neris, the nurse and confidante of Medea, has a memorable long aria
with bassoon obbligato at the opera's exact halfway point,
promising faithfulness to her mistress lying exhausted before her
(the diva taking an onstage break before the ordeal of the second
half).
	   Accompanying them, Tullio Serafin's orchestra sounds its
primitive recording age, uncomfortably shrill, particularly in the
orchestral interludes. Cherubini's original Medee is a setting of a
French text intelligently adapted from the plays of Euripides,
Seneca, and Corneile by Francois-Benoit Hoffmann. Because it
combines singing and declaimed speech, and most singers are not
actors, it never became popular, and even in Lachner's fully
musical version demands a supreme soprano to make it a success.
	   Yet Beethoven and Brahms, rightly, thought very highly of it.
The music combines the spirit of the Sturm und Drang (Storm and
Stress) movement with the opera techniques of Rameau and Gluck. It
is hardly memorable melodically, it more than makes up for this by
a realistic vocal line undermined by a writhing, rumbling, and
frequently erupting orchestral accompaniment. No other opera I've
heard is more relentless, beginning agitatedly with Glauce's
nervousness over her approaching marriage to the final minute when
Medea burns down the temple.
	   Nuova Era's world premiere recording is of Patrick Fournillier's
live performance of Cherubini's original, 1797 score and text,
which he himself altered in later years. Its declaimed lines, in
quite effective alexandrines, match the arias, intensifying the
music as well as allowing Medea especially to rest her voice
frequently.
	   The conditions of a live performance result in an orchestral
sound as uncomfortably piercing as Serafin's in 1957, accompanied
throughout by the discreet noise of stage movements and audience
coughing. But Fournillier's Creon, Jean-Philippe Courtis, aided by
the spoken text, stands up bravely to Jano Tamar's Medee who, while
not as authoritative as Callas' (and which other Medea is likely to
be?), acquits herself magnificently in a still demanding role. The
performances all declaim very notably, though their Italian French
accents jar somewhat, and the offstage singing in Acts II and III
is always clearer than in the Callas version.
	   I am generally for original against revised versions of works,
but in this case I feel that the Lachner adaptation deserves to
continue in popularity, and not only because of Callas. If its
Italian translation and recitatives are weaker than Hoffmann's
text, its single tone - and Lachner's new music matches Cherubini's
in intensity - and the discreet cuts in the original's arias make
for a more immediate opera.
	   Indeed, both versions deserve to be regularly performed and
recorded.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:MARIA-CALLAS-ELEMENT sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
