<HEADLINE>
GenSan Furniture Makers Undergo Training, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
GenSan Furniture Makers Undergo Training, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Furniture makers in General Santos City, Mindanao are expected
to hike productivity this year after local artisans and members of
furniture manufacturing cooperatives went through a series of
training conducted by experts from the Forest Products Research and
Development Institute, an agency of the Department of Science and
Technology.
	   The continuing training and technical assistance kicked off with
a five-day furniture processing seminar designed for members of
GenSan Furniture Manufacturers Multipurpose Cooperative,
particularly those members classified as micro-cottage
entrepreneurs.
	   The group was under the auspices of Notre Dame, of Dadiangas
College's Notre Dame Business Resource Center Foundation, which
also got assistance from the Department of Trade and Industry
regional office.
	   FPRDI's technical participation - which came after a dialogue
between technical services chief Engr. Flex Moredo and NDBRCF
President Robert McGovern - included technology transfer in machine
and woodworks, wood drying and protection, joinery production,
waste utilization, planning and quality control.
	   FPRDI researchers are about to come up with three manuals
separately detailing advanced techniques and solutions on finishing
works for handicraft and furniture industries, especially those
made from rattan, bamboo, and buri midrib.
	   Health and safety procedures, waste management, and special
effects finishing tricks are also included.
	   A builder's manual for the construction of low-cost classrooms
using mainly the versatile woodwool cement bonded board explains
notes on design, site location, building orientation, construction
steps, materials handling, tools, manpower requirements and cost
estimates.
	   On the other hand, the botanical manual on Philippine mangrove
trees is a helpful guide in identifying local mangrove species for
foresters, environment specialists, and forestry students.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
