<SLUG> UPGRADE-CAPABILITIES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Upgrade capabilities, fund managers told, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Upgrade capabilities, fund managers told, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   DEPUTY Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim said managers of
unit trust funds have to continuously upgrade their capabilities
and maintain a high degree of professionalism.
	   He said the unit trust industry was important because it helped
mobilise funds from the public and addressed social disparities.
	   Anwar, who is also Finance Minister, said the Government would
strive to protect unit trust holders, whether it was a private or
Government-backed fund.
	   He added that it was important that the public had confidence in
the country's economic and financial system and that the Government
would take the necessary steps to turn the economy around.
	   ``I believe we can revive the economy. Those involved in this
business of trust, be prepared to take the right measures and make
necessary adjustments. With resilience, we shall overcome.''
	   Anwar was officiating the second annual Unit Trust Conference
and Exhibition organised by the Federation of Malaysian Unit Trust
Managers in Kuala Lumpur yesterday.
	   He also launched the federation's new corporate logo and
website. Also present was Securities Commission chairman Datuk Dr
Mohd Munir Abdul Majid.
	   Anwar said although the unit trust industry had grown over the
last few years, it accounted for only 9.5 per cent of the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange's capitalisation.
	   ``It is too small compared with the unit trust industries in
other countries such as India where it accounts for 25 per cent of
market capitalisation while in Thailand it accounts for 15 per
cent.''
	   He said the industry could ensure the viability of the KLSE
through injection of liquidity, thus preventing the capital market
from being vulnerable to outflow of funds.
	   The decision to freeze the launch of Government-backed funds in
December last year was to allow existing funds to enhance their
performance as well as give space to the industry to grow.
	   Anwar also commended the federation for its effort to make
comprehensive information available to unitholders.
	   Meanwhile, Munir said unit trust managers must have proper
standards, practices and codes of conduct firmly in place.
	   ``Such standards and practices should go beyond regulatory
requirements to both promote and maintain unitholders' interest and
to safeguard the reputation of the entire industry.''
	   Munir said as at March 31, a total of 47.3 billion trust units
were issued, up 4.4 per cent from the end of last year.
	   There are 31 management companies with a total of 85 funds, he
said, adding that six more funds have been approved.
	   
</TEXT>
