<SLUG> LOCAL-MANUFACTURERS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Local Manufacturers Back Closure of Duty-Free Shops, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Local Manufacturers Back Closure of Duty-Free Shops, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Federation of Philippine Industries (FPI) and the Kilusan
Tungo sa Pambansang Tangkilikan are supporting a government order
to close down duty-free shops in Clark and Subic by the end of the
year.
	   In an executive order, President Fidel Ramos ordered that all
privately-owned duty-free shops in the two former US military bases
be closed down by Dec. 31, 1998.
	   FPI Chair Jesus Arranza said he has asked the Supreme Court to
immediately rule on a case filed by the Coconut Oil Refiners
Association, Philippine Association of Meat Processors Inc.,
Federation of Free Farmers, Bukluran ng Manggagawang Pilipino
questioning the President's order.
	   The final resolution of the case will determine whether
duty-free shops in Clark and Subic should be closed down.
	   After a series of hearings, the congressional oversight
committee submitted a report stating that the bases conversion law
did not intend to allow the establishment of duty-free shops that
can import finished products.
	   The law allows these firms to import only raw materials.
	   Local manufacturers have complained duty-free shops in the
country are being used to smuggle cheap imports into the country,
resulting in unfair competition and depriving government of taxes.
	   Arranza said the huge volume of smuggled goods passing through
duty-free shops had contributed to the growing trade deficit and
depreciation of the peso.
	   ``The existence of duty-free shops in Clark and Subic and in all
other economic zones is not only illegal but also immoral,'' he
said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
