</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> A-YEN-FOR-SOME-SENSE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A yen for some sense, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
A yen for some sense, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ASIAN currency traders have listened to the news of the yen's
fall with dread in their hearts. Economists and analysts are
predicting the end of the world as we know it for Asia and one look
at the tracking charts for the region's currencies and stock
markets is enough to send everyone running for cover. Most
economists say that the yen's decline has not only battered Asia's
recovery but is sounding alarm bells across the world.
	   Unless Japan comes up with a convincing programme to stimulate
its economy, Asia's emerging markets will suffer a further blow.
The yen's decline is a reflection of a weakening economy and Japan
may be unable to buy products from a troubled South Korea, Thailand
and Indonesia. Asian manufacturers may also have a harder time
competing against Japanese goods sold elsewhere, especially in the
US.
	   Lest we forget, every coin has two sides. A weaker yen will also
mean cheaper loans for many developing countries. As Japan is one
of the most aggressive countries in terms of overseas development
assistance (ODA), servicing loans will be less onerous for many.
Malaysia was the seventh largest recipient of ODA loans under the
Japanese Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund (OECF), with loans
amounting to US$9.4 billion (US$1  &QC;  RM3.94) last year. Since March
1961, Japan has disbursed 15.805 trillion yen (100 yen  &QC;  RM2.83) to
85 countries. As one of the main recipients, Malaysia will benefit
from a weaker yen, especially with regards to cheaper Japanese
goods as well as components and parts for development projects.
	   The day after the yen broke through its seven-year low against
the US dollar, the Tokyo stock market celebrated. Yesterday,
trading pushed up the 225-share Nikkei average index by 235.46
points or 1.54 per cent to close at 15,530.17 yesterday. As
investors began to rake in the the profits, buyers, especially
foreigners, stormed the market in anticipation of some easy gains.
As the depreciating yen makes Japanese products less expensive
abroad, Asia must position itself to reap these benefits.
	   However, there is a possibility that a much weaker yen will
force Japan to cut down on its loans and financial assistance to
some countries. If this happens, developing countries will be left
with no choice but to accept the US dollar ODA package. With their
own currencies in a limbo, these economies must brace themselves
for a more difficult future.
	   The greenback's gain over the yen has many disadvantages. The
impact was highlighted last Sunday in a report by the Bank for
International Settlements, which coordinates the activities of the
world's central banks. The dollar, according to the bank, was
overvalued by 33 per cent against the yen and 21 per cent against
the mark. This doesn't look good as it makes American exports less
competitive and increases the likelihood of the US trade deficit
growing further. The dollar rose as high as 141.79 yen, its
strongest since June 19 1991, when it traded at 141.20 yen. It was
at 1.7786 marks, up from from 1.7751 marks amid concerns that
Russia's financial troubles will hurt Germany.
	   The weaker yen makes Japanese exports cheaper and more
competitive, while increasing the price of Asian imports to Japan.
However, the international community should realise that a plunge
in the yen will create problems not only for the Japanese economy
but also for Asia, the US and Europe. If the yen depreciates,
Japanese companies operating in Malaysia will see their income in
ringgit fall even if they maintain the same export volume. Japan
must therefore make some major moves to prevent the yen from
depreciating further. There is not much that the G-7 can do for the
yen without the Japanese Government providing support policies.
	   Even a surprising round of central bank intervention measures to
support the yen will only have a temporary impact if Japan's
policies are not changed. However, such measures, although
successful, may only serve to divert attention from the real cause
of the problem: the frail and finicky global system that allows
currencies to be so volatile. Half measures will no longer suffice.
It is time for the world to arrest the rot before the entire
financial system collapses.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
