<SLUG> TOKYO-HIGHER sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tokyo: Higher, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Tokyo: Higher, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SHARE prices closed 1.5 per cent higher yesterday mostly
benefiting from buying of export-related issues on the yen's
weakness, brokers said.
	   ``Sony and other consumer electricals were bought due to the
recent weakness of the yen,'' a broker at Orix Securities said.
	   The key Nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange gained 235.46 points to end the day at 15,530.17.
The Topix index of all issues on the first section rose 10.32
points at 1,208.68.
	   Turnover was subdued on volume estimated at 310 million shares,
compared with 251.3 million shares the day before.
	   Late buying of the futures contract pushed prices higher after
limited profit taking was seen in the afternoon session, brokers
said.
	   The market managed to absorb selling in leading banks after the
Long- Term Credit Bank plunged on rumour of cancelling a tie-up
with SBC Warburg Securities, a brokerage arm of Swiss Bank Corp,
brokers said.
	   LTCB closed 7.7 per cent lower, but rebounded strongly in the
afternoon after the bank dismissed the rumour in a statement and
news conference.
	   The stock lost 14.4 per cent in the morning. It ended down 14
yen at 167.
	   Public funds also supported the key Nikkei index.
	   ``There was modest buying from public funds towards the morning
close,''
	   the Orix broker said.
	   ``But overall, public fund buying was sporadic.''
	   Most exporters finished higher, with Sony up 250 yen at 11,670,
Aiwa up 120 at 4,300 and Sharp ahead 58 at 1,098.
	   
</TEXT>
