<SLUG> LOCAL-MARINE-EXPERTS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Local Marine Experts Save Diwal, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Local Marine Experts Save Diwal, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Local marine scientists have successfully rehabilitated the rare
and exquisite-tasting angel wing clam, a bivalve known in Western
Visayas as diwal, which was previously feared to be on the brink of
extinction, the Philippine Council for Aquatic and Marine Research
and Development said.
	   Diwal is ``one of the most-sought and expensive marine food in
the country.''
	   Strong demand, coupled with deterioration of its natural habitat
over the years, pushed its population down to alarming levels.
	   But a joint research made by marine experts at the University of
the Philippines-Visayas in Miag-ao, Iloilo campus and in Nova
Pacific Research Institute yielded crucial information on diwal's
reproduction process including embryo formation and larval
development.
	   By understanding its reproduction process, the experts scored a
breakthrough when they achieved mass production of diwal in
hatcheries that served as laboratories.
	   Now the experts have developed an A to Z method for larval
spawning and rearing adapted to diwal's natural environment and
experts hope to conduct additional field research in Roxas City,
San Dionisio town in Iloilo, and another still undisclosed site in
Negros Occidental.
	   On Tilapia Meanwhile, an information manual in the development
of the so-called YY technology or the production of genetically
male tilapia (GMT) is now off the press, the Central Luzon State
University announced.
	   The 67-page manual details tilapia's biology, problems on early
sexual maturity and the development of YY technology and its
proposed dissemination strategies in the Philippines.
	   Tilapia farm operators and interested entrepreneurs will surely
benefit from the manual's section on culture performance of GMT in
intensive hatchery production systems, and extensive to
semi-intensive pond production.
	   The manual was co-authored by Dr. Tereso Abella of CLSU and Dr.
Graham Mair of the University of Wales Swansea in the UK.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
