<SLUG> TENAGA-POISED-MALAKOFF sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tenaga poised to have 20pc stake in Malakoff, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Tenaga poised to have 20pc stake in Malakoff, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   TENAGA Nasional Bhd is poised to become a substantial
shareholder in Malakoff Bhd under a share swap exercise.
	   In a memorandum of understanding signed yesterday, Tenaga
Nasional has proposed to inject its entire stake in wholly-owned
subsidiary TNB Janamanjung Sdn Bhd into Malakoff.
	   The MoU will also see Tenaga Nasional injecting its 20 per cent
stake in Segari Energy Ventures Sdn Bhd into Malakoff, which
already holds a 75 per cent stake in it.
	   This will see the issue of new Malakoff shares to Tenaga
Nasional - with details of quantum and price to be finalised later.
	   Tenaga Nasional is finally expected to have at least a 20 per
cent stake in Malakoff.
	   Tenaga Nasional executive chairman Datuk Dr Tajuddin Ali
yesterday said in Kuala Lumpur that Malakoff was chosen for the
exercise as it was ``...
	   the best selection for the benefit of the company (Tenaga
Nasional), shareholders and country.
	   ``We have considered several options to ensure that the project
can be implemented and does not burden us in view of our current
financial position.''
	   The MoU is expected to be concluded within two months.
	   TNB Janamanjung is now building a 2,100MW coal-fired power plant
in Manjung, Perak, costing about RM6.9 billion.
	   The Manjung power plant is being built on 245ha of the 320ha of
reclaimed land in Teluk Penchalang about 10km south of Lumut in
Perak.
	   Of the 245ha, 70ha is for the power plant and 175ha for the ash
pond.
	   The remaining area will be used as port facilities, coal stock
piles and common access road.
	   The power plant will be based on three units of 700MW each. The
first unit is due for commercial operation in July, 2001.
Successive units are expected to come onstream at six-month
intervals.
	   On why Tenaga Nasional decided to dispose of its interest in
IPPs, Tajuddin said it was inconsistent with the utility's present
direction.
	   ``TNB Janamanjung was set up in early 1997 ... before my time
... It's not inconsistent with our future moves. It is the right
time for us to not be directly involved in the power generation
business.
	   Nevertheless, he described the disposal as ``something
consistent with the restructuring of the (energy and
telecommunications) industry.''
	   In a statement issued on behalf of Tenaga Nasional and Malakoff,
Commerce International Merchant Bankers Bhd said the proposal was
expected to provide long-term benefits to Tenaga Nasional.
	   Malakoff's Segari Energy owns a power plant in Lumut capable of
generating 1,303MW of electricity. Malakoff also has a 20 per cent
stake in Port Dickson Power Bhd, another IPP.
	   Malakoff is also acquiring from Malaysian Resources Corporation
Bhd the entire stake in Teknik Janakuasa Sdn Bhd - operator of the
Segari Energy Lumut plant - via another share swap.
	   MRCB is a substantial shareholder in Malakoff, and UK-based
National Power plc will acquire a 15 per cent stake in Malakoff -
based on the enlarged capital after the acquisition of Teknik
Janakuasa is completed.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
