<HEADLINE>
No reports on lay-offs from hotels: Minister, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
No reports on lay-offs from hotels: Minister, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ariff AwangASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Culture, Arts and Tourism Ministry has yet to receive any
reports on retrenchment in the hotel industry, its minister Datuk
Sabbaruddin Chik said.
	   He said hotel occupancy nationwide currently is still at 70 per
cent and this indicates that there are still ample career
opportunities in the industry.
	   ``With this high rate of hotel occupancy there is no reason for
hotel managements to retrench workers in this sector,'' he told
reporters after witnessing the Memorandum of Agreement between HRR
Travel-Trade Management Services Sdn Bhd and Wigan &AMP; Leigh College
of the UK in Kuala Lumpur yesterday.
	   The agreement signals the partnership between both organisations
for the provision of education and training in the hospitality and
tourism sector.
	   He pointed out that the hotel industry has slightly better
prospects this year compared with 1997 and the ministry forecasts
an increase in visitors due to the ringgit's depreciation, which
gives Malaysia a competitive edge, and the forthcoming Kuala Lumpur
Games '98.
	   Last year, he noted that 6.2 million tourists visited the
country, a 13- per cent drop compared with 1996, when the country
had 7.1 million visitors.
	   The ministry has revised its forecast for this year and expects
6.8 million tourists.
	   Sabbaruddin said the agreement between HRR Travel-Trade
Management Services and Weigh &AMP; Leigh College also indicates a
favourable outlook for the hospitality and tourism industry.
	   ``If prospects for the hospitality and tourism industry are
unfavourable fewer institutions will be offering such courses but
as a matter of fact there are more doing so,'' he said, adding that
students will not enrol for courses if job opportunities are not
promising.
	   So far, he said, the ministry has granted licences to 35
institutions to conduct training for the hospitality and tourism
industry and all of these institutions comply with National
Occupational Skill Standards requirements.
	   These requirements, he said, are in line with the Tourism
Industry Act 1992 under which all tourism training institutions
that provide ``multi skills'' courses have to be licenced.
	   The minister admitted that currently institutions which offer
multi skills courses in tourism are still insufficient and the
Government encourages the setting up of more such institutions.
	   At present, he said, there are about 130,000 employees working
in hotels in the country but the industry still lacks trained
personnel as not all hospitality and tourism graduates are absorbed
by the hotel sector.
	   Meanwhile, in Subang Jaya yesterday, Sabbaruddin also advised
hotels in the country to eliminate the ``double plus sign'' for
their room tariffs for the convenience of their guests.
	   Hotels should instead display a ``nett'' pricing for their room
rates, he told reporters after launching Faber Hotels Industry
Holdings Sdn Bhd's Malaysia Bagus Luxury Holidays packages.
	   ``If, for example, the rate is at RM100++, this means that
customers will have to pay RM115, which is inclusive of the RM10
for the 10 per cent service charge and RM5 for the 5 per cent
government tax.
	   ``Instead of displaying RM100++, hotels should instead fix the
pricing at RM115 from the beginnning,'' he said.
	   The ministry, he added had long suggested that hotels eliminate
the ``double plus sign'' pricing, but most were reluctant to take
up the proposal.
	   However, the Malaysian Hotel Association had at the end of last
month assured the ministry that all its member hotels will display
the nett pricing by October.
	   Sabbaruddin said the ministry does not intend to enforce the
proposal but leaves it to the hotels to consider the matter.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
