<HEADLINE>
Five-Month Car Sales Shrink 49%, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Five-Month Car Sales Shrink 49%, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Angel G. AlegreASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Passenger car sales fell 49% in the first five months of the
year to 17,146 units when measured against last year's record.
	   For the month of May alone, car sales slipped 55.3% to 2,951
units compared with the year-ago 6,603.
	   Rising car prices due to the weak peso discouraged sales, the
Chamber of Automotive Manufacturers of the Philippines Inc. said in
a report yesterday.
	   The industry group said higher down-payment requirements and
financing charges, and the slow and selective approval of financing
applications also led to poor turnover.
	   ``Passenger car sales continue to be adversely affected by
increased selling prices resulting from...the devaluation of the
peso,'' Campi said.
	   Mitsubishi Motor Philippines Corp., a unit of Mitsubishi Motors
Corp., sold the highest number of cars at 8,840 units during the
five-month period.
	   It was followed by Toyota Motor Philippines Corp., a unit of
Toyota Motor Co., which sold 6,927 units and Honda Cars Philippines
Inc., a unit of Honda Motor Co. Ltd., which sold 5,746 units.
	   
</TEXT>
