<HEADLINE>
RM4.5b contract awarded to Anglo-French firm, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
RM4.5b contract awarded to Anglo-French firm, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE RM4.5 billion engineering, procurement and construction
contract for the 2,100 megawatt power plant in Manjung, Perak has
been awarded to Anglo-French firm GEC Alsthom and consortium
partner Peremba Construction Sdn Bhd.
	   The power plant, valued at RM6.9 billion, is owned by Tenaga
Nasional Bhd's wholly-owned TNB Janamanjung Sdn Bhd. It will be
ready for commercial operations in mid-2001.
	   Funding for the RM4.5 billion EPC contract will come from export
credit agencies from the United Kingdom and France, GEC Alsthom
Power Plant Ltd managing director of power generation division Nick
Salmon said yesterday.
	   GEC Alsthom, which takes the technical and commercial lead for
the consortium, will be supplying the main mechanical plant
including turbines, generators and boilers.
	   Peremba Construction will carry out the construction and civil
works as well as provide the main electrical equipment.
	   ``We will ensure that local contractors would participate in at
least 40 per cent of the sub-contract works under the EPC
contract,'' said Salmon after receiving the EPC contract from
Energy, Telecommunications and Posts Minister Datuk Leo Moggie in
Shah Alam.
	   Moggie had earlier witnessed the signing of a power purchase
agreement between Tenaga Nasional Bhd and TNB Janamanjung Sdn Bhd
and presented the licence to TNB Janamanjung to generate power from
the plant.
	   TNB Janamanjung has been given a 25-year concession to generate
power from the Manjung plant. The power is sold to Tenaga Nasional
at 11.95 sen per kilo-watt hour.
	   Moggie said, in order to improve the country's competitiveness,
the energy supply system and services would have to be continuously
upgraded in terms of capacity, reliability and efficiency.
	   Noting that the country needed a generation capacity of 11,500MW
from the current maximum demand of 8,500MW to satisfy the expected
growth, he said that it was imperative to see a nominal reserve
margin of 30 per cent maintained against the backdrop of the
increasing demand.
	   
</TEXT>
