<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   With its historical relics undamaged by two world wars and
classical chamber music played live on shopping boulevards, Vienna
exceeded my wife Nina's expectations. She also experienced a number
of ``firsts'' such as hotel signs, which urged guests not to use
towels to preserve the environment against the ill effect of soap
chemicals.
	   In my case, the trip to Austria opened my eyes to Graz, a city
about 300 kilometers southeast of Vienna. As our train approached
Graz, the profile of the countryside grew in beauty...green hills
with tree farms cultured for pulp and grass meadows freshly trimmed
for animal feed.
	   Graz has its share of tourist sights. But to me Graz stands out
as a model of a successful dispersal program, an undertaking where
our own Board of Investments has so far failed to produce results.
With the development of industrial communities in the outskirts,
people are moving out of Graz. Of course, commercial establishments
in the city complain about decreasing business opportunities and
revenues. But the people of Graz are really benefiting from the
comfort of uncrowded facilities and traffic-free streets.
	   Peter Rosenkranz, a native of Graz and married to Nina's
ex-classmate Dely, however, now complains about German incursions
into the business scene.
	   German hardware stores, for instance, are coming in with a full
range of lower priced goods, specifically Chinese-sourced products.
Peter finds himself no longer competitive with wooden specialty
doors, which he imports from the Philippines.
	   Peter has decided to retire in the Philippines. But he will
certainly retain Graz as a vacation haven.
	   
</TEXT>
