<SLUG> SEEKING-CLARITY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Seeking clarity and purpose in Land Law provisions, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Seeking clarity and purpose in Land Law provisions, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Bhag SinghASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   WE LIVE in a country with good laws and generally law abiding
citizens. A good legal system is not only necessary to create a
stable society but also to protect and safeguard the individual's
rights.
	   However, laws sometimes have braoder and wider objectives beyond
merely regulating the conduct of individuals within a country or
providing boundaries for action.
	   A very early example of this broader objective may be seen in
Land Law.
	   At a time when Malaysia was not yet independent and needed to be
developed, there was a need to attract people who would invest and
help in the development of the country.
	   Land was cheap - at least by present day standards - and long
leases were offered. It may still be possible to come across leases
of 999 years in some parts of the country although one sees less
and less of such examples nowadays.
	   It was also common to alienate land on what was commonly called
a ``freehold'' basis but what is in our own context more
appropriately termed ``grant in perpetuity''. Similarly, the
changing of hands of land may be discouraged by placing
restrictions or imposing taxes.
	   However, the power to make such laws and the eventual enactment
of laws and regulations as well as the formulation of policies, are
tools which can be used to achieve certain desired objectives.
	   Thus in more recent times, such restrictions, especially with
regards to the purchase and sale of land by foreigners, have been
used to protect the local population. Foreigners may therefore only
buy properties of a certain value.
	   This has been achieved by means of incorporating specific
provisions in the National Land Code as well as requiring such
purchases to be approved by the Foreign Investment Commitee which
has its own guildelines for this purpose.
	   While foreigners are generally blamed for causing prices of
landed property to soar and making houses unaffordable for most of
the local population, this may not be unwelcome from the view of
the construction indsutry.
	   However, when such effects become widespread, there are likely
to be social and political repercussions. In this event, some
restraints are inevitable. In Malaysia, various restraints have
been imposed, setting out the price range of what may be purchased
alongside heavy ``levies'' on purchases by foreigners.
	   However, the fact remains that on occassion, the presence of
foreigners as purchasers of property, can be beneficial to the
local economic climate. This is especially so in times of economic
turmoil.
	   When an economic slowdown occurs, a country becomes more
concessionary to foreigners and makes available a broader range of
landed properties for them to buy. Levies may also be abolished in
the hope of attracting foreign investment.
	   While such swings and changes are not likely to enhance our
credibility with genuine long term investors, they may also not
serve our own expectations.
	   It was recently reported that the delay by the Foreign
Investment Committee in approving applications by foreigners
wishing to purchase houses costing more than RM250,000 has earned
the wrath of the Housing and Local Government Ministry.
	   This occurence is difficult to understand since the Government
had decided that houses above a certain value can be purchased by
foreigners.
	   Why should the agencies that have been given the task of
granting approvals be so slow in acting?
	   There seems to be an attitude amomgst some authorities granting
approvals that they may do so at their whim and fancy. They forget
that such departments and authorities are there to serve the people
in order that transactions may take place smoothly for the general
good of the country.
	   It would be beneficial to the country if the authorities could
provide definite guidelines and criteria for obtaining approvals in
respect of a particular transaction or category of transactions.
Where such criteria is met approval should follow as a matter of
course.
	   If this is done, then those who enter into transactions can
consider the criteria at the outset. In this manner, much time will
saved and productivity enhanced. Of course, this assumes that the
criteria are made known.
	   On the converse, exercising discretion without clear and
detailed guidelines can lead to abuse. Clearly detailed criteria
will help lessen any dissatisfaction and add to the general
credibility of any system.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
