<HEADLINE>
BMITA-PSD's 12th joint training programme for govt servants, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
BMITA-PSD's 12th joint training programme for govt servants, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Adeline OngASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE British Malaysian Industry and Trade Association (BMITA) and
the Public Services Department (PSD) announced yesterday their 12th
joint training programme for Malaysian government servants.
	   The programme offers a lengthy attachment as well as training
for Malaysian civil servants in British companies, which enables
them to gain genuine work experience in the private sector and to
complete commercial projects during the programme.
	   BMITA's chairman Mr Tim O'Brien said 11 senior government
officers will participate in the 1998 programme, which lasts for
six months and includes 18 weeks' attachment together with
management courses and the completion of commercial projects.
	   ``The programme begins on June 15 with two weeks' pre-attachment
training at the National Institute of Public Administration
(Intan),'' O'Brien said at a press conference in Kuala Lumpur.
	   Participating companies sponsoring a candidate each will be
Malaysian Tobacco Company Bhd, HongKong Bank Malaysia Bhd, ICI
Paints Malaysia Sdn Bhd, Teamwork Corp Sdn Bhd, Standard Chartered
Bank Malaysia Berhad, Rothmans of Pall Mall (M) Sdn Bhd, BP
Malaysia Sdn Bhd, Unilever Malaysia, British Airways and Commercial
Union.
	   Glaxo Wellcome and Malayan Cement will take two candidates each.
	   ``The programme will be funded by British interests, including a
contribution from the British Government. In the light of the
recent economic downturn, all elements of the programme will be
undertaken in Malaysia,'' he said.
	   He said the programme provides an opportunity for senior
government officers to experience the dynamics of modern day
business management systems.
	   ``The initiative reflects the emphasis placed on government and
business interests working together effectively to ensure the
continued, rapid development of Malaysia,'' he added.
	   This year's BMITA-JPA Management Development Programme will be
launched by Deputy Minister in the Prime Minister's Department
Datuk Fauzi Abdul Rahman on June 15.
	   The programme is linked with the ``Britain in Malaysia - Just
Between Friends'' initiative.
	   The first BMITA Management Training Programme was launched in
1983 with an attachment of 20 participants for a period of one
year.
	   Such training programmes have so far benefitted more than 160
government officiers from various departments and ministries.
	   BMITA was formed in 1963. It is an organisation made up or more
than 200 companies and individuals who are involved in trade
between Malaysia and Britain, British equity investments in
Malaysia and the provision of services in Malaysia through joint
ventures.
	   The primary objective of BMITA is to promote and foster
bilateral trade, services and investment between Malaysia and
Britain and to maintain and improve commercial and official
relationships between the two countries.
	   
</TEXT>
