<HEADLINE>
Honda's Lesson, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Honda's Lesson, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Tom Brokaw reported in his NBC newscast yesterday that Honda was
fined $70 million for dismantling anti-pollution devices in two
million of its cars that were sold in the US. We can only surmise
that the devices were removed to improve profitability. In any
event, $70 million is a hefty sum and surely Honda will have
learned its lesson, painfully.
	   I can only wonder what kind of anti-pollution devices are
required of vehicles sold in the Philippines. For one thing, new
vehicles are not even equipped with catalytic converters that are
used for unleaded fuel. In other words, using unleaded gasoline in
this country does not serve any anti-pollution purpose whatsoever.
In fact, if enough vehicles use unleaded gasoline without catalytic
converters, the resulting pollution will be even worse than that
emitted by leaded fuel.
	   Definitely A Priority Pollution from fuel emissions is killing
Metro Manilans. So cleaning up MM's air should definitely be a
priority because it involves the health of over 10 million
Filipinos. That is just about 20% of the population. What can be
more important than that?
	   
</TEXT>
