<BODY>
<SLUG> UNIT-TRUST-INDUSTRY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Unit trust industry expands despite economic slowdown, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Unit trust industry expands despite economic slowdown, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Pratap ParameswaranASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE local unit trust industry continued to grow despite the
economic problems with increasing number of units in circulation,
the Securities Commission (SC) said yesterday.
	   As at March 31 1998, 47.3 billion units were in issue, up 4.4
per cent from the end of 1997 and up 21.3 per cent from the end of
1996, SC chairman Datuk Dr Mohd Munir Abdul Majid said in his
address at the second annual unit trust conference and exhibition
held in Kuala Lumpur.
	   The industry itself was valued at about RM43 billion, accounting
for 9.5 per cent of the market capitalisation of the Kuala Lumpur
Stock Exchange.
	   There were 31 management companies in operation, with a total of
85 funds under management and six more funds approved but not yet
launched, said Munir.
	   ``Notwithstanding the growth however, the industry still has a
lot more promise, if indications and the experience in more
developed markets are anything to go by,'' he said.
	   He said that the development of unit trust funds would bring
about greater institutionalisation of the domestic market, and also
contribute to the efficiency, stability, breadth and depth of the
Malaysian securities market.
	   Munir also stressed that unit trust participants, particularly
management companies, needed to have proper standards, practices
and codes of conduct firmly in place.
	   Such standards and practices should be sufficiently detailed and
scrupulously observed, he stressed.
	   Touching on disclosure-based regulations, Munir said management
companies must come to terms with their duty to disclose all
information fully and in a timely manner in the prospectus, annual
and interim reports and other documents of a unit trust fund.
	   Meanwhile, Abdul Azim Mohd Zabidi, president of the Federation
of Malaysian Unit Trust Managers (FMUTM) in his welcome address,
warned that the impending liberalisation of the financial markets
under World Trade Organisation (WTO) rules, ``if done too quickly,
may result in the demise of a number of local players''.
	   Suggesting a number of steps to be taken before liberalisation,
Azim called for emphasis on what he called `intra-liberalisation'.
	   ``... We should encourage local unit trust management companies
to take a more active role in the regional, if not international
markets,'' he said.
	   Furthermore, local companies should strongly consider merging
amongst themselves so that the pooling of their resources will
place them in a better position to be more resilient and
competitive in the global market place, added Azim.
	   The local unit trust industry, Abdul Azim said, still has room
for enhancing professionalism, and in this light, FMUTM now
requires employees of unit trust management companies involved in
the marketing of unit trust products to register with the
federation.
	   This comes on the back of commencing the provisional
registration of all tied agents two years ago. As at the end of
May, the federation had 14,963 tied-agents from 14 unit trust
management companies registered.
	   Further move to inject professionalism in the industry include
requiring tied agents to sit for examinations conducted by the
FMUTM and commencing talks with the Mara Institute of Technology
(ITM) and the Securities Institutes of the UK and Australia to
develop relevant courses and to guide the federation in
establishing its own institute.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:UNIT-TRUST-INDUSTRY sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
