<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Chess-Computers </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kasparov and Topalov to battle assisted by computers
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LEON, Spain (AP) _ World Chess Champion Garry Kasparov of Russia
and Bulgarian Grand Master Veselin Topalov claimed one win each on
Wednesday in the first two matches of their experimental tournament
that permits constant consultation with computers.
	   The six-game competition held in this northern Spanish city has
been dubbed as the ``chess of the future'' by the players who sat
beside Chessmaster 5500 program, designed by the U.S. company
Mindscape.
	   The seating had to be rearranged before the competition began
when the Bulgarian said he could see Kasparov's screen.
	   Topalov appeared less at ease at the start, consulting the
computer more frequently than his Russian opponent before he
settled down to win the first game with the white pieces. He lost
the second with the black.
	   Each player was allowed a maximum 60 minutes to make their
moves, adding extra pressure to the human-computer dynamic. Normal
competition games that can sometimes stretch on for hours or even
days.
	   The next two matches in the groundbreaking challenge that seeks
to eliminate human error while retaining human imagination and
creativity were scheduled for Thursday.
	   No title is at stake but the winner will earn dlrs 6,600 and the
loser dlrs 3,000.
	   Without computers, Topalov, 23, the world's No. 4, has defeated
Kasparov twice and lost six of the 15 games they have played. The
remainder were draws.
	   Over the last quarter of a century computers, despite being
barred from professional competitions, have come to dominate the
chess world. Modern programs, many of them designed under
Kasparov's guidance, have proved themselves capable of beating most
humans, including Kasparov himself.
	   (jt)
</TEXT>
