<BODY>
<SLUG> RESIDENTS-POWER-PLANT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Residents: Power plant causing woes, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Residents: Power plant causing woes, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Patrick SennyahASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PORT DICKSON, Tues. - More than 60 families living near a power
plant in Tanjong Gemuk are at their wits' end over endless woes
allegedly caused by noise and vibration from its turbines.
	   Taman NLFCS Residents' Association committee chairman S. Gabriel
claimed that despite numerous appeals to the authorities on the
matter, no action had been taken and lately the situation had
worsened.
	   ``About three weeks ago, large cracks began appearing on the
road in front of our houses and the IPP's (independent power
producer's) perimeter fencing which we believe could have been
caused by vibration from the plant.''
	   He said some of the cracks were more than half a metre deep and
this caused fears that the road might soon collapse.
	   ``Now, we not only have to live with the noise and vibration but
also the damaged road.''
	   He said the residents moved into the two rows of 60 terrace
houses in 1992 while the plant, which began operating with a single
turbine, was set up in 1994.
	   ``Since 1995, the plant had been operating three turbines,
causing our plight to worsen,'' he said, adding that the turbines
were on from 8.30am to 8pm.
	   Gabriel said the vibration had also caused cracks on the walls
of some houses.
	   ``Despite numerous complaints to the authorities, no action has
been taken and now with cracks appearing on the road, we are really
worried for our safety.''
	   According to him, experts from the Department of Environment and
Universiti Kebangsaan Malaysia visited the area recently.
	   He said they had conducted tests at the place but to date
nothing had been done to solve their problems.
	   An official of the State DOE confirmed that tests had been
conducted and said a report had been submitted to the Menteri
Besar's office for further action.
	   The New Straits Times had highlighted the problem faced by the
residents in October 1996.
	   Former Port Dickson Power managing director/chief executive
officer Lt Kdr (R) Mohd Ismail Che Mat Din had replied then that
the noise and vibration were well within the limits set by the DOE.
	   He had said three independent tests carried out showed the noise
level to be not more than 60 decibels.
	   ``Each time we conduct the test, the plant will have to run the
turbines, costing us up to RM200,000,'' he had said, adding that
the plant was built after approvals were obtained from the
authorities.
	   Its Environmental Impact Assessment report had been approved by
the DOE.
	   He had said if the residents were still not satisfied with
measures taken by the company and the authorities, they could
appoint their own independent consultant to conduct tests at the
place.
	   ``If the independent tests showed that the plant did not breach
the limit, the residents must pay the costs.''
	   
</TEXT>
