</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> NO-WATCHLIST-BUY-EARLY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
No Watchlist But Yearly Monitoring: BSP, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
No Watchlist But Yearly Monitoring: BSP, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Arvin P. PanesASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Bangko Sentral ng Pilipinas (BSP) Governor Gabriel C. Singson
confirmed yesterday that banks with cashflow problems were
subjected to close monitoring every year.
	   ``Every year we have banks under close supervision,'' he said,
adding that there was nothing ``abnormal'' about putting illiquid
banks under stringent surveillance as this was in line with BSP's
functions.
	   Singson was reacting to a newspaper report (not The Business
Daily) that 17 financially-troubled banks were under tight
surveillance. The report came amid BSP's decision to close down
Commonwealth Savings Bank.
	   Commonwealth Savings Bank has been in the red for the past three
years due to a high nuber of past due loans. The bank's situation
worsened after its parent company Eyco Group had been declared
insolvent by the Securities and Exchange Commission.
	   ``It is not unusual since we close down small banks every
year,'' he said.
	   He stressed, however, that no more banks would be shut down this
year.
	   BSP Deputy Governor for Bank Supervision and Services Alberto V.
Reyes, however, denied the existence of a ''watchlist'' of troubled
banks.
	   ``It is fiction. There are no commercial, thrift, and rural
banks which are insolvent. The system is entirely healthy,'' he
said.
	   According to Reyes, central monetary authorities have been
religiously checking banks' foreign exchange position, level of
exposure to real estate, and consumer loans.
	   ``We have not been monitoring the banks supposed to have been
included in the list. But since July 1997, we have been monitoring
all banks' foreign currency transactions; their exposure to auto
and salary loans; and we are daily tallying the interest rates
charged by banks,'' Reyes said.
	   The BSP said the practice was meant to ensure compliance with
banking rules and regulations.
	   Reyes also said BSP was willing to give incentives to banks
which resort to mergers to gain viability.
	   Reyes said the perks would benefit both foreign and local banks.
``Such a move is being considered. It will be endorsed to the
Monetary Board as soon as the banks submit their proposals,'' he
said.
	   Reyes said the policy-making Monetary Board would review the
specific petitions of the industry's major organizations such as
the Bankers Association of the Philippines, the Chamber of Thrift
Banks, and the Rural Bankers Association of the Philippines.
	   One incentive would be to give a bank with excessive past-due
levels access to BSP's rediscounting window provided it merges with
another bank.
	   Reyes also said bank-owned properties appraised by
duly-designated assessors would be treated as capital.
	   ``The appraised fair market value should be evaluated by an
independent appraiser approved by the central bank,'' Reyes
explained.
	   The measures are on top of the current benefits allowed by BSP,
namely: extension of the 20% individual and 30% corporate ceilings
on bank ownership, and allowing banks to have more than 11
directors.
	   Under the Memorandum of Economic and Financial Program (MEFP)
between government and the International Monetary Fund, the BSP is
enjoined to come up with measures to protect local banks from the
effects of economic crises.
	   Banking reforms include raising banks' minimum capitalization,
``dealing expeditiously'' with troubled banks; and loan-loss
provisioning to serve as a safety net in case of loan defaults.
	   Meanwhile, Senator Juan M. Flavier yesterday asked Singson to
sack bank examiners who failed to detect huge loan exposures of
several small banks which have been closed or are facing
insolvency.
	   Flavier said huge cash outflow in the form of directors,
officers, stockholders and related interest (Dosri) loans and not
the currency crisis was to blame for the thrift banks' financial
woes.
	   ``The BSP, through bank examiners, is supposed to detect Dosri
loans to safeguard the money of depositors. We had several events
in the past and we should learn from them. Why did it happen again
this time? The loss of money of small time depositors should be
stopped,'' the senator stated.
	   Flavier pointed out that a bank could not hide a high Dosri
level without the connivance of bank examiners.
	   Orient Commercial Bank, Richmond Bank, and Mindanao Development
Bank are reportedly facing closure procedures as they have been on
extended bank holidays.
	   He also said he intended to file a bill that would require the
Philippine Deposit Insurance Corp. (PDIC) to increase the coverage
amount for deposits from the current P100,000 to P500,000.
	   ``The PDIC charter should be amended to increase the amount for
which deposit are covered by insurance because times have changed
and the value of the peso has gone down,'' Flavier maintained.
	   PDIC's charter was last amended in 1992 when Republic Act 7400
increased the maximum insurance coverage to P100,000 from the
previous figure of P50,000.
	   PDIC acts as receiver of banks ordered closed by the BSP. Its
functions include gathering, controlling, and taking charge of
assets and liabilities of banks that have been declared insolvent
by government.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
