<SLUG> BC-Iraq-Diplomatic Reshuffle,0251 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Saddam orders biggest diplomatic reshuffle since Gulf War
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Iraqi President Saddam Hussein has ordered
at least 10 ambassadors, including his half brother, to return to
Baghdad in his biggest diplomatic reshuffle since the Gulf War,
Iraqi diplomats said Wednesday.
	   Instructions sent to the embassies gave no reason for the move,
said the diplomats, speaking from several Middle Eastern embassies.
They said new ambassadors have been named to fill the vacancies.
	   The diplomats who were recalled include Saddam's half brother,
Barzan al-Tikriti, who was Iraq's representative to the U.N offices
in Geneva.
	   The Iraqi ambassadors to Yemen, Algeria, India, Tunisia,
Pakistan, Jordan, and the Cairo-based Arab League were also
recalled, said the diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity.
	   The envoy to the Arab League, Nabil Najim, is a close associate
to Saddam and a member of his Tikriti clan. He is expected to be
named an undersecretary in the Foreign Ministry, the diplomats
said.
	   Some 30 junior diplomats also were transferred to the Foreign
Ministry in Baghdad, they said.
	   Most of the ambassadors have been in their post for more than
eight years. Iraq routinely rotates its envoys every four years.
	   Several Iraqi ambassadors defected to the West after they were
moved from their post in the past few years. The last was Majid
al-Samarra'i, the ambassador to Bulgaria. He defected to Britain
last year. 	   
</TEXT>
