COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SINGAPORE's key stock index closed one per cent lower yesterday
as currency concerns overshadowed banking reforms aimed at turning
the city into a top Asian financial center.
	   The Straits Times Industrials index ended 11.36 points down at
1,117.21, off a low of 1,109.19, while the broader All-Singapore
index was down 0.22 points at 314.33.
	   Turnover rose to 144.081 million shares worth S$294.988 million,
from 109.539 million shares valued at S$207.338 million.
	   Falling stocks led those rising 142 to 131 with 318 others
unchanged.
	   Top gainer was Jurong Shipyard Ltd which rose 45 cents to
S$8.00, while the biggest loser was Creative Technology Ltd which
ended 40 cents lower at S$28.40.
	   Development Bank of Singapore Ltd's foreign tranche was the only
``Big Four'' bank to finish higher, adding 10 cents to close at
S$9.25 on volume of 2.12 million shares.
	   
</TEXT>
