<SLUG> FRESH-PUMPKINS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fresh pumpkins, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Fresh pumpkins, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   R.S. MurthiASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE SMASHING PUMPKINS - Adore (Virgin/73.21/LP): Arguably the
most adventurous of the alternative rock bands to emerge on the
scene this decade, The Smashing Pumpkins spring yet another
surprise on fans who expect more of the eclecticism that
characterised their last album, Mellon Collie And The Infinite
Sadness.
	   This is a pretty straightforward light-rock effort that owes
more to the British ambient movement than to any of the Seattle
grunge bands in terms of tone, texture and atmosphere.
	   Indeed, on the most effective cuts here, including Ava Adore and
Daphne Descends, synthesisers overshadow guitars. And the beats
have a strong electronic resonance.
	   Singer Billy Corgan's lyrics alternate between anguish and
ecstasy - extremes of emotion which bring an alluringly languid
beauty to the ballads here, especially the ethereal Once Upon A
Time.
	   It take a while to really get into the music, but once you do,
you'll be enthralled by the freshness of approach.
	   (Distributed by EMI) Performance: Sound: VARIOUS ARTISTS -
Twentieth Century Blues/The Songs Of Noel Coward (EMI/59:30/I):
More than any other songwriter of his time, Noel Coward defined the
charm of being British in a style of entertainment that was as
pride-stirring as it was self-mocking.
	   His Broadway-influenced songs evoke scenes of England in the
`30s and `40s as depicted in various films set in that era.
	   This tribute to Coward by contemporary artists has an equal
amount of hits and misses. But despite the shortcomings, it's still
an interesting project.
	   And you have people like Marianne Faithfull (Mad About The Boy),
Bryan Ferry (I'll See You Again) and Sting (I'll Follow My Secret
Heart) to thank for not overdressing Coward's work.
	   Texas (Parisian Pierrot), Pet Shop Boys (Sail Away), Suede (Poor
Little Girl) and Robbie Williams (There Are Bad Times Just Around
The Corner) among those who take too much liberty with the
material, making it sound like ordinary dance-pop fodder.
	   Proceeds from the album will go to the Red Hot AIDS Charitable
Trust.
	   (Distributed by EMI) Performance: 1/2 Sound: LENNY KRAVITZ - 5
(Virgin/66:35/I): Kravitz continues his rather extended journey
into the past, deftly recycling funk, soul and disco without
seeming blatantly derivative.
	   He's been doing this long enough to know how to make old ideas
sound fresh, and it's this ability to reinvigorate ripped-off riffs
that makes much of his new recording so engaging.
	   On some tracks, he will remind you of Prince at his most
inspired, but these moments are too few and far between to generate
excitement.
	   Still, there's enough here to remind you that what an undying
source of inspiration rock from the '60s and '70s is.
	   (Distributed by EMI) Performance: 1/2 Sound: DANNY WILDE + THE
REMBRANDTS - This Spin (EastWest/39:01/I): Best known as the band
that sang the Friends theme, The Rembrandts are pretty much a bunch
of lightweights with a gift for melody.
	   The songs here are catchy and boast a nifty line or two, but
they all seem to have a tiresome one-dimensional feel.
	   They would certainly work better as TV sitcom themes than
stand-alone pop pieces.
	   (Distributed by Warner Music) Performance: 1/2 Sound: HANSON - 3
Car Garage: The Indie Recordings '95-'96 (Mercury/Moe/45:01/I):
These are the demo sessions that got the three boys signed to a
major label and shot them to international fame.
	   It's a presentation of talent in its raw state, packaged for
fans who just can't get enough of the oh-so-cute things.
	   Well, it does show than the Hanson kids are no flash in the pan,
but really, it's just a demo collection that should have stayed in
the can.
	   Tracks include Day Has Come, With You In My Dreams and a
spirited but sparkless version of Mmmbop.
	   (Distributed by PolyGram Records) Performance: Sound:
ASIANDUBFOUNDATION - Rafi's Revenge (FFRR/49:03/I): Where dub meets
the East for a marriage that's not always happy.
	   The trouble is, the Eastern motifs serve as nothing more than
mild ornamentation on what are essentially frantically remixed
dance tracks.
	   And the ersatz rap style is not going to have any true fan of
the form convinced.
	   (Distributed by PolyGram Records) Performance: Sound: VARIOUS
ARTISTS - Allez! Ola! Ole! (Columbia/75:12/LP): Brought out to feed
the World Cup fever, this compilation features songs by artists
representing the various participating countries.
	   A project like this is, of course, going to have as many good
tracks as bad ones. So if you're thinking of buying it, check out
Do You Mind If I Play by Youssou N'Dour &AMP; Axelle Red, Don't Come
Home Too Soon by Del Amitri and Pais Tropical by Daniela Mercury
before you lay your money down.
	   (Distributed by Sony Music) Performance: Sound: RATINGS
Excellent Very Good Good Fair Poor I - Import LP - Locally Pressed
UPCOMING RELEASES The Love Movement - A Tribe Called Quest Spirit
Trail - Bruce Hornsby Other Voices Too - Nancy Griffith Volume VIII
- Anthrax Mermaid Avenue - Billy Bragg &AMP; Wilco We Ran - Linda
Ronstadt Awakenings - Color Me Badd TOP 10 POP/ROCK ALBUMS IN THE
U.S. THIS WEEK 1. City Of Angels/Motion Picture Soundtrack -
Various Artists 2. Godzilla: The Album/Movie Soundtrack - Various
Artists 3. It's Dark and Hell Is Hot - DMX 4. The Limited Series -
Garth Brooks 5. Backstreet Boys - Backstreet Boys 6. Before These
Crowded Streets - Dave Matthews Band 7. Sparkle - Sparkle 8. Songs
from Ally McBeal - Vonda Shepard 9. Come On Over - Shania Twain 10.
Titanic/Motion Picture Soundtrack - Various Artists
	   
</TEXT>
