Shares close broadly higher, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Shares close broadly higher, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) closed higher yesterday
on late strong buying interest especially on blue-chip stocks.
	   In early trading, the market was lacklustre and range-bound as
investors stayed sidelined and refrained from entering the market
in the absence of new leads, analysts said.
	   According to analysts, days of weakness and the firmer ringgit
helped to spur buying interest.
	   Blue-chips stocks, Malayan Banking rose 24 sen to RM5.20,
Telekom increased 30 sen to RM7.60, Petronas Gas jumped 35 sen to
RM8.15, and Dutch Baby moved up 30 sen to close at RM9.70.
	   The KLSE Composite Index (KLCI) rose 7.85 points to 505.64
compared with Monday's close of 497.79.
	   The Broader Emas Index increased 1.07 points to 129.53 while the
Second Board Index dipped 0.18 point to close at 108.87.
	   Across the causeway, the Singapore Straits Times Industrials
Index dropped 11.36 points to close at 1,117.21.
	   On the home front, the scoreboard showed gainers outpacing
losers 317 to 211 while 186 counters remained unchanged.
	   The broad-based BT Ordinaries inched up 0.82 point to 122.60
while the 30-share New Straits Times Industrial Index dipped 13.43
points to close 2,974.62.
	   Total turnover dropped to 84.244 million shares valued at
RM179.801 million yesterday compared with 99.210 million shares
valued at RM225.384 million on Monday.
	   Turnover on the main board was 69.730 million shares worth
RM166.170 million while trade on the Second Board was 6.485 million
shares worth RM11.416 million.
	   Malayan Banking was the most active counter with 11.122 million
shares, followed by Commerce-Asset with 4.164 million shares and
Magnum with 3.163 million shares done.
	   
</TEXT>
