<SLUG> KEN-HLGS-CONFIDENT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ken Hlgs confident of maintaining earnings, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Ken Hlgs confident of maintaining earnings, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Zety Fazilah BaharuddinASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KEN Holdings Bhd, with three government projects in Hong Kong
worth HK$130 million (HK$100  &QC;  RM53.80), is confident of
maintaining its profitability for the financial year ending
December 31 1998.
	   The construction and civil engineering group posted a pre-tax
profit of RM5 million, on the back of RM91.4 million in turnover.
	   Chairman and managing director Tan Boon Kang said the group is
working on the first Hong Kong project worth HK$30 million, while
the other two - amounting to HK$100 million - are still awaiting
approvals.
	   The group through its Hong Kong subsidiary, Kenly (HK) Ltd, has
secured specialist engineering projects which include
micro-tunnelling, soil- nailing, anchoring and slope rehabilitation
and stabilisation works.
	   Speaking after Ken Holdings' annual general meeting in Kuala
Lumpur yesterday, Tan said the contribution of overseas projects to
the group's earnings will increase.
	   Currently, about 75 per cent of the group's profit comes from
local projects, and the remaining 25 per cent from overseas.
	   Tan said the higher profit will also be achieved through its
on-going projects secured from the Malaysian Government and the
private sector totalling RM130 million.
	   On the local front, the group has deferred its RM17 million
condominium project in Petaling Jaya due to the slowdown in the
construction industry.
	   ``However, we are still hoping to complete the construction work
within the next three to four years,'' Tan said, adding that Ken
Holdings is currently seeking approval from the relevant
authorities to sell the property at a lower price.
	   If approved, the project is expected to generate sales of about
RM170 million.
	   Asked whether the group is exposed to ringgit fluctuations, Tan
said that it is fortunate because 90 per cent of its raw materials
are sourced locally. ``We purchase only machinery and parts.
Therefore, we are not affected.''
	   
</TEXT>
