<SLUG> BC-Britain-Obit-English, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sir David English, Associated Newspapers chief, dead at 67
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Updates throughout with career details, reaction, survivors &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Sir David English, chairman and group
editor-in-chief of Associated Newspapers _ who was editor of the
Daily Mail for more than 20 years_ died Wednesday after suffering a
stroke. He was 67.
	   English was admitted to St. Thomas's Hospital in London on
Tuesday and died on Wednesday, said Lawrence Sear, managing editor
of the Daily Mail.
	   English, who joined Associated Newspapers in 1969, became editor
of the Daily Mail in 1971 and transformed the tabloid over the next
two decades. In 1992 he was appointed overall editor of the group
whose other major newspapers include The Mail on Sunday and
London's Evening Standard.
	   Under his leadership, the Daily Mail became the self-assured
voice of middle England, identifying a fertile new market between
the traditional tabloid territory and the broadsheets.
	   He was knighted in 1982, and on Wednesday evening Prime Minister
Tony Blair's office announced that English was to have been given a
life peerage this week and made a member of the House of Lords.
	   Blair, told of English's death, called the newspaperman ``a
truly outstanding journalist. He never lost his love and enthusiasm
for his chosen profession and never lost his eye for a good
story.''
	   The Daily Mail's present editor, Paul Dacre, said, ``At heart he
was a newspaperman's newspaperman. ``He could do every job on the
paper better than anyone else and was an inspiration to everybody
who worked with him at the Mail.''
	   Said Lord Rothermere, chairman of the Daily Mail, ``He was
simply the best of his generation and the most able and talented
editor that I and Fleet Street have known. He took over the
editorship of the Daily Mail at the lowest ebb in its fortunes and
carried out with genius its conversion to a middle market
tabloid.'' -	   English's competitors, too, praised his skills.
	   ``David English was the newspaper genius that every journalist
of my generation looked up to and aspired to emulate,'' said Piers
Morgan, editor of The Mirror. ``He was a brilliant editor, a superb
technician and the most formidable of opponents.''
	   David Montgomery, chief executive of Mirror Group, called
English ``The greatest master of popular tabloid journalism of his
generation.''
	   Simon Kelner, editor of The Independent, called English ``truly
the journalist's journalist.''
	   And, ``If there has been a greater journalist, I've not met
him,'' said Kelvin MacKenzie, former deputy chief executive of
Mirror Group Newspapers and former editor of The Sun.
	   ``David was a colossal figure in post-war British journalism. He
defined the craft of newspapering for generations of young
journalists,'' said Les Hinton, executive chairman of News
International.
	   English is survived by his wife, Lady Irene, and three children.
No funeral arrangements were announced.
	   (acw)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Britain-Obit-English, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
