<SLUG> BC-Nigeria, 3rd Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nigerian opposition angrily dismisses new leader's promises
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS with five grafs to UPDATE with opposition planning to
challenge new leader's appointment in high court. Pickup 4th graf
pvs: To the contrary, ... &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By TIM SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Angrily dismissing vague promises of a
transition to civilian rule, Nigeria's opposition movement
Wednesday lashed out at the country's new ruler and called for
Nigerians to reject his government.
	   Gani Fawehinmi, a Lagos attorney and one of the country's
best-known opposition activists, said he would file a suit in the
Nigerian high court challenging the appointment of Gen. Abdulsalam
Abubakar.
	   Fawehinmi said there was nothing in Nigerian law to say that a
chief of defense staff succeeds the head of state. Abubakar took
the helm of Africa's most populous nation after the death Monday of
Gen. Sani Abacha, a close ally who had run Nigeria as a
dictatorship for five years.
	   ``Nigerians must intensify their struggle to end military
rule,'' Fawehinmi said. ``Nigerians should expect nothing but a
continuation of economic persecution and political oppression.''
	   The denunciations followed a televised speech Tuesday by
Abubakar, who promised to proceed with a transition to civilian
rule that Abacha began. He gave no details on how that would
happen.
