<HEADLINE>
Federation wants merger of unit trust firms, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Federation wants merger of unit trust firms, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Federation of Unit Trust Managers plans to submit a
blueprint to the Securities Commission which consists, among
others, a proposal to merge the country's unit trust companies.
	   Federation president Abdul Azim Mohd Zabidi said FMUTM was
finalising details of the blueprint and would present the plan to
the regulatory body within two weeks.
	   There are 35 unit trust companies in the country.
	   Abdul Azim said the federation did not put a definite target on
the number of unit trust companies after the merger.
	   ``The recent merger of finance companies has resulted in the
final number of eight companies ... we might be looking at
something like that.''
	   The proposed merger would ensure the growth of the unit trust
industry with the eventual liberalisation of the financial sector,
he told reporters after the official opening of the second annual
Unit Trust Conference and Exhibition in Kuala Lumpur yesterday.
	   The conference was officiated by Deputy Prime Minister and
Finance Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim.
	   Abdul Azim said other matters in the blueprint included tax
issues which continued to be a constraint to product appeal, adding
that the federation was seeking tax relief and tax exemption on
investment of unit trust funds.
	   ``The proposal on the tax issue had been mooted to the Finance
Ministry two weeks ago.''
	   He said the tax relief and exemption were in areas such as
long-term savings plans, funding for retirement through unit trusts
and exemption of interest income received by unit trusts.
	   The blueprint will also cover issues on cross-border sales to
allow unit trust companies to increase their investment in foreign
stock markets.
	   The increase in foreign investment would also increase the unit
trust industry market capitalisation, he said adding that market
capitalisation was targeted to increase to 40 per cent within the
next 15 years.
	   Abdul Azim said including Amanah Saham Nasional, Amanah Saham
Bumiputera and Amanah Saham Wawasan, the market capitalisation was
at 9.5 per cent.
	   ``But if we take out the funds, it's only about 2.5 per cent.
So, there is massive room for improvement over the next years in
the unit trust industry.''
	   Abdul Azim said although the SC allowed managers in the unit
trust industry to invest outside Malaysia, they were constrained by
Bank Negara in terms of exchange control regulations.
	   Under the SC guideline, the managers can invest up to 90 per
cent, but most exposure on foreign investment by the central bank
is up to 10 per cent of the value of the fund.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
