<HEADLINE>
Sarawak Oil Palms to expand interest in estates, refining, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Sarawak Oil Palms to expand interest in estates, refining, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PRODUCTION of fresh fruit bunches (FFB) is expected to fall this
year due to the prolonged drought in northern Sarawak, Sarawak Oil
Palms Bhd chairman Datuk Amar Hamid Bugo says in his annual
statement.
	   However, this has been cushioned by the large upsurge in crude
palm oil (CPO) prices at the end of last year and a further
increase to RM2,000 a tonne during the first quarter of this year.
	   The new kernel crushing facilities in Bintulu and the reduction
in forwarding costs, too, have compensated for the lower FFB crops
and it augurs well for 1998.
	   To strengthen its position, the group's is negotiating with
relevant parties to expand its oil palm interest, both in
plantations and refining.
	   It is expected to be completed within this year.
	   Reviewing operations last year, Hamid says the group established
a nursery for 85 per cent-owned subsidiary SOP Plantations (Suai)
Sdn Bhd, with first plantings projected within 1998.
	   The group also started replanting to replace mature palms, to
maintain the production of FFB.
	   In line with the expansion of its plantation interests, three
subsidiaries were established - SOP Plantations, a joint venture
with Sarawak State Financial Secretary Inc, SOP Plantations
(Balingian) Sdn Bhd a joint venture with Lembaga Masjid Mukah, and
SOP Plantations (Niah) Sdn Bhd.
	   The three subsidiaries will facilitate the development of
integrated oil palms projects.
	   Sarawak Oil Palms posted a group pre-tax profit of RM20.79
million for the year ended December 31 1997, compared to the
previous RM18.66 million.
	   Turnover, however, was lower at RM54.68 million in 1997, against
RM57.52 million in 1996. Profit after tax was RM14.29 million
compared with RM12.69 million previously.
	   Earnings per share came to 15.05 sen compared with 13.37 sen in
the previous year. No dividend has been recommended.
	   
</TEXT>
