<HEADLINE>
Singer expects sales to go up, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Singer expects sales to go up, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SINGER (Malaysia) Sdn Bhd, a wholly-owned subsidiary of Berjaya
Singer Bhd, expects its sales to increase by between five per cent
and 10 per cent for the current financial year through its ``Mega
Double'' consumer promotions campaign.
	   Singer managing director San Wan Hing said the company recorded
turnover of more than RM400 million for the year ended Dec 31,
1998.
	   He was speaking to journalists after the launching of the
promotion campaign, starting from this month to August, by Berjaya
Singer deputy executive chairman Tengku Datuk Adnan Tengku Mansor
in Kuala Lumpur yesterday.
	   At the ceremony, Tengku Adnan also presented a mock cheque for
RM1.5 million to Bank Simpanan Nasional chairman Datuk Ahmad Zahid
Hamidi.
	   The cheque is to acquire BSN premium savings certificates, which
will be given away as gifts to qualified customers.
	   During the promotion campaign, each customer buying singer
products valued at RM995 and above, in cash or with its easy
payment scheme, is entitled to a minimum of two units and a maximum
of five units of the BSN premium savings certificates.
	   In addition, customers can participate in the ``double''
contests - BSN's premium draws (in July, August and September) and
a Singer contest.
	   Tengku Adnan said the Singer contest offers more than RM200,000
worth of prizes, which range from Kriss motorcycles to holiday
packages and a whole range of Singer products.
	   San said the company is expected to increase the price of its
products by a single digit percentage in the second half of this
year.
	   ``So far we have been maintaining the prices at the same level
and absorbing the extra cost,'' he said.
	   On the company's operation, he said Singer plans to increase its
sales agents by 10 per cent nationwide from the current 4,000.
	   Singer retails and markets an extensive range of furniture and
household electrical durables which carry the Singer label.
	   The company has been marketing its products in Malaysia for 93
years.
	   
