<SLUG> GOLDEN-PHAROS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Golden Pharos optimistic of return to black, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Golden Pharos optimistic of return to black, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Francis FernandezASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   GOLDEN Pharos Bhd is confident of returning to the black this
year, going by the performance achieved in the year's first half
compared with last year's corresponding period.
	   Chairman Datuk Mohd Azahar Othman said the confidence stems from
Golden Pharos' ability to garner RM5 million in sales revenue per
month from the export of its high end doors to its main markets in
the US and Europe.
	   He was speaking to reporters after the group's annual general
meeting yesterday. For the financial year ended December 31 1997
Golden Pharos posted a group after tax loss of RM19.06 million
together with a turnover of RM141.84 million and a loss per share
of 16.4 sen.
	   Currently out of the group's production output of 18,000 doors
per month, 99 per cent of the output are exported to US and Europe
and Golden Pharos is hopeful that once it gets the Forest
Sustainable Certification sometime this year, it will be in a
better position to sell its products in the European market.
	   This certification, Mohd Azahar said is needed by the year 2000,
by the United Kingdom and other European countries to enable the
group to export its products to this markets.
	   Meanwhile for the expectation of higher exports, the company
would increase the production capacity to 20,000 doors per month,
he said.
	   The company would continue to focus on producing high-end doors
and its plan to venture further downstream to produce pre-finished
doors has been deferred due to the current economic situation, he
said.
	   Mohd Azahar also said that the company has 140,000 ha forest
concession in Terengganu which would allow them to source
internally rather than to source for higher price of raw material
from the open market.
	   
</TEXT>
