<SLUG> PHASE-ONE-OF-SC'S-READY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Phase one of SC's guidelines ready, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Phase one of SC's guidelines ready, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Securities Commission has completed phase one of formulating
marketing guidelines of unit trust funds for the marketing staff of
banks.
	   This includes developing disciplinary procedures for agents and
sales people with the aim of enhancing sales practices in the
industry. It is expected to commence later this year.
	   The formulation of phase two of the marketing guidelines for
institutional agents will commence in the second half of this year.
	   In addition, the Securities Commission will be promoting good
practices and compliance among management companies (companies
which establish the funds) through enforcing minimum standards for
compliance and internal controls, said its issues and investment
division manager Jas Bir Kaur in Kuala Lumpur yesterday.
	   She was presenting a talk on ``The regulatory framework of unit
trust funds'' at the Second Annual Unit Trust Conference and
Exhibition organised by the Federation of Malaysian Unit Trust
Managers.
	   She said the Securities Commission would also be promoting good
accounting and reporting practices among management companies,
especially in the areas of improving interim and annual reports.
	   Besides the Securities Commission, other regulatory authorities
include Bank Negara, the Ministry of Finance, the Economic Planning
Unit, the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange and Registrar of Companies.
	   During her talk, Jas Bir said the Malaysian unit trust fund
industry, which may be generally categorised as equity funds, fixed
interest funds and Islamic funds, had a net asset value of RM42.9
billion with about 47.3 billion units in circulation among 83
funds.
	   Its assets account for 9.49 per cent of the Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exchange market capitalisation and 14 per cent of the total fund
management industry sized at RM234 billion.
	   There are currently 8.33 million accounts in existence and the
average holding per account stands at about 5,700 units (including
those under Permodalan Nasional Bhd such as Amanah Saham Nasional
and Wawasan 2020).
	   
</TEXT>
