</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> UNIT-TRUST-BODY-TO sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Unit trust body to submit code of ethics to SC next week, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Unit trust body to submit code of ethics to SC next week, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Pratap ParameswaranASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Federation of Malaysian Unit Trust Managers (FMUTM) is
expected to submit a code of ethics for fund management companies
to the Securities Commission next week.
	   The federation's professional ethics committee, in a six
month-long process, has finalised the code after consultation with
its members, said executive director Jacob Thomas yesterday.
	   The code, containing the industry's minimum best practices, will
require fund management companies to be more stringent in their
operations, he said, adding that the federation has looked at
models of other countries before coming up with the code.
	   ``The code is a basic one, ...and members can add on later if
they want,''
	   said Jacob.
	   The main issue inherent in the code is that of investment, Jacob
said.
	   One of the guidelines stipulates that an investment manager is
discouraged from making an investment in a personal capacity a week
before and after his or her fund management company makes a similar
investment.
	   The code, to contain a list of approved stockbrokers, will also
have guidelines so that transactions by stockbrokers can be
monitored, Jacob said.
	   Jacob said this to reporters at the sidelines of the second
annual unit trust conference and exhibition, and the unveiling of
the federation's new corporate logo and website, held in Kuala
Lumpur.
	   Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister Datuk Seri Anwar
Ibrahim officiated at the conference and delivered a keynote
address at the event.
	   Meanwhile, the SC said it will continue to promote good
compliance and control among fund management companies as part of
its three-year business plan beginning 1998.
	   One of the thrusts in the plan is its collaboration with the
FMUTM in coming up with a code of ethics, said Ms Jas Bir Kaur,
manager of the SC's issues and investment division in her speech at
the conference.
	   ``The SC, in its audit of management companies, have come across
inadequate internal controls and compliance, and varying degrees of
control in these companies,'' she said.
	   The SC wants to ensure a high level of minimum standards for
fund management companies, she said in her paper, ``The Regulatory
Framework of Unit Trust Funds''.
	   Part of the plan also includes, having these companies adopt
good accounting and reporting practices which included making unit
trust prospectus more reader-friendly.
	   Furthermore unit trust companies need to adopt a more
appropriate dividend policy with their disclosure of where the
dividends are coming from, she said.
	   In his paper on ``The Role &AMP; Responsibilities of the Trustee'',
Ms Ong Sau Yin, managing director of HSBC (Malaysia) Trustees Bhd,
said trustees have a wider role to play in providing investment
managers with comprehensive operations and fund administration
support.
	   ``The wider role, not only includes trustee and custodianship
services but also registrar services, fund valuation and full
accounting services,''
	   she said.
	   Ong also said that the feeling within the industry is that the
appointment of trustees for fund management companies by the SC
will no longer be an automatic process.
	   There is a possibility that the SC will see whether the trustee
has the necessary financial and human resources, and the required
systems in place before taking on the role of a trustee for fund
management companies.
	   The SC may even conduct a due diligence audit on the trustee
before granting approval, she said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
