<SLUG> BC-Hungary-Chess,0242 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Polgar leads 3-1 after second day of play against Karpov
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) _ Hungary's Judit Polgar, the world's top
woman chess player, held a 3-1 lead Wednesday over reigning world
champion Anatoly Karpov halfway through a four-day competition.
	   In the first game of the day, Polgar, 21, played the black
pieces, and started with a Ben-Oni defense. Karpov, of Russia, took
a slight advantage but then lost on time after the 82nd move.
	   In speed matches the players have 30 minutes each.
	   In the second game of the day, Karpov, 47, fought with the
Caro-Kann defense, and the game ended in a tie with the 57th move.
	   ``I think I was not for a moment threatened to be defeated
today. It will be tough in the next days, but I feel well and am
confident,'' Polgar said after Wednesday's competition.
	   ``Judit dominated the whole day, but Karpov is such a great
chess player that he is capable of surprising us even from such a
losing position,'' international master Janos Szabolcsi said.
	   The competition, sponsored by the state oil company MOL and
several smaller companies, is the first time in chess history that
the top male and female chess players have competed.
	   This was the second day of a four-day, eight-game speed match
challenge. Each win is worth one point, while a tie is worth a
half-point.
	   Polgar won one match on the first day of competition and tied in
the second. 	   
</TEXT>
