<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Arafat </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Newspaper: Arafat may retire after signing withdrawal deal
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ A government-owned newspaper said that
Yasser Arafat will step down as leader of the Palestinian Authority
for health reasons, possibly after signing a deal with Israel on a
withdrawal from the West Bank.
	   The Al-Gomhuriya newspaper reported in its early Thursday
edition that Ahmed Qurai, head of the Palestinian Legislative
Council, or Salim Zaanoun, speaker of the Palestine National
Council, will take over until a new president is elected.
	   The newspaper said it based its report on Palestinian sources,
but did not further identify the sources.
	   ``Palestinian sources confirmed that Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat will retire for health reasons,'' the newspaper said.
	   The newspaper said its sources ``suggested that Arafat may
retire after signing the agreement with Israel on the Israeli
withdrawal from the West Bank.''
	   Israel's Cabinet is expected to vote by the end of the week on a
U.S. initiative for a 13 percent pullback from the West Bank, which
Israel seized from Jordan in the 1967 Mideast War. The Palestinians
already have accepted the proposal.
	   Arafat is expected in Cairo Thursday for talks with President
Hosni Mubarak on the stalled Middle East peace process.
	   There have been persistent rumors that the health of the
68-year-old Palestinian leader is failing.
