<SLUG> PENGKALEN'S-RIGHTS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pengkalen's rights issues to be bigger, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Pengkalen's rights issues to be bigger, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Desmond NgiamASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PENGKALEN Holdings Bhd and its subsidiary Pengkalen Capital Bhd
have increased the size of the rights issues announced on March 9
to raise more cash to beef up the capital base of the group's two
stockbroking firms.
	   Under the two revised rights issue proposals, the group will
realise higher proceeds totalling about RM1.02 billion compared to
RM650.32 million from the original proposals.
	   Kimara Equities Sdn Bhd and Pengkalen Securities Sdn Bhd,
subsidiaries of Pengkalen Capital, were placed under trading
restrictions by the Securities Commission on April 23 and May 7,
respectively, for failing to fulfil the minimum liquid funds
requirement.
	   In a statement issued yesterday, Pengkalen Holdings announced
the revision of its original two-for-one rights issue of 397.23
million new shares at RM1 each to a three-for-one rights issue of
595.84 million shares at RM1 each.
	   Pengkalen Capital, in a separate statement, announced the
revision of its original three-for-one rights issue of 253.09
million shares at RM1 each to a five-for-one rights issue of 421.81
million shares at RM1 each.
	   Pengkalen Holdings said the revision of its original rights
issue was to ``raise larger capital in view of the increase in the
size of the cash call by its subsidiary Pengkalen Capital''.
	   Of the proceeds of RM595.84 million accruing to Pengkalen
Holdings under its revised rights issue, RM220.43 million will be
used to subscribe for its entitlement of 220.43 million new shares
under Pengkalen Capital's revised rights issue.
	   Another RM366 million will be used to repay bank borrowings
and/or to apply for any excess application in Pengkalen Capital's
rights issue, and RM9.41 million as working capital.
	   Pengkalen Holdings said its parent company, Malayan United
Industries Bhd which currently holds a 80.72 per cent stake in it,
had agreed to subscribe for its full entitlement amounting to
480.94 million shares.
	   Pengkalen Capital said the revision of its rights issue was to
accommodate a larger size of capital raising for injection into
Kimara Equities and Pengkalen Securities.
	   Of its proceeds of RM421.81 million, RM267 million will be used
to subscribe for its entitlement of 267 million new shares under
Pengkalen Securities' revised rights issue, and RM148 million to
subscribe in new shares of Kimara Equities. Another RM6.81 million
will be used as working capital for Pengkalen Capital.
	   It also said Kimara Equities and Pengkalen Securities yesterday
obtained a six-month restraining order from the High Court against
all further intended actions against the two stockbroking firms.
	   
</TEXT>
