<SLUG> MALAYAN-CEMENT-BRACES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Malayan Cement braces for drop in profit, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Malayan Cement braces for drop in profit, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Vasantha GanesanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   DUE to a steep drop in demand for cement in the region, local
cement manufacturer, Malayan Cement Bhd anticipates lower pre-tax
profits for the financial year ending December 31 1998.
	   ``Profits will be reduced for the current financial year, since
there is a reduction of 25 per cent from the cement activities
itself,'' Malayan Cement's managing director, Jeffery C. Pope said
after the company's annual general meeting yesterday.
	   For the financial year ended December 31 1997, the group
recorded a RM172.28 million pre-tax profit on the back of a
RM921.94 million turnover.
	   It is estimated that in Peninsular Malaysia alone between
January and May this year, cement consumption has contracted by
some 25 per cent compared to the corresponding period last year.
	   In view of the reduction, Pope said exports to other potential
markets are being developed.
	   ``We are (currently) exporting clinker to Singapore and
supplying to grinding plants in Malaysia,'' he said, adding that
the export market is also limited as the whole Asian region is
experiencing an excess of clinker.
	   When asked if the company will look into exporting to North and
South America, Pope said there is only a slim possibility since
shipping cost is very high.
	   Additionally, the lower demand in the region's cement industry
has caused Malayan Cement, a member of the Blue Circle Group, to
reduce its production significantly, but below 25 per cent.
	   Pope said the excess of supply had caused the export price to
fall below the domestic price by 30 to 35 per cent in terms of US
dollars.
	   Meanwhile, Malayan Cement announced that Mr Alister Cox will be
appointed as managing director in place of Pope upon his secondment
to another company within Group.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
