w2000 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  NEED-FOR-CLEAR-PLANSsked     06-10 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> NEED-FOR-CLEAR-PLANS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`Need for clear expansion plans', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
`Need for clear expansion plans', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ALL telecommunications firms must draw up clear network
expansion plans to allow for easier co-operation between the
players - with the aim of providing better services to customers
within the country.
	   Energy, Telecommunications and Posts Minister Datuk Leo Moggie
yesterday said this was a requirement already stated in the
telecommunications licences - known as Universal Service Obligation
(USO).
	   So far, only Telekom Malaysia had submitted this USO plan, he
said after chairing a dialogue between the ministry and its
industry players in Kuala Lumpur.
	   The other operators, while having drawn up network expansion
plans, have not finalised when they would ``roll-out'' their
infrastructure expansion - largely due to the need to optimise
investment funds in the current economic climate.
	   These operators are Binariang Bhd, Celcom (Malaysia) Sdn Bhd,
Mutiara Telecommunications Sdn Bhd, Time Telecommunications Sdn Bhd
and PrismaNet (Malaysia) Sdn Bhd.
	   Given the difficulties involved in getting commitments from all
operators on their roll-out plans, Leo Moggie suggested that the
Telecommunications Department draw up an industry-wide roll-out
plan instead.
	   He said: ``We have not come up with the detailed plan but we
believe that other players must also participate in some aspect of
the USO.''
	   Leo Moggie said the ministry might look at the licensing
conditions of the existing telecommunications companies as a means
to compel then to participate in the USO.
	   ``There might be some existing criteria in the licence which can
be used as a requirement for the telecommunications companies to
have a roll-out plan.''
	   Leo Moggie said that nothing definite had been decided yet.
	   Meanwhile, an analyst said that it was high time the ministry
introduced steps to allow the telecommunications player to assist
Telekom Malaysia in constructing networks.
	   ``This topic of reducing Telekom Malaysia's burden of building
networks in rural areas has been talked about for a long time but
to no avail,'' she said.
	   ``The move should be implemented before equal access becomes a
reality.
	   ``I think it is only fair for other players to share the cost of
constructing networks in the country,'' another analyst said.
	   At the dialogue, Leo Moggie said there were fewer complaints on
the energy, telecommunications and posts services from industry
players as well as related associations.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
