<SLUG> PALM-OIL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Palm oil, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Palm oil, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   CRUDE palm oil physicals were down by RM30 to RM2,350 in line
with the continued weakness of futures prices yesterday.
	   The price was at the high end and there was also uncertainties
brought about by volatile swings on the ringgit, a dealer said.
	   On the Kuala Lumpur Commodity Exchange, crude palm oil futures
continued to slide on lack of fresh and positive leads.
	   June lost RM28 to settle at RM2,330, July shed RM22 to RM2,311,
August was down RM22 to RM2,288 and September lost RM24 to RM2,273.
	   Turnover increased to 1,162 lots from 774 lots on Monday but
open interest decreased to 6,769 contracts from 6,853 contracts.
	   JF Apex Futures Sdn Bhd said futures prices opened lower and
continued to slide in early trading before being confined to a
narrow range.
	   Prices slipped further in afternoon trading after the ringgit
strengthened to 3.9450 to the US dollar.
	   JF Apex Futures said the CPO futures were expected to trade
sideways in thin volume in the coming days with a downside
potential capped at the RM22.60 level due to the absence of fresh
fundamentals.
	   
</TEXT>
