<SLUG> CALL-TO-CONSIDER sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Call to consider `re-nationalising' projects of national interest, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Call to consider `re-nationalising' projects of national interest, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Shahriman JohariASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Government should consider taking back privatized projects
of national interests into the public sector's fold as the private
sector may not be capable in handling them in the present slowdown.
	   The director and Head of Malaysian Research with Salomon Smith
Barney in Singapore Azman Mokhtar said, hence certain projects
which are strategic in nature and clear in national interest have
to be somewhat ``re- nationalised'' and maintained by the
Government due to the private sector's incapacity to handle them.
	   Azman did not name any of these projects as specifics but gave a
few examples such as the Bakun Dam and the Mass Transit System.
	   The multi-billion Bakun hydro-electric project is expected to
fulfill the country's future energy needs. Costing some RM13.6
billion, the contract was awarded to Ekran Bhd.
	   Last year, as a result of the economic downturn, the Government
has deferred a total of RM65 billion worth of projects which
included Bakun.
	   Ekran then announced that it was no longer interested with the
project after the Government's decision to delay the project. The
Minister of Finance Incorporated has since taken over the
construction of the dam.
	   On the Mass Transit System, Azman said that not many of these
projects are privatized in the world. This is due to its importance
as a public transportation project which will benefit the country.
	   ``In the case of bailouts, we should take a step back and deal
with it on a case by case basis, whether the projects to be taken
over are strategic and fit with national interest,'' he mentioned.
	   However, similar to Pengurusan Danaharta Nasional Bhd, the
national asset management company set up to take up non-performing
loans, re- nationalisation should be a temporary measure by the
Government, Azman stressed.
	   He was speaking to reporters after presenting a paper on
``Malaysian Economic Analysis'' at an executive briefing on
``Transforming the Corporation for Global Competitiveness: A CEO's
Imperative'', yesterday.
	   The briefing was organised by Intaha Consulting Sdn Bhd.
	   Meanwhile, Azman also mentioned that the Yen's alarming fall
could yet trigger another currency devaluation effect in Asia, more
so if China is pressured into devaluating its yuan.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
