AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KOLEJ Tuanku Ja'afar, the only independent, co-educational
secondary boarding school in Mantin, offers a strong boarding
system for students.
	   Its principal Patrick Briggs said the system was at the core of
college life which enabled students to achieve personal development
while gaining an education.
	   ``Self-discipline is crucial to success and there are many
examples of individuals who have obtained places in universities in
the UK, US and Australia, as a result of the start they received at
Kolej Tuanku Ja'afar,'' Briggs said.
	   To name a few, since early this year, Ainul Hazura Mohd Rashid
is pursuing an Engineering course at the Imperial College London
together with another former KTJ student, Seung Taek Oh.
	   Cambridge has accepted Muhammad Nurazli Razali to pursue Land
Economy at Robinson College while Heng Yen Lee is studying Chemical
Engineering at Christ's College.
	   Todate, there are 12 KTJ scholars pursuing or have completed
various degree courses at top UK universities.
	   Engineering student Tan Yee Ho of the Jesus College in Oxford,
who scored four A grades at A-level, is the second KTJ product
accepted by the university.
	   The college has a conducive environment for studies.
	   Its director of studies Anthony Finch offers guidance on the
choice of subjects for students from Form Four to Lower Six.
	   Finch also assists students to select tertiary courses.
	   KTJ started with 150 students in 1992. It has an enrolment of
520 now.
	   In line with its drive to improve itself, more facilities are
being provided including a new boarding houses this year.
	   Sixth Form students will have their own rooms.
	   There will also be a resident tutor and matron in each house
which will have a surau, a library, laundry room and pantry.
	   The college also organises Sunday activities like expeditions,
games and club functions to ensure students have a holistic
education.
	   KTJ A-level courses will commence in August. Registration is
open for the next intake.
	   
</TEXT>
