<HEADLINE>
Council to get more people to use local ports, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Council to get more people to use local ports, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Alex ChoongASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Malaysian National Shippers' Council is embarking on a drive
to get more importers, exporters and shippers to use local ports,
its president Datuk Kerk Choo Ting said yesterday.
	   ``We have already upgraded our port facilities, transport system
and moving into a complete paperless transaction with the
application of electronic data interchange,'' he added.
	   Kerk, who is also the Deputy Minister of International Trade and
Industry, said according to 1995 statistic more than 37 per cent of
the country's cargo for export and import used the Singapore port.
	   ``We are talking of about 5.6 million containers (TEUs) entering
or leaving Singapore port,'' he added.
	   If only another 20 to 30 per cent of these containers were to
come through the local ports, one could imagine the kind of
businesses spin-off for the auxillary maritime industries, Kerk
said.
	   Kerk, who was speaking to reporters after the opening of the
Fourth Biennial International Maritime Conference in Petaling Jaya,
said that the council was working very hard to woo local importers,
exporters and shippers' to use the local ports.
	   ``We cannot expect changes overnight.
	   ``There is still this traditional business link involving our
local businessmen with Singapore.
	   ``It will take quite awhile for them to shift their operations
here. We are moving towards this end,'' he added.
	   Kerk said the Government had already taken measures to improve
facilities and efficiency at local ports and the throughputs
recorded were much higher than before.
	   ``There were complaints before by our businessmen about
facilities and efficiency in local ports but all these have been
overcome.
	   ``Our ports are now among the best in the world. Therefore,
there is no reason why they should continue to use our neighbour's
port,'' he added.
	   Kerk added that the country also offered competitive sea freight
rate and it is an impetus for businessmen to use our ports.
	   
</TEXT>
