<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup Roundup, 5th Ld-Writethru,0784 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Brazil wins first game of France '98
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Norway-Morocco &QL; 
 &UR; By JOSEPH WHITE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ On a day when the Air France strike ended, the
first hooligan was arrested and bugs walked on stilts, it should
have been expected that a bizarre goal would decide the first game
of the 16th World Cup.
	   Scottish defender Tommy Boyd knocked the ball into his own goal
with his chest after a save by goalkeeper Jim Leighton in the 73rd
minute to give defending champion Brazil a 2-1 victory Wednesday
before 80,000 people at the new Stade de France near Paris.
	   ``I couldn't get out of the way,'' Boyd said. ``It was probably
the worst feeling I have ever had to lose a game like that.''
	   Also Wednesday, Norway and Morocco drew 2-2 at Montpellier in
another Group A match. Group B action begins Thursday when Cameroon
faces Austria in Toulouse and Italy plays Chile in Bordeaux.
	   Boyd's own goal ended a surprising threat from Scotland, for
whom even a draw would have been a stunning upset. The match pitted
the tournament's only four-time champions against a nation that has
never been past the first round in seven previous World Cups.
	   Early on, it appeared Brazil would produce the expected rout.
Cesar Sampaio scored on a header off a corner kick just four
minutes into the game.
	   ``Scoring like that, the first goal, makes me unbelievably
happy,'' Sampaio said. ``During those first five seconds one
forgets about everything else, it's like a dream.''
	   But Sampaio's foul on Kevin Gallacher led to John Collins'
penalty equalizer in the 38th minute, boosting Scottish hopes for
an upset.
	   ``There's no denying that the better team won the game,''
Scotland manager Craig Brown said. ``But we had a great chance not
to lose.''
	   At Montpellier, Tahar set up two goals with long, precision
passes, while Norway netted twice on clumsy plays off free kicks in
the first-ever meeting between the two countries.
	   Tahar set up Moustafa El Hadji in the 38th minute and Abdeljilil
Hadda in the 59th, while Youssef Chippo had an own goal in
first-half injury time and defender Dan Eggen scored in the 61st
for Norway. On both Norwegian goals, goalkeeper Driss Benzekri
collided with another player, springing the ball loose.
	   The two goals doubled the Norwegians' scoring output from the
entire 1994 World Cup, when they scored only once in three games
before being eliminated. The Moroccans also have an immediate show
of improvement _ they lost all of their three games before heading
home from the United States four years ago.
	   The Brazil-Scotland game was preceded by a colorful ceremony
featuring 600 acrobats and volunteers _ including stiltwalkers
dressed as striped insects and trumpeting bungee jumpers _ all
acting out the planting of a ``magic garden'' on the field.
	   Away from the field, police identified a known soccer hooligan
from Scotland as one of 15 people still in custody late Wednesday
as a result of overnight clashes between drunken fans and police.
	   The confrontations followed Tuesday's pre-tournament parade
through the streets of Paris.
	   Thirty-four police were injured in the violence, with one in
critical condition after being hit in the head with a beer bottle.
	   There were other World Cup-related arrests in Bologna, Italy.
Italian police detained 23 people suspected of belonging to a
militant Algerian Islamic group accused of plotting terror attacks
during the tournament.
	   The new roundup brings to nearly 100 the number of people who
have been arrested on such suspicions over the past several weeks.
Arrests also have occurred in France, Germany, Belgium and
Switzerland.
	   There was also good news Wednesday morning. Air France and its
pilots resolved a 10-day strike that had severely embarrassed the
country in the days leading up to the World Cup.
	   The company called for an immediate return to work. But the
airline has said it could take three days for service to return to
normal once the strike ended.
	   The kickoff of the Brazil-Scotland game not only marked the
start of competition, but it was also the deadline for teams to
petition FIFA to replace injured or sick players on their rosters.
	   Italy replaced striker Fabrizio Ravanelli, suffering from an
infection in his right lung, with Parma forward Enrico Chiesa.
Nigeria called up Mobi Oparaku to fill the spot vacated by defender
Jero Shakpoke, who was diagnosed with a broken left collarbone
suffered in the 5-1 loss to the Netherlands last week.
	   (jw) 	   
</TEXT>
