<HEADLINE>
More IT options, distance learning programme soon, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
More IT options, distance learning programme soon, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Jasbir SinghASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   DUE to the excellent response to its Information Technology
courses, and calls for more places for tertiary education, HELP
Institute is planning to expand its range of courses and also offer
a distance learning programme.
	   The head of its School of Information Technology Dr Patrick Kee
said the college hoped to offer the new distance learning programme
soon.
	   He said the programme would be so designed that students would
be able to get all the study material they need through the
Internet.
	   The whole process will be done through the Internet including
downloading of study material and perhaps even, in the future,
audio and video study material.
	   ``An allocation of RM1.5 million has been made and work has
started on three new computer laboratories that will not only allow
us to offer distance learning courses but also make available more
advanced computers to students.''
	   Kee said one of the three new laboratories would be dedicated
for teaching multimedia technology while the other two would be for
general use.
	   Once ready, there will be a total of 300 computers available for
students.
	   This will ensure that all students who pass through the
college's doors are computer literate and ready to take on the
challenges of an Information Society.
	   Kee said the college was expanding its IT infrastructure
including multimedia facilities to offer all students access to the
Internet.
	   ``We realise that the Internet will play a very significant role
in the future business and home environment and are therefore
asking all students to take up a course that will familiarise them
with the Internet.''
	   He said the college had drawn up an introductory course for all
new students that will familiarise them with the Internet and its
applications.
	   Students who take up Information Technology courses will have to
undergo a longer course which would introduce them to programming
languages like JAVA.
	   
