<HEADLINE>
Well-recognised matriculation qualification, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Well-recognised matriculation qualification, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   A. RamASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE one-year Canadian Matriculation Programme offered by Sunway
College is ideal for school-leavers keen to pursue tertiary studies
overseas as it is accepted by international universities.
	   The programme is equivalent to the pre-university courses
offered by secondary schools in Ontario.
	   More than 80 per cent of the teaching staff are Ontario-trained
and to ensure compliance with the guidelines on subjects, the
programme undergoes regular inspection by the Canadian Education
Ministry in Ontario.
	   Under this programme, students are given the flexibility of a
part course-work and part examination-based course.
	   Since its introduction in 1990, more than 2,000 students have
used it to gain entry into international universities.
	   There are two intakes each year, in January and July. The next
intake is now on.
	   Currently, Sunway offers two types of courses under the
programme. One is the Ontario Academic Course (OAC) or university
preparatory programme and the other the foundation course or
pre-OAC.
	   The fee for the programme is RM1,300 per subject for each
semester.
	   Subjects offered under the OAC include Accounting, Economics,
Law, Computer Studies, English, Geography, Calculus, Biology,
Chemistry and Physics.
	   The pre-OAC offers subjects like English as a Second Language,
Computer Fundamentals and Mathematics.
	   The programme's major attraction is its flexibility which allows
students to do a number of subjects which they are comfortable with
over one semester.
	   They are allowed to accumulate the number of subjects until they
pass a minimum of six subjects.
	   Upon successful completion of six OAC subjects, students receive
the Ontario Secondary Schools Diploma (OSSD).
	   ``Our pre-university programme has a graduation rate of more
than 90 per cent and our students have no problem being accepted by
international universities to do degree courses,'' Sunway College's
Canadian Matriculation Programme director John Futa said.
	   Futa said: ``The OSSD is a highly recognised pre-university
qualification that allows students to pursue their higher education
in universities in Australia, Canada, New Zealand, the United
Kingdom and the United States.''
	   Students can also further their studies through of the twinning
programmes offered at Sunway College.
	   Besides preparing students for entry into universities, the
programme also grooms them with skills to make them well-rounded
individuals.
	   Every year, selected graduates receive Certificate of
Recognition for Outstanding Leadership through their contributions
to the Students' Council, sporting events and the programme's
in-house newspaper.
	   One of the receipients, Tan Lit Kah said the well-rounded
programme ``was what makes CMP a `learning for life' experience and
not just an academic one''.
	   Tan also praised the ``academic rigours'' of the programme, its
cultural, social and sporting activities, the strong support among
students and the dedication of the lecturers.
	   In addition to the Canadian Matriculation Programme, Sunway
College also offers two other pre-university courses, the Cambridge
Board's GCE A-level and the Australian Matriculation Programme.
	   Also offered is a British Engineering foundation course from
Leicester University which is a direct and dedicated route to an
Engineering degree.
	   
</TEXT>
