MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE country lost a top educationist when Winston Pereira, the
chairman of the Raffles Education Group passed away, recently.
	   Winston, 45, was the founder of the Raffles Education Group and
former managing director of Stamford College when it was still run
by the Pereira family.
	   Calm and soft spoken, he was instrumental in the rise of
Stamford College as one of the largest colleges in the country, a
success that he repeated with the Olympia Business School which he
took over in 1995.
	   Within three years, the number of campuses increased to five
nationwide with a student population of 7,000 studying courses in
Accountancy, Banking, Computer Science, Business and Marketing,
Mass Communication, Tourism and Hospitality and Secretarial
Science.
	   Winston built up the new college with the same determination
that enabled him to put his seven siblings through school and
university after their father died when Winston was 17.
	   An uncle, Eric Pereira, the founder of Stamford, took Winston
under his wings and taught him the ropes of the business.
	   Winston worked his way up to the post of managing director until
1992 when the family sold its stake in the college.
	   ``He always believed that education should be for all and that
is what made him set up the OBS, which initially offered only
correspondence courses,'' said younger brother and deputy chairman
Colin Pereira.
	   Colin said his brother believed that education should be brought
to the people not the other way around, which is why the college
opened a campus in Kuantan.
	   ``Nothing gave him more satisfaction than seeing the students,
who he often referred to as his children, graduate,'' Colin said,
adding that Winston had never missed any graduation ceremony since
the OBS was founded.
	   College registrar Mary Reggie who worked with Winston for 18
years said he handled the students very well and they were often
surprised that the college chairman took an effort to listen to
their problems and offer advice and assistance.
	   ``He always had comforting words for those with problems and
generous to those with difficulties.
	   ``He had the memory of an elephant and a good eye for details,''
she added.
	   ``He always strove for a balance between his business and social
obligations, which is why the fees charged by the college are
significantly lower than other colleges,'' said another brother
Kevin.
	   ``All decisions made had to ultimately benefit the students,''
he added.
	   ```Don't worry, we'll sort it out', was his favourite phrase
whenever anyone came with a problem and solve it, he did.''
	   Deputy director of corporate affairs Jean Francois Jadin said:
``It was always a learning experience working for him and there
were no problems that could not be overcome.''
	   Although Winston is no longer them, his brothers at Raffles,
together with the management team, want to achieve the targets that
he had set - to have centres in every State and in Indonesia,
Singapore and Bangladesh.
	   So while Winston has departed, his legacy remains in the
corridors of the college and in the hearts of students and staff.
	   
</TEXT>
