<SLUG> INVESTMENTS-WORTH sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Investments worth RM12.46b approved, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Investments worth RM12.46b approved, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE International Trade and Industry Ministry has approved 269
manufacturing projects valued at RM12.46 billion between January
and April, Minister Datuk Seri Rafidah Aziz said yesterday.
	   She said the ministry had yet to approve another 212
manufacturing projects valued at RM4.02 billion.
	   Last year, a total of 759 projects valued at RM25,821 million
were approved by Miti.
	   Of the total, 462 were new projects while 297 were for expansion
and diversification of existing operations.
	   Rafidah was speaking at a seminar ``Will Malaysia Continue to be
An Attractive Location for Swedish Investment'' organised by the
Malaysian- Swedish Business Association in Kuala Lumpur.
	   During a question-and-answer session at the seminar, Rafidah
said despite the current economic situation, Malaysia remained an
attractive place for foreign direct investors.
	   ``Basic policies and incentives for manufacturing remain intact
and additional flexibilities have been introduced.
	   ``Export-oriented companies are now allowed to sell in the
domestic market without requiring a change in their equity
structure.''
	   Previously, only companies which are export-oriented were
allowed to have 100 per cent foreign equity.
	   She urged companies which need a regional centre or headquarters
to consider Malaysia.
	   Rafidah said: ``Malaysia is not attractive to all types of
manufacturing operations.
	   ``For example, if you want to establish a labour-intensive
manufacturing plant then this is not the place.''
	   However she added that Malaysia was an attractive investment
location for companies that could contribute towards technological
and skills development.
	   To enhance Malaysia's manufacturing sector, priority will be
accorded to research and development efforts with incentives for
companies undertaking research and development.
	   Rafidah said the Malaysian-Swedish Business Association members
should disseminate the right information about Malaysia to
entrepreneurs in Sweden so that the ``right'' companies would take
advantage of the attractive investment climate in the country.
	   ``Tell them the good and the bad to draw a right picture about
Malaysia.''
	   
</TEXT>
