<SLUG> BC-France-US-Kosovo, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sanctions ineffective, Contact Group prepares options
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with French comment, details on meeting &QL; 
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHER BURNS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Aiming to stop the growing conflict in Yugoslavia's
Kosovo province, Western and Russian officials appeared to close
ranks Wednesday by drawing up options against Belgrade that go
beyond ineffective economic sanctions.
	   The talks by the so-called Contact Group came on the eve of a
NATO defense ministers' meeting in Brussels to consider military
options in the wake of Serb army bombardments of ethnic Albanian
homes in independence-minded Kosovo.
	   On Friday foreign ministers from the Group of Eight
industrialized nations are to meet in London to consider the
options drawn up Wednesday by the Contact Group, whose members
``were in perfect agreement,'' the French Foreign Ministry said.
	   ``The deterioration of the situation showed that the time
remaining for a political solution was increasingly short,'' the
ministry said.
	   The group, including France, the United States, Britain,
Germany, Italy and Russia, agreed that Serbian President Slobodan
Milosevic was responsible for the increase in violence after
defying international economic sanctions.
	   The proposals to the G-8 would include a first ``phase of
persuasion'' in which Russia is to play an important role in
contacting both Serb-dominated Yugoslavia and the Kosovo Albanians,
said the Contact Group's French representative Jacques Blot at a
news briefing.
	   If Belgrade does not respond, the Contact Group would meet to
carry out the measures agreed on, he said. Blot declined to
describe the options under consideration, only to say they were not
sanctions.
	   Asked if Russia had agreed to possible military intervention, he
said: ``No delegation has excluded the military option.''
	   Blot said the Contact Group felt the U.N. war crimes tribunal in
the Hague, the Netherlands, should investigate cases in Kosovo.
While the European Union and Washington have called some cases
ethnic cleansing, Blot refused to use the term.
	   A senior U.S. official at the Contact Group meeting said the
bombing of homes to clear a cordon sanitaire near the Albanian
border, while aimed at stopping arms shipments, constituted ethnic
cleansing.
	   The growing conflict threatens regional stability, and
Washington feels ``all options are open'' to pressure Serbia, the
official said on condition of anonymity.
	   The conflict in Kosovo, where the ethnic Albanian majority seeks
independence, has killed 250-300 people and created as many as
100,000 refugees, the official said. Among them are up to 85,000
displaced people in Kosovo, 10,000 in Albania and thousands of
others who have fled to other countries.
	   Witnesses said Serbian MiG-21 jets have bombed homes, and
international observers have seen heavy artillery damage to homes.
	   (cb)
</TEXT>
