<BODY>
<SLUG> YOUNG-POOR-AND-WORKING sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Young, poor and working in a brothel, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Young, poor and working in a brothel, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Muharyani OthmanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   I WATCHED with such interest and sadness a documentary entitled
The Selling of Innocents, about the trafficking of girls for
prostitution in the slums of India, shown repeatedly over Mega TV's
HBO channel.
	   Many young girls, mostly from remote Indian villages, are sold
to brothels in Bombay and other cities by their parents or male
siblings to settle debts. And these girls could spend the next 10
years or more paying up their purchase price to the procurers who
roam villages to recruit them.
	   Some are promised jobs in the city. Radio and television, with
their portrayal of the sophisticated and glamorous city life, also
contribute to the problem.
	   Those fortunate enough to be rescued from the clutches of
procurers and pimps report of beatings, torture, rape, sodomy,
isolation and starvation.
	   Ironically, some of the traffickers are women themselves.
	   The documentary brought viewers to the mountain villages of
Nepal, 1,500km from Bombay and one of the world's poorest
countries, where young girls are favoured by procurers for their
light complexion, good looks and docility.
	   These girls, it seems, are raised to obey their fathers,
brothers and husbands in a country where women are considered
little more than chattels, and hence easily sold off to pay family
debts.
	   Some 100,000 young Nepalese girls are believed to be working in
the city brothels of India.
	   The documentary also looked at the issue of girls given away to
temples to dance and slave for them, but who ended up in brothels
as some of the temples have links with them.
	   Social activists like Dr Gracy Fernandez and Vinod Gupta are
creating public awareness on the issue through campaigns to educate
sex workers on safe sex, distributing free condoms, rescuing them
from brothels and setting up shelters.
	   The documentary took a look at the work of Gupta, a former
politician whose non-governmental organisation, with police help,
is conducting raids on Bombay's slum brothels.
	   One raid was conducted based on a plea for help contained in a
letter slipped out of the Solapur brothel. The raiding team
initially failed to find anyone Then they broke into the padlocked
backrooms and attic and saw frightened teenage prostitutes huddled
together in the dark. These girls had not stepped out of the
brothel in three years.
	   The madams, who had earlier disappeared, soon returned but were
not arrested by the police. Apparently, some personnel were on the
brothel's kickback list.
	   The documentary also focused on goings-on in the Solapur brothel
and its poor living conditions. Some women complained of not having
enough to eat while they also had to fend for their children. Some
had HIV/AIDS, and although they received free condoms from
volunteer groups, many clients refused to use them.
	   In some villages, women are fighting back as they realise the
only way out is to be economically independent and to provide
education to their daughters - something they were doing only for
sons.
	   They conduct talks to change outdated thinking that places women
as second-class citizens.
	   ``We women must change because even we are not happy when
daughters are born,'' a woman activist told a crowd of village
women, watched sheepishly by some of the menfolk.
	   Although we are moving into the next millennium, one thing is
obvious from this documentary - that we have still a long way to go
in ending discrimination, ill-treatment and exploitation of women,
who make up half of humanity.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
