<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-St. Maarten-Immigration Accord,0263 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
St. Maarten residents call immigration accord racist
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PHILIPSBURG, St. Maarten (AP) _ Hundreds of St. Maarten
residents are protesting what they call racist proposals to allow
Europeans to enter the island freely while requiring visas from
residents of other Caribbean islands.
	   About 700 of the Dutch territory's 34,000 residents sent a
petition Wednesday to the United Nations and the Caribbean
Community urging them to oppose a proposed immigration treaty
between the Netherlands and France. The two countries share the
island of St. Martin.
	   Currently, all foreigners must have visas to enter St. Maarten,
where the island's main airport is located.
	   Under the agreement, the 300 million residents of the European
Union's 15 member countries would be able to enter without visas.
	   France approved the agreement in 1994, and the Dutch legislature
is expected to vote on it this fall.
	   Opponents call the accord racist, noting that most residents in
neighboring Caribbean countries are black.
	   ``The agreement is arguably an instrument of genocide by
substitution _ perceivably legalized ethnic cleansing against the
current St. Maarten population,'' said pro-independence author
Lasana M. Sekou, who helped organize the petition and a protest
against the accord in March.
	   The petition asks the United Nations and the Caribbean Community
``to engage all efforts, legislative and lobbyist, with the Dutch
and French governments against the Franco-Dutch accord before it is
ratified as a treaty.'' 	   
</TEXT>
