<HEADLINE>
Pan-African leader predicts African teams in World Cup final
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   OUAGADOUGOU, Burkina Faso (AP) _ President Blaise Campaore, the
new leader of Africa's largest political body, the Organization of
African Unity, on Wednesday predicted that two African teams will
meet in the World Cup final.
	   Campaore, who became OAU chairman in his capacity as Burkina
Faso's president at a summit of heads of state here offered best
wishes to the five African teams _ Cameroon, Morocco, Nigeria,
Tunisia and South Africa _ contesting the Cup.
	   ``There will be two African teams in the final,'' Campaore said
to applause during the pan-African summit's closing ceremonies.
	   ``I would like, in the name of the whole of Africa, to address
the unanimous support of the continent and our wishes for success
to our noble representatives,'' he added.
	   Campaore, a keen soccer follower, was a vocal supporter of his
own national side, low-ranked Burkina Faso, during the African Cup
of Nations hosted by the West African country in February. Burkina
Faso lost in the tournament quarterfinals after surpassing all
expectations.
	   (gam) 	   
</TEXT>
