<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turks and Caicos-Haitian Refugees,0427 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police question survivors who claim officer shot Haitian refugees
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   COCKBURN TOWN, Turks and Caicos (AP) _ Police questioned
survivors Wednesday who claim an officer shot at and hit refugees
on a Haitian sloop overcrowded with boat people.
	   At least six people drowned when the vessel capsized after
Monday's shooting, just 15 miles (25 kilometers) from
Providenciales, the largest of the British Turks and Caicos
islands. A tourism boom there has attracted hundreds of Haitians to
work on resort construction sites and in hotels.
	   Some of the 75 survivors claim there were 113 people on the
boat, but police divers and other searchers found no more bodies or
survivors Wednesday, said Bryan Davies, deputy police commissioner
of the island chain between Cuba and the Bahamas and about 600
miles (950 kilometers) southeast of Florida.
	   Davies said investigators looking for clues were working
Wednesday to raise the boat, a 35-foot (10.5-meter) wooden sailing
sloop submerged just off French Cay.
	   Marine police on a launch apparently had tried without success
to get the captain of the sloop to stop.
	   ``One of the officers present admits that warning shots were
fired,'' Davies said in a telephone interview. He said the marine
police were armed with small submachine guns since most of their
work involves drug interdiction against heavily armed
narcotraffickers.
	   ``Some of the passengers are alleging that people were shot,
although none of the survivors have any injuries from bullets, nor
any of the six bodies that we recovered,'' Davies said.
	   A pathologist from Miami's Dade County coroner's office was
expected to arrive Wednesday to establish whether any of the bodies
had bullet wounds, Davies said.
	   The investigation was hampered and likely to be prolonged
because the survivors spoke only Creole and were reluctant to give
information since their trip was illegal.
	   Five Creole-speaking police officers arrived Wednesday from
Bermuda, another British territory, to help interrogate the
detained survivors.
	   Davies said the sloop was just one of dozens that come to the
Turks and Caicos from its southern neighbor, many carrying drugs
and illegal immigrants.
	   ``Last year alone we sent back over 1,000 (refugees) and since
Christmas the police alone have detained more than 200,'' he said.
	   Officials estimate about 8,000 Haitians live among the islands'
15,000 citizens, about 2,000 of them illegally.
</TEXT>
