<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Latin American Briefs,0400 </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Contains items from Peru, Guatemala, and El Salvador. &QL; 
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LIMA, Peru (AP) _ Peru and the United States signed an agreement
Wednesday to gradually increase the number of flights between the
countries leading to an open skies policy in 2002.
	   The agreement increases the number of flights allowed each week
from 42 to 63 immediately, and will raise the number allowed each
year until June 2002. From then on, there will be no restrictions
on the number of flights, Transportation Minister Antonio Paucar
said.
	   The treaty also increases the number of U.S. destinations
permitted for Peruvian flights to 15 from six.
	   It increases the number of destinations in Peru allowed for U.S.
flights to three, meaning flights can land not only in Lima, but
also in the Andean city of Cusco and the Amazon jungle city of
Iquitos.
	   Cusco is the airport nearest to the ancient Incan citadel of
Machu Picchu, Peru's top tourist attraction.
	   With flights to Iquitos, Peruvian authorities hope to encourage
ecotourism to its Amazon rain forest.
	   ___
	   GUATEMALA CITY, Guatemala (AP) _ Guatemala appointed Juan Jose
Serra, its ambassador to Mexico, as its new economy minister on
Wednesday.
	   Serra will take office on July 1, government spokesman Ricardo
de la Torre Gimeno said.
	   He will replace Mauricio Wurmser, who resigned.
	   ___
	   SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) _ The Lempa River Hydroelectric
Commission on Wednesday successfully auctioned the first
installment of shares in electrical utilities as part of a
government privatization program.
	   In two hours, the nearly 70,000 shares in the first batch were
snapped up on the Salvadoran stock exchange for a total of 12
million colones, equivalent to dlrs 1.5 million.
	   Stock exchange president Guillermo Hidalgo Quelh said there was
great demand for the shares and called the sale ``a smashing
success.''
	   A total of 1.6 million shares are being auctioned in the four
batches, for an estimated dlrs 7 million. Each batch is sold over
six days; Wednesday was the first day of the first batch.
	   Around 75 percent of the shares of the four public utilities
were purchased by strategic partners at the beginning of the year
for dlrs 586.1 million.
	   Another 20 percent were reserved for the workers, and now the
remaining five percent is being sold.
</TEXT>
