<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0651 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Albanians rally in Kosovo's capital, appeal for NATO help
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with Albanians ending daily protests in
Pristina, Albanian professors reported beaten, Serbian ruling
party's statement, Serbs bringing in fresh reinforcements in
Kosovo, comments from British official. &QL; 
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ About 20,000 people filled the
streets of Kosovo's capital on Wednesday in the 60th day of
protests against the Serb crackdown on the province's
independence-seeking ethnic Albanians. Waving photos of people
killed in the crackdown, they appealed for help from NATO.
	   Organizers of the demonstrations in Pristina later called a halt
to such protests amid indications that Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic would back efforts to ease tensions in the southern
province.
	   More than 250 people have died since Serb security forces
started offensives in early March aimed at stopping militant
separatists in the province, where ethnic Albanians outnumber Serbs
by 9-to-1.
	   After earlier imposing sanctions, Western powers are taking a
hard look this week at the use of force to stop the crackdown.
	   Demonstrators in Pristina chanted ``U-C-K,'' the Albanian
language acronym for the militant Kosovo Liberation Army.
	   The protesters carried photos that they said were those of
victims in the crackdown and waved posters _ one imploring, `Help,
NATO, help.''
	   Groups leaving the rally got into a stone-throwing melee near
the university with Serbs. Police broke up the brawl.
	   Organizers later said they would stop ``this form of protest.''
It was not clear why their decision to stop the protests came now,
or whether the decision would stick.
	   Also Wednesday, Serb police burst into a meeting of the
underground Albanian-only university in Pristina, beating 24
professors and one student, the pro-Albanian Kosovo Information
Center said. Six professors were badly injured.
	   Serbia and the smaller republic of Montenegro make up what
remains of Yugoslavia.
	   After presiding over a leadership meeting of his ruling
Socialist Party, Milosevic issued a statement Wednesday saying that
the party ``supports measures taken by the state bodies aimed at
normalizing the situation'' in Kosovo.
	   The party also stressed the need for ``organized efforts to
decrease tensions and take measures that would restore confidence
between members of different ethnic communities in Kosovo,'' the
state news agency Tanjug reported. But it also warned that
``terrorists'' would be ``decisively'' confronted.
	   Meanwhile, the Kosovo Information Center, which is linked to the
ethnic Albanians, said Serbian government forces had brought in
reinforcements near the town of Djakovica, where Albanians spotted
10 buses with troops, seven trucks and six armored vehicles.
	   The center also said a group of Kosovo Albanian parties appealed
to the U.N. Security Council for ``urgently needed'' military
actions by NATO, claiming that economic sanctions already levied
against Serbia were not enough.
	   NATO defense ministers were scheduled to meet in Brussels on
Thursday and Friday to discuss Kosovo, and possible military
intervention was expected to be on the agenda, alliance officials
said.
	   Chased by the fighting, thousands of ethnic Albanian refugees
from Kosovo have trekked on perilous mountain paths into northern
Albania.
	   An estimated 12,000 refugees have fled to Albania, a U.N.
refugee official, Mans Nyberg, said Wednesday in Belgrade.
	   An additional 5,200 fled to Montenegro, Nyberg said. There were
other reports that as many as 10,000 had fled to the neighboring
republic.
	   Nyberg estimated that about 42,000 Kosovo people were displaced
within the province. A Kosovo-based human rights organization
earlier had estimated the total at 50,000.
</TEXT>
