<SLUG> BC-UN-Netherlands,0351 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With UN-Drug Summit
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Netherlands cites its drug program as means of curbing demand,
death &QL; 
 &UR; By NICOLE WINFIELD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ The Netherlands cited its permissive drug
laws Wednesday as an effective way to combat the hard drug trade
and keep people safe from drug-related illnesses.
	   Speaking to the U.N. General Assembly's anti-drug session, Dutch
Foreign Minister Hans van Mierlo said the primary goal of his
government's drug policy was to ``protect health and social
well-being and to reduce the harm and risks associated with drug
abuse.''
	   The Netherlands allows its citizens to use marijuana for
therapeutic and recreational purposes. Officials argue that by
tolerating the small-scale trade in those drugs makes users less
likely to progress to harder drugs such as heroin and cocaine.
	   ``Now one may ask whether our programs do not lead to an
increase in drug abuse,'' van Mierlo said. ``Our experience is that
they do not.
	   ``On the contrary, needle exchange programs, for instance, have
not led to more intravenous drug use, but they have led to less
people sharing needles. Consequently, few addicts in the
Netherlands suffer from AIDS,'' he said.
	   The Netherlands policy is a model for those who support
legalization or decriminalization of drugs _ something the U.N.
drug fighting board rejected Wednesday.
	   ``The board appreciates the frustration of the public, the
frustration of the government officials, the frustration of the
people in the field, on the issue that the war against drugs has
failed,'' said Hamid Ghodse, president of the International
Narcotics Control Board.
	   However, legalization is not the answer but is rather a
``shortcut'' that doesn't solve the problem, Ghodse said.
	   In his speech, van Mierlo said by making some drugs legal, the
government ``prevents drug users from going underground, where we
cannot reach them.''
	   The Netherlands doesn't consider drug users criminals, van
Mierlo said. Drug users ``on the contrary, should be provided the
help they need.'' 	   
</TEXT>
