<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-US Roundup, 1st Ld-Writethru,0412 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mariners stop Giants' streak; Mets down Devil Rays
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: NEW with Wednesday's early games; will be updated &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) _ The longest winning streak in the majors
this year ended Wednesday when the San Francisco Giants lost 4-1 to
the Seattle Mariners, and the Giants may have lost a lot more than
a game.
	   David Segui drove in three runs for the Mariners, who broke
their own four-game losing streak and ended the Giants' 11-game
winning streak.
	   Right-hander Orel Hershiser left the game for San Francisco
after being hit on the wrist by a line drive, and Barry Bonds left
the game with tightness in his left calf. He was hit by a pitch in
the leg earlier in the game.
	   The two injuries came hours after the Giants placed second
baseman Jeff Kent on the disabled list with a sprained right knee.
He was hurt in Tuesday night's game against the Mariners.
	   Segui, who went 1-for-4 and had his average drop one point to
.341, had a two-run single in the first and an RBI groundout in the
third. Russ Davis added an RBI single in the fifth for Seattle.
	   Rey Sanchez had an RBI single in the fifth for the Giants.
	   Bill Swift (6-3) allowed one run on five hits in seven innings
for Seattle. Swift, who pitched for the Giants in 1992-94, struck
out seven as he won his fourth straight start. Heathcliff Slocumb
pitched the ninth for his first save. Hershiser (6-4), who had won
his previous six starts, allowed four runs on six hits and five
walks before being knocked out of the game in the fifth.
 &UR; Mets 3, Devil Rays 2
	   In New York, Al Leiter won his fourth straight start and the New
York Mets got two gift runs on five walks by Rick White in the
first inning for a win over the Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
	   Leiter (7-3) allowed one run and four hits with nine strikeouts
in six innings. The left-hander dropped his ERA to 1.70, second in
the NL to Atlanta's Greg Maddux.
	   The Mets got just four hits, but took advantage of White's
first-inning wildness and Butch Huskey's sixth-inning homer to win
for the 12th time in their last 14 home games.
	   Mike DiFelice had two of Tampa Bay's six hits. The Devil Rays
have lost seven of nine.
	   Dennis Cook struck out the side in the eighth as the Mets
recorded a season-high 14 strikeouts. Mel Rojas allowed an RBI
double to Wade Boggs in the ninth before picking up his second
save.
</TEXT>
