<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-LPGA Oldsmobile Classic,0305 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Andrews feeling good about her game
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   EAST LANSING, Michigan (AP) _ Donna Andrews has putted her way
to the top of the LPGA money list.
	   Andrews, 31, has earned more than dlrs '465,000 this season with
a victory in the Longs Drugs Challenge in early April and runner-up
finishes in each of the last three LPGA events heading into the
Oldsmobile Classic, which gets under way Thursday.
	   ``My whole game has been good,'' Andrews said Wednesday
following a pro-am round. ``I am hitting a lot of greens and
fairways, but the big difference is that I have started making some
putts. My putting has been more consistent, although it still comes
and goes.''
	   Andrews, who suffered a back injury in 1995, credits more time
on the practice green.
	   ``I have been able to spend more time working on it. About 15
minutes a day was all I could spend standing there putting,'' she
said.
	   ``I don't think I have changed my (putting) stroke, but I have
changed my routine. Now my routine is much more solid. This is
probably the best I have ever putted. I am rolling the ball more
consistently than ever.''
	   Andrews, who has won six times on the LPGA tour, including three
times in 1994, tied for 17th in last year's Olds Classic.
	   ``I have always played OK here, but I have never felt that I
played real well here.
	   ``I have had a lot of great weeks lately, but I feel like I
still am not at the top of my game. I know I can play better. I am
not playing the best golf I can play.''
	   Andrews will be vying for the dlrs '97,500 winner's share of the
Oldsmobile Classic's dlrs '650,000 purse. The tournament, which Pat
Hurst won last year, will be played Thursday through Sunday on the
par-72 course at Walnut Hills Country Club.
</TEXT>
