<SLUG> BC-UN-Hungary </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With UN-Drug Summit
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Hungary opposes legalizing drugs &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Hungary opposes any effort to legalize
``soft'' drugs or distribute limited amounts of heroin to addicts _
rejecting programs underway in the Netherlands and Switzerland.
	   ``Hungary is against any attempt to liberalize access to soft
drugs or to heroin distribution techniques, and it continues to
oppose legalization of any illegal drugs,'' Welfare Minister Mihaly
Kokeny said Wednesday.
	   Speaking at the final session of the three-day U.N. General
Assembly special session on drugs, Kokeny said such practices
``would contradict not only the spirit of the U.N. Convention but
it could have an adverse affect on anti-drug educational activities
among young people.''
	   The Netherlands permits its citizens to use limited amounts of
marijuana for medical or recreational use. Switzerland reported
success in a program to give limited amounts of heroin to addicts.
	   The Swiss plan was designed to curb heroin use, reduce crime and
prevent the spread of HIV through dirty needles.
</TEXT>
