<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Buick Classic,0559 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Els seeks three-peat at Buick Classic
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JOEL STASHENKO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HARRISON, New York (AP) _ Ernie Els hasn't just prevailed the
last two years at the Buick Classic, he has pulverized both the
field and the course.
	   Two firsts, one second and one fourth in four career
appearances, dlrs 662,850 in winnings and consecutive wire-to-wire
victories.
	   Now Els goes for a three-peat starting Thursday. He is trying to
become only the 13th golfer to win the same tournament three
straight years and the first since Tom Watson at the Byron Nelson
Classic (1978-80).
	   Since the start of the 1996 tournament at Westchester Country
Club, Els has never been out of the lead or over par in eight
rounds.
	   The South African won the 1996 tournament by eight strokes. Last
year, he tied the four-round tournament record of 16-under 268.
	   Els, in his aw-shucks manner, has few answers about why he has
played so well on the par-71 layout, which is regarded as one of
the tougher courses on the PGA Tour.
	   ``When you've had success at a certain golf course, you feel at
home,'' Els said. ``This is a good golf course. I've always liked
to come here and play.''
	   Others, however, have their theories about Els' success.
	   ``With the greens being so firm, Ernie hits the ball very high
and very long and lands the ball softly on the greens,'' Jim Furyk
said. ``That plays perfectly to this golf course.''
	   Davis Love III thinks it's because ``he hits it real straight
and he's a great putter.'' And for someone who hits the ball as far
as Els, he is also an unusually patient and methodical player, Love
said.
	   Foreign players have traditionally played well at the Buick
Classic _ Lee Janzen in 1994 was the only American-born winner
since 1991 _ and that may again be the case.
	   Only two of the top 10 players on the PGA money-leader list, No.
7 Furyk and No. 8 Mark Calcavecchia, are entered. Players such as
Fred Couples, Tiger Woods and Justin Leonard preferred to take the
week off or prepare early for next week's U.S. Open at The Olympic
Club in San Francisco.
	   The prospect of having to play in suburban New York and then fly
cross country for practice at the Open caused several top American
players to skip the Buick Classic.
	   ``It's so far away,'' Furyk said. ``If you play well here, the
flights are limited. It's going to be hard to get out. You're going
to get in (to San Francisco) real late on Sunday night and
therefore it's probably going to cut some of your (practice) time
down on Monday.''
	   On the other hand, 17 of the top 30 players internationally are
at the Buick, led by the top-ranked Els, 1993 and 1995 Buick
Classic winner Vijay Singh, Darren Clarke, Jesper Parnevik, Jose
Maria Olazabal, Joe Ozaki and Lee Westwood. Many are treating the
tournament as a stopover on their way to the West Coast.
	   ``Basically, it is halfway between England and San Francisco,''
Westwood said.
	   Plus, the Westchester Country Club resembles a U.S. Open course,
with its narrow, tree-lined fairways, thick rough and fast, firm
greens.
	   Els, who will defend his 1997 U.S. Open title at Olympica, said
courses such as Westchester remind him of the ones he played
growing up in South Africa.
</TEXT>
