<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Israel-Palestinian,0408 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Streets empty in Israel and Palestinain territories
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: repeating to some points to correct style on slug &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos JRL106-108

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ In the West Bank town of Hebron, a middle aged
man carried a TV across the city's dusty streets to the Al Quds
Cafe Wednesday so Palestinian patrons, some in Arab robes, could
enjoy the opening game of the World Cup soccer tournament.
	   In the executive dining room of Israel's parliament, the
Knesset, TVs were ordered to remain switched on to the World Cup
all month long so lawmakers could pop-in for updates in between
sessions.
	   All across Israel and the Palestinian territories Wednesday,
streets were deserted, sunflower seeds _ a favorite Israeli
accompaniment to sporting events _ were hard to come by and pizza
parlors hired extra delivery staff.
	   In Ramallah, West Bank, Palestinian men and women broke with
religious tradition and sat together at the Kanbata cafe drinking
beer and munching pretzels in front of a large screen TV. The cafe
strung soccer balls and French and Brazilian flags from the
ceiling.
	   In Jerusalem, Scottish soccer fans shared drinks with Israeli
soldiers at the Underground English Pub where a pint of beer sold
for the special World Cup price of five shekels (dlrs 1.75).
	   ``Everybody will make time to come watch this, it's a universal
unifier,'' said Banan Hazir, a 28 year-old Palestinian student of
international relations. ``If you look all around the world, the
rich, the poor, the education and uneducated are all watching and
here the occupier and the occupied are watching,'' Hazir said
during half-time in the Brazil-Scotland opener.
	   Anwa Mikhel, who owns a magazine stand in downtown Jerusalem had
a television set up at the stand and said sunflower seed sales had
shot up 50 percent during the day.
	   ``I'm crazy about soccer, this game means a lot to me. Even if
there was a wedding or I had to be with my girlfriend, I would
choose to be here,''he said.
	   At the Al Quds cafe in Hebron, Mohammed Netzeb smoked from the
traditional Arab water pipe and watched the World Cup on the cafe's
new TV. ``I plan to leave work for any important matches,'' he said
adding that he hopes Arab teams do well in the tournament.
	   The month-long World Cup, which opened Wednesday, is to be
played in 10 French cities.
</TEXT>
