<SLUG> BC-Caribbean-Sugar, 1st Ld-Writethru,0273 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sugar production from six Caribbean countries reaches 472,000 tons
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS weight conversions throughout. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) _ The six member countries of Sugar
Association of the Caribbean together produced about 472,000 metric
tons (512,000 short tons) of sugar between November and May 31, the
group reported Wednesday.
	   Barbados, Trinidad and Tobago, Belize, St. Kitts and Nevis,
Guyana and Jamaica exported about 253,000 metric tons (278,300
short tons) to Europe under treaty arrangements giving preference
to Caribbean sugar, and 35,400 metric tons (38,900 short tons)
under other arrangements, the group said.
	   Sugar exports to the United States totaled 31,000 metric tons
(34,000 short tons), and 13,800 metric tons (15,100 short tons)
went to other markets.
	   Barbados produced 47,900 metric tons (52,700 short tons),
Belize, 92,000 metric tons (101,000 short tons), and Jamaica
produced 141,300 metric tons (155,400 short tons). St. Kitts
produced 21,500 metric tons (23,700 short tons), Guyana 90,000
metric tons (99,000 short tons), and Trinidad and Tobago, 78,800
metric tons (86,700 short tons), the association said.
	   The sugar harvest began in November in Jamaica, December in
Belize, and January in Trinidad and Tobago, Barbados and St. Kitts
and Nevis. The harvest started in February in Guyana.
	   In April, the association lowered its projections for the
1997-1998 crop from 732,000 metric tons (805,200 short tons) to
725,000 metric tons (797,500 short tons) because of drought in some
islands caused by the El Nino weather phenomenon.
</TEXT>
