</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Norway-Sophie's Movie,0647 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
After TV and musical versions, ``Sophie's World'' becoming a movie
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo Available &QL; 
 &UR; By DOUG MELLGREN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   OSLO, Norway (AP) _ In ``Sophie's World,'' philosopher Jostein
Gaarder wrote about a girl and a philosophy teacher who discover
they don't exist. Now they're about to star in a movie.
	   ``It's really exciting,'' said Gaarder on his first visit to the
set where his global bestseller is being turned into a movie.
``It's really like we are there.''
	   Gaarder's thinly-veiled philosophy textbook for teens
unexpectedly sold more than 15 million copies in 44 languages,
becoming the world's most-sold fiction title in 1995.
	   Since then, it was made into a British television series and a
CD-ROM. On Friday (June 12), the musical version is opening in
Germany.
	   Norway's state broadcasting network NRK now is turning it into a
full-length movie in the most expensive film project, at dlrs 10
million, ever attempted in this northern European country of 4.4
million people.
	   ``I was just writing a little book. I wasn't trying to write a
bestseller. If I had, it wouldn't have been a bestseller,'' said
Gaarder, 45. ``I was just trying to make philosophy accessible to
young people.''
	   The former high school philosophy teacher got bored with writing
a standard textbook, and decided to turn in it into a novel
starring 14-year-old _ almost 15! _ Sophie Amundsen and her
mysterious philosophy teacher.
	   In Gaarder's tale, Sophie starts receiving anonymous letters
posing such questions as: ``Who are you'' and ``Where does the
world come from?''
	   Eventually, the mysterious letter-writer, by the name of Alberto
Knox, emerges to teach the girl _ and now millions of readers _
about Western philosophy by meeting Socrates, Plato and other
greats.
	   Sophie and Alberto eventually discover they exist only in a book
that another character, Norwegian Major Albert Knag, is writing for
his own 14-year-old daughter. That infuriates Sophie and Alberto
and is a twist that opens the way for some of Gaarder's philosophy
lessons.
	   ``It's an impossible book to make into a movie,'' he said. But
Gaarder said he was pleased with the clips he has seen so far, and
understood that his 500-page work would have to be trimmed and
changed to fit the screen.
	   ``I feel no ownership of this movie,'' said Gaarder, who is not
involved in the production. Despite interest from Hollywood,
Gaarder said he preferred the movie being made in the book's
original language, Norwegian.
	   Director Erik Gustavsen, 42, said he trying to stick closely to
the original, but that it has to be adapted for the screen. The
main guideline, he added, is that philosophy lessons for young
people remain intact.
	   ``What we are trying to do is make the ultimate coming-of-age
movie,'' he said.
	   During Gaarder's Tuesday evening (June 9) visit to the NRK
studio in downtown Oslo, Sophie and Alberto were meeting William
Shakespeare at the premiere of Hamlet.
	   When the sequence was over, Gaarder mixed with a crowd of
colorfully clad actors, live chickens and a plastic roasted calf at
a medieval market scene.
	   After pausing to talk with Sophie _ actress Silje Storstein, age
14 _ Gaarder said, ``She really is a lot like the Sophie I
imagined.'' Gaarder also met Alberto, protrayed by veteran Swedish
actor Tomas von Bromssen.
	   Silje was picked from 4,500 hopefuls to portray Sophie. She said
she has become more interested in philosophy, but doesn't share the
obsession of her character who gives up everything to learn more.
	   ``It's not like I feel the need to rush home and read
philosophy,'' said Silje. ``Maybe if I started getting mysterious
letters.''
	   The movie is due to be released in Norway in August 1999, and
will be followed up with subtitled versions for other countries. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-FEA-Norway-Sophie's Movie; CT:i; 
