<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup Roundup,0840 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bugs, own goals get World Cup off to odd start
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous &QL; 
 &UR; By BRIAN TRUSDELL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Bugs on stilts and own goals. If that's any
indication, it's going to be a weird World Cup.
	   The usually dominant Brazilians opened defense of their World
Cup title in atypically Brazilian style Wednesday, relying on the
gift a second-half own goal by Tommy Boyd to beat Scotland 2-1.
	   Boyd wasn't the only goat, though. Youssef Chippo also cost his
team a goal, heading in one in first-half injury time as Morocco
drew 2-2 with Norway and barely missed a major upset.
	   The miscued goals were only a part of a peculiar beginning to
soccer's 16th world championship.
	   A 15-minute opening ceremony, including what were officially
described as ``strange insects'' on stilts, inaugurated France '98
at the filled, gleaming Stade de France prior to the
Brazilian-Scotland match.
	   But the gods seemed to be with FIFA and the French organizers.
On the day the World Cup began, Air France pilots ended their
10-day strike avoiding a potentially embarrassing transportation
problem for fans and teams.
	   There wasn't a dearth of goals in Wednesday's openers, but there
were few of the classic variety. John Collins scored Scotland's
lone tally on a penalty; Norway got its scores off the own goal and
a fortuitous bounce off a free kick; and Brazil won thanks to Boyd.
	   Italy and Chile, which were to open the Group B schedule in
Bordeaux, and Cameroon and Austria, which squared off in Toulouse,
had a chance to restore the glory when they played Friday.
	   In the Paris suburb of Saint-Denis, Brazil was less than elated
with its performance, but was happy to take the victory.
	   ``We made mistakes in the first half,'' admitted Brazilian coach
Mario Zagallo. ``But we changed our way of playing, pressed them
more and dominated.''
	   ``Brazil is happy and we got the three points. These opening
games aren't easy.''
	   It looked like it was going to be for Brazil the way it started.
Scotland took nearly 30 seconds to get the ball out of its own half
after kicking off, and within four minutes Cesar Sampaio had given
the South Americans the lead.
	   The defender deflected in a corner from Bebeto, getting his head
to the ball before Craig Burley and Collins to beat keeper Jim
Leighton.
	   The Brazilians controlled the possession and the majority of
play, but Cesar Sampaio gave his goal back seven minutes before
halftime, running over the back of Kevin Gallacher to give Collins
a chance from the penalty spot.
	   But the Scots also were in a generous mood. Doggedly hanging on
and desperate to gain the point from the draw, Boyd inadvertently
turned the ball into his own net while trying to come back and help
on the play.
	   Cafu fought off Gordon Durie in the penalty area to beat him to
a long ball from Dunga and touched it into goalkeeper Leighton with
the outside of his right foot.
	   Leighton was able to block the shot, but the rebound caromed off
the chest of a backtracking Boyd and dropped into the net.
	   ``I think we were brave, but perhaps not good enough,'' Scotland
coach Craig Brown said. ``They deserved to win, but we shouldn't
have lost. That's the way we're looking at it.''
	   In Montpellier, the Moroccans were looking at their draw almost
as a victory. Having lost all three games in their 1994 appearance
in the United States, and clearly the underdog in Group A, the only
downside to their performance was Chippo's askew header that cost
them a victory outright.
	   ``We were rather disappointed when after the first goal we made
that mistake,'' coach Henri Michel said. ``This is our weak point
(inconsistency) and we have to work on that.''
	   Tahar set up both goals with pinpoint long balls, sending in
Moustafa El Hadji in the 38th minute and Abdeljilil Hadda in the
59th.
	   Hadji used his feed to contort Dan Eggen before getting off a
shot that squeezed inside the right post, and Hadda ran onto
Tahar's ball down the right side before placing the ball into the
upper right corner.
	   Chippo's error came after Benzekri collided with Henning Berg as
they leapt for Stig Inge Bjornebye's free kick from the left of the
box. The ball went off Berg's shoulder and then to Chippo, whose
flicking header caught the inside of the right post and bounced in
instead of away.
	   Eggen equalized for Norway two minutes after Morocco had gone
ahead 2-1. Bjornebye's free kick bounced in the penalty area after
a defender Noureddine Naybet and goalkeeper Driss Benzekri
collided, leaving Eggen an open net to knock in a header.
	   ``I think we started very well and should have scored very
easily but didn't,'' Norwegian coach Egil ``Drillo'' Olsen said.
``After that we lost control. We couldn't stop them from creating
chances. They were tired at the end of the match when we were the
better team.''
</TEXT>
