<HEADER>
w2176 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Soccer-Brazil-     06-10 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Brazil-Scotland,0541 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Forget hot-shot Ronaldo; Boyd's chest gives victory to Brazil
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT MILLWARD &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAINT-DENIS, France (AP) _ It wasn't Ronaldo's amazing speed or
a power-packed Roberto Carlos free kick that earned Brazil its 2-1
World Cup victory over Scotland.
	   It was Tommy Boyd's chest.
	   The Scottish defender will go down on the list of Brazil's
goalscorers because he couldn't avoid scoring the defending
champion's winner 17 minutes from the end.
	   ``It hit me on the chest and I couldn't get out of the way,''
the 33-year-old Celtic defender said after Scotland's opening day
defeat. ``It was probably the worst feeling I have ever had to lose
a game like that.''
	   Boyd's own goal before 80,000 fans at the Stade de France
settled the game and gave Brazilian coach Mario Zagallo the start
he wanted.
	   ``We made mistakes in the first half,'' Zagallo said. ``But we
changed our way of playing, pressed them more and dominated.
	   ``Brazil is happy and we got the three points. These opening
games aren't easy.''
	   The veteran coach jumped off the bench several times to bellow
his frustration at the Brazilian players who had taken a
fourth-minute lead and then allowed the upstart Scots back into the
game.
	   Cesar Sampaio was the hero and then villain for the Brazilians,
heading his team in front from Bebeto's left-wing corner and then
pushing Kevin Gallacher in the back to concede John Collins'
36th-minute equalizer from the penalty spot.
	   The Brazilians, with substitute Denilson tearing open the
Scottish defense after entering the field in the 70th minute, were
looking at their sharpest when they scored the second goal.
	   Denilson started a move that transferred to Dunga, who curled a
long through ball to the overlapping Cafu.
	   The fullback got past Gordon Durie and flipped a shot goalwards
with his right foot. Goalkeeper Jim Leighton, who rescued Scotland
earlier with two brilliant saves from Roberto Carlos and Ronaldo,
closed him down and blocked the shot.
	   But the ball bounced out to Boyd, who was at the wrong place at
the wrong time. He looked aghast as the ball struck him at the
junction of his chest and shoulder and rebounded back into an empty
net.
	   Cafu ran off and celebrated the goal with a somersault with the
Scottish players looked at each other in total dismay.
	   ``I think the reaction of the Brazilian team on their winning
goal reflected the credit for Scotland,'' said Scottish coach Craig
Brown. ``They realized they were fortunate to win the game.
	   ``There's no denying that the better team won the game, but we
had a great chance not to lose.
	   ``It was shocking the way we conceded both goals. We could have
got more out of the game with a bit more care at the back.
	   ``Other than that I thought the team played well, particularly
in the last 25 minutes of the second half,'' Brown said. ``We did
have chances, but we didn't have the final finish, a cutting edge.
	   ``But when you lose a goal at the beginning of the game it puts
you in a very difficult position, especially against the world
champions.''
</TEXT>
