w2178 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Belarus-SewerWar     06-10 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Belarus-Sewer War,0665 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Deja vu in Belarus: Former Soviets and West in smelly diplomatic
</HEADLINE>
dispute &QL; 
 &UR; By MITCHELL LANDSBERG &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ A little Cold War has broken out in Belarus, the
most unapologetically Soviet of former Soviet republics.
	   This being the 90s, the dispute has nothing to do with missiles,
spies or Marxist ideology. This time, West and East are fighting
over sewers.
	   The sewage in question flows out of the foreign diplomatic
compound on the outskirts of Minsk, the Belarusian capital. Here,
in pleasant pine woods, ambassadors from the United States, Russia,
France, Germany and other countries live in comfort, if not
splendor, behind gates and fences.
	   Belarusian authorities have decided the sewage and plumbing
system that serves the 1940s-era compound is badly antiquated and
requires replacement _ urgently _ and the diplomats need to move
out.
	   On Wednesday, which was to have been the deadline for the
diplomats to clear out, Belarus announced that it was postponing
their eviction until next week. But it wasn't backing down.
	   ``I think they should use the time left to remove the
furniture,'' suggested Oleg Novikov, deputy head of the Dipservice
state agency in charge of maintaining the diplomatic residences. It
was not clear how the eviction would take place.
	   Western ambassadors have dug in their heels and refused to move.
U.S. Ambassador Daniel Speckhard called it the gravest violation of
the Vienna Convention on embassy operations since the end of the
Cold War.
	   As embassy disputes go, this one pales in comparison to, say,
the Iranian students' seizure of the U.S. Embassy in Tehran in
1979.
	   Belarus stands out mainly because it happens to have an
authoritarian president, Alexander Lukashenko, who pines for the
days of the Soviet Union and loves to thumb his nose at the West.
	   The West has been sharply critical of Lukashenko's government,
accusing it of violating human rights by stifling democracy and
dissent.
	   Last year, the previous U.S. ambassador was recalled to
Washington for a month to protest the expulsion of a lower-level
U.S. diplomat who was accused of being a CIA agent and fomenting
dissent.
	   This time, Belarus has a whole slough of ambassadors and their
governments hopping mad.
	   ``Forcing these diplomats out of their residences goes against
the rules of human rights and politics,'' German Foreign Ministry
spokesman Markus Ederer fumed Wednesday.
	   The United States, Russia, France, Germany and Lithuania have
formally protested the planned eviction. France and Lithuania said
they will recall their ambassadors for consultations if Belarus
persists, and Washington has said it will also take some action in
response.
	   Belarus has offered the ambassadors what it considers a fair
deal: spacious, Soviet-style apartments in central Minsk or land
near the disputed Drozdy diplomatic compound on which to build new
houses.
	   Unacceptable, the diplomats say: Under the Vienna accord,
diplomatic residences are considered the sovereign territory of the
diplomats' country. Lukashenko, who has a residence down the road,
turned that on its head Wednesday, claiming that the diplomatic
complex belongs to him.
	   ``This is the residence of the head of state, you should know,''
he told reporters _ twice.
	   The ambassadors don't dispute that their houses, built for
Soviet bigwigs, could use some fixing up. In fact, they say, they
already have poured lots of money into fixing them. They would be
willing to spend more on the plumbing problem.
	   Opposition leader Stanislav Schuschkevich said Lukashenko's real
goal is to beef up his security at Drozdy.
	   ``The problem is, our president suffers from paranoia,''
Schuschkevich said. ``He sees spies and coup plotters everywhere.
... He might think his neighbors, the foreign ambassadors, want to
kill him. And he wants to show everyone that he can do whatever
comes to his mind to do.'' 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Belarus-Sewer War; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
