<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Jamaica-TV,0215 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Jamaicans carry TVs to work for first World Cup matches
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) _ Office employees carried televisions to
work and bank customers stood transfixed before sets in bank
lobbies as Jamaica turned its attention to the World Cup on
Wednesday.
	   Few telephones rang and traffic on Kingston's streets dropped
off as the first round of matches began Wednesday morning. Most
televisions were tuned to the face-off between Brazil, the
defending champion, and Scotland.
	   Interest in the World Cup on this Caribbean island has been
intense since Jamaica won its first-ever berth in the championship
playoffs.
	   It will be the first chance a Caribbean country has had at the
World Cup since Haiti played in 1974.
	   Prime Minister Percival J. Patterson announced he would leave
Thursday for France to attend tourism promotions tied to the team
and watch the Jamaicans play in their first match against Croatia
on June 14.
	   He will also attend the team's match against Argentina on June
21. Both of those games will be on Sundays.
	   Business owners said they are bracing for massive absences on
Jamaica's first weekday match, a June 26 game against Japan at
Gerland Stadium in Lyon.
</TEXT>
