<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Mount of Contention,0706 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Battle for Jerusalem shifts to biblical Mount of Olives
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos JRL101-5 &QL; 
 &UR; By LAURA KING &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Terraced with thousands of Jewish graves,
dotted with venerable Christian churches, home to a quiet Arab
neighborhood, the biblical Mount of Olives has become the latest
battleground in the fight for Jerusalem.
	   A Jewish seminary on its slopes has won permission to expand,
drawing a furious reaction from Palestinians who say the housing
project will change the character of a traditionally Arab area.
	   That, along with growing Jewish footholds elsewhere in the
city's eastern sector, is seen by the Palestinians as a deliberate
Israeli stragegy to doom their hopes for a capital in east
Jerusalem, which they call ``Al-Quds'' _ the holy.
	   Israel claims sovereignty over all Jerusalem, and says it will
never relinquish it.
	   The status of the city as a whole is to be settled in later
negotiations, and Palestinians say changes now in the character of
Arab neighborhoods captured by Israel in the 1967 war _ facts on
the ground, as both sides call them _ will greatly affect the
outcome of those talks.
	   ``The people have to mobilize themselves ... to defend
Jerusalem,'' said Palestinian Cabinet Secretary Ahmed Abdel-Rahman,
a day after the Beit Orot yeshiva won approval to build 58 Jewish
homes on Mount of Olives land that had originally been set aside
for an Arab girls' school.
	   Palestinians consider the Mount of Olives particularly strategic
in their capital aspirations, because it serves as a land link
between the Muslim holy sites of the Old City and other Palestinian
neighborhoods to the east.
	   Recent weeks have seen a sharp escalation of activity by groups
seeking to bring more Jews to east Jerusalem.
	   Below the Mount of Olives, protesters gathered again Wednesday
in the east Jerusalem neighborhood of Silwan. Earlier this week,
under cover of darkness, Jewish settlers moved into five
apartments, setting off shouting and shoving matches with Arab
neighbors.
	   A stone's throw away, in the walled Old City, Israeli
authorities this week hastily convened an archeological dig after
Jewish settlers set up sheds on the site in the Muslim Quarter.
With the start of the dig, the settlers were allowed to stay on,
serving as guards.
	   Palestinians and Israeli peace activists claim the government of
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and the Jerusalem municipality is
colluding with the settlers.
	   From biblical times, the mount has been a place of portent.
	   Scripture says that from its slopes, Jesus pronounced his lament
over Jerusalem's impending doom. The Roman army of Titus made its
summit a staging ground for its siege of the city. Apocalyptic
prophecy has it that here will begin the resurrection of the dead,
with the appearance of the Messiah.
	   The mount, with sweeping views of all Jerusalem, is the site of
the world's oldest and largest Jewish cemetery, dating back to the
15th century, with tens of thousands of graves.
	   Between 1948 and 1967, when the area was under Jordanian
control, a roadway was built through the Jewish burial ground on
the Mount of Olives. Gravestones were smashed and some used for
building and paving.
	   ``This area is holy to us, sacred,'' said Chaim Silberstein,
director of the Beit Orot yeshiva. ``Jews must have sovereignty
over it, and all Jerusalem.''
	   Silberstein says there is nothing political about the seminary's
building activity. It has housing for only 40 of its 150 students,
he says, and simply needs more.
	   But the activity fits in with a pattern of expansion. Beit Orot
was founded by an extreme right-wing settler, lawmaker Benny Elon.
And the housing would be built on land purchased by Miami
multimillionaire Irving Moskowitz, who has been a driving force
behind Jewish settlements in east Jerusalem.
	   Asked about the timing of the housing project, coming as it does
amid fitful efforts to restart the Israeli-Palestinian peace
process, Silberstein shook his head.
	   ``There will never be a time when it will please the Arabs that
we build housing,'' he said. ``It is they who are being militant
about this, not us.'' 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Israel-Mount of Contention; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:ASIA;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
