<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup Briefs,0740 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Includes items on Jamaicans glued to World Cup on TV; Troussier may
</HEADLINE>
take over Sheffield Wednesday; Italy reacting to Brazil goal; the
Maldinis; Brazilians abandoning work to watch game against
Scotland &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) _ Office employees carried televisions to
work and bank customers stood transfixed before sets in bank
lobbies as Jamaica turned its attention to the World Cup on
Wednesday.
	   And Jamaica's team doesn't even play until Sunday.
	   Few telephones rang and traffic on Kingston's streets dropped
off as the opening matches between Brazil and Scotland began
Wednesday morning local time.
	   Interest in the World Cup on the Caribbean island has been
intense since Jamaica won its first-ever berth in the tournament.
	   It is the first appearance for a Caribbean country at the World
Cup since Haiti played in 1974. Jamaica plays Croatia on Sunday,
followed by a match against Argentina on June 21.
	   Both of those games will be on Sundays, but business owners said
they are bracing for massive absences on Jamaica's first third
match, June 26 against Japan. That one falls on a weekday.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   VICHY, France (AP) _ Controversial South Africa coach Philippe
Troussier appears almost certain to become the next manager of
English club Sheffield Wednesday following talks with chairman Dave
Richards.
	   Troussier is a known disciplinarian and has a reputation for a
fiery temper, having fallen foul of several football authorities
during the 10 years he has spent coaching in Africa.
	   But Sheffield Wednesday is now believed to see the 43-year-old
Frenchman as the one to take over from Ron Atkinson, whose contract
was not renewed at the end of last season.
	   Troussier confirmed on Wednesday he had received an offer from
the Owls.
	   ``Nothing's signed, but we have been talking and there's a very
good chance of things succeeding,'' Troussier said.
	   His contract with Bafana Bafana expires with the conclusion of
France '98, and Troussier has made it known he would like to work
in Europe following his decade in Africa.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   BORDEAUX, France (AP) _ Italian coach Cesare Maldini nearly
jumped to his feet when he saw Brazil's winning goal against
Scotland on a distant television screen during his news conference
in Bordeaux on Wednesday.
	   ``Brazil has scored!'' he shouted before answering the next
question.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   SAINT-JEAN D'ARDIERES, France (AP) _ With nothing to do other
than soccer at their isolated training camp in southern France, the
U.S. players are making friends with the animals. And there's a lot
of them.
	   ``Peacocks, ducks, rosters, geese, deer, billy goats,'' forward
Brian McBride said, to name a few.
	   While they feed the animals, players haven't given them names.
	   ``That will probably be after we get back from Paris,'' he said,
laughing.
	   The team is also amusing itself by playing darts.
	   ``We've broken almost every single dart,'' McBride said. ``I
don't know if it's because people throw hard or we're no good at
darts.''
	   ___ &QC; 
	   BORDEAUX, France (AP) _ Coach Cesare Maldini said he could not
see any family conflict in coaching his son Paolo on Italy's
national team.
	   ``He's a player, I'm the coach. We respect the roles. I'm proud
to be the coach of all Italian players, not only of Paolo,''
Maldini said on the eve of Italy's match with Chile.
	   Paolo Maldini, a 30-year-old veteran defender of AC Milan, is
Italy's captain.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ Rush hour came early Wednesday as
Brazilians abandoned work to watch their team's first appearance in
this year's televised World Cup.
	   In front of the big hotels in Rio de Janeiro's Copacabana
district, tourists jostled with prostitutes and transvestites in an
effort to glimpse Brazil's match with Scotland on televisions at
beachside beer stands. Brazil won the game, 2-1.
	   The normally packed beaches were bare, and roads that were
jammed an hour before the game _ broadcast at 12:30 p.m. local time
(1430 GMT) _ emptied as it approached.
	   Half an hour before kickoff, Rio's downtown business district
was a ghost town except for random crowds clad in green and yellow
_ Brazil's national colors _ blowing on cheap plastic trumpets and
waving flags before large-screen TVs set up at several stores.
</TEXT>
