<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Albania-Cash for Kosovo,0598 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kosovo rebels supported by cash and supplies from emigres
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By BRIAN MURPHY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAJRAM CURRI, Albania (AP) _ The wad of Swiss francs was as big
as his fist. He waved both _ the money and clenched hand _ in the
direction of Kosovo as an old riverboat chugged towards the border.
	   ``You must have bullets and courage for victory. You can't buy
courage, but without money, there will be no bullets,'' growled
Ylber Malaj, a 45-year-old ethnic Albanian, who left the Serbian
province of Kosovo 20 years ago and emigrated to Switzerland.
	   Malaj is part of a distant, but vitally important front for the
separatist rebels battling Serbian forces in Kosovo. Ethnic
Albanian emigres in Europe and the United States are mobilizing
cash, supplies and a serious morale boost in the effort to turn the
Kosovo Liberation Army into a formidable new militia.
	   The aid pipeline runs mainly from Central Europe to Tirana and
then on to northeastern Albanian towns, such as Bajram Curri, named
for an Albanian hero who fought for Kosovo's independence in the
1920s.
	   Most money goes to buy weapons looted during last year's anarchy
in Albania: a Kalashnikov sells for 350 German marks (nearly dlrs
200). Other funds are given to Albanian families housing some of
the more than 10,000 refugees who have fled to Albania to escape
the fighting.
	   A Western diplomat in Albania who spoke on condition of
anonymity called the assistance ``a crucial element'' in
strengthening the KLA.
	   About 400,000 ethnic Albanians from Kosovo live in Germany. At
least 100,000 others are scattered through Europe, mainly in
Switzerland and Scandinavia.
	   The flow of outside help is welcomed by supporters of the KLA,
whose popularity has risen sharply in Kosovo since Serbian police
and soldiers began a crackdown in March.
	   It poses diplomatic problems for the government of Albania,
which is publicly committed to cutting off the flow of arms into
neighboring Kosovo, but in practice can do little to control it or
stop ethnic Albanians from funneling assistance.
	   This week, the Kosovo Albanians' government in exile announced
from its base in Germany that it would impose a war tax on kinfolk
working abroad, to fund the fight against Serbia.
	   Older emigres and their descendants in the United States are
also doing their share.
	   Muharrem Gocaj, 64, left Kosovo 20 years ago and owns a
restaurant and bar in Detroit. Every two weeks, he says, he gives
between dlrs 500 and 1,000 for the Albanian cause.
	   He's now back in Albania on his first visit since 1946, when he
trekked through the mountains with his mother from Kosovo _ much as
today's refugees do _ to his grandmother's house in the border
village of Tropoja.
	   ``Every Albanian should go back to Kosovo,'' he said. ``They
should buy guns here with the money they bring and go back to
fight.''
	   In Tropoja now, the emigres have quickly established themselves
as the early brokers of the separatist drive.
	   ``There are only two ways to support the war,'' said Bejrem
Mehmeti, who traveled from Austria last week. ``You can send money
to buy weapons or cross the border and fight. Both are equally
needed.''
	   A group of young Albanians from Europe last week set up a
council to receive refugees, organize food and returns for Kosovars
who want to go back.
	   Rustem Caca, 30, who lives in Germany, said supply depots have
been established around Germany with food, clothes and medicine to
ship to Kosovo or KLA guerrillas in Albania. 	   
</TEXT>
