<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-People and Places,0638 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
People and places in the news
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items on the Spice Girls, Mordecai Richler, Prince
Harry, James Belushi and a wild turkey terrorizing a mailman. Some
items may also have moved as separates. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ The Spice Girls say there's no bad blood with Geri
Halliwell, the departed Ginger Spice.
	   ``If Geri walked through the door now we would all be like,
`Hello,''' Posh Spice Victoria Adams said Tuesday. ``It would be
like friends meeting up. It's not nasty, we've all said that. We
all love each other and we all love Geri.''
	   The four remaining Spices will tour the United States beginning
June 14 and hope to record the pop group's third album later this
year.
	   Ms. Halliwell dropped out May 31 because of ``differences
between us.''
	   ``Of course we've been in touch with her _ there's a lot of
things to sort out,'' Sporty Spice Melanie Chisholm said. ``We
really do wish her well _ we want her to succeed.''
	   ___
	   MONTREAL (AP) _ Novelist Mordecai Richler is expected to remain
a few more days at the Montreal General Hospital where he is
recovering from surgery, a hospital spokeswoman said Wednesday.
	   ``It's too early to say (when he will be discharged),'' said
Chantal Beauregard. ``The operation went well and he is now
resting.''
	   Published reports have said Richler had a kidney operation but
Beauregard declined to discuss it. ``Mr. Richler and his family
have requested privacy at this time,'' she said, adding the author
will likely issue a statement in a few days.
	   Richler, 67, told the Montreal Gazette on Monday before the
operation that his general health was ``terrific'' and he expected
to be home in a week.
	   He said he needed something done about his kidney and that the
operation was pretty routine. He refused to be more specific.
	   Richler, noted for his biting satire in novels and articles, had
to cancel an appearance this week to receive the Stephen Leacock
Memorial Medal for Humor for his latest novel, Barney's Version.
	   ___
	   LONDON (AP) _ Prince Harry is heading for the playing fields of
Eton, just like his big brother Prince William.
	   St. James's Palace said Wednesday that Harry, 13, was
``thrilled'' to pass the entrance examination for the famous
boarding school. Fees at Eton are about 15,000 pounds (dlrs 24,000)
a year per pupil.
	   Harry and William, 15, are the sons of Prince Charles and the
late Princess Diana.
	   William entered Eton three years ago.
	   The school is just across the River Thames from Windsor Castle,
a favorite weekend base for the princes' grandmother, Queen
Elizabeth II.
	   ___
	   ALBANY, New York (AP) _ Snarling dogs aren't the only threats to
mail carriers. Just ask people in Albany who've watched a wild
turkey terrorizing their mailman.
	   Letters went undelivered several times over the past week, since
the mailman ran afoul of the bird. People in the Albany
neighborhood say they've seen the turkey pecking at the mail
truck's tires and chasing it down the street.
	   As soon as the truck pulls up, the intimidating turkey _ which
stands 24 inches (61 centimeters) to 30 inches (76 centimeters)
tall _ trots out and fans its tail feathers.
	   ``For the safety of the driver, he has been instructed not to
get out of the truck when the turkey is there,'' Postal Service
spokeswoman Mary Madonna said.
	   People who live along the street said they like having the
turkey around, even if it means having their mail service
disrupted.
	   The spokeswoman met Monday with residents to discuss what to do
about mail delivery. One possibility would be to put a row of
mailboxes at the end of the street.
	   ``They say neither rain, nor sleet nor dark of night will keep
them away,'' said resident Jim Palmer. ``I guess that doesn't
include turkeys.'' 	   
</TEXT>
