<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Canada-Drugs,0404 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Canadian official says Canada is drug-producer, cites Vancouver HIV
</HEADLINE>
crisis &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT H. REID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Thanks to a flourishing marijuana
business, Canada has become an illicit drug exporter, a Canadian
official said. He said the Vancouver area is additionally facing a
major HIV crisis because of intravenous drug use.
	   Speaking Wednesday to the final session of the U.N. General
Assembly special session on drugs, Solicitor-General Andrew Scott
said Canada had developed into a major producer of cannabis,
``especially indoors.''
	   ``Indeed, we have become an exporting country,'' Scott said.
``Cannabis is the most commonly used illicit drug in Canada,
followed by cocaine and heroin with moderate use of synthetic
drugs.''
	   U.S. and Canadian officials believe marijuana harvesting has
become so lucrative that it now ranks as British Columbia's most
lucrative agricultural product _ with illegal revenues estimated at
anywhere from dlrs 400 million to more than dlrs 3 billion a year.
	   Scott said a high priority for Canada's anti-drug program was to
combat intravenous drug use and the resulting spread of HIV because
of the use of polluted needles.
	   ``In this regard, Canada is experiencing a particularly serious
health crisis in Vancouver, with a high level of overdose deaths
and one of the highest rates of HIV infections in developed
countries,'' Scott said.
	   The Vancouver-Richmond Health Board, in a study released last
October, estimated that as many as half of the 6,000 to 10,000 drug
addicts in the city have HIV, the virus that leads to AIDS.
	   Officials agreed last year to spend an additional dlrs 3.3
million for a needle exchange program.
	   In the past year, the U.S. Customs Service has nearly doubled
its enforcement effort along the northern border _ especially with
Washington State _ because of a surge of high quality marijuana
smuggled in from British Columbia.
	   U.S. officials said the Canadian product is so potent that it
can earn as much as dlrs 6,000 a pound in parts of California _ 10
times the typical price for marijuana from Mexico.
	   As a result of the crackdown in the West, U.S. officials say
Canadian growers are stepping up operations in Ontario to exploit
markets in New York, Michigan and New England.
</TEXT>
