w2193 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UN-TheDrugWars     06-10 0376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-The Drug Wars,0382 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
More than one war on drugs, and the last one was disastrous
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NICOLE WINFIELD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ As world leaders talked this week about
how nations were losing the ``war on drugs,'' the head of the U.N.
narcotics board recalled Wednesday what happened the last time a
big war was fought over drugs.
	   Opium became legal in China after it lost the Opium Wars with
Britain, resulting in the addiction by millions of Chinese, Dr.
Hamid Ghodse told reporters.
	   Ghodse, the president of the International Narcotics Control
Board, raised the point Wednesday as the U.N. General Assembly
special session on drugs came to a close.
	   He was rejecting suggestions _ raised this week by some
delegations and special-interest groups _ that the war on drugs was
doing more harm than good and that drugs should be legalized.
	   The loss of the two Opium Wars was disastrous because it
``succeeded to legalize drugs in China,'' Ghodse said. An estimated
20 million people were addicted at the time, he said.
	   ``Therefore, we have already experienced this: that drugs become
legalized by the force of wars,'' he said, implying that the
reverse may become true someday and the drug epidemic would end.
	   Britain first went to war in 1842 after a Chinese official
seized opium imported by British merchants to finance lucrative
exports of Chinese tea.
	   Chinese forces were quickly defeated. The humiliated Qing
Dynasty was forced to hand over Hong Kong to Britain _ an enduring
wound to Chinese national pride until it regained the territory
last year.
	   On Monday, Chinese cabinet member Luo Gan reminded participants
at the U.N. session of the ``untold suffering'' China suffered from
drugs that were forced on the country by Western colonists.
	   ``We attach great importance to and are very much concerned
about the comeback of drugs in China,'' he said.
	   Ghodse also expressed his worry about the comeback of
opium-based drugs _ and the movements in parts of Europe towards
legalizing these drugs.
	   ``If we get heroin dens, the only difference from the opium dens
is that the heroin dens would be in more luxurious houses,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
