r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-BirthRate     06-10 0238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Birth Rate </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan's births hit record low, divorces at all-time high
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The average number of babies born in Japan dropped
to a record low last year while divorces hit an all-time high, a
Japanese Ministry of Health and Welfare official said Thursday.
	   There were only 1.39 babies born per woman born in Japan in
1997, breaking a previous record low of 1.42 registered in 1995,
said the official, who declined to be named.
	   The ministry's statistics, compiled in an annual government
report, show that 1.19 million babies were born in 1997, or 14,874
less than in the previous year and the third-lowest total ever
recorded.
	   The report said the figures were partially a result of the
growing tendency of Japanese women to marry later in life and wait
longer to have children.
	   Also, 222,650 divorces, the most ever recorded, were registered
last year, surging to a a record high of 1.78 per 1,000 people from
1.66 the previous year.
	   Besides the increase in divorces, the number of marriages during
the year fell by nearly 20,000 to 775,080, the ministry said.
	   In addition to the low birthrates, Japan's 125 million people
have the world's longest average life spans. The country is
expected to displace Sweden by 2005 as home to the planet's oldest
population.
	   In 1997, a total of 913,398 Japanese died, an increase of 17,187
compared to the previous year.
 &UR; (kgo-cd) 	   
</TEXT>
