<HEADER>
w2206 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Argentina-ArrestedGen 1stLd-Writethru   06-10 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Argentina-Arrested General, 1st Ld-Writethru,0562 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Argentina's army chief: Detention of former dictator won't
</HEADLINE>
jeopardize civilians &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: LEADS throughout to CLARIFY that general was detained but has
not been charged, RAISES reference to kidnapping related to dirty
war. &QL; 
 &UR; By KEVIN GRAY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) _ Despite Argentina's history of
military rule, the detention of a former dictator will not strain
relations between the armed forces and the civilian population, a
top army official said.
	   ``We maintain a close relationship,'' Juan Carlos Zabala, the
country's joint chief of staff, said Wednesday. ``We have proven
that in all the actions we have carried out.''
	   Zabala said he was surprised by the detention of Jorge Rafael
Videla on suspicion of child kidnapping under the military
dictatorship, but indicated he would not challenge the move.
	   Although democracy was restored in 1983, President Carlos
Menem's pardon of all middle-ranking and senior officers in 1990
has left an uneasy relationship between the military and the
general population.
	   Human rights groups, outraged by the pardon, have searched for
ways to circumvent the order and bring former military officials to
justice.
	   Tuesday's detention of Videla, who seized power in a 1976 coup,
reveals one of the loopholes in the pardon, which does not include
child kidnapping.
	   Videla is suspected of ordering the kidnapping of children born
to parents who were killed during the 1976-83 dictatorship. He was
also charged with falsifying identity documents.
	   Videla, who has not commented on the case, faces his first court
hearing Thursday.
	   In Paris for the opening ceremonies of the World Cup, Menem said
he supported Videla's detention.
	   ``All those who commit this type of crime must answer for it
before the courts,'' he said.
	   Federal Judge Roberto Marquevich, who ordered Videla's
detention, said the former president could be tried for up to ``36
to 38 cases'' involving disappearances stemming from past military
rule.
	   Speaking with reporters Wednesday, the judge would not discuss
those cases. Nor would he rule out the possibility that others may
be suspected.
	   ``I'm analyzing the cases but I'm not able to say much,''
Marquevich said. ``Other people may be called to testify.''
	   Videla's detention follows an investigation into five child
kidnappings, including two children given to Norberto Bianco, a
former military doctor who fled to Paraguay after democracy was
restored. The children were born to parents who disappeared during
military rule.
	   Bianco and his wife Susana Wehrli were eventually extradited to
Argentina and jailed on kidnapping charges.
	   The two children have since married and now reside in Paraguay.
There was no information on the other three children mentioned in
the charges.
	   As a top military official during the dictatorship, Videla had
final authority over death squads that operated against political
opponents, mainly leftists, from 1976 to 1983.
	   The Argentine government says 9,000 people disappeared during
that period and are presumed dead; human rights groups put the
figure much higher, at 30,000.
	   Videla was sentenced to life in prison in 1985 for human rights
abuses during the dictatorship. But he was released under the 1990
amnesty.
</TEXT>
