<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Poland-Germany-Youth Center,0455 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kohl, Buzek to dedicate international youth center
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ANDRZEJ STYLINSKI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ Eight years after a symbolic meeting of
Polish and German leaders that paved the way for reconciliation
between the two neighbors, they will meet again to open a youth
center dedicated to getting people to talk.
	   Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek and German Chancellor Helmut Kohl are
to cut the ribbon Thursday at the International Center for Youth
Meetings in Krzyzowa, or Kreisau, as the small Silesian town is
called in German.
	   Kohl and Buzek are to meet Polish, German and Czech youth and
take part in an ecumenical service. They also plan to hold a
face-to-face meeting to discuss bilateral relations and European
integration.
	   Krzyzowa, which was part of Germany before 1945, was a
meeting-place for anti-Nazi resisters during World War II.
	   After the fall of the Iron Curtain, just as the Berlin Wall was
being dismantled, it became a symbolic place of Polish-German
reconciliation.
	   Kohl and postwar Poland's first non-communist prime minister,
Tadeusz Mazowiecki, embraced each other during a religious service
there. That meeting paved the way for a historic 1991 Polish-German
friendship treaty as well as for the the youth center project.
	   A Polish-German foundation, with some 30 million marks (dlrs 17
million) from German authorities, carried out renovation of the
estate, which once belonged to Count Hellmuth James von Moltke.
	   Von Moltke and a group of Germans who opposed the Nazis met in
Krzyzowa during the war to plan the ill-fated, 1944 attempt on
Hitler's life.
	   But they also discussed concepts for a postwar Europe with a
focus on cross-border integration as a way of overcoming
nationalistic feelings, the thinking that five decades later
brought opening of the European Union and NATO for former East Bloc
foes.
	   The conspirators were hanged and the rest of those living on the
estate were expelled after postwar borders of Poland were redrawn
and moved to the west. They were replaced by Poles from eastern
regions that became part of the Soviet Union after the war.
	   The center, which has been in operation since 1994, has 116
beds, a 220-seat multi-purpose hall and a gymnasium, and it has
played host to school and youth groups from around Europe as well
as Israel.
	   Eight years since the fall of communism, Polish German relations
are booming.
	   Focusing on cooperation from trade and defense to fighting last
summer's Oder River floods, both nations have done a lot to bury
the ghosts of World War II - the Nazis' brutal six-year occupation
and the postwar expulsion of millions of Germans. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Poland-Germany-Youth Center; CT:i; 
