<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Drugs-Needle Exchange,0389 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New Zealand says needle exhange program effective in combatting
</HEADLINE>
AIDS &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT H. REID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ New Zealand's needle exchange program was
largely responsible for keeping HIV infection rates among the
lowest in the world, the country's customs chief said Wednesday.
	   John Delamere, who also serves as associate health minister,
said less than one percent of New Zealand's population was infected
with HIV, the virus that causes AIDS.
	   He attributed the low rate to a needle exchange program for
addicts, which was begun a decade ago before HIV ``had become
established within the injecting drug using community.''
	   ``Analysts believe that this timely response has helped prevent
the spread of HIV/AIDS amongst injecting drug users and into the
wider community,'' Delamere told the final session of the three-day
U.N. General Assembly special session on drugs.
	   Delamere noted that needle exchange, as well as programs to wean
addicts off heroin by giving them methadone, are widely opposed by
critics who believe they encourage drug abuse.
	   ``For me, the answer `well, it works,' seems to be the best
response to the critics, who I suspect would have us blindly march
down the road towards a `war on drugs,' a philosophy which many
agree hasn't worked,'' he added.
	   Those remarks contrast sharply with the prevailing view in many
developed countries, including the United States.
	   In April, Republicans in the U.S. House of Representatives
pushed through legislation that would permanently ban federal
funding for needle exchanges.
	   Democrats accused their Republican counterparts of being more
interested in scoring election-year political points than in
fighting illegal drugs. But White House drug policy chief Barry
McCaffrey said federal funding would jeopardize the battle against
drugs.
	   Delamere acknowledged that New Zealand had not been spared the
effects of the global drug epidemic. He said drug use was
especially prevelant among the country's indigenous Maori
population, of which he is a member.
	   He said drug control and education programs designed for the
mainstream population ``have often not provided effective for the
Maori.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
