<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. dollar climbs, Tokyo stocks decline
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar rose against the yen Thursday
morning as traders bet that the Group of Seven industrialized
nations was unlikely to intervene to defend the yen. Tokyo stock
prices fell.
	   In morning trading, the dollar bought 141.44 yen, up 0.60 yen
from late Wednesday in Tokyo and just above its late New York level
of 141.43 yen overnight.
	   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 126.62 points, or 0.83
percent, to 15,212.64 in the first 30 minutes of trading. On
Wednesday, the Nikkei sank 190.91 points, or 1.23 percent.
	   Currency traders had been looking to see if G-7 deputy finance
ministers who met in Paris on Wednesday would decide to support the
Japanese currency. But traders said statements from the meeting
signaled no change in policy on the yen.
	   Recent signs that Japan's economy is slowing, such as rising
unemployment and falling corporate profits, have hurt the yen.
	   Japanese officials, though, have warned that the yen may have
weakened excessively against the dollar, suggesting possible
yen-buying intervention.
	   On the Tokyo stock exchange, stocks opened lower led by sharp
drops in bank and securities shares amid worries about bad loans in
the Japanese financial system.
	   The weakness of the yen, which erodes the value of Japanese
stocks held by foreign investors, also hurt sentiment.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section fell 11.72 points, or 0.98 percent, to 1,186.88. The
TOPIX fell 10.08 points, or 0.83 percent the day before.
	   The yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese government
bond rose to 1.200 percent early Thursday from Wednesday's close of
1.195 percent, driving its price down to 112.02 yen from 112.06
yen.
 &UR; (tz) 	   
</TEXT>
