<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria,0535 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New leader's promises draw denunciations from opposition
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By TIM SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Resistance to Nigeria's new military
leader mounted amid signs that he was too preoccupied with
consolidating his power base to focus on his vague promise to usher
in civilian rule.
	   Nigeria's boisterous opposition movement, denouncing Gen.
Abdulsalam Abubakar as nothing new, said Wednesday it planned to
challenge his appointment in court and called for a nationwide
strike for democracy.
	   Gani Fawehinmi, a Lagos attorney and one of the country's
best-known opposition activists, said he would file suit in the
Nigerian high court challenging Abubakar's appointment to replace
dictator Gen. Sani Abacha, who died Monday.
	   Fawehinmi said there was nothing in Nigerian law to say that a
chief of defense staff succeeds the head of state in Africa's most
populous nation.
	   ``Nigerians must intensify their struggle to end military
rule,'' Fawehinmi said.
	   The denunciations _ by an opposition tired of decades of
oppression _ followed a televised speech Tuesday by Abubakar, who
promised to proceed with a transition to civilian rule that Abacha
began. He gave no details on how that would happen.
	   ``The empty maiden address of Gen. Abubakar has confirmed that
there is no hope for Nigeria in Abacha's successor,'' said
Fawehinmi, speaking at a press conference on behalf of the umbrella
opposition group, the Joint Action Committee for Nigeria.
	   He said the group would go ahead with demonstrations in Lagos
planned for Friday, the fifth anniversary of annulled presidential
elections that were apparently going to be won by Moshood Abiola, a
billionaire businessman now in prison.
	   The group called on people to observe a nationwide 24-hour
strike, staying away from their jobs and keeping off the roads. It
also urged them not to recognize Abubakar's government.
	   It was not clear just how many people would heed the callsfor a
strike. Similar calls for demonstrations have sometimes resulted in
only a few hundred people turning out.
	   Abubakar, meanwhile, appeared to be taking care to avoid any
internal threats to his fledgling government.
	   Two members of his inner circle were placed under house arrest
in the capital, Abuja, two independent sources confirmed Wednesday,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
	   ``I don't see it getting better for now,'' said Clement Nwankwo,
head of the Constitutional Rights Project. He did add, though, that
pressure on Nigeria's opposition groups, which has been increasing
in recent months, may ease for a while.
	   Abacha had blatantly manipulated the system to ensure he would
be the only candidate in Aug. 1 presidential elections. The
transition was to be completed by Oct. 1.
	   Government opponents said they had few expectations of change in
a country whose economy is crushed despite its vast oil reserves.
	   Little in Nigeria functions these days, from the water supply to
the telephones. The only people who manage to live easily are those
who can afford to buy generators, truck in their own water and hire
security guards to fend off the rampant crime. 	   
</TEXT>
