<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Subway Strike </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Seoul subway workers go on strike to press for pay hikes
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Seoul's unionized subway workers went
on strike Thursday after last-minute negotiations with management
on demands for pay hikes broke down.
	   But the walkout failed to disrupt the normal running of trains,
which were being operated by nonunion workers.
	   Management cautioned, however, that a prolonged strike could
cause the subway's normal three-minute interval between trains
during rush hours to be increased.
	   The Seoul subway's 9,000 unionized workers began the strike at 5
a.m. (2000 GMT Wednesday), demanding a 7.8 percent pay hike and a
reduction in work hours from the present 42 to 40 per week.
	   Management rejected the demands, saying that the subway
consistently loses money.
	   Sohn Jang-ho, head of the Seoul Subway Authority, reported
``some progress'' during overnight talks but refused to elaborate,
though he indicated the strike could end within the day.
	   The central government ruled the strike illegal because it was
launched while the case was under review by the government's labor
arbitration committee.
	   At management's request the government committee was to rule on
the case later Thursday. Under Korean law, a 15-day cooling-off
period is mandatory for a labor case under review by the committee.
	   The subway union has rejected the committee's role, accusing it
of siding with management. In past labor disputes, the union has
never honored the committee's role.
 &UR; (ps)
</TEXT>
