w2226 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sweden-MilitaryYearbo     06-10 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sweden-Military Yearbook,0604 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Despite progress on key fronts, world still a risky place
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ED McCULLOUGH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) _ Some bitter regional conflicts have
subsided. Global military spending continues to decline.
Once-mighty arsenals are being dismantled.
	   Yet the world remains a dangerous place.
	   That's a finding of the Stockholm International Peace Research
Institute, which published its authoritative yearbook on Wednesday.
	   There were 25 major armed conflicts in 1997, strife in which at
least 1,000 people were killed. That's down from 27 the previous
year and 36 in 1989.
	   World military expenditure declined by about one-third from 1988
to 1997, when spending was estimated at 740 billion dollars. The
biggest cutbacks were made by the republics that made up the former
Soviet Union.
	   Among other positive signs, Russia and the United States are
ahead of schedule in taking apart strategic nuclear weapons.
	   The cease-fire in Northern Ireland curtailed the last major
armed conflict in Europe. And peace accords last year in Liberia,
Tajikistan, Bangladesh and Nicaragua are ``major successes,'' the
report stated.
	   Nevertheless, the authors of the SIPRI yearbook, which is
regarded as a definitive assessment of global security issues, were
solemn, not cheerful, as they presented the 29th edition at a news
conference.
	   The testing last month of nuclear devices by India and Pakistan
could lead to a disastrous confrontation, one expert said.
	   ``War is quite possible,'' said Eric Arnett, author of the
military research and development section of the yearbook. ``It's
also quite possible that nuclear weapons might be used.''
	   The neighboring Asian countries have fought three wars since
1947 _ two over Kashmir, which is divided between them and where
each side has already positioned thousands of troops.
	   Arnett said India appeared to have 20-30 nuclear warheads,
compared with 10-20 for Pakistan.
	   The next ``crisis'' with Iraq strongman Saddam Hussein may be
right around the corner. By ``late summer, early autumn,'' when
United Nations inspectors press ahead with their search for
biological weapons, Hussein likely will resist, said Peter Jones,
author of the report's section on the Middle East.
	   ``The United States and Britain ... are determined to see that
he does comply,'' Jones added. ``I do think we are building toward
a crisis.''
	   SIPRI noted that most conflicts since the end of the Cold War
occur within a single country rather than between nations; and
happen more often in ``failed'' authoritarian states rather than in
democratic, prosperous ones.
	   That should indicate to governments as they enter the 21st
century that true peace means more than countries arming themselves
so heavily that no one will attack them, the respected research
institute said.
	   ``The security agenda ahead must be founded on a new political
philosophy, encompassing a common, institutionalized system of
standards and shared values rather than concepts based on the
balance of power,'' it stated.
	   The institute called for the ``complete elimination of nuclear
weapons,'' though the report and comments from its authors
indicated that was unlikely to take place any time soon.
	   Peace prospects for the Middle East remain distant, for which
Jones blamed Israeli Prime Minister Benhamin Netanyahu.
	   ``Although there is ample blame for all the parties involved,
the conclusion cannot be escaped that Netanyahu's commitment to the
peace process has never been more than equivocal,'' he stated. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sweden-Military Yearbook; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
(REG:ENGL;)
