<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Chiapas,0650 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rebels, state police clash in Chiapas; at least one policeman dead
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous to UPDATE with government confirmation of six
rebels supporters dead, nine injured overall and 52 arrested,
government and Zapatista accounts of clashes, other details.
CORRECTS community name to Union Progreso. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos pursuing &QL; 
 &UR; By ALEJANDRO RUIZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico (AP) _ In one of the
deadliest clashes since the early days of the Zapatista uprising,
six people believed to be Zapatista rebels and a police officer
were killed when the army tried to retake control of a town
sympathetic to the rebels in the southern state of Chiapas.
Fifty-two people were arrested.
	   Nine people were injured, including seven police officers. One
officer was wounded when a police helicopter was fired on and
forced to land.
	   Peace talks have been stalled for two years and tensions have
been rising between supporters of the government and those of the
Zapatista National Liberation Army, which staged a brief uprising
in 1994 in the name of Indian rights.
	   Clashes between the supporters of both sides have been
increasingly frequent, but military clashes involving the rebels
have been rare.
	   The state government said the raid in the municipality of El
Bosque, 25 miles (40 kms) north of San Cristobal, was intended to
capture criminal suspects and restore order to the area following
violence in recent months. They have used similar justifications
for other raids on rebel-supporting villages.
	   Details of the fighting remained unclear because state police
and soldiers prevented most foreign and national journalists from
getting near the scene.
	   Zapatista supporters said that security forces entered the
communities of Union Progreso and Chabajebal firing guns,
destroying houses and chasing after villagers.
	   The government said villagers had fired the first shots. Jose
Luis Zenteno, a public security officer, said he and several others
policemen were driving to search a house in Chabajebal when several
men _ wearing the ski masks used by Zapatista rebels _ opened fire
with automatic weapons. Zenteno said one officer was killed and
five were wounded in the 7 a.m. ambush.
	   Five of the six Zapatistas killed in fighting in Chabajebal wore
military-style uniforms similar to those used by Zapatistas, the
government said.
	   By late afternoon, officials said the fighting had stopped, the
communities were under government control and soldiers were combing
the mountains in search of rebels.
	   The fighting came a day after six government supporters were
ambushed in the village of Los Platanos. The government said it was
only the latest in a series of attacks that have killed three
people and injured 11 since April. The Zapatistas denied
responsibility for Tuesday's attack.
	   The government accused the Zapatistas of trying to trigger a
situation ``similar to that which occurred unfortunately in
Acteal,'' so they could blame the government and security forces.
Pro-government paramilitaries killed 45 people in the pro-Zapatista
village of Acteal in December, reportedly to avenge the killing of
the brother of a local official.
	   It said it had asked for the army's help in capturing 15
suspects wanted for crimes including homicide and robbery and to
``reestablish a state of law'' in the municipality.
	   Zapatista sympathizers had set up a rebel town council in El
Bosque 2 1/2 years ago. Members of the ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party had their own town council at a house a few
blocks away.
	   The two town councils appeared to coexist peacefully until
Wednesday.
	   Overall, supporters of the Zapatistas have set up 32 parallel
town councils _ most of them a symbolic presence _ since late 1994.
The government late last year began breaking them up, and 28 now
remain. 	   
</TEXT>
