<SLUG> BC-World Bank-Japan,0429 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Head of World Bank urges Japan to shore up its economy
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By SETH SUTEL &QC; 
 &UR; AP Business Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Adding his voice to a chorus of world finance
officials, World Bank President James Wolfensohn urged Japan to act
in a ``definitive way'' to shore up its economy.
	   Wolfensohn told a group of Japanese executives Wednesday night
that a recovery in their country was key to restoring growth in
struggling Asian economies like Thailand and Indonesia which rely
on Japan for trade and investment.
	   ``Japan has to react'' to its economic problems, Wolfensohn said
in a speech to the annual meeting of the Japan Society. ``Not just
for Japan, but because the world is coming to count on you now.''
	   Wolfensohn ticked off a list of woes ailing Japan, including
record joblessness, the drastic weakening of the yen against other
currencies, a crisis in the banking sector and waning confidence
among industry leaders.
	   Noting that Japan's massive dlrs 5.2 trillion economy dwarfs
those of its neighbors _ Indonesia's economy is just 5 percent the
size of Japan's _ Wolfensohn said it was important to consider the
strength of Japan's position in the region. ``Japan is the
locomotive ... and now it's not going well,'' he said.
	   ``So, small wonder that we look to Japan with concern ...
because they're our partners, and we're deeply concerned,'' he
said.
	   Wolfensohn struck a more conciliatory tone in his comments
directed at Tokyo compared to senior U.S. officials, some of whom
have used more stringent language in pressing Japan to make greater
efforts to strengthen its economy.
	   Last month, Japanese officials came under pressure at a summit
of world leaders in Birmingham, England to follow through on its
promises to stimulate its economy. A recent package of Japanese
stimulus measures has been criticized as coming up short, and on
Friday, Japan is expected to announce that its economy contracted
for two straight quarters, putting it into recession.
	   But Wolfensohn expressed confidence that Japan would come
through on its promises to get itself back on its feet _ and
hopefully its struggling Asian neighbors as well.
	   ``Japan has everything that is necessary to get it right,''
Wolfensohn said. ``It has the people, it has the education, it has
the resources _ and all it needs to do is act in a definitive
way.''
	   The World Bank, along with its sister organization, the
International Monetary Fund, makes loans to developing nations in
an effort to combat poverty and foster economic development. 	   
</TEXT>
