<SLUG> BC-NATO-Kosovo,0751 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Defense ministers to seek plans for Kosovo intervention
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Recaps previous to UPDATE with quotes from White House, US
leaning toward military exercises in Albania, Macedonia. &QL; 
 &UR; By JEFFREY ULBRICH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ As Yugoslavia strengthens its forces in
embattled Kosovo province, NATO officials appear increasingly
likely to order military action to stop the violence.
	   NATO defense ministers were opening a two-day meeting in
Brussels on Thursday to discuss Kosovo. Ahead of the meeting, there
was a growing conviction that the only way of defusing the
situation could be through military force.
	   U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen acknowledged ``a general
consensus there should be accelerated planning'' and that ``all
NATO members feel an increased sense of urgency.''
	   ``There is a genuine concern throughout the region that if this
goes unchecked, it could have much wider implications than just
Kosovo,'' he said on Wednesday. Many fear a new, bigger Balkan war.
	   White House spokesman Mike McCurry said in Washington Wednesday
the goal was ``to clearly indicate that NATO will define and
project its interests in the Balkans in a way that reminds the
Belgrade authorities of how seriously we take the violence that has
occurred in Kosovo, directed against the Kosovar Albanians.''
	   McCurry said U.S. action should be seen as ``one that in concert
with the actions of other governments, particularly European Union
governments, can have an impact.''
	   More than 250 people have died in fighting between government
forces and the Kosovo Liberation Army, the armed wing of the ethnic
Albanian independence movement. Ethnic Albanians, who make up 90
percent of the province's population, demand independence from
Serbia, the larger of the two republics in Yugoslavia.
	   The United States and its allies support autonomy for Kosovo but
oppose rebel demands for independence.
	   Also Wednesday, the six-nation Contact Group, which monitors
Yugoslavia, met in Paris to discuss ways to solve the Kosovo
crisis. The group planned to offer proposals to the Group of Eight
industrialized nations, set to meet Friday in London.
	   The Contact Group includes the United States, Russia and Western
European countries. It planned to propose a first ``phase of
persuasion,'' in which Russia would contact both Yugoslavia and the
Kosovo Albanians, said group's French representative Jacques Blot.
	   If Belgrade does not respond, the Contact Group would meet again
to carry out other measures agreed on, said Blot, who declined to
describe the options.
	   NATO ambassadors worked late Wednesday on detailed instructions
for the military, including a clear statement of the objective of
any intervention.
	   Also under debate were a series of proposed immediate measures,
including air maneuvers in the next few days over Albania and
Macedonia in a show of strength, establishing military training and
exercise centers, and using NATO transport to cope with refugee
flows.
	   McCurry said there had been discussions about the use of air
forces, something that should be taken up by NATO military experts.
	   The United States and the European Union have imposed economic
sanctions on Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, but hold out
little hope they will result in a government pullback in Kosovo.
	   NATO military planners have for the past two weeks been studying
indirect options for pressuring Milosevic, including dispatching up
to 20,000 troops to Albania and Macedonia, reinforcing the existing
750-member U.N. force in Macedonia, and helping both countries
secure borders while dealing with refugees and arms smuggling.
	   The Clinton administration is signaling it wants NATO to
organize air exercises in Albania and Macedonia.
	   A U.S. official traveling with Cohen said the defense ministers
``are likely to endorse ... planning for air exercises in Albania
and Macedonia.'' The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
noted the details of the exercise will be worked out by NATO
military experts.
	   In London on Wednesday, British Prime Minister Tony Blair said
that military force is necessary for a diplomatic solution of the
Kosovo crisis.
	   Britain is leading an effort to win U.N. Security Council
approval for a resolution authorizing ``all necessary means'' to
deal with the situation in Kosovo. The United States is backing the
plan, but Russia has opposed it so far. 	   
</TEXT>
