<SLUG> BC-UN-Switzerland,0460 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Swiss official said Switzerland not heading toward drug
</HEADLINE>
legalization &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT H. REID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Switzerland's controversial program of
distributing heroin and other hard drugs to selected addicts does
not mean the country is heading toward legalizing drugs, the
country's vice president said.
	   ``I wish to repeat this loud and clear here: Switzerland is not
moving toward drug liberalization,'' Ruth Dreifuss told the closing
session of the three-day U.N. General Assembly special session on
drugs.
	   ``Quite the contrary,'' she added Wednesday. ``Heroin remains a
banned substance in Switzerland and it can only be prescribed with
special authorization from the Confederation in specialized
institutions.''
	   Last September, Swiss voters overwhelmingly endorsed their
government's liberal drug policies, including the controversial _
but seemingly successful _ state distribution of heroin.
	   Dreifuss said the results of studies indicated that the program
of ``medical presciption of drugs'' made it possible ``to reach
high-dependent drug addicts who had tried other forms of therapy
but without success. Their state of health has considerably
approved, as have their social situations.''
	   She said prescribing morphine and heroin to addicts was simply
one treatment option and ``many conditions need to be present for
such therapies so as not to cause more harm than good.''
	   ``Given the magnitude of these problems and aware that there is
no single solution to solve them, the government of Switzerland has
opted for a pragmatic, coherent policy to reduce drug addiction and
its negative consequences and combat organize crime,'' Dreifuss
added.
	   She said other elements of the Swiss program treatment,
education and strict law enforcement, especially in the control of
money-laundering and precursor drugs, which can be synthesized into
narcotics.
	   Nevertheless, the Swiss program has raised concern in
Switzerland and elsewhere in Europe that the country could emerge
as a ``drug island'' on the continent.
	   Swiss officials insist, however, that the program has reduced
drug deaths and allowed many addicts to break their dependency.
	   Results of a three-year study released in last year showed a big
drop in crime among addicts on the program; a huge improvement in
their health; an increase in the number of those with steady
housing and jobs; and promising signs that some would try to kick
the habit.
	   There are an estimated 30,000 addicts in Switzerland _ one of
the highest rates in Europe. But unlike many countries, the death
toll is falling.
</TEXT>
