<SLUG> BC-SCI-Science Briefs,0897 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Brain transplants ease symptom resembling Huntington's disease in
</HEADLINE>
monkeys &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Monkeys that were made clumsy by brain damage
showed significant recovery when they received transplants of
embryonic tissue to their brains, an encouraging result for
treating Huntington's disease with transplants.
	   Scientists have already started putting embryonic tissue into
the brains of some Huntington's patients to see if it can treat the
genetic disorder. Huntington's erodes concentration and memory and
causes twitching, clumsiness and difficulty in walking, speaking
and swallowing.
	   The new work is reported in the June issue of the journal Nature
Medicine by scientists at Cambridge University in England. They
damaged part of the brains of 12 marmosets by injecting quinolinic
acid. That made the monkeys very clumsy in one hand during a test
in which they grasped food from step-like shelves.
	   Six of the monkeys later received transplants of embryonic
monkey brain tissue to the damaged areas of their brains. That made
them much less clumsy in the food-grasping task for up to nine
months.
	   Studies of their brains showed the grafted tissue could survive
at least a year after transplant, without anti-rejection drugs.
	    &UR; ___
	   CHICAGO (AP) _ Add age-related hearing loss to the list of
health problems cigarette smokers are more likely to face.
	   A five-year study of 3,753 middle-age and older people found
that smokers are 1.7 times as likely to have age-related hearing
loss as nonsmokers.
	   Lead researcher Karen Cruickshanks, associate professor of
ophthalmology and visual sciences at the University of Wisconsin
Medical School in Madison, said the findings suggest an association
between smoking and hearing loss but more study is needed to
determine if a direct cause-and-effect relationship exists.
	   Hearing loss may be a coincidence, Cruickshanks said Monday.
	   ``It's most likely that there are many factors that play a role
in the age-related loss of hearing, and possibly smoking is one of
them,'' she said.
	   The National Institute on Aging funded the study, published in
Wednesday's Journal of the American Medical Association.
	   The study, started in 1993, took place in Beaver Dam, Wisconsin,
using participants from a large population-based study on vision
and factors that might affect vision loss. Participants were ages
48 to 92.
	   The more people smoked, the study found, the greater their risk
of hearing loss: People who smoked an average of a pack a day for
40 years were 1.3 times as likely to have a hearing loss as those
who had smoked a pack a day for a decade.
	   Forty-six percent of those studied were nonsmokers, 39.3 percent
were ex-smokers and 14.7 percent were current smokers. Data was
incomplete for some of the original participants.
	   Of participants between the ages of 60 and 69, 35.3 percent of
nonsmokers suffered a hearing loss, 47.3 percent of ex-smokers and
56.4 percent of current smokers.
	   Hearing loss is estimated to affect 30 percent to 35 percent of
adults ages 65 to 75 years old in the United States.
	   The study defined hearing loss as an average loss of more than
25 decibels compared with normal hearing. People with this mild
form of hearing loss would have some trouble understanding
conversation when there is background noise.
	   The study accounted for several factors, including age,
occupational noise exposure and history of cardiovascular disease.
	   Dr. John Leonetti, a professor at Loyola University Medical
Center in Maywood who specializes in the study of ear-related
disorders, said doctors like himself already believe smoking can
cause hearing loss.
	   Leonetti, who was not involved in the study, advises patients to
avoid nicotine, caffeine and chocolate _ all things that can
constrict the body's small vessels.
	   ``I think it's important to get the word out ... that counseling
patients about smoking is important with respect to hearing loss,''
he said.
	    &UR; ___
	   BOSTON (AP) _ Women run up 30 percent higher annual medical
bills than men do, but it's not necessarily because they're sicker.
	   A Canadian study found that women's higher medical costs can be
explained largely by the expense of pregnancy and childbirth as
well as uniquely female diseases.
	   Many studies have found that women use more medical resources,
and experts have wondered whether the explanation is that women are
more willing to seek care or that they actually get sick more
often.
	   The latest study, directed by Cameron A. Mustard of the
Institute for Work and Health in Toronto, was based on a review of
all 1.1 million people covered by provincial health insurance in
Manitoba in 1994. The results were published in Thursday's New
England Journal of Medicine.
	   Overall, women's bills averaged dlrs 1,164 per year, while men's
were dlrs 918. The figures are in Canadian dollars.
	   Twenty-two percent of women's health costs were for specifically
female conditions, while just 3 percent of men's health bills were
for male conditions, such as prostate treatment.
	   Since women live longer, their lifelong medical bills are
substantially higher than men's. The researchers calculated that up
to the year she dies, a woman's lifetime medical expenses in
Manitoba average dlrs 85,131, while a man's are dlrs 58,950. 	   
</TEXT>
