<SLUG> BC-Nicaragua-Ortega,0260 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sandinista chief ordered to court on rape charges
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By RODOLFO GARCIA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) _ A judge has ordered former President
Daniel Ortega to appear in court to face charges he raped and
abused his stepdaughter.
	   Attorneys for Ortega, secretary-general of the leftist
Sandinista National Liberation Front, have claimed he has immunity
because he is a deputy in the National Legislature. But Managua
criminal judge Marta Quezada said Wednesday that claim was never
made in pretrial documents.
	   Ortega's lawyer, Ramon Rojas, said such a claim was unnecessary
because it is public knowledge that Ortega is a legislator. He said
Ortega would not be in contempt of court if he ignores the summons.
	   Zoilamerica Narvaez, 30, filed a complaint alleging that she had
been molested by her stepfather since she was 11 years old.
	   Ortega led the Sandinistas since before they overthrew dictator
Anastasio Somoza in 1979 and served as president from 1979 to 1989.
He has not responded publicly to Narvaez's allegations.
	   In her criminal complaint, Narvaez claimed Ortega had molested
her since she was 11. In her account, she said he raped her at age
15 and sometimes forced her to have sex with a third person while
he watched.
	   She said the sexual abuse continued after her marriage and the
birth of her two children, lasting until she went public with her
charges in March.
	   His wife and one of her sons has defended him, accusing Narvaez
of having mental problems. 	   
</TEXT>
