<SLUG> BC-Japan-Elections </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Elections for upper house of Japan's Parliament expected July 12
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Elections for Japan's upper house of Parliament
will take place July 12, an official said Thursday, in a vote
expected to serve as a referendum on Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto's 2-year-old administration.
	   Parliament's decision Wednesday to extend its current session
until June 18 effectively means the polls must be held by July 12
under current law, said an upper house parliamentary affairs
official, who declined to be named.
	   The date must await formal approval from Japan's Cabinet, the
official added.
	   The polls will be the first upper house elections since
Hashimoto came to power in early 1996 and will give his Liberal
Democratic Party a chance to regain a majority in the body, which
it lost in 1989.
	   Defections from a weakened opposition allowed the conservative
LDP, long the dominant party in Parliament, to reclaim its majority
in the more powerful lower house last September for the first time
since 1993.
	   Every three years, half of the 252 seats in Japan's upper house,
known as the House of Councillors, are elected to six-year terms.
Barring an early dissolution of Parliament, lower house elections
will not be held until 2000.
	   The LDP led Japan from 1955 until 1993, when a short-lived
reformist coalition came to power.
 &UR; (cd) 	   
</TEXT>
