<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. dollar climbs to new seven-year high, Tokyo stocks fall
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar climbed to a new seven-year high
against the yen Thursday morning amid continued uncertainty about
the Japanese and other Asian economies. Tokyo stock prices fell.
	   The dollar bought 141.76 yen, up 0.92 yen from late Wednesday in
Tokyo, to a level not seen since early June, 1991. In New York
overnight, the currency settled at 141.43 yen.
	   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 274.77 points, or 1.79
percent, moving to 15,064.49 at the close of morning trading. On
Wednesday, the Nikkei sank 190.91 points, or 1.23 percent.
	   Currency traders said the dollar's rise was spurred by sharp
falls in share prices in Japan and Taiwan, leading to safe-haven
dollar-buying on rekindled fears of further financial turmoil in
Asia
	   ``The stock market falls in Japan and Taiwan highlighted the
sentiment that Asia is still unstable,'' said Shuji Takano,
assistant manager of foreign exchange at ABN-Amro Bank N.V.
	   Also contributing to the dollar's advance was lack of a firm
commitment to stem the yen's slide by the Group of Seven deputy
finance ministers who met in Paris on Wednesday, traders said.
	   Traders said statements from the meeting signaled no change in
G-7 policy on the yen.
	   Recent signs that Japan's economy is slowing, such as rising
unemployment and declining corporate profits, have hurt the yen.
	   Japanese officials, though, have warned that their currency may
have weakened excessively against the dollar, suggesting possible
yen-buying intervention.
	   Share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange continued to fall as
investors were discouraged by the continued weakening of the yen
against the dollar.
	   Among early losers were banking issues, which sold off on
renewed concerns about the bad loans saddling Japan's financial
system. Investors are concerned that banks' problem loans overseas
will swell due to the weakening of the yen, traders said.
	   The weakness of the yen, which erodes the value of Japanese
stocks held by foreign investors, also hurt sentiment.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section fell 21.13 points, or 1.76 percent, to 1,177.47. The
TOPIX fell 10.08 points, or 0.83 percent, the day before.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond rose to 1.245 percent from Wednesday's close of
1.195 percent, driving its price down to 111.68 yen from 112.06
yen.
 &UR; (tz-km-dj)
</TEXT>
