<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Stocks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hong Kong Shares plunge to new lows
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Battered by the yen's weakness, Hong Kong
stocks fell to new lows Thursday morning as the benchmark index
lost 3.1 percent just minutes after the opening bell, hitting its
lowest level since Feb. 1995.
	   Analysts said there was no positive news on the horizon and the
market was seeking a new floor.
	   ``The market will test lower support levels to establish a firm
bottom,'' said Ben Kwong, an analyst at Dharmala Securities.
	   The blue-chip Hang Seng Index opened down 97.79 points to
7,881.58, but immediately picked up the pace and started falling
sharply.
	   After 15 minutes of trading, the index was down 293.90 points to
7,685.47. It has moved as low as 7,673.25.
	   On Wednesday, the index fell 412.09 points, or 4.9 percent, to
7,979.37, a three-year low. It has lost 7.1 percent over the past
two sessions.
	   The Hong Kong market has been battered by the weak yen, which
has sent investors scurrying for safer markets, far away from Asia.
	   In morning trading in Tokyo, the U.S. dollar rose against the
yen as traders bet that the Group of Seven industrialized nations
was unlikely to intervene to defend the yen.
	   The dollar bought 141.44 yen, up 0.60 yen from late Wednesday in
Tokyo and just above its late New York level of 141.43 yen
overnight.
	   The yen's weakness has sent local interbank interest rates
soaring, which means higher costs for local firms.
	   The benchmark three-month Hong Kong interbank offered rate
jumped to 14 percent early Thursday from 11 percent late Wednesday.
	   The yen's weakness also has triggered fears of a devaluation of
the Chinese yuan, which would wreak havoc on Hong Kong's economy
and the ability of its government to defend the Hong Kong dollar's
peg to the U.S. currency.
	   Kwong said if the yen continues to weaken, pushing rates higher,
the market will likely fall sharply, he said.
	   He also said investors are looking to the government to offer
some new solutions for the dramatic decline in asset prices,
including property and equity prices, Kwong said.
	   ``The government may need to do more to restore market
confidence,'' he said.
	   Hong Kong's Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa insisted Wednesday the
government will keep its 14-year currency peg to the U.S. dollar,
despite increasing calls for action to help Hong Kong fight a
liquidity crunch.
	   He also ruled out further tax cuts or injecting government funds
to keep the financial markets from sliding further. 	   
</TEXT>
