<HEADLINE>
Train crash in southern Japan leaves 29 injured
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Twenty nine people were injured when two train cars
collided Thursday on Japan's southern island of Shikoku, a police
spokesman said.
	   One female passenger suffered a broken leg in the collision,
according to a spokesman for the Kochi prefectural, or state,
police department. Twenty-eight others were taken to a nearby
hospital, although most received only mild injuries.
	   The accident involved two single-car trains run by Tosa Kuroshio
railway in Kochi prefecture, about 625 kilometers (391 miles)
southwest of Tokyo, said the spokesman, on condition of anonymity.
	   One train carrying 40 passengers had stopped on the track near
the town of Ogata due to a mechanical problem. The other was
dispatched to tow it to the nearest station but approached too fast
and was unable to stop before colliding with it.
