<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Opposition Arrest </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police release detained opposition lawmaker
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos planned
 &UR; By ALVIN UNG &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Malaysian police Thursday released
an opposition member of Parliament four hours after detaining him
for speaking at a political rally banned by authorities, an
opposition party spokesman said.
	   Lim Guan Eng, deputy secretary-general of the Democratic Action
Party, was taken to the Petaling Jaya police station at about 10.30
p.m. (1330 GMT) Wednesday shortly after he spoke to 2,000
supporters.
	   Lim and three other detained party members were released early
Thursday.
	   ``We still don't know if he will have to appear in court or what
the charge against him is,'' said Y.C. Foo, Lim's secretary.
	   The three colleagues had apparently tussled with policemen who
were trying to cart away amplifiers and speakers used at the
political rally.
	   Police dispersed the crowd shortly after midnight. Several
scuffles broke out but no injuries were reported.
	   A police spokesman was not immediately available for comment.
	   ``With the government bent on establishing a police state, this
is the end of the freedom of expression in Malaysia,'' Lim said in
a telephone interview from the police station.
	   This is the fourth time police have shut down public meetings
over the past 10 days and the third time police have disbanded
opposition gatherings.
	   Dozens of organizations have decried it as an assault on civil
liberties and free speech.
	   At Wednesday's fund-raising dinner for Lim, who has been
sentenced to 18 months in prison for printing a pamphlet that
questioned Malaysia's political system, police in riot gear stood
watch. The gathering had not received approval from authorities.
	   A number of DAP leaders spoke during the dinner. Vehicles
clogged the road adjoining the field, where more than 60 dinner
tables had been placed for their supporters.
	   As the night continued, hundreds of people from the surrounding
neighborhoods also gathered to watch the spectacle. Shortly after
Lim began to speak, dozens of police in riot gear moved in to nab
him.
	   ``We're not criminals, we're not robbers, we're not even threat
to the nation,'' Lim's father, party secretary-general Lim Kit
Siang and the opposition leader in Parliament, shouted into the
microphone shortly after police led his son away.
	   ``In Indonesia, the people who have been muzzled for three
decades are beginning to experience a new freedom of expression,''
said Lim Sr. ``But in Malaysia, the government has suddenly become
afraid of the voice of the people.'' 	   
</TEXT>
