<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Gambling Lawmaker </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Australian casino drops plan to sue Malaysian lawmaker: report
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ An Australian casino has dropped
plans to sue a Malaysian lawmaker after he agreed to settle a
gambling debt of 4.8 million Malaysian ringgit (dlrs 1.2 million)
in installments, a newspaper reported Thursday.
	   Private investigators representing the casino in Perth said that
the member of parliament had paid up the first installment on
Wednesday, the New Straits Times reported.
	   ``We have got no further interest in the MP's case as he has
promised to pay the amount in due course,'' said Christopher White,
a private investigator working on behalf of the casino.
	   Lawsuits would, however, be filed against six other Malaysians
who owed the casino 2.4 million ringgit (dlrs 615,000), he said.
	   The debts were all incurred since 1994.
	   More than 100 Malaysian gamblers ran up debts totaling 60
million ringgit (dlrs 15 million) over the last four years in 10
casinos in Australia, a popular destination for rich Malaysians,
dailies had reported earlier.
	   In 1995, a Las Vegas casino sued a Malaysian businessman to
recover a dlrs 1.3 million gambling debt. 	   
</TEXT>
