<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Russia-Runaway Ship </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Runaway ship found sailing off Russia's far eastern coast
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ A Russian ship that sailed away from
court-ordered custody with two South Korean captives aboard has
been spotted off Russia's far eastern coast, officials said
Thursday.
	   The 683-ton refrigerator ship Tibiya was found sailing off the
Russian island of Sakhalin, South Korean maritime police said,
quoting Russian officials.
	   The ship disappeared earlier this week from the port of Pusan on
South Korea's southeast coast, where it had been impounded by a
local court in a legal dispute over an unpaid debt.
	   ``The two Korean men are alive, and we are talking through
diplomatic channels to bring them home once the ship arrives at its
base in Magadan,'' a Russian fishing base in the Sea of Okhotsk,
said a police investigator, speaking on condition of anonymity.
	   When the ship docked at Pusan on April 7 for repairs, a South
Korean dry dock company filed suit with a local court, seeking
payment of dlrs 1.5 million incurred for earlier repair work.
	   Court-hired private guards were posted on the ship to enforce a
court order to impound the ship. When it came time to replace the
guards on Monday, the ship was gone.
	   Chavshov Alexay, 36, the ship's Russian owner, was arrested
later at Kimhae airport near Pusan as he tried to leave South
Korea. He was accused of instructing his vessel's 18-man crew to
flee. 	   
</TEXT>
